// Technical Practice Flashcards - Investment Banking (1346 Questions)
export type Flashcard = { q: string; a: string; category: string; firm?: string; difficulty?: 'Intermediate' | 'Advanced' };

export const IB_FLASHCARDS: Flashcard[] = [
// ═══ ACCOUNTING & FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (1-80) ═══
{q:"Walk through the three core financial statements and explain the main purpose of each.",a:"The income statement shows revenue, expenses, and net income over a period. It measures profitability. The balance sheet shows assets, liabilities, and equity at a point in time. It measures financial position. The cash flow statement reconciles net income to actual cash generated across operating, investing, and financing activities.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do the three financial statements connect to each other in a fully integrated model?",a:"Net income from the IS flows into retained earnings on the BS and is the starting point for CFO on the CFS. D&A from the IS is added back on the CFS and reduces PP&E on the BS. CapEx on the CFS increases PP&E on the BS. Debt issuance/repayment on CFS changes debt on the BS. Ending cash on the CFS ties to cash on the BS.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you could review only one financial statement to assess a business, which would you choose and why?",a:"The cash flow statement, because it shows actual cash generated and spent regardless of accounting choices. It reveals whether the business converts profits to cash, how much it reinvests, and how it finances itself. You can also reverse-engineer approximate income and balance sheet positions from it.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If allowed two financial statements, which combination would you select and how would you recreate the third?",a:"Income statement and balance sheet. From two consecutive balance sheets you can derive the change in cash (top of CFS), and from the IS you get net income and non-cash items. Working capital changes come from BS deltas. CapEx approximated from PP&E changes plus depreciation. Financing flows from debt and equity changes.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company records an additional $20 in depreciation. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the impact on all three statements.",a:"Income statement. The extra $20 of depreciation is an expense, so pre-tax income falls $20. At a 25% tax rate that saves $5 of tax, so net income falls $15, not $20.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $15. Depreciation never cost any cash, so you add the full $20 straight back. Cash actually rises $5.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $5 and PP&E is down $20, so assets fall $15. Retained earnings fall $15 with net income, so both sides fall $15 and it balances.\n\nThe point: the $5 of cash is the tax you did not have to pay. Depreciation is a non-cash charge that shields real cash.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If depreciation increases by $15 and the tax rate is 25%, how does this affect net income and cash flow?",a:"Pre-tax income falls by 15, tax savings of 3.75, so net income decreases by 11.25. On the CFS, NI -11.25 plus D&A add-back +15 = net cash increase of 3.75 (the tax shield).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does a non-cash expense like depreciation increase cash flow from operations?",a:"Depreciation reduces taxable income without requiring a cash outflow. The resulting tax savings is real cash kept by the company. On the CFS, depreciation is added back to net income because it was deducted on the IS but no cash left the business.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Where can depreciation appear on the income statement, and why might presentation differ by company?",a:"It can appear as a separate line item, embedded within COGS (for manufacturing equipment), or within SG&A (for office assets). Presentation depends on the nature of the depreciated assets and industry conventions. Analysts must check the CFS or notes to find total D&A.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A $25 increase in accrued expenses is being recognized as an expense. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the impact on the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $25 accrual is recognized as an expense now even though nothing has been paid, so pre-tax income falls $25. Tax drops $6.25 at 25%, leaving net income down $18.75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $18.75. The accrued liability rose $25, and a liability you have booked but not paid is a source of cash, so add $25 back. Cash rises $6.25.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $6.25, accrued liabilities are up $25, and retained earnings are down $18.75. Liabilities and equity net to a $6.25 increase, matching cash.\n\nThe point: accrual accounting books the expense when it is incurred, not when it is paid. Until you pay, the only cash effect is the lower tax bill.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Inventory rises by $30, paid in cash, and no inventory has yet been sold. What happens to each statement?",a:"Income statement. Nothing happens. Inventory sits on the balance sheet as an asset and only becomes an expense through COGS when the goods are actually sold.\n\nCash flow statement. Building inventory is a use of cash in working capital, so cash falls $30.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $30 and inventory is up $30. Total assets are unchanged. No equity effect, because nothing touched the income statement.\n\nThe point: this is a pure swap of one asset for another. It is a classic test of whether you know that spending cash is not the same as recording an expense.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does a change in inventory not immediately affect the income statement?",a:"Inventory is an asset on the balance sheet until it is sold. Only when inventory is sold does the cost transfer to COGS on the income statement. This follows the matching principle. Expenses are recognized in the same period as the associated revenue.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company issues $200 of new term debt to fund $200 of new PP&E. Show the impact at close on the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing at close. Borrowing money and buying an asset are not income or expense events.\n\nCash flow statement. The $200 debt raise is an inflow in financing, and the $200 of CapEx is an outflow in investing. They offset exactly, so net cash is zero.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E is up $200 and debt is up $200. Assets and liabilities both rise $200. Equity does not move.\n\nThe point: on day one this is only a financing and investing event. The income statement stays clean until the asset starts depreciating and the debt starts accruing interest, which is the next year's question.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"One year later, that $200 of PP&E is depreciated straight-line over 10 years; the debt pays 8% cash interest, with no principal amortization. Tax rate is 25%. Show the Year 1 impact.",a:"Income statement. Depreciation is $20 a year ($200 over 10 years) and interest is $16 ($200 at 8%). Together they cut pre-tax income $36. Tax falls $9 at 25%, so net income falls $27.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $27. Add back the $20 of depreciation, which is non-cash. Cash falls $7. The interest is real cash out, the depreciation is not.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $7 and PP&E is down $20, so assets fall $27. Debt is unchanged because no principal amortizes. Retained earnings fall $27, so it balances.\n\nThe point: both charges reduce earnings, but only interest actually drains cash.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In Year 3 the undepreciated PP&E is written down to zero and the remaining debt is repaid in full. Tax rate is 25%. How do the three statements change in that year?",a:"Income statement. The remaining book value is written off. After two years of depreciation the asset carries $140 ($200 less $60), so the impairment is $140. Add the final year's $16 of interest and pre-tax income falls $156. Tax benefit of $39 at 25% leaves net income down $117.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $117. The $140 impairment is non-cash, so add it back, along with the $20 of depreciation. Then the $200 debt repayment is a real financing outflow. The write-down costs no cash; the repayment costs all of it.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E goes to zero, debt goes to zero, cash falls by the repayment, and retained earnings fall by net income.\n\nThe point: an impairment is an accounting event, not a cash event. The cash in this year leaves through the debt repayment.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company purchases $40 of raw materials inventory that will be manufactured and sold later. Describe the timing of when costs appear on the income statement.",a:"At purchase, 40 moves from cash to raw materials inventory. No IS impact. During manufacturing, costs transfer to work-in-progress, still no IS impact. Only when finished goods are sold does the cost appear as COGS on the IS, matched against the revenue from that sale.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"The company sells finished goods for $100 in revenue and $60 of cost that was previously inventory. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Revenue is up $100 and COGS is up $60, so gross profit is $40. Tax of $10 at 25% leaves net income up $30. The $60 of COGS is inventory you already paid for in an earlier period.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $30. Inventory fell $60 as the goods shipped, which is a source of cash, so add $60. If the sale was for cash, receivables do not move and cash rises $90. If it was on credit, receivables rise $100, which is a use of cash, and cash falls $10 until the customer pays.\n\nBalance sheet. Inventory is down $60, retained earnings are up $30, and either cash or receivables absorbs the $100 of revenue.\n\nThe point: profit and cash are not the same thing. Whether this sale helps cash this quarter depends entirely on whether the customer pays now or later.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Under what scenarios can shareholders' equity become negative? What does that signal?",a:"Large accumulated losses exceeding paid-in capital, massive share buybacks funded by debt, or large impairment charges. It signals the company has returned or lost more value than shareholders originally invested. Common in highly leveraged companies or those with persistent losses.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Define working capital in a simple way and explain why it matters in valuation.",a:"Working capital is current operating assets (AR, inventory) minus current operating liabilities (AP, accrued expenses), excluding cash and debt. It matters because changes in WC consume or release cash, directly affecting free cash flow and therefore valuation in a DCF.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does a consistently negative working capital position indicate about a business model?",a:"The company collects cash from customers before paying suppliers. It's funded by its operations. Common in subscription businesses, retailers with fast inventory turns, and companies with strong bargaining power. It's generally a positive sign of cash flow efficiency.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is operating working capital and why do bankers prefer it to total working capital in models?",a:"Operating working capital excludes cash, short-term debt, and current portion of long-term debt. Focusing only on trade-related items like AR, inventory, AP, and accrued expenses. Bankers prefer it because cash and debt are treated separately in enterprise value calculations and capital structure analysis.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company records a $120 impairment on an intangible asset. Tax rate is 25%. How does this flow through the three statements?",a:"Income statement. The $120 impairment is an expense, so pre-tax income falls $120. Tax benefit of $30 at 25% leaves net income down $90.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $90. The impairment is non-cash, so add the full $120 back. Cash rises $30.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $30 and the intangible is down $120, so assets fall $90. Retained earnings fall $90 and it balances.\n\nThe point: an impairment admits the asset is worth less than the carrying value. No cash moves, and the only cash effect is the $30 of tax saved, which is why cash goes up on a charge that sounds bad.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the difference between an impairment charge and regular depreciation or amortization.",a:"D&A is systematic allocation of an asset's cost over its useful life. Predictable and planned. Impairment is an unplanned write-down when the asset's fair value drops below its carrying value, reflecting a sudden loss of value. Impairment is typically non-recurring; D&A is recurring.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a $150 equity injection from a new investor affect the three statements at closing?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Selling shares to an investor is a financing transaction, not revenue.\n\nCash flow statement. A $150 inflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $150 and equity is up $150, split between common stock at par and additional paid-in capital for the rest.\n\nThe point: money from owners is never income. This is a very common trap, because the company clearly has more money and it is tempting to run it through the income statement.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A government injects $300 of equity into a distressed bank. Walk through the accounting.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. An equity injection is money from an owner, not revenue, even when the owner is the government.\n\nCash flow statement. A $300 inflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $300 and equity is up $300, booked to common stock, preferred stock, or APIC depending on the instrument used.\n\nThe point: this is a recapitalization. The bank now holds more loss-absorbing capital, so its capital ratios improve, but it has not earned anything.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A lender forgives $80 of outstanding debt principal. Tax rate is 25%. Describe the impact on the financial statements.",a:"Income statement. Forgiven debt is taxable income, so the company books an $80 gain on extinguishment. Tax of $20 at 25% leaves net income up $60.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $60. The $80 gain is non-cash, so subtract it. Cash falls $20, which is exactly the tax owed on the forgiveness.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $20, debt is down $80, and retained earnings are up $60. Liabilities fall more than assets, so equity rises.\n\nThe point: being forgiven a debt makes you better off, so the tax authority treats it as income. The company pays real cash tax on a gain that brought in no cash.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is deferred tax, and how can it arise in a transaction or modeling context?",a:"Deferred tax arises from timing differences between book and tax treatment. A DTL means you owe taxes later (e.g., accelerated tax depreciation vs straight-line book). A DTA means future tax benefits (e.g., NOLs). In M&A, asset step-ups create DTLs as the new tax basis differs from book.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do deferred tax liabilities typically get created on an acquisition balance sheet?",a:"When purchase price allocation steps up asset values above their tax basis, the difference creates a DTL. The acquirer will depreciate/amortize at the higher book value but can only deduct the lower tax basis, creating a future tax obligation.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might a deferred tax asset be impaired following an acquisition?",a:"If the target has NOLs or other DTAs, Section 382 limitations may restrict annual usage post-acquisition. If the acquirer cannot realize the full benefit, the DTA must be written down. Also, a change in control may trigger valuation allowances if future profitability is uncertain.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company changes its revenue recognition policy to earlier recognition. What are some likely effects on the statements over time?",a:"Initially: higher revenue and NI, but AR increases faster (recognized revenue not yet collected). Over time the effect normalizes. Cash flow may not change much since actual collections are unchanged. Could inflate current-period metrics but creates a pull-forward effect.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the difference between cash and accrual accounting, and why accrual is standard for corporate analysis.",a:"Cash accounting records transactions when cash moves. Accrual records revenue when earned and expenses when incurred, regardless of cash timing. Accrual is standard because it better matches economic activity to the period it occurs, giving a more accurate picture of performance.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Under what conditions would capitalizing an expenditure be more appropriate than expensing it?",a:"When the expenditure provides economic benefit beyond the current period, such as purchasing equipment, building a factory, or developing software with multi-year utility. The cost is spread over the asset's useful life via depreciation or amortization rather than hitting the IS immediately.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Give examples of line items that are typically capitalized and amortized rather than expensed immediately.",a:"PP&E (depreciated), patents and trademarks (amortized), capitalized software development costs, leasehold improvements, deferred financing costs, and certain R&D costs under IFRS when technical feasibility is demonstrated.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does an increase in other current assets often represent, and how would you treat it in a model?",a:"Often represents prepaid expenses, tax receivables, or other short-term items. In a model, you'd typically project it as a percentage of revenue or hold it flat. An increase is a use of cash in working capital on the CFS.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you interpret a materially large goodwill balance on a company's balance sheet?",a:"It indicates the company has made significant acquisitions and paid premiums above the fair value of identifiable net assets. A large goodwill balance means future impairment risk if acquired businesses underperform, and it inflates total assets without generating direct cash flows.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When might you see goodwill decrease over time without any obvious acquisition or divestiture activity?",a:"Goodwill impairment testing. If the reporting unit's fair value falls below its carrying value, goodwill must be written down. This can happen due to deteriorating business conditions, lower earnings expectations, or market declines that reduce the implied value of past acquisitions.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain what retained earnings represent and list the main drivers of changes in this line item.",a:"Retained earnings is the cumulative net income minus cumulative dividends paid since inception. It increases with net income and decreases with dividends, share buybacks charged to RE, and comprehensive losses. It's the primary link between the IS and the equity section of the BS.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a profitable company still show negative operating cash flow in a given period?",a:"Large working capital investments (AR buildup, inventory buildup), significant one-time cash payments (taxes, settlements), or rapid growth requiring upfront cash outlays. Revenue is recognized but cash hasn't been collected, or cash expenses exceed accrual-based expenses.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a company with net losses still generate positive operating cash flow?",a:"Large non-cash charges like D&A, impairments, or stock-based compensation reduce net income without using cash. Favorable working capital changes (collecting AR, deferring payments) also boost cash. The operating cash flow adds back these non-cash items.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between accounts payable and accrued expenses?",a:"AP represents amounts owed for goods/services already invoiced by suppliers. There's a specific invoice. Accrued expenses represent obligations incurred but not yet invoiced, like wages earned but unpaid, or utilities consumed but not billed. Both are current liabilities.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does the choice of depreciation method (straight-line vs. accelerated) affect financial statements over the life of an asset?",a:"Accelerated front-loads depreciation expense, reducing NI and taxes early but boosting them later. Straight-line spreads evenly. Over the asset's full life, total depreciation and total tax are the same. It's a timing difference. Accelerated is better for cash flow early on due to tax deferral.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain how stock-based compensation flows through the three financial statements.",a:"Income statement. Stock-based compensation is an operating expense like any other salary, so it reduces pre-tax income and net income.\n\nCash flow statement. Net income is lower, but the company paid in shares rather than cash, so the full SBC expense is added back in operating cash flow.\n\nBalance sheet. Additional paid-in capital rises inside equity, offsetting the hit to retained earnings, so total equity barely moves. The diluted share count rises as options and RSUs vest.\n\nThe point: SBC is non-cash but it is not free. The cost is paid by existing shareholders through dilution, which is why adding it back to reach adjusted EBITDA is one of the most argued-over practices in the market.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company issues $50 of new common shares at par to employees as compensation. Tax rate is 25%. How does this affect each statement?",a:"Income statement. The $50 of shares issued to employees is compensation expense, so pre-tax income falls $50. Tax benefit of $12.50 at 25% leaves net income down $37.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $37.50. The company paid in stock, not cash, so add the $50 back. Cash rises $12.50 from the tax saving.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $12.50, common stock and APIC are up $50, and retained earnings are down $37.50. Net equity is up $12.50.\n\nThe point: cash went up while shareholders got poorer. The company paid its people with ownership, so the cost lands in the share count rather than the bank account.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you treat operating leases versus finance leases on the statements, and why does it matter in valuation?",a:"Under ASC 842, both go on the BS as right-of-use asset and lease liability. Finance leases: front-loaded expense (interest + amortization). Operating leases: straight-line rent expense. In valuation, you must decide whether to treat lease liabilities as debt (adding to EV) and adjust EBITDA accordingly for consistency.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the impact of increasing days sales outstanding (DSO) on cash flow and working capital?",a:"Rising DSO means customers are taking longer to pay. AR grows faster than revenue, consuming cash. Working capital increases, reducing free cash flow. It can signal collection problems, more lenient credit terms, or revenue recognition issues.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company starts offering more generous payment terms to customers, what working capital changes would you expect?",a:"AR would increase as customers take longer to pay. DSO rises. This is a use of cash in working capital, reducing FCF. Revenue might increase if the terms attract more customers, but the cash conversion cycle lengthens.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you estimate maintenance capex versus growth capex from disclosures or limited data?",a:"Maintenance CapEx approximates depreciation (replacing existing assets). Growth CapEx is total CapEx minus maintenance. Some companies disclose the split. Otherwise, use D&A as a proxy for maintenance, or compare CapEx to revenue growth, if CapEx grows faster, the excess is likely growth-related.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What might you infer if a company's capital expenditures are consistently below its depreciation expense?",a:"The company is underinvesting in its asset base. Spending less on replacement than assets are wearing out. Short-term this boosts FCF, but long-term it may signal deteriorating competitive position, aging infrastructure, or an asset-light transition.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you treat restructuring charges in your analysis of a company's normalized earnings power?",a:"Add them back to calculate normalized EBITDA since they're non-recurring. But scrutinize frequency, if a company takes restructuring charges every year, they may be a real cost of doing business and shouldn't be fully added back.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When might it be appropriate to adjust EBITDA for stock-based compensation in valuation work?",a:"SBC is a real economic cost (dilution) so many argue it shouldn't be added back. However, since it's non-cash and doesn't affect debt capacity, some LBO models and credit analyses add it back. The key is consistency, if you add it back, use higher diluted share counts.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the implications if a company repeatedly records large one-time charges?",a:"If one-time charges recur, they're not truly one-time. They represent a real cost of doing business. Analysts should be skeptical of adjusted metrics that exclude them. It may indicate poor acquisitions, operational problems, or aggressive accounting to inflate adjusted earnings.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the concept of minority interest and where it appears on the statements.",a:"Minority interest (non-controlling interest) represents outside ownership in a subsidiary the parent consolidates at 100%. On the IS, minority interest's share of NI is subtracted. On the BS, it appears in equity. In EV, it's added because the parent consolidates 100% of revenue/EBITDA.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you adjust enterprise value for non-controlling interests, and why?",a:"Add NCI to EV because the parent consolidates 100% of the subsidiary's revenue and EBITDA, but doesn't own 100% of the equity. Adding NCI ensures the numerator (EV) matches the denominator (full EBITDA) in valuation multiples.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between non-controlling interest and equity-method investments in another company?",a:"NCI: parent owns >50%, consolidates 100% of subsidiary's financials, NCI represents the outside minority. Equity method: parent owns 20-50%, records its proportional share of the investee's NI as a single line item. The investee's full financials are NOT consolidated.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is interest income often classified below operating income in an income statement?",a:"Interest income comes from cash/investments, not core operations. Separating it from operating income gives a cleaner view of the business's operational profitability. It also aligns with the EV framework where operating metrics are capital-structure neutral.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would capitalizing interest during construction of an asset affect the statements?",a:"Income statement. No interest expense hits the income statement during construction, because the interest is capitalized into the asset instead. Reported net income is higher than it would be otherwise.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E rises by the capitalized interest. That interest will come back later as extra depreciation once the asset is placed in service.\n\nCash flow statement. The interest is still paid in cash, but it is classified as CapEx in investing rather than as an operating outflow. Operating cash flow looks better and free cash flow is unchanged.\n\nThe point: total cash is identical. Capitalizing interest only moves the cost across statements and delays it, which flatters both earnings and operating cash flow in the build years.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company sells an asset for $70 that has a book value of $50. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The asset sold for $70 with a book value of $50, so the company books a $20 gain. Tax of $5 at 25% leaves net income up $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $15. The $20 gain is not an operating item and the full proceeds are counted below, so subtract the $20 out of operating. Then show the $70 of proceeds as an inflow in investing. Cash rises $65.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $65, PP&E is down $50, so assets rise $15. Retained earnings are up $15.\n\nThe point: the gain is subtracted in operating so the $70 is not double counted. Only $65 sticks, because $5 went to tax on the gain.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you detect aggressive revenue recognition practices using the three statements over multiple periods?",a:"Look for: revenue growing faster than cash collections (rising DSO), declining cash conversion, increasing gap between NI and CFO, growing deferred revenue or unbilled receivables, and revenue spikes at quarter-end. Compare revenue trends to industry peers and operational metrics.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might you reclassify certain other income or other expense items when normalizing earnings?",a:"To separate recurring operating performance from non-recurring or non-operating items (FX gains/losses, asset sales, litigation settlements). This gives a cleaner view of sustainable earnings power for valuation and comparability purposes.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the difference between cash taxes paid and income tax expense on the income statement.",a:"Income tax expense is the accrual-based GAAP provision, including current and deferred portions. Cash taxes paid is the actual cash outflow to tax authorities. They differ due to timing differences (deferred taxes), NOL utilization, tax credits, and refunds.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company's effective tax rate diverges meaningfully from the statutory rate. What might cause that?",a:"International operations with different tax rates, R&D tax credits, non-deductible expenses (goodwill impairment, certain SBC), tax-exempt income, NOL utilization, valuation allowances on DTAs, or permanent differences between book and tax treatment.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a share repurchase affect earnings per share and book value per share?",a:"EPS increases because the denominator (share count) decreases while NI is roughly the same (slightly lower due to lost interest on cash used). Book value per share may increase or decrease depending on whether shares were repurchased above or below book value.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the accounting implications of a stock split versus a stock dividend?",a:"Stock split: shares multiply, par value adjusts proportionally, no journal entry needed. Just a memo. Stock dividend: new shares issued, retained earnings decreases, common stock/APIC increases. Both increase share count but a stock dividend transfers value within equity accounts.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company issues convertible debt. How is it reflected on the balance sheet at issuance?",a:"Under US GAAP (ASU 2020-06), convertible debt is generally recorded entirely as a liability at face value. Under older rules, it was bifurcated into debt and equity components. The conversion feature may require separate accounting depending on the specific terms.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When would you apply the if-converted method versus the treasury stock method for EPS?",a:"If-converted: used for convertible securities. Assume all converted, add back interest savings to NI, increase share count. Treasury stock method: used for options/warrants. Assume exercised, proceeds used to buy back shares at market price, net dilution added to shares.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you estimate fully diluted shares outstanding from a capitalization table?",a:"Start with basic shares outstanding. Add net dilution from in-the-money options/warrants using treasury stock method. Add shares from RSU vesting. Add potential shares from convertible securities using if-converted method (if dilutive). Exclude out-of-the-money instruments.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you reconcile net income to operating cash flow starting from the income statement?",a:"Start with NI. Add back non-cash charges (D&A, SBC, impairments, deferred taxes). Subtract non-cash gains. Adjust for working capital changes: subtract increases in AR/inventory, add increases in AP/accrued liabilities. Add back other non-operating items to arrive at CFO.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might you adjust reported EBITDA for unusual or non-recurring items in a sell-side process?",a:"To present normalized earnings power. Showing what the business earns on a sustainable, run-rate basis. Buyers want to pay for recurring profitability, not one-time charges or windfalls. Common adjustments: restructuring, litigation, M&A costs, one-time revenue items.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Describe how changes in provisions or reserves affect the three statements.",a:"When the provision is created. The income statement takes the expense and net income falls. The balance sheet shows a new liability and lower retained earnings. The cash flow statement adds the provision back, because booking a reserve moves no cash.\n\nWhen the provision is used. The income statement shows nothing, because the expense was already taken when the reserve was set up. The liability comes down and cash goes out.\n\nThe point: provisions split the accounting hit from the cash hit. The expense lands the day management estimates it, the cash leaves later, and the size of the estimate is at management's discretion, which is why reserves are a classic place to look for earnings management.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What does a growing deferred revenue balance tell you about a company's business model?",a:"The company is collecting cash before delivering services. A sign of strong demand and subscription/prepayment-based revenue. It's a positive working capital dynamic. However, it also represents an obligation to deliver, so quality and sustainability matter.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you treat deferred revenue when estimating free cash flow?",a:"Increases in deferred revenue add to CFO (cash collected but not yet recognized as revenue). In a DCF, this is captured in working capital changes. For normalized FCF, consider whether deferred revenue growth is sustainable or a one-time catch-up.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company reclassifies a portion of long-term debt as current. How does that impact your analysis?",a:"Working capital deteriorates (current liabilities increase). Current ratio and quick ratio decline. It signals upcoming refinancing need or maturity wall. In EV calculations, the debt treatment doesn't change, but liquidity analysis becomes more important.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you account for pension obligations and why are they important in valuation?",a:"Pension obligations appear as a liability (PBO minus plan assets = funded status). Underfunded pensions are debt-like obligations that should be considered in EV. Pension expense appears on the IS. Changes in actuarial assumptions can materially swing the liability and affect equity.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the key differences between IFRS and US GAAP that matter most for banking analysis?",a:"Revenue recognition (timing differences), lease accounting (converging but nuances remain), inventory (LIFO allowed under GAAP, not IFRS), R&D capitalization (more common under IFRS), goodwill (IFRS amortizes in some jurisdictions), and financial instruments classification.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company capitalizes R&D while peers expense it. How would you adjust to make metrics comparable?",a:"Expense the capitalized R&D in the period incurred to match peers. This reduces NI and EBITDA. Remove the amortization of previously capitalized R&D from the IS. Remove the capitalized asset from the BS. This normalizes margins and returns across the comp set.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you adjust a company's financials to evaluate its performance excluding foreign exchange volatility?",a:"Use constant-currency analysis: apply prior-period exchange rates to current-period foreign revenues and costs. Many companies disclose organic/constant-currency growth in press releases. This isolates true operational performance from FX translation effects.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does goodwill not amortize under US GAAP, and how is impairment tested conceptually?",a:"FASB determined goodwill has an indefinite life, so systematic amortization isn't appropriate. Instead, companies test annually (or when triggers arise) by comparing reporting unit fair value to carrying value. If carrying value exceeds fair value, goodwill is impaired by the difference.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the practical modeling implications of a company with large off-balance sheet guarantees?",a:"They represent contingent liabilities that could become real obligations. You may need to adjust EV to reflect the risk, apply probability-weighted liability estimates in scenarios, or note them as risk factors. Lenders and rating agencies treat them as quasi-debt.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How can you use the cash flow statement to evaluate the quality of a company's earnings?",a:"Compare CFO to NI, if CFO consistently exceeds NI, earnings quality is high (cash-backed). If NI exceeds CFO, earnings may be inflated by accruals. Check for large non-cash add-backs, working capital deterioration, and whether CapEx matches depreciation.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Describe a situation where the cash flow statement looks strong but the business is actually deteriorating.",a:"A company delays paying suppliers (AP increases), draws down inventory without replenishing, or collects prepayments for services it may not deliver. These boost short-term CFO but mask declining revenue, margin erosion, or unsustainable working capital harvesting.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Describe a situation where the income statement looks weak but the underlying cash generation is attractive.",a:"Heavy D&A or amortization of intangibles from past acquisitions depresses NI, but the business generates strong operating cash flow since those are non-cash charges. Also, restructuring charges may temporarily depress earnings while the underlying business is healthy.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
// ═══ VALUATION & DCF (81-170) ═══
{q:"List the main valuation methodologies used in investment banking and briefly define each.",a:"1) DCF: intrinsic value from discounted projected cash flows. 2) Trading Comps: relative value from public peer multiples. 3) Precedent Transactions: value implied by past M&A deal multiples. 4) LBO Analysis: value based on sponsor return requirements. 5) Sum-of-Parts: segment-level valuation for diversified companies.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In what situations would you favor a DCF over a multiples-based valuation and vice versa?",a:"DCF when the company has predictable cash flows, unique characteristics making comps imperfect, or when you want to test specific assumptions. Comps when there are good public peers, the company lacks reliable projections, or for quick market-based sanity checks.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is an intrinsic valuation often more sensitive to assumptions than a trading comparables analysis?",a:"A DCF depends on projected growth, margins, CapEx, WACC, and terminal value. Small changes in any compound over time. Comps anchor to market prices and peer multiples, which embed collective expectations. The DCF's sensitivity to terminal assumptions alone can swing value 20-30%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When screening for trading comparables, what are the typical quantitative and qualitative filters you apply?",a:"Quantitative: similar size (revenue/market cap), growth rates, margins, capital intensity. Qualitative: same industry/sub-sector, business model, end markets, geographic mix, and stage of lifecycle. No comp set is perfect. Judgment is key.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you decide which multiples are most relevant for a particular industry?",a:"Match the multiple to what drives value in that sector. Capital-light tech: EV/Revenue or EV/EBITDA. Capital-intensive industrials: EV/EBIT (captures D&A). Banks: P/TBV, P/E. REITs: P/FFO, P/AFFO. Pharma: EV/EBITDA with pipeline-adjusted metrics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might EV/EBITDA be preferred to EV/EBIT for some sectors and the opposite for others?",a:"EV/EBITDA works well for comparing companies with different D&A policies or capital structures. EV/EBIT is better for capital-intensive businesses where D&A represents a real cost of maintaining assets. Ignoring it would overstate cash generation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain why equity value-based multiples and enterprise value-based multiples capture different things.",a:"EV multiples (EV/EBITDA, EV/Revenue) measure the value of the entire firm relative to pre-financing metrics. Capital structure neutral. Equity multiples (P/E, P/BV) measure value to equity holders relative to post-interest metrics. Mixing them (e.g., EV/NI) is a mismatch.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What adjustments do you make to enterprise value to arrive at an adjusted firm value suitable for multiples?",a:"Start with equity value (market cap). Add debt, preferred stock, minority interest. Subtract cash and equivalents. May also add unfunded pensions, capitalize operating leases, add contingent liabilities. Subtract equity investments or non-operating assets valued separately.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you value a company with negative EBITDA using market-based methods?",a:"Use EV/Revenue as the primary multiple. Also consider forward multiples if profitability is expected. User/subscriber-based metrics for tech (EV/subscriber, EV/GMV). DCF with explicit path to profitability. Comparable transaction multiples from recent deals in the space.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some pitfalls of relying on headline P/E ratios when comparing companies?",a:"P/E is distorted by capital structure (leverage inflates EPS), tax rate differences, non-recurring items, different share count methodologies, and accounting policy choices. Two companies with identical operations but different leverage will show very different P/Es.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you normalize earnings for a cyclical business before applying trading multiples?",a:"Use mid-cycle or through-cycle average earnings rather than peak or trough. Look at 5-10 year average margins and apply them to current revenue. Alternatively, use normalized EBITDA based on average utilization rates or commodity prices.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might you exclude certain outlier companies when constructing a trading comps set?",a:"If a comp has extreme multiples due to distress, pending M&A, one-time events, or vastly different growth profile, it can skew the range and mislead the analysis. Exclude with explanation, but show the full set for transparency.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you calendarize financials to ensure consistency across companies with different fiscal year-ends?",a:"Weight financials proportionally. For a company with a March FY end, the calendar year estimate blends 75% of the March FY and 25% of the next March FY. This ensures all comps are on the same time basis for fair comparison.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the logic behind using forward rather than trailing multiples in some sectors.",a:"Forward multiples reflect where the market expects the company to be, not where it has been. This matters more for high-growth companies or sectors undergoing rapid change. Markets are forward-looking, so forward multiples better capture current pricing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the advantages and disadvantages of precedent transaction analysis versus trading comparables?",a:"Precedents reflect actual prices paid including control premiums and synergies. Realistic for M&A. But they may be stale (different market conditions), have limited data, and premiums vary widely. Comps are current but reflect minority value without control premium.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you select relevant precedent transactions for valuing a target in a sale process?",a:"Screen for: same or similar industry, comparable size, similar time period (ideally last 3-5 years), similar deal type (strategic vs financial buyer), and geographic relevance. Adjust for market conditions if comparing across different rate environments.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do precedent transactions often imply higher valuation multiples than trading comparables?",a:"Because acquisition prices include a control premium (20-40% typical), expected synergies, scarcity value in competitive auctions, and strategic motivations. Trading comps reflect minority, uncontrolled share prices without these premiums.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through a simple DCF from revenue to valuation output.",a:"Project revenue → operating expenses → EBIT → tax-effect → add back D&A → subtract CapEx → subtract WC changes = UFCF. Discount each year's UFCF at WACC. Calculate terminal value and discount it back. Sum all PVs = Enterprise Value. Subtract net debt = Equity Value. Divide by diluted shares = per share value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the key drivers of free cash flow in a standard corporate DCF?",a:"Revenue growth rate, operating margins (EBIT margin), tax rate, depreciation and amortization, capital expenditures, and working capital changes. Terminal value assumptions (growth rate or exit multiple) also dominate the output.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is the free cash flow to firm (unlevered) approach common in banking DCF work?",a:"UFCF is capital-structure neutral. It values the entire firm before financing decisions. This allows comparison across companies with different leverage, and WACC accounts for the blended cost of all capital. It separates operating value from financing value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Define the formula for unlevered free cash flow starting from EBIT.",a:"UFCF = EBIT × (1 - Tax Rate) + D&A - CapEx - Change in Net Working Capital. This captures cash generated by operations available to all capital providers (debt and equity) before any financing costs.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is WACC conceptually, and why is it used as the discount rate in an unlevered DCF?",a:"WACC is the weighted average return required by all capital providers (debt and equity), weighted by their proportion of the capital structure. Since UFCF belongs to all providers, WACC is the appropriate rate to discount it. It reflects the blended cost of financing the entire firm.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through the calculation of WACC and the main inputs required.",a:"WACC = (E/V) × Cost of Equity + (D/V) × Cost of Debt × (1-T). Inputs: market cap (E), net debt (D), total firm value (V=E+D), cost of equity (CAPM), pre-tax cost of debt (yield on existing debt or new issuance), and marginal tax rate (T).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain how to estimate the cost of equity using CAPM and the intuition behind each term.",a:"Cost of Equity = Risk-Free Rate + Beta × Equity Risk Premium. Risk-free rate: time value of money (10-year Treasury). Beta: sensitivity to market risk. ERP: extra return investors demand for stocks over bonds. Together: the return equity investors require for bearing this company's risk.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you estimate beta for a private company using public comparables?",a:"Get observed (levered) betas for public comps. Unlever each using their D/E ratios to isolate business risk. Take the median unlevered beta. Relever at the target's assumed capital structure. This gives a beta reflecting the target's business risk and financing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain why you unlever and then relever beta when estimating cost of equity.",a:"Observed betas include both business risk and financial risk (leverage). To compare business risk across companies, you must strip out leverage effects (unlever). Then you relever for the target's specific capital structure to get the appropriate beta for that company's financing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Describe the two main approaches to estimating terminal value.",a:"1) Gordon Growth (Perpetuity): TV = Final Year FCF × (1+g) / (WACC-g). Assumes the business grows at a constant rate forever. 2) Exit Multiple: TV = Final Year EBITDA × Exit Multiple. Applies a market-based multiple to terminal year earnings. Both should be cross-checked.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When would you favor a perpetuity growth terminal value versus an exit multiple approach?",a:"Perpetuity growth is more theoretically grounded for stable, mature businesses. Exit multiple is more market-anchored and intuitive for bankers. In practice, most analysts use exit multiple as primary and perpetuity growth as a cross-check to validate the implied growth rate.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you choose an appropriate long-term growth rate in a Gordon Growth terminal value?",a:"It should approximate long-term nominal GDP growth (2-3% for developed markets). It should not exceed the economy's growth rate because no company can grow faster than the economy indefinitely. Consider the company's industry growth and competitive position within that range.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some indicators that your DCF output is overly dependent on the terminal value?",a:"If terminal value represents more than 75-80% of total enterprise value, the explicit forecast period is adding little information. This suggests either the forecast period is too short, the terminal growth rate is too aggressive, or the exit multiple is too high.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Describe how you would value a bank differently from a traditional industrial company.",a:"Banks use deposits as operational funding (not traditional debt), so EV/EBITDA doesn't work. Use equity-based metrics: P/E, P/TBV, dividend discount model, or residual income model. Focus on ROE, NIM, credit quality, and capital ratios rather than EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you value an early-stage high-growth technology company with minimal earnings?",a:"EV/Revenue multiples using comparable high-growth companies. DCF with explicit path to profitability (model margin expansion over time). Comparable transactions from recent funding rounds or acquisitions. Unit economics analysis (LTV/CAC). TAM/SAM/SOM framework for market sizing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Describe a sum-of-the-parts valuation and when it is most applicable.",a:"Value each business segment separately using the most appropriate methodology and peer set for each. Sum the segment values, add corporate-level assets, subtract corporate overhead and net debt. Most useful for conglomerates or companies with distinct business lines trading at a discount.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does an LBO analysis help a strategic buyer decide its maximum bid in an auction?",a:"The LBO sets a valuation floor. The maximum a financial sponsor would pay while achieving target returns. A strategic buyer should be willing to pay at least this much (since they have synergies) but the LBO provides a reference for how competitive the auction will be.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do changes in the risk-free rate affect both DCF valuation and multiples?",a:"Higher risk-free rate → higher WACC → lower PV of cash flows → lower DCF value. It also compresses trading multiples as investors demand higher returns. The effect is larger for long-duration growth stocks where more value sits in distant future cash flows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the rationale for using enterprise value rather than equity value in most trading multiples.",a:"EV captures the value of the entire business to all capital providers, making it independent of capital structure. This allows fair comparison of companies with different leverage. EV paired with pre-interest metrics (EBITDA, Revenue) avoids the distortion that debt creates in equity-only metrics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you treat capitalized operating leases when computing enterprise value and EBITDA multiples?",a:"Add the present value of operating lease obligations to EV (they're debt-like). Add back the lease expense to EBITDA (since the obligation is now in EV). This ensures numerator and denominator are consistent and comparable across companies with different lease vs own decisions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you incorporate scenario analysis into a DCF framework?",a:"Build base, bull, and bear cases with different assumptions for growth, margins, CapEx, and terminal value. Probability-weight the scenarios (e.g., 25% bull, 50% base, 25% bear) and compute a weighted-average valuation. Present the range to show risk-reward distribution.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the logic behind using mid-year discounting in a DCF, and when do you apply it?",a:"Mid-year convention assumes cash flows arrive evenly throughout each year rather than at year-end. It shifts discount factors back by half a year, slightly increasing present values. Used for most corporate DCFs; year-end convention may be used for seasonal businesses.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the most common errors junior analysts make when building DCFs?",a:"Mismatching EV and equity value metrics, incorrect WACC components, terminal growth rate exceeding GDP, not discounting terminal value, using book values instead of market values in WACC, circular references not resolved, inconsistent tax rates, and not sanity-checking output vs market.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
// ═══ M&A CONCEPTS & MERGER MODELS (171-260) ═══
{q:"Explain the main strategic reasons a corporate buyer might pursue an acquisition.",a:"Revenue growth (new markets, customers, products), cost synergies (eliminate redundancies), technology or IP acquisition, talent acquisition, vertical integration, competitive positioning, or diversification. The core thesis must be that combined value exceeds standalone values.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a financial buyer's acquisition rationale differ from a strategic buyer's?",a:"Financial buyers (PE) focus on IRR through leverage, operational improvement, and exit at a higher multiple. They rarely have synergies. Strategic buyers focus on long-term integration, synergies, and strategic fit. Strategics can typically pay more because synergies increase the target's value to them.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Define accretion and dilution in the context of an acquisition.",a:"Accretive: pro forma EPS exceeds buyer's standalone EPS. The deal adds to earnings per share. Dilutive: pro forma EPS is lower. Determined by comparing earnings yield of target to cost of financing. Not the sole measure of value creation.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the key drivers that determine whether a deal is accretive or dilutive to EPS?",a:"Relative P/E ratios (stock deals), cost of financing (debt yield vs target earnings yield), synergies, purchase accounting adjustments (intangible amortization), foregone interest on cash, new shares issued, and tax impacts.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a buyer proceed with a slightly dilutive deal anyway?",a:"If the strategic rationale is compelling. Access to growth markets, critical technology, defensive positioning, or long-term synergies that eventually make it accretive. EPS accretion is a short-term metric; value creation is what ultimately matters.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through the high-level steps of building a basic merger model.",a:"1) Input buyer and target standalone financials. 2) Set purchase price, consideration mix, and financing. 3) Build sources & uses. 4) Purchase price allocation (goodwill, intangibles). 5) Calculate pro forma adjustments (synergies, new interest, amortization, shares). 6) Combine IS. 7) Compute pro forma EPS vs standalone.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you estimate synergies in an M&A transaction, and what types exist?",a:"Cost synergies: headcount reduction, facility consolidation, procurement savings, IT rationalization. Revenue synergies: cross-selling, bundling, geographic expansion. Estimate by benchmarking similar deals, identifying overlapping functions, and applying realization timelines. Cost synergies are more credible.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why are synergy estimates often scrutinized or discounted by investors?",a:"Management often overstates synergies to justify premiums. Revenue synergies are particularly uncertain because they depend on customer behavior. Integration execution risk is real. Many deals fail to capture projected synergies. Market discounts them until proven.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between a stock-for-stock deal and a cash deal, and how do each affect the buyer's balance sheet?",a:"Cash deal: buyer uses cash/debt, no new shares. Balance sheet sees cash decrease or debt increase, goodwill created. Stock deal: buyer issues new shares, no cash outflow. Share count increases, goodwill created, no debt impact. Hybrid uses both.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does the mix of cash versus stock consideration affect accretion/dilution?",a:"More cash (funded by debt): accretive if target's earnings yield exceeds after-tax cost of debt. More stock: accretive if buyer's P/E is higher than target's effective P/E (including premium). Cash deals avoid dilution but increase leverage; stock deals increase share count.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the difference between a stock purchase, asset purchase, and 338(h)(10) election conceptually.",a:"Stock purchase: buyer acquires target's shares, inherits all assets and liabilities, no tax step-up. Asset purchase: buyer selects specific assets/liabilities, gets tax step-up, avoids unwanted liabilities. 338(h)(10): treated as stock purchase legally but asset purchase for tax. Step-up with simpler execution.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you compute the purchase price in an acquisition, including equity value, net debt, and assumed items?",a:"Offer price × diluted shares = equity value. Add target's net debt (debt minus cash), preferred stock, minority interest, and other debt-like items (unfunded pensions, capital leases). Subtract excess cash or non-operating assets. This gives total enterprise value / purchase price.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through how you allocate purchase price to tangible and intangible assets in a purchase price allocation.",a:"Step up tangible assets (PP&E, inventory) to fair value. Identify and value intangible assets (customer relationships, brand, technology, non-competes). Record assumed liabilities at fair value. Create deferred tax liabilities on step-ups. Residual = goodwill.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How is goodwill created in an acquisition, and why is it considered a residual?",a:"Goodwill = Purchase Price - Fair Value of Identifiable Net Assets Acquired. It's a residual because it captures everything that can't be separately identified and valued. Expected synergies, assembled workforce, brand premium, and the control premium paid.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the role of identifiable intangibles in purchase price allocation?",a:"Customer relationships, technology/patents, brand/trade names, non-compete agreements, and order backlog are valued separately. They're amortized over their useful lives (5-20 years typically), creating a real expense that reduces post-deal EPS and can make deals look dilutive.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you treat transaction expenses versus financing fees in a merger model?",a:"Transaction expenses (advisory, legal, accounting) are expensed immediately. They reduce NI in Year 1 but are non-recurring. Financing fees (bank commitment fees, bond issuance costs) are capitalized and amortized over the life of the debt. Recurring annual expense.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the key credit metrics you would examine for a buyer post-transaction?",a:"Total Debt / EBITDA (leverage ratio), Net Debt / EBITDA, Interest Coverage (EBITDA / Interest), Fixed Charge Coverage, Debt / Total Capitalization. Also check pro forma credit ratings impact and covenant compliance.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What factors influence the premium a buyer is willing to pay in an all-cash acquisition?",a:"Expected synergies, strategic value of the asset, scarcity/competitive dynamics, target's standalone prospects, current market conditions, buyer's financial capacity, and the cost of not doing the deal (competitive threat).",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are common closing conditions that can derail an announced transaction?",a:"Regulatory/antitrust approval failure, shareholder vote failure, material adverse change in the target, financing condition (if applicable), litigation injunctions, and failure to obtain required third-party consents.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does regulatory risk influence how you position valuation and structure?",a:"High antitrust risk may require divestitures (reducing synergies), reverse break fees to protect the seller, longer timelines affecting financing costs, and potentially lower headline premiums to reduce scrutiny. Structure may need remedies built in upfront.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the role of a fairness opinion in an M&A transaction?",a:"A formal written opinion from a financial advisor that the consideration in a transaction is fair, from a financial point of view, to the relevant party (usually target shareholders). It provides legal protection to the board fulfilling its fiduciary duties.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you build an M&A premiums analysis, and what does it show?",a:"Collect premiums paid in comparable transactions (offer price vs unaffected share price at 1-day, 1-week, 1-month prior). Calculate median and mean premiums. This shows the typical control premium in the sector and helps set expectations for negotiation range.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Under what conditions might an acquisition be value-destructive even if it is EPS accretive?",a:"If the buyer overpays relative to the target's intrinsic value, synergies don't materialize, integration fails, or the combined company's cost of capital increases. EPS accretion can be manufactured through financial engineering while actual value is destroyed.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the concept of a carve-out or spin-off and why a company might pursue it.",a:"Carve-out: selling a portion of a subsidiary to outside investors (IPO or sale). Spin-off: distributing subsidiary shares to existing shareholders, creating an independent company. Done to unlock hidden value, improve focus, achieve higher combined multiples, or satisfy regulatory requirements.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would higher interest rates affect M&A volumes and valuation levels across the market?",a:"Higher rates increase cost of debt financing (reducing LBO capacity), compress valuation multiples (higher discount rates), and widen bid-ask spreads between buyers and sellers. Volume typically decreases until sellers reset expectations. Strategic deals with strong rationale still proceed.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you assess whether a proposed acquisition will improve or dilute a company's credit rating?",a:"Analyze pro forma leverage ratios, interest coverage, FCF/debt, and compare to rating agency thresholds. Cash-funded deals may be neutral; heavily debt-funded deals may trigger downgrades. Synergies and deleveraging timeline matter. Rating agencies publish their methodology.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the difference between horizontal, vertical, and conglomerate M&A strategies.",a:"Horizontal: acquiring a competitor in the same industry (scale, market share). Vertical: acquiring a supplier or customer (supply chain control). Conglomerate: acquiring an unrelated business (diversification). Horizontal faces most antitrust scrutiny.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a go-shop provision and when might it be used?",a:"A post-signing period (typically 30-60 days) where the target can actively solicit competing bids. Used to protect the board from fiduciary duty claims, particularly in management-led buyouts or single-bidder deals. The initial bidder gets a lower break fee if topped.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you think about management rollover equity in a sponsor-led buyout of a public company?",a:"Management rolls existing equity into the new private entity, aligning incentives with the sponsor. It reduces the equity check needed. Tax-efficient for management (no current gain recognition). Signals confidence in the business. Typically 10-30% of total equity.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you weigh short-term EPS accretion against long-term strategic value in an M&A recommendation?",a:"Short-term EPS is a sanity check, not the decision criterion. The real question is whether the deal creates NPV-positive value through synergies, growth, or strategic positioning. Many value-creating deals are initially dilutive. Frame the analysis around long-term ROIC vs cost of capital.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
// ═══ LBO & FINANCIAL SPONSORS (261-340) ═══
{q:"Walk through the key steps of building a basic LBO model.",a:"1) Set entry valuation (EV/EBITDA). 2) Build sources & uses. 3) Project operating financials (revenue, EBITDA, CapEx, WC). 4) Build debt schedule (mandatory/optional paydown, interest). 5) Calculate FCF and debt paydown. 6) Set exit assumptions (multiple, year). 7) Compute exit equity, IRR, and MOIC.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does using leverage amplify equity returns in a buyout?",a:"Debt is cheaper than equity and reduces the equity check. As the company repays debt with cash flow, equity value grows while the initial investment stays fixed. If the business performs, the sponsor captures all the upside above debt repayment. But leverage also amplifies downside risk.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you construct the sources and uses table in an LBO?",a:"Uses: equity purchase price, transaction fees, financing fees, refinanced debt. Sources: sponsor equity, various debt tranches (revolver, TL, bonds), seller rollover, management rollover. Sources must equal uses. The equity check is typically the balancing item.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the main types of debt instruments used in leveraged buyouts and how do they differ?",a:"Revolver (undrawn facility), Term Loan A (amortizing, bank-held), Term Loan B (minimal amort, institutional), Senior Secured Notes, Senior Unsecured Notes, Subordinated/Mezzanine Debt. They differ in priority, cost, amortization, covenants, and investor base.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between maintenance covenants and incurrence covenants?",a:"Maintenance: tested regularly (quarterly), must be in compliance at all times. Breach triggers default. Incurrence: only tested when the company takes a specific action (new debt, dividend). More borrower-friendly. Cov-lite loans typically have incurrence only.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is PIK interest and why would a sponsor agree to use PIK instruments?",a:"Payment-in-Kind interest compounds and adds to principal rather than being paid in cash. Sponsors use it to preserve cash flow for operations or other investments. It's more expensive (higher rate) but reduces near-term cash burden. Increases total debt over time.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is cash flow generation more important than accounting earnings in LBO analysis?",a:"Debt is repaid with cash, not accounting profits. A company with high EBITDA but poor cash conversion (heavy CapEx, WC needs) may struggle to service debt. FCF drives deleveraging, which drives equity returns. LBO models focus on cash available for debt service.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you estimate a reasonable exit multiple range in an LBO?",a:"Use current trading comps, precedent transactions, and historical trading ranges. Conservative assumption: exit at entry multiple (no expansion). Base case may allow modest expansion if operational improvements justify it. Sensitize across a range.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you compute the sponsor's IRR and money-on-money multiple in an LBO model?",a:"IRR: the discount rate that makes PV of exit equity proceeds equal to initial equity investment, accounting for timing. MOIC = Exit Equity Value / Initial Equity Investment. Both are computed from the equity waterfall. IRR captures time value; MOIC captures total return.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you estimate debt capacity for a target in an LBO?",a:"Start with EBITDA × maximum leverage multiple lenders will accept (typically 4-6x). Check interest coverage (EBITDA/Interest > 2x), fixed charge coverage, and FCF debt service capacity. Stress test under downside scenarios. Lenders set the ceiling based on credit metrics.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a dividend recap and why might a sponsor pursue one?",a:"The portfolio company issues new debt and pays the proceeds as a dividend to the sponsor. It returns capital to the sponsor without selling the company, boosting IRR by reducing the equity at risk. Risk: increases leverage on the company.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does the tax shield from interest expense affect LBO returns?",a:"Interest expense is tax-deductible, reducing the company's tax bill. This creates additional after-tax cash flow available for debt repayment. The tax shield effectively subsidizes the cost of debt, making leverage more attractive. Higher tax rates increase the benefit.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does an LBO set a floor under a company's valuation in a sale process?",a:"The LBO determines the maximum price a financial sponsor can pay while meeting return targets (typically 20%+ IRR). In an auction, this represents the minimum competitive bid. Strategic buyers with synergies should be willing to exceed this floor.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What characteristics make a business an ideal LBO candidate?",a:"Stable and predictable cash flows, strong market position, low CapEx requirements, manageable working capital, defensible competitive advantages, proven management, margin improvement potential, and hard assets that can support secured debt.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What attributes would make a business challenging for a leveraged buyout?",a:"Volatile/cyclical earnings, heavy capital expenditure needs, high customer concentration, negative FCF, commodity price exposure, regulatory uncertainty, high existing leverage, or technology disruption risk. These reduce debt capacity and increase default probability.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How can a sponsor create value in a portfolio company beyond financial engineering?",a:"Operational improvements (pricing optimization, procurement savings, SG&A rationalization), revenue growth initiatives, management upgrades, strategic repositioning, add-on acquisitions (buy-and-build), technology investments, and governance improvements.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you incorporate management rollover equity in an LBO model?",a:"Management's rollover reduces the sponsor's equity check (it's a source of funds). In the model, management equity is a separate line in sources. At exit, management participates pro-rata in equity proceeds. Often combined with a management equity incentive pool (options/sweet equity).",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When would a sponsor consider taking a portfolio company public rather than selling it outright?",a:"When public market valuations exceed private sale multiples, the business has a compelling equity story, the company is large enough for public market liquidity, or the sponsor wants a partial exit while retaining upside. IPOs allow staged exits over time.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you approach an LBO of a cyclical business differently from a defensive one?",a:"Lower leverage (3-4x vs 5-6x), model through a full cycle including a downturn, build larger cash reserves, use more conservative exit assumptions, focus on fixed charge coverage in downside, and structure debt with fewer maintenance covenants to avoid technical default in a trough.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Describe stress-testing techniques you would apply to an LBO model.",a:"Revenue decline scenarios (10-30%), margin compression, working capital deterioration, CapEx overruns, delayed exit, multiple compression at exit, interest rate increases on floating-rate debt, and covenant breach analysis. Test whether the company survives each scenario without distress.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why is entry valuation often the single most important driver of LBO returns?",a:"A lower entry multiple means less equity invested for the same EBITDA. This directly increases MOIC. It also provides a larger cushion against multiple compression at exit. EBITDA growth and deleveraging help, but overpaying at entry is the hardest mistake to overcome.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the main reasons an LBO might fail to meet its targeted returns?",a:"Overpaying at entry, revenue/EBITDA declining post-close, inability to achieve operational improvements, rising interest rates on floating debt, forced exit at compressed multiples, failed add-on strategy, management turnover, or macro/industry disruption.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
// ═══ CAPITAL MARKETS & MACRO (341-410) ═══
{q:"What are the main functions of an equity capital markets (ECM) team within an investment bank?",a:"Advise on equity issuance (IPOs, follow-ons, convertibles, rights offerings), price offerings, manage bookbuilding and allocation, coordinate with syndicate and sales teams, and provide market intelligence on equity demand and investor appetite.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the main functions of a debt capital markets (DCM) team?",a:"Advise on debt issuance (investment grade bonds, high yield, leveraged loans, private placements), structure and price offerings, manage syndication, coordinate with credit investors, and monitor credit markets for optimal timing.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain how a traditional bookbuilt IPO process works from mandate to pricing.",a:"Bank wins mandate → due diligence and S-1 filing → SEC review → roadshow (management presents to investors) → bookbuilding (orders collected at various prices) → pricing (based on demand, typically evening before trading) → allocation → first day of trading.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a direct listing differ from a traditional IPO in terms of process and economics?",a:"No new shares issued (existing shares sold), no underwriters (advisory role only), no lockup period, price discovered by market open auction rather than bookbuilding. No capital raised for the company. Lower fees but no price stabilization or guaranteed demand.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a SPAC and why did they become more prominent in recent years?",a:"Special Purpose Acquisition Company. A blank-check shell that IPOs, holds cash in trust, and then merges with a private target within ~2 years. SPACs surged because they offered faster path to public markets, price certainty, and ability to use forward projections. Volume declined as regulatory scrutiny and returns deteriorated.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the concept of a yield curve and what information it conveys.",a:"A yield curve plots bond yields across maturities (3-month to 30-year). Normal curve slopes upward (longer = higher yield for duration risk). It conveys market expectations for growth, inflation, and monetary policy. The shape changes as these expectations shift.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does an inverted yield curve typically signal about economic expectations?",a:"Short-term rates exceed long-term rates, signaling that markets expect future rate cuts due to economic slowdown or recession. Historically a reliable recession predictor. Banks suffer because they borrow short and lend long. Inverted curves compress net interest margins.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What tools does the Federal Reserve have to influence short-term interest rates?",a:"Federal funds rate target, open market operations (buying/selling Treasuries), discount window lending, reserve requirements, interest on excess reserves (IOER), reverse repos, forward guidance, and quantitative easing/tightening (balance sheet operations).",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is quantitative easing and why might a central bank implement it?",a:"QE is large-scale asset purchases (Treasuries, MBS) by the central bank to inject liquidity, lower long-term rates, and stimulate the economy when short-term rates are already near zero. It expands the central bank's balance sheet and pushes investors into riskier assets.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How did ultra-low interest rates influence equity market valuations in the period after 2020?",a:"Lower discount rates increased PV of future cash flows, boosting equity valuations, especially long-duration growth stocks. Low bond yields pushed investors into equities (TINA - There Is No Alternative). Multiple expansion drove returns more than earnings growth.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between monetary and fiscal policy, and how do both affect markets?",a:"Monetary: central bank controls money supply and rates (affects cost of capital, credit availability). Fiscal: government spending and taxation (affects demand, deficits, and sectoral flows). Both influence growth, inflation, and asset prices through different transmission mechanisms.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do changes in the 10-year Treasury yield impact equity valuations and sector rotations?",a:"Rising 10-year: compresses equity multiples (higher discount rate), hurts growth/duration stocks most, benefits financials (wider NIM). Falling 10-year: expands multiples, benefits growth stocks, hurts bank profitability. Drives rotation between value and growth.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Define beta and alpha in the context of portfolio returns.",a:"Beta measures a portfolio's sensitivity to market movements. 1.0 moves with the market, >1.0 amplifies, <1.0 dampens. Alpha is return in excess of what beta would predict. The manager's value-add from skill (security selection, timing) beyond passive market exposure.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How can rising credit spreads signal stress in financial markets even if equity indices are near highs?",a:"Credit markets often lead equities in detecting distress. Widening spreads mean bond investors are demanding more compensation for default risk, signaling deteriorating credit conditions. Equity indices can stay elevated due to a few large-cap names masking broader weakness.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What factors would you monitor daily to stay informed on market conditions before an interview?",a:"Equity indices (S&P, Dow, Nasdaq), 10-year Treasury yield, credit spreads (IG and HY), VIX, FX rates (DXY), commodity prices (oil, gold), Fed commentary, major earnings, M&A announcements, and macro data releases (CPI, jobs, PMI).",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you articulate a near-term and long-term view on equity markets to a senior banker?",a:"Structure as: current conditions (growth, rates, earnings), near-term catalysts (Fed decisions, earnings season, geopolitics), risks (inflation persistence, credit tightening, geopolitical escalation), and sector implications. Be balanced. Show you can think through multiple scenarios.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Advanced"},
// ═══ BEHAVIORAL & FIT (411-500) ═══
{q:"Walk me through your story and how it led you to pursue investment banking.",a:"Structure: present → relevant past → why banking. Start with what you're doing now, connect key experiences that built relevant skills (analytical, teamwork, interest in deals/markets), and explain why IB is the logical next step. Keep it under 2 minutes.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why are you specifically interested in investment banking rather than sales and trading or asset management?",a:"IB: transaction-focused, steep learning curve, exposure to strategic decision-making, client advisory, analytical depth in modeling. Differentiate from S&T (short-term market focus) and AM (long-term investment focus). Show you understand what the role actually entails.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why are you interested in this particular bank compared with others you are interviewing with?",a:"Reference specific: culture, group focus, deal flow, people you've spoken with, training reputation, or recent transactions. Be genuine and specific. Generic praise fails. Show you've done real research beyond the website.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you worked under significant time pressure and how you handled it.",a:"Use STAR: Situation, Task, Action, Result. Show composure, prioritization, quality maintenance under deadline. Banking values this because the job is constant deadline pressure. Give a specific example with measurable outcome.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Describe a situation where you took initiative on a project without being asked.",a:"Show proactivity: identified a gap or opportunity, proposed a solution, executed without being told. This is critical in banking. Analysts who anticipate needs and take ownership stand out from those who wait for instructions.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you received critical feedback and how you responded.",a:"Show coachability: listened without defensiveness, understood the feedback, implemented changes, followed up to show improvement. Banking is a feedback-intensive culture. Interviewers want to know you can handle direct criticism constructively.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you failed at something significant and what you learned.",a:"Be honest about a real failure, not a disguised success. Show ownership (not blaming others), what you learned, and how you changed your approach going forward. Demonstrate resilience and growth mindset.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you dealt with a difficult team member and what you did.",a:"Show maturity: listened to understand their perspective, found common ground, adapted your approach, maintained professionalism. If unresolved, escalated appropriately. Don't badmouth the person. Focus on resolution and what you learned.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you led a team without an official leadership title.",a:"Show influence without authority: organized the group, set direction, delegated tasks, held people accountable, and delivered results. Banking leadership is often informal. You earn it through competence and reliability, not titles.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Give an example of when attention to detail made a material difference in your work.",a:"Specific example where catching a small error (number, formatting, logic) prevented a significant problem. Banking lives and dies by accuracy. A misplaced decimal in a model or a typo in a client document can have real consequences.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you had to make a decision with incomplete information.",a:"Show structured thinking under uncertainty: identified what you knew, made reasonable assumptions, decided with available information, and planned for contingencies. This is daily life in banking. Deals move fast and you rarely have perfect data.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do you think you can handle the lifestyle and hours associated with investment banking?",a:"Don't minimize the hours. Show awareness of the reality, demonstrate relevant experience with sustained intensity (sports, academics, work), and express genuine motivation for the work itself. The best answer is that you've already lived through demanding periods and thrived.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What has been your most meaningful leadership experience and why?",a:"Choose something with real stakes where your leadership made a measurable difference. Explain what you learned about yourself and others. Connect it to how you'd lead on a deal team. Organizing work, motivating a group, delivering under pressure.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you went above and beyond what was expected.",a:"Show initiative and work ethic: you identified something beyond your job description, did it anyway, and it created real value. This is what banking rewards. Analysts who proactively add value rather than just completing assigned tasks.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you had to persuade someone senior to see things your way.",a:"Show diplomatic assertiveness: presented evidence, listened to their concerns, adapted your argument, found common ground. Don't frame it as winning an argument. Frame it as influencing through quality of reasoning.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would your previous manager or professor describe your strengths and weaknesses?",a:"Be honest and self-aware. Strengths should be banking-relevant (analytical, detail-oriented, reliable under pressure). Weakness should be real but manageable, with specific steps you're taking to improve. Don't say 'perfectionist' or 'work too hard.'",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Pick a recent M&A transaction and walk me through the strategic rationale.",a:"Choose a real deal you've genuinely followed. Know: buyer, target, price, multiple, premium, strategic rationale, financing, market reaction. Show you can think critically about why the deal makes sense (or doesn't) beyond headlines.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Choose a company you follow; how would you value it and what is your investment thesis?",a:"Pick a company you actually know. Structure: business overview → key drivers → valuation method → your view on whether it's fairly valued. Include risks. This tests whether you think like an investor, not just a student who memorized formulas.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Pitch me a stock in 2-3 minutes, focusing on key drivers and valuation.",a:"Structure: 1) Recommendation (buy/sell). 2) What the company does. 3) Why the market is wrong. 4) Valuation support. 5) Catalyst/timeline. 6) Key risks. Be concise, confident, and ready for pushback.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you respond when someone more senior than you is clearly wrong about something important?",a:"Raise it respectfully with evidence. Frame it as a question ('I may be missing something, but when I looked at X, I found Y...'). If they disagree, make your case once more clearly, then defer to their judgment. Never be combative, but don't stay silent on material errors.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What do you find most appealing about working in a deal team environment?",a:"The collaborative intensity, working toward a tangible outcome (deal closes), exposure to different companies and industries, learning from senior bankers, and the satisfaction of delivering high-quality work under pressure. Be specific about what excites you.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What do you think will be the hardest adjustment for you coming into banking?",a:"Be honest. Don't pretend nothing will be hard. Common answers: sustained hours, managing competing deliverables, the precision required, or learning the unwritten cultural norms. Then explain how you plan to handle it, citing past experience with similar challenges.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Where do you see your career in five to ten years, and how does banking fit into that path?",a:"Show banking as foundational, not just a stepping stone. Common paths: stay in banking, move to PE/HF, corporate strategy, or entrepreneurship. Whatever you say, emphasize that you want to learn and contribute fully in the analyst role first.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What do you think differentiates a top analyst from an average one?",a:"Anticipating needs before being asked, extreme attention to detail, ability to see the bigger picture beyond the model, strong communication up and down, resilience under pressure, and being someone the team can rely on at 2 AM on a live deal.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you handle being staffed on three live deals at once with conflicting deliverables?",a:"Communicate proactively with all deal leads about capacity. Prioritize by deadline and importance. Flag conflicts early rather than trying to do everything silently. Ask for help or delegate where appropriate. Quality over quantity. Never let a deliverable go out with errors.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you stay current on markets and finance news on a daily basis?",a:"Mention specific sources: WSJ, Bloomberg, Financial Times, Dealogic, company filings, earnings calls, and industry publications. Show it's a genuine daily habit, not interview prep. Reference something specific you read recently to prove it.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What questions do you have for me about the role, team, or firm?",a:"Ask thoughtful questions: What does the deal pipeline look like? What differentiates analysts who succeed here? What's your favorite deal you've worked on and why? What would the first 6 months look like? Never say 'no questions'. It signals lack of interest.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you do not receive an offer from us, what will you do next?",a:"Show persistence, not desperation. You'll continue recruiting at other banks because you're committed to banking. Briefly mention what you'd take away from the experience regardless. Don't threaten or guilt. Show resilience and professionalism.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"At the end of a long week, what would make you feel it was a successful week on the desk?",a:"Learning something new, delivering high-quality work that helped the deal team, earning trust from a senior banker, contributing to a live deal milestone, or helping a colleague succeed. Show that your satisfaction comes from meaningful work and growth, not just hours logged.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},

// ═══ EXPANDED QUESTIONS (219-800) ═══
{q:"If a company switches from FIFO to LIFO during a period of rising costs, what happens to COGS, net income, and inventory on the balance sheet?",a:"COGS increases (expensing newer, higher-cost inventory first), net income decreases, and the inventory balance on the BS decreases. Taxes paid decline due to lower pre-tax income, so cash flow improves despite lower reported earnings.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company prepays $60 of rent covering the next 12 months. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements at payment and after 6 months.",a:"At payment. The income statement shows nothing, because paying early does not consume anything yet. Cash falls $60 and a $60 prepaid expense asset appears. You have swapped cash for a right to 12 months of rent.\n\nAfter six months. Half the benefit is used up, so rent expense of $30 hits the income statement. Tax falls $7.50, leaving net income down $22.50. On the cash flow statement, net income is down $22.50 but the prepaid asset fell $30, which is a source of cash, so cash actually rises $7.50 from the tax saving. No rent cash moves, because it was all paid in month one.\n\nBalance sheet. The prepaid asset is down $30 and retained earnings are down $22.50.\n\nThe point: the expense follows the benefit, not the payment.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might two companies in the same industry report different gross margins even if their products are nearly identical?",a:"Different cost allocation methods (what goes into COGS vs SG&A), depreciation policies, manufacturing vs outsourcing models, geographic labor cost differences, inventory accounting (FIFO vs weighted average), and volume-based purchasing discounts all affect reported gross margins.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company records a $50M warranty provision. Tax rate is 25%. How does this affect the three statements at recognition and when the warranty claim is paid?",a:"At recognition. The income statement takes a $50 warranty expense as soon as the sale is made, because the obligation is created then. Tax falls $12.50, leaving net income down $37.50. On the cash flow statement, the provision is non-cash, so it is added back and cash rises $12.50. On the balance sheet, a $50 warranty liability appears and retained earnings fall $37.50.\n\nWhen a claim is paid. The income statement shows nothing, because the expense was already booked. The warranty liability falls and cash falls with it.\n\nThe point: matching. The cost of honoring a warranty belongs in the period you made the sale, not years later when the product breaks.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the difference between a defined benefit and defined contribution pension plan and why it matters in valuation.",a:"DB: employer promises a specific retirement benefit and bears investment risk. The funded status (PBO minus plan assets) appears on the BS as a liability if underfunded. DC: employer contributes a fixed amount, employee bears investment risk. No ongoing liability. DB plans create debt-like obligations that should adjust EV.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between operating leverage and financial leverage, and how does each affect earnings volatility?",a:"Operating leverage is the proportion of fixed vs variable costs. High fixed costs mean small revenue changes cause large profit swings. Financial leverage is debt in the capital structure. Interest is fixed, so changes in EBIT are magnified at the NI level. Combined, they determine total earnings volatility.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has $200M of goodwill and performs its annual impairment test. The reporting unit's fair value is $350M and its carrying value including goodwill is $400M. What happens?",a:"The test. Fair value of $350M is below the carrying value of $400M, so the reporting unit is worth less than the books claim. Goodwill is written down by the $50M difference and the remaining goodwill drops to $150M.\n\nIncome statement. A $50M impairment charge, which cuts pre-tax income and net income.\n\nCash flow statement. The charge is non-cash, so it is added straight back. The only cash effect is the tax benefit on the charge.\n\nBalance sheet. Goodwill falls $50M and retained earnings fall by the after-tax hit.\n\nThe point: goodwill impairment is management admitting an acquisition is worth less than they paid. It costs no cash, which is why the market often shrugs at the charge itself and focuses on what it says about the deal.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why do bankers care about the cash conversion cycle, and how do you calculate it?",a:"CCC = DSO + DIO - DPO. It measures how quickly a company converts inventory investments into cash collections. Shorter CCC means less working capital tied up, freeing cash for debt service or growth. Important in LBO and DCF analysis because WC changes directly affect FCF.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain how sale-leaseback transactions work and their financial statement impact.",a:"Company sells an owned asset (e.g., building) and immediately leases it back. Proceeds increase cash. The asset leaves the BS. A right-of-use asset and lease liability appear. The company shifts from depreciation expense to lease expense. It monetizes real estate value while retaining use.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does revenue recognition under ASC 606 work, and why did this standard change how companies report?",a:"ASC 606 uses a 5-step model: identify contract, identify performance obligations, determine transaction price, allocate to obligations, recognize when satisfied. It shifted many companies from point-of-sale to over-time recognition (or vice versa), affecting reported growth rates and working capital.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between basic and diluted EPS, and when do convertible securities get included in the diluted calculation?",a:"Basic EPS = NI / weighted average basic shares. Diluted includes the impact of potentially dilutive securities (options via treasury stock method, convertibles via if-converted). Convertibles are only included if the conversion is dilutive, if adding back interest and adding shares would lower EPS.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company writes down inventory by $30. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through all three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $30 write-down runs through COGS or a separate line, so pre-tax income falls $30. Tax benefit of $7.50 at 25% leaves net income down $22.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $22.50. The write-down moved no cash, so add the $30 back. Cash rises $7.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $7.50 and inventory is down $30, so assets fall $22.50. Retained earnings fall $22.50.\n\nThe point: the company is admitting the goods will not sell for what they cost. The cash already left when the inventory was bought, so all that happens now is the loss gets recognized and the tax bill drops.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you analyze a company's working capital intensity relative to peers, and what metrics do you use?",a:"Compare DSO, DIO, DPO, and NWC as a percentage of revenue across peers. A company with higher DSO may have collection issues or aggressive revenue recognition. High DIO suggests slow-moving inventory. Low DPO might mean less supplier negotiating power. These drive FCF differences.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between treasury stock method and the options exercise approach for calculating diluted shares?",a:"Treasury stock method assumes all in-the-money options are exercised, the company receives the exercise price as proceeds, and uses those proceeds to buy back shares at the current market price. Only the net new shares (shares issued minus shares repurchased) are added to diluted count.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain how intercompany eliminations work in consolidation and why they matter.",a:"When a parent consolidates a subsidiary, all intercompany transactions (sales, receivables, payables, loans) must be eliminated to avoid double-counting. Without elimination, consolidated revenue, assets, and liabilities would be overstated. The process ensures the combined entity reflects only external transactions.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company buys back $100M of its own shares. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. No direct impact. Buying your own stock is a financing decision, not an expense. The only echo is slightly less interest income on the cash that left.\n\nCash flow statement. A $100M outflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $100M and treasury stock rises $100M, which is a contra-equity account, so equity falls $100M. Assets and equity both drop $100M.\n\nThe point: net income does not change but the share count does, so EPS rises. That is mechanical, not value creation. The company is smaller by exactly the cash it spent.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is comprehensive income and how does it differ from net income?",a:"Comprehensive income includes NI plus other comprehensive income (OCI): unrealized gains/losses on available-for-sale securities, foreign currency translation adjustments, pension actuarial gains/losses, and cash flow hedge adjustments. These items bypass the IS and go directly to equity via OCI.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you calculate free cash flow to equity (FCFE) and when would you use it instead of UFCF?",a:"FCFE = NI + D&A - CapEx - Change in WC + Net Borrowings. It represents cash available to equity holders after all obligations. Use FCFE when valuing equity directly (e.g., banks where debt is operational). Use UFCF for most corporate valuations discounted at WACC.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might a football field valuation chart show widely different ranges across methodologies, and what does that tell you?",a:"Wide dispersion suggests high uncertainty about the company's value. Different methodologies emphasize different drivers (cash flow, comparable pricing, deal premiums). It can also indicate the company is difficult to comp, has volatile cash flows, or is in a transitional period. The overlap zone is the most defensible range.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you handle a negative terminal growth rate in a DCF, and when might it be appropriate?",a:"A negative terminal growth rate is appropriate for declining industries (coal, legacy media). The math still works in the Gordon Growth formula as long as WACC exceeds the (negative) growth rate. The terminal value will be lower, reflecting the expectation that the business shrinks over time.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the implied perpetuity growth rate from an exit multiple terminal value, and why should you always calculate it?",a:"Rearrange Gordon Growth: g = WACC - (FCF / TV). If the implied growth rate is above 3-4%, the exit multiple may be too aggressive. If it is negative, the multiple may be conservative. This cross-check ensures your exit multiple and DCF assumptions are internally consistent.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you value a company with significant NOLs (net operating losses), and where does this value show up?",a:"NOLs have value because they reduce future taxes. Value them as PV of expected tax savings (NOL balance × tax rate, discounted at cost of equity). This value shows up as a DTA on the BS. In valuation, you can add the PV of NOL benefits to equity value, but discount for Section 382 limitations in M&A.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a sum-of-the-parts premium or discount, and what causes it?",a:"A conglomerate discount occurs when the combined entity trades below the sum of its parts. Caused by complexity, lack of focus, capital misallocation, or transparency issues. A premium might arise from diversification benefits or unique synergies between segments. The gap is often a catalyst for activist involvement or spin-offs.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the difference between trailing and forward multiples and when each is more appropriate.",a:"Trailing (LTM) multiples use historical data, more reliable but backward-looking. Forward (NTM) multiples use consensus estimates. Reflect market expectations but depend on analyst accuracy. Forward multiples are preferred for growth companies where the past does not reflect the future. Trailing is better for stable businesses.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does the size premium affect WACC estimation for small companies?",a:"Small companies tend to earn higher returns than CAPM predicts. The size premium (often 2-5% for micro-caps) is added to cost of equity. This increases WACC and decreases DCF valuation. It reflects higher risk, less liquidity, and less diversified operations. Data from Duff & Phelps is commonly used.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a leveraged recapitalization analysis and how does it differ from a standard LBO analysis?",a:"A leveraged recap values the company assuming it takes on debt and returns cash to shareholders via a special dividend or buyback, but remains public. Unlike an LBO, there is no change of control or control premium. It shows how much value can be created through capital structure optimization alone.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you handle minority discounts and control premiums in valuation?",a:"Trading comps reflect minority value (no control). Precedent transactions reflect control value (includes premium). If you are valuing for M&A, use precedent multiples or add a control premium (20-40%) to trading comps. For a minority stake, discount from control value by 15-30%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is EV/Revenue sometimes the only usable multiple, and what are its limitations?",a:"For companies with negative EBITDA/EBIT/NI, revenue is the only positive metric. Used for early-stage tech, biotech, and high-growth companies. Limitations: ignores profitability differences entirely, so a company burning cash at 50% margins looks the same as one at 5% margins. Always pair with growth and margin analysis.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you value a subscription-based SaaS business differently from a traditional business?",a:"Key metrics: ARR growth, NRR, churn, LTV/CAC, Rule of 40. Use EV/Revenue or EV/ARR multiples. In a DCF, model subscription cohorts separately, account for expansion revenue, and project margin expansion toward steady-state. Recurring revenue warrants higher multiples due to predictability.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you adjust for differences in capital structure when comparing EV/EBITDA multiples across peers?",a:"EV/EBITDA is already capital-structure neutral by design. EV captures all capital providers and EBITDA is pre-interest. However, companies with significantly different lease structures, pension obligations, or off-balance sheet items may need further EV adjustments for true comparability.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is an asset-based valuation and when is it most appropriate?",a:"Value a company based on the fair value of its assets minus liabilities. Most useful for asset-heavy businesses (real estate, natural resources), holding companies, liquidation scenarios, or companies with negative earnings where cash flow methods fail. Often sets a floor valuation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you build a sensitivity table for a DCF, and what variables should you sensitize?",a:"Create a data table with two variables (e.g., WACC vs terminal growth rate, or revenue growth vs EBIT margin). Show the resulting equity value per share in each cell. Key sensitivities: WACC (8-12%), terminal growth (1-3%), exit multiple (6-10x), and revenue CAGR. Present the range to stakeholders.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a company's implied valuation from a DCF differ significantly from where it actually trades?",a:"DCF relies on subjective assumptions (growth, margins, WACC) that may differ from market consensus. The market also prices in sentiment, liquidity, technical factors, and information the analyst may not have. Significant deviation should trigger a review of assumptions, not an automatic conclusion that the market is wrong.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you value a company going through a turnaround where current financials are distressed?",a:"Use normalized or forward multiples based on projected post-turnaround performance. A DCF modeling the recovery path (margin expansion, revenue stabilization) with higher discount rates to reflect risk. Comparable transaction multiples from similar turnaround acquisitions. Never value a turnaround on trailing metrics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk through how you would calculate the IRR in a paper LBO without a calculator.",a:"Memorize approximations: 2x in 3 years is roughly 26% IRR, 2x in 5 years is roughly 15%, 3x in 5 years is roughly 25%, 2.5x in 4 years is roughly 26%. For a paper LBO, calculate exit equity, divide by entry equity to get MOIC, then use the approximation table based on holding period.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between mandatory and optional debt repayment in an LBO model?",a:"Mandatory: scheduled amortization required by the credit agreement (e.g., 1% annual on TLB, 5-10% on TLA). Optional: excess FCF after all obligations used to prepay debt (cash sweep). Optional paydown accelerates deleveraging and improves returns. The order follows the debt waterfall. Cheapest debt first or sweep provisions.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a cash flow sweep work in an LBO, and why do lenders require it?",a:"A cash sweep requires the borrower to use a percentage (typically 50-75%) of excess cash flow to repay debt. Excess CF = CFO minus CapEx, mandatory amort, taxes, and working capital. Lenders require it to accelerate deleveraging, reducing credit risk. The sweep percentage often steps down as leverage decreases.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a sponsor choose to use a holding company structure for an LBO?",a:"Tax efficiency (interest deductibility at HoldCo level), structural flexibility (easier to add/remove assets), liability containment (OpCo issues stay at OpCo), and easier dividend distributions. However, HoldCo debt is structurally subordinated to OpCo debt since HoldCo only receives what flows up from OpCo.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a credit agreement, and what are the key sections a PE associate should understand?",a:"The credit agreement governs the loan: definitions (EBITDA calculations, permitted add-backs), covenants (leverage ratio, coverage tests), events of default (what triggers acceleration), permitted actions (dividends, acquisitions, additional debt), and pricing terms (spread, LIBOR/SOFR floor, OID). Understanding the flex provisions is critical for the financing.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you model a revolver in an LBO and why is it treated differently from term loans?",a:"The revolver is a committed but typically undrawn facility. It is a source of liquidity, not initial financing. In the model, if operating cash flow is insufficient in a given period, the revolver is drawn. When cash flow recovers, it is repaid first. Model a commitment fee on the undrawn portion (typically 25-50 bps).",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a debt-to-equity swap in a distressed LBO context, and why does it happen?",a:"When a company cannot service its debt, creditors may convert their debt claims into equity ownership, effectively taking control. This reduces the debt burden, avoids formal bankruptcy, and gives creditors upside in the restructured entity. Existing equity is usually wiped out or heavily diluted.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does the debt paydown schedule affect the sensitivity of IRR to exit multiple?",a:"If most debt is repaid by exit, equity value is close to EV regardless of multiple. Returns depend mainly on EBITDA growth. If significant debt remains, even small multiple changes have large equity impacts. Higher remaining debt at exit means returns are more sensitive to exit multiple assumptions.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between a gross and net leverage ratio, and why does it matter in credit analysis?",a:"Gross leverage = Total Debt / EBITDA. Net leverage = (Total Debt - Cash) / EBITDA. Net leverage gives credit for cash on hand. For companies with significant cash balances, gross leverage overstates credit risk. Lenders typically focus on net leverage for covenant testing but may use gross for initial sizing.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you model add-on acquisitions in an LBO, and why are they a key part of the value creation thesis?",a:"Model the add-on as a separate investment: additional equity and/or debt required, incremental EBITDA, integration costs, and timing. Add-ons create value through multiple arbitrage (buying small companies at lower multiples than the platform trades at), revenue synergies, geographic expansion, and capability additions.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the concept of 'ability to pay' in an LBO, and how do you calculate it?",a:"The maximum price a sponsor can pay while achieving minimum return targets (typically 20%+ IRR). Work backwards: given target IRR, holding period, exit assumptions, and financing terms, solve for the maximum entry EV. This sets the ceiling for the sponsor's bid in an auction.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does working capital seasonality affect LBO modeling and debt sizing?",a:"Seasonal WC swings create periods where cash is consumed (e.g., inventory build before holiday season) and periods where cash is released. The revolver must be sized to cover peak WC needs. Failing to account for seasonality can lead to liquidity shortfalls. Model WC quarterly if seasonality is significant.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is structural subordination in an LBO capital structure?",a:"Debt at a parent/holding company level is structurally subordinated to debt at the operating company level because the parent only receives cash after OpCo satisfies all its obligations. In bankruptcy, OpCo creditors have first claim on OpCo assets. HoldCo creditors only get what is left after OpCo debts are paid.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might a sponsor accept a lower IRR on a large-cap buyout versus a mid-market deal?",a:"Large-cap deals offer larger absolute dollar returns despite lower IRRs, which matters for GP economics (management fees and carry on larger fund sizes). They also tend to have lower risk (more stable businesses), better access to capital markets, and more predictable exit paths. Mid-market offers higher IRRs but smaller absolute gains.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you stress-test an LBO model for a recession scenario?",a:"Model 15-25% revenue decline over 2 years, margin compression of 200-400bps, WC deterioration, delayed CapEx cuts, and assume no voluntary debt repayment. Check if the company can still cover interest (coverage ratio > 1.5x), maintain covenant compliance, and avoid drawing the full revolver. The model should survive without breaching covenants.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a reverse merger and why might a company choose it over a traditional IPO?",a:"A private company acquires a public shell company, effectively becoming public without the IPO process. Advantages: faster, cheaper, avoids roadshow and SEC review delays. Disadvantages: less capital raised, negative stigma, potential shell company liabilities. Less common now due to SPACs and direct listings offering alternatives.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you analyze whether a company should be a buyer or a seller in the current market environment?",a:"Buyers are favored when: their stock is highly valued (currency for deals), interest rates are low (cheap financing), and targets are available at reasonable prices. Sellers are favored when: multiples are at cycle highs, the business is at peak performance, or strategic alternatives are limited. The same environment can favor both depending on relative positioning.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a material adverse change (MAC) clause, and why was it tested during COVID?",a:"A MAC clause allows the buyer to walk away if the target experiences a material deterioration between signing and closing. During COVID, several buyers attempted to invoke MAC clauses due to pandemic-related declines. Courts generally ruled that pandemics were not MACs because they affected entire industries, not specific targets. This reinforced that MACs require company-specific, durable harm.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you model the impact of purchase accounting adjustments on pro forma earnings?",a:"Step up target assets to fair value, creating new D&A charges. Write up intangibles (customer relationships, technology, brand) that amortize over 5-20 years, reducing pro forma NI. Create DTLs on step-ups. Goodwill is the residual. These adjustments are non-cash but affect reported EPS and accretion/dilution analysis.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a collar in an M&A transaction, and when is it used?",a:"A collar sets a price range for stock consideration, if the buyer's stock price falls below the floor, the exchange ratio adjusts to protect the target; above the cap, the ratio adjusts to protect the buyer. Used in stock-for-stock deals to reduce risk of price fluctuations between announcement and closing. Provides certainty to both sides.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the difference between a tender offer and a merger vote, and when each is used.",a:"Tender offer: buyer goes directly to target shareholders, who individually decide whether to sell their shares. Faster (20 business days minimum). Merger vote: requires board approval and shareholder majority. Takes longer but is standard for friendly deals. Tender offers are common in hostile situations or when speed matters.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a contribution analysis in M&A, and how does it inform the exchange ratio in a merger of equals?",a:"Contribution analysis compares what percentage each party contributes to the combined entity across metrics: revenue, EBITDA, NI, assets. If Company A contributes 60% of EBITDA and Company B contributes 40%, the ownership split should approximate 60/40 for it to be 'fair.' The exchange ratio translates this into share terms.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does the tax structure of a deal (taxable vs tax-free) affect the buyer and seller differently?",a:"Tax-free (stock-for-stock 368 reorganization): target shareholders defer capital gains tax but buyer cannot step up asset basis. Taxable (cash or taxable stock): target shareholders pay capital gains tax immediately but buyer can step up asset basis, creating future tax deductions (D&A shield). The trade-off affects pricing negotiation.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a break-up fee and how is it typically sized?",a:"A break-up fee (termination fee) is paid by the target to the buyer if the deal is terminated under certain conditions (board changes recommendation, accepts superior proposal). Typically 2-4% of deal equity value. It compensates the buyer for time and expense invested. Too high a fee can deter competing bids and face legal challenges.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you analyze the financing of a cash acquisition. Debt vs equity vs cash on hand?",a:"Model three sources: existing cash (loses interest income), new debt (new interest expense, commitment fees), and new equity (dilution from shares issued). Each has a different cost. Optimal mix minimizes blended cost while maintaining investment-grade credit metrics. Run the accretion/dilution under each scenario.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a credit spread, and what causes spreads to widen or tighten?",a:"Credit spread = corporate bond yield minus risk-free rate (Treasury). Represents the premium for default risk. Widens during economic stress (flight to quality, higher default expectations, reduced liquidity). Tightens during economic expansion (confidence, low defaults, strong demand for yield). Watched closely as a leading indicator.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the relationship between bond prices and interest rates, and why it matters for portfolio valuation.",a:"Bond prices and interest rates move inversely. When rates rise, existing bonds with lower coupons become less attractive, so their prices fall. Longer-duration bonds are more sensitive to rate changes. This matters because large rate moves can significantly impact the value of fixed-income portfolios and pension plan assets.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the VIX and what does it actually measure?",a:"VIX measures implied volatility from S&P 500 options prices. Essentially the market's expectation of 30-day volatility. A high VIX (>30) signals fear and uncertainty. A low VIX (<15) signals complacency. It is often called the 'fear index.' It does not predict direction. Only the magnitude of expected moves.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do stock buybacks affect EPS, valuation multiples, and the balance sheet?",a:"EPS. Net income is unchanged and the share count falls, so EPS rises. This is arithmetic, not performance.\n\nValuation multiples. The P/E looks lower because the denominator grew, but equity value fell too, since the cash left the business. Enterprise value is roughly unchanged: cash went down and so did the market cap.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash falls, treasury stock rises, and total equity falls. Leverage rises, because the same debt now sits against a smaller equity base.\n\nThe point: a buyback creates value only if the shares are bought below intrinsic value. Above it, management is destroying value while reporting higher EPS, which is exactly why EPS accretion is a bad test of whether a buyback was smart.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is duration in bond investing, and why does it matter for equity investors too?",a:"Duration measures a bond's price sensitivity to interest rate changes. A 5-year duration means a 1% rate increase causes roughly a 5% price decline. For equity investors, growth stocks with cash flows far in the future behave like long-duration assets. They are more sensitive to discount rate changes than value stocks.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain how the Federal Reserve's balance sheet operations (QE/QT) affect asset prices beyond just interest rates.",a:"QE: Fed buys Treasuries/MBS, injecting reserves into banks, compressing term premium, pushing investors into riskier assets (portfolio rebalancing effect), lowering volatility, and expanding liquidity. QT reverses this: drains liquidity, widens spreads, increases volatility, and creates selling pressure. The balance sheet size is a measure of monetary accommodation.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a leveraged loan, and how does the leveraged loan market differ from the high-yield bond market?",a:"Leveraged loans are floating-rate, senior secured bank debt used primarily in LBOs and leveraged companies. Key differences from HY bonds: loans are secured (bonds often unsecured), floating rate (bonds are fixed), prepayable without penalty (bonds have call protection), and traded in a separate market with different investors (CLOs vs mutual funds).",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do CLOs work and why are they important for PE-backed companies?",a:"Collateralized Loan Obligations pool leveraged loans and issue tranches of securities with different risk/return profiles. CLOs are the largest buyers of leveraged loans (~65% of the market), so their demand directly affects loan pricing and availability. When CLO formation slows, leveraged loan capacity tightens, affecting LBO financing.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What happened to SVB (Silicon Valley Bank) in 2023 and what does it illustrate about interest rate risk?",a:"SVB held large unrealized losses on long-duration Treasury and MBS portfolios as rates rose rapidly. When depositors (concentrated tech/VC clients) withdrew funds, SVB had to sell securities at losses, triggering a bank run. It illustrates how duration mismatch between assets and liabilities can create solvency crises even without credit losses.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between investment-grade and high-yield credit, and where is the dividing line?",a:"Investment grade: BBB- or higher (S&P) / Baa3 or higher (Moody's). High yield: BB+ and below. The divide is significant because many institutional investors (pensions, insurance companies) have mandates restricting them to IG. A downgrade from IG to HY ('fallen angel') forces selling, causing price dislocation. IG spreads are typically 50-200 bps; HY spreads are 300-800+ bps.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between levered and unlevered beta, and why do you unlever peer betas before relevering?",a:"Levered beta reflects both business risk and financial risk (debt amplifies equity volatility). To compare pure business risk across peers with different capital structures, you unlever each peer's beta using Hamada's equation. Then you relever at the target company's capital structure to get the appropriate beta for its specific leverage.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you determine the appropriate risk-free rate for a DCF, and does it matter whether you use the 10-year or 30-year Treasury?",a:"Use the 10-year Treasury yield for most corporate DCFs because it approximates the duration of projected cash flows (5-10 year explicit forecast). The 30-year may be more appropriate for very long-duration assets like infrastructure or real estate. Consistency matters. The risk-free rate in CAPM should match the ERP benchmark.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the equity risk premium, where does it come from, and how sensitive is the DCF to different ERP assumptions?",a:"ERP is the excess return equity investors demand over the risk-free rate. Sources: historical realized premium (Ibbotson: ~5-7%), survey-based (Fernandez: ~5-6%), or implied from current market prices (Damodaran: varies). A 1% change in ERP can swing DCF value by 10-15%. Always disclose your ERP assumption.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you handle a company with negative free cash flow in the explicit forecast period of a DCF?",a:"Negative FCF in early years is common for high-growth or turnaround companies. Project the path to positive FCF. Show margin expansion, revenue scaling, or CapEx normalization. Discount the negative cash flows normally. The terminal value will carry most of the valuation. Ensure the terminal year reflects sustainable positive FCF.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a stub period in a DCF and how do you handle it?",a:"A stub period is the partial year between the valuation date and the first full fiscal year end. Discount the stub period cash flows using a fractional discount factor (e.g., if 8 months remain, the discount factor exponent is 8/12). This ensures you are not over- or under-counting the first year of cash flows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does the terminal value calculation change if you assume the company will be acquired rather than operating in perpetuity?",a:"Instead of Gordon Growth, use an exit multiple on terminal year EBITDA based on precedent transaction multiples (which include control premiums). This is conceptually different. You are modeling a sale, not perpetual operation. The implied perpetuity growth rate from this exit multiple may be higher than what standalone operations would justify.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is one deal in the news right now, and what do you think about the strategic rationale?",a:"You MUST have a current deal ready. Know: buyer, target, price, multiple, strategic rationale, financing, regulatory concerns, and your view on whether the price was fair. Show you follow markets actively, not just for interview prep.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you had to pick between investment banking and private equity right now, which would you choose and why?",a:"Trick question. If interviewing for IB, emphasize that you want the foundational training, deal exposure, and analytical skills IB provides. Acknowledge PE is interesting but frame IB as the right next step. Never say you are using banking purely as a stepping stone, even if you are.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is one thing about investment banking that concerns you, and how would you handle it?",a:"Show self-awareness: the hours, the lifestyle trade-offs, or the steep learning curve. Then show how you have prepared or why you believe you can handle it. Reference specific experiences where you thrived under similar pressure. Never say nothing concerns you. That signals you have not thought about it seriously.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you stay organized when managing multiple complex workstreams simultaneously?",a:"Be specific about your system: priority matrix, daily to-do lists, time-blocking, communication protocols for flagging delays. Banking analysts manage 2-3 live deals plus pitches. The best answer references a specific time you managed competing priorities and how your system prevented things from falling through cracks.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you had to deliver bad news to someone. How did you handle it?",a:"Show directness with empathy. Explain: what the bad news was, how you prepared to deliver it, what you said, and how the person responded. The best answers show you did not avoid the conversation, you were honest without being harsh, and you followed up with a path forward. Banking requires delivering hard truths to clients.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What would you do in your first week as an analyst to set yourself up for success?",a:"Listen more than you talk. Learn the team's workflow, tools, and preferences. Understand the active deal pipeline. Build relationships with other analysts (they will teach you more than anyone). Ask smart questions that show you prepared. Offer to help on anything, even mundane tasks. First impressions are permanent in banking.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you were staffed on a deal and noticed a material error in a presentation that was about to go to a client, what would you do?",a:"Flag it immediately to the associate or VP, even if it means the deliverable is delayed. Propose a fix and timeline. Never let an error reach the client. Banking is a zero-defect culture for client-facing materials. The temporary discomfort of flagging an error is far better than the permanent damage of a mistake reaching a client.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me through a company or industry you find interesting and why.",a:"Pick something you genuinely know and care about. Structure: what the company/industry does, why it is interesting to you specifically, what the key financial drivers are, and one investment thesis or trend you see playing out. Show you can think like an investor, not just a student who read a textbook.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you build trust with people quickly in a professional setting?",a:"Competence first. Deliver quality work on time. Then: follow through on commitments, communicate proactively (especially bad news), ask good questions that show you prepared, and be reliable when things get difficult. Trust in banking is built deal by deal, deliverable by deliverable. It cannot be faked or accelerated.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the biggest misconception people have about investment banking?",a:"Many think it is just about working long hours and building models. The reality is that banking is a client service business. Relationship management, communication, and the ability to synthesize complex information into clear recommendations are as important as technical skills. The best bankers are advisors, not just spreadsheet jockeys.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you model revenue for a company with a subscription-based business model versus a transactional one?",a:"Subscription: model by cohort, existing ARR × (1 + NRR) + new ARR from new customer additions. Account for churn, upsell, and downsell separately. Transactional: model by volume × price, segmented by product/geography. Subscription models are more predictable but require understanding of retention dynamics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a contribution margin analysis and why is it important in modeling a company with multiple product lines?",a:"Contribution margin = revenue minus variable costs for each product/segment. It shows which products actually contribute to covering fixed costs and generating profit. A company with high aggregate margins might have one profitable segment subsidizing unprofitable ones. This analysis informs valuation (segment-level multiples) and strategic decisions (divesting underperformers).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you model a spin-off in a merger model or valuation context?",a:"Value the parent and spin-off separately using appropriate peer sets and multiples for each. Project standalone financials for the spin-off (may need to allocate shared costs). Model one-time separation costs. The thesis is usually that the sum of parts exceeds the combined whole due to reduced conglomerate discount and improved management focus.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between a mandatory convertible and a traditional convertible bond?",a:"Traditional convertibles are optional. Holders choose whether to convert to equity. They have lower coupons than straight debt because of this optionality. Mandatory convertibles automatically convert at maturity at a predetermined ratio. They are economically closer to equity (dilution is certain) but structured as debt for accounting/tax purposes.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does the healthcare sector's valuation differ from technology, and what sector-specific metrics matter?",a:"Healthcare uses EV/EBITDA but also pipeline-adjusted metrics (rNPV for pharma), EV/bed (hospitals), membership multiples (managed care), and revenue per script (pharmacy). Patent cliffs, regulatory risk (FDA approvals), and reimbursement rates create unique valuation challenges. Technology uses EV/Revenue, ARR multiples, and growth-adjusted metrics (Rule of 40).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a dividend discount model and when is it appropriate to use?",a:"DDM values equity as the PV of expected future dividends. Most appropriate for mature, stable companies with consistent dividend policies (banks, utilities, REITs). Formula: Price = D1 / (Ke - g). Less useful for growth companies that reinvest rather than distribute. A two-stage DDM models high growth transitioning to stable growth.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you model a restructuring in a financial model, and what are the key assumptions?",a:"Model the reorganization plan: which claims are impaired, recovery rates for each class, DIP financing terms, emergence capital structure, and post-emergence operating projections. Key assumptions: enterprise value at emergence, administrative costs, priority of claims, and timeline. The fulcrum security analysis identifies where value breaks.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the role of the investment banking analyst on a live M&A transaction from start to finish?",a:"Analyst is the workhorse: build the merger model, run comps and precedents, create the CIM or buyer presentation, prepare management presentations, coordinate the data room, track buyer feedback, support due diligence requests, prepare board materials, and assist with fairness opinion analysis. You touch every workstream.",category:"Behavioral",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you bridge from enterprise value to equity value per share, and what are common adjustments that people miss?",a:"EV - net debt - preferred stock - NCI + equity investments = equity value. Divide by diluted shares. Commonly missed: unfunded pension obligations, capitalized operating leases (if added to EV), non-operating assets (excess land, investments), litigation reserves, and tax assets/liabilities. Each adjustment should be consistent with your EV calculation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a PIPE (Private Investment in Public Equity) and when is it used?",a:"A PIPE is a private placement of stock (or convertible securities) in an already-public company. Used when the company needs capital quickly without the time/expense of a secondary offering. Common in SPAC transactions, distressed situations, and growth financings. Investors typically get a discount to market price and sometimes warrants.",category:"Capital Markets",difficulty:"Intermediate"},

// ═══ CORE INTERVIEW QUESTIONS - 3-STATEMENT, MATH, CONCEPTUAL ═══
{q:"Accounts receivable increases by $50 with no other changes. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The revenue was already recognized when the sale was made. This is only about collection.\n\nCash flow statement. Receivables rising is a use of cash in working capital, so cash falls $50.\n\nBalance sheet. Receivables are up $50 and cash is down $50. Total assets are unchanged.\n\nThe point: this is a swap of one asset for another. The company has booked the profit and is waiting to be paid, which is why growing receivables faster than revenue is one of the first signs of either weak collections or aggressive revenue recognition.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Accounts payable increases by $40 with no other changes. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The expense was already recognized when the goods or services were received.\n\nCash flow statement. Payables rising is a source of cash, because you have the goods and have not paid for them yet. Cash rises $40.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $40 and accounts payable are up $40. Assets and liabilities both rise $40, and equity does not move.\n\nThe point: stretching payables is effectively an interest-free loan from your suppliers. It flatters operating cash flow, but only once, and only until the suppliers push back.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company receives $100 in cash from a customer for a service to be delivered next year. Walk through the statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The company has been paid but has not delivered anything, so nothing has been earned.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash rises $100, shown as an increase in deferred revenue within operating.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $100 and deferred revenue, a liability, is up $100. It is a liability because the company owes the customer a service.\n\nThe point: this is the healthiest cash a business can take in, money before delivery. It is also why deferred revenue is watched so closely at subscription companies: it is a forward look at revenue that is already contracted and paid for.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company pays $80 cash to prepay insurance for the next 2 years. Walk through the statements at payment.",a:"Income statement. Nothing yet. Paying early does not consume any coverage.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash falls $80 in operating.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $80 and a prepaid insurance asset of $80 appears. Total assets are unchanged. It is an asset because the company is owed two years of coverage.\n\nThe point: over the next two years, $40 a year moves from the prepaid asset onto the income statement as expense, with no further cash moving. The expense follows the coverage, not the payment.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Revenue increases by $100, all collected in cash. COGS is $60. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through all three statements.",a:"Income statement. Revenue is up $100 and COGS is up $60, so gross profit is $40. Tax of $10 at 25% leaves net income up $30.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $30. The customer paid cash, so receivables do not move, and the inventory effect is already in COGS. Cash rises $30.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $30 and retained earnings are up $30. Both sides rise $30.\n\nThe point: this is the clean case. When a sale is collected immediately, profit and cash are the same number. Compare it with the credit sale version, where they are not.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Revenue increases by $100 but the customer pays on credit. COGS is $60. Tax rate 25%. Walk through all three.",a:"Income statement. Identical to the cash sale. Revenue up $100, COGS up $60, gross profit $40, tax $10, net income up $30. The income statement does not care whether you were paid.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $30. Receivables rise $100, a use of cash. Inventory falls $60, a source of cash. Net cash is down $10.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $10, receivables are up $100, inventory is down $60, so assets rise $30. Retained earnings are up $30.\n\nThe point: the company just booked its most profitable sale of the period and its cash went down. Profitable companies go bankrupt exactly this way, by growing on credit faster than they collect.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company issues $500 of bonds at par. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing today. Borrowing is not income.\n\nCash flow statement. A $500 inflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $500 and long-term debt is up $500. Assets and liabilities both rise $500, and equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the income statement stays clean on day one. The cost shows up every period after this as interest expense. Issuing at par simply means the coupon matched the market rate, so there is no premium or discount to amortize.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company repays $200 of debt principal using cash. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Repaying principal is returning borrowed money, not an expense. Only the interest portion of a debt payment ever touches the income statement.\n\nCash flow statement. A $200 outflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $200 and debt is down $200. Assets and liabilities both fall $200, and equity does not move.\n\nThe point: this is the single most common beginner error, running principal through the income statement. If principal were an expense, borrowing would have to be income, and it is not.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company declares and pays a $30 cash dividend. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. A dividend is a distribution of profit that was already earned and already taxed, not a cost of doing business.\n\nCash flow statement. A $30 outflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $30 and retained earnings are down $30. Assets and equity both fall $30.\n\nThe point: dividends skip the income statement entirely and hit equity directly. That is the structural difference between paying your lenders, which is an expense, and paying your owners, which is not.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"SG&A increases by $20 due to higher salaries paid in cash. Tax rate 25%. Walk through all three statements.",a:"Income statement. SG&A rises $20, so pre-tax income falls $20. Tax falls $5 at 25%, leaving net income down $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $15. Salaries were paid in cash and there is nothing non-cash to add back, so cash falls $15.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $15 and retained earnings are down $15.\n\nThe point: cash falls $15, not $20, because the tax authority absorbs a quarter of any deductible expense. Contrast this with depreciation, where net income falls but cash actually rises.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company purchases $300 of equipment using $100 cash and $200 of new debt. Walk through the statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing at close. Buying an asset and borrowing are not income statement events.\n\nCash flow statement. CapEx of $300 is an outflow in investing and the $200 debt raise is an inflow in financing, so net cash falls $100, which is the equity the company put in.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E is up $300, cash is down $100, so assets rise $200. Debt is up $200. Equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the full $300 of CapEx shows in investing even though only $100 of the company's own cash left. Depreciation and interest start hitting next period.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Interest expense is $25 paid in cash. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Interest of $25 cuts pre-tax income $25. Tax falls $6.25 at 25%, so net income falls $18.75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $18.75. Interest was paid in cash and there is nothing to add back, so cash falls $18.75.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $18.75 and retained earnings are down $18.75.\n\nThe point: the company wrote a $25 cheque but is only $18.75 poorer, because the interest was deductible and the tax bill dropped $6.25. That $6.25 is the interest tax shield, and it is the entire reason debt is cheaper than equity and the reason a levered DCF discounts at a lower rate.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A customer returns $40 of product. The original COGS was $25. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the statements assuming a cash refund.",a:"Income statement. Revenue falls $40 and COGS falls $25 as the goods come back into inventory, so gross profit falls $15. Tax falls $3.75 at 25%, leaving net income down $11.25.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $11.25. Inventory rises $25 as the product returns to the shelf, which is a use of cash, so subtract $25. Net cash falls $36.25.\n\nBalance sheet. The company refunded $40 and saved $3.75 of tax, so cash falls $36.25. Inventory is up $25, so assets fall $11.25. Retained earnings fall $11.25 and it balances.\n\nThe point: the cash going out ($36.25) is much larger than the profit hit ($11.25), because you hand back the full price while only the margin was ever profit. The rest comes back as inventory you now have to sell again.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company collects $70 of accounts receivable. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The revenue was recognized when the sale happened. Collecting is not a second revenue event.\n\nCash flow statement. Receivables falling is a source of cash, so cash rises $70.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $70 and receivables are down $70. Total assets are unchanged.\n\nThe point: a pure swap of one current asset for a better one. This is the mirror image of the sale on credit, where profit was booked and cash was not.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company writes off $20 of uncollectible accounts receivable that was already reserved in the allowance. Walk through the statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The expense was already taken when the allowance was created, which is the whole purpose of reserving in advance.\n\nCash flow statement. No cash impact. Nothing moved.\n\nBalance sheet. Gross receivables fall $20 and the allowance falls $20, so net receivables are unchanged.\n\nThe point: this is housekeeping. The loss was recognized the day the company estimated it, and this entry only removes the specific dead account from the books. If writing off a bad debt hit earnings, the company would be taking the same loss twice.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company records $15 of bad debt expense (creating a new allowance). Tax rate 25%. Walk through the statements.",a:"Income statement. Bad debt expense of $15 cuts pre-tax income $15. Tax falls $3.75, leaving net income down $11.25.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $11.25. The reserve is an estimate, not a payment, so add the $15 back. Cash rises $3.75 from the tax saving.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $3.75, the allowance rises so net receivables fall $15, and retained earnings fall $11.25.\n\nThe point: the company is predicting that some customers will not pay and taking the hit now. Because the allowance is management's estimate, it is a well-known lever for smoothing earnings, which is why analysts track it against receivables.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Amortization of an intangible asset is $10. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Amortization of $10 cuts pre-tax income $10. Tax falls $2.50, leaving net income down $7.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $7.50. Amortization is non-cash, so add the full $10 back. Cash rises $2.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $2.50 and the intangible is down $10, so assets fall $7.50. Retained earnings fall $7.50.\n\nThe point: mechanically identical to depreciation, just applied to an intangible such as a patent or customer list instead of a machine. The asset falls by the full charge while cash rises by the tax shield.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company converts $50 of debt into equity (debt-to-equity swap). Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. If the equity handed over is worth the same as the debt cancelled, nothing happens. If the shares are worth less than the debt, the company books a gain on extinguishment, and if worth more, a loss.\n\nCash flow statement. Nothing. No cash changes hands, so it appears only as a non-cash disclosure.\n\nBalance sheet. Debt falls $50 and equity rises $50. Total assets do not move.\n\nThe point: this is the core move in a restructuring. Creditors become owners, leverage drops overnight, and the company survives without spending a dollar. The old shareholders pay for it through dilution.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"An asset with book value of $80 (cost $120, accumulated depreciation $40) is sold for $100. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the statements.",a:"Income statement. Book value is $80 (cost $120 less $40 of accumulated depreciation) and the asset sold for $100, so the gain is $20. Tax of $5 leaves net income up $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $15. Subtract the $20 gain out of operating, because the whole $100 is about to be counted in investing and you would otherwise double count it. Then add the $100 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $95.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $95 and net PP&E is down $80, so assets rise $15. Retained earnings are up $15.\n\nThe point: the gain is only the amount above book value. The company collects $100 but keeps $95 after the $5 of tax on the gain.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Stock-based compensation of $30 is recorded. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $30 of stock-based compensation is an operating expense, so pre-tax income falls $30. Tax falls $7.50, leaving net income down $22.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $22.50. The company paid in shares, not cash, so add the $30 back. Cash rises $7.50 from the tax saving.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $7.50, APIC is up $30, and retained earnings are down $22.50, so equity nets up $7.50. The diluted share count rises.\n\nThe point: cash went up and the business is no better off. The cost was paid in ownership rather than money, which is why treating SBC as free is one of the most common valuation mistakes.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company capitalizes $50 of software development costs instead of expensing them. How do the statements differ versus expensing?",a:"If they capitalize. No expense hits the income statement now, so net income is $50 higher. A $50 intangible appears on the balance sheet. The cash still leaves, but it is classified as investing rather than operating, so operating cash flow looks stronger. That $50 then amortizes over future years, creating expense later.\n\nIf they expense. Net income takes the full $50 hit now, cash flows out through operating, and there is no future amortization to carry.\n\nThe point: identical cash, in the same amount, at the same time. All capitalizing does is move the cost from today to later and from operating to investing. That is why software capitalization policy is a red flag worth checking: it can manufacture both earnings growth and operating cash flow without anything real changing.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"COGS increases by $30 due to rising raw material prices. All inventory was purchased on credit. Tax rate 25%.",a:"Income statement. COGS rises $30, so gross profit falls $30. Tax falls $7.50, leaving net income down $22.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $22.50. The materials were bought on credit, so payables rose $30 and no cash has left yet. Add $30 back. Cash actually rises $7.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $7.50, payables are up $30, and retained earnings are down $22.50. Assets rise $7.50, and liabilities plus equity also rise $7.50.\n\nThe point: the company just got less profitable and its cash went up, purely because it has not paid the supplier yet. The $7.50 is the tax saving. The real cash pain arrives when the payable is settled.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company receives a tax refund of $40. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $40 refund reduces tax expense, so net income rises $40. If it relates to a prior period it usually shows up as a discrete tax item rather than in the normal effective rate.\n\nCash flow statement. A $40 operating inflow.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $40. If the company had already booked a receivable for it, that receivable clears and equity does not move. If it was unexpected, retained earnings rise $40.\n\nThe point: whether it touches the income statement depends entirely on whether the company already anticipated it. If they accrued it, the earnings were taken earlier and this is just collection.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Deferred revenue decreases by $60 as services are delivered. Walk through the three statements. Tax rate 25%.",a:"Income statement. The service has now been delivered, so $60 of revenue is finally recognized. Tax of $15 leaves net income up $45.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $45. Deferred revenue fell $60, and a falling liability is a use of cash, so subtract $60. Net cash falls $15, which is the tax now owed.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $15, deferred revenue is down $60, and retained earnings are up $45.\n\nThe point: the cash arrived in an earlier period, when the customer paid. This period the company records the profit and pays the tax on it, so recognizing revenue actually costs cash. It is the reverse of the usual intuition.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company records a $100 restructuring charge for employee severance. $60 is paid now, $40 to be paid next year. Tax rate 25%.",a:"Income statement. The full $100 charge is taken now, because the obligation exists as soon as the plan is announced, regardless of when people are paid. Tax falls $25, leaving net income down $75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $75. Only $60 was actually paid, so the $40 still accrued is added back as non-cash. Net cash falls $35, which reconciles: $60 paid out less $25 of tax saved.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $35, a $40 restructuring liability sits on the books for next year, and retained earnings are down $75. Assets fall $35, and liabilities plus equity fall $35 too.\n\nThe point: the earnings hit and the cash hit are different sizes and land in different years. The income statement takes all $100 today, while $40 of the cash does not leave until next year.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why is cash not included in enterprise value?",a:"Cash is a non-operating asset. An acquirer gets the target's cash, effectively reducing the net purchase price of the operations. If you included cash in EV, you would be double-counting. Paying for the cash and then receiving it. EV measures the value of the operations, not the balance sheet.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is debt included in enterprise value?",a:"When you buy a company, you assume its debt obligations. The equity holders get paid the equity value, but the debt holders still need to be repaid. EV represents the total cost to acquire and own the entire business. You need to pay the equity holders AND deal with the debt.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do we add back depreciation in a DCF but then subtract capital expenditures?",a:"D&A is a non-cash expense that reduced net income but did not use cash, so we add it back to get actual cash flow. CapEx is a cash outflow that does not appear on the income statement, so we subtract it. Together, the net effect captures the true cash cost of maintaining and growing the asset base.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does a higher discount rate decrease the present value of future cash flows?",a:"A higher discount rate means investors require a higher return to compensate for risk. This makes future cash flows worth less today because you need a bigger discount to justify waiting. Mathematically, PV = CF / (1+r)^n. As r increases, the denominator grows and PV shrinks.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might EBITDA be a misleading measure of cash flow?",a:"EBITDA ignores: (1) capital expenditures required to maintain the business, (2) working capital changes that consume or release cash, (3) taxes actually paid, and (4) interest payments. A company with high EBITDA but massive CapEx requirements generates far less actual cash than EBITDA implies.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is EBIT sometimes better than EBITDA for comparing capital-intensive businesses?",a:"In capital-intensive industries (manufacturing, utilities, telecom), D&A represents a real ongoing cost of replacing worn-out assets. Ignoring it via EBITDA overstates the cash available to investors. EBIT captures this cost, making it a better proxy for sustainable operating profitability in these sectors.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do two companies with identical EBITDA trade at different multiples?",a:"Growth rates (higher growth = higher multiple), margins and margin trajectory, capital intensity (lower CapEx = higher FCF conversion), revenue quality (recurring vs one-time), end market risk, management quality, competitive moat, geographic exposure, and customer concentration all affect how investors price each dollar of EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might you use EV/EBITDA instead of P/E when comparing companies?",a:"P/E is distorted by capital structure (interest expense differs by leverage), tax rates, and non-cash charges. EV/EBITDA is capital-structure neutral since EV captures all capital and EBITDA is pre-interest. This allows apples-to-apples comparison across companies with different debt levels.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do precedent transactions typically yield higher valuations than trading comps?",a:"Precedent transactions include a control premium (20-40%) that buyers pay for the ability to control and restructure the target. They also reflect synergies and competitive bidding dynamics. Trading comps reflect minority share prices without any control premium or synergy value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between equity value and enterprise value, and why do people confuse them?",a:"Equity value is the value to common shareholders (market cap). EV is the total value of the business to ALL capital providers (equity + debt - cash). People confuse them because they mix equity metrics with EV multiples, for example, dividing EV by net income is wrong because NI is an equity metric (after interest).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the intuition behind the WACC formula? Why do we weight the costs of debt and equity?",a:"WACC represents the blended return that all investors (debt and equity) require. Debt investors accept lower returns because they have priority in bankruptcy. Equity investors demand higher returns because they bear more risk. The weights reflect each group's proportion of total capital. The tax adjustment on debt reflects the interest tax shield.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why can you not use a terminal growth rate higher than the long-term GDP growth rate?",a:"If a single company grew faster than the economy forever, it would eventually become larger than the entire economy, which is impossible. The terminal growth rate represents perpetual growth, so it must be at or below nominal GDP growth (2-3% for developed markets). Higher rates produce unrealistically large terminal values.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has revenue of $500M growing 8% per year. What is revenue in Year 3?",a:"Year 1: $500M × 1.08 = $540M. Year 2: $540M × 1.08 = $583.2M. Year 3: $583.2M × 1.08 = $629.9M. Quick shortcut: $500M × 1.08^3 = $500M × 1.2597 = $629.9M.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has $200M EBITDA, trades at 10x EV/EBITDA, has $500M net debt. What is its equity value?",a:"EV = $200M × 10 = $2,000M. Equity value = EV - net debt = $2,000M - $500M = $1,500M. If there are 100M shares outstanding, equity value per share = $15.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has a market cap of $800M, $300M in debt, $50M in cash. What is its enterprise value?",a:"EV = Market Cap + Debt - Cash = $800M + $300M - $50M = $1,050M. Enterprise value represents the total price to acquire and control the business.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"WACC is 10% and terminal growth is 2%. Terminal year FCF is $50M. What is the terminal value?",a:"TV = FCF × (1+g) / (WACC - g) = $50M × 1.02 / (0.10 - 0.02) = $51M / 0.08 = $637.5M. This represents the value of all cash flows beyond the explicit forecast period, discounted to the end of the forecast.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you discount $100 back 3 years at a 10% discount rate, what is the present value?",a:"PV = $100 / (1.10)^3 = $100 / 1.331 = $75.13. Each year, the $100 is worth about 9-10% less. The further out a cash flow is, the less it is worth today.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Enterprise value is $1B. EBITDA is $100M. D&A is $20M. CapEx is $30M. What is EV/EBITDA and EV/EBIT?",a:"EV/EBITDA = $1B / $100M = 10.0x. EBIT = EBITDA - D&A = $100M - $20M = $80M. EV/EBIT = $1B / $80M = 12.5x. EV/EBIT is always higher than EV/EBITDA because EBIT is a smaller number.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Paper LBO: Buy at 8x $100M EBITDA. 60% debt, 40% equity. EBITDA grows to $120M in 5 years, and $200M of debt is paid down over the hold. Same exit multiple. What is the MOIC?",a:"Entry EV = $800M. Debt = $480M, equity = $320M. Assume $200M debt repaid over 5 years. Exit EV = $120M × 8 = $960M. Exit debt = $280M. Exit equity = $960M - $280M = $680M. MOIC = $680M / $320M = 2.1x. IRR is roughly 16%.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Paper LBO: Buy at 7x, $50M EBITDA. 50% debt. EBITDA grows 10% annually. Repay $15M debt per year. Exit at 7x in 5 years. MOIC?",a:"Entry EV = $350M. Debt = $175M, equity = $175M. Year 5 EBITDA = $50M × 1.1^5 = $80.5M. Exit EV = $80.5M × 7 = $563.5M. Debt at exit = $175M - (5 × $15M) = $100M. Exit equity = $563.5M - $100M = $463.5M. MOIC = $463.5M / $175M = 2.6x. IRR roughly 21%.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A buyer pays 12x EBITDA for a target with $50M EBITDA. The buyer has a P/E of 20x. Is the deal likely accretive or dilutive in an all-stock transaction?",a:"The buyer's P/E of 20x means it pays $20 for every $1 of earnings. The target at 12x EBITDA, if we assume NI is roughly 40% of EBITDA, that is $20M NI. Implied target P/E = $600M / $20M = 30x. Since the buyer (20x) is buying at a higher implied P/E (30x), the deal is likely DILUTIVE in an all-stock deal (buying a more expensive earnings stream).",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a buyer has a P/E of 25x and the target has a P/E of 15x, is an all-stock deal accretive or dilutive?",a:"Accretive. The buyer is trading at a higher multiple (25x) than the target (15x), meaning the buyer's shares are relatively more expensive. When a high P/E buyer acquires a low P/E target in stock, the combined EPS increases because you are adding cheaper earnings. The larger the P/E gap, the more accretive.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In a quick accretion/dilution analysis, how do you determine if a deal is accretive using P/E ratios alone?",a:"If the buyer's P/E is higher than the target's P/E in an all-stock deal, the deal is accretive. If lower, it is dilutive. For a cash deal: if the cost of financing (after-tax interest rate) is less than the target's earnings yield (inverse of P/E), the deal is accretive. This is a quick shortcut for first-pass analysis.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has 100M shares at $20 each, $200M in debt, and $50M cash. What is EV? Now if the stock drops to $15, what is the new EV?",a:"Original: Equity = 100M × $20 = $2B. EV = $2B + $200M - $50M = $2.15B. At $15: Equity = 100M × $15 = $1.5B. EV = $1.5B + $200M - $50M = $1.65B. EV changed by $500M because only the equity portion changed. Debt and cash stayed constant.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has EV of $500M, $100M debt, $25M cash, 50M diluted shares. What is the implied share price?",a:"Equity value = EV - Debt + Cash = $500M - $100M + $25M = $425M. Share price = $425M / 50M shares = $8.50 per share. This is the standard 'bridge' from EV to equity value per share.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Depreciation increases by $10. Tax rate is 40%. What is the impact on cash flow?",a:"Cash increases by $4. Depreciation reduces pre-tax income by $10, saving $4 in taxes (10 × 40%). On the CFS, NI drops by $6 but D&A is added back +$10, net +$4. The cash benefit equals the depreciation multiplied by the tax rate. This is the depreciation tax shield.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"CapEx increases by $50. What happens to the three statements in Year 1 assuming 10-year straight-line depreciation and 25% tax rate?",a:"Income statement. Only the depreciation shows up. $50 over 10 years is $5 a year, so pre-tax income falls $5. Tax falls $1.25, leaving net income down $3.75. The $50 of CapEx itself never touches the income statement.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $3.75. Add back $5 of depreciation, then show the $50 of CapEx as an outflow in investing. Net cash falls $48.75.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $48.75, net PP&E is up $45 ($50 spent less $5 depreciated), so assets fall $3.75. Retained earnings fall $3.75.\n\nThe point: this is why EBITDA flatters capital-intensive businesses. Earnings fell $3.75 while nearly $49 of real cash walked out the door.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company with $100M EBITDA, 30% margins, and 5% revenue growth trades at 8x. What is the implied revenue?",a:"If EBITDA margin is 30%, then EBITDA = Revenue × 0.30. So Revenue = $100M / 0.30 = $333.3M. Quick check: $333.3M × 30% = $100M EBITDA. EV = $100M × 8 = $800M. Next year revenue = $333.3M × 1.05 = $350M.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Free cash flow is $75M. WACC is 10%. FCF grows 3% annually forever. What is the enterprise value using a perpetuity growth model?",a:"EV = FCF / (WACC - g) = $75M / (0.10 - 0.03) = $75M / 0.07 = $1,071.4M. This is a simplified single-stage DCF assuming constant growth. In practice, you would project explicit years first and apply this formula only to the terminal value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"An LBO uses 5x leverage on $80M EBITDA. The sponsor contributes 40% equity. What are the entry EV, debt, and equity amounts?",a:"If 5x leverage means Debt/EBITDA = 5, then debt = $400M. If debt is 60% of EV, then EV = $400M / 0.60 = $666.7M. Equity = $666.7M × 0.40 = $266.7M. Alternatively: if told total leverage is 5x and that represents 60% of sources, EV = Debt + Equity. The answer depends on whether 5x means debt only or total leverage.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In a DCF, if terminal value represents 85% of total enterprise value, what does that tell you?",a:"The explicit forecast period (usually 5-10 years) is contributing very little to the total value. This suggests: (1) the forecast period may be too short, (2) the terminal growth rate or exit multiple may be too aggressive, or (3) near-term cash flows are genuinely small relative to long-term potential. Always sanity-check by calculating the implied perpetuity growth rate.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company A acquires Company B for $200M in cash funded entirely by new debt at 5% interest. Company B earns $15M in NI. Tax rate 25%. Is this accretive?",a:"After-tax cost of debt = 5% × (1 - 0.25) = 3.75%. Financing cost = $200M × 3.75% = $7.5M. Company B contributes $15M NI. Net EPS impact = +$15M - $7.5M = +$7.5M. The deal is ACCRETIVE by $7.5M because the target's earnings exceed the after-tax cost of financing.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you raise the discount rate in a DCF by 1%, what happens to the valuation? What about raising the terminal growth rate by 1%?",a:"Raising the discount rate by 1% decreases the valuation. Cash flows are discounted more heavily, and the terminal value shrinks (larger denominator in Gordon Growth). Raising the terminal growth rate by 1% increases the valuation. The terminal value grows (smaller denominator). Terminal growth rate changes often have a larger impact because they affect the largest component of value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"EBITDA is $150M, D&A is $30M, CapEx is $40M, tax rate is 25%, change in NWC is -$10M (use of cash). Calculate unlevered free cash flow.",a:"UFCF = EBIT × (1-T) + D&A - CapEx - Change in NWC. EBIT = EBITDA - D&A = $150M - $30M = $120M. NOPAT = $120M × 0.75 = $90M. UFCF = $90M + $30M - $40M - $10M = $70M. Alternatively: EBITDA × (1-T) + D&A × T - CapEx - NWC change.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Cost of equity is 12%, pre-tax cost of debt is 6%, tax rate is 25%, debt is 40% of capital, equity is 60%. What is WACC?",a:"WACC = (E/V) × Ke + (D/V) × Kd × (1-T) = 0.60 × 12% + 0.40 × 6% × 0.75 = 7.2% + 1.8% = 9.0%. The after-tax cost of debt is 4.5% (6% × 75%), which is why debt is cheaper than equity and why companies use leverage.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Risk-free rate is 4%, beta is 1.2, equity risk premium is 6%. What is the cost of equity using CAPM?",a:"Cost of Equity = Rf + Beta × ERP = 4% + 1.2 × 6% = 4% + 7.2% = 11.2%. A beta above 1 means the stock is more volatile than the market, requiring a higher return. If beta were 0.8, cost of equity would be 4% + 4.8% = 8.8%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company's stock price is $40, it has 200M diluted shares, $1B in debt, $300M in cash, and $150M in preferred stock. What is EV?",a:"Equity value = $40 × 200M = $8B. EV = $8B + $1B + $150M - $300M = $8.85B. Preferred stock is added because it represents a claim senior to common equity. Cash is subtracted because it offsets the cost of acquiring the operations.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In a merger model, the buyer issues 50M new shares at $20 each to acquire a target. What is the consideration and how does this affect the buyer?",a:"Total consideration = 50M × $20 = $1B in stock. The buyer's share count increases by 50M, diluting existing shareholders. If the target contributes less earnings per share than the buyer's current EPS, the deal is dilutive. If more, accretive. The buyer's balance sheet now consolidates all target assets and liabilities.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company with $50M NI has 100M shares (EPS = $0.50). It acquires a target with $10M NI by issuing 30M new shares. What is pro forma EPS?",a:"Pro forma NI = $50M + $10M = $60M. Pro forma shares = 100M + 30M = 130M. Pro forma EPS = $60M / 130M = $0.46. Original EPS was $0.50, so this deal is DILUTIVE by $0.04 per share (or 8%). The buyer's shareholders now earn less per share.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Same deal but with $5M in annual synergies (pre-tax) and 25% tax rate. Is it still dilutive?",a:"After-tax synergies = $5M × 0.75 = $3.75M. Pro forma NI = $60M + $3.75M = $63.75M. Pro forma EPS = $63.75M / 130M = $0.49. Still slightly dilutive vs $0.50, but synergies nearly close the gap. With $7M+ in pre-tax synergies, the deal becomes accretive.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has enterprise value of $2B. It has $600M in debt, $100M in cash, 10M options outstanding with a $10 strike price, and the current stock price is $30. How many diluted shares and what is equity value per share?",a:"Equity value = $2B - $600M + $100M = $1.5B. Treasury stock method: 10M options exercised, proceeds = 10M × $10 = $100M. Shares repurchased = $100M / $30 = 3.33M. Net dilution = 10M - 3.33M = 6.67M new shares. If basic shares = 75M, diluted = 81.67M. Price = $1.5B / 81.67M = $18.36.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},

// ═══ FUNDAMENTALS & RAPID-FIRE ═══
{q:"What is COGS and how does it impact margins?",a:"COGS (Cost of Goods Sold) represents the direct costs of producing goods or services. Raw materials, direct labor, manufacturing overhead. Higher COGS lowers gross profit and compresses gross margins. It is the first expense subtracted from revenue on the income statement.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is gross profit?",a:"Revenue minus COGS. It measures how efficiently a company produces its goods or delivers its services before accounting for overhead costs like SG&A. Gross margin (gross profit / revenue) is a key indicator of pricing power and production efficiency.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is EBITDA and why do bankers use it?",a:"Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortization. EBITDA = EBIT + D&A. Bankers use it because it approximates operating cash flow and allows comparison across companies with different capital structures, tax situations, and depreciation policies. It is the most common denominator in valuation multiples.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is net income?",a:"The final profit after all expenses. COGS, SG&A, D&A, interest, and taxes. It represents earnings available to common shareholders and flows into retained earnings on the balance sheet. It is the starting point of the cash flow statement.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does an increase in net working capital reduce cash flow?",a:"When NWC increases, the company is tying up more cash in operations. Building inventory, extending more credit to customers (AR up), or paying suppliers faster (AP down). These all consume cash. Conversely, a decrease in NWC releases cash back to the company.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is depreciation and why is it important?",a:"Depreciation allocates the cost of a tangible long-term asset (PP&E) over its useful life. It reduces reported income each year but is a non-cash charge. No actual cash leaves the business. It is important because it creates a tax shield (reduces taxes) and affects both EBIT and net income.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is capex and how is it different from a regular expense?",a:"Capital expenditures (CapEx) are investments in long-term assets like equipment, buildings, or technology. Unlike regular expenses that hit the income statement immediately, CapEx is capitalized on the balance sheet as an asset and then gradually expensed through depreciation over its useful life.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is inventory and why can it be risky?",a:"Inventory represents goods held for sale or in production. It is risky because it ties up cash, can become obsolete or spoil, and may need to be written down if it cannot be sold at its carrying value. High inventory relative to sales (high Days Inventory Outstanding) is a warning sign.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is debt in the context of a company\'s balance sheet?",a:"Debt is borrowed capital that must be repaid with interest. It appears as a liability. Current portion (due within 1 year) and long-term portion. Debt creates fixed obligations (interest and principal payments) that increase financial risk but also provide tax benefits since interest is tax-deductible.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is dilution and how does it occur?",a:"Dilution is the reduction in existing shareholders\' ownership percentage when new shares are issued. Through stock offerings, option exercises, convertible securities converting, or stock-based compensation. EPS decreases because net income is spread across more shares.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is return on equity (ROE) and what does it measure?",a:"ROE = Net Income / Shareholders\' Equity. It measures how effectively a company generates profit from shareholders\' investment. Higher ROE suggests better capital efficiency. However, high leverage can artificially inflate ROE by reducing the equity base, so it should be evaluated alongside leverage metrics.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is return on assets (ROA) and what does it measure?",a:"ROA = Net Income / Total Assets. It measures how efficiently a company uses its total asset base to generate profit. Unlike ROE, it is not distorted by leverage. A higher ROA indicates better asset utilization. Asset-light businesses (software) typically have higher ROA than asset-heavy ones (manufacturing).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is margin expansion?",a:"Margin expansion means a company is becoming more profitable per dollar of revenue. Gross margin, EBITDA margin, or net margin is increasing over time. It can result from pricing power, operating leverage (fixed costs spread over more revenue), cost cuts, or mix shift toward higher-margin products.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is leverage in a corporate finance context?",a:"Leverage refers to the use of debt to finance a company\'s operations and growth. It amplifies both returns and risk, if the business earns more than the cost of debt, equity holders benefit disproportionately. If it earns less, equity holders absorb the losses while debt payments remain fixed.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does EPS increase after a share buyback?",a:"A buyback reduces the number of shares outstanding. Since net income stays roughly the same (slightly lower due to lost interest on cash used), dividing the same earnings by fewer shares produces a higher EPS. This is mechanical. It does not necessarily mean the business is more profitable.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Revenue increases by $100 with no additional costs. Tax rate is 25%. Walk me through all three statements.",a:"Income statement. Revenue rises $100 with no costs against it, so pre-tax income rises $100. Tax of $25 leaves net income up $75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $75. Nothing non-cash and no working capital movement, so cash rises $75.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $75 and retained earnings are up $75.\n\nThe point: this is the textbook version, and it is deliberately unrealistic. Real revenue carries variable cost and usually arrives as a receivable rather than cash. The exercise is testing whether you can move cleanly through the three statements, not whether the scenario is plausible.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Goodwill impairment of $30. Tax rate is 25%. Walk me through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. A $30 impairment cuts pre-tax income $30. Tax benefit of $7.50 leaves net income down $22.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $22.50. The write-down is non-cash, so add the $30 back. Cash rises $7.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $7.50 and goodwill is down $30, so assets fall $22.50. Retained earnings fall $22.50.\n\nThe point: goodwill only exists because someone paid more than the fair value of the net assets. Impairing it is management conceding the acquisition underperformed. No cash moves, and cash actually rises by the tax benefit.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Does capex hit the income statement immediately?",a:"No. CapEx is capitalized on the balance sheet as PP&E and then expensed gradually over its useful life through depreciation. Only the annual depreciation charge hits the income statement, not the full purchase price in the year of acquisition.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does depreciation affect cash directly?",a:"No. Depreciation is a non-cash charge. No cash leaves the business when depreciation is recorded. However, it indirectly increases cash by reducing taxable income and therefore reducing taxes paid. The net cash benefit equals the depreciation amount multiplied by the tax rate.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does interest expense affect EBITDA?",a:"No. EBITDA is calculated before interest expense. Interest is a financing cost, not an operating cost, so it appears below the EBITDA line. This is why EBITDA allows comparison across companies with different capital structures.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does depreciation affect EBITDA?",a:"No. The \'DA\' in EBITDA stands for Depreciation and Amortization. These are explicitly added back. EBITDA is calculated before D&A, so changes in depreciation policy do not affect EBITDA.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does depreciation affect EBIT?",a:"Yes. EBIT (Earnings Before Interest and Taxes) is calculated after depreciation. Higher depreciation reduces EBIT. This is why EBIT is sometimes called operating income. It includes the cost of using long-term assets.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does interest expense affect net income?",a:"Yes. Interest expense is deducted before arriving at net income. Higher interest costs reduce pre-tax income and therefore net income. This is why highly leveraged companies have lower net income relative to their operating income.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Do dividends affect net income?",a:"No. Dividends are a distribution of earnings to shareholders, not an expense. They do not appear on the income statement. They reduce retained earnings on the balance sheet and show up as a financing outflow on the cash flow statement.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does issuing new stock affect net income?",a:"No. Equity issuance is a financing activity, not an operating event. It does not appear on the income statement. It increases cash and equity on the balance sheet and shows up as a financing inflow on the cash flow statement. However, it dilutes EPS by increasing the share count.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does a share buyback affect net income?",a:"Not directly. A buyback is a financing activity. Cash decreases, equity decreases (treasury stock). Net income is slightly lower due to lost interest income on the cash used, but the primary effect is on EPS (which increases because of fewer shares outstanding).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What increases enterprise value?",a:"Higher equity value (stock price increase or share issuance) and more debt both increase EV. Lower cash also increases EV since cash is subtracted. Anything that makes the business more valuable to all capital providers increases EV.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What decreases enterprise value?",a:"Lower equity value (stock price decline), less debt, and more cash all decrease EV. Cash reduces EV because it offsets the cost of acquiring the operations. Paying down debt with cash has no net EV effect (debt down, cash down. They cancel).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},

// ═══ SCENARIO & CONCEPTUAL FLOWS ═══
{q:"If a company's tax rate increases, how does that affect the financial statements?",a:"Income statement. Tax expense rises and net income falls. Everything above the tax line is untouched, so EBIT and EBITDA do not move.\n\nCash flow statement. Lower net income and a bigger real tax payment mean operating cash flow falls.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash falls and retained earnings fall with it.\n\nThe point: this is one of the few changes that hurts cash without any operational cause. It also lowers a DCF, because unlevered free cash flow starts from EBIT times one minus the tax rate. It cuts the value of the interest tax shield too, which makes debt slightly less attractive.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company increases prices but volume stays constant, what happens to the financials?",a:"Revenue increases because price × volume is higher. If costs are largely fixed, margins expand significantly. Gross margin, EBITDA margin, and net margin all improve. Cash flow increases. This is why pricing power is one of the most valued business attributes.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company cuts costs significantly, what happens to margins and cash flow?",a:"Operating and net margins improve because expenses fall while revenue stays the same. Cash flow increases as less cash is spent on operations. However, if the cuts are too deep (reducing headcount, R&D, marketing), revenue may decline in future periods.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company becomes more efficient with inventory and turns it faster, what happens?",a:"Less cash is tied up in inventory (inventory balance decreases). This releases working capital and improves cash flow. Days Inventory Outstanding (DIO) decreases. The company can operate with less capital, improving return on assets and free cash flow.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If accounts receivable decreases, what happens to the three statements?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The revenue was recognized at the point of sale.\n\nCash flow statement. Receivables falling is a source of cash, so cash rises.\n\nBalance sheet. Receivables fall and cash rises by the same amount. Total assets are unchanged.\n\nThe point: customers are paying faster, so days sales outstanding improves and the cash conversion cycle shortens. The company is turning profit it already booked into money it can actually use.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If accounts payable decreases, what happens to the three statements?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The expense was recognized when the goods or services were received.\n\nCash flow statement. Payables falling is a use of cash, so cash falls.\n\nBalance sheet. Payables fall and cash falls with them. Assets and liabilities both decline.\n\nThe point: the company is settling with suppliers sooner, which uses cash without any change in profit. It can mean stronger discipline or captured early-payment discounts, but a sharp involuntary drop can also mean suppliers have tightened terms, which is an early distress signal.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If inventory decreases with no change in sales, what happens?",a:"Income statement. Nothing immediately, since inventory only becomes COGS when it sells.\n\nCash flow statement. Inventory falling releases cash, so cash rises.\n\nBalance sheet. Inventory falls and cash rises by the same amount. Total assets are unchanged.\n\nThe point: with sales flat, the company is running down stock it already paid for and converting it into cash. Good for liquidity, but worth checking why. Better inventory management is one story; being unable to afford restocking, or stockouts that will cost future sales, is a very different one.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens if a company delays paying its suppliers?",a:"Cash flow statement. Payables rise, meaning the company is holding cash it owes, so operating cash flow improves.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up and accounts payable are up by the same amount.\n\nIncome statement. Nothing. The expense was already booked when the goods arrived.\n\nThe point: this is free financing from suppliers and it flatters operating cash flow. But it only works once, since payables cannot stretch forever, and it is one of the classic tells of a company running short of cash. Push too far and suppliers demand cash on delivery, which is when the problem becomes visible to everyone.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens if a company collects cash faster from customers?",a:"Cash flow statement. Receivables fall, which is a source of cash, so operating cash flow rises.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up and receivables are down by the same amount.\n\nIncome statement. Nothing. The sale was recognized when it happened.\n\nThe point: days sales outstanding falls and the cash conversion cycle shortens, meaning the business funds itself with less working capital. That is unambiguously good, and unlike stretching payables it reflects real strength: creditworthy customers and disciplined collections.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If depreciation decreases, what happens to the three statements?",a:"Income statement. A smaller depreciation charge means higher pre-tax income, a higher tax bill, and higher net income.\n\nCash flow statement. Net income is higher but the add-back is smaller. The two nearly cancel, and cash comes out slightly lower, by the tax on the depreciation you no longer take.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E declines more slowly and retained earnings are higher.\n\nThe point: earnings look better and the company is worse off in cash, because a smaller depreciation shield means a larger real tax payment. This is why extending useful lives is a classic way to manufacture earnings growth, and why it costs cash to do it.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company finances capex entirely with debt, what happens to the statements?",a:"At close. The income statement shows nothing. The debt raise is a financing inflow and the CapEx is an equal investing outflow, so net cash does not move. On the balance sheet, PP&E and debt both rise by the same amount, and equity is untouched.\n\nEvery period after. Depreciation and interest both hit the income statement, so net income falls. Depreciation gets added back on the cash flow statement, but the interest is real cash going out.\n\nThe point: financing an asset entirely with debt costs nothing on day one and everything afterwards. It works only if the asset returns more than the after-tax cost of the debt. If it does not, the interest keeps coming regardless of what the asset earns, which is exactly how leveraged companies fail.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company refinances debt at a lower interest rate, what happens?",a:"Income statement. Interest expense falls, so pre-tax income and net income both rise. Any one-time fees or call premiums hit now, sometimes as a loss on extinguishment.\n\nCash flow statement. Less cash goes out in interest each period, so operating cash flow improves. The upfront fees are an outflow in the refinancing year.\n\nBalance sheet. Debt is roughly unchanged unless the principal was resized. Retained earnings rise as the interest saving accumulates.\n\nThe point: the business has not improved at all. The company simply cut the price of its money, which lifts equity value because more of the same operating profit now reaches shareholders instead of lenders.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If interest rates rise on a company's floating-rate debt, what happens?",a:"Income statement. Interest expense rises and net income falls, even though nothing about operations changed and the principal is identical.\n\nCash flow statement. More cash goes out in interest, so operating cash flow falls.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash falls and retained earnings fall.\n\nThe point: the company got worse without doing anything wrong. This is why the fixed versus floating mix matters so much in a leveraged structure. A borrower running tight coverage can breach an interest coverage covenant on a rate move alone, which is what makes floating-rate debt dangerous for an LBO in a rising rate environment.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If stock-based compensation increases, what happens to the three statements?",a:"Income statement. The SBC expense rises, so net income falls.\n\nCash flow statement. Net income is lower but the whole charge is added back as non-cash, so cash is barely touched and actually ticks up by the tax saving.\n\nBalance sheet. APIC rises and retained earnings fall, so total equity moves very little. The diluted share count climbs as awards vest.\n\nThe point: cash is untouched and shareholders are worse off. The cost shows up in the share count, not the bank account, which is why adding SBC back to EBITDA is so contested. It is non-cash, but the dilution is entirely real.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If an acquisition is done using stock instead of cash, what happens?",a:"Income statement. Nothing on day one. Purchase accounting effects, such as amortization of acquired intangibles, arrive in later periods.\n\nCash flow statement. No cash moves at all. It is a non-cash financing transaction and shows up only as a disclosure.\n\nBalance sheet. The target's assets and liabilities are consolidated at fair value, goodwill is created for whatever was paid above that, and equity rises by the value of the shares issued.\n\nThe point: no cash leaves and the buyer's existing owners still pay, through dilution. Stock deals are usually chosen when the buyer's shares are richly valued or the cheque is too big for cash, and the accretion test then turns on the buyer's P/E against the target's.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If goodwill increases after an acquisition, what does that mean?",a:"The buyer paid more than the fair value of the target's identifiable net assets. The excess is goodwill, representing expected synergies, brand value, customer relationships, or strategic value that cannot be separately identified. Higher goodwill means a larger premium was paid.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If goodwill is later impaired, what does that signal?",a:"The acquired business is worth less than what was paid. The acquisition underperformed expectations. It is a negative signal to investors suggesting overpayment, failed integration, or deteriorating business fundamentals. The impairment is a non-cash charge that reduces assets and equity but does not directly affect cash.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company's equity value increases but debt stays constant, what happens to enterprise value?",a:"Enterprise value increases. EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash. If equity rises and debt is unchanged, EV goes up. This typically happens when the stock price appreciates, reflecting improved business fundamentals or market sentiment.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company builds up a large cash balance, what happens to enterprise value?",a:"Enterprise value decreases because cash is subtracted from EV. EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash. More cash means a lower EV, all else equal. This is because an acquirer would receive the cash, reducing the effective cost of buying the operations.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If shares outstanding increase, what happens to EPS?",a:"EPS decreases. EPS = Net Income / Shares Outstanding. More shares in the denominator means less earnings per share, even if total net income is unchanged. This is dilution. Each shareholder owns a smaller piece of the same earnings pie.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If shares outstanding decrease, what happens to EPS?",a:"EPS increases. Fewer shares in the denominator means each remaining share captures more of the total earnings. This is why companies do share buybacks. It mechanically boosts EPS without requiring any improvement in the actual business.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If net income increases but cash flow does not, what could explain that?",a:"Working capital is consuming the additional earnings. AR or inventory is growing faster than revenue, or the company is paying suppliers faster (AP decreasing). Revenue is being recognized on the IS but the cash has not been collected. This is a cash conversion problem and a red flag.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If cash flow is strong but net income is low, what could explain that?",a:"High non-cash charges like depreciation, amortization, or impairments are depressing net income without actually using cash. The CFS adds these back, revealing strong underlying cash generation. This is common in capital-intensive businesses or companies that recently made large acquisitions (amortization of intangibles).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do bankers care so much about 3-statement flow questions in interviews?",a:"Because they test whether you truly understand how business decisions impact financials holistically, not just one statement in isolation. Every transaction touches multiple statements, and bankers need analysts who can think through the full picture when building models, analyzing deals, and advising clients.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the biggest mistake candidates make on 3-statement flow questions?",a:"Forgetting the Cash Flow Statement bridge. Specifically, not adding back non-cash items (D&A, SBC, impairments) or missing working capital effects. Many candidates get the IS right but then say cash changes by the same amount as net income, which is almost never true.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the correct mindset when answering any 3-statement flow question?",a:"Be structured: always go IS first, then CFS, then BS. On the IS, walk through to net income. On the CFS, start with NI, add back non-cash items, account for working capital changes, then investing and financing. On the BS, show that assets = liabilities + equity and that cash ties to the CFS.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},

// ═══ VALUATION, DCF, COMPS, PRECEDENTS ═══
{q:"What are Comparable Companies (Comps)?",a:"Valuing a company by applying trading multiples (EV/EBITDA, P/E, EV/Revenue) from similar publicly traded companies. You select peers with similar size, growth, margins, and industry, then apply their median multiples to the target's financials to get an implied valuation range.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does Enterprise Value represent?",a:"The total value of a company's core operations available to all capital providers. Equity holders, debt holders, and preferred shareholders. It answers: what would it cost to buy the entire business and all its obligations?",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does Equity Value represent?",a:"The value attributable only to common shareholders, what remains after all debt and other obligations are satisfied. For public companies, equity value equals market capitalization (share price times shares outstanding).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you bridge from Equity Value to Enterprise Value?",a:"EV = Equity Value + Total Debt + Preferred Stock + Minority Interest - Cash. You add debt-like claims because EV represents value to ALL providers, and you subtract cash because it is a non-operating asset that offsets the purchase price.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is EBITDA commonly used as the denominator in valuation multiples?",a:"EBITDA approximates operating cash flow and is capital-structure neutral. It is calculated before interest (financing), taxes (jurisdiction-dependent), and D&A (accounting policy-dependent). This allows fair comparison across companies with different leverage, tax rates, and depreciation methods.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a valuation multiple?",a:"A ratio that compares a measure of value (EV or equity value) to a financial metric (EBITDA, earnings, revenue, book value). It expresses how much investors are willing to pay per unit of a financial metric. Example: 10x EV/EBITDA means investors pay $10 for every $1 of EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What determines a company's valuation multiple?",a:"Growth rate (higher growth = higher multiple), profitability/margins, risk profile, capital intensity, revenue quality (recurring vs one-time), competitive position, management quality, and industry dynamics. Companies with better fundamentals across these dimensions trade at premium multiples.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do high-growth companies trade at higher multiples?",a:"Investors are willing to pay more per dollar of current earnings or EBITDA because they expect those metrics to grow significantly. A company growing 30% annually will have much higher earnings in 5 years than one growing 5%, so today's multiple reflects that future value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do risky companies trade at lower multiples?",a:"Higher risk means greater uncertainty about future cash flows. Investors demand a higher return (higher discount rate) to compensate, which reduces the present value of those cash flows. Lower present value relative to current earnings translates to a lower multiple.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between intrinsic and relative valuation?",a:"Intrinsic valuation (DCF) values a company based on its own projected cash flows and fundamentals, independent of what the market says. Relative valuation (Comps, Precedents) values it based on how similar companies are priced by the market. DCF is bottoms-up; relative is market-anchored.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When are Comps most useful?",a:"When there are good publicly traded peers with similar business models, growth profiles, and size. Comps are fast, market-based, and reflect current investor sentiment. They work best in efficient markets where comparable companies actually exist.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When are Precedent Transactions most useful?",a:"When advising on M&A. They show what acquirers have actually paid for similar businesses, including control premiums and synergies. They are most relevant when recent comparable transactions exist in similar market conditions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do bankers use multiple valuation methods instead of just one?",a:"To triangulate a valuation range and sanity-check assumptions. Each method has strengths and weaknesses. DCF is assumption-heavy, Comps depend on peer selection, Precedents may be stale. Using all three provides a more robust and defensible valuation range.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a valuation range and why is it presented as a range rather than a single number?",a:"A range of values derived from different methodologies and assumptions. Valuation is inherently imprecise. Presenting a range acknowledges this uncertainty and is more credible than claiming a company is worth exactly $X. The overlap across methods is typically the most defensible zone.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the CAPM formula and what does each component represent?",a:"Cost of Equity = Risk-Free Rate + Beta x Equity Risk Premium. Risk-free rate: compensation for time (10-year Treasury). Beta: the stock's sensitivity to market movements. ERP: the extra return investors demand for holding stocks instead of risk-free bonds. Together: the total return equity investors require.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is beta and what does a beta of 1.5 mean?",a:"Beta measures how much a stock moves relative to the overall market. A beta of 1.5 means the stock is 50% more volatile than the market, if the market goes up 10%, the stock is expected to go up 15%. Higher beta = higher risk = higher required return = higher cost of equity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is terminal value and why is it needed in a DCF?",a:"Terminal value captures the value of all cash flows beyond the explicit forecast period (usually 5-10 years). It is needed because a company does not stop operating after the forecast. The business continues generating cash indefinitely. Terminal value often represents 60-80% of total DCF value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why can the terminal growth rate not exceed WACC in the perpetuity growth model?",a:"Mathematically, if g >= WACC, the denominator (WACC - g) becomes zero or negative, producing infinite or nonsensical values. Conceptually, no company can grow faster than the cost of capital forever. It would eventually consume the entire economy. The growth rate should approximate long-term GDP growth (2-3%).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Which terminal value method is more commonly used in practice?",a:"The exit multiple method is more common in practice because it is intuitive, market-anchored, and easy to benchmark against current trading multiples. The perpetuity growth method is more theoretically grounded and is typically used as a cross-check to verify the implied growth rate from the exit multiple is reasonable.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What drives DCF valuation the most?",a:"Terminal value assumptions (exit multiple or perpetuity growth rate), WACC, and revenue growth rate. Small changes in any of these can swing the valuation significantly. This is why sensitivity analysis is critical. You need to show how the output changes across different assumptions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is terminal value such a large percentage of DCF value?",a:"Because the explicit forecast (5-10 years) captures only a fraction of the company's total life. The terminal value captures everything beyond. Decades of future cash flows compressed into one number. For high-growth companies with low near-term FCF, terminal value can be 80%+ of total value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to DCF valuation if WACC increases?",a:"Valuation decreases. A higher WACC means future cash flows are discounted more heavily, reducing their present value. Both the explicit period cash flows and the terminal value shrink. A 1% increase in WACC can reduce valuation by 10-15%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to DCF valuation if the growth rate increases?",a:"Valuation increases. Higher growth means larger future cash flows and a higher terminal value (larger numerator in perpetuity growth formula, or higher terminal EBITDA in exit multiple method). Growth is the most powerful value driver in a DCF.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to DCF valuation if capex increases?",a:"Valuation decreases. Higher CapEx reduces free cash flow (FCF = EBIT(1-T) + D&A - CapEx - change in NWC). Less FCF means less value when discounted. However, if the CapEx funds growth that generates returns above WACC, the long-term effect may be positive.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to DCF valuation if working capital increases?",a:"Valuation decreases. An increase in net working capital is a use of cash that reduces free cash flow. The company is tying up more cash in operations (inventory, receivables) rather than generating it for investors.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is a DCF so sensitive to assumptions?",a:"Because small changes in growth, margins, WACC, or terminal value compound over a multi-year forecast. A 1% change in WACC or terminal growth can swing the output by 15-20%. This is why bankers always run sensitivity and scenario analyses rather than presenting a single DCF number.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is a DCF less reliable for startups and early-stage companies?",a:"Startups have unpredictable cash flows, unproven business models, and no historical track record to base projections on. A DCF requires projecting specific cash flows. Garbage in, garbage out. For startups, relative valuation (EV/Revenue) or venture-style methods are more appropriate.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is a DCF more reliable for stable, mature companies?",a:"Stable companies have predictable revenue, margins, and cash flows with a long track record. This makes projections more reliable and reduces the sensitivity to assumptions. The DCF output is more meaningful when the inputs are grounded in observable historical patterns.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is discounting and why do we do it?",a:"Converting future cash flows into their present value. We discount because of the time value of money. A dollar today is worth more than a dollar tomorrow because you could invest it and earn a return. The discount rate reflects both the time value and the risk of receiving those future cash flows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to valuation if risk increases?",a:"The discount rate increases to compensate investors for bearing more risk. Higher discount rate means future cash flows are worth less today, so valuation decreases. Risk can increase from business-specific factors (competition, regulation) or macro factors (recession, rate hikes).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the mid-year convention in a DCF and why is it used?",a:"Instead of assuming all cash flows arrive at year-end, the mid-year convention assumes they arrive in the middle of each year. This is more realistic since businesses generate cash throughout the year, not in a lump sum on December 31. It slightly increases the present value since cash flows are discounted for a shorter period.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Which is more common in IB. An unlevered or levered DCF?",a:"Unlevered DCF is far more common. It values the entire enterprise using UFCF discounted at WACC, producing enterprise value. Levered DCF values only the equity using FCF to equity discounted at cost of equity. Unlevered is preferred because it separates operating value from financing decisions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What makes a good comparable company for a comps analysis?",a:"Similar industry/sub-sector, similar size (revenue, market cap), similar growth profile, similar margins, similar business model, and similar geographic exposure. No comp is perfect. You are looking for the closest approximations and should note meaningful differences.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the most common EV-based multiples?",a:"EV/EBITDA (most common, capital-structure neutral), EV/Revenue (for unprofitable companies), and EV/EBIT (for capital-intensive industries where D&A is a real cost). The right multiple depends on the industry and what drives value in that sector.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the most common equity-based multiples?",a:"P/E (Price to Earnings, the most common equity multiple), P/B (Price to Book, common for banks), and PEG (P/E divided by growth rate). Equity multiples include the effect of leverage, so they are not comparable across companies with different debt levels.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When would you use P/E instead of EV/EBITDA?",a:"P/E is most useful for comparing stable, profitable companies in the same industry with similar capital structures. It is the standard for financial institutions (banks, insurance) where debt is operational and EV-based multiples are less meaningful. It is less useful when comparing companies with different leverage.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is EV/EBITDA generally preferred over P/E?",a:"EV/EBITDA is capital-structure neutral. It compares the value of the entire business to a pre-interest metric. P/E is distorted by leverage (two identical businesses with different debt levels will have very different P/Es). EV/EBITDA allows apples-to-apples comparison regardless of how a company is financed.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is LTM (Last Twelve Months)?",a:"The most recent twelve-month period of financial results, calculated by taking the last full fiscal year, adding the most recent quarter, and subtracting the same quarter from the prior year. LTM gives the most current view of trailing performance.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is NTM (Next Twelve Months)?",a:"The projected twelve months of financial results, based on consensus analyst estimates. NTM multiples are forward-looking and reflect market expectations for future performance rather than historical results.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a trading multiple vs a transaction multiple?",a:"A trading multiple is based on a company's current public market price, what minority shareholders pay daily. A transaction multiple is based on the price paid in an acquisition, what a buyer paid for control. Transaction multiples are higher because they include a control premium.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why are transaction multiples typically higher than trading multiples?",a:"Transaction multiples include a control premium (20-40%) paid for the ability to control the business, plus the value of expected synergies. Trading multiples reflect only the minority share price without any premium for control or synergies.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a premium in M&A and how is it calculated?",a:"The premium is the amount above the target's unaffected share price that the acquirer pays. Calculated as (Offer Price - Unaffected Price) / Unaffected Price. Typical premiums are 20-40%. The unaffected price is usually the price before any M&A rumors leaked.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is selection bias in comparable company analysis?",a:"Choosing companies that support a desired valuation outcome rather than selecting the most truly comparable peers. For example, including a high-growth outlier to inflate the median multiple. Good analysts select comps objectively based on business similarity, not based on what multiple they produce.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is normalization in valuation?",a:"Adjusting financials for one-time, non-recurring, or unusual items to reflect sustainable run-rate performance. Examples: removing restructuring charges, litigation settlements, one-time gains, or COVID impacts. Normalized financials give a cleaner basis for applying multiples or projecting cash flows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is an outlier in comps and how do you handle it?",a:"A data point far from the rest of the peer set, for example, a company trading at 25x EBITDA when peers are at 8-12x. This could be due to a pending acquisition, distress, or fundamentally different business. Handle by removing it from the median calculation but noting it separately with an explanation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is median typically preferred over mean in comps analysis?",a:"Median is less affected by extreme outliers. If one comp trades at 30x and the rest at 8-12x, the mean gets pulled up significantly, while the median stays in the 8-12x range. Median provides a more reliable central measure of where the peer group actually trades.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a DCF give a lower valuation than comps?",a:"The analyst may be using more conservative growth assumptions than what the market is pricing in. Or the market may be in a period of optimism/bubble where trading multiples are inflated beyond what fundamentals support. The DCF reflects the analyst's own assumptions; comps reflect market consensus.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a DCF give a higher valuation than comps?",a:"The analyst may have more aggressive growth assumptions, or the market may be undervaluing the company due to short-term concerns, lack of coverage, or sector-wide pessimism. The DCF can capture value that the market is missing if the assumptions are justified.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Which valuation methodology is the most correct?",a:"None of them. Valuation is a range, not a precise number. Each method has strengths and limitations. The goal is to triangulate across methods and arrive at a defensible range. The 'right' answer depends on the context (M&A, IPO, restructuring) and the quality of inputs.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company has no debt, how do enterprise value and equity value compare?",a:"EV = Equity Value - Cash. Without debt, there is no debt to add. So EV is simply market cap minus cash. If the company also has no cash, EV equals equity value exactly.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If EBITDA increases but enterprise value stays constant, what happens to the EV/EBITDA multiple?",a:"The multiple decreases. Multiple = EV / EBITDA. If the denominator (EBITDA) grows but the numerator (EV) stays the same, the ratio shrinks. This means the company is getting cheaper relative to its earnings power.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If enterprise value increases but EBITDA stays constant, what happens to the multiple?",a:"The multiple increases. EV / EBITDA gets larger when EV grows with flat EBITDA. This means investors are paying more per dollar of EBITDA. The company is getting more expensive.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to valuation if the risk-free rate increases?",a:"WACC increases (risk-free rate feeds into cost of equity via CAPM and into cost of debt). Higher WACC means lower DCF valuation. Trading multiples also tend to compress because investors can earn higher returns in risk-free bonds, reducing the relative attractiveness of equities.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to valuation if beta increases?",a:"Cost of equity increases (CAPM: Ke = Rf + Beta x ERP), which raises WACC and reduces DCF valuation. A higher beta signals the stock is more volatile and risky, so investors demand a higher return, discounting future cash flows more heavily.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is valuation not a precise science?",a:"Because it depends heavily on subjective assumptions. Growth rates, discount rates, terminal values, peer selection. Reasonable people can disagree on these inputs and arrive at meaningfully different values. This is why valuation is always presented as a range with supporting logic, not a single definitive number.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is more important than the final valuation number in an IB interview?",a:"The assumptions and reasoning behind it. Interviewers want to see that you understand the drivers of valuation, why you chose certain growth rates, how you selected comps, what the key sensitivities are. A candidate who gets the 'wrong' number but explains the logic clearly will outperform one who memorizes a formula.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the biggest driver of your valuation score in IB interviews?",a:"Your ability to explain the logic clearly and structured. Walk through each methodology step-by-step, explain why you made each assumption, and show you understand how the pieces connect. Technical precision matters, but clear communication and business intuition matter more.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What mistake do candidates commonly make on valuation questions?",a:"Memorizing formulas without understanding the underlying drivers and intuition. They can recite WACC = (E/V)(Ke) + (D/V)(Kd)(1-T) but cannot explain why debt is tax-adjusted or what happens to valuation when beta changes. Interviewers test understanding, not memorization.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the goal of valuation in investment banking?",a:"To estimate a realistic range of value that supports decisions. Pricing an M&A deal, setting an IPO range, evaluating a restructuring, or advising on a fairness opinion. It is a tool for decision-making, not an academic exercise.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},

// ═══ M&A, ACCRETION/DILUTION, LBO ═══
{q:"What is an acquisition?",a:"When one company purchases another by buying its equity or assets to gain control. The acquirer absorbs the target's operations, employees, and obligations. Can be friendly (board-approved) or hostile (direct appeal to shareholders).",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a merger?",a:"A combination of two companies into one entity, often framed as a merger of equals. In practice, one company is usually dominant. Mergers require shareholder approval from both sides and result in a single surviving entity.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a buyer prefer an asset purchase over a stock purchase?",a:"Asset purchases let the buyer cherry-pick specific assets and avoid unwanted liabilities (lawsuits, pension obligations). The buyer also gets a step-up in asset basis, creating future tax deductions through higher depreciation. Downside: more complex, contracts may need reassignment.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a seller prefer a stock sale?",a:"Cleaner exit. The seller transfers the entire entity including all liabilities. Often better tax treatment for the seller (capital gains vs ordinary income). Simpler execution since contracts, licenses, and permits typically transfer automatically with the entity.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do buyers pay a premium in acquisitions?",a:"To incentivize target shareholders to sell (they need a reason to give up their shares), and because the buyer expects to create additional value through synergies, operational improvements, or strategic positioning that justifies paying above the current market price.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are synergies and why do they matter in M&A?",a:"Additional value created by combining two companies that neither could achieve alone. They matter because they justify the premium paid. Cost synergies (headcount reduction, facility consolidation) are more reliable than revenue synergies (cross-selling, market expansion), which are harder to realize.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Give examples of cost synergies in an acquisition.",a:"Eliminating duplicate corporate functions (HR, finance, legal), consolidating office space and facilities, reducing headcount in overlapping roles, leveraging combined purchasing power for better supplier pricing, and rationalizing IT systems. Cost synergies are typically realized within 1-2 years.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Give examples of revenue synergies in an acquisition.",a:"Cross-selling products to each other's customer bases, expanding into new geographies using the combined distribution network, pricing power from increased market share, and bundling complementary products. Revenue synergies are harder to quantify and take longer to realize than cost synergies.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What determines whether a deal is accretive or dilutive?",a:"Three factors: (1) relative valuation. Is the buyer paying more or less per dollar of earnings than its own stock trades at, (2) financing method. Cash, debt, or stock each have different costs, and (3) synergies. Additional earnings that offset financing costs. The interplay of all three determines the EPS impact.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does paying with stock often dilute EPS?",a:"Issuing new shares increases the share count (denominator of EPS). Unless the target's earnings contribution exceeds the dilution from new shares, EPS drops. This happens when the buyer's P/E is lower than the effective P/E paid for the target.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does paying with cash often lead to accretion?",a:"No new shares are issued, so there is no dilution. The only cost is the foregone interest income on the cash used (or interest expense on new debt). If the target's earnings yield exceeds this cost, the deal is accretive. Cash deals avoid the dilution problem entirely.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is purchase price in an M&A context?",a:"The total value paid for the target company, including the premium over market price. It equals the offer price per share times diluted shares outstanding. The purchase price determines goodwill (excess over fair value of net assets) and is the starting point for accretion/dilution analysis.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is transaction structure in M&A?",a:"The mix of consideration used to fund the deal. Cash, stock, debt, or a combination. Structure affects accretion/dilution, tax treatment, risk allocation, and post-deal ownership. An all-cash deal has no dilution but uses liquidity; an all-stock deal preserves cash but dilutes shareholders.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is goodwill in an M&A context?",a:"The excess of the purchase price over the fair value of the target's identifiable net assets. It represents intangible value. Expected synergies, brand, customer relationships, and workforce. That cannot be separately identified. Goodwill sits on the balance sheet and is tested annually for impairment.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a step-up in an acquisition?",a:"Revaluing the target's assets from book value to fair market value as part of purchase price allocation. The step-up creates higher depreciation/amortization expense going forward (reducing reported earnings) but also provides a tax benefit if it is a taxable transaction. The difference between new and old basis creates a deferred tax liability.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is amortization of intangibles and how does it affect post-deal earnings?",a:"Acquired intangible assets (customer relationships, technology, brand) are amortized over their useful life (5-20 years). This creates a non-cash expense that reduces reported net income post-acquisition. It is one of the key purchase accounting adjustments in a merger model and often makes deals appear more dilutive than they truly are on a cash basis.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is deal rationale?",a:"The strategic reason for an acquisition, why this target, why now, and how does it create value. Common rationales: accelerate growth (new markets/products), achieve cost savings (scale economies), acquire technology or talent, vertical integration, or defensive positioning against competitors.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a hostile takeover?",a:"An acquisition attempt made without the approval of the target's board of directors. The acquirer goes directly to shareholders via a tender offer or proxy fight. The target may deploy defenses (poison pill, white knight, staggered board). Hostile deals often result in higher premiums.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a friendly deal?",a:"An acquisition where both the buyer and target boards agree to the transaction terms. The target's board recommends that shareholders vote in favor. Most M&A transactions are friendly. The process is more collaborative and typically results in smoother integration.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is due diligence?",a:"A comprehensive investigation of the target's business before closing. Financials, legal, tax, operations, customers, IT, environmental, and HR. It verifies that the target is what it claims to be and identifies risks that could affect valuation or deal structure. Findings can lead to price adjustments or deal termination.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does accretion mean in simple terms?",a:"The deal increases the acquirer's earnings per share (EPS). After the acquisition, each existing shareholder earns more per share than before. This is generally viewed positively by the market, though accretion alone does not guarantee value creation.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does dilution mean in M&A?",a:"The deal decreases the acquirer's EPS. After the acquisition, each existing shareholder earns less per share. This is generally viewed negatively, though a dilutive deal can still be value-creating if the long-term strategic benefits outweigh the short-term EPS reduction.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the basic test for whether a deal is accretive or dilutive?",a:"Compare the target's earnings yield (E/P, inverse of P/E) to the cost of financing. For a cash deal: if the target's yield exceeds the after-tax cost of debt, it is accretive. For a stock deal: if the target's P/E is lower than the buyer's P/E, it is accretive.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is earnings yield?",a:"Net income divided by price (or market cap). The inverse of P/E. A P/E of 20x implies an earnings yield of 5%. It represents the return on your investment if you bought the entire company. Used to compare against financing costs in accretion/dilution analysis.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When is a cash-financed deal accretive?",a:"When the target's earnings yield exceeds the after-tax cost of the cash used. If you fund with debt at 5% pre-tax (3.75% after-tax at 25%) and the target yields 6%, the deal is accretive because you are earning more from the target than you are paying in financing costs.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When is a stock-financed deal accretive?",a:"When the target's P/E is lower than the buyer's P/E. The buyer is using expensive currency (high P/E shares) to buy cheap earnings (low P/E target). The math works because adding more earnings per new share issued increases overall EPS.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does a lower target P/E help accretion?",a:"A lower P/E means you are buying earnings more cheaply. Paying less per dollar of net income. If you pay 10x for a target's earnings and your own stock trades at 20x, each dollar of target earnings is acquired at half the cost, boosting combined EPS.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does issuing high-P/E stock help accretion?",a:"High-P/E stock is expensive currency. Each share issued carries a high price tag. When you use expensive shares to buy a company with cheaper earnings, you are effectively getting more earnings per share issued than you gave up, which increases pro forma EPS.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do synergies affect accretion/dilution?",a:"Synergies add incremental earnings to the combined company, pushing the deal toward accretion. Even a deal that would be dilutive before synergies can become accretive once cost savings and revenue enhancements are factored in. The larger the synergies, the more accretive the deal.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What factors reduce accretion in a deal?",a:"High purchase price (overpaying), high financing costs (expensive debt or low buyer P/E for stock deals), large integration and transaction costs, significant amortization of acquired intangibles, and lower-than-expected synergies. All of these increase costs or reduce incremental earnings.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the typical accretion/dilution timeline?",a:"Deals are often dilutive in the first 1-2 years due to transaction costs, integration expenses, and the time needed to realize synergies. They typically become accretive in years 2-3 as synergies ramp up and one-time costs roll off. Buyers often present a multi-year accretion trajectory.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a break-even deal in accretion/dilution terms?",a:"A deal where pro forma EPS equals the buyer's standalone EPS. No accretion or dilution. This helps determine the maximum price a buyer can pay before the deal becomes dilutive, or the minimum synergies needed to make a dilutive deal break even.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does debt financing affect accretion/dilution?",a:"Debt adds interest expense (reducing earnings) but avoids share dilution. If the after-tax cost of debt is less than the target's earnings yield, using debt is accretive. Debt is often the most accretive financing source because interest rates are typically lower than equity yields.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does stock financing affect accretion/dilution?",a:"Stock avoids interest expense but increases the share count (dilution). Accretive only if the buyer's P/E exceeds the target's P/E. Stock deals also share future upside/downside with target shareholders who receive buyer shares.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is debt often more accretive than stock for financing an acquisition?",a:"Because the after-tax cost of debt (e.g., 3-5%) is almost always lower than the equity earnings yield implied by the buyer's P/E (e.g., 5-8%). Debt is cheaper capital, so it creates less drag on EPS than the dilution from issuing new shares.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why can strategic buyers typically pay more than financial buyers?",a:"Strategic buyers can realize synergies (cost savings, revenue enhancements) that financial buyers cannot. These synergies increase the target's value to the strategic buyer, justifying a higher price. Financial buyers (PE firms) can only pay what the standalone cash flows and leverage will support.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you calculate the target's EPS contribution in a merger model?",a:"Start with the target's net income, adjust for purchase accounting (intangible amortization, D&A step-up), add after-tax synergies, subtract incremental interest expense or foregone interest income, and adjust for any tax rate changes. This gives the net EPS contribution that flows into pro forma combined EPS.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is financing cost in M&A context?",a:"The cost of funding the acquisition. Interest expense on new debt, foregone interest income on cash used, or dilution from shares issued. Each financing source has a different cost, and the optimal mix minimizes the total financing cost while maintaining credit quality.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is pro forma ownership in a stock deal?",a:"The ownership split between the buyer's and target's shareholders after the deal closes. If the buyer issues 30M new shares and had 100M before, the target's shareholders own 30/130 = 23% of the combined company. This affects governance, voting power, and the distribution of future value.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens if synergies are overestimated?",a:"The deal may become dilutive when actual results fall short of projections. The buyer overpaid based on unrealistic assumptions, destroying shareholder value. This is one of the most common M&A failures. Management overpromises synergies to justify a deal price.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why are synergies inherently risky?",a:"They require execution. Integrating systems, cultures, processes, and people. Cost synergies depend on successful layoffs and consolidation. Revenue synergies depend on customer behavior that cannot be controlled. Historical data shows that most deals fail to capture projected synergies fully.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the key takeaway for accretion/dilution analysis?",a:"Accretion/dilution is driven by the interplay of three things: relative valuation (target P/E vs buyer P/E), financing method (cash, debt, stock), and synergies. A deal can be accretive and still destroy value (overpayment), or dilutive and still create value (strategic benefits). EPS impact is one lens, not the whole picture.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Who typically does leveraged buyouts?",a:"Private equity firms. They raise funds from institutional investors (LPs), use those funds plus significant debt to acquire companies, improve operations, and sell at a profit within 3-7 years. The PE firm acts as the general partner (GP) managing the investment.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do PE firms use leverage (debt) in LBOs?",a:"Leverage amplifies equity returns. If you buy a company for $100 using $40 equity and $60 debt, and sell for $150, your equity goes from $40 to $90 (2.25x return). Without debt, the same sale gives $100 to $150 (1.5x). Debt magnifies gains but also magnifies losses.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the goal of an LBO?",a:"Buy a company, improve its operations and cash flow generation, pay down debt using that cash flow, and sell the company at a higher valuation in 3-7 years. The PE firm aims to generate 20%+ IRR for its investors through a combination of EBITDA growth, debt paydown, and ideally multiple expansion.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the three main drivers of LBO returns?",a:"(1) EBITDA growth. Increasing revenue and/or margins to grow operating profit. (2) Debt paydown. Using cash flow to repay debt, which increases equity value. (3) Multiple expansion. Selling at a higher EV/EBITDA multiple than you bought at. The best LBOs achieve all three simultaneously.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is IRR (Internal Rate of Return)?",a:"The annualized rate of return that makes the present value of all cash flows equal to zero. It is the primary return metric in PE because it accounts for both the magnitude and timing of returns. A 2x return in 3 years has a higher IRR than a 2x return in 5 years.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What IRR do PE firms typically target?",a:"20-25% net IRR is the typical target, though this varies by strategy and market conditions. Top-quartile funds consistently achieve 20%+ net returns. Gross IRR (before fees) is higher, typically 25-30%. The hurdle rate for LP capital is usually 8%.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the entry multiple in an LBO?",a:"The EV/EBITDA multiple paid at purchase. For example, buying a company with $100M EBITDA at 8x means the entry EV is $800M. The entry multiple is the single most important driver of LBO returns. Overpaying at entry is the hardest mistake to recover from.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does multiple expansion increase LBO returns?",a:"If you buy at 8x EBITDA and sell at 10x, the exit EV is higher than entry EV even without any EBITDA growth. The difference goes entirely to equity holders since debt is fixed. Multiple expansion is a powerful return driver but is largely market-dependent and not within the sponsor's control.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does debt paydown increase equity returns in an LBO?",a:"As the company repays debt with its cash flow, the equity value grows, because EV minus debt equals equity. If EV stays at $800M but debt drops from $500M to $300M, equity goes from $300M to $500M without any multiple expansion or EBITDA growth. This is the most reliable return driver.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is sponsor equity in an LBO?",a:"The PE firm's own capital contribution to the deal. The equity check. Typically 30-50% of the total purchase price. The remainder is funded by debt. The sponsor equity is the amount at risk and the base for calculating MOIC and IRR.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is debt tranching in an LBO?",a:"Structuring the debt into multiple layers with different risk/return profiles: senior secured debt (lowest cost, first priority), subordinated/mezzanine debt (higher cost, lower priority), and sometimes high-yield bonds. Each tranche has different interest rates, covenants, and repayment terms.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is senior debt in an LBO?",a:"The safest, lowest-cost layer of debt. It has first priority on the company's assets in default. Includes revolving credit facilities and term loans. Senior debt typically has the lowest interest rate (SOFR + 200-400 bps), the tightest covenants, and mandatory amortization.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is mezzanine debt?",a:"A layer of debt subordinated to senior debt, higher risk, higher return. Interest rates of 12-20%, sometimes with equity warrants attached. It fills the gap between senior debt capacity and the equity check. Mezzanine lenders have lower priority than senior lenders in bankruptcy.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is cash flow generation the most important factor in an LBO?",a:"Cash flow services the debt. It pays interest, funds mandatory amortization, and enables optional debt paydown through cash sweeps. Without sufficient cash flow, the company cannot service its debt obligations and risks default. Cash flow generation is what makes leverage possible and safe.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is an exit strategy in PE?",a:"How the PE firm plans to sell its investment and realize returns. The three main exit routes are: (1) sale to a strategic buyer, (2) sale to another PE firm (secondary buyout), and (3) IPO. The choice depends on market conditions, company size, and buyer interest.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is MOIC (Multiple of Invested Capital)?",a:"Exit equity value divided by entry equity value. If you invest $200M and receive $600M at exit, MOIC is 3.0x. MOIC measures total return regardless of time. It is simpler than IRR but does not account for how long the investment was held.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between MOIC and IRR?",a:"MOIC measures total return (3x means you tripled your money). IRR measures annualized return (accounts for timing). A 3x MOIC in 3 years is ~44% IRR. The same 3x in 7 years is ~17% IRR. PE firms report both. MOIC shows magnitude, IRR shows efficiency.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What increases IRR in an LBO?",a:"Faster exit (shorter holding period for same return), higher exit value (EBITDA growth + multiple expansion), more debt paydown (increases equity value), and lower entry price (smaller initial equity check). Time is the enemy of IRR. The same MOIC over fewer years produces higher IRR.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What decreases IRR?",a:"Longer holding period, low or negative EBITDA growth, multiple contraction at exit, inability to pay down debt, and overpaying at entry. Even a profitable investment can have a mediocre IRR if it takes too long to realize.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a typical leverage level in an LBO?",a:"4-6x Debt/EBITDA is typical, though this varies by market conditions and business quality. Stable, cash-generative businesses can support higher leverage (5-6x). Cyclical or capital-intensive businesses use less (3-4x). Peak leverage in frothy markets has reached 7x+.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What makes a good LBO candidate?",a:"Stable, predictable cash flows. Strong market position. Low capital expenditure requirements. Manageable working capital needs. Defensible competitive advantages. Proven management team. Margin improvement potential. Hard assets that can secure debt. In short: a cash machine that can reliably service debt.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why should you avoid high-capex businesses in an LBO?",a:"High CapEx consumes cash that would otherwise be used to pay down debt. Less debt paydown means lower equity returns. A company spending 15% of revenue on CapEx has much less free cash flow than one spending 3%, even at the same EBITDA. LBOs need cash flow, not just earnings.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why should you avoid volatile or cyclical companies in an LBO?",a:"Volatile earnings increase the risk of not being able to service debt during downturns. LBO debt is fixed. Interest and amortization payments do not decrease when EBITDA drops. A company that swings from $100M to $50M EBITDA could breach covenants and face default. Predictability is critical.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is exit equity value in an LBO?",a:"Enterprise value at exit minus net debt remaining at exit. Exit EV = Exit EBITDA x Exit Multiple. Exit equity = Exit EV - remaining debt. This is the cash the PE firm receives (or the value of its shares in an IPO). MOIC = exit equity / entry equity.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is entry equity value in an LBO?",a:"The sponsor's initial investment. Total purchase price minus the debt used to finance the deal. If EV is $800M and debt is $500M, entry equity is $300M. This is the denominator in the MOIC calculation and the cash flow used to calculate IRR.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the single biggest driver of returns in an LBO?",a:"Cash flow generation. Everything else. EBITDA growth, debt paydown, multiple expansion. Depends on the company's ability to generate free cash flow. Strong FCF enables aggressive debt repayment, funds growth initiatives, and provides a cushion against downturns. Without cash flow, leverage becomes a liability, not an advantage.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a deal be accretive but still destroy value?",a:"If the buyer overpays. The EPS increase is mechanical (cheap financing) but the price exceeds intrinsic value. The buyer's stock may drop because the market recognizes the overpayment. Accretion is an accounting test; value creation is an economic test. They are not the same thing.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might a deal be dilutive but still be a good deal?",a:"If the long-term strategic benefits outweigh the short-term EPS reduction, for example, acquiring transformative technology, entering a high-growth market, or building critical scale. Many of the best acquisitions in history were initially dilutive but created enormous long-term value.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why is EPS not a perfect metric for evaluating acquisitions?",a:"EPS ignores cash flow quality, risk changes, balance sheet impact, and long-term value creation. A deal can be accretive simply by buying a cheap company with low-quality earnings. EPS also does not account for the premium paid or whether it was justified by actual synergies.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What matters more than accretion in evaluating an acquisition?",a:"Value creation, whether the combined entity is worth more than the sum of its parts. This depends on whether synergies are real and achievable, whether the price paid was reasonable relative to the value received, and whether the strategic rationale is sound. Accretion is a necessary but not sufficient condition.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do PE firms use IRR instead of EPS to evaluate deals?",a:"PE firms are not public companies. They do not have shareholders tracking quarterly EPS. They care about total return on invested capital over the holding period. IRR measures the annualized return incorporating both magnitude and timing, which is what LPs (their investors) use to evaluate performance.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If interest rates rise, what happens to LBO activity?",a:"LBO activity decreases. Higher rates increase the cost of debt financing, reducing the amount of leverage sponsors can use and compressing returns. Higher rates also tend to compress valuation multiples, widening the gap between buyer and seller price expectations. Deal volume typically slows until expectations reset.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If debt markets tighten, what happens to LBOs?",a:"Less leverage is available, meaning sponsors must contribute more equity per deal. This reduces returns (lower leverage = lower IRR for the same MOIC). Pricing on debt increases and terms become less favorable. Some deals become unfeasible because the returns do not meet hurdle rates.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the biggest risk in an LBO?",a:"Inability to service debt. If the company's cash flow declines, due to recession, competition, operational failure, or customer loss. It may not be able to make interest payments or meet covenant requirements. This leads to default, restructuring, or total loss of equity. Leverage amplifies downside risk as much as it amplifies upside.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens if EBITDA declines after an LBO?",a:"The leverage ratio (Debt/EBITDA) increases because the denominator shrinks. Interest coverage deteriorates. The company may breach debt covenants, triggering technical default. Cash flow for debt paydown dries up. In severe cases, the sponsor loses its entire equity investment. This is why stable cash flows are the most important LBO criterion.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is multiple contraction and how does it affect LBO returns?",a:"Multiple contraction means selling at a lower EV/EBITDA multiple than you bought at. Even if EBITDA grows, selling at a lower multiple reduces exit EV and therefore equity value. If you buy at 10x and sell at 7x, EBITDA needs to grow significantly just to break even on the equity investment.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is timing important in an LBO?",a:"Timing affects both entry and exit. Buying during a downturn (lower multiples, less competition) and selling during an upturn (higher multiples, more buyers) maximizes returns. Holding period directly impacts IRR. The same MOIC over a shorter period produces a much higher IRR. Market timing is a major source of PE returns.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the hardest part of M&A modeling?",a:"Correctly modeling synergies and purchase accounting adjustments. Synergies are uncertain and require judgment about what is achievable. Purchase accounting (PPA, intangible amortization, deferred taxes) involves complex adjustments that affect pro forma earnings. Getting these wrong can fundamentally change whether a deal appears accretive or dilutive.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What separates top candidates on M&A and LBO questions?",a:"Understanding the trade-offs and business logic, not just memorizing formulas. Top candidates can explain WHY a deal is accretive (not just calculate it), articulate the risks of leverage, discuss when synergies are realistic vs aspirational, and connect technical answers to real business decisions.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the core idea behind all M&A and LBO questions?",a:"How is value created, transferred, or destroyed? In M&A: synergies create value, premiums transfer value from buyer to seller, and overpayment destroys value. In LBOs: operational improvement and deleveraging create value, leverage amplifies returns (and risk), and the exit determines whether value is realized.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},

// ═══ FINAL EXPANSION TO 600 ═══
{q:"A company pays $50 in cash to settle a lawsuit. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"If it was never accrued. The income statement takes a $50 litigation expense, tax falls $12.50, and net income falls $37.50. On the cash flow statement, $50 of cash went out but $12.50 came back through a lower tax bill, so cash falls $37.50. On the balance sheet, cash and retained earnings both fall $37.50.\n\nIf it was already accrued. The liability was set up when the loss became probable, so the income statement shows only the difference between the accrual and the actual settlement. The liability comes off and the cash goes out.\n\nThe point: the answer depends entirely on whether the company saw it coming. A company that reserves properly takes the earnings hit early and only moves cash at settlement.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why do we subtract changes in working capital when calculating free cash flow?",a:"Because working capital changes represent cash tied up in or released from operations that is not captured by net income. If AR increases, revenue was recognized but cash was not collected, so we subtract it. If AP increases, expenses were recognized but cash was not paid, so we add it back. FCF should reflect actual cash generated.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has $100M EBITDA, 3x net debt, and trades at 8x EV/EBITDA. What is its equity value?",a:"EV = $100M x 8 = $800M. Net debt = $100M x 3 = $300M. Equity value = EV - Net Debt = $800M - $300M = $500M. This is the standard EV-to-equity bridge that bankers use constantly.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company has a P/E of 20x, what is its earnings yield?",a:"Earnings yield = 1 / P/E = 1 / 20 = 5%. This means for every dollar of market cap, the company generates $0.05 in earnings. Earnings yield is useful for comparing the return on buying a stock versus the cost of debt when analyzing accretion/dilution in M&A.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between a revolver and a term loan?",a:"A revolver is a committed but typically undrawn credit facility, like a corporate credit card that can be drawn and repaid as needed. A term loan is fully drawn at close and repaid on a set schedule (amortization). Term loans have mandatory repayment; revolvers provide flexible liquidity for working capital needs.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why does paying down debt increase equity value in an LBO even if enterprise value stays the same?",a:"Because equity value = EV minus net debt. If EV stays at $800M and debt decreases from $500M to $300M through cash flow repayment, equity goes from $300M to $500M. The sponsor's equity grows without any need for EBITDA growth or multiple expansion. This is the deleveraging return driver.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company earns $200M revenue with 30% EBITDA margins. What is EBITDA?",a:"EBITDA = $200M x 30% = $60M. EBITDA margin = EBITDA / Revenue. This is a fundamental calculation. Bankers need to move fluidly between revenue, margins, and EBITDA since valuation multiples are applied to EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between a cash buyer and a stock buyer in M&A, and why does it matter?",a:"A cash buyer uses cash on hand or debt to pay. No dilution to existing shareholders, but uses liquidity and may increase leverage. A stock buyer issues new shares. Preserves cash but dilutes existing shareholders. Cash deals are simpler and give the target certainty of value; stock deals share future risk and upside with the target's shareholders.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If EBITDA is $100M and total debt is $600M, what is the leverage ratio? Is this high or low?",a:"Leverage ratio = Debt / EBITDA = $600M / $100M = 6.0x. This is on the higher end. Typical LBO leverage is 4-6x. Above 6x is considered aggressive and may signal covenant risk or limited margin for error. Lenders get uncomfortable above this level for most businesses.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me through how you would calculate enterprise value from a company's 10-K.",a:"Start with market cap (share price x diluted shares from the 10-K). Add total debt (short-term + long-term from the balance sheet). Add preferred stock and minority interest if any. Subtract cash and cash equivalents. The result is enterprise value. Always use diluted shares (include in-the-money options via treasury stock method).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might two companies in the same industry with identical EBITDA have different enterprise values?",a:"Different growth rates, margin trajectories, capital intensity, management quality, competitive positioning, customer concentration, geographic mix, recurring vs one-time revenue, and risk profile. A company growing 20% with 90% recurring revenue deserves a much higher multiple than one growing 2% with project-based revenue, even at the same EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to the three statements when a company issues a stock dividend instead of a cash dividend?",a:"Income statement. Nothing.\n\nCash flow statement. Nothing. No cash leaves the business at all.\n\nBalance sheet. Retained earnings fall and common stock plus APIC rise by the same amount. Total equity is identical. The share count goes up.\n\nThe point: this is a reshuffle inside equity that hands every shareholder more shares while each share now represents a smaller slice of the same company. Nobody is better off. EPS falls purely because the denominator grew, which is why a stock dividend is closer to a stock split than to a real dividend.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company buys back $75M of bonds trading at 90 cents on the dollar. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the impact.",a:"The trade. The company spends $67.5M of cash ($75M face at 90 cents) to cancel $75M of debt, so it extinguishes the obligation for less than face value.\n\nIncome statement. A $7.5M gain on extinguishment. Tax of $1.875M leaves net income up $5.625M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $5.625M. Subtract the $7.5M non-cash gain out of operating, then show the $67.5M repurchase as a financing outflow.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $67.5M, debt is down $75M, and retained earnings are up $5.625M. Liabilities fall more than assets, so equity rises and leverage drops.\n\nThe point: the bonds trade at 90 because the market doubts repayment. The company is using cash it has to buy back its own debt cheaply, which deleverages and books a profit. The catch is that the cash is gone, so this only makes sense if liquidity is not the binding constraint.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In an LBO, what does it mean when someone says the deal is 'levered 5x'?",a:"It means total debt at close equals 5 times EBITDA. If EBITDA is $100M, the deal has $500M of debt. The remaining purchase price is funded by sponsor equity. Higher leverage amplifies equity returns but increases default risk. 5x is a common middle-ground level for stable businesses.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the treasury stock method and when is it used?",a:"Used to calculate diluted shares from in-the-money options and warrants. Assume all in-the-money options are exercised, the company receives the exercise proceeds, and uses those proceeds to buy back shares at the current market price. Only the net new shares (exercised minus repurchased) are added to the diluted count. Out-of-the-money options are excluded.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is net income not a good proxy for cash flow?",a:"Net income includes non-cash charges (D&A, SBC, impairments) that reduce income without using cash. It also misses cash consumed by working capital changes, CapEx, and debt repayment. A company can report positive net income while burning cash if AR is growing, inventory is building, or CapEx exceeds D&A. Always look at the cash flow statement.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a fairness opinion and who provides it?",a:"A formal written opinion from an independent financial advisor (usually an investment bank) stating that the consideration in a transaction is fair, from a financial point of view, to a particular party (usually the target's shareholders). It provides legal protection to the board of directors in fulfilling their fiduciary duties. It does not guarantee the deal is the best possible outcome.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between gross debt and net debt, and which matters more?",a:"Gross debt = total debt outstanding. Net debt = gross debt minus cash and cash equivalents. Net debt matters more for valuation because cash on the balance sheet can be used to repay debt, reducing the effective cost of acquiring the business. EV uses net debt. However, lenders often focus on gross leverage for covenant testing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company's unlevered beta is 1.0 and it has a D/E ratio of 0.5 with a 25% tax rate, what is its levered beta?",a:"Levered beta = Unlevered beta x (1 + (1-T) x D/E) = 1.0 x (1 + 0.75 x 0.5) = 1.0 x 1.375 = 1.375. The levered beta is higher because financial leverage amplifies equity risk. This feeds into CAPM to calculate cost of equity, which feeds into WACC.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a PIK toggle and why might a company use it?",a:"A PIK (Payment-In-Kind) toggle gives the borrower the option to pay interest in cash or let it accrue onto the principal balance. Companies use it to preserve cash during periods of tight liquidity. The trade-off: PIK interest compounds, increasing total debt over time. Lenders charge a higher rate for PIK because they bear more risk.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does a sale-leaseback transaction affect the three statements?",a:"Income statement. A gain or loss on the sale, depending on the price versus book value. After that, depreciation on the building disappears and rent expense takes its place.\n\nCash flow statement. A large one-time inflow in investing from the sale, then ongoing lease payments as an operating outflow.\n\nBalance sheet. The building comes off, cash comes in, and a right-of-use asset with a matching lease liability appears.\n\nThe point: the company keeps using the building and turns a static asset into cash today, but it has swapped an owned asset for a contractual obligation. Under current accounting that obligation sits on the balance sheet, so the leverage does not disappear, it just changes name. Companies do this to fund operations when other financing is expensive, which is why it can be a distress signal.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In a merger model, why do you create goodwill?",a:"Goodwill = purchase price minus fair value of identifiable net assets acquired. It arises because buyers pay more than book value for expected synergies, brand value, customer relationships, and other intangibles that cannot be separately identified on the balance sheet. Goodwill sits on the acquirer's balance sheet and is tested annually for impairment, not amortized.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a 338(h)(10) election and why would a buyer want it?",a:"It treats a stock purchase as an asset purchase for tax purposes. The buyer gets a step-up in the tax basis of the target's assets, creating higher future tax deductions through depreciation and amortization. This is valuable because it reduces future cash taxes. The seller typically requires compensation (higher price) because they face higher taxes at close.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company's cost of debt is 6% and the tax rate is 25%, what is the after-tax cost of debt?",a:"After-tax cost of debt = 6% x (1 - 0.25) = 6% x 0.75 = 4.5%. The tax shield makes debt cheaper than its stated rate because interest is tax-deductible. This is why debt is almost always cheaper than equity and why WACC uses the after-tax cost of debt.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a pro forma balance sheet in M&A and what adjustments does it include?",a:"The pro forma balance sheet shows the combined company at close. Key adjustments: eliminate target's old equity, add goodwill and intangible assets from purchase price allocation, record new debt from deal financing, adjust for transaction and financing fees, create deferred tax liabilities on asset step-ups, and reflect any cash used. It must balance: assets = liabilities + equity.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Advanced"},

{q:"What is the difference between a strategic buyer and a financial buyer, and how does it affect the price they can pay?",a:"A strategic buyer is an operating company acquiring for synergies. They can pay more because cost savings and revenue enhancements increase the target's value to them. A financial buyer (PE firm) has no synergies and pays based on standalone cash flows and leverage capacity. Strategics typically pay higher multiples, which is why PE firms often lose in competitive auctions against strategic bidders.",category:"M&A",difficulty:"Intermediate"},

// ═══ EXPANDED ACCOUNTING SET (from IB Interview Questions workbook) ═══
{q:"What are the three main financial statements, and what does each one show?",a:"The three main financial statements are: • Income Statement - Shows revenues, expenses, and net profit (or loss) over a period. • Balance Sheet - Presents assets, liabilities, and shareholders' equity at a point in time. • Cash Flow Statement - Details the company's cash inflows and outflows, categorized into operating, investing, and financing activities.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How are the three main financial statements interconnected?",a:"The three financial statements are closely linked to provide a full picture of a company's financial health. Net Income from the Income Statement connects to both the Balance Sheet and the Cash Flow Statement. It flows into the Shareholders' Equity section on the Balance Sheet under Retained Earnings, and it is the starting point for the Cash Flow Statement. Changes in Balance Sheet items, such as inventory or accounts receivable, are reflected as adjustments in the operating activities section of the Cash Flow Statement. Investing and financing activities, such as capital expenditures or issuing debt, affect Balance Sheet items like PP&E, debt balances, and Shareholders' Equity. The ending cash balance on the Cash Flow Statement flows back to the Balance Sheet, ensuring that all three statements reconcile.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does net income flow into the Balance Sheet?",a:"Net income from the Income Statement flows into the retained earnings line under Shareholders' Equity. The formula is: New Retained Earnings = Previous Retained Earnings + Net Income - Dividends Paid",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you could only look at one financial statement, which would it be? If you could only look at two, which would they be?",a:"One financial statement: You'd choose the Cash Flow Statement because it provides a clear view of the company's cash inflows and outflows, which are crucial for assessing liquidity and financial health. Two financial statements: You'd choose the Income Statement and Balance Sheet, since the Cash Flow Statement can be derived from them (provided you have beginning and ending Balance Sheets that align with the period covered by the Income Statement).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does the Income Statement typically include?",a:"Revenue (sales), Cost of Goods Sold (COGS), Operating Expenses (e.g., SG&A), Other Income/Expenses (e.g., interest expense), Taxes, and Net Income (bottom line).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How is the Balance Sheet organized, and what does it tell you?",a:"It follows the equation: Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity. Assets are listed in order of liquidity, while liabilities are listed by maturity. Equity represents what's left over for the owners after liabilities are subtracted from assets. The balance sheet provides a snapshot of a company's resources (Assets) and shows how those assets were financed (Liabilities and Shareholders' Equity) at a given date.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How is the Cash Flow Statement structured?",a:"It has three sections: • Operating Activities - Starts with net income and adjusts for non-cash items and changes in working capital. • Investing Activities - Relates to purchase or sale of long-term assets like equipment or investments. • Financing Activities - Involves issuing or repaying debt/equity and paying dividends.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Under what circumstances might a company record revenue before actually receiving cash?",a:"Under accrual accounting, revenue is recognized when it's earned and collection is reasonably assured. Examples include credit sales, subscription services billed before receipt of cash, and long-term contracts that recognize revenue over the service period.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the fundamental difference between cash-based accounting and accrual-based accounting?",a:"Cash-based. Recognizes revenue and expenses only when cash changes hands. Accrual-based. Recognizes revenue when earned and expenses when incurred, regardless of when cash is exchanged.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can a company be profitable but still run out of cash? How?",a:"Yes. Under accrual accounting, revenue can be recorded before the cash is received, and expenses can be recorded before the cash is paid out. Common reasons include: • Significant investment in Working Capital (Inventory, A/R). • High Capital Expenditures (Capex). • Large debt principal repayments. • Dividend payments to shareholders.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can you provide an example of a scenario where an asset increases but it doesn't immediately affect the Income Statement?",a:"Buying inventory (whether with cash or on credit) increases the inventory asset on the Balance Sheet but doesn't affect the Income Statement until that inventory is sold (at which point it appears under COGS).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does depreciation affect each financial statement?",a:"• Income Statement - Depreciation is an expense that reduces operating income and net income. • Cash Flow Statement - Depreciation is added back in the operating section since it's non-cash. • Balance Sheet - Accumulated depreciation reduces the value of fixed assets (PP&E).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If depreciation expense increases by $10 and the tax rate is 30%, how is net income impacted?",a:"Pre-tax income falls by $10, so tax expense is $3 lower (30% of $10). Net income decreases by $7 overall.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is working capital, and why is it important?",a:"Working Capital = Current Assets - Current Liabilities. It measures a company's short-term liquidity and ability to meet near-term obligations. A positive working capital suggests the firm can comfortably pay off its short-term liabilities.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When might negative operating net working capital (NWC) be a good thing?",a:"Negative operating NWC can be healthy when customers pay before delivery while suppliers/landlords are paid later-so A/P and accruals exceed A/R and inventory (e.g., fast-food, grocery, big-box retail, certain e-commerce). The supplier/customer float funds the business, improving cash conversion and reducing external capital needs-as long as it's durable (high turns, predictable demand, bargaining power).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Name some non-cash expenses and explain why they're added back on the Cash Flow Statement.",a:"Depreciation, Amortization, Stock-based compensation, and Asset write-downs. These reduce net income but do not require an actual cash outflow during the period, so adding them back restores the true cash position.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do changes in inventory generally affect the Income Statement?",a:"Simply buying more inventory has no immediate effect on the Income Statement until the inventory is sold. Once sold, it is recorded as Cost of Goods Sold, reducing the company's gross profit.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the relationship between accounts receivable, accounts payable, and cash flow?",a:"Accounts Receivable - Revenue recognized but not yet collected; an increase in AR can reduce short-term cash flow. Accounts Payable - Expenses incurred but not yet paid; an increase in AP can boost short-term cash flow.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A client pays $10,000 in advance for a service next quarter. Does that immediately raise net income?",a:"No. The $10,000 is recorded as deferred revenue on the Balance Sheet until the service is performed. Only then is it recognized as revenue on the Income Statement, affecting net income.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does it mean to capitalize an expense rather than expense it immediately?",a:"Capitalizing places the cost on the Balance Sheet as an asset if it confers future economic benefit (lasting more than one year). It is then depreciated or amortized over time, rather than reducing net income in a single period.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you derive the Cash Flow Statement from the Income Statement and Balance Sheet?",a:"Begin with net income, add back non-cash expenses (like depreciation) and adjust for changes in working capital (derived from current assets and liabilities). Then incorporate cash flows from investing and financing activities. The ending result is the net change in cash.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can shareholders' equity go negative, and if so, under what circumstances?",a:"Yes. Persistent losses can drive retained earnings negative. Also, leveraged buyouts or dividend recapitalizations can deplete equity if owners take out large cash amounts.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What do intangible assets represent on the Balance Sheet?",a:"They are non-physical assets such as patents, trademarks, and customer relationships, often recognized through acquisitions. Intangible assets are recorded separately from goodwill and may be amortized depending on their useful lives.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might EBITDA be an imperfect measure of cash flow?",a:"EBITDA omits capital expenditures, changes in working capital, interest, and tax payments. These items can significantly affect actual cash flow, making EBITDA an incomplete measure of liquidity.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are treasury shares (treasury stock), and how do they show up in shareholders' equity?",a:"Treasury shares are previously issued shares repurchased by the company. They appear as a contra-equity account in shareholders' equity, reducing total equity.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between depreciation and amortization?",a:"Depreciation applies to tangible assets (e.g., PP&E), while amortization applies to intangible assets (e.g., patents, trademarks). Both spread the asset's cost over its useful life, but they differ in terms of the asset type.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you forecast depreciation for a multi-year model if the company only provides total PP&E figures?",a:"You might estimate a historical depreciation rate (depreciation as a percentage of beginning PP&E). If available, refine with management guidance on capex plans and asset life, or build a schedule splitting out different asset classes.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are deferred tax assets (DTAs) and deferred tax liabilities (DTLs), and when do they arise?",a:"These result from timing discrepancies between deductions recognized for cash-based taxes versus deductions reported for accounting purposes. • Deferred Tax Liabilities (DTLs) occur when tax expense is recognized on the Income Statement, but the actual cash payment hasn't yet occurred. • Deferred Tax Assets (DTAs) occur when taxes are paid in cash before being recognized as expenses on the Income Statement. Most commonly, these arise from asset write-ups and write-downs during M&A transactions: asset write-ups create deferred tax liabilities, while asset write-downs create deferred tax assets.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Under what circumstances might goodwill be written down, and how is that shown in the financial statements?",a:"Goodwill is written down if a review shows the fair value of the acquired business (or intangible assets) is below its carrying amount. The write-down appears as an impairment charge on the Income Statement and reduces the Goodwill line item on the Balance Sheet.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company raises $100 of debt to purchase manufacturing equipment, how does that affect the statements immediately?",a:"Income statement. Nothing immediately. Borrowing is not income and buying equipment is not an expense. The interest and depreciation both start in later periods.\n\nCash flow statement. A $100 inflow in financing from the debt and a $100 outflow in investing for the equipment. They offset exactly, so net cash is zero.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E is up $100 and debt is up $100. Assets and liabilities both rise, and equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the money was raised and spent in the same breath, so the cash balance never changes even though $100 came in and $100 went out. The company is now bigger and more levered, and the cost of both decisions lands from next period onward.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company raises $100 of debt to purchase manufacturing equipment. One year later, that equipment has 10% depreciation, and the debt carries 5% interest (no principal repayment). Walk through the changes to the 3 statements after one year. Assume a 40% tax rate.",a:"Starting on the IS... • Depreciation expense of $10 and interest expense of $5 reduce pre-tax income by $15. • With a 40% tax rate, you pay $6 in taxes, so net income is down by $9. Moving onto the SCF... • Net income is down $9. • Add back the $10 of non-cash depreciation. • Net cash from operations is therefore up $1 (-$9 + $10). • No other changes in financing or investing this period, so overall net change in cash is +$1. Finally, on the BS... • Assets: Cash is up $1. PP&E is down $10 due to depreciation. Net change in assets is -$9. • Liabilities: Debt remains at $100, since no principal repayment was made. • Shareholders' Equity: Retained Earnings is down $9, matching the decrease in net income. ...and the Balance Sheet balances",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does stock-based compensation expense flow through each financial statement?",a:"Income statement. Stock-based compensation is an operating expense like cash salary, so pre-tax income and net income both fall.\n\nCash flow statement. Net income is lower, but the company paid in shares rather than money, so the entire expense is added back in operating. Cash actually ends up slightly higher, by the tax saved on the deduction.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up by that tax saving and liabilities do not move. Inside equity, APIC rises by the full expense while retained earnings fall by the after-tax amount, so total equity barely moves. The diluted share count climbs as awards vest.\n\nThe point: no cash left, and shareholders still paid. The cost is settled in ownership rather than money, which is why adding SBC back to reach adjusted EBITDA is one of the most contested practices in the market. It is genuinely non-cash and the dilution is genuinely real.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When should non-recurring charges be added back to EBITDA, and when might they remain?",a:"They are added back if they are truly one-time and affect operating income (e.g., a major restructuring). If charges recur often or are non-operational (like interest), you generally don't adjust EBITDA for them.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why is a capital lease accounted for differently than an operating lease?",a:"A capital lease effectively transfers ownership rights for a longer term, often covering most of an asset's useful life. It is capitalized on the Balance Sheet as both an asset and a corresponding lease liability, incurring depreciation and interest expenses. An operating lease is treated more like a rental, though updated accounting rules often require capitalizing many leases anyway.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If the Cash Flow Statement shows higher depreciation than the Income Statement, why might that happen?",a:"Some depreciation may be embedded across various Income Statement line items (e.g., part in COGS, part in SG&A). The footnotes or the Cash Flow Statement might combine these amounts, leading to a higher total depreciation number than what is explicitly shown on the Income Statement.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you typically model items such as accounts payable or deferred revenue in a 3-statement forecast?",a:"They are often projected as a percentage of the associated line item (e.g., AP as a % of COGS; deferred revenue as a % of sales). The changes in these balances then affect operating cash flow in the forecast.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Describe a bottom-up vs. top-down approach for revenue forecasting.",a:"Bottom-up. Start with individual products/customers, unit volumes, prices, or subscription rates, then aggregate upward. Top-down. Begin with the total addressable market, estimate market share, and derive revenue from that broader metric.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Besides losses, what else might cause retained earnings to decrease?",a:"Retained earnings can also decrease due to dividends paid or certain accounting restatements that lower previously reported net income.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How should significant one-time gains or losses be handled when evaluating a company's ongoing profitability?",a:"They are typically removed or adjusted out to show normalized earnings (like adjusted EBITDA or adjusted net income). This approach highlights recurring profitability rather than one-off events.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the concept of the mid-year convention in depreciation and why it might be used.",a:"The mid-year convention assumes assets are placed in service (or disposed of) halfway through the year, so only a half-year's depreciation is recorded in the first and last years. It can increase accuracy for capital-intensive firms purchasing assets continuously throughout the year.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Under what circumstances might a company have positive net income but be unable to pay its bills?",a:"• Large accounts receivable that delay actual cash inflows. • High interest or principal due immediately on debt. • Significant capital expenditures not reflected in net income timing.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company divests a portion of a subsidiary but still retains majority ownership, how are the statements affected?",a:"If control is retained (e.g., 80% → 60%), the sale is an equity transaction: no gain/loss on the Income Statement and no asset remeasurement. Cash increases by proceeds; on the Balance Sheet, Non-controlling Interest (NCI) is adjusted to reflect the new minority share and the plug goes to parent equity/APIC. On the Cash Flow Statement, proceeds are a financing inflow (changes in ownership interests with NCI are financing, not investing). Going forward, \"Net income attributable to NCI\" rises and \"to the parent\" falls; in CFO, starting from consolidated NI, you add back NI attributable to NCI (non-cash to the parent), so no direct operating cash impact from the split itself.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is other comprehensive income (OCI), and how is it different from net income?",a:"OCI includes items like foreign currency translation adjustments, unrealized gains/losses on certain securities, and pension adjustments that bypass the Income Statement. Net income reflects the operating profitability, while OCI accumulates in shareholders' equity (Accumulated OCI).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How might net operating losses (NOLs) factor into a company's financial projections?",a:"NOLs can offset future taxable income, reducing cash taxes. You reduce forecasted taxable income by the available NOLs until they're used up, lowering tax expense and boosting cash flow in those periods.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Where might you see intangible asset amortization on the Income Statement, and how do you project it?",a:"It could be combined with operating expenses (often SG&A) or shown as a separate line item. Projection methods vary: a straightforward approach uses straight-line over the asset's life, whereas a detailed model may allocate different assets distinct amortization schedules.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you see a large jump in deferred revenue, what would you want to investigate?",a:"Check if billing practices changed, new subscription deals were introduced, or recognized revenue lagged new billings. A surge in deferred revenue often means customers have paid upfront for services not yet delivered.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you treat convertible debt on the financial statements, and under what circumstances might it be considered equity?",a:"Convertible debt is initially a liability, with interest expense recognized. If conversion triggers (e.g., a certain stock price), the debt may convert to equity. Some standards split convertible instruments into debt and equity portions from the start, depending on conversion likelihood.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might a company use accelerated depreciation for tax purposes but straight-line for GAAP reporting?",a:"Accelerated depreciation lowers taxable income sooner, deferring cash tax payments and improving short-term cash flow. Straight-line depreciation smooths earnings for GAAP, reducing volatility in reported financial statements. This timing difference creates deferred tax liabilities.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a bill-and-hold arrangement, and how does it affect revenue recognition?",a:"In a bill-and-hold arrangement, the customer is billed but the seller retains possession until a future date. Revenue recognition may be delayed until the customer obtains control under specific criteria, because delivery is typically a key factor in recognizing revenue.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Assuming a 30% tax rate, walk me through 3 statements with a $50 increase in stock-based compensation.",a:"Starting on the IS... • Pre-tax income down by 50 • NI down by 35 Moving onto the SCF... • NI down by 35 • Add back 50 in CFO since stock-based compensation is a non-cash expense • Net change in cash is up 15 Finally, on the BS... • A: Assets up by 15 (cash up 15) • L: No change in liabilities • SE: Shareholder's Equity up by 15 (stock-based comp up 50, NI down 35) ...and the Balance Sheet balances",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Assuming a 30% tax rate, walk me through 3 statements with a $120 decrease in depreciation.",a:"Starting on the IS... • Pre-tax income up $120 • NI up $84 Moving onto the SCF... • NI +84 • Depreciation is down by 120, meaning you lose that 120 non-cash add-back • Net cash down 36 Finally, on the BS... • A: Cash down 36, PP&E up 120, net +84 • L: No change • SE: +84 from NI ...and the Balance Sheet balances",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Assuming a 30% tax rate, walk me through 3 statements with a $100 interest expense (50% cash / 50% PIK) and $50 interest income.",a:"Starting on the IS... • Net interest expense is 50 (100 expense - 50 income) • Pre-tax income down 50 • NI down 35 Moving onto the SCF... • NI -35 • Add back 50 PIK in CFO • Net +15 in cash Finally, on the BS... • A: Cash +15 • L: Debt +50 (PIK portion) • SE: -35 in Retained Earnings ...and the Balance Sheet balances",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Assuming a 30% tax rate, walk me through 3 statements with a $20 decrease in Deferred Revenue.",a:"Starting on the IS... • Revenue +20 (Deferred revenue is recognized) • Pre-tax income +20 • NI +14 Moving onto the SCF... • NI +14 • Subtract 20 from Deferred Revenue (Non-cash revenue) • Net -6 in cash (Taxes paid) Finally, on the BS... • A: Cash -6 • L: Deferred Revenue -20 • SE: +14 in Retained Earnings ...and the Balance Sheet balances",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"MULTI-STEP: Assuming a 20% tax rate. Year 0: Buy PP&E for $100 using Debt. Year 2: PP&E depreciates over 10-year period using straight-line. After two years, you sell the PP&E for $120. Walk me through the statements for the sale transaction only.",a:"Year 0, for context. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of CapEx is an investing outflow and the $100 of debt is a financing inflow, so cash does not move. PP&E and debt both rise $100.\n\nThe sale in Year 2. Two years of depreciation at $10 a year leaves a book value of $80. Selling at $120 gives a $40 gain, and after 20% tax net income rises $32.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $32. Subtract the $40 gain out of operating so it is not counted twice, then add the full $120 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $112.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $112 and PP&E is down $80, so assets rise $32. Retained earnings are up $32 and it balances.\n\nThe point: the gain is measured against depreciated book value, not the original price. Depreciation had already written the asset down to $80, so selling at $120 books a profit even though the asset only appreciated $20 above what was paid.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"MULTI-STEP: Assuming a 20% tax rate. You raise $100 debt with 5% interest and 10% yearly principal repayment. You purchase $100 of short-term assets with 10% yearly interest income. Walk through Part 1) at purchase and Part 2) after one year.",a:"At purchase. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of debt is a financing inflow and the $100 of assets bought is an investing outflow, so net cash is zero. Assets and debt both rise $100.\n\nAfter one year. The assets earn 10%, so interest income is $10, and the debt costs 5%, so interest expense is $5. Pre-tax income is $5 and net income is $4 after 20% tax.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $4, then repay 10% of principal, which is $10 out in financing. Net cash falls $6.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $6, debt is down $10, and retained earnings are up $4. Assets fall $6, and liabilities plus equity fall $6 too.\n\nThe point: the spread is genuinely profitable, earning 10% on money that costs 5%, and cash still goes down, because principal amortization is far larger than the spread. Profitable and cash-hungry at the same time.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Revenue is $100M with EBITDA of $10M, and 50% of costs are variable. If revenue drops by 10%, what happens to EBITDA?",a:"At $100M revenue and $10M EBITDA, total costs are $90M. Half ($45M) are variable, half ($45M) fixed. Revenue falls 10% to $90M. Variable costs drop to $40.5M. Fixed costs stay at $45M. Total costs = $85.5M. New EBITDA = $90M - $85.5M = $4.5M. EBITDA declines by $5.5M (from $10.0 to $4.5).",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"MULTI-STEP: Year 0: Buy Land for $90 using cash. Year 2: Straight-line depreciation over 10 years. Sell land for $90. Walk through statements.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. Cash falls $90 in investing and land of $90 appears. A pure asset swap.\n\nYear 2, and this is the trap. Land is not depreciated, because it has an indefinite useful life. So there is no depreciation in any year and the book value is still $90.\n\nThe sale. Selling at $90 against a book value of $90 is no gain and no loss, so the income statement shows nothing and there is no tax. Cash rises $90 in investing and land comes off at $90. Equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the question hands you a depreciation schedule for an asset that cannot be depreciated. Applying it would create a fake book value, a fake gain, and a fake tax bill. The answer is to notice the premise is wrong.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you calculate DSO, inventory days, and days payable?",a:"DSO = (Accounts Receivable / Revenue) x 365 Inventory Days = (Inventory / COGS) x 365 Days Payable = (Accounts Payable / COGS) x 365",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you are the CFO and about to miss earnings by $0.01, what levers can you pull?",a:"You can manipulate short-term timing of revenue or expenses: • Early recognition of some revenue if permissible • Delay certain expenses (e.g., marketing or SG&A) • Change inventory accounting methods • Adjust depreciation assumptions • Repurchase a small number of shares to reduce share count All subject to legal and accounting constraints.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is Sarbanes-Oxley (SOX) and what impact does it have?",a:"SOX is a 2002 U.S. law passed in response to major accounting scandals (Enron, WorldCom). It mandates stricter internal controls, audits, and CEO/CFO certification of financial statements, increasing corporate governance, transparency, and compliance costs.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the differences in impact when you compare an Asset Write-Down vs. a Liability Write-Down?",a:"An Asset Write-Down is recorded as a non-cash impairment charge on the Income Statement, reducing net income. It is then added back to net income in CFO. A Liability Write-Down (e.g., gain on debt extinguishment) is recorded as a non-cash gain on the Income Statement, increasing net income. This gain is then subtracted from net income in CFO.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Days Payable Outstanding goes from 30 days to 90 days. Source or use of cash?",a:"It is a source of cash because you delay paying suppliers. By postponing payables, you keep the cash longer and can reinvest it until you must pay the bills.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Revenue of 100 with a 20% margin and 50/50 variable/fixed cost split. How does EBITDA change if volume increases 10%?",a:"EBITDA increases from 20 to 26. Total Costs = 100 - 20 = 80. Fixed = 40, Variable = 40. Volume +10%: Revenue = 110, Variable Costs = 44. Fixed Costs stay at 40. New EBITDA = 110 - 44 - 40 = 26.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You sell PP&E for $100 cash for a gain of $20. Assume 25% tax rate. Walk through the 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The gain is $20, so pre-tax income rises $20 and net income rises $15 after 25% tax.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $15. Subtract the $20 gain out of operating, because the full proceeds are about to be counted in investing. Then add the $100 of proceeds. Cash rises $95.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $95 and PP&E comes off at its book value of $80, since a $100 sale with a $20 gain means the asset was carried at $80. Assets rise $15 and retained earnings rise $15.\n\nThe point: the gain is subtracted in operating purely to avoid double counting, not because it is not real. The company keeps $95 of the $100, with $5 going to tax on the gain.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Land with book value $300 sold for $400 cash. 25% tax rate. Walk through the 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The gain is $100 ($400 less the $300 book value). Tax of $25 leaves net income up $75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $75. Subtract the $100 gain out of operating, then add the $400 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $375.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $375 and land is down $300, so assets rise $75. Retained earnings are up $75.\n\nThe point: land is never depreciated, so its book value is still the original cost. The entire $100 of appreciation lands as gain in the year of sale, and the company keeps $375 of the $400 after tax.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company with $500 cash and $500 SE purchases $1,000 of PP&E using $500 cash and $500 new debt. Walk through statements at purchase.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Buying an asset is not an expense.\n\nCash flow statement. The full $1,000 of CapEx is an investing outflow and the $500 debt raise is a financing inflow, so net cash falls $500.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E is up $1,000 and cash is down $500, so assets rise $500. Debt is up $500 and equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the company just spent every dollar of its cash. Note that the whole $1,000 shows in investing even though only half was the company's own money. Depreciation and interest start next period, and with no cash left the asset had better start producing.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you could get only one GAAP line to assess a company, which would you choose and why?",a:"Many prefer cash flow from operations (CFO) since it's a pure measure of cash generated from core operations, less impacted by accounting assumptions than net income alone. However, some might choose net income for a clean measure of profitability after all expenses. Answers can vary, but CFO is often considered most indicative of a firm's health.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some examples of non-recurring charges?",a:"Restructuring costs, asset write-downs, goodwill impairments, and legal settlements. These occur outside the normal course of business and are usually excluded from metrics like EBITDA when analyzing core performance.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a stock option?",a:"A derivative contract giving the holder the right, but not the obligation, to buy (call) or sell (put) a set number of shares at a predetermined strike price before or at expiration.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In the P/E ratio, should shares used to calculate EPS be point-in-time or average over a period?",a:"The number of shares should be an average over the period (weighted average shares outstanding). EPS uses Net Income (accumulates over a period) divided by weighted average shares outstanding. This matches timing of earnings generation with share count. Using point-in-time would misstate EPS if shares were issued or repurchased. The P/E numerator (current price) is point-in-time, but EPS uses period-average shares for consistency.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company wants to boost its EPS, what actions can it take?",a:"• Increase net income through revenue growth or cost reductions • Repurchase shares to reduce shares outstanding • Improve operating margins through efficiency gains • Divest underperforming or non-core assets • Acquire accretive businesses • Optimize capital structure • Reduce tax burden • Cut dividend to retain more earnings • Recognize deferred tax assets or one-time gains Note: Some provide sustainable EPS growth while others are financial engineering. The market values sustainable operational improvements more highly.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assuming 25% tax rate, walk through 3 statements for sale of asset for $500 with book value of $400.",a:"Income statement. The gain is $100 ($500 less the $400 book value). Tax of $25 leaves net income up $75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $75. Subtract the $100 gain out of operating, then add the $500 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $475.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $475 and the asset is down $400, so assets rise $75. Retained earnings are up $75.\n\nThe point: only the $100 above book value is taxable, not the $500 received. The company collects $500 and keeps $475.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assuming 25% tax rate and 10-year straight-line depreciation, walk through 3-statement impact of $100 Capex financed with cash. Part 1: At purchase. Part 2: After one year.",a:"At purchase. Nothing on the income statement, because buying an asset is not an expense. Cash falls $100 in investing and PP&E rises $100. Total assets are unchanged, just a swap of cash for a machine.\n\nAfter one year. Depreciation is $10 ($100 over 10 years), so pre-tax income falls $10 and net income falls $7.50. On the cash flow statement, net income is down $7.50 but the $10 of depreciation is added back, so cash actually rises $2.50. On the balance sheet, cash is up $2.50 and PP&E is down $10, so assets fall $7.50, matching retained earnings.\n\nThe point: all $100 of cash left in year one and none of it touched earnings. Then earnings take a $10 hit each year with no cash attached. This split between when cash moves and when the expense lands is the whole reason CapEx-heavy businesses look so different on EBITDA than on free cash flow.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through a $10 inventory purchase with cash, then selling it for $20. No taxes.",a:"At purchase. Nothing on the income statement, because inventory is not an expense until it sells. Cash falls $10 and inventory rises $10. Total assets are unchanged.\n\nAt sale. Revenue is $20 and COGS is $10, so net income is $10 with no tax in this scenario. On the cash flow statement, net income is up $10 and inventory falls $10, which is a source of cash, so cash rises $20. On the balance sheet, cash is up $20 and inventory is down $10, so assets rise $10, matching retained earnings.\n\nThe point: cash left in the first step and came back doubled in the second, while the expense only appeared at the moment of sale. That lag between paying for inventory and getting paid for it is the working capital cycle, and it is why a fast-growing retailer can be profitable and still run out of money.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the accounting treatment when you receive $10 but haven't provided the service yet? What happens when you finally provide it?",a:"When the $10 arrives. Nothing on the income statement, because nothing has been earned. Cash rises $10 and a $10 deferred revenue liability appears. It is a liability because the company now owes the customer a service.\n\nWhen the service is delivered. The income statement finally books $10 of revenue and net income rises $10. On the cash flow statement, net income is up $10 but deferred revenue falls $10, which offsets it exactly, so no cash moves. On the balance sheet, the liability comes off and retained earnings rise $10.\n\nThe point: the cash and the revenue happen in different periods. The company gets paid first and earns it later, which is the best working capital position a business can have and the reason subscription models are prized.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assuming 25% tax rate, walk through 3 statements after inventory sold for $20 in cash. Inventory cost was $10.",a:"Income statement. Revenue is $20 and COGS is $10, so gross profit is $10. Tax of $2.50 leaves net income up $7.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $7.50. Inventory fell $10 as the goods shipped, which is a source of cash, so add $10. Cash rises $17.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $17.50 and inventory is down $10, so assets rise $7.50. Retained earnings are up $7.50.\n\nThe point: the customer handed over $20, and $17.50 sticks after the $2.50 of tax. The cash for the inventory was spent in an earlier period, which is why cash rises by more than profit here.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Accounts Receivable increases by $2. Walk through 3 statements assuming 40% tax rate.",a:"Income statement. The receivable came from a sale, so revenue rises $2 and pre-tax income rises $2. Tax of $0.80 at 40% leaves net income up $1.20.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $1.20. Receivables rose $2, which is a use of cash, so subtract $2. Net cash falls $0.80.\n\nBalance sheet. Receivables are up $2 and cash is down $0.80, so assets rise $1.20. Retained earnings are up $1.20.\n\nThe point: the company made a profitable sale and its cash went down. The customer has not paid, but the tax authority still wants its $0.80 now. That is the mechanic behind growing companies burning cash.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has EBIT larger than EBITDA. Why would that be puzzling?",a:"EBITDA = EBIT + D&A, and D&A is a positive value. If D&A appears negative, this is unusual and usually indicates an error, a reversal, or an accounting adjustment.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through the 3 statements right after a company issues $100 million of debt.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Borrowing is not income.\n\nCash flow statement. A $100M inflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $100M and debt is up $100M. Assets and liabilities both rise, and equity does not move.\n\nThe point: on day one the business is completely unchanged, just holding someone else's money. The interest starts hitting the income statement next period, which is when the debt actually costs something.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Does a 10% increase in revenue result in a 10% increase in profits?",a:"Only if costs scale 100% with revenue. With fixed costs, operating leverage makes profit grow >10%; if margins compress, profit could grow <10% or even fall.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Intuitively, why does an increase in net working capital reduce cash on the cash-flow statement?",a:"An increase either builds current assets or pays down current liabilities, both of which use cash. Growing inventories, receivables or prepaids ties up cash before revenue is collected. Reducing payables or accrued expenses sends cash out the door sooner.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Beginning with revenue, how do you calculate EBITDA?",a:"EBITDA = Revenue - COGS - Operating Expenses + Depreciation & Amortization (if D&A was included in either COGS or OpEx buckets) Start with revenue. Subtract COGS for gross profit. Subtract SG&A, R&D and other OpEx for operating income. Add back any D&A included in COGS or OpEx.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain EBITDA to me as if I were a 5-year-old.",a:"EBITDA is how much money a business makes from selling things, after paying for what it needs to make those things, but before paying interest on loans, taxes to the government, or accounting for its stuff getting old. It's like your lemonade stand's profits before you pay back money you borrowed from your parents, pay your allowance tax, or count that your pitcher got a crack in it.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What financial metric does EBITDA approximate?",a:"EBITDA approximates cash flow from operations before changes in working capital. It represents the operating cash generation by excluding non-cash charges (D&A), financing costs (interest), and taxes. However, EBITDA is not true cash flow since it ignores working capital changes and capital expenditures.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assuming 30% tax rate, walk through 3 statements for a $10 million increase in depreciation expense.",a:"Income statement. Depreciation rises $10M, so pre-tax income falls $10M. Tax falls $3M at 30%, leaving net income down $7M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $7M. Depreciation is non-cash, so add the full $10M back. Cash rises $3M.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $3M and PP&E is down $10M, so assets fall $7M. Retained earnings fall $7M.\n\nThe point: earnings fell and cash rose. The $3M is exactly the tax the company no longer owes, which is the depreciation tax shield. It is the clearest demonstration that net income and cash are different measures.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the key differences between a 10-K and a 10-Q?",a:"• 10-K: Annual report with audited financial statements. • 10-Q: Quarterly report with unaudited financial statements. • 10-K is more comprehensive (business overview, risk factors, MD&A). • 10-Q provides updates on quarterly performance and changes. • 10-K filed once per year; 10-Q filed three times per year. • 10-K has stricter disclosure requirements.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assuming 25% tax rate, walk through 3 statements if revenue increases by $100 and Gross Margin is 50%.",a:"Income statement. Revenue rises $100 and a 50% gross margin means COGS of $50, so gross profit is $50. Tax of $12.50 leaves net income up $37.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $37.50. Inventory fell $50 as the goods sold, which is a source of cash, so add $50. Cash rises $87.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $87.50 and inventory is down $50, so assets rise $37.50. Retained earnings are up $37.50.\n\nThe point: this assumes the customer paid in cash and the inventory was already sitting on the shelf, bought in an earlier period. That is why cash rises more than profit. Sell the same goods on credit and cash would go the other way.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What specific balance sheet items do you look at when considering net working capital?",a:"NWC = Operating Current Assets - Operating Current Liabilities. Assets: Accounts Receivable, Inventory, Prepaids Liabilities: Accounts Payable, Accrued Expenses, Deferred Revenue Exclude cash, debt, and other financing items.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is EBITDA, conceptually?",a:"A proxy for recurring operating cash flow before non-cash charges and capital-structure effects. It strips out D&A, interest, taxes and one-offs to facilitate comparability across companies.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Given Revenue = 1000, COGS + SG&A = 600, D&A = 200 (not included in COGS+SG&A). Calculate EBITDA.",a:"Answer: 400 EBITDA = Revenue - COGS - SG&A = 1,000 - 600 = 400 (D&A excluded). Common mistake: adding D&A to cash OPEX. You add D&A back only when starting from EBIT or if the 600 includes D&A. Here it does not.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What's the difference between cash and GAAP EPS?",a:"GAAP EPS follows accounting rules and includes non-cash expenses like depreciation, amortization, stock-based comp, and sometimes intangible write-downs. Cash EPS often excludes non-cash charges to show a closer approximation of actual cash flow generation per share.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Would you rather have $100 in inventory or $100 in receivables?",a:"$100 in receivables. Receivables convert to cash faster and carry no storage or obsolescence risk, improving liquidity and working-capital efficiency. Note: While inventory might be sold for a profit, interviews typically prioritize liquidity and asset quality, making receivables the standard answer.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a $10 increase in unearned revenue flow through the 3 statements?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The company has been paid but has not delivered, so nothing is earned yet.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash rises $10, shown as an increase in unearned revenue inside operating.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $10 and deferred revenue, a liability, is up $10. Equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the company is holding customer money it has not earned. It is a liability because if the company never delivers, it owes that money back. Revenue and the matching tax only arrive later, when the work is done.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me from EBITDA to Levered FCF.",a:"EBITDA - Cash Taxes (after interest shield) - CapEx - Change in NWC - Cash Interest - Mandatory Debt Principal Repayments = Levered Free Cash Flow Start above D&A, so you don't subtract and add it back; D&A only affects taxable income, captured in Cash Taxes. LFCF is cash to equity after interest and required amortization.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Revenue is growing at 10%. Under what circumstances would EBITDA grow at a different percentage?",a:"If margins change. Examples: Operating leverage, price increases, cost cuts, or rising input costs can drive EBITDA growth faster or slower than the top line.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Sell a $100 gift card with $20 COGS and 20% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements at sale and at full redemption.",a:"At sale. Nothing on the income statement, because a gift card is a promise, not a sale. Cash rises $100 and a $100 deferred revenue liability appears.\n\nAt redemption. Now the goods are handed over, so revenue is $100 and COGS is $20, giving pre-tax income of $80. Tax of $16 at 20% leaves net income up $64.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $64. Deferred revenue falls $100, a use of cash, so subtract $100. Inventory falls $20, a source of cash, so add $20. Net cash falls $16, which is exactly the tax now due.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $16 and inventory is down $20, so assets fall $36. Deferred revenue is down $100 and retained earnings are up $64, so liabilities plus equity fall $36 too.\n\nThe point: all the cash came in at sale and all the profit and tax land at redemption. This is why retailers love gift cards, they get the money months before they owe anything.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assume a $200 sale, book value $40, 60% tax rate. Walk through the 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The gain is $160 ($200 less the $40 book value). Tax of $96 at 60% leaves net income up $64.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $64. Subtract the $160 gain out of operating, then add the $200 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $104.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $104 and the asset is down $40, so assets rise $64. Retained earnings are up $64.\n\nThe point: at a 60% tax rate the government takes $96 of the $160 gain, so the company collects $200 and keeps only $104. It shows how brutally the tax rate cuts into the proceeds when an asset has been depreciated down to a low book value.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"From a net income perspective, would you rather have an additional dollar of revenue or cut a dollar of operating expense?",a:"Cutting $1 of expense increases NI by $1 × (1-tax), whereas $1 of extra revenue only increases NI by $1 × margin × (1-tax), which is lower unless margin = 100%.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assume 40% tax rate. Walk through impact of a $10 write-down of PP&E on 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The $10 write-down cuts pre-tax income $10. Tax falls $4 at 40%, leaving net income down $6.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $6. The write-down moved no cash, so add the full $10 back. Cash rises $4.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $4 and PP&E is down $10, so assets fall $6. Retained earnings fall $6.\n\nThe point: the company is admitting the asset is worth less than the books say. The cash was spent years ago, so the only cash effect today is the $4 of tax saved.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"As a CFO during rising prices, would you prefer FIFO or LIFO inventory accounting, and why?",a:"It depends on the CFO's priorities. FIFO: Higher NI (cheaper inventory expensed first), higher taxes, BS reflects current market value. Preferred for stronger reported earnings. LIFO: Lower NI (expensive inventory expensed first), lower taxes, preserves cash. Preferred to minimize tax burden and maximize cash flow. Most CFOs prefer LIFO during inflation to reduce taxes, though IFRS prohibits LIFO.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If D&A is included in SG&A, how would you calculate implied D&A given EBITDA and EBIT?",a:"D&A = EBITDA - EBIT Since EBITDA is before D&A and EBIT is after, the difference between them is precisely the D&A amount.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You have balance sheets for Year 1 and Year 2 plus the cash-flow statement. How would you calculate depreciation for Year 2?",a:"Using CapEx from the CFS and PP&E from the balance sheet (assuming no asset sales): • CapEx = Year 2 PP&E - Year 1 PP&E + Depreciation • Depreciation = CapEx - Year 2 PP&E + Year 1 PP&E",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a negative change in Net Working Capital affect cash flow?",a:"A negative change in NWC (decrease) increases cash flow. Decrease in NWC means: receivables collected faster, inventory reduced, or payables increased. All free up cash. In the Cash Flow Statement, a negative change in NWC is added back to operating cash flow.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does an increase in accounts payable affect unlevered free cash flow?",a:"It raises it dollar-for-dollar. Higher AP is a source of cash, lowering ΔNWC in the FCF formula and boosting unlevered FCF.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company sells $100 of goods on account, cost $50, 20% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. Revenue is $100 and COGS is $50, so pre-tax income is $50. Tax of $10 at 20% leaves net income up $40.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $40. Receivables rose $100 because the sale was on account, which is a use of cash, so subtract $100. Inventory fell $50, a source of cash, so add $50. Net cash falls $10.\n\nBalance sheet. Receivables are up $100, inventory is down $50, and cash is down $10, so assets rise $40. Retained earnings are up $40.\n\nThe point: the most profitable thing the company did all period made its cash go down $10, because the tax is due now and the customer has not paid. Selling on account means funding your customer until they do.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Ice cream shop grows from $100 to $500 revenue. How do margins change? Which SG&A line increases most?",a:"Both Gross Margin and Operating Margin likely improve due to economies of scale, fixed cost absorption, and operational efficiency. Within SG&A, Sales & Marketing would increase the most to drive 5x revenue growth, including advertising, promotions, and headcount for new locations.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You have 100 revenue, 30% EBITDA margin, $10 D&A, 25% tax rate. What is net income?",a:"Net income = $15. EBITDA = $30. EBIT = $30 - $10 = $20. Taxes = 25% × $20 = $5. NI = $20 - $5 = $15",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through 3-statement impact of purchasing $50M equipment using cash on hand.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Buying equipment is not an expense.\n\nCash flow statement. A $50M outflow in investing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $50M and PP&E is up $50M. Total assets are unchanged, and neither liabilities nor equity move.\n\nThe point: a straight swap of one asset for another. Nothing touches earnings until the equipment starts depreciating next period, which is exactly why CapEx never appears on the income statement and why EBITDA ignores it entirely.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company issues $50M debt and immediately pays $50M special dividend. 25% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Borrowing is not income and a dividend is not an expense, so neither leg of this touches earnings.\n\nCash flow statement. A $50M financing inflow from the debt and a $50M financing outflow to shareholders. Net cash is zero.\n\nBalance sheet. Assets do not move at all. Debt is up $50M and retained earnings are down $50M, so equity falls $50M.\n\nThe point: this is a dividend recap. The company borrowed money and handed it straight to its owners. The business is identical, the shareholders are $50M richer, and every dollar of that came from loading the balance sheet with debt. It is a favourite of PE sponsors and a nightmare for lenders, which is why credit agreements restrict it.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Sale generates $4 gross profit. Revenue $10, COGS $6, 25% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. Revenue is $10 and COGS is $6, so gross profit is $4. Tax of $1 leaves net income up $3.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $3. Inventory fell $6 as the goods shipped, which is a source of cash, so add $6. Cash rises $9.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $9 and inventory is down $6, so assets rise $3. Retained earnings are up $3.\n\nThe point: cash rises three times more than profit, because the $6 of inventory was paid for in an earlier period. The customer's $10 arrives now and only $1 goes to tax.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Which affects Net Income most: 10% price increase, 10% volume increase, or 10% COGS reduction? Follow-up: Could COGS cut ever beat price?",a:"10% price increase usually has the biggest impact-it boosts revenue dollar-for-dollar with no extra cost, so the entire uplift flows to NI. Volume increases add variable costs. COGS cuts save only the cost line. If margins are extremely thin or demand is highly price-elastic, a COGS cut could outweigh a price hike.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How can a company generate cash from its working capital? Provide specific examples.",a:"1. Collecting receivables faster: Early payment discounts, improve collections, or factor receivables. 2. Reducing inventory: Just-in-time systems, better demand forecasting, liquidate slow-moving stock. 3. Extending payables: Negotiate longer terms without damaging relationships. Example: A retailer collects from customers in 10 days but pays suppliers in 60 days, generating a 50-day cash benefit.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company starts with PP&E of $600. Records $500 CapEx. Ends with PP&E of $800. What explains the change?",a:"Depreciation of $300 during the year. Reconciliation: Beginning PP&E $600 + CapEx $500 - Depreciation $300 = Ending PP&E $800 Other possibilities: Asset sales/disposals, impairment charges, FX translation adjustments.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Construct an Income Statement to Net Income: Revenue $100, Gross Margin 80%, PP&E $50, Depreciation 10%, Debt $100, Interest 15%, Tax 20%.",a:"Revenue: $100. COGS: $20. Gross Profit: $80. Depreciation: $5 ($50 × 10%). EBIT: $75. Interest: $15 ($100 × 15%). Pre-tax: $60. Tax: $12. Net Income: $48",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk through 3 statements when company buys $200 machine using $100 debt and $100 cash.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Buying a machine is not an expense.\n\nCash flow statement. The full $200 of CapEx is an outflow in investing and the $100 debt raise is an inflow in financing, so net cash falls $100.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E is up $200 and cash is down $100, so assets rise $100. Debt is up $100 and equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the whole $200 shows in investing even though only $100 of the company's own money left. Depreciation and interest both start next period.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"25% tax rate. Asset with $500 book value sold for $400 ($100 loss). Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The asset sold for $400 against a $500 book value, so there is a $100 loss. That loss is deductible, giving a $25 tax benefit, so net income falls $75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $75. Add the $100 loss back in operating, since the full proceeds are counted below. Then add the $400 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $425.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $425 and the asset is down $500, so assets fall $75. Retained earnings fall $75.\n\nThe point: a loss on paper and a large cash inflow at the same time. The company collects $400 and gets $25 back from the tax authority, so it ends up $425 richer in cash while reporting a loss.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"25% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements following $5M inventory write-down.",a:"Income statement. The $5M write-down runs through COGS, so pre-tax income falls $5M. Tax benefit of $1.25M leaves net income down $3.75M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $3.75M. The write-down moved no cash, so add $5M back. Cash rises $1.25M.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $1.25M and inventory is down $5M, so assets fall $3.75M. Retained earnings fall $3.75M.\n\nThe point: the company is conceding the goods will never sell for what they cost. The cash left when the inventory was bought, so today the only cash effect is the tax saving.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would an auto manufacturer's income statement differ from a software company's?",a:"Auto: High COGS (materials, labor), lower gross margins (15-25%), significant D&A from plants, higher working capital, cyclical revenue. Software: Low COGS (hosting, support), high gross margins (70-90%), lower D&A, higher R&D and S&M as % of revenue, deferred revenue common, more predictable recurring revenue.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company raises $200 debt at 10% interest. 20% tax rate. Walk through first year statements.",a:"Income statement. The only thing that hits earnings is the interest. $200 at 10% is $20, so pre-tax income falls $20. Tax falls $4 at 20%, leaving net income down $16. The $200 of principal never touches the income statement.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $16, which already reflects the interest paid. The $200 debt raise is an inflow in financing. Net cash rises $184.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $184, debt is up $200, and retained earnings are down $16. Assets rise $184, and liabilities plus equity rise $184 too.\n\nThe point: the company is holding $184 more cash and is $16 poorer. It has borrowed money it has not yet put to work, and it is already paying for the privilege.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does Goodwill impairment impact Net Income?",a:"Goodwill impairment is a non-cash charge that reduces Net Income dollar-for-dollar (after tax effects). The impairment flows through the IS as an expense, reducing pre-tax income and NI. On the CFS, it's added back in CFO since it's non-cash, resulting in no impact on actual cash flow.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You purchase $50 of inventory using cash. How do the 3 statements change?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Inventory is an asset until it sells, then it becomes COGS.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash falls $50 as a use of working capital in operating.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $50 and inventory is up $50. Total assets are unchanged, and neither liabilities nor equity move.\n\nThe point: spending cash is not the same as recording an expense. The expense waits until the goods are sold, which is the matching principle in its simplest form.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Define working capital and list core components. What would Walmart's working-capital profile look like?",a:"Working Capital = Current Assets - Current Liabilities (often focusing on operating items). Components: Cash, AR, inventory, AP, accrued expenses. Walmart: Likely negative working capital due to quick customer payments, slower payables, and high inventory turnover.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Describe the difference between financial accounting and managerial accounting.",a:"Financial: External reporting, follows GAAP/IFRS, historical, mandatory/audited, examples include IS/BS/CFS. Managerial: Internal reporting, no required standards, forward-looking with budgets/forecasts, not audited. In IB, financial accounting is more relevant as it forms the basis for valuation, due diligence, and transaction analysis.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Buy $100 PPE using all debt, 10% interest, 10% depreciation, 25% tax. Walk through Year 0 and Year 1.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of CapEx is an investing outflow and the $100 of debt is a financing inflow, so cash does not move. PP&E and debt both rise $100.\n\nYear 1. Depreciation is $10 and interest is $10, so pre-tax income falls $20. Tax falls $5, leaving net income down $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $15, then add back the $10 of depreciation. Cash falls $5.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $5 and PP&E is down $10, so assets fall $15. Debt is unchanged and retained earnings are down $15.\n\nThe point: both charges are $10 and only one costs cash. The interest is real money leaving; the depreciation is an accounting allocation of money that left in Year 0.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Salesforce sells $100 contract upfront for 1-year service. 25% tax rate. Walk through at signing and six months later.",a:"At signing. Nothing on the income statement, because no service has been delivered. Cash rises $100 and a $100 deferred revenue liability appears.\n\nSix months later. Half the contract has been delivered, so $50 of revenue is recognized. Tax of $12.50 leaves net income up $37.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $37.50. Deferred revenue fell $50, a use of cash, so subtract $50. Net cash falls $12.50, which is the tax now owed.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $12.50, deferred revenue is down $50, and retained earnings are up $37.50.\n\nThe point: the customer paid everything on day one and the revenue trickles in over the year. Recognizing it actually costs cash, because tax comes due as the revenue is earned. That is the SaaS model: collect first, earn later.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company buys PP&E for $800, 20-year life, straight-line, no salvage. Sells at end of Year 4 for $700. 20% tax rate. Walk through statements at sale.",a:"Book value first. Depreciation is $40 a year ($800 over 20 years), so after four years accumulated depreciation is $160 and the book value is $640.\n\nIncome statement. Selling at $700 against a $640 book value gives a $60 gain. Tax of $12 at 20% leaves net income up $48.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $48. Subtract the $60 gain out of operating, then add the $700 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $688.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $688 and PP&E comes off at $640, so assets rise $48. Retained earnings are up $48.\n\nThe point: the asset sold for $100 less than it cost and still booked a gain, because depreciation had already written it down to $640. The gain measures against book value, not purchase price.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do PIK bonds affect the 3 financial statements?",a:"Income statement. PIK interest is a real expense and is accrued exactly like cash interest, so pre-tax income and net income both fall.\n\nCash flow statement. No cash interest is paid, so the whole PIK charge is added back as non-cash. Cash actually rises by the tax shield.\n\nBalance sheet. The debt balance grows by the PIK amount, because the interest is paid in more debt rather than money. Retained earnings fall by the after-tax charge.\n\nThe point: the borrower pays nothing today and owes more tomorrow. Interest compounds into principal, so the balance snowballs. It preserves near-term liquidity, which is why it appears in LBOs and distressed structures, and it is also why PIK is the most expensive money in the capital structure.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Should a company use operating or capital leases for factories and buildings?",a:"Capital lease. Factories/buildings are long-term assets, so a capital lease transfers ownership rights. The leased asset and liability appear on the BS. Expenses split into depreciation and interest rather than a single operating expense.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In a tax-free world, what happens when moving from FIFO to LIFO? What if not tax-free?",a:"Tax-free: COGS and inventory change but not taxes. Under LIFO in rising costs, COGS is higher, NI lower, inventory lower. Not tax-free: Also see tax implications of lower NI and potentially a LIFO reserve adjustment impacting deferred taxes.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company purchases asset for $100, sells for $110. 20% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The asset cost $100 and sold for $110, so the gain is $10. Tax of $2 at 20% leaves net income up $8.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $8. Subtract the $10 gain out of operating, then add the $110 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $108.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $108 and the asset is down $100, so assets rise $8. Retained earnings are up $8.\n\nThe point: only the $10 of appreciation is taxable, not the $110 collected. The company keeps $108, giving up $2 to tax.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"25% tax rate. In Year 0 acquire $100M PP&E (50% debt, 50% equity). In Year 1 sell for $100M after 1 year depreciation (10-yr SL). No interest. Walk through both years.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. The $100M of CapEx is an investing outflow, offset by $50M of debt and $50M of equity in financing, so cash does not move. PP&E is up $100M, debt is up $50M, and common stock is up $50M.\n\nYear 1. Depreciation is $10M, taking book value to $90M. Selling at $100M then books a $10M gain. The gain and the depreciation exactly cancel, so pre-tax income is zero, there is no tax, and net income is zero.\n\nCash flow statement. Net income is zero, add back $10M of depreciation, subtract the $10M gain, then add $100M of proceeds. Cash rises $100M.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $100M and PP&E is down $100M, so assets are unchanged, as are liabilities and equity.\n\nThe point: the company got every dollar back and reported zero profit. Depreciation had understated the asset's real value, and the gain on sale corrected it. The two offset because the asset never actually lost value.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When would you capitalize vs. expense software engineer costs? Walk through 3-statement impact of $100 costs at 25% tax.",a:"When you capitalize. Only during the development stage, once the project is technically feasible and will deliver future benefit. Preliminary planning, training, and maintenance are always expensed.\n\nIf capitalized. Nothing hits the income statement, so net income is unchanged. The $100 of cash leaves through investing, and a $100 asset appears. That asset then amortizes over future years.\n\nIf expensed. The income statement takes the full $100, so net income falls $75 after the 25% tax benefit. Cash falls $75, since the tax saving offsets part of the outlay.\n\nThe point: the same engineers doing the same work, and one version reports $75 more profit and stronger operating cash flow. That is why a jump in capitalized software costs is worth interrogating: the cash is identical, only the reporting changed.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A uses 10-yr depreciation, Company B uses 5-yr. $200 asset, 25% tax. Compare Year 1 impact.",a:"Company A, ten-year life. Depreciation is $20, so net income falls $15. Adding the $20 back means cash rises $5. PP&E falls $20.\n\nCompany B, five-year life. Depreciation is $40, so net income falls $30. Adding the $40 back means cash rises $10. PP&E falls $40.\n\nThe comparison. Company B reports half the net income of Company A and generates twice the cash.\n\nThe point: the businesses are identical. The only difference is an accounting assumption. B's faster schedule creates a bigger tax shield, so it keeps $10 instead of $5 while reporting worse earnings. Cash follows the tax deduction, not the reported profit, which is why depreciation policy is a real lever on value even though it looks cosmetic.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Purchase PP&E for $100 with $50 debt and $50 equity. Year 1: $20 EBITDA, 40% tax, 10% interest, 10-yr SL depreciation. Walk through both years.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of CapEx is an investing outflow, funded by $50 of debt and $50 of equity in financing, so net cash is zero. PP&E is up $100, debt is up $50, equity is up $50.\n\nYear 1. EBITDA is $20, depreciation is $10, and interest is $5 ($50 at 10%), so pre-tax income is $5. Tax of $2 at 40% leaves net income of $3.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $3, and add back $10 of depreciation. Operating cash flow is $13.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $13 and PP&E is down $10, so assets rise $3. Retained earnings are up $3.\n\nThe point: $3 of accounting profit and $13 of cash. The gap is the depreciation, which is a charge against a machine that was paid for last year. This is exactly why leveraged deals are underwritten on cash flow rather than net income.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Given two balance sheets, how would you calculate EBITDA for the fiscal year?",a:"Infer NI from change in Retained Earnings (assuming no dividends), back into Pre-Tax Income, add Interest (from debt balances), and add D&A (from PP&E/intangible changes). This yields EBITDA. Assumptions: No dividends, no write-downs, no capex, no disposals, consistent tax rate.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Buy truck for $100 (50% debt, 50% equity). 20-yr SL depreciation. Non-amortizing debt, 10% coupon, 20% tax. Walk through 3 statements after 1 year.",a:"Income statement. Depreciation is $5 ($100 over 20 years) and interest is $5 ($50 at 10%), so pre-tax income falls $10. Tax falls $2 at 20%, leaving net income down $8.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $8, and add back $5 of depreciation, so operating cash flow is negative $3. The purchase and financing legs offset each other, so cash is down $3 overall.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $3 and PP&E is $95 ($100 less $5 of depreciation), so assets rise $92. Debt is up $50 and equity is up $42 ($50 in, less $8 of losses), so liabilities plus equity rise $92 too.\n\nThe point: the truck loses value on a schedule while the debt costs real cash every year. Non-amortizing means the $50 principal is still owed in full at the end, so nothing is being paid down.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A/R $30, Inventory $50, A/P $20 at year-end. Q1 revenue $90, 80% gross margin. DSO 90, DIO 45, DPO 60. How much did cash flow change from working capital?",a:"Cash flow decreased by $27. Previous OWC = $30 + $50 - $20 = $60. Q1 COGS = $18. New A/R = $90. New Inventory = $9. New A/P = $12. New OWC = $90 + $9 - $12 = $87. Change = $87 - $60 = +$27. Increase in OWC means cash decreased by $27.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company issues $200M PIK debt at 10%. 40% tax rate. Walk through Year 0 and Year 1.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. A $200M financing inflow, and cash and debt both rise $200M.\n\nYear 1. PIK interest of $20M is a real expense, so pre-tax income falls $20M. Tax falls $8M at 40%, leaving net income down $12M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $12M. No cash interest was paid, so add the $20M back as non-cash. Cash rises $8M.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $8M, debt is up $20M to $220M, and retained earnings are down $12M.\n\nThe point: the company's cash went up while it got poorer. It paid its lenders in more debt, so the balance compounds. This buys liquidity today at the price of a much larger obligation later, which is the whole trade with PIK.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Sell asset (BV $100M) for $120M. 25% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The gain is $20M ($120M less the $100M book value). Tax of $5M leaves net income up $15M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $15M. Subtract the $20M gain out of operating, then add the $120M of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $115M.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $115M and the asset is down $100M, so assets rise $15M. Retained earnings are up $15M.\n\nThe point: only the $20M above book value is taxed, not the $120M received. The gain is stripped out of operating so the proceeds are not counted twice, once in earnings and again in investing.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"$1,000 debt write-down. 25% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. Having $1,000 of debt written down is a benefit, so the company books a $1,000 gain. Tax of $250 leaves net income up $750.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $750. The gain brought in no cash, so subtract the full $1,000. Net cash falls $250, which is exactly the tax owed.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $250, debt is down $1,000, and retained earnings are up $750.\n\nThe point: the company is $1,000 less indebted and $250 poorer in cash. Debt forgiveness is taxable income, so real cash goes out to the tax authority on a gain that never brought a dollar in.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Buy widget machine for $100 (50% debt, 50% equity). 5x EBITDA multiple. 10% interest, 40% tax, 10-yr SL. Walk through at purchase and after 1 year.",a:"At purchase. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of CapEx is an investing outflow, funded by $50 of debt and $50 of equity, so net cash is zero. PP&E is up $100, debt is up $50, and common stock is up $50.\n\nYear 1. At a 5x EBITDA multiple, the $100 machine implies $20 of EBITDA. Depreciation is $10 and interest is $5 ($50 at 10%), so pre-tax income is $5. Tax of $2 at 40% leaves net income of $3.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $3, add back $10 of depreciation, and operating cash flow is $13.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $13 and PP&E is down $10, so assets rise $3. Retained earnings are up $3.\n\nThe point: $3 of profit and $13 of cash from the same year. The multiple is just telling you what EBITDA the asset produces; the gap between the two numbers is depreciation on money spent last year.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Factory purchased for $500, 40-yr SL depreciation. After 10 years written down to $125. 20% tax rate. Walk through the write-down.",a:"Book value first. Depreciation is $12.50 a year ($500 over 40 years), so after ten years accumulated depreciation is $125 and the book value is $375.\n\nIncome statement. Writing the factory down to $125 means a $250 impairment. Tax benefit of $50 at 20% leaves net income down $200.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $200. The impairment is non-cash, so add $250 back. Cash rises $50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $50 and PP&E is down $250, so assets fall $200. Retained earnings fall $200.\n\nThe point: depreciation had the factory at $375 and management is saying it is really worth $125. The impairment is the accounting catching up with reality. No cash moves except the $50 of tax saved.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"$50M debt extinguished with no repurchase. 25% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The obligation disappeared without payment, so the company books a $50M gain on extinguishment. Tax of $12.5M leaves net income up $37.5M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $37.5M. The gain brought in no cash, so subtract the full $50M. Net cash falls $12.5M, the tax owed.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $12.5M, debt is down $50M, and retained earnings are up $37.5M. Equity rises and leverage falls.\n\nThe point: the company is meaningfully better off and its cash still went down. Cancelling debt is taxable income, so the only cash that moves is the tax bill on a windfall that arrived entirely on paper.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Year 1: Buy $50 inventory (cash). Year 2: Sell for $100 (30% tax). How would answer change if customers paid on credit?",a:"Year 1. Nothing on the income statement. Cash falls $50 and inventory rises $50.\n\nYear 2, cash sale. Revenue is $100 and COGS is $50, so pre-tax income is $50. Tax of $15 at 30% leaves net income up $35. On the cash flow statement, net income is up $35 and inventory falls $50, a source of cash, so cash rises $85. On the balance sheet, cash is up $85 and inventory is down $50, so assets rise $35, matching retained earnings.\n\nYear 2, if sold on credit. The income statement is identical, net income up $35, because the income statement does not care whether you were paid. But receivables rise $100 instead of cash, so operating cash flow is $35 plus $50 minus $100, which is negative $15. Cash falls $15.\n\nThe point: same sale, same profit, and a $100 swing in cash. The only difference is who is funding the gap between delivery and payment.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"20% EBITDA margin, 15% EBIT margin, 10% NI margin. Which increases NI most: $50 revenue, $11 EBITDA, or $6 EBIT?",a:"The $11 EBITDA increase. Revenue +50 → NI +5. EBITDA +11 → NI +5.5. EBIT +6 → NI ≈ 4.0. 5.5 > 5 > 4, so EBITDA bump wins.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"25% tax rate. Sell asset (BV $1,000) for $800. Use half of proceeds to repay debt. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The asset sold for $800 against a $1,000 book value, so there is a $200 loss. Tax benefit of $50 leaves net income down $150.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $150, and add the $200 loss back in operating. Add the $800 of proceeds in investing, then subtract the $400 of debt repaid in financing. Net cash rises $450.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $450 and the asset is down $1,000, so assets fall $550. Debt is down $400 and retained earnings are down $150, so liabilities plus equity fall $550 too.\n\nThe point: three separate things at once. The loss is accounting, the $800 is real cash in, and the $400 repayment is real cash out. The company reports a loss, ends up with $450 more cash, and is less levered than it started.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What accounting changes could artificially increase reported EBITDA?",a:"• Capitalizing expenses that should be expensed • Aggressive revenue recognition • Reclassifying operating expenses as non-operating • Reducing reserves for bad debts or warranties • Changing inventory methods • Extending asset useful lives • Adding back unusual items as \"adjustments\"",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk through 3-statement impact when Subway sells a $5 sandwich (cash). $1 wages, $1 inventory, $0.50 depreciation. 40% tax rate.",a:"Income statement. Revenue is $5, COGS is $1, wages are $1, and depreciation is $0.50, so EBIT is $2.50. Tax of $1 at 40% leaves net income of $1.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $1.50. Add back $0.50 of depreciation, which is non-cash. Inventory fell $1 as the sandwich was made, a source of cash, so add $1. Operating cash flow is $3.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $3, inventory is down $1, and PP&E is down $0.50, so assets rise $1.50. Retained earnings are up $1.50.\n\nThe point: the customer's $5 came in as cash, the wages went out as cash, and the other two costs did not move any money this period. The ingredients were bought earlier and the oven was bought years ago, which is why cash is double the profit.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Buy back $100M debt at 90 cents on the dollar. 30% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"The trade. The company spends $90M to retire $100M of face value, because the debt trades at 90 cents.\n\nIncome statement. A $10M gain on extinguishment. Tax of $3M at 30% leaves net income up $7M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $7M. Subtract the $10M non-cash gain, then show the $90M repurchase as a financing outflow. Net cash falls $93M.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $93M, debt is down $100M, and retained earnings are up $7M. Liabilities fall more than assets, so equity rises.\n\nThe point: the company cancelled $100M of obligation for $93M all-in and deleveraged in the process. The debt was only available at 90 because the market doubted repayment, so this works exactly when the company is healthier than its bonds imply.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the differences between operating and capital leases?",a:"Under ASC 842/IFRS 16, most leases must now be capitalized on the BS with an ROU asset and lease liability. Difference is in IS recognition: • Finance (Capital) Leases: Interest and amortization as separate expenses. • Operating Leases: Single lease expense, typically straight-line.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Sell $240/year subscription. Walk through initial sale and after one month. 20% tax rate.",a:"At signing. Nothing on the income statement. Cash rises $240 and a $240 deferred revenue liability appears.\n\nAfter one month. One twelfth of the service has been delivered, so revenue is $20. Tax of $4 at 20% leaves net income up $16.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $16. Deferred revenue falls $20, a use of cash, so subtract $20. Net cash falls $4, which is the tax due.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $4, deferred revenue is down $20 to $220, and retained earnings are up $16.\n\nThe point: all the cash arrived on day one and the revenue is released a month at a time. Each month the company recognizes profit and pays tax on it, so the cash balance slowly drains from a pile it collected up front. That float is the structural advantage of annual prepaid subscriptions.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"25% tax rate. Buy $200 machine with $100 cash and $100 bond (5-yr, 10% interest). SL depreciation over 5 years. Walk through Time 0 and Year 1.",a:"Time 0. Nothing on the income statement. The $200 of CapEx is an investing outflow and the $100 bond is a financing inflow, so net cash falls $100. PP&E is up $200, cash is down $100, and debt is up $100.\n\nYear 1. Depreciation is $40 ($200 over 5 years) and interest is $10 ($100 at 10%), so pre-tax income falls $50. Tax falls $12.50, leaving net income down $37.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $37.50, and add back $40 of depreciation. Cash rises $2.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $2.50 and PP&E is down $40, so assets fall $37.50. Retained earnings fall $37.50.\n\nThe point: earnings fell $37.50 and cash went up. The depreciation shield is larger than the cash interest, so the reported loss is mostly an accounting allocation of money spent at Time 0.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Hire consultant for 500 in Year 0. Walk through 3 statements. Then assume you capitalize it. 30% tax.",a:"If expensed. The income statement takes the full $500, so pre-tax income falls $500 and net income falls $350 at a 30% tax rate. Cash falls $350, because the tax saving offsets part of the payment. Retained earnings fall $350.\n\nIf capitalized. Nothing hits the income statement, so net income is unchanged. The full $500 of cash leaves through investing and a $500 intangible appears. In later years it amortizes, say $100 a year, cutting net income $70 after tax while the $100 gets added back on the cash flow statement.\n\nThe point: the same consultant, the same $500, and two completely different sets of financials. Expensing shows a worse year now, capitalizing shows a better year now and a drag for years afterwards. The cash out is $500 either way; only the timing of the deduction changes.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"IT consultant costs $500. 50% tax rate. Part 1: Expense immediately. Part 2: Capitalize. Walk through Year 0 for each.",a:"If expensed. The income statement takes the full $500, so pre-tax income falls $500 and net income falls $250 at a 50% tax rate. Cash falls $250, because the tax authority absorbs half the cost. Retained earnings fall $250.\n\nIf capitalized. Nothing hits the income statement. The full $500 of cash leaves through investing and a $500 asset appears. Net income is unchanged this year.\n\nThe point: at a 50% tax rate, expensing costs the company only $250 of cash while capitalizing costs the full $500 today, because there is no deduction yet. Capitalizing reports higher earnings and worse cash flow in year one, which is the opposite of what most people assume.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a convertible bond and how does it work?",a:"Debt with an embedded option to exchange for shares. Lower coupon than straight debt due to conversion feature. Acts like debt below strike price, like equity above. Gives downside protection plus upside equity participation.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Receive $100 cash upfront for 1-year subscription. 25% tax rate. Walk through at receipt and after one month.",a:"At receipt. Nothing on the income statement. Cash rises $100 and a $100 deferred revenue liability appears.\n\nAfter one month. One twelfth of the year has been delivered, so revenue is $8.33. Tax of $2.08 leaves net income up $6.25.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $6.25. Deferred revenue falls $8.33, a use of cash, so subtract it. Net cash falls $2.08, the tax due.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $2.08, deferred revenue is down $8.33, and retained earnings are up $6.25.\n\nThe point: the company collected everything in month one and now hands back cash to the tax authority each month as it earns the revenue. Cash comes first, profit follows, and tax follows profit.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Depreciation was overstated by $10. 10% tax rate. Walk through adjustments.",a:"Income statement. Reversing the overstatement cuts depreciation $10, so EBIT and pre-tax income both rise $10. Tax rises $1 at 10%, leaving net income up $9.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $9, but the depreciation add-back is now $10 smaller. Net cash falls $1.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $1 and PP&E is up $10, since it was written down too far, so assets rise $9. Retained earnings are up $9.\n\nThe point: correcting the error makes earnings look better and leaves the company with less cash, because a smaller depreciation deduction means a bigger tax bill. Depreciation is the one expense where less of it costs you money.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In an inflationary environment, would cash flow be higher under LIFO or FIFO?",a:"LIFO results in higher cash flow. LIFO expenses the most recent (higher-cost) inventory first, leading to higher COGS, lower taxable income, lower taxes paid, and thus higher operating cash flow.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk through accounting for a convertible bond at issuance and upon conversion.",a:"At issuance. Under current guidance (ASC 470-20 as amended by ASU 2020-06) most convertibles are not split into debt and equity pieces, so the entire proceeds are recorded as a debt liability. Cash and debt both rise. There is no separate equity component unless the conversion feature has to be bifurcated as a derivative.\n\nOn conversion. The debt's carrying value comes off the books and shares are issued in its place, with par going to common stock and the remainder to APIC. No gain or loss is recognized, because this is a conversion the holder was always entitled to, not a settlement.\n\nThe point: no cash moves on conversion. Debt simply becomes equity, leverage falls, and the share count rises. The company financed itself cheaply, since converts carry low coupons, and paid for it with dilution once the stock performed.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Purchases $300k inventory (cash). Writes off 50% at year-end. 20% tax rate. Walk through both events.",a:"At purchase. Nothing on the income statement. Cash falls $300k and inventory rises $300k.\n\nAt the write-off. Half the inventory is worthless, so a $150k expense hits the income statement. Tax benefit of $30k at 20% leaves net income down $120k. On the cash flow statement, the write-off is non-cash, so the $150k is added back and cash rises $30k. On the balance sheet, inventory falls $150k and retained earnings fall $120k.\n\nCombined. Cash is down $270k, inventory is up $150k, and retained earnings are down $120k.\n\nThe point: the $300k of cash left at purchase. The write-off just recognizes that half of it was wasted, and the only cash that moves at that moment is $30k coming back as a tax benefit.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk through how a capital lease affects 3 statements upon inception.",a:"Income statement. Nothing at inception. Signing a lease is not an expense.\n\nCash flow statement. No cash moves, because the lessor is providing the asset rather than the company buying it. It appears as a non-cash disclosure.\n\nBalance sheet. A right-of-use asset appears at the present value of the lease payments, with an equal lease liability against it. Equity does not move.\n\nThe point: the company has effectively borrowed to buy the asset, and the accounting reflects that. From here the lease produces depreciation on the asset and interest on the liability rather than a single rent expense, which pushes cost earlier in the lease and lifts EBITDA, since depreciation and interest both sit below it.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"40% tax rate. $10 increase in warranty expense. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. Warranty expense rises $10, so pre-tax income falls $10. Tax falls $4 at 40%, leaving net income down $6.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $6. Nothing has actually been paid out, it is an accrual, so add the $10 back. Cash rises $4.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $4, the warranty liability is up $10, and retained earnings are down $6.\n\nThe point: the company is booking the estimated cost of future repairs in the period it made the sale. No cash leaves until customers actually claim. The $4 is just the tax saved on an expense that is still only a prediction.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company moves from 6-month upfront subscription ($60) to monthly ($10). Impact on statements?",a:"Income statement. Almost nothing over six months, since revenue is recognized as the service is delivered either way. Total revenue is the same $60.\n\nCash flow statement. This is where it hurts. The company used to collect $60 on day one and now collects $10 a month, so early-period operating cash flow drops sharply.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is lower throughout, and the deferred revenue balance largely disappears, since there is no longer a big prepayment sitting as a liability.\n\nThe point: the income statement barely notices and the cash position gets materially worse. The company has stopped being funded by its customers and now funds them instead. Monthly plans usually reduce churn and widen the funnel, so the trade is lower working capital float for a bigger customer base.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Issue $500 BV debt at par. Walk through statements. Follow-up: Debt trades at $400. What does this tell you?",a:"At issuance. Nothing on the income statement. A $500 financing inflow, and cash and debt both rise $500.\n\nThe follow-up. The bond was issued at par and now trades at $400, which means buyers demand a higher yield than the coupon pays. Either market interest rates have risen, which repriced every bond, or the market thinks this borrower is more likely to default and wants more compensation.\n\nHow to tell which. Compare it with government bonds of the same maturity. If rates moved, everything fell together. If only this bond fell, the credit spread widened and the problem is company-specific.\n\nThe point: yield equals the risk-free rate plus a credit spread. The balance sheet still says $500, because debt is carried at amortized cost. The market is saying it is worth $400, and the company could theoretically buy it back at a discount and book a gain.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"$50 increase in interest expense, 50% PIK / 50% cash. 30% tax rate. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. All $50 of interest is an expense, whether it is paid in cash or paid in kind. Pre-tax income falls $50 and tax falls $15 at 30%, leaving net income down $35.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $35. Only half the interest was actually paid, so add the $25 of PIK back as non-cash. Net cash falls $10, which reconciles: $25 of cash interest paid less $15 of tax saved.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $10, debt is up $25 as the PIK rolls into principal, and retained earnings are down $35.\n\nThe point: the income statement takes the full hit while only half the cash leaves. The other half compounds into the loan balance, which is why PIK protects near-term liquidity and quietly grows the obligation.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"40% tax rate. Sell factory (BV $100) for $80. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The factory sold for $80 against a $100 book value, so there is a $20 loss. Tax benefit of $8 at 40% leaves net income down $12.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $12, and add the $20 loss back in operating, since the proceeds are counted below. Then add the $80 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $88.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $88 and PP&E is down $100, so assets fall $12. Retained earnings fall $12.\n\nThe point: the company reports a loss and collects $88 of cash. The loss is the gap between the sale price and what the books claimed, and it is worth $8 in tax relief, so the company actually banks more than the $80 sale price.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"25% tax rate. $20 increase in interest expense ($10 PIK, $10 cash). Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. All $20 of interest is an expense, whether paid in cash or rolled into the loan. Pre-tax income falls $20 and tax falls $5, leaving net income down $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $15. Only $10 was actually paid, so add the $10 of PIK back as non-cash. Net cash falls $5, which reconciles: $10 of cash interest out, less $5 of tax saved.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $5, debt is up $10 as the PIK capitalizes, and retained earnings are down $15.\n\nThe point: the earnings hit is twice the cash hit. Half the interest is quietly compounding into the principal instead of leaving the building.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A buys B for $230 equity value. B has $120 assets, $35 existing goodwill, $80 liabilities. Fair value of identifiable assets is $50 higher. What is new goodwill?",a:"Fair-value net identifiable assets = (120 - 35) + 50 - 80 = 55. Goodwill = Purchase Price - 55 = 175.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A owns 70% of Company B ($700 NI). Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. Control means full consolidation, so all $700 of Company B's net income is reported, not 70% of it. Below the line, $210 is attributed to the non-controlling interest, leaving $490 as net income to the parent.\n\nCash flow statement. Start from consolidated net income of $700, because all of B's cash is inside the group. The NCI split is an attribution, not a cash movement.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash rises with the earnings. Retained earnings rise $490 and the non-controlling interest, which sits inside equity, rises $210.\n\nThe point: consolidation is about control, not ownership percentage. Company A controls B, so it takes every line of revenue and expense onto its statements and then hands back the 30% it does not own on a single line. This is exactly why you subtract NCI when bridging from enterprise value to equity value.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Purchase asset for 400 at 5x EBITDA, 50% debt/50% cash, 50% PIK / 50% regular interest at 10%, 10-yr SL, 25% tax. Year 1 write off debt. Walk through statements.",a:"Setting up. The asset costs $400 at 5x EBITDA, so EBITDA is $80. It is funded with $200 of debt and $200 of cash. Depreciation is $40 over ten years, and interest is $20 ($200 at 10%), split $10 cash and $10 PIK.\n\nIncome statement. EBITDA of $80 less $40 of depreciation gives EBIT of $40. Less $20 of interest leaves $20. Then the debt is forgiven: the balance had grown to $210 with the PIK, so the gain is $210. Pre-tax income is $230, tax is $57.50, and net income is $172.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $172.50. Add back $40 of depreciation and $10 of PIK, then subtract the $210 non-cash gain. Cash rises $12.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $12.50 and PP&E is down $40, so assets fall $27.50. Debt falls $200 net (it grew $10 on PIK then vanished entirely) and retained earnings are up $172.50, so liabilities plus equity fall $27.50 too.\n\nThe point: the company reports a huge profit and collects $12.50 of cash. Almost all the earnings are a forgiveness gain that never brought a dollar in, and the tax on it is real money out.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"2023: A/R=150, Inv=100, A/P=150. 2024: A/R=250, Inv=200, A/P=250. Revenue 2000, GP 1000. Calculate cash conversion cycle.",a:"COGS = 1,000. DSO ≈ 36.5. DIO ≈ 54.8. DPO ≈ 73.0. CCC = 36.5 + 54.8 - 73.0 ≈ 18 days.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A owns 70% of B ($700 NI this year). Walk through 3 statements for Company A.",a:"Income statement. Company A controls B, so it consolidates all $700 of net income. It then attributes $210 to the non-controlling interest, leaving $490 attributable to the parent.\n\nCash flow statement. Start from consolidated net income and add back the $210 of NCI, because that income is inside the group's cash even though it belongs to someone else. Cash rises by the full $700 unless dividends are paid out to the minority holders.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $700, retained earnings are up $490, and the NCI line inside equity is up $210.\n\nThe point: A reports every dollar B earns and only keeps 70% of it. The other 30% sits in equity as NCI rather than being excluded, which is why NCI has to be added when you build enterprise value from a consolidated market cap.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"EBITDA 120, 10x EV/EBITDA, 20% EBITDA margin, 10% interest expense, 5x Debt/EBITDA, 20x P/E, no D&A. What is the effective tax rate?",a:"50%. EV=1,200. Debt=600, Equity=600. NI=600/20=30. Interest=10%×600=60. EBT=120-60=60. 30=(1-t)×60 → t=50%.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"$100 equipment, 10-yr SL, no salvage, 40% tax. Walk through Year 0 (cash purchase) and Year 1.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement, because buying equipment is not an expense. Cash falls $100 in investing and PP&E rises $100. Total assets are unchanged.\n\nYear 1. Depreciation is $10, so pre-tax income falls $10. Tax falls $4 at 40%, leaving net income down $6.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $6, and add back the $10 of depreciation. Cash rises $4.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $4 and PP&E is down $10, so assets fall $6. Retained earnings fall $6.\n\nThe point: all $100 of cash left in Year 0 and never touched earnings. Then earnings fall $10 a year while cash actually rises $4, because the depreciation shields $4 of tax. Cash and profit are on completely different schedules.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are NOLs and how can a company use them?",a:"NOL occurs when expenses exceed revenues. Generates a carryforward applied against future taxable income. Recorded as deferred tax assets on BS. Tax benefit realized when it reduces cash taxes, often years later. Companies aim to use NOLs as soon as they have sufficient taxable income.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Rising prices: effect on cash flow switching from FIFO to LIFO? Why?",a:"LIFO yields higher COGS → lower taxable income → lower taxes → higher operating cash flow. FIFO uses older (cheaper) inventory → lower COGS → higher taxable income → more taxes → lower cash flow.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do NOLs affect 3 statements when generated and when used?",a:"When the loss is generated. The company records a tax benefit that softens the reported net loss, and a deferred tax asset appears for the future deduction. On the cash flow statement the benefit is non-cash, so it is subtracted out. No cash comes in, because you cannot collect a refund on tax you never paid.\n\nWhen the NOL is used. The company is profitable and reports tax expense in the normal way, but a chunk of it is deferred rather than payable, so no cash tax is actually paid. That deferred piece is added back on the cash flow statement, and the DTA on the balance sheet gets drawn down.\n\nThe point: the years when tax expense appears and the years when tax cash leaves are not the same years. An NOL is a real asset, cash the company will not have to hand over later, which is why buyers value them in a deal and why the tax rules limit how much of an acquired NOL a buyer can use.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"40% tax rate. $100M non-cash impairment charge. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"Income statement. The $100M impairment cuts pre-tax income $100M. Because the write-down is not deductible until the asset is actually sold, the benefit is deferred rather than current, creating a $40M deferred tax asset. Net income falls $60M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $60M. Add back the $100M impairment as non-cash, then subtract the $40M increase in the DTA, which is also non-cash. Net cash is zero.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is unchanged, the DTA is up $40M, and PP&E is down $100M, so assets fall $60M. Retained earnings fall $60M.\n\nThe point: not a single dollar moved. This is the cleanest illustration of a non-cash charge. Earnings fell $60M, cash is untouched, and the $40M sitting in the DTA is a promise of a deduction the company can only use once it disposes of the asset.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Levered FCF Yield 10%, EBITDA $100M, CapEx $5M, Interest $25M, NWC decrease $10M, Tax $5M, Net Debt $500M, FDSO 100M. Find LFCF.",a:"LFCF = $75mm. EBITDA 100 - CapEx 5 = 95. +10 NWC decrease = 105. -25 interest -5 taxes = 75.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"$100 equipment, 50% cash/50% debt. Year 2: $10 depreciation, $10 interest. 30% tax. Walk through both years.",a:"Year 1. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of CapEx is an investing outflow and the $50 of debt is a financing inflow, so net cash falls $50. PP&E is up $100, cash is down $50, and debt is up $50.\n\nYear 2. Depreciation is $10 and interest is $10, so pre-tax income falls $20. Tax falls $6 at 30%, leaving net income down $14.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $14, and add back $10 of depreciation. Cash falls $4.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $4 and PP&E is down $10, so assets fall $14. Debt is unchanged and retained earnings are down $14.\n\nThe point: two charges of $10 each, and only the interest actually takes cash. The depreciation is an allocation of the money spent in Year 1.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Issue $100 equity, use proceeds to pay down $100 debt. Walk through statements. How does this affect valuation?",a:"Income statement. Nothing on the day it happens. Issuing shares is not income and repaying principal is not an expense.\n\nCash flow statement. A $100 financing inflow from the equity and a $100 financing outflow to repay the debt. Net cash is zero.\n\nBalance sheet. Assets do not move at all. Debt falls $100 and common stock rises $100, so total capital is unchanged, only its composition changed.\n\nValuation. Enterprise value is unchanged, since equity went up exactly as much as debt came down and EV is blind to capital structure. Equity value per share is a different matter: interest expense drops so future net income rises, but there are more shares to divide it among, and the company loses the interest tax shield.\n\nThe point: this is deleveraging, not value creation. The business generates the same cash. All that changed is who has a claim on it, and the company traded a cheaper, tax-deductible funding source for a more expensive one.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Factory purchase for 100 (all debt, 10% interest). $10 depreciation in Year 2, repay 20 principal in Year 2. 30% tax. Walk through.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of CapEx is an investing outflow and the $100 of debt is a financing inflow, so cash does not move. PP&E and debt both rise $100.\n\nYear 2. Depreciation is $10 and interest is $10, so pre-tax income falls $20. Tax falls $6 at 30%, leaving net income down $14.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $14, and add back $10 of depreciation, so operating cash flow is negative $4. Then the $20 of principal repaid is a financing outflow. Net cash falls $24.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $24 and PP&E is down $10, so assets fall $34. Debt is down $20 and retained earnings are down $14, so liabilities plus equity fall $34 too.\n\nThe point: earnings fell $14 while cash fell $24. The principal repayment is $20 of real cash that never touches the income statement, which is why a company can look profitable and still be starved by its amortization schedule.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"25% tax rate. Repurchase $100 bonds for $80 cash. Walk through 3 statements.",a:"The trade. The company pays $80 of cash to retire $100 of face value, because the bonds trade at a discount.\n\nIncome statement. A $20 gain on extinguishment. Tax of $5 leaves net income up $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $15. Subtract the $20 non-cash gain, then show the $80 repurchase as a financing outflow. Net cash falls $85.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $85, debt is down $100, and retained earnings are up $15. Liabilities fall more than assets, so equity rises.\n\nThe point: $100 of obligation cancelled for $85 all-in once the tax is paid. The company is less levered and $85 lighter on cash, which is only a good trade if it has liquidity to spare.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Leverage Ratio 4x, Interest Coverage 5x, EBIT $80m. Taxes paid $19.2M. What is the tax rate?",a:"30%. Interest = EBIT/coverage = 80/5 = 16. EBT = 80 - 16 = 64. Tax Rate = 19.2/64 = 30%. (Leverage ratio is a distraction.)",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How can a supermarket improve working capital? How about a healthcare IT company?",a:"Supermarket: Negotiate longer supplier terms, reduce inventory via better forecasting/JIT, accelerate cash collection (usually cash basis already). HCIT: Shorten payment cycles with hospital customers, milestone-based billing, extend vendor payment terms, minimize inventory (less relevant for software). Key difference: Supermarkets focus on physical inventory and supplier terms; HCIT focuses on receivables collection and service delivery timing.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Raise $100 preferred stock (9% coupon), invest in $100 long-term assets (10% yield). 30% tax. Walk through Year 0 and Year 1.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. The $100 of preferred raised is a financing inflow and the $100 invested is an investing outflow, so net cash is zero. Assets are up $100 and preferred stock inside equity is up $100.\n\nYear 1. The investment yields 10%, so income is $10. Tax of $3 at 30% leaves net income of $7. Then the preferred dividend of $9 is deducted below net income, leaving negative $2 attributable to common.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $7, then pay the $9 dividend as a financing outflow. Net cash falls $2.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $2 and retained earnings are down $2.\n\nThe point: the company earns 10% on money that costs 9% and still goes backwards. The investment income is taxed, so only $7 survives, while the preferred dividend is paid from after-tax money and gets no deduction. That non-deductibility is precisely why preferred is more expensive than debt.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"30% tax rate. Year 0: Raise $100m debt at 10% cash interest. Year 1: Interest accrued and paid. Walk through both years.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. A $100m financing inflow, and cash and debt both rise $100m.\n\nYear 1. Interest is $10m ($100m at 10%), so pre-tax income falls $10m. Tax falls $3m at 30%, leaving net income down $7m.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $7m. The interest was paid in cash and there is nothing non-cash to add back, so cash falls $7m.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $7m, debt is unchanged at $100m, and retained earnings are down $7m.\n\nThe point: the company wrote a $10m cheque and is only $7m poorer, because the interest was deductible. Compare this with the PIK version, where the same $10m of expense would leave cash higher and the debt balance growing.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"40% tax rate. $300m loan with 10% PIK interest. Walk through after one year.",a:"Income statement. PIK interest is a real expense, so the $30m ($300m at 10%) cuts pre-tax income $30m. Tax falls $12m at 40%, leaving net income down $18m.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $18m. No cash interest was paid, so add the entire $30m back. Cash rises $12m.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $12m, debt is up $30m to $330m, and retained earnings are down $18m.\n\nThe point: the company's cash went up $12m while it took on $30m more debt. It paid its lender in more debt and pocketed the tax shield. That is the appeal and the trap of PIK: free liquidity now, compounding principal later.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"40% ownership JV vs 60% ownership. Then 40%-owned JV earns $100m NI, pays $30m dividends. 25% tax on dividends. Walk through 3-statement impact.",a:"Which method. A 40% stake without control means the equity method, one line on each statement. A 60% stake means consolidation, taking every line and booking a non-controlling interest for the 40% you do not own. At 40% here, it is the equity method.\n\nIncome statement. The company books its 40% share of the JV's earnings, so $40M, as a single equity-method line. It received $12M of dividends and pays $3M of tax at 25% on those, leaving net income up $37M.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $37M. The $40M of equity earnings is non-cash, so subtract it, then add the $12M of dividends actually received. Operating cash flow is $9M.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $9M and the investment in affiliate is up $28M ($40M of earnings less $12M of dividends taken out), so assets rise $37M. Retained earnings are up $37M.\n\nThe point: the company books $40M of profit and sees $12M of it. The rest sits in the JV, which is why equity-method earnings are a classic quality-of-earnings flag: profit you report but cannot spend.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"25% tax rate. SaaS company: $120 annual subscription paid upfront. Walk through at point of sale and after one month.",a:"At the point of sale. Nothing on the income statement, because nothing has been delivered. Cash rises $120 and a $120 deferred revenue liability appears.\n\nAfter one month. One twelfth of the year has been served, so revenue is $10. Tax of $2.50 leaves net income up $7.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $7.50. Deferred revenue falls $10, a use of cash, so subtract it. Net cash falls $2.50, which is the tax now owed.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $2.50, deferred revenue is down $10, and retained earnings are up $7.50.\n\nThe point: the customer funded the company on day one. Every month after, the company recognizes profit and gives a little cash back to the tax authority. Collect first, earn later, which is why deferred revenue is the most watched line at any SaaS business.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"$10M received upfront for 2-year subscription. Revenue recognized straight-line. 20% tax rate. Walk through Year 0, Year 1, Year 2.",a:"Year 0. Nothing on the income statement. Cash rises $10M and a $10M deferred revenue liability appears.\n\nYear 1. Half the two-year term is delivered, so revenue is $5M. Tax of $1M at 20% leaves net income up $4M. On the cash flow statement, net income is up $4M but deferred revenue falls $5M, so net cash falls $1M. On the balance sheet, deferred revenue drops to $5M and retained earnings rise $4M.\n\nYear 2. Identical. Another $5M of revenue, $4M of net income, $1M of cash out for tax, and deferred revenue goes to zero.\n\nThe point: $10M of cash arrived in Year 0 and none of it was profit yet. The company then pays $1M of tax in each of the next two years as it earns the revenue. The cash and the earnings are entirely out of sync, which is the whole point of the deferred revenue account.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is operating leverage? Using Peloton as an example, analyze its degree of operating leverage.",a:"Operating leverage measures how revenue changes affect EBIT. High fixed costs relative to variable costs = high operating leverage → disproportionate profit growth (and vice versa). DOL = % Change in EBIT / % Change in Revenue Peloton: High fixed costs (content, studios, tech infrastructure). Variable costs (bike manufacturing, shipping). During growth, strong leverage as subscription revenue scales. During decline, negative leverage as revenue drops cause larger EBIT declines.",category:"Accounting",difficulty:"Advanced"},

// ═══ EXPANDED ENTERPRISE & EQUITY VALUE SET (from EV & Equity Value Q&A workbook) ═══
{q:"You are evaluating two potential acquisition targets with identical financial performance and the same equity value. Company A has $100 in cash and no debt. Company B has no cash and $100 in debt. Which company would you prefer to acquire and why?",a:"Company A is preferable. Since both have the same Equity Value (Price), Company A has a significantly lower Enterprise Value (effectively $200 less than B). Assuming Equity Value = X: EV(A) = X - 100 Cash. EV(B) = X + 100 Debt. You are paying the same upfront price for both (Equity Value), but with Company A you get $100 cash, whereas with B you assume $100 debt. A is much cheaper.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"After an acquisition, how are the pro-forma Enterprise Value and Equity Value of the combined company calculated?",a:"Pro-Forma Equity Value: Acquirer Equity Value + Value of Consideration Paid (cash, stock, or both). If all-stock: Acquirer EqV + (shares issued × acquirer share price). If cash/debt: Typically just acquirer's standalone equity value (no dilution). Pro-Forma Enterprise Value: Sum of standalone Enterprise Values: Acquirer TEV + Target TEV. Alternatively: PF Equity Value + PF Net Debt + PF Preferred Stock + PF NCI. PF Net Debt = (Acquirer Debt + Target Debt + New Debt Issued) - (Acquirer Cash + Target Cash - Cash Used). Key: Account for new debt issued for financing and cash used to fund the deal when calculating pro-forma metrics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Enterprise Value is 500, senior debt 100, undrawn revolver 50, cash 50, equity investments 50, and unfunded pension obligations of 100. What is the equity value?",a:"$400. Net Debt = 100 - 50 = 50. Debt-like Pension Obligation = 100. Non-core Equity Investments (cash-like) = -50. EV = Eq Value + 50 + 100 - 50 = Eq Value + 100. Set 500 = Eq Value + 100 → Eq Value = 400.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does paying cash dividends impact enterprise value?",a:"Unchanged. Cash falls and equity value falls by the same amount, so the two cancel in the EV formula.\n\nThe point: the company handed money to its owners. The operations are untouched, so what the business is worth is untouched. The shareholders are not richer either, they simply moved value from inside the company to their own pockets, which is why a stock drops by roughly the dividend on the ex-date. This is the same mechanic as a buyback, which also leaves EV flat.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company has 100 common shares at $10 each, with 10 options at a $20 strike price. What is the fully diluted equity value?",a:"$1,000. The options are out-of-the-money (strike $20 > share price $10), so no dilution. Diluted shares = 100; equity value = 100 × $10.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Consider the following list of valuation multiples. Which of them are conceptually valid? EV/Sales, Price/Sales, EV/EBITDA, P/E",a:"EV/Sales, EV/EBITDA, and P/E are valid; Price/Sales is conceptually flawed. Enterprise numerator (EV) should pair with pre-interest denominators (Sales, EBITDA). Equity numerator (Price) must pair with post-interest Net Income. Price/Sales mixes equity value with a metric available to all capital providers.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You have an EPS of $2, 100 shares outstanding, a P/E of 4x, $200 in debt, $75 in NCI, $50 in cash and $100 in inventory. What is the Enterprise Value (EV)?",a:"$1,025. Net Income (NI) = EPS * Shares Outstanding = $2 * 100 = $200. Equity Value = P/E * NI = 4 * $200 = $800. EV = Equity Value + Debt + NCI - Cash = $800 + $200 + $75 - $50 = $1,025.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If equity value doubles with debt and cash unchanged, what happens to enterprise value?",a:"EV rises by the same absolute amount as the equity increase. Formula EV = Equity + Debt - Cash; only equity changed.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain why valuation multiples such as EV/Net Income and Equity Value/EBITDA are conceptually flawed.",a:"These multiples mismatch numerator and denominator. EV/Net Income: EV represents value to all capital providers (debt + equity). Net Income is value to equity holders only (after interest and taxes). Mismatch makes comparison across companies invalid. Equity Value/EBITDA: Equity Value represents value to equity holders only. EBITDA is operating profit available to all capital providers (debt + equity). Different capital structures distort the multiple, making comparisons meaningless. Correct pairings: EV with operating metrics (EBITDA, EBIT, Revenue), Equity Value with equity metrics (Net Income, EPS).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would raising capital through a primary share issuance affect earnings per share (EPS)? Assume proceeds are held in cash.",a:"EPS declines because the share count rises while net income remains relatively flat. The higher denominator dilutes EPS. Interest income on the new cash slightly lifts net income but rarely offsets the dilution.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Conceptually, what is enterprise value?",a:"The total value of a company's core operations, available to every capital provider.\n\nStart at market cap, add debt and preferred because a buyer assumes those claims, and subtract cash because it comes back to the buyer at close.\n\nThe point: the useful way to hold it in your head is that EV is the price of the business and equity value is the price of the shares. A company with a $1B market cap and $2B of debt costs an acquirer far more than $1B. That is exactly why you pair EV with pre-interest metrics like EBITDA and market cap with post-interest metrics like net income.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A firm with $500 million EV issues $100 million of new debt to invest in a project with $100 million NPV. What is the new enterprise value?",a:"EV goes up by $100m. $100m of debt has no impact on TEV (increase in debt is offset by increase in cash). Positive NPV project adds $100m to operational value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has share price $6, 50 million shares, and $100 million cash. What is enterprise value (assuming no debt)?",a:"$200m. EqV = 6 x 50m = $300m. Basic EV formula = EqV + Debt - Cash. EV = 300 + 0 - 100. EV = $200m.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has an Enterprise Value (EV) of $200 and a face value of debt of $300. What is the equity value? Why?",a:"Equity Value = EV - Debt = $200 - $300 = -$100. The negative result means creditors' claims exceed EV. Common equity is effectively out-of-the-money and would be worth ≈ $0 in practice, indicating distress. In practice, a company's market cap can't be negative (shares would trade at or near zero), but an implied negative number like this is common in distress modeling exercises.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A firm has Net Debt / EBITDA = 3x, EV / EBITDA = 10x, and market cap = $560 million. What is its enterprise value?",a:"$800m. Net Debt = 3x EBITDA → EV = 10x EBITDA. EV = EqV + Net Debt → 10x EBITDA = 560 + 3x EBITDA → 7x EBITDA = 560 → EBITDA = 80m. EV = 10 x $80m = $800m.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A firm shows share price of $6, cash of $100 million, total enterprise value of $500 million, and 100 million shares outstanding. What is its current debt balance?",a:"$0. EqV = Share Price * Shares Outstanding = $6 * 100m = $600m. TEV = EqV + Debt - Cash. $500 = $600 + Debt - $100. Debt = $500 - $600 + $100 = $0.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You acquire 60% of a company for $1.5bn in equity. It has $400m revenue, $200m EBITDA, $175m cash, and $75m debt. What is the equity value, what is the net debt, and what is the EV?",a:"Equity Value = $2.5 bn. Net Debt = $75m - $175m = -$100m (net cash). Enterprise Value = 2.5 - 0.1 = $2.4 bn.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk me from Enterprise Value to Equity Value for the following two companies: Company A: EV of $1.5B, Debt of $500M, Cash of $200M. Company B: EV of $1.0B, Debt of $100M, Cash of $500M.",a:"Equity Value = EV - Debt + Cash. Company A: Equity Value = $1.5B - $500M + $200M = $1.2B. Company B: Equity Value = $1.0B - $100M + $500M = $1.4B.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Part 1: Given a company's EBITDA, EV/EBITDA multiple, net debt, shares outstanding, and a list of options with their strike prices, how would you calculate the price per share? Part 2: How would your approach change if you were given Net Income and a P/E multiple instead of EBITDA and an EV/EBITDA multiple?",a:"Part 1: Using EV/EBITDA: 1. Calculate EV = EBITDA * EV/EBITDA multiple. 2. Calculate Equity Value = EV - Net Debt. 3. Apply Treasury Stock Method for options to get diluted shares. 4. Share Price = Equity Value / Diluted Shares Outstanding. Part 2: Using P/E: 1. Calculate Equity Value = NI * P/E multiple. 2. Apply Treasury Stock Method for options to get diluted shares. 3. Share Price = Equity Value / Diluted Shares. Key difference: With P/E, you start at equity value directly; with EV/EBITDA, you must bridge from EV to equity value by subtracting net debt.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has a stock price of $20 a share and a P/E of 20x (so EPS is 1). The company has 10M shares outstanding. How does a 2-for-1 stock split affect EV?",a:"Does not affect EV. There are now 20m shares outstanding, and EPS is now 0.5, but EV stays unchanged.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you find a company's market cap using only its 10-K?",a:"The cover page discloses 'aggregate market value of common stock held by non-affiliates' as of the last business day of the second fiscal quarter-effectively the market cap on that date.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company EV/EBITDA goes from 10x to 20x, and EV/Revenue goes from 2x to 4x. What happened to EBITDA margin and revenue?",a:"The EBITDA margin remained perfectly unchanged (at 20%). You calculate this via: EV/Revenue divided by EV/EBITDA (4x / 20x = 20% margin, which is the same as the initial 2x / 10x = 20%). While the absolute level of revenue cannot be determined from the ratios alone, a common interview interpretation is that valuation expanded (multiple expansion) while underlying operations and margins stayed roughly flat.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Calculate the Fully Diluted Equity Value for a company with the following details: Basic Shares Outstanding: 1 billion, Current Share Price: $50, Restricted Stock Units (RSUs): 50 million, Options: 40 million outstanding at a $25 strike price.",a:"$53.5 billion. RSUs convert 1:1 into shares, adding 50 million shares. Options are in-the-money ($25 strike < $50 price). Using TSM: 40m - (40m * $25 / $50) = 40m - 20m = 20m net new shares. Total Diluted Shares = 1,000m + 50m + 20m = 1,070m. Fully Diluted Equity Value = 1,070m * $50 = $53.5 billion.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does issuing $200m in Equity for an IPO affect Enterprise Value?",a:"Unchanged. Equity value rises $200M and cash rises $200M, which is subtracted, so they offset.\n\nThe point: the company raised money and its operations are identical. That is the whole reason EV is the right measure for comparing businesses, since it is blind to how a company chose to fund itself. Note this only holds for the primary shares, where cash actually enters the company. Secondary shares sold by existing holders bring in no cash and change neither EV nor the share count.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If all cash is needed for operations, is it included in Enterprise Value?",a:"Yes. Operating cash is an operating asset, so it stays inside enterprise value rather than being netted out.\n\nThe logic is that you only subtract cash a buyer could take out on day one without harming the business. Cash the business genuinely needs to function is no different from inventory.\n\nThe point: this is why the textbook rule is to subtract excess cash, not all cash. In practice most people subtract the whole balance because splitting operating from excess is a judgment call. For a retailer holding tills full of float, or an insurer holding reserves, that shortcut materially understates enterprise value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Can a company have a negative EV? What does that mean? Follow-up: How would you value a company with negative EV?",a:"Yes. It happens when cash and equivalents exceed market cap plus debt and other claims. It often signals distress, excess cash or market mispricing. Valuation approach: Value cash at face and debt at par. Use relative or asset-based methods for operations. Cross-check with liquidation analysis if distress is likely.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company has $6 per share with 50 shares outstanding, $100 in cash, and an Enterprise Value (EV) of $500, what is the company's debt?",a:"First, calculate the Equity Value: $6/share * 50 shares = $300. Using the EV formula: EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash. $500 = $300 + Debt - $100 → Debt = $300.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two companies are 100% comparable. Why might one trade at a premium (e.g. higher EV/EBITDA multiple)?",a:"Differences in margins, growth rates, investor sentiment, management strength, capex, capital structure, or working capital needs can all drive a higher multiple for one over the other.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has the following metrics: Gross Debt / EBITDA = 5.0x, EV / EBITDA = 10.0x, Market Cap = $400M, Cash = $100M. Calculate its Total Enterprise Value (TEV).",a:"$600M. Debt = 5.0x * EBITDA and EV = $400M + 5.0x * EBITDA - $100M = 10.0x * EBITDA. $300M + 5.0x * EBITDA = 10.0x * EBITDA. $300M = 5.0x * EBITDA. EBITDA = $60M. TEV = 10.0x * $60M = $600M.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company issues $500m in new shares. How do equity value, enterprise value, EV/EBITDA, and P/E change?",a:"Equity Value: Increases by $500m (cash raised). Enterprise Value: Unchanged (Equity +$500m, Cash +$500m offset). EV/EBITDA: Unchanged (EV and EBITDA unchanged). P/E: Increases (Equity Value increases, Net Income initially unchanged).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do enterprise value and equity value change if $50 in cash is stolen? What if that cash was operational?",a:"Excess Cash: Equity Value -50, EV unchanged (cash is subtracted in the EV bridge). Operational Cash: Both Equity Value and EV drop 50 because operating cash is part of core assets and not deducted from EV.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What characteristics of a company would generate a higher valuation multiple?",a:"Common reasons include: Higher revenue/EBITDA growth than peers, Market leadership or strong moat, Valuable patents/IP, Favorable geography/resources, Exceptional management team.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If two companies have the same growth prospects, market capitalizations and industries, why might you value one using EV/Sales and the other using EV/EBITDA?",a:"Possibly one has negative or unreliable EBITDA, so EV/EBITDA isn't meaningful. Or large non-cash/one-time items might distort EBITDA, pushing you toward a top-line multiple like EV/Sales.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You have two identical companies, except for their capital structure. Company A is capitalized with 30% debt and 70% equity, while Company B is capitalized with 100% equity. Which company has the higher Net Income, WACC, and Enterprise Value?",a:"Net Income: Company B is higher. Company A has interest expense reducing NI, while B has none. WACC: Company A is lower. Debt is cheaper than equity (due to tax shield), lowering overall WACC. Enterprise Value: Company A is higher. Due to the tax-deductibility of interest, using debt creates a 'tax shield' that adds value to the firm. Therefore, the levered firm's Enterprise Value will be greater than the unlevered firm's value by the present value of this tax shield, assuming all else is equal.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When would you focus on valuing a company's equity rather than their enterprise value, and why?",a:"You focus on equity value when you care about the portion of value attributable specifically to shareholders, such as evaluating stock price performance or assessing per-share metrics. Enterprise value is more relevant when you're comparing operating performance across companies that have different capital structures. In situations like acquisitions that affect the entire capital structure, enterprise value is often the starting point. But if your primary consideration is the shareholder impact or any equity-based return, you focus on equity value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why add Noncontrolling Interest (NCI) to Enterprise Value?",a:"When a company owns more than 50% of another company, it must consolidate the entire financial performance of that subsidiary into its own financial statements (even if it doesn't own 100%). This means the parent company reports the subsidiary's full (100%) financial results. When consolidating a subsidiary not fully owned, metrics like EBITDA reflect 100% of the sub. Therefore, to make EV comparable to metrics like EBITDA, you need to include Noncontrolling Interest when calculating Enterprise Value to ensure that both your numerator and denominator fully reflect 100% ownership of the subsidiary.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company finds $1,000 in cash, what is the impact on its Enterprise Value and Equity Value?",a:"Equity Value increases by $1,000 (cash is an asset belonging to equity holders). Enterprise Value remains unchanged (EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash; cash increase offsets equity value increase).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the net impact on a company's Enterprise Value if it raises $50m in equity, raises $75m in debt, and pays out a $100m dividend?",a:"No change to Enterprise Value. Raise $50M equity: Cash +$50M, Equity Value +$50M. EV unchanged (EqV +$50M, Cash +$50M offset). Raise $75M debt: Cash +$75M, Debt +$75M. EV unchanged (Debt +$75M, Cash +$75M offset). Pay $100M dividend: Cash -$100M, Equity Value -$100M. EV unchanged (EqV -$100M, Cash -$100M offset). Net effect: no change to EV.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company has an EV of 900, debt of 300, and cash of 100, what is the equity value, and what is it after a 3-for-1 stock split?",a:"Equity value = EV - Net Debt = 900 - 300 + 100 = 700. After a 3-for-1 split, equity value remains 700; share price divides by 3 while share count triples.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has an Equity Value of $5 billion, $2 billion of debt, and $2 billion of cash. If the company uses all of its cash for operations, what happens to its Enterprise Value?",a:"EV increases to $7 billion. Initial EV = $5B + $2B - $2B = $5B. After using cash: EV = $5B + $2B - $0 = $7B. Cash decreases by $2B, increasing EV by $2B. Note: Equity Value remains unchanged initially, but the use of cash for operations may impact future value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What items might be considered 'cash-like' and therefore subtracted from enterprise value?",a:"Short-term investments or marketable securities, Excess cash beyond operating needs, Some equity investments or JV stakes if easily liquidated, Potentially net operating loss carryforwards under certain assumptions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are five reasons you might prefer using an EV/EBITDA multiple over a P/E multiple for valuation?",a:"EV/EBITDA is capital-structure neutral and more reflective of core operating performance. Advantages: Ignores financing choices (debt vs equity) and share-count differences. Excludes non-cash depreciation and amortisation distortions. Not affected by jurisdiction-specific tax rates or NOL utilisation. Can value pre-tax loss-making companies if EBITDA is positive. More comparable across industries with different accounting standards.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two companies have the same EV/EBITDA multiple but different P/E multiples. What could explain this difference?",a:"Key factors explaining the difference: Capital structure: Different debt levels affect equity value (P/E numerator) but not enterprise value (EV/EBITDA numerator). Depreciation & Amortization: Higher D&A reduces Net Income (lowering EPS, raising P/E) but doesn't affect EBITDA. Interest expense: Higher debt means more interest, reducing NI and EPS, thus raising P/E, while EV/EBITDA is unaffected. Tax rates: Different effective tax rates impact NI but not EBITDA. Non-operating items: One-time gains/losses, investments in associates affect NI but not EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has an EBITDA of $200 million and is valued at a 10.0x EV/EBITDA multiple. It has $500 million in debt, $100 million in cash, and 50 million shares outstanding. What is the company's implied share price?",a:"$32. Enterprise Value = $200 × 10 = $2,000. Equity Value = $2,000 - $500 + $100 = $1,600. Share Price = $1,600 / 50 = $32.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Would you rather buy a company with a high or low P/E multiple?",a:"Typically, you'd prefer buying at a lower P/E for better value. But it's relative to growth and risk; sometimes a high P/E might still be worthwhile if growth justifies it.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why would a company prefer to take out debt instead of equity?",a:"Debt financing can be cheaper than equity (tax-deductible interest), and it avoids diluting existing shareholders. Also, if the company generates stable cash flows, servicing debt is feasible, and it potentially boosts ROE through leverage.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What items are sometimes considered 'debt-like' and added back when calculating enterprise value?",a:"Capital leases, Unfunded pension obligations, Legal or environmental liabilities, Some forms of preferred stock or near-debt instruments.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If two companies are in the same industry and have the exact same Enterprise Value, why might one have a significantly different EBITDA than the other?",a:"The market assigns a higher EV/EBITDA multiple to the perceived higher-quality firm, so identical EVs translate into different EBITDA levels. Drivers of multiple variation: Growth prospects and margin durability. Recurring versus transactional revenue mix. Regulatory or geographic risk profile. Capital-expenditure intensity and free-cash conversion. Potential synergies or strategic value to acquirers.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company trades at 7x EV/EBITDA with $100M in EBITDA, $100M in cash, $300M in debt, and 100M shares outstanding. What is the implied share price?",a:"$5. Enterprise Value (EV) = Multiple x EBITDA = 7 x $100M = $700M. Equity Value = EV + Cash - Debt = $700M + $100M - $300M = $500M. Implied Share Price = Equity Value / Shares Outstanding = $500M / 100M = $5.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What will happen to equity value as net debt increases?",a:"If net debt rises, the enterprise value could stay the same (theoretically), so equity value could decrease to keep EV constant (assuming no other changes). Another way to see it: higher net debt often signals more financial risk, possibly reducing the market's valuation of equity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do we find the diluted share count?",a:"Pull basic shares from the latest filing, then adjust: Add net in-the-money options/warrants via the Treasury Stock Method. Add all RSUs. Add shares from in-the-money convertibles using the if-converted method. The sum equals diluted shares.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has 10,000 shares at $20 a share. There are 100 call options at an exercise price of $10, 50 restricted stock units (RSUs), and 100 convertible bonds at a price of $10 and par value of $100. What is the diluted equity value?",a:"Basic shares: 10,000 x $20 = $200,000 nominal market cap perspective. Options: 100 options @ $10 = $1,000 in proceeds. At $20 share price, you buy back 50 shares, net 50 new shares. RSUs add 50 shares. Convertibles: Each $100 par bond converts at $20 share price into additional shares. Total diluted shares and diluted equity value calculated accordingly.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why is NCI (Non-Controlling Interest) included in EV?",a:"Because the parent consolidates 100% of the subsidiary's revenue and EBITDA, you add NCI so Enterprise Value reflects 100% of those earnings.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has $50 million of EBITDA and is valued at a 4.0x multiple. It has $100 million of senior debt and $200 million of junior debt. What is the value of the company's equity?",a:"-$100 million (negative equity / underwater). EV = $50M EBITDA * 4.0x = $200M. Total Debt = $100M + $200M = $300M. Equity Value = EV - Debt = $200M - $300M = -$100M. The company is over-leveraged. Equity holders would receive nothing; even junior debt holders may face losses in liquidation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you calculate a company's equity value given its P/E ratio, tax rate, revenue, shares outstanding, gross margin, debt, interest rate, and SG&A expenses?",a:"Calculation steps: 1. Gross Profit = Revenue * Gross Margin. 2. EBIT = Gross Profit - SG&A. 3. Interest Expense = Debt * Interest Rate. 4. EBT = EBIT - Interest Expense. 5. Net Income = EBT * (1 - Tax Rate). 6. Equity Value = Net Income * P/E Ratio. Alternatively: EPS = Net Income / Shares Outstanding. Share Price = EPS * P/E. Equity Value = Share Price * Shares Outstanding.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Would a company generally prefer to finance with debt or equity, and why?",a:"There's no one right answer; it depends. Debt can be preferred due to lower cost (tax deductibility) and no ownership dilution. But too much debt is risky. Equity financing can be preferable if the company is early-stage or experiencing unstable cash flows, making regular debt payments risky. Equity doesn't require repayment, provides financial flexibility, and can strengthen the balance sheet, despite diluting existing ownership.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has a Market Cap of $500 million, Debt of $700 million, and Cash of $200 million. Part 1: What is its Enterprise Value? Part 2: The company then uses all its cash to repurchase debt at 50 cents on the dollar. Walk me through the impact on Enterprise Value. Assume a 25% tax rate.",a:"Part 1: Initial Enterprise Value is $1,000 million. EV = $500M + $700M - $200M = $1,000M. Part 2: The new Enterprise Value is $950 million. The company uses $200M cash to repurchase debt at a 50% discount, retiring $400M of face value ($200M / 0.50). This creates a $200M pre-tax gain on debt extinguishment ($400M face value. $200M cash paid). This gain is taxed at 25%, resulting in a $50M tax payment ($200M * 25%). This tax is a cash outflow that reduces the total value of the firm. The after-tax gain is $150M ($200M - $50M), which flows to Retained Earnings and increases Market Cap by $150M to $650M. New Debt = $700M - $400M = $300M. New Cash = $200M - $200M = $0. New EV = $650M (New Mkt Cap) + $300M (New Debt) - $0 (New Cash) = $950M. Enterprise value decreases by $50M, which is the amount of value lost to the government via taxes on the gain.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A and Company B have identical EV/EBITDA. Company A has a higher P/E multiple. Why might this be the case?",a:"The difference often lies in: Capital structure (e.g. varying interest expense), Tax rates, Different non-cash charges affecting net income but not EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company has 10 options outstanding with a $50 average strike and the stock trades at $100, what happens to net income when they are all exercised?",a:"Net income is not directly impacted by a plain vanilla option exercise because the company issues shares for cash. The direct effect is on share count (dilution) rather than NI. However, any associated stock-based comp expense would have already been recognized earlier, not at exercise. The company receives cash equal to the strike price × options exercised (here, $50 × 10 = $500), which increases Assets (Cash) and Additional Paid-In Capital.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A $100 fine is announced. What is the impact on enterprise value?",a:"No impact on TEV. Either reduces cash (if immediately paid) or is recognized as a liability (fine payable), offsetting the decrease in equity value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the impact on a company's EV/EBITDA and P/E multiples from the following actions? Part 1: The company issues debt to buy back shares. Part 2: The company issues new shares and holds the proceeds as cash on its balance sheet.",a:"Part 1: Debt-Financed Buyback: EV/EBITDA: Generally unchanged (EV remains constant as Debt rises and Equity falls by similar amounts; EBITDA is unaffected). P/E: Usually decreases. Mechanically, if Cost of Debt (after-tax) is lower than Earnings Yield, EPS increases. Higher EPS with same share price = lower P/E. The P/E may also contract because the company is now more leveraged and riskier, increasing the cost of equity. Part 2: Equity Issuance: EV/EBITDA: Unchanged (Equity up, Cash up; EV = Equity + Debt - Cash remains constant). P/E: Increases. Equity Value rises immediately due to new shares, but Net Income only increases slightly (interest income on cash), causing P/E to rise (or EPS to dilute).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A has an EV/EBITDA multiple of 10x, and Company B has a multiple of 12x. Which company is more leveraged?",a:"Cannot determine leverage from EV/EBITDA multiples alone. EV/EBITDA is a capital structure-neutral metric. A higher multiple typically indicates higher growth expectations, better margins, lower risk, or superior market position, not leverage levels. To assess leverage, you need to examine Debt/EBITDA, Debt/Equity, Interest Coverage, or review the balance sheet directly.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does a $100 million secondary sale of shares by existing investors impact TEV and equity value?",a:"No change in either. Shares simply move from existing holders to new investors; the company raises no cash and issues no new shares → equity value and TEV stay flat.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has the following information. Calculate the share price: P/E = 25x, EV/EBITDA = 12x, Tax Rate = 25%, Revenue = $2,000M, Shares Outstanding = 150M, Gross Margin = 50%, $1,000M debt at 10% interest, SG&A (including D&A) = $500M. Assume no other liabilities or equity line items besides debt and common shareholders' equity.",a:"Build the income statement first. Revenue is $2,000M and a 50% gross margin gives gross profit of $1,000M. SG&A of $500M leaves EBIT of $500M. Interest is $100M ($1,000M at 10%), so pre-tax income is $400M. Tax of $100M at 25% leaves net income of $300M.\n\nThen apply the multiple. P/E is equity value over net income, so equity value is 25 times $300M, or $7.5B.\n\nThen get to the share price. $7.5B divided by 150M shares is $50 per share.\n\nThe point: the EV/EBITDA multiple is a distractor. P/E is an equity multiple, so it takes you straight from net income to equity value with no bridge through debt and cash. If they had given you only EV/EBITDA, you would have had to compute enterprise value, subtract the $1,000M of debt, and then divide.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Calculate Enterprise Value given the following information. Assume a 20% tax rate: Annual Interest Expense = $20, Equity Value = $1,000, EV/EBITDA = 12x, P/E = 25x, Cost of Debt = 10%, Annual D&A = $30.",a:"$1,200. Method 1 (Shortcut): Total Debt = Interest Expense / Cost of Debt = $20 / 10% = $200. EV = Equity Value + Debt = $1,000 + $200 = $1,200 (assuming no cash). Method 2 (Income Statement walk): From P/E = 25x and Equity Value = $1,000, find Net Income: NI = $1,000 / 25 = $40. Find Pre-Tax Income (EBT): EBT = NI / (1 - Tax Rate) = $40 / (1 - 0.20) = $50. Find EBIT: EBIT = EBT + Interest Expense = $50 + $20 = $70. Find EBITDA: EBITDA = EBIT + D&A = $70 + $30 = $100. Calculate Enterprise Value: EV = EBITDA * EV/EBITDA Multiple = $100 * 12x = $1,200.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Part 1: If you had to explain Enterprise Value to a 10-year-old, how would you do it? Part 2: What's the formula? Part 3: Bridge to equity value. Part 4: What are some other non-equity claims subtracted out to get to equity? Part 5: Why do we add minority interest?",a:"Part 1: Imagine buying a lemonade stand: you pay for the stand plus any IOUs the owner owes (debt), but you keep the cash in the jar. Part 2: Formula: EV = Equity + Debt + Preferred Stock + Minority Interest - Cash. Part 3: Bridge: Equity = EV - Debt - Preferred Stock - Minority Interest + Cash. Part 4: Other claims: Pension obligations, Operating lease liabilities (capitalized), Deferred tax liabilities. Part 5: Minority Interest is added because consolidated financials include 100% of a subsidiary's results; adding the minority piece keeps valuation consistent.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Part 1: A company has an Enterprise Value of $550, Debt of $60, Cash of $10, and 10 shares outstanding. What is its share price? Part 2: The company then raises $50 of new debt and holds it as cash. What is the new share price? Part 3: Instead, the company raises $50 of debt and uses the proceeds to pay a dividend. What is the new share price? Part 4: As another alternative, the company raises $50 of debt and uses the proceeds to repurchase stock. What is the new share price? Part 5: Comparing the dividend and share repurchase scenarios, in which case are investors better off?",a:"Part 1: Share Price: $50. Equity Value = EV - Debt + Cash = $550 - $60 + $10 = $500. Share Price = $500 / 10 shares = $50. Part 2: Raise Debt, Hold Cash: $50. New Cash = $10 + $50 = $60. New Debt = $60 + $50 = $110. Equity Value = $550 - $110 + $60 = $500. Share Price = $500 / 10 shares = $50 (unchanged). Part 3: Raise Debt, Pay Dividend: $45. New Debt = $60 + $50 = $110. Cash unchanged at $10 (raised cash paid out). Equity Value = $550 - $110 + $10 = $450. Share Price = $450 / 10 shares = $45. Part 4: Raise Debt, Repurchase Stock: $50. New Debt = $60 + $50 = $110. Shares Repurchased = $50 / $50 = 1 share. New Shares Outstanding = 10 - 1 = 9 shares. Equity Value = $550 - $110 + $10 = $450. Share Price = $450 / 9 shares = $50. Part 5: Investor Comparison: Investors are economically indifferent in a perfect market with no taxes. Dividend: Investors receive $5/share cash, hold shares worth $45 = $50 total value. Buyback: Investors hold shares worth $50. However, in practice, buybacks are often preferable due to tax efficiency (capital gains vs. dividend taxation).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In FY1, EV/EBITDA = 5x and EV/Revenue = 2x. In FY2, EV/EBITDA = 6x and EV/Revenue = 1x. Assume EV remains constant. How much does revenue change between FY1 and FY2?",a:"Revenue doubles from FY1 to FY2, increasing by 100%. FY1: EV/Revenue = 2x → Revenue = EV / 2. FY2: EV/Revenue = 1x → Revenue = EV. Change in Revenue: Revenue in FY2 = 2 x Revenue in FY1.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Share price=$50, Basic shares=200. Securities: 50 options (strike $20), 30 RSUs, $6k converts ($1k par, $40 conversion price). What is the fully diluted equity value?",a:"$20,500. 1. The options are in-the-money since the exercise price ($20) is below the current price ($50). Exercising 50 options at $20 each generates $1,000 for the company, which it uses to buy back shares at the current price of $50 per share ($1,000 / $50 = 20 shares repurchased). Thus, there is a net issuance of 30 new shares. 2. RSUs lead to the creation of 30 additional shares. 3. Each convertible bond ($1,000 par value) converts at $40 per share, resulting in 25 new shares per bond ($1,000 / $40). With a total bond value of $6,000, the total new shares issued are 150 ($6,000 / $1,000 x 25). 4. The total diluted shares outstanding are 200 (original) + 30 (options) + 30 (RSUs) + 150 (convertibles) = 410 shares. 5. At the current share price of $50, the diluted equity value equals 410 x $50 = $20,500. Common mistake: options add 30, not 20 - TSM = 50 - (50×20)/50 = 30.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is enterprise value, conceptually?",a:"What the operating business itself is worth, to everyone with a claim on it.\n\nYou build it from market cap by adding debt and preferred, because a buyer inherits those obligations, and subtracting cash, because a buyer gets the cash back at close so it effectively reduces the price.\n\nThe point: the intuition is that EV is what you would pay to own the business free and clear, independent of how it happens to be financed. Equity value is what the shareholders own after the lenders are satisfied. That is why two identical businesses with different debt loads have the same EV and very different equity values.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You are given the following information for a company: EPS = $1.00, P/E Multiple = 15x, Shares Outstanding = 100, Total Debt = $500, Cash = $0. Part 1: Calculate the Equity Value and Enterprise Value. Part 2: Now, assume the following: Tax Rate = 20%, Interest Rate on Debt = 10%, D&A = $25. Calculate the EV/EBITDA multiple.",a:"Part 1: Equity Value and Enterprise Value: Equity Value = $1,500. Enterprise Value = $2,000. Share Price = EPS × P/E = $1.00 × 15 = $15. Equity Value = Share Price × Shares = $15 × 100 = $1,500. EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash = $1,500 + $500 - $0 = $2,000. Part 2: EV/EBITDA Multiple: Answer: 10.0x. Net Income = EPS × Shares = $1.00 × 100 = $100. Pre-Tax Income = NI / (1 - Tax Rate) = $100 / 0.80 = $125. Interest Expense = Debt × Interest Rate = $500 × 10% = $50. EBIT = Pre-Tax Income + Interest Expense = $125 + $50 = $175. EBITDA = EBIT + D&A = $175 + $25 = $200. EV/EBITDA = $2,000 / $200 = 10.0x.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In FY1, EV/EBITDA = 5x and EV/Revenue = 2x. In FY2, EV/EBITDA = 6x and EV/Revenue = 1x. Assume EV remains constant. How do EBITDA margins change between FY1 and FY2?",a:"EBITDA margins decrease from 40% in FY1 to approximately 16.7% in FY2. FY1: EBITDA = EV / 5. Revenue = EV / 2. EBITDA Margin = (EV / 5) / (EV / 2) = 2/5 = 40%. FY2: EBITDA = EV / 6. Revenue = EV. EBITDA Margin = (EV / 6) / EV = 1/6 ≈ 16.7%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Use the following information: Enterprise value = $1,500, Market value of equity = $1,000, Book value of equity = $500, Non-controlling interest = $50, Net income = $100, Net income margin = 25%, EPS = $2. Answer the following: 1. Net debt, 2. Current share price, 3. P/E multiple, 4. Revenue, 5. EV/Revenue multiple, 6. Why might you use P/E instead of EV/Revenue?",a:"Part 1: Net Debt: $450. Net debt = EV - Equity value - NCI = 1,500 - 1,000 - 50 = 450. Part 2: Share Price: $20. Shares = Net income / EPS = 100 / 2 = 50. Price = Market cap / Shares = 1,000 / 50 = 20. Part 3: P/E Multiple: 10×. P/E = Price / EPS = 20 / 2 = 10×. Part 4: Revenue: $400. Revenue = Net income / Margin = 100 / 25% = 400. Part 5: EV/Revenue: 3.75×. 1,500 / 400 = 3.75×. Part 6: P/E vs. EV/Revenue: P/E is widely available for profitable public companies and reflects equity-holder economics. EV/Revenue is useful when earnings are negative or distorted but is a cruder measure because it ignores margins and capital structure.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has the following characteristics: Total Assets: $3,000, Leverage (Total Debt / Book Equity): 3.0x, Price to Book Value (P/BV): 2.0x. Answer the following questions: 1. What are the company's Total Debt, Book Equity, and Market Cap? 2. Assuming zero cash, what is the company's Enterprise Value? 3. If the company trades at a 15.0x P/E multiple, what is its Net Income? 4. In a separate scenario, if this company has an EBITDA of $200 and is sold for an 8.0x EV/EBITDA multiple, what is the implied Enterprise Value of the transaction? 5. Following on from the previous part, what is the implied P/E ratio of the transaction?",a:"Key Outputs: Total Debt $2,250, Book Equity $750, Market Cap $1,500, Enterprise Value $3,750, Net Income $100, Transaction EV $1,600, Implied P/E ≈ -6.5× (equity underwater). Calculations: Assets = Debt + Equity → 3,000 = 4E → E = 750. Debt = 3× 750 = 2,250. Market Cap = 2.0× 750 = 1,500. EV = 1,500 + 2,250 = 3,750. NI = 1,500 ÷ 15 = 100. Transaction EV = 8× 200 = 1,600. Equity Value at exit = 1,600 - 2,250 = -650 → P/E = -650 ÷ 100 = -6.5×.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company trades at 11x EV/EBITDA with $100M EBITDA, $100M cash, $300M debt, 100M shares. What is the implied share price?",a:"$9. EV = 11 * $100M = $1,100M. Equity Value = $1,100M + $100M - $300M = $900M. Share Price = $900M / 100M Shares Outstanding = $9.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Debt/EBITDA = 8x, Debt/Equity = 1x. What is EV/EBITDA?",a:"16x. Debt (D) = Equity (E). EV = D + E → EV = 2D. Debt/EBITDA = 8x → D = 8 x EBITDA. EV / EBITDA = (2D) / EBITDA = 2D / EBITDA = 2 * 8 = 16x.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Beyond the standard components of debt, cash, preferred stock, and minority interest, what are some less-common items you might consider when calculating a company's Enterprise Value?",a:"Less-common EV adjustments: Operating Leases: Under new accounting standards (ASC 842), these may need adjustment. Pension Obligations: Unfunded pension liabilities can be added to EV. Contingent Liabilities: Pending litigation or environmental liabilities. Equity Investments in Affiliates: Non-controlling stakes in other companies. Earnout Obligations: Future payments contingent on performance. Non-Core Assets: Excess real estate or investments held for sale may be subtracted like cash. Deferred Tax Assets/Liabilities: In certain contexts, material DTLs may be added.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is unusual about a company with an EV/EBITDA multiple of 15x and an EV/EBIT multiple of 12x?",a:"This implies negative Depreciation & Amortization, which is impossible under normal accounting. If EV/EBITDA = 15x, then EBITDA = EV / 15. If EV/EBIT = 12x, then EBIT = EV / 12. Since EBITDA = EBIT + D&A, we have: EV / 15 = EV / 12 + D&A. Solving: D&A = EV / 15 - EV / 12 = -EV / 60. This implies negative D&A, which is not possible. The situation is unusual because EV/EBIT should always exceed EV/EBITDA since EBIT is smaller than EBITDA. The data likely contains an error or special accounting treatment.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company provides the following financial data: Revenue: $2,000, SG&A: $500, Total Debt: $1,000, Interest Rate on Debt: 10%, Tax Rate: 25%, Shares Outstanding: 100, P/E Multiple: 20.0x. What is the company's current share price?",a:"$210. EBIT = 2,000 - 500 = 1,500. Interest = 1,000 × 10% = 100. Pre-tax = 1,400 → NI = 1,400 × (1 - 25%) = 1,050. EPS = 1,050 / 100 = 10.5. Price = EPS × P/E = 10.5 × 20 = 210.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Given the following information, what is the company's share price? EBITDA: $100 million, EV/EBITDA Multiple: 7.0x, Net Debt: $400 million, Shares Outstanding: 50 million.",a:"$6 per share. Enterprise Value = $100m × 7.0x = $700m. Equity Value = $700m - $400m Net Debt = $300m. Share Price = $300m / 50m shares = $6.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has $55M in EBITDA and trades at a 10x EV/EBITDA multiple. Assuming the company has $150M in debt, $50M in cash, and 20M shares outstanding, what is its share price?",a:"$22.50. EV = 10x * $55M = $550M. Equity Value = EV - Debt + Cash = $550M - $150M + $50M = $450M. Share Price = $450M / 20M shares = $22.50.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are limitations of using the Exit Multiple Method when conducting valuation?",a:"It assumes you can sell the company at a chosen multiple in the future, which may be unpredictable (especially in cyclical industries). Often you mitigate by providing a range of exit multiples and compare with a Gordon Growth approach for cross-checking.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk me from Enterprise Value to a per-share stock price.",a:"Steps: 1. Start with Enterprise Value. 2. Subtract Net Debt (Debt - Cash). 3. Subtract Noncontrolling Interest and Preferred Stock. 4. This gives you Equity Value. 5. Divide Equity Value by Diluted Shares Outstanding. 6. Result is the per-share stock price.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some multiples you could use for a company with a negative Net Income?",a:"Move up the income statement until you find a line that is still positive. EV/EBITDA first. If EBITDA is also negative, EV/Revenue.\n\nIf revenue is minimal too, use whatever drives value in that industry: EV per subscriber, per user, per daily production, per store.\n\nThe point: a negative denominator produces a negative multiple, which carries no information at all. The mistake is reading it as very cheap. It is a signal that the metric does not apply to this company yet, so you find one that does.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has $200 in equity value, $300 in debt, $50 in cash, preferred stock of 25, and goodwill of 100. What is enterprise value?",a:"$475. EV = 200 + 300 + 25 - 50 = 475. Goodwill is already embedded in equity value and need not be adjusted.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When using valuation multiples, why does an EBITDA multiple yield Enterprise Value while an Earnings multiple yields Equity Value?",a:"The difference lies in what each metric represents in the capital structure. EBITDA: Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization. It's an operating metric available to all investors (debt and equity), so it corresponds to Enterprise Value. Earnings (Net Income): Bottom-line profit after interest and taxes, belonging only to equity holders. Therefore, it corresponds to Equity Value. Multiples must match: enterprise-level metrics (EBITDA) pair with EV, while equity-level metrics (Earnings) pair with Equity Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In a public comparables analysis, why is the EV/Earnings multiple conceptually flawed and therefore not used?",a:"EV/Earnings is conceptually flawed due to a mismatch between numerator and denominator. Enterprise Value represents value to all stakeholders (debt and equity holders). Earnings (Net Income) is after interest expense, representing value only to equity holders. This creates inconsistency: EV should be paired with pre-interest metrics (EBITDA, EBIT, Unlevered FCF), while Earnings should be paired with equity value (P/E ratio). Using EV/Earnings would make companies with different capital structures incomparable, defeating the purpose of using capital structure-neutral metrics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"From the following list, which valuation multiples are conceptually flawed because they mismatch capital structure claims? Explain why. EV/EBITDA, Price/EBITDA, EV/Net Income, P/E",a:"Price/EBITDA and EV/Net Income are flawed. Price/EBITDA pairs equity value with a pre-interest metric. EV/Net Income pairs enterprise value with a post-interest metric. EV/EBITDA and P/E are correctly matched.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has $100M EBITDA, is comparable at 5x EV/EBITDA, has $200M in Debt, and issues $100M in Equity. What is the impact on EV and Equity Value? How does ownership change?",a:"Enterprise Value is unchanged at $500M, Equity Value increases to $400M, and existing shareholders are diluted to 75% ownership (25% dilution). Pre-Raise Analysis: EBITDA = $100M and EV/EBITDA = 5x → Enterprise Value (EV) = $500M. Total Debt = $200M → Equity Value = $300M (since EV = Equity + Net Debt). After Raising $100M in Equity: Equity Value increases from $300M to $400M. Net Debt becomes $200M (existing debt) - $100M (new cash) = $100M. EV remains $500M (Equity + Net Debt = $400M + $100M). New investors own $100M / $400M = 25% dilution.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two companies have the same Enterprise Value, but one has a higher debt-to-equity ratio. Which company will have the higher P/E multiple?",a:"The company with lower leverage (less debt) will have the higher P/E ratio. Reasoning: Same Enterprise Value: Both companies have the same total value available to all capital providers. Risk Effect (Dominant Factor): Higher leverage increases financial risk for equity holders. This increased risk leads to a higher cost of equity. Valuation Impact: Investors will pay less for a dollar of riskier earnings, which directly translates to a lower P/E multiple. Net Result: The risk effect dominates the mechanical effects on the P/E formula; higher leverage = lower P/E multiple.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company with an Enterprise Value of $5 billion has no debt and no cash. If it issues $2 billion in new debt and holds the proceeds as cash, what is its new Enterprise Value and Equity Value?",a:"EV = $5B, Equity Value = $5B. EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash. Initially: $5B = Equity Value + $0 - $0, so Equity Value = $5B. After issuance: EV = Equity Value + $2B - $2B = Equity Value. Enterprise Value remains $5B (debt and cash offset). Equity Value remains $5B (no change to underlying business value).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If the EV/EBIT of a company is 3x and its EV/EBITDA is 4x, what does that tell you about the company?",a:"EBITDA is < EBIT, so D&A is negative. Because EV is constant, a higher EV/EBITDA multiple means the EBITDA denominator is smaller than EBIT, which only happens if D&A is recorded as a credit (e.g., reversal of impairment, amortization of negative goodwill, or other non-recurring income). It's worth noting that this scenario is unusual and likely reflects an accounting anomaly rather than normal operations.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You are given a company's share price, number of shares outstanding, cash balance, and a relevant peer-derived EV/EBITDA multiple. How would you calculate the implied value of the company's debt?",a:"Steps: 1. Calculate Equity Value: Share Price × Shares Outstanding. 2. Estimate EBITDA from comparable analysis or financial statements. 3. Calculate Enterprise Value: EBITDA × Peer EV/EBITDA Multiple. 4. Solve for Debt: EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash → Debt = EV - Equity Value + Cash.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In a tax-free world, a firm with $500 million EV issues $100 million of new debt. What is the new EV?",a:"Enterprise value remains $500 million, assuming the cash is retained on the balance sheet and not spent. TEV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash. Adding debt and adding the same amount of cash cancels out.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You have a company with an EV/Revenue of 2x and an EV/EBITDA of 10x. What is the EBITDA margin?",a:"20%. Because an EV/Revenue of 2x and EV/EBITDA of 10x implies EBITDA is 1/5th of revenue (i.e. 20% margin).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company's stock trades at $15 per share, and it has 100 shares outstanding. The company also has $600 in debt, $100 in cash, and generated $200 in EBITDA. What is the company's EV/EBITDA multiple?",a:"10.0x. Equity Value = $15 * 100 = $1,500. EV = $1,500 + $600 - $100 = $2,000. EV/EBITDA = $2,000 / $200 = 10.0x.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"The company issues $300 million of new equity that is not invested in the business. What happens to enterprise value?",a:"Unchanged. Equity value rises $300M because new shares were sold, and cash rises $300M, which gets subtracted. The two cancel exactly.\n\nThe point: this is the cleanest test of what enterprise value measures. The company obviously has more money and is bigger on the equity side, and the operations produce exactly the same cash as yesterday. EV values the business, not the bank balance. Raising money does not make a business more valuable, it just parks capital inside it.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do share buybacks affect a company's Earnings Per Share (EPS)?",a:"Share buybacks typically increase EPS. Mechanics: Company repurchases shares, reducing shares outstanding. If Net Income remains constant, EPS = NI / Shares Outstanding increases. However, if buyback is debt-financed, increased interest expense reduces NI, partially offsetting EPS benefit. If cash-financed, company loses interest income on that cash, slightly reducing NI. Net effect is usually accretive to EPS, especially if company buys back shares at prices below intrinsic value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does raising $200m in Debt and using cash to buy a new piece of equipment affect Enterprise Value?",a:"EV up by 200. EV = EqV + Debt - Cash etc. +200 debt (from raise). -200 cash (borrowing in form of debt). The equipment purchase is a decrease in cash, which gets subtracted from EV formula (increasing it).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"100 shares outstanding at $5 a share, $600 debt, $300 cash. Calculate EV.",a:"$800. Enterprise Value = Equity Value (100 × $5 = $500) + Debt ($600) - Cash ($300).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you have two companies with the same Enterprise Value, but one has higher leverage than the other, which one has the higher P/E ratio?",a:"The company with lower leverage (less debt) will have the higher P/E ratio. Reasoning: Risk: Higher leverage increases the financial risk for equity holders. Investors demand a higher rate of return to compensate for this increased risk. Cost of Equity and P/E: A higher required return on equity (Cost of Equity) translates directly to a lower P/E multiple an investor is willing to pay for a dollar of earnings. Conclusion: Therefore, the company with higher leverage will be perceived as riskier and will trade at a lower P/E multiple.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You serve on a company's board and own a significant stake. The CEO claims the stock is up 20% this year. Does that mean it's performing well?",a:"You need context: if the market or sector is up 50%, then a 20% gain is an underperformance. It's about relative returns, not just absolute percentage change.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has an enterprise value of $100 but a market cap of $50. Does that mean the firm is undervalued?",a:"Not necessarily. Market cap (equity value) is one of multiple components that make up total enterprise value. Whether the firm is undervalued depends on fundamental/intrinsic analysis, not just TEV vs. EqV.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is a multiple such as Equity Value / Sales conceptually flawed?",a:"Equity Value / Sales is flawed because it compares an equity metric (Equity Value) to an enterprise metric (Sales). Sales benefits all stakeholders (debt and equity holders), not just equity. Companies with different capital structures would be incomparable. A highly leveraged company would appear cheaper despite higher financial risk. The correct multiple is EV/Sales, which compares enterprise-level value to enterprise-level revenue.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between total cash and excess cash?",a:"Total Cash is all cash and cash equivalents on the balance sheet. Excess Cash is cash beyond what the company needs for day-to-day operations (working capital requirements). In Enterprise Value calculations, only excess cash is subtracted, as operating cash is necessary for the business. Determining excess cash requires judgment about minimum cash needs.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does paying down $100M debt affect a company's enterprise value?",a:"Unchanged, assuming cash was used. Debt falls $100M and cash falls $100M, and since EV adds debt and subtracts cash, the two moves cancel.\n\nThe point: the company swapped an asset for the removal of a liability of the same size. Nothing about the operations changed, so nothing about enterprise value should. Equity value is also roughly unchanged for the same reason. What does change is future earnings, since interest expense drops, which is why the equity gets slightly more valuable over time.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Net Income: $100, EBITDA: $350, P/E: 8x, EV/EBITDA: 4x. What is net debt?",a:"First, calculate Equity Value using P/E: Equity Value = P/E * Net Income = 8 * $100 = $800. Next, calculate Enterprise Value using EV/EBITDA: EV = EV/EBITDA * EBITDA = 4 * $350 = $1,400. Finally, Net Debt = EV - Equity Value = $1,400 - $800 = $600.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the primary benefits and drawbacks of using the EV/EBITDA multiple compared to the P/E multiple for valuation?",a:"EV/EBITDA: Neutral to capital structure and taxes. Useful across sectors and leverage levels. Ignores capex. Can overvalue capital-intensive firms. P/E: Directly reflects equity return after all expenses. Simple and widely quoted. Distorted by leverage, tax strategies, and non-cash items.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might a company with the same P/E ratio as its peers have a lower EV/EBITDA multiple?",a:"This wedge occurs when a company has a different capital structure or D&A profile. Key drivers: Higher Depreciation & Amortization: This depresses Net Income (raising P/E) but is added back to EBITDA (lowering EV/EBITDA). Different Tax Rates: A higher tax rate depresses Net Income without affecting EBITDA. Different Interest Expenses: Higher leverage/interest lowers Net Income, keeping P/E high, while EV/EBITDA is capital structure neutral.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When bridging from Enterprise Value to Equity Value, why are Non-Controlling Interest (NCI) and Preferred Stock subtracted?",a:"Both NCI and Preferred Stock are subtracted because: Non-Controlling Interest (NCI): When a company consolidates a majority-owned subsidiary, it includes 100% of the subsidiary's value in Enterprise Value. However, the parent doesn't own 100% of the equity. Minority shareholders own a portion. NCI represents the claim that minority shareholders have on the consolidated entity. Must subtract NCI to arrive at equity value attributable only to common shareholders of the parent. Preferred Stock: Preferred shareholders have a claim senior to common equity but junior to debt. Enterprise Value includes all claims, but equity value refers specifically to common equity. Must subtract preferred stock value to isolate value for common shareholders.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What metric is used in the numerator of the EBITDA multiple, and what is the underlying principle for pairing them?",a:"Enterprise Value. Principle: pair a capital-structure-neutral numerator (EV) with a capital-structure-neutral denominator (EBITDA) so both reflect value available to all stakeholders before interest.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Please provide the standard formula for Enterprise Value. Then, discuss what other items you might add to create a more comprehensive or fully-loaded Enterprise Value calculation.",a:"Simple EV Formula: EV = Equity Value + Debt + Minority Interest + Preferred Stock - Cash. More comprehensive EV Formula: EV = Equity Value + Debt + Minority Interest + Preferred Stock - Cash - Net Operating Losses - Investments + Capital Leases + Pension Obligations. The more comprehensive version simply adjusts for other non-operating assets and off-balance-sheet obligations that behave just like debt or cash. In short, you add anything that acts like debt or a claim on the business, and subtract everything you're acquiring that acts like cash or a receivable.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does paying down $300 of debt affect the Enterprise Value?",a:"No change. Remember: EV = Equity Value + Debt - Cash. According to the enterprise value formula, the changes in debt and cash offset each other. Since paying down debt is a capital structure change, it's important to recognize that this action does not impact the company's enterprise value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company's share price is $51. It has 30 shares authorized and 20 shares outstanding. What is its equity value?",a:"$1,020 (51 × 20). Authorized shares are irrelevant to market cap.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do we look at both Enterprise Value and Equity Value?",a:"Enterprise Value reflects the company's value attributable to all investors. Equity Value represents only the portion available to shareholders. We look at both because Equity Value is what the public sees, while Enterprise Value offers a more holistic view of the company's worth.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When evaluating an acquisition, should you focus on Enterprise Value or Equity Value?",a:"You focus on Enterprise Value, because it reflects the total amount that all investors (debt and equity) are entitled to. Equity Value ignores debt and other obligations that an acquirer will likely have to assume or refinance.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the basic formula for Enterprise Value?",a:"Enterprise Value = Equity Value + Debt + Preferred Stock + Minority Interest - Cash. Sometimes, other items like capital leases and unfunded pension obligations are added, but this is the standard starting formula.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is Minority Interest added in the calculation of Enterprise Value?",a:"When a company owns more than 50% of another entity, it consolidates 100% of that subsidiary's financial results in its own statements. Metrics like revenue and EBITDA then reflect the entire subsidiary, so you add Minority Interest to align the ownership value with those consolidated figures.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you calculate fully diluted shares?",a:"Start with the basic share count and add the dilutive effect of options, warrants, or convertible securities. Use the Treasury Stock Method for options and warrants: assume in-the-money instruments are exercised and any proceeds buy back shares.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has 100 shares at $10 each and 10 options at a $5 strike. What is its fully diluted Equity Value?",a:"Basic Equity Value is 100 × $10 = $1,000. Those 10 in-the-money options generate $5 × 10 = $50 if exercised. The company uses that $50 to repurchase 5 shares at $10 each, so net new shares = 5. Fully diluted share count is 105. Fully diluted Equity Value is 105 × $10 = $1,050.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Another company has 100 shares at $10 each and 10 options at a $15 strike. What is its fully diluted Equity Value?",a:"Since the exercise price ($15) exceeds the current share price ($10), the options are out-of-the-money. No dilution occurs, so fully diluted Equity Value remains 100 × $10 = $1,000.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why subtract cash when calculating Enterprise Value? Is it always correct?",a:"Cash is subtracted because it's seen as a non-operating asset that can reduce the net purchase price. In reality, you should subtract only excess cash beyond what's needed for daily operations, but most models subtract total cash for simplicity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Should Debt always be added to Equity Value when calculating Enterprise Value?",a:"In almost all cases, yes. Debt typically has to be repaid or assumed by the acquirer, so it increases the effective price of the target. Very rare exceptions exist if the acquirer doesn't pay off the debt, but that's uncommon in M&A.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can Enterprise Value be negative? What does that imply?",a:"Yes. If a company has very large cash balances or a minuscule market capitalization, the result can be negative. This situation typically arises for distressed companies or certain financial institutions with huge cash holdings.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can a company have a negative Equity Value?",a:"A company's market equity value (i.e., its market cap) cannot be negative, as share prices and share counts cannot be negative. However, a company's book equity value (from the balance sheet) can be negative if it has sustained significant losses over time. Additionally, a company's implied equity value (calculated from Enterprise Value) can be negative in a valuation or restructuring scenario. This occurs if the company's total debt and other senior claims exceed its enterprise value, indicating that equity holders would receive nothing in a sale.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do we add Preferred Stock to Equity Value when calculating Enterprise Value?",a:"Preferred Stock has debt-like characteristics: fixed dividends and a higher claim on assets than common equity. From an acquirer's viewpoint, it's more like debt than equity, so it's included in Enterprise Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has 1 million shares at $100 each and $10 million in convertible bonds, par $1,000, conversion price $50. How many diluted shares are there?",a:"Each $1,000 bond converts into $1,000 ÷ $50 = 20 shares. There are $10 million ÷ $1,000 = 10,000 bonds, for 10,000 × 20 = 200,000 new shares. Total shares = 1,000,000 + 200,000 = 1.2 million (since the bonds are in-the-money).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How is Equity Value different from Shareholders' Equity?",a:"Equity Value is a market-based measure (share price × shares), while Shareholders' Equity is the book value from the Balance Sheet. Equity Value can't be negative, but Shareholders' Equity can be, depending on a company's assets and liabilities.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Besides Cash, Debt, Preferred Stock, and Minority Interest, which other items might appear in Enterprise Value?",a:"You might adjust for capital leases, unfunded pension obligations, equity investments, or other non-operating assets or liabilities. Different banks treat these differently, but the main idea is 'add debt-like items, subtract cash-like items.'",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do you add Non-Controlling Interest (Minority Interest) when moving from Equity Value to Enterprise Value?",a:"Minority Interest pertains to a subsidiary that you partially own and fully consolidate. It's not truly your 'equity,' but you still recognize 100% of the subsidiary's performance (EBITDA). Hence, you add Minority Interest separately to Enterprise Value so that the numerator (EV) captures the full value of the subsidiary, matching the denominator (EBITDA) which captures the full earnings.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In an acquisition, do you value a target based on basic shares or fully diluted shares?",a:"You typically use the fully diluted share count, because any in-the-money options or convertible securities will likely vest or convert in a change-of-control scenario. That increases the effective purchase price.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Could a company's Enterprise Value ever match its Equity Value exactly?",a:"Yes, in theory EV can equal Equity Value when all bridge items sum to zero: Net Debt = Debt - Cash = 0 (either both are zero or they offset). No preferred stock. No non-controlling (minority) interests. Because most companies carry some net debt, preferred stock, or minority interest, exact parity is uncommon in practice.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might you subtract 'long-term investments' in the Enterprise Value formula?",a:"If the company owns sizable non-core investments (like minority stakes or securities) that generate returns unrelated to its main operations, some argue those should be subtracted (like cash) to reflect net operating value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Is the Enterprise Value the same as the purchase price in an acquisition?",a:"It's generally close to the purchase price, but not always exactly the same. For instance, you might negotiate adjustments for cash and debt levels at closing, so the final 'purchase price' may differ slightly from the initially calculated EV.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Would you consider 'marketable securities' similarly to cash when calculating Enterprise Value?",a:"Generally yes, if they are liquid and can be easily converted to cash. They're often treated as cash equivalents and subtracted from Equity Value in arriving at Enterprise Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How might unfunded pension obligations affect Enterprise Value?",a:"Unfunded pension obligations represent additional liabilities and are added to Enterprise Value as they signify future cash outflows and financial obligations.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What role does preferred stock play in Enterprise Value calculations?",a:"Preferred stock has debt-like characteristics, such as fixed dividends and higher claim on assets than common equity. Therefore, it is added to Equity Value when calculating Enterprise Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might you add Unfunded Pension Obligations but not Accounts Payable in Enterprise Value?",a:"Accounts Payable is usually a short-term, operational liability that doesn't require separate financing. Unfunded Pension Obligations are larger, long-term obligations that often demand external financing. They're more 'debt-like.'",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How might you treat Equity Interests when calculating Enterprise Value?",a:"If a company's metrics (like revenue or EBITDA) exclude the affiliate company's performance, you subtract the Equity Interest from the parent's EV. The logic: you don't want to 'pay' for a business whose revenue or EBITDA you aren't actually consolidating.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Should you use the market or book value for Debt in Enterprise Value?",a:"Ideally, use market value if it's available (especially if the debt trades significantly above or below par). In practice, many models just use the book value from the Balance Sheet for simplicity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Could the dilution from stock options exceed 10% of the company's market cap?",a:"Theoretically yes, especially for tech or startup companies with significant option pools. Such large dilution is uncommon but not impossible.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you factor in Convertible Preferred Stock in the Enterprise Value calculation?",a:"If it's in-the-money, treat it like additional shares. If it's out of the money, consider it more like debt (since it pays a fixed dividend and ranks above common equity).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do RSUs and Performance Shares affect the diluted share count?",a:"RSUs are effectively common shares that vest, so you add them to the share count once they're granted. Performance Shares convert if certain targets are met (e.g. share price, EPS), so you include them in the diluted count if they are in-the-money.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How are Options Exercisable vs. Options Outstanding handled for share dilution?",a:"If not all options are exercisable yet, you might only consider the portion that's exercisable. However, in an acquisition, typically all outstanding options become exercisable, so you might use the total.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might we not apply the Treasury Stock Method to convertible bonds?",a:"Convertible bonds don't generate cash proceeds for the company upon conversion, unlike stock options with an exercise price. They're treated as either 100% debt (if out-of-the-money) or additional shares (if in-the-money).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Does free cash flow (FCF) calculation impact how Equity Interests are handled in Enterprise Value?",a:"Yes. If your EBITDA or other operational metrics exclude the affiliate's performance, you subtract the Equity Interest. If you included affiliate earnings in FCF, you wouldn't subtract the Equity Interest in EV to remain consistent.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you treat performance-based stock options in the share count?",a:"Similar to standard options, but with an extra hurdle. You only count them in the diluted share count if the performance conditions (e.g., hitting an EBITDA or Revenue target) are met or are highly likely to be met. If the performance targets are not met, you ignore them, even if the strike price is otherwise in-the-money.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Can convertible debt ever be subtracted from Equity Value?",a:"Normally, no. You either treat it as debt (out-of-the-money) or additional shares (in-the-money). There's no scenario where it directly subtracts from Equity Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What if a company's debt trades at a discount? Does that affect Enterprise Value?",a:"Technically yes, if you use market values. The 'true' debt liability is lower. Practically, most models use book values for Debt, so it usually doesn't alter the Enterprise Value in standard practice.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do capital leases factor into Enterprise Value?",a:"They are generally treated like debt, since they represent a contractual obligation. So you add them to Equity Value to arrive at Enterprise Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you treat operating leases for Enterprise Value under new accounting standards?",a:"Under ASC 842/IFRS 16, many operating leases appear on the Balance Sheet with corresponding liabilities. These lease liabilities are generally considered debt-like, so they get added in the Enterprise Value calculation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why do you subtract equity investments (20-50% ownership) when calculating Enterprise Value from Equity Value?",a:"The parent doesn't consolidate those financials in its top-line metrics (Revenue/EBITDA). So you remove the value of that ownership stake from Equity Value to keep the resulting Enterprise Value aligned with the portion of revenue/EBITDA being captured (Operating Value).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How might you handle Net Operating Losses (NOLs) in Enterprise Value?",a:"NOLs can be viewed as an asset that reduces future taxes, so some practitioners subtract them (like cash). Many ignore them because they're less liquid than cash and may expire. Treatment varies by bank and scenario.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Do options always create more dilution than warrants?",a:"Not necessarily. It depends on strike prices, volumes, and structures. Either can be more dilutive if they are deeply in-the-money and represent many potential shares.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What if only part of a convertible issue is in-the-money?",a:"You would split it proportionally. The in-the-money portion converts into equity, and the rest remains as debt.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How are minority interests treated when consolidating financial statements?",a:"Minority interests represent the portion of subsidiary equity not owned by the parent. In EV calculations, minority interests are added to reflect the full consolidated financial performance.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
// === VALUATION QUESTIONS (from PDF upload) (249 new questions) ===
{q:"When would a Liquidation Valuation be most relevant?",a:"It's frequently used in bankruptcy scenarios to see if equity holders receive any leftover value. It can also help decide if selling assets individually yields more than a going-concern sale.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In what industries is EV/EBITDA commonly used and why?",a:"Industries with similar capital structures, such as manufacturing, technology, and consumer goods, often use EV/EBITDA because it allows for comparison of operational efficiency without the distortion of financing choices.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you incorporate market sentiment into a Comparable Companies Analysis?",a:"In Public Comps, sentiment is already embedded in trading multiples at the valuation date. You don't add a separate 'sentiment input.' Make it explicit by using a recent pricing date or short VWAP window, leaning on NTM multiples if estimates better capture current conditions, and benchmarking against sector/company historical multiple bands to flag froth or dislocation. For cyclicals, normalize to mid-cycle margins so temporary swings don't overstate value, show valuation ranges/sensitivities, and triangulate with DCF and precedents.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You are given a company's historical P/E, EV/EBITDA, and EV/EBIT ratios over the past five years. What factors would you analyze to understand the trends in these multiples and what might they indicate about the company's performance and market perception?",a:"Analyze: Financial Performance (revenue/earnings growth, margin expansion/contraction, capital intensity changes). Capital Structure (leverage trends affecting EV/EBITDA vs P/E divergence, interest coverage). Market Perception (sector rotation, competitive positioning changes, growth expectations vs peers). Operational Factors (D&A intensity widening EBITDA-EBIT gap, quality of earnings). Rising multiples generally indicate improving growth or sentiment; declining multiples suggest deteriorating fundamentals or increased risk.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has $100m in sales with a 10% EBITDA margin. Which would you prefer: a 10% increase in quantity sold, a 5% increase in price, or a 5% reduction in cost?",a:"The 5% increase in price yields the highest absolute EBITDA ($15M). 10% Increase in Quantity (costs scale proportionally): Revenue = $110M, Costs = $99M, EBITDA = $11M. 5% Increase in Price (no volume drop): Revenue = $105M, Costs = $90M, EBITDA = $15M. 5% Reduction in Costs: Revenue = $100M, Costs = $85.5M, EBITDA = $14.5M. In practice, if meaningful price sensitivity exists, the cost reduction may become more desirable.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What's the problem with EBITDA? What's the problem with EBIT? What's another metric that helps solve both?",a:"EBITDA: Ignores capex (no reflection of ongoing maintenance or growth investments). EBIT: Includes depreciation (a non-cash item) but might still not reflect actual cash outflows for capex. EBITDA - Capex: Helps account for ongoing reinvestment needs, offering a closer proxy to true cash flow.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you calculate the Terminal Value for a forestry company?",a:"For a forestry company, Terminal Value should reflect long-term sustainable harvest and regrowth cycles. Approaches: 1) Perpetuity Growth Method with a low stable growth rate (0-2%) reflecting sustainable timber yields and inflation. 2) Exit Multiple using EV/EBITDA from comparable forestry companies at maturity. 3) Asset-Based Approach valuing standing timber inventory and land at terminal year using per-acre or per-ton metrics. Use conservative assumptions given commodity price volatility and biological constraints.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you had a few minutes on a plane with a CEO, what key questions would you ask to quickly form a high-level valuation of their company?",a:"Essential questions: 1) What is your current annual revenue and EBITDA margin? 2) What is your revenue growth rate over the past 2-3 years? 3) What is your net debt position (or cash balance)? 4) Who are your closest public comparables? 5) What are your key value drivers and competitive advantages? 6) What is your capital intensity (annual capex as % of revenue)? With these answers, you can quickly apply a trading comp multiple to EBITDA and triangulate an approximate Enterprise Value and Equity Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you can't find EBITDA for a company (for example, a private comp), where might you look?",a:"Sources and proxies: Add D&A from the cash-flow statement to EBIT from the income statement. Use management presentations or lender information memos. Check equity research or industry reports. Ask management directly or infer using peer margins.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company could sell for 10x EBITDA in a private sale or IPO at a 12x EBITDA multiple, how would you determine which is the better option?",a:"Key considerations beyond valuation multiple: Timing & Certainty (private sale offers faster execution and deal certainty; IPO has market risk and longer timeline). Transaction Costs (IPO involves underwriting fees 5-7%, legal costs, and ongoing compliance expenses). Liquidity (IPO may have lock-up periods; private sale provides immediate full liquidity). Market Conditions (IPO valuation depends on market receptivity). Strategic Value (buyer in private sale may pay premium for synergies). Future Optionality (IPO maintains independence and strategic flexibility). After adjusting for costs and risks, compare net proceeds and execution probability.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you build a public-company comparables set?",a:"Look at a few factors: Industry, Financials (Revenue, EBITDA), and Geography. Industry is the most important factor. Examples of screens: Retail apparel brands with market caps above $2 billion, Enterprise SaaS companies with growth rates above 30%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Compare EV/EBIT, EV/EBITDA, and P/E in terms of what they measure and when you use them.",a:"EV/EBIT and EV/EBITDA are capital-structure neutral, reflecting value available to both debt and equity investors. P/E factors in capital structure since net income is after interest. EV/EBIT is more relevant if depreciation is sizable, while EV/EBITDA is common where depreciation is smaller.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do rising central bank rates affect the cost of equity?",a:"They raise the risk-free rate in CAPM and typically widen equity risk premia, so the cost of equity increases.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assume 100 EBITDA at an 8x multiple, 20% margin, 10% cost of debt, 5x Debt/EBITDA, 10x P/E, and 5 in D&A. Calculate the implied tax rate.",a:"Approximately 33%. EV = 800; Debt = 500, so Equity = 300. NI = 300/10 = 30. EBIT = 95. Interest = 50. EBT = 45, Taxes = 15, so 15/45 = 33%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you explain the valuation of a private car wash to the car wash owner?",a:"You could use a market-based approach (comparable company analysis with local or similar small businesses) and an income-based approach (a simplified DCF). For the DCF, forecast cash flow (revenue from car washes minus operating costs) and discount at a rate reflecting the business's risk. Because it's private and possibly small-scale, look at local transaction multiples or industry rules of thumb (e.g., a multiple of EBITDA or SDE).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Other than the control premium, what are some reasons that precedent transaction analysis often yields a higher valuation than comparable company analysis?",a:"Synergy value (buyers pay premium for expected cost or revenue synergies). Strategic value (acquisitions unlock value not reflected in public trading). Competitive bidding (multiple bidders drive up price). Lack of liquidity discount (private companies trade at discount, but buyers pay for control). Tax benefits (asset step-up and NOL utilization). Scarcity value (limited availability of attractive targets in consolidating industries).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Forward revenue multiple is 5x, forward EBITDA multiple is 10x. Two-year forward revenue multiple is 10x, two-year forward EBITDA multiple is 25x. What does this tell you about the business? If EV is 200m, do some calculations.",a:"Next Year: Revenue = 200/5 = 40, EBITDA = 200/10 = 20. Two Years Out: Revenue = 200/10 = 20, EBITDA = 200/25 = 8. The steep jump in multiples implies earnings are expected to fall sharply. Investors think the current downturn is temporary or the company is highly cyclical.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the differences between EBITDA and FCF?",a:"EBITDA is earnings before interest, tax, depreciation, and amortization. Free cash flow subtracts the things EBITDA ignores: capex, cash taxes, interest, and working capital movements.\n\nThe point: the gap between them is the whole story for a capital-intensive company. A telecom can post enormous EBITDA and almost no free cash flow, because it spends everything on the network. EBITDA measures operating profitability and free cash flow measures what actually reaches investors. Companies do not go bankrupt from low EBITDA, they go bankrupt from running out of cash.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why would a company with a higher growth rate typically command higher valuation multiples?",a:"Higher growth rates increase the present value of future cash flows. Key reasons: Faster earnings growth leads to higher terminal value. Investors pay premium for companies that compound returns faster. Growth companies reinvest more efficiently. Higher growth often signals competitive advantages or innovation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company A has a Net Debt of $500 and trades at an EV/EBITDA multiple of 12.5x, while its direct peers trade at an average of 13.0x. What are some potential reasons for this valuation discount?",a:"Lower growth prospects: slower revenue or EBITDA growth. Higher risk profile: more cyclical, geographic or customer concentration. Weaker margins: lower or declining profitability. Higher leverage: $500 Net Debt may represent higher Debt/EBITDA. Management or governance concerns. Smaller size: less liquidity, scale disadvantages. Industry headwinds or company-specific competitive disadvantages.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two companies have the same financial statements, growth projections, same industry, but trade at different EV/EBITDA multiples. Why could that happen?",a:"Qualitative factors the numbers miss: Perceived risk (contract quality, customer concentration). Management credibility or governance. Liquidity of the float or index inclusion. M&A rumors or takeover premium. Differing ESG profiles or regulatory risks.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has EBITDA Margin: 20%, EV/Revenue Multiple: 3.0x, Revenue: $30. What is the company's EV/EBITDA multiple?",a:"15x. EBITDA = Revenue x EBITDA Margin = $30 x 20% = $6. EV = Revenue x EV/Revenue = $30 x 3.0 = $90. EV/EBITDA = $90 / $6 = 15x.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you had two identical companies, each with the same products, and one traded at 10x EBITDA and another at 20x, which one would you choose to invest in?",a:"At first glance, the cheaper (10x) might seem more attractive. But you need to investigate reasons for the higher multiple: better management, higher margins, better growth prospects, or lower risk. If all truly is identical, the lower multiple could suggest undervaluation, but in reality there might be intangible differences justifying the higher multiple.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You are comparing two companies, A and B, which are operationally identical except for their size. Company A: Share price $10, 100 shares, Net Debt $100, EBITDA $100. Company B: Share price $100, 100 shares, Net Debt $1,000, EBITDA $1,100. Which would you prefer?",a:"Company B is superior. Company A: EV = ($10 x 100) + $100 = $1,100, EV/EBITDA = 11.0x, Debt/EBITDA = 1.0x. Company B: EV = ($100 x 100) + $1,000 = $11,000, EV/EBITDA = 10.0x, Debt/EBITDA = 0.91x. Company B trades at a lower multiple (10.0x vs 11.0x) and has lower leverage (0.91x vs 1.0x), offering better value with a stronger credit profile.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two airlines have the same enterprise value. One uses capital leases, the other operating leases. Which trades at a higher EBITDA multiple?",a:"The airline with operating leases trades at a higher EBITDA multiple because lease expense reduces EBITDA, making the multiple higher.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the most commonly used valuation multiples?",a:"On the enterprise side: EV/Revenue, EV/EBITDA, and EV/EBIT. On the equity side: P/E and P/B.\n\nThe rule that governs which you use is matching. Anything above the interest line pairs with enterprise value, because that money belongs to lenders and shareholders both. Anything after interest, like net income, pairs with equity value.\n\nThe point: EV/EBITDA dominates because it neutralizes capital structure, tax, and depreciation policy, so you can compare a levered company in one country with an unlevered one in another. P/B is mostly reserved for banks, where book value actually means something.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has an EV/Sales multiple of 5x and an EBITDA margin of 20%. What is its EV/EBITDA multiple?",a:"25x. EBITDA = Revenue x 20% = 0.2 x Revenue. EV = 5x x Revenue. EV/EBITDA = (5 x Revenue) / (0.2 x Revenue) = 5 / 0.2 = 25x.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is a sum of parts valuation, and how does it work?",a:"Value each business segment independently with the most appropriate method (DCF or multiples), then sum the segment values and subtract net debt and corporate adjustments. This isolates businesses with different growth, risk and capital-intensity profiles, producing a more precise consolidated valuation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Aside from the 'big three,' what other valuation methodologies exist?",a:"Additional methods include: Liquidation Valuation, Sum-of-the-Parts, LBO Analysis, Replacement Value, M&A Premiums Analysis, Future Share Price Analysis.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the relationship between Cost of Debt and WACC?",a:"Because after-tax Cost of Debt is usually below Cost of Equity, adding reasonable leverage lowers WACC up to an optimal point. Beyond that point, default risk lifts both the Cost of Debt and the equity risk premium, causing WACC to rise.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two companies, A and B, both trade at 10x EV/EBITDA now. Next year, A is projected to trade at 9x, B at 11x. How is the main driver of returns different between them?",a:"Company A's return must come primarily from EBITDA growth and debt pay-down because the multiple is contracting. Company B benefits from multiple expansion, so valuation re-rating, not operating growth. Will drive a larger share of returns.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two identical companies are sold to the same buyer at drastically different multiples. Why?",a:"One may have had more competition in the bidding process. Or perhaps recent bad news depressed stock price, or different market sentiment at deal time.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would a company taking on more debt impact WACC?",a:"Initially WACC falls because after-tax debt is cheaper than equity. Beyond an optimal point, rising default risk pushes up the cost of both debt and equity, so WACC rises.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company believes its forward earnings will be significantly higher than what the market is projecting, resulting in a lower internal forecast for its forward multiple. How would you advise this company?",a:"Advisory recommendations: 1) Enhanced disclosure. Increase transparency through detailed guidance. 2) Investor outreach. Conduct roadshows and investor meetings. 3) Management credibility. Ensure track record of meeting/beating guidance. 4) Strategic communication. Highlight sustainable competitive advantages. 5) Consider buybacks if stock is undervalued. 6) Improve business mix. Highlight higher-margin, faster-growing segments.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has an EPS of $7 and a P/E multiple of 15x. The corporate tax rate then drops from 30% to 15%. Assuming the P/E multiple remains constant, what is the new share price?",a:"$127.50. Current Share Price = $7 x 15x = $105. Current Pre-Tax Income = $7 / (1 - 30%) = $10. New Net Income = $10 x (1 - 15%) = $8.50. New Share Price = $8.50 x 15x = $127.50.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Is relying on an EBITDA multiple always the best approach to value a business? What about P/E?",a:"It depends on the company's capital intensity, accounting peculiarities, and industry norms. EBITDA excludes CapEx and changes in working capital, so it can gloss over cash needs. P/E is also influenced by capital structure and tax strategies. The right multiple varies by situation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does a reduction in the corporate tax rate affect a company's valuation?",a:"A lower corporate tax rate generally increases valuation. Higher After-Tax Cash Flows is the primary benefit, lower taxes lead to higher net income and free cash flow. Higher WACC (Slightly) because lower tax rate reduces the benefit of the interest tax shield. Net Effect: higher cash flows almost always outweigh the slightly higher WACC, resulting in higher overall valuation. Higher Trading Multiples as investors are willing to pay more.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company A has a 1-year forward EV/Revenue multiple of 5x and a 2-year forward multiple of 3x. Company B has a 1-year forward multiple of 5x and a 2-year forward multiple of 4x. Assuming all else is equal, which company represents a better investment and why?",a:"Company A represents the better investment. The decline in forward multiples indicates expected revenue growth. Company A's multiple compresses from 5x to 3x, implying 67% revenue growth (5x / 3x = 1.67x). Company B's compresses from 5x to 4x, implying only 25% revenue growth (5x / 4x = 1.25x). Company A demonstrates significantly stronger revenue growth prospects.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk through how to calculate a company's Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC), and explain why the cost of debt is tax-affected.",a:"WACC = Cost of Equity x (% Equity) + Cost of Debt x (% Debt) x (1 - Tax Rate). Cost of Equity via CAPM = Risk-free rate + Beta x Equity risk premium. Cost of Debt from current or implied borrowing cost. Interest expense is tax-deductible, so the after-tax cost of debt is Cost of Debt x (1. T), lowering the firm's effective financing cost.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does increasing taxes impact valuation?",a:"Reduces Free Cash Flow: Higher statutory taxes reduce after-tax profit/NOPAT, lowering free cash flow. Lowers WACC (with fixed D/E): Bigger interest tax shield lowers after-tax cost of debt. Higher T leads to lower levered beta and lower Cost of Equity. Net: overall valuation impact usually declines because the FCF hit typically outweighs the discount-rate benefit. Common pitfall: don't double-count the tax shield.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Do you always pick the median multiple for a group of comps or transactions?",a:"Usually yes, but not strictly. If your target is underperforming, you might use the 25th percentile. If it's outperforming, you might use the 75th.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Calculate EV given: LFCF yield = 10%, EBITDA = 150, D&A = 50, interest expense = 10, capex = 30, Increase in A/R = 20, Decrease in A/P = 10, Increase in Inventory = 5, taxes = 25, debt = 300, cash = 75.",a:"EV = 725. EBIT = 100. NI = 65. LFCF = 50 (CFO [65 NI + 50 D&A - 35 NWC] - 30 Capex). Equity Value = 50/0.10 = 500. EV = 500 + 300 - 75 = 725.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If one company trades at a 10x multiple and another comparable company trades at 30x, what are some reasons that could explain this difference?",a:"Growth expectations (30x company likely has much higher growth rate). Profitability and margins. Risk profile (lower risk increases multiples). Market positioning and competitive moats. Size and scale differences. Sector dynamics. Capital efficiency and ROIC differences. Management quality. Cyclicality (defensive businesses command higher multiples).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Please answer the following: 1. How much of a premium is typically paid when acquiring a public company? 2. How does tax reform affect valuation and M&A trends? 3. What is your outlook on the M&A market for the upcoming year?",a:"Part 1: Acquisition premiums typically range from 20-40% over unaffected stock price. Part 2: Lower corporate tax rates increase after-tax cash flows, raising DCF valuations and making acquisitions more attractive. Changes to interest deductibility affect LBO financing. Repatriation rules influence cross-border M&A. Part 3: Structure answer around interest rate environment, financing availability, strategic vs financial buyer activity, regulatory climate, sector-specific trends, and geopolitical factors.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What could a CEO do with an influx of cash to create value? List in order of least to most discretionary.",a:"From least to most discretionary: Maintain required cash for operations. Pay down existing debt. Invest in core business (capex, R&D). Make acquisitions. Pay dividends or repurchase shares.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Is EBITDA always the best metric to use for multiples? What are other options?",a:"EBITDA is popular because it's a proxy for operating cash flow, but it can ignore capex, working capital needs, and interest. Alternatives include EBIT (accounts for depreciation), EBITDA-Capex (factors in maintenance spending). For banks, you might use P/E or P/B.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When using Free Cash Flow multiples, do you pair FCF with Enterprise Value or Equity Value?",a:"If it is Unlevered FCF, pair it with Enterprise Value. If it is Levered FCF, pair it with Equity Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company provides: LFCF Yield: 10%, EBITDA: $100, CapEx: $5, Interest Expense: $25, Decrease in Working Capital: $10, Tax Expense: $5. What is the company's market capitalization?",a:"$750. LFCF = EBITDA - Cash Interest - Cash Taxes - CapEx - Change in NWC = $100 - $25 - $5 - $5 - (-$10) = $75. Market Cap = LFCF / LFCF Yield = $75 / 10% = $750.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Back-to-back questions on Beta: 1. What does beta measure and how is it calculated? 2. What does a beta of -1 or 2 indicate? 3. What does a beta of 0 signify?",a:"Beta measures an asset's systematic risk relative to the market. Beta = Covariance(stock, market) / Variance(market). Beta = -1 moves opposite the market one-for-one. Beta = 2 is twice as volatile as the market in the same direction. Beta = 0 means no correlation with market movements.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You are given three companies, each with an EBITDA of $100M, and EV/EBITDA multiples of 2.0x, 3.0x, and 4.0x. Plot the Enterprise Value and explain the shape.",a:"Company 1: EV = $100M x 2.0x = $200M. Company 2: EV = $100M x 3.0x = $300M. Company 3: EV = $100M x 4.0x = $400M. The graph shows a linear relationship between EV/EBITDA multiples and Enterprise Value. Each 1.0x increase in multiple adds $100M. Higher multiples reflect better growth prospects, margins, or lower risk.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company is growing at 10% into perpetuity and has a 4% dividend yield. What should you buy it at?",a:"Use Gordon Growth: required return = yield + growth = 14%. Pay 1 / (14% - 10%) = 25x the current dividend to achieve that return.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk me through a DCF, then walk me through an LBO. Follow-ups: If we change the discount rate? If we increase taxes? If we do a dividend recap? Compare high yield debt vs bank debt.",a:"DCF: Project unlevered FCF for 5-10 years, calculate terminal value, discount both at WACC, sum to enterprise value. LBO: Determine purchase price and sources/uses, project operations and debt schedule, apply exit multiple to EBITDA, subtract remaining net debt for exit equity, compute IRR and MOIC. Follow-ups: 1) Higher discount rate lowers DCF value; in LBO lowers the price to hit target IRR. 2) Higher taxes reduce FCF, decreasing DCF value and slowing debt pay-down, hurting LBO returns. 3) Dividend recap raises new debt to pay a dividend, increasing leverage and boosting equity IRR. 4) High-yield: unsecured, higher coupons, bullet maturity, loose covenants. Bank debt: secured, lower rates, amortizing, maintenance covenants.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are Net Operating Losses (NOLs)? Assume you are valuing a shell company whose only asset is $1 million in NOLs, and assume a 25% tax rate. How much would you pay?",a:"NOLs are accumulated tax losses carried forward to offset future taxable income. Maximum value = $1M NOL x Tax Rate. At 25% tax rate, saves $250k. However, practical value is lower due to Section 382 limitations, time value of money, uncertainty about generating sufficient taxable income, and expiration risk. Realistic valuation: 15-25% of face value, or $150k-$250k.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What factors might affect a company's valuation given the current market environment?",a:"Interest Rates (higher rates compress multiples). Inflation (erodes purchasing power and margins). Economic Growth (slower growth reduces revenue expectations). Market Sentiment (risk-on vs risk-off). Sector Trends (AI, energy transition drive premium multiples in certain sectors). Geopolitical Risk. Credit Markets (tighter credit increases cost of capital). M&A Activity (robust deal flow drives multiples higher).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you approach the valuation of a leveraged loan?",a:"Key approaches: 1) DCF. Discount contractual loan payments at risk-adjusted rate. 2) Market Comparables. Reference trading prices of similar loans in secondary market. 3) Credit Analysis. Assess borrower's creditworthiness, covenant package, collateral, and recovery prospects. 4) Yield Analysis. Compare yield-to-maturity to market benchmarks. Consider seniority, security, covenants, and company performance.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two companies, same sizes, industry, growth, but one is American and publicly listed, and the other is private in Colombia. Which has a higher valuation?",a:"The publicly listed U.S. company often trades at a higher multiple due to greater liquidity, regulatory transparency, and perceived lower risk. The private Colombian company might be discounted for less liquidity, potential political/currency risk, and less disclosure.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Would you rather invest in a company with 30% margins and 10% market share or a company with 10% margins and 30% market share? What if the industry is nascent?",a:"Typically, higher margins are preferable as they indicate better profitability. However, higher market share can provide economies of scale and stronger competitive positioning. If the industry is nascent and growing, prioritizing market share might be advantageous to establish a dominant position early on, even if current margins are lower.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Would you pay a higher multiple for a business that owns its machines (depreciating them) or one that leases them?",a:"You would pay a higher multiple for the leasing business because lease payments get deducted from EBITDA, resulting in lower EBITDA and a higher multiple. Leased: $10M gross profit, $5m lease expense, $5m EBITDA. Owned: $10M gross profit, $5m D&A, $10m EBITDA. Same $50M price = 10x for lease vs 5x for own. Analysts often use EBITDAR to neutralize this difference.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What do bankers use valuations for in real life?",a:"They're used in pitch books and client presentations to guide expected valuation ranges. They also appear in deal documents (like Fairness Opinions) and feed into merger and LBO models.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company A has $30M in EBITDA with a multiple of 10x. It has $250M in senior debt and $100M in subordinated debt. What are these trading at in dollar terms?",a:"EV = 300M. Senior is fully covered at par (250M). Only 50M remains for the subordinated piece, so it's at 50% of par (50M).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the relationship amongst P/E, EPS, Price/Share, Market Cap, Net Income, and Share Count.",a:"EPS = Net Income / Shares Outstanding. Price per Share x Shares Outstanding = Market Cap (Equity Value). P/E = Price per Share / EPS = Market Cap / Net Income.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company A has a 40% EBITDA margin, trading at 8x EBITDA. Company B has a 10% margin, trading at 16x. Why is comparing them tricky?",a:"Huge margin differences can distort multiples. The lower-margin business may show a higher multiple, but it doesn't necessarily mean it's overvalued.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are some different valuation multiples that can be used to value a company? Which for high-growth tech? Which for mature industrial?",a:"Common multiples: EV/Revenue, EV/EBITDA, EV/EBIT, P/E, P/B, P/S, EV/Subscribers, EV/Users. High-Growth Tech: EV/Revenue (often pre-profitable), EV/Gross Profit, EV/Users or EV/ARR for SaaS. Mature Industrial: EV/EBITDA (standard for cash flow-generating businesses), P/E (reflects earnings stability), EV/EBIT (for capital-intensive with significant D&A).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If one company trades at a P/E of 15x and another at 10x, which would you recommend an investor buy?",a:"P/E ratio alone is insufficient. Consider: Growth Rates (higher growth justifies higher P/E). Risk Profile. Profitability Quality (sustainable vs one-time). Industry Dynamics. Capital Structure. Market Position. The 10x could be a value opportunity or reflect poor prospects. The 15x could be fairly valued for growth or overvalued.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is the tax rate an important consideration in the context of valuation?",a:"Tax rate directly impacts: DCF (affects after-tax cash flows and WACC through after-tax cost of debt). Net Income (higher tax rates reduce NI, lowering equity value in P/E-based valuations). After-Tax Cost of Debt (debt provides tax shield; lower tax rates reduce this benefit). Comparability (companies in different jurisdictions require adjustments). M&A (tax structure of deal significantly impacts value to buyer and seller).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Given: P/E=20x, EV/EBITDA=10x, Int Exp=$20M, Int Rate=5%, Dep=$20M, Market Cap=$200M. What is the effective tax rate?",a:"50%. NI = Market Cap / P/E = $200m / 20x = $10M. Debt = Int Exp / Int Rate = $20m / 5% = $400M. EV = Market Cap + Debt = $600M. EBITDA = EV / (EV/EBITDA) = $60M. EBT = EBITDA - D&A - Int Exp = $60m - $20m - $20m = $20M. Tax = EBT - NI = $20m - $10m = $10M. Tax Rate = $10m / $20m = 50%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You are advising a publicly traded client with broadcasting (peers at 7x EBITDA) and digital media (peers at 14x EBITDA). Client trades at 8x consolidated. No synergies. What strategic recommendation would you make?",a:"Spin off or sell the digital media business. The conglomerate trades at 8x, below the 14x for pure-play digital media. Market is applying a conglomerate discount. Separating allows digital media to trade at its natural 14x. Sum-of-the-parts exceeds current consolidated 8x. Sell digital media to capture the 14x multiple arbitrage.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"ParentCo owns 100% of CoffeeCo (private, $100m EBITDA) and 80% of DonutCo (public, $200m EBITDA, trades at 5x EBITDA). ParentCo: $10/share, 100m shares, $500m debt, $200m cash. What is the implied multiple for CoffeeCo?",a:"5x. ParentCo Equity Value = $10 x 100m = $1,000m. DonutCo TEV = $200m x 5x = $1,000m. NCI = 20% x $1,000m = $200m. ParentCo TEV = EqV ($1,000m) + Debt ($500m) + NCI ($200m) - Cash ($200m) = $1,500m. Implied CoffeeCo TEV = $1,500m - $1,000m = $500m. Implied Multiple = $500m / $100m = 5x.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Describe a lesser-known valuation methodology. Explain how it works and when you would use it.",a:"Sum of the Parts (SOTP) analysis for conglomerates or multi-segment companies. Value each division separately using a suitable methodology (Comps, DCF, etc.) and then add them, adjusting for net debt/corporate overhead. Used when segments have very different business models, growth rates, or risk profiles.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you have two companies, same EBIT and same Revenue, and one has 90% Debt while the other has 10% Debt, which company has a higher P/E ratio?",a:"The company with 90% debt has higher interest expenses, which reduces net income. With lower net income, for a given share price, the P/E ratio would be higher. P/E = Share Price / (Net Income per share). A smaller denominator makes the ratio higher.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Let's say you have a money tree that produces $100 in perpetuity. How would you value it?",a:"Value = Cash Flow / Discount Rate. If the discount rate is 5%, the value is $100 / 0.05 = $2,000.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the four main valuation methodologies? Follow-up 1: Key components for each? Follow-up 2: Rank them from highest to lowest valuation.",a:"Four Main: 1) Comparable Company Analysis (Comps). 2) Precedent Transaction Analysis. 3) Discounted Cash Flow (DCF). 4) Leveraged Buyout (LBO). Key Components: Comps use trading multiples from similar public companies. Precedents use acquisition multiples from comparable M&A. DCF projects unlevered FCF, discounts at WACC, adds Terminal Value. LBO calculates maximum price a PE firm can pay to achieve target IRR. Ranking highest to lowest: Precedents > DCF > Comps > LBO.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When might you not use a DCF in valuation?",a:"If a company's cash flows are highly unpredictable or if debt and working capital are integral to operations, as in banks. Early-stage firms and biotech with uncertain future cash flows might also make a DCF less reliable.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How might you value a company with no revenue or profit, like a pre-revenue startup?",a:"You would rely on 'creative' multiples such as EV/Users or EV/Traffic. A DCF might be too speculative if you cannot reliably forecast future cash flows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company's WACC is 12%, and its after-tax cost of debt is 7%. Its capital structure is 50% debt and 50% equity. What is the company's cost of equity?",a:"17%. WACC = (Weight of Debt x Cost of Debt) + (Weight of Equity x Cost of Equity). 12% = (50% x 7%) + (50% x Cost of Equity). 12% = 3.5% + (50% x Cost of Equity). Cost of Equity = 17%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has a $1 billion top line and a 20% EBITDA margin. Comparable companies are valued at 6x EV/EBITDA. What is the Enterprise Value?",a:"EBITDA = $1 billion x 20% = $200 million. EV = 6 x $200 million = $1.2 billion.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can Equity Value ever be negative?",a:"Market Cap (current Equity Value) cannot be negative. However, Shareholders' Equity on the balance sheet can be negative.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"On a conceptual level, how does a firm create economic value?",a:"If a firm invests capital at a return that exceeds its cost of capital, it's creating economic value. ROIC > WACC means every dollar invested returns more than it costs, leading to value creation for shareholders.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"With a 2x sales multiple and a 5x EBITDA multiple, what is the EBITDA margin?",a:"EV/Sales = 2x and EV/EBITDA = 5x. EBITDA Margin = EBITDA / Sales = (EV / Sales) / (EV / EBITDA) = 2 / 5 = 40%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two identical companies (revenue, growth, risk etc.), one public, one private. Which is valued higher?",a:"The public company is typically valued higher due to: Liquidity Premium (public shares are easily traded), Transparency (greater disclosure), Access to Capital (easier access to public markets). Private companies often have a valuation discount for lack of marketability (DLOM).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you value a REIT, and why is it different from a normal company?",a:"REITs often use Price/FFO or Price/AFFO because depreciation is high yet not truly economic. Cap rates and NAV are also key. You may do property-by-property valuation rather than a corporate-level DCF.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Strengths and weaknesses of each valuation methodology (DCF, Comps, Precedents)?",a:"DCF: Theoretically most sound, but heavily dependent on assumptions (WACC, terminal growth rate). Comps: Market-based and easy to calculate, but can be skewed if comps aren't truly comparable or market is over/undervalued. Precedent Transactions: Captures real premiums paid, but every deal is unique in timing, synergy assumptions, and market conditions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you 'calendarize' a public company's financials if their fiscal year doesn't match the calendar year?",a:"Use the trailing 12 months approach: TTM = Most recent FY + New partial period - Old partial period. For forward periods, adjust projections to align with calendar months, often using quarterly filings.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has a $200M market cap and trades at 10x P/E. What is its net income?",a:"$20 mm ($200 mm / 10 = $20 mm).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the four most commonly used valuation methods? Rank from highest to lowest.",a:"Typical ranking: Precedent Transactions (includes control premiums and expected synergies), Discounted Cash Flow (intrinsic value based on future free cash flow), Public Trading Comparables (current market sentiment), Leveraged Buy-Out (what a financial sponsor can pay while hitting IRR hurdle). Order can shift by cycle or sector.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why would an acquiror pay 30x revenue for a target with no profit? How do you value such a company?",a:"Possibly for strategic value, rapid user growth, or a unique product that can become profitable at scale. Use revenue multiples, user metrics, or a long-term DCF projection modeling eventual profitability. The high multiple reflects growth expectations and potential network effects.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A is financed with debt, while identical Company B has no debt. 1) How would their P/E multiples differ? 2) If both companies' revenues increase by 30%? 3) Which has a higher cost of capital?",a:"Part 1: Company B (unlevered) has higher P/E. Leverage adds risk, causing investors to demand higher return on equity, resulting in lower P/E. Part 2: Company A's P/E could compress or expand. NI grows faster for levered companies (fixed interest), but strong growth also de-risks. Part 3: Company B (unlevered) has higher cost of capital since its capital structure is 100% equity, which is more expensive than debt.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does beta typically vary across different industries? Which would have higher beta: American Airlines or Amazon?",a:"High Beta (>1.0): Technology, retail, airlines (cyclical, volatile). Low Beta (<1.0): Utilities, consumer staples, healthcare (stable, defensive). American Airlines would have higher beta due to cyclicality, fuel cost sensitivity, economic sensitivity, and high operational leverage. Amazon is more diversified (e-commerce, AWS, advertising) with less cyclical, more stable cash flows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"P/E is 40x, EV/Revenue is 10x, net income is $15mm, $400mm in debt, no cash. Depreciation is $10mm, EBITDA margin is 50%, and tax rate is 25%. What is the interest rate?",a:"5%. Equity value = 40 x 15 = $600mm; EV = 600 + 400 = $1,000mm. Revenue = 1,000 / 10 = $100mm; EBITDA = 50% x 100 = $50mm. EBIT = 50 - 10 = $40mm; EBT = 15 / 0.75 = $20mm. Interest expense = 40 - 20 = $20mm. Interest rate = 20 / 400 = 5%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When you look at a company's stock price, how do you decide if it's undervalued or overvalued?",a:"Steps: 1) Intrinsic Valuation via DCF. 2) Relative Valuation comparing multiples to comps and historical ranges. 3) Growth Analysis (PEG ratio). 4) Margin Analysis. 5) Qualitative Factors (competitive position, management). 6) Market Sentiment. If DCF and comps both suggest stock trades significantly below fair value, and fundamentals support it, likely undervalued.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Debt/EBITDA of 5x and Interest Coverage of 4x. What is the interest rate?",a:"5%. Interest expense = EBITDA / 4. Debt = 5 x EBITDA. Interest rate = (EBITDA / 4) / (5 x EBITDA) = 1 / 20 = 5%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does having a higher percentage of the capital structure in debt change the WACC?",a:"It lowers WACC up to an optimal leverage point, then raises it. Debt is cheaper than equity (tax shield + seniority), so replacing equity with debt pushes WACC down. Beyond a certain leverage, rising default risk drives up cost of both debt and equity, causing the familiar U-shape.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Answer: 1. What is your favorite and least favorite valuation method? 2. What happens to WACC if cost of debt increases? Cost of equity? 3. Why would one company have a higher multiple? 4. Why might a financial sponsor pay more than a strategic acquirer?",a:"Part 1: Sample - Favorite DCF (fundamental, captures company-specific growth and risk), Least Favorite Precedent Transactions (outdated, influenced by timing). Part 2: Higher cost of debt or equity both increase WACC. Part 3: Growth prospects, profitability, competitive position, management, risk profile. Part 4: Unusual but possible reasons: superior operational capabilities, cheaper capital access, competitive auction, or market timing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You are reviewing comparable companies analysis with five companies. Four trade in an 8-10x EV/EBITDA range, but one trades at 20x. What are possible reasons and what steps would you take?",a:"Possible reasons: Higher growth, better margins/ROIC, M&A speculation, unique technology/IP, temporarily depressed EBITDA, different business model, market inefficiency. Investigation steps: Review financial metrics, analyze EBITDA quality for one-time items, compare business models, review recent news for M&A activity, assess if it truly belongs in the comp set, consider excluding or creating separate category.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you select Comparable Companies or Precedent Transactions?",a:"Most commonly screen by: Industry, Financial metrics (Revenue, EBITDA), Geography. For transactions, also timeframe. Industry is often the key factor, then refine from there.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What impact do Stock Options have on the overall valuation of a company?",a:"Stock Options can dilute share count upon exercise, potentially lowering EPS. When modeling, they should be included in the diluted share count to provide a more accurate Equity Value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When selecting precedent transactions, how far back would you typically look? When might you look further?",a:"Typical lookback: 2-3 years. Situations justifying longer: Limited deal activity (niche industries). Market dislocation (recent downturn makes older deals more representative). Cyclical industries (include full cycle). Mega-deals or transformational transactions. Stable industry dynamics. Always adjust for changes in market conditions, interest rates, and industry dynamics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does Capital Expenditure (CapEx) affect EV/EBIT, EV/EBITDA, and P/E?",a:"EV/EBITDA: No direct impact as EBITDA excludes D&A. EV/EBIT: Higher CapEx leads to higher D&A, which lowers EBIT, increasing the EV/EBIT multiple. P/E: Higher CapEx leads to higher D&A, which lowers pre-tax income and NI, increasing P/E (assuming EV/equity held constant). CapEx drives depreciation which impacts EBIT and NI.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You have a coverage ratio of 4 and a debt ratio of 2 and need the interest rate. How do you compute it?",a:"Let EBIT = 100. Interest = EBIT / Coverage = 100 / 4 = 25. Debt = Ratio x EBIT = 2 x 100 = 200. Cost of debt = Interest / Debt = 25 / 200 = 12.5%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why would you use EBITDA instead of FCF or EBIT?",a:"EBITDA normalizes for CapEx and D&A among similar companies, removing financing effects. EBIT might be better for industries where D&A is material, and FCF includes differences in capital structure and CapEx that can muddy comparisons.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You have missing info (like EBITDA) for several Precedent Transactions. How do you find it?",a:"Try press releases, news articles, or deal reports that mention the seller's numbers. Look at buyer's equity research or databases like Capital IQ for estimates.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you usually present different valuation methods to a client or investor?",a:"Typically with a 'football field' chart that shows a range of values derived from each method. This visually communicates how various methodologies imply different valuations.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A firm has Unlevered Beta = 1, Equity Risk Premium = 5%, Risk-free Rate = 5%, Tax = 50%, D/E = 1. Find the cost of equity.",a:"12.5%. Levered Beta = 1 x [1 + (1 - 50%) x 1] = 1.5. Cost of Equity = 5% + (1.5 x 5%) = 12.5%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Is a company with a 50x P/E overvalued or undervalued? Why?",a:"You can't know from P/E alone. Must compare with industry, growth expectations, risk. 50x might be too high if growth doesn't warrant it, or fair if it's a fast-growing firm.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A pharmaceutical company and an auto manufacturer have identical financials. Which has the larger equity value?",a:"The pharma company likely has the higher equity value. Pharma typically trades at higher multiples due to growth potential, IP, and less cyclicality.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You are given a table of a company's valuation multiples (EV/EBITDA, EV/EBIT, and P/E) from 2019 to 2020. What would you look for to determine if one might not make sense?",a:"Check for internal consistency: EV/EBITDA should be lower than EV/EBIT (since EBITDA > EBIT). If D&A is significant, expect a large gap between EV/EBIT and EV/EBITDA. Compare P/E movement to EV/EBITDA. Divergence may indicate changing leverage or tax rates. Look for anomalies in capital structure affecting enterprise vs equity multiples.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Would you pay more for a company with Operating Assets or Operating Leases, assuming the same Enterprise Value?",a:"You would pay more for the one with operating leases because those lease expenses lower EBITDA, inflating the multiple.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What happens to the cost of debt as a company's rating improves?",a:"As credit ratings improve, lenders perceive lower default risk, which generally lowers the interest rate demanded. Cost of debt decreases, improving WACC.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What valuation method would you use for a coal mine that will cease operations in ten years?",a:"Build a finite-life DCF model that forecasts yearly cash flows until shutdown and adds a salvage value, with no perpetuity. A perpetual multiple or Gordon Growth approach would overstate value because production stops after year 10.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why is EBITDA commonly used in finance?",a:"It approximates operating cash flow, removes capital structure effects (interest, taxes), it's widely recognized for comparable valuations using EV/EBITDA, and strips out some non-cash or one-time items.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might you prefer using a TTM multiple over a forward multiple in comparable companies analysis?",a:"TTM multiples are based on actual past performance, providing a concrete basis. Forward multiples rely on forecasts, which can be uncertain and vary based on analyst assumptions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some downsides of using public comps for valuation?",a:"No two companies are perfectly comparable, so results can be skewed. The stock market can fluctuate or be driven by sentiment. Thinly traded stocks may not reflect true investor views.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would a greater proportion of debt affect WACC?",a:"Initially lowers WACC thanks to cheaper after-tax debt, but beyond an optimal leverage point distress risk pushes WACC back up.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the differences between the EV/EBITDA, EV/EBIT, and P/E valuation multiples?",a:"EV/EBITDA: Enterprise value to EBITDA, capital structure-neutral, excludes D&A and interest. EV/EBIT: Enterprise value to EBIT, includes D&A impact, still capital structure-neutral. P/E: Price to Net Income, equity-based, reflects capital structure and taxes. EV/EBITDA most commonly used for comparing companies with different leverage and capex intensity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Is Amazon more valuable as a consolidated company, or would shareholder value be maximized by selling off some of its business segments?",a:"Amazon is likely more valuable consolidated due to synergies and strategic integration. AWS subsidizes retail investments, Prime ecosystem creates powerful flywheel effects, shared infrastructure/logistics. Arguments for breaking up: AWS might command higher multiples standalone, eliminates conglomerate discount, reduces regulatory scrutiny. On balance, synergies likely exceed conglomerate discount.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you value Tesla, and how would you select an appropriate set of comparable companies?",a:"Valuation Approaches: DCF (project vehicle deliveries, ASPs, margins, energy business), Comparable Companies (mix of auto OEMs and tech companies), Sum-of-the-Parts (automotive, energy, solar, autonomous driving separately). Comparable Selection: Traditional auto companies trade at lower multiples, tech companies at higher, consider EV-only manufacturers (Rivian, Lucid). Best Method: DCF is most appropriate given Tesla's unique profile, with sensitivity analysis on key assumptions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you do an M&A premiums analysis?",a:"Select public deals, focusing on the share price premium paid over the seller's pre-announcement price. Calculate 1-day, 20-day premiums for each transaction. Find medians and apply them to your company's share price to gauge a possible takeover premium.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You are advising a U.S. firm considering acquisition of a Chinese oil field services firm. How would you value the target?",a:"Use standard methods with cross-border adjustments: DCF (forecast in local currency, apply country risk premium, convert to USD), Comparable Companies (use global and regional peers, adjust for market differences), Precedent Transactions (review similar cross-border deals). Key considerations: Regulatory approval (CFIUS, Chinese authorities), currency risk and hedging, political and operational risks, synergies, strategic fit, integration challenges and cultural differences.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Does an LBO or a DCF typically produce a higher valuation?",a:"A DCF often results in a higher valuation because it captures long-term growth potential by discounting all future free cash flows plus terminal value. An LBO focuses on returns required by financial sponsors given leverage and exit multiples, which tends to set a 'floor' valuation. However, there's no absolute rule. Either model can produce higher depending on assumptions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How could you tell from a company's trading multiple whether it is attractive to pitch to a potential acquirer?",a:"A lower multiple vs peers might suggest undervaluation, especially if fundamentals are comparable. You'd also consider synergy potential, strategic fit, and discount to precedent deals.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If two companies have the same EBITDA, why might they have different P/E multiples?",a:"P/E multiples differ based on what's below EBITDA: Depreciation & Amortization (higher D&A reduces EBIT and NI). Interest Expense (more leverage reduces NI). Tax Rate (higher effective rates reduce NI). Non-Operating Items. Share Count. Growth Expectations.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When is it more appropriate to use an EV/EBITDA multiple versus an EV/EBIT multiple?",a:"Use EV/EBITDA when comparing companies with different D&A policies (useful when D&A is accounting-driven). Use EV/EBIT when analyzing capital-intensive industries (Manufacturing, Airlines) where D&A represents a real capital cost, or when companies have similar capital structures.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When pulling equity research, how do you decide whose estimates to use?",a:"You might use a consensus from multiple analysts or pick the most detailed 'middle-of-the-road' forecast. Avoid using only your bank's research to limit bias.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If net interest coverage is 5x and gross debt ratio is 5x, what is the interest rate on the debt?",a:"Approximately 4%. Interest = EBITDA/5. Debt = 5 x EBITDA. Interest rate = (EBITDA/5)/(5 x EBITDA) = 1/25 = 4%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Once you select your comps and transactions, how do you use them to value a company?",a:"Take the median multiples from each set and multiply by the relevant metric for the target. For instance, if the median EV/EBITDA is 7x and your firm's EBITDA is 100 million, its implied EV is 700 million.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Think about a company you are familiar with. How would you approach valuing that company?",a:"Comprehensive approach: 1) Understand the business model and growth drivers. 2) Comparable Company Analysis with appropriate multiples. 3) Precedent Transactions. 4) DCF Analysis. 5) Triangulate results from multiple methodologies to arrive at a valuation range.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Both M&A premiums analysis and Precedent Transactions look at past deals. How do they differ?",a:"M&A premiums analysis focuses on how much above the seller's stock price was paid. Precedent transactions look more at valuation multiples like EV/EBITDA rather than per-share premiums.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What would the WACC be for a company with a beta of 0 and no debt? Follow-up: Given this company is very risky but has a low WACC, how would you proceed with a DCF?",a:"WACC would equal the risk-free rate. Beta of 0 indicates no correlation with market returns, not low risk. Approaches: Add a company-specific risk premium, adjust cash flow projections to reflect higher uncertainty, use comparable company analysis to cross-check rather than relying solely on DCF.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you were deciding on a new investment, what three financial figures would you look at first?",a:"Revenue history and forecast, EBITDA (or net income) trends, and CapEx or overall FCF requirements. These help gauge size, profitability, and how much cash is needed to maintain or grow the business.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you were opening a sandwich shop, how should you value it? What discount rate? What makes a good sandwich shop competitive?",a:"Valuation: Comparable Company Analysis, DCF (project based on foot traffic, average ticket, margins), Asset-Based, Precedent transactions in quick-service restaurant space. Discount Rate: High (15-25%) reflecting small business risk, limited diversification, operational risk, and lack of liquidity. Competitive Advantages: Prime location, differentiated menu, strong brand and loyalty, operational efficiency, quality ingredients.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you value a celebrity?",a:"DCF: Project future cash flows from endorsements, appearances, media deals, royalties. Discount at rate reflecting career longevity risks. Comparable Approach: Analyze compensation for similar celebrities with similar audience reach. Precedent Transactions: Review deals for similar celebrity partnerships. Key considerations: Brand strength, career stage, diversification of income streams, reputational risk.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company has $120M in perpetual unlevered free cash flow; no debt initially. RFR = 4%, Beta = 1, ERP = 6%. Part 1: What is EV? Part 2: Company raises $800M debt, tax rate 25%, interest 10%. What is EV now? Part 3: CoD is 5% and target mix is 60% equity / 40% debt. What is WACC?",a:"Part 1: Cost of Equity = 4% + 1 x 6% = 10%. EV = 120 / 0.10 = $1.2 billion. Part 2: Raising $800M debt and holding cash leaves EV unchanged at $1.2 billion (Debt and Cash offset). Part 3: WACC (60% equity, 40% debt): After-tax Cost of Debt = 5% x (1 - 25%) = 3.75%. WACC = 0.6 x 10% + 0.4 x 3.75% = 7.5%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How can differences in capital structure between companies affect the EV/EBITDA multiple?",a:"While EV/EBITDA is designed to be capital-structure neutral, significant differences in debt levels can indicate underlying financial stability or risk. This qualitative aspect can influence investor perceptions and, consequently, the relative multiples.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) formula? What is the relationship between IRR and WACC?",a:"CAPM: Cost of Equity = Risk-Free Rate + Beta x (Market Return - Risk-Free Rate). A project should be accepted if its IRR exceeds the company's WACC. WACC represents the minimum required return.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Aside from standard metrics like EV/EBITDA or EV/Revenue, what is another key metric to evaluate efficiency?",a:"Return on Invested Capital (ROIC) = NOPAT / Invested Capital, where Invested Capital = Total Debt + Total Equity - Cash. Measures how efficiently a company generates returns from its capital investments. ROIC > WACC creates value; ROIC < WACC destroys value. Other metrics: Cash Conversion Cycle, Asset Turnover.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might investors prefer EV/EBIT over EV/EBITDA for certain investments?",a:"Investors may dislike EBITDA because it excludes capital expenditures, which can be significant. EBIT includes D&A, providing a more realistic measure of operating expenses and a practical proxy for CapEx. Investors care about true cash generated after reinvestment.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two tech companies with different growth rates. What would be a good ratio to compare them?",a:"EV/Revenue or EV/Growth (like EV/EBITDA-growth), especially if they aren't profitable. PEG ratios (P/E to Growth). In high-growth SaaS, EV/ARR (Annual Recurring Revenue) can be more relevant.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain a future share price analysis.",a:"Project the company's share price in 1 or 2 years using a median P/E from comps. Multiply median P/E by future EPS to get future share price, then discount back to Present Value at the Cost of Equity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might two companies with the same revenue trade at different valuation multiples?",a:"Profitability (one has higher EBITDA or net margins). Growth Rate. Business Model (recurring revenue valued higher). Customer Concentration. Competitive Position. Capital Intensity. Leverage. Industry Dynamics.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you were buying a vending machine company, would you pay more for one that owns or leases machines?",a:"Leased scenario might lead to higher EV/EBITDA because lease costs hit EBITDA, making the multiple appear higher. Owned machines use depreciation (below EBITDA), so EBITDA is higher and the multiple appears lower, potentially looking cheaper.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you screen for comparable companies (Comps)?",a:"Use objective filters first then qualitative judgment: Industry/business model, Geography, Size (revenue, EBITDA, market cap), Growth and margin profile, Capital structure/leverage. Pull from databases (CapIQ, FactSet), apply filters, then read filings to confirm comparability.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If debt is cheaper than equity, why would a company ever raise capital with equity?",a:"Debt capacity constraints, financial flexibility (no mandatory payments), covenant restrictions, credit rating concerns, market timing (high stock prices make equity attractive), growth companies (unstable cash flows make debt risky). Beyond a certain point, additional debt becomes prohibitively expensive.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the problem with the ratio EV/Net Income? What would be a better ratio?",a:"EV/Net Income is problematic because net income is affected by non-cash items, taxes, and financing decisions, making it less comparable. A better ratio is EV/EBITDA, which focuses on operational performance and is less influenced by capital structure and accounting.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do bankers use EBITDA to compare businesses? What are some drawbacks?",a:"Bankers use EBITDA because it provides a measure of operational performance excluding financing and accounting decisions. Drawbacks: ignoring capital expenditures, working capital changes, not accounting for debt, leading to an incomplete view of financial health.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Consider two identical companies, except A has a mix of debt and equity, B is 100% equity. 1) Which has higher P/E? 2) If both outperform, which provides greater return to equity? 3) Which has higher WACC?",a:"Part 1: Company B (100% equity) has higher P/E. Leverage increases financial risk, compressing P/E. Part 2: Company A provides greater returns because leverage magnifies equity returns. Part 3: Company B has higher WACC since debt is cheaper and tax-deductible.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might we discount public comps for a private target but not discount Precedent Transactions?",a:"In M&A deals, the buyer acquires the entire company, so shares become illiquid regardless. Public comps assume liquid public shares. For a private firm, you'd discount because its shares are not publicly traded.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the four main valuation methodologies?",a:"Comparable Companies, Precedent Transactions, Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) Analysis, and Leveraged Buyout (LBO) analysis.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Equity risk premium is 5%, risk-free rate is 5%, unlevered beta is 1, D/E ratio is 1x, and tax rate is 50%. Calculate the cost of equity.",a:"Levered Beta = 1 x [1 + (1 - 50%) x 1] = 1.5. Cost of Equity = 5% + 1.5 x 5% = 12.5%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Part 1: Given a bond's price, par value, coupon rate, and maturity, how do you calculate YTM? Part 2: How would YTM be impacted if coupon payments changed from annual to semi-annual?",a:"Part 1: YTM is the IRR that equates PV of all future cash flows to current bond price. Approximation: YTM = [C + (F - P) / n] / [(F + P) / 2]. Part 2: Semi-annual coupons typically result in slightly higher effective YTM due to more frequent compounding. The stated YTM with semi-annual payments must be doubled for annual rate.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has an equity value of 200M and debt of 300M. It has a purchase price multiple of 10. What is EBITDA?",a:"EBITDA is $50M. EV = 200 equity + 300 debt = 500. 500 / 10 = 50.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is debt cheaper than equity? What is the correlation with interest rates?",a:"Debt sits higher in the capital stack and receives fixed coupons, so investors demand lower returns than residual equity holders. Interest rates set the risk-free baseline; as central-bank rates rise, absolute cost of debt climbs and the after-tax advantage versus equity narrows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Under what circumstances might a valuation from Precedent Transactions be lower than from Comparable Companies?",a:"Distressed sales during downturns. Stale precedents when valuations were depressed. Current market exuberance. Strategic vs financial buyers. Market timing (precedents from bear market, comps from bull market). Smaller/lower quality targets. Generally uncommon since precedents include control premium.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can you explain what a 'football field' valuation chart is and what it shows?",a:"A football field chart is a visual summary of valuation ranges from different methodologies, displayed as horizontal bars. Each bar represents a range from one method, X-axis shows enterprise value or equity value per share, Y-axis lists methodologies. Allows quick comparison, helps identify consensus range where methods overlap, and is commonly used in pitch books and fairness opinions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me through a Sum-of-the-Parts valuation.",a:"Value each division individually, often using different sets of comps or a mini-DCF per segment. Then add them up for a total combined valuation.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Rank in terms of EV impact: $10 decrease in expenses, $10 decrease in CapEx, or $10 increase in revenue.",a:"Most to least accretive: 1) $10 CapEx decrease (lifts FCF dollar-for-dollar). 2) $10 expense decrease (boosts EBIT, but only by 10 x (1-tax)). 3) $10 revenue increase (flows through at the after-tax margin, so impact is smallest).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the theoretical upper limit of a company's WACC?",a:"The theoretical upper limit is the company's cost of equity (unlevered). This occurs when the company has zero debt (100% equity financing). As debt increases, WACC initially decreases due to tax shield benefits, but excessive leverage increases financial risk, raising both cost of debt and equity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Are there scenarios where you might see Equity Value / Revenue used?",a:"It's unusual, but might apply to large banks or financial institutions with heavy debt usage or negative enterprise value. Also possibly if comparing both financial and non-financial companies together.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might two direct competitors with the same net income trade at different valuation multiples?",a:"Growth expectations, quality of earnings, capital structure, market position, management quality, investor sentiment and liquidity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"P/E of Nvidia vs. GM. Which is higher?",a:"Nvidia. Its rapid growth and capital-light model command a materially higher earnings multiple than GM's cyclical, asset-heavy auto business.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"You have a standard x vs y plot of WACC vs Leverage. What is the shape?",a:"A U-shaped curve. WACC falls at first as tax-advantaged debt replaces costlier equity, bottoms out at the optimal capital structure, then climbs as financial distress risk overwhelms the tax benefit.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you approach valuing an oil and gas company?",a:"Use multiples like P/MCFE or P/NAV and rely on Reserve Reports for production forecasts. Often use a Net Asset Value model rather than a traditional DCF, given the importance of commodity prices and reserve depletion.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why would two companies with identical financial statements trade at different P/E ratios?",a:"Growth expectations, risk profile, management quality, competitive position, capital structure, market sentiment, liquidity, and accounting quality differences.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are levered and unlevered beta? Why do you adjust beta?",a:"Unlevered beta isolates business risk; levered beta adds financial risk from debt. Un-lever peers to strip out capital-structure effects, average them, then re-lever at target debt-to-equity to derive beta consistent with the firm's planned leverage in CAPM cost-of-equity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does the EV/EBITDA multiple help in valuing companies?",a:"EV/EBITDA provides a capital-structure neutral metric comparing enterprise value to EBITDA. Useful for comparing companies within the same industry regardless of debt levels.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does multiple expansion influence Precedent Transactions valuations?",a:"If the broader market has experienced multiple expansion since those deals occurred, the precedent multiples might understate current value. If multiples contracted, historical precedents might imply unrealistically high valuation. Analysts must adjust for market conditions between transaction date and current date.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Pick an industry sector. How would you create a comparable company set and what key factors would you consider?",a:"Steps: 1) Industry/Sector. 2) Business Model. 3) Size (revenue, EBITDA, market cap). 4) Geography. 5) Growth Profile. 6) Profitability. 7) End Markets. Tailor criteria to the sector, for healthcare consider therapeutic areas, for retail consider brick-and-mortar vs e-commerce.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"$400mm EBITDA at 6x multiple, $600mm debt, $200mm cash. What is equity value?",a:"$2.0B. EV = 6 x 400 = 2,400. Equity = EV - Debt + Cash = 2,400 - 600 + 200 = 2,000.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two companies have different EV/EBITDA multiples but identical financials. How can that happen?",a:"Qualitative factors like brand strength, management quality, or growth expectations not reflected in current numbers. Liquidity and market sentiment. Different capital structures or projected changes in margins.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you account for a strong competitive advantage in your valuation?",a:"Use multiples at the higher end of the range. Add a premium to comps or use more optimistic projections in a DCF.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Select two similar publicly traded companies. Why does one trade at a higher multiple?",a:"Higher revenue growth rate, superior profit margins, stronger market position, better management execution, more recurring revenue, lower capital intensity and higher ROIC.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What types of companies might have a negative beta? If a company's beta is -1, is it possible to have a negative WACC?",a:"Negative beta companies: Gold mining, discount retailers, certain utilities, treasury securities. Yes, negative WACC is theoretically possible if beta is sufficiently negative. DCF implication: A negative discount rate would make valuation mathematically undefined or infinite, suggesting the model breaks down.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might a company's EV/EBITDA trade at a discount to peers while its P/E trades at a premium?",a:"This suggests favorable capital structure: Lower debt reduces EV but not equity value. Less interest expense means higher net income. Lower EV/EBITDA (due to less debt) but higher P/E (due to higher NI). Company may also have significant cash holdings.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company reports: Revenue $100, Gross Margin 60%, SG&A $20 (includes all D&A), P/E 25x, EV/EBITDA 10x, Tax Rate 20%, Cash $0, Debt $200 at 5%, Bonds $200 at 10%. What is D&A?",a:"$20. Gross Profit = $60. EBIT = $60 - $20 = $40. Interest = ($200 x 5%) + ($200 x 10%) = $30. EBT = $40 - $30 = $10. NI = $10 x (1 - 20%) = $8. Equity Value = $8 x 25x = $200. EV = $200 + $400 = $600. EBITDA = $600 / 10x = $60. D&A = EBITDA - EBIT = $60 - $40 = $20.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do higher central bank rates affect the cost of equity?",a:"They raise it. Under CAPM, Cost of Equity = Risk-free Rate + Beta x Equity-Risk-Premium. When a central bank hikes policy rates, government bond yields move up, flowing through to a higher cost of equity, raising discount rates and lowering valuations.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you value Sony after they announced their entry into the electric vehicle space?",a:"Use SOTP: 1) Value Core Businesses (Gaming, entertainment, electronics, financial services) using comps or DCF. 2) Value EV Business Separately using pure-play EV comps (Tesla, Rivian, Lucid). 3) Apply 30-50% discount for execution risk and lack of scale. 4) Sum Components. EV business may initially drag on overall valuation but offers long-term optionality.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What valuation methodologies are most appropriate for an IPO?",a:"Comparable Company Analysis (most heavily weighted since investors compare to existing public alternatives). Precedent Transaction Analysis (review recent IPOs in same sector). DCF Analysis (less emphasis due to uncertainty but used as supplementary check).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Which would have a higher cost of equity. Lyft or Meta?",a:"Lyft. It's smaller and has a higher beta, so its required return is higher than a large, diversified tech company like Meta.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company has $175 million of debt and $175 million of cash. What multiples would you prioritize and how would you rank their output?",a:"Prioritize EV-based multiples (EV/EBITDA, EV/Sales) since debt and cash offset. Rank highest to lowest: P/E > EV/EBITDA > EV/Sales. P/E is usually highest because Net Income is the smallest denominator.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you value a bank such as Goldman Sachs?",a:"Banks are valued using P/B and P/E multiples, ROE, net interest margin, and capital ratios. A Dividend Discount Model (DDM) is common, discounting future dividends by cost of equity. DCF is less common due to bank balance sheet complexity and regulatory capital requirements.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Would you apply a control premium when using Precedent Transactions to value a company?",a:"No. Precedent transactions already represent past acquisitions where buyers paid for control, so the control premium is inherently built in. You only apply a control premium to Public Comps, as those reflect minority, non-controlling stakes.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you value a private company?",a:"You can still use Comps, Precedents, and a DCF. Apply a discount to public comps to reflect illiquidity. Data like Beta or share price won't exist, so estimate from public peers.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might two companies in the same industry with very similar operations trade at different EV/EBITDA multiples?",a:"Different forward growth rates. Margin and cost-structure resilience. Capital intensity and FCF conversion. ROIC differences. Business-risk profile. Size, liquidity and trading float. Scarcity value or strategic buyer interest.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain the appropriate use cases for EV/EBIT, EV/EBITDA, and EV/EBITDAR. What are drawbacks of EBITDAR?",a:"EV/EBIT: When D&A is consistent or immaterial. EV/EBITDA: Standard for most industries, neutralizes depreciation differences. EV/EBITDAR: For companies with significant operating leases (airlines, retail). EBITDAR Limitations: Less commonly used, can overstate profitability by excluding real operating costs, rent is a genuine cash expense, modern accounting (ASC 842/IFRS 16) reduces need for EBITDAR.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Would you expect the cost of equity to be higher in a typical LBO model or a standard DCF model for the same company?",a:"Higher in the LBO because extreme leverage magnifies equity risk, so sponsors target 20-30% returns versus 8-12% required by diversified public investors.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company A and Company B have identical balance sheets. What are six reasons Company A could have a higher valuation?",a:"1) Higher Revenue Growth. 2) Better Margins (superior unit economics or pricing power). 3) Stronger Market Position (greater competitive moat or brand value). 4) Superior Management (track record of execution). 5) Lower Risk Profile (more stable cash flows). 6) Better Industry Dynamics (more attractive sector).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might you use an LBO Analysis in valuing a company that isn't being sold to PE?",a:"An LBO can establish a 'floor' valuation, reflecting what a financial buyer could pay to achieve a target IRR. Strategic buyers might pay more, but the LBO sets a lower bound.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you handle valuation for banks and financial institutions?",a:"You often use P/E or P/BV instead of EV-based multiples because debt is central to their business model. You might use a Dividend Discount Model (DDM) rather than a standard DCF.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Beyond the four main methodologies, what is a fifth methodology?",a:"Sum-of-the-Parts (SOTP) Valuation. Value each business segment separately, apply appropriate methodology to each, sum segment values, subtract Net Debt. Useful for conglomerates or companies with diverse operations where a single multiple doesn't capture full value.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In general, can you use private companies as comps or for WACC in a DCF?",a:"Not usually, because private firms lack market caps or Betas. You can use them in Precedent Transactions if data is disclosed.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Rank the 4 main methodologies from highest to lowest valuation. Is there a strict order?",a:"Typically: Precedent Transactions highest (control premiums), then Comparable Companies, then DCF (depends on assumptions), then LBO as floor. But no absolute ranking. It shifts by cycle or sector.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the difference between intrinsic value and relative value?",a:"Intrinsic value uses company-specific cash flows/risk (DCF). Relative value compares multiples to similar companies or deals (Comps, Precedents).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How far back and forward would you go for multiples in Comps or Precedents?",a:"Typically TTM and then 1-2 years forward. Going beyond 2 years forward is less common, especially for transactions data which is often limited.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk me through some factors about why a company would be valued greater than its peers, both quantitatively and qualitatively.",a:"Quantitative: Higher revenue growth, superior profit margins, strong/consistent free cash flows, lower debt levels, higher ROE/ROIC. Qualitative: Strong brand recognition, competitive advantages (products, technologies, patents), experienced management, strategic partnerships, positive market perception, geographic diversification reducing risk.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why would a company with higher leverage have a higher beta than an otherwise identical company with lower leverage?",a:"Higher leverage increases financial risk, which increases equity beta. Debt obligations are fixed, so equity holders absorb all volatility in earnings. More debt creates larger percentage swings in net income available to equity. Formula: Levered Beta = Unlevered Beta x [1 + (1 - Tax Rate) x (Debt / Equity)].",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Calculate Beta given: correlation between stock and market is 0.5, ratio of standard deviation of stock to market is 2.0.",a:"Beta = Correlation x (Std Dev Stock / Std Dev Market) = 0.5 x 2.0 = 1.0. A beta of 1.0 means the stock moves in line with the market on average, despite having twice the volatility, because the correlation is only 0.5.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Should you use forecast or historical multiples for public comps and precedent transactions?",a:"Public Comps: Forward multiples (reflect market expectations and future growth). Precedent Transactions: Historical (LTM) multiples (transactions are priced on actual, verifiable results at deal announcement). Some practitioners use NTM for both if forward visibility is strong.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company H has $150M unlevered FCF, a 2% risk-free rate, a 4% market risk premium, and a beta of 2. What is the EV if the company is all equity?",a:"$1.5 billion. Cost of equity = 2% + (2 x 4%) = 10%. With zero-growth perpetuity, EV = 150 / 0.10 = 1,500M = $1.5B.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you observed two apparently identical companies in the same industry, but one traded at a significantly higher multiple, what are two or three reasons?",a:"1) Growth Prospects (superior growth trajectory). 2) Profitability & Margins (better operating leverage). 3) Competitive Position (stronger brand, market share, or moat). Even 'identical' companies differ in quality of earnings, growth sustainability, risk profile, and strategic positioning.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Typically, Precedent Transactions produce higher values than public comps. Any scenario where that might not be true?",a:"If recent M&A deals were at very low multiples or if the M&A market conditions differ significantly from the public market, transactions might be lower or similar.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Calculate the implied tax rate for: P/E 20x, EV/EBITDA 10x, Market Cap $200, Interest Expense $20, Pre-tax Cost of Debt 5%, D&A $20, no cash.",a:"50%. NI = $200 / 20x = $10. Debt = $20 / 5% = $400. EV = $200 + $400 = $600. EBITDA = $600 / 10x = $60. EBIT = $60 - $20 = $40. EBT = $40 - $20 = $20. Tax = $20 - $10 = $10. Tax Rate = $10 / $20 = 50%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How can you decrease a company's Equity Value?",a:"Pay it out or borrow against it. Dividends and buybacks move cash from the company to shareholders, so equity value falls by the amount that left. Raising debt to fund either does the same while adding a liability.\n\nOperationally, equity value falls whenever the business is worth less or the claims ahead of shareholders grow.\n\nThe point: notice that none of these make shareholders poorer in the dividend and buyback cases. The value moved rather than vanished. That is different from equity value falling because the business deteriorated, where the value genuinely disappeared. The same downward move means two completely different things.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is Beta? Would Bitcoin have a high or low Beta?",a:"Beta measures how much an asset's returns move relative to the market. Bitcoin is highly volatile and tends to swing more than the equity market, so it would have a Beta well above 1.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A target company has: EV/EBITDA 10x, EBITDA $200M, Total Debt $900M, Cash $100M. An acquirer purchases at a 25% premium. What is the equity purchase price? What is the transaction EV?",a:"Equity Purchase Price: $1,500M. Standalone EV = 10x x $200M = $2,000M. Standalone Equity Value = $2,000M - $900M + $100M = $1,200M. Purchase Price = $1,200M x 1.25 = $1,500M. Transaction EV: $2,300M. Transaction EV = $1,500M + $900M - $100M = $2,300M.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a sum-of-the-parts analysis, and why might you use it?",a:"SOTP values each business segment separately and adds them to arrive at total enterprise value. Useful for conglomerates with divisions that trade on different multiples or have distinct risk/growth profiles, and can reveal hidden value or break-up potential.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In the context of evaluating a project, what is the fundamental difference between IRR and WACC?",a:"IRR is the discount rate that makes a project's NPV zero based solely on its cash flows. WACC is the firm's overall hurdle rate that compensates investors for debt-service risk, equity risk, and potential liquidity constraints. A project should be accepted if IRR exceeds WACC.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If two companies in the same industry trade at different EV/EBITDA multiples (e.g., 15x and 10x), what could explain this?",a:"Growth rates, profitability and margins, risk profile, market position, size and scale, capital structure, management quality, and market sentiment.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some key factors to consider when selecting Comparable Companies?",a:"Industry sector, size, growth rate, capital structure, geographic location, and profitability metrics to ensure comparability.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A company and its peer have similar growth and margins. Why might one trade at a premium multiple?",a:"Possibilities include recent earnings beats, patent advantages, or being the market leader. Could also have intangible reasons causing the market to price it higher.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Part 1: How would you value your prior employer? Part 2: How would you value one of its specific product lines?",a:"Part 1: Use standard approaches. DCF, comparable company analysis, precedent transactions. Consider company-specific factors like competitive position and margin structure. Part 2: Segment-level valuation requires isolating segment revenues, EBITDA, CapEx. Use standalone DCF with segment-specific risk, or identify pure-play peers for comparable approach. Consider synergies and shared costs.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the relationship between P/B ratio and ROE?",a:"P/B is approximately ROE x (Payout Ratio) / (Cost of Equity - NI Growth Rate). Higher ROE typically drives higher P/B because investors pay more per book dollar when equity earns superior returns.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why would the market value a company with recurring revenue at a high EV/EBITDA? When would it value it lower?",a:"High multiple: Visibility and stability of cash flow, low churn and strong pricing power, scalable asset-light model. Lower multiple scenarios: Decelerating growth or rising churn, contractual price resets, customer concentration, regulatory overhang or high capital needs.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Under what circumstances could a company's cost of debt exceed its cost of equity?",a:"Rare but can occur in severe financial distress: High default risk where debt holders demand extremely high yields. Equity option value, in distressed scenarios equity can be viewed as a deeply out-of-the-money call option with lower implied cost of equity. Under normal circumstances, cost of equity exceeds cost of debt.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between a levered DCF and an LBO?",a:"Both value equity but use different mechanics. A Levered DCF projects Levered Free Cash Flow and discounts at Cost of Equity to tell you what equity is worth today. An LBO projects the same cash flows but solves for the IRR a sponsor earns given a purchase price, leverage and exit multiple; it doesn't discount cash flows.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you value a coffin company?",a:"Standard approaches: DCF (project stable demand, typical margins), comparable company multiples (other funeral/casket businesses), and precedent transactions in the death-care industry. Coffin company might have stable, non-cyclical cash flows, so DCF can be quite reliable.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you value Tesla, and what key items would you include in a pitchbook?",a:"Valuation: DCF (project deliveries, ASPs, margins, new revenue streams with scenario analysis), Trading Comps (auto OEMs and EV pure-plays), Precedent Transactions (limited relevant precedents). Key Pitchbook Items: Production capacity and delivery forecasts, margin trajectory and cost reduction, market share by geography, regulatory credits, adjacent businesses (energy, solar, FSD), competitive landscape.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If we use an industry-specific multiple like EV/Scientists or EV/Subscribers, do we use Equity Value or Enterprise Value?",a:"You generally use Enterprise Value because these operational metrics apply to all capital providers.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a Sum-of-the-Parts valuation work?",a:"Value each division or segment separately, then add those valuations together for the total. Common for conglomerates with multiple unrelated divisions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Calculate the EV/Revenue multiple for: Company A: $100M Revenue, 30% EBITDA Margin, 8x EV/EBITDA. Company B: $50M Revenue, 20% EBITDA Margin, 10x EV/EBITDA.",a:"Company A: EBITDA = $100M x 30% = $30M, EV = $30M x 8x = $240M, EV/Revenue = $240M / $100M = 2.4x. Company B: EBITDA = $50M x 20% = $10M, EV = $10M x 10x = $100M, EV/Revenue = $100M / $50M = 2.0x.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the pros and cons of perpetuity growth method vs exit multiple method for terminal value?",a:"Perpetuity growth: ties TV to infinite series of cash flows growing at stable rate, more theoretical, heavily dependent on chosen growth rate. Exit multiple: based on current market conditions and comparable company multiples, more aligned with real transactions but relies on a single multiple that might fluctuate.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me through an IPO valuation. How is it different from a standard private valuation?",a:"Rely on public comps (no Precedents or typical DCF in many cases). Pick a valuation multiple, apply to the company's metrics to get implied Equity Value. Subtract IPO proceeds or factor them in to get a per-share price based on total shares.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has perpetual FCF of $100M, growing at 5% annually, discount rate 10%, market cap $2B (100M shares at $20). What does this tell you?",a:"The company appears undervalued. DCF EV = $100M x 1.05 / (0.10 - 0.05) = $2,100M. Current Market Cap = $2,000M. Implied undervaluation = $100M or 5%. Could indicate market skepticism about growth, higher perceived risk, or temporary mispricing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Is the WACC for a company financed with 100% debt higher than for a company with a mix?",a:"Not necessarily. While debt has lower cost, 100% debt-financed company faces extreme financial risk and distress costs, making that debt very expensive. A balanced capital structure typically minimizes WACC.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Given forward multiples: 1Y EV/EBITDA = 12x, 2Y EV/EBITDA = 10x, 1Y P/E = 18x, 2Y P/E = 20x. Part 1: What is implied by each change? Part 2: Likely cause?",a:"Part 1: EV/EBITDA compression (12x to 10x) implies strong EBITDA growth. P/E expansion (18x to 20x) implies earnings growth lagging equity value. Part 2: Company has EBITDA growth but margin compression below EBITDA line. Likely: Increased D&A from investments, rising interest expense, higher tax rate, or one-time charges impacting net income disproportionately.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Given four multiples (EV/Earnings, EV/EBITDA, Price/EBITDA, Price/Earnings), which are valid and which are not?",a:"Valid: EV/EBITDA (enterprise metric to enterprise metric), Price/Earnings (equity to equity). Invalid: EV/Earnings (mismatch. EV is enterprise, Earnings is equity-level), Price/EBITDA (mismatch. Price is equity, EBITDA is enterprise-level).",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me about different valuation methods and the pros and cons of each.",a:"Public Comps. Quick and market-based; subject to sentiment swings. Precedent Transactions. Includes control premium; past deals may be stale or incomparable. DCF. Theoretically sound; highly sensitive to long-term assumptions. LBO. Floors value via IRR constraints; only relevant if sponsors are realistic buyers.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some flaws with Precedent Transactions?",a:"They may not be perfectly comparable due to differing deal sizes, structures, and market conditions. Data can be limited, especially for small private deals. Deal prices can be influenced by one-off motivations or synergy assumptions.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company trades at 2.0x EV/Sales and 5.0x EV/EBITDA, what is its EBITDA margin?",a:"40%. 2.0 x Sales = 5.0 x EBITDA. EBITDA / Sales = 2.0 / 5.0 = 0.40 = 40%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is CAGR, and how do you calculate it?",a:"CAGR (compound annual growth rate) is the annualized rate assuming compounding over n periods. Formula: (Ending / Beginning)^(1/n) - 1. For adjacent years (n = 1), it equals simple YoY growth.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A bond: Face Value $1,000, Annual Coupon Rate 10%, Purchase Price $500, Years to Maturity 3. What is YTM using the approximation formula?",a:"Approximately 35.6%. Annual Coupon = $1,000 x 10% = $100. YTM = [C + ((F - P) / n)] / [(F + P) / 2] = [$100 + ($500 / 3)] / [$750] = $266.67 / $750 = 35.6%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two companies are the same size, same industry, same revenue, but different EBITDAs. What are some possible reasons?",a:"Different cost structures (COGS, labor efficiency). Different operating expense levels (SG&A, R&D). Different business models (asset-light vs asset-heavy). Different pricing strategies. Geographic or customer mix differences. Different stages of growth. One-time charges or unusual items.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two companies appear very similar, yet one trades at a higher EV/EBITDA. Why? Would a company investing more in Capex have a higher or lower multiple?",a:"Possible drivers: Growth, margin, or cyclicality differences. Leverage or liquidity risk. IP quality or regulatory moats. Other metrics to check: EV/Sales, EV/EBIT, P/E, FCF yield, ROIC. Heavy ongoing Capex depresses FCF, usually leading to a lower EV/EBITDA multiple.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Give a few examples of industry-specific multiples. Why do they matter?",a:"EV/Unique Visitors for Internet, EV/Proven Reserves for Oil & Gas, Price/FFO for REITs. They are crucial because different industries have unique key value drivers not captured by standard multiples.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Two companies have the same EV/EBITDA multiple, but one is significantly more leveraged. How would you expect their P/E ratios to compare?",a:"The more leveraged company will have a lower P/E ratio. Same EV/EBITDA implies similar operating value. Higher leverage means higher risk equity, investors demand higher return, which translates to lower P/E.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two similar companies trade at 15x and 20x EV/EBITDA. Why might you argue in favor of acquiring the company with the higher multiple?",a:"Reasons to acquire the 20x company: 1) Superior Growth. 2) Quality of Earnings (more recurring revenue, higher margins). 3) Competitive Advantages. 4) Synergy Potential. 5) Strategic Fit. 6) Lower Risk Profile. If it generates superior long-term value, the higher multiple may be justified.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a driver behind choosing an appropriate discount rate in a DCF?",a:"The discount rate should reflect the company's cost of capital, incorporating both cost of equity and cost of debt, adjusted for the company's capital structure.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the key value drivers in a DCF versus an LBO model?",a:"DCF: Free Cash Flow growth, Discount rate (WACC), Terminal value assumptions. LBO: Entry valuation, Leverage and cost of debt, Cash-flow growth and margin expansion, Exit multiple and timing.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the limitations of using EV/EBITDA as a valuation metric?",a:"EV/EBITDA does not account for capital expenditures, changes in working capital, or differences in D&A policies. It may also ignore non-operating income or expenses, making it an incomplete measure.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you handle NOLs in a valuation, and why might you include them?",a:"Project how they offset taxable income, discounting tax savings to today. If significant, treat them like a non-operating asset that adds value (similar to cash), although approaches vary.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company traded at 10x EV/EBITDA in 2023 and 12x in 2024. What does that imply?",a:"Investors now pay more for each dollar of EBITDA. The expansion signals either higher expected growth or lower perceived risk; EV rose faster than EBITDA.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Companies A, B, and C all have the same EBITDA. Their EV/EBITDA multiples are 8x, 9x, and 10x now, but forward multiples are 10x, 9x, and 8x respectively. Which would you invest in?",a:"Company C. Company A is expected to have declining EBITDA (forward multiple rises 8x to 10x). Company B has stable EBITDA (stays 9x). Company C is expected to have growing EBITDA (falls 10x to 8x). The market pays a premium for future growth.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When is it most appropriate to use EV/EBITDA vs P/E vs EV/Revenue for valuation?",a:"EV/EBITDA: Comparing companies with different capital structures, normalizes for leverage, most common in M&A and LBO. P/E: Profitable companies with comparable capital structures, equity-focused. EV/Revenue: Unprofitable or early-stage companies where EBITDA is negative or not meaningful.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"For a company in the Dow 30, would you expect a valuation from public comps or a DCF to be higher?",a:"It depends, but DCF often yields higher valuations because it is forward-looking and can reflect long-term growth potential not yet priced in. Public comps reflect current market sentiment. For mature Dow 30 companies with stable cash flows, differences are usually modest.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A has an EPS of $7 and a P/E of 15x. If the tax rate drops from 30% to 15%, what is the new share price?",a:"$127.50. Current Share Price = $7 x 15x = $105. Pre-tax income = $7 / (1 - 30%) = $10 per share. New NI = $10 x (1 - 15%) = $8.50. New Share Price = $8.50 x 15x = $127.50.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you were trying to decide between selling a machine today or in one year, what would you consider?",a:"Compare the present value of the sale price now vs the expected sale price in one year discounted back, factoring in potential depreciation, usage cost, opportunity cost, and additional income from using the machine for that year.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Company has Equity Value of $100m and P/E = 10x. The company reduces operational costs by $10m/year. What is the new Equity Value?",a:"If P/E is 10x, $10m/year in additional net income translates to an extra $100m in equity value (10 x $10m). New equity value = $100m + $100m = $200m. In practice you'd adjust for taxes.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Where does the cost of preferred stock range vs Cost of Equity and Cost of Debt?",a:"Between them. Preferred dividends are contractually senior to common equity but junior to debt, so investors demand a return higher than debt yet lower than equity.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has $120 in EBITDA at a 10x multiple and a 20% EBITDA margin. Debt/EBITDA is 5x, interest rate is 10%, P/E is 20x, and no D&A. What is the tax rate?",a:"50%. EV = 1,200; Debt = 600, so Equity = 600. NI = 600/20 = 30. EBIT = 120 (assume no D&A). Interest = 60. EBT = 60. Taxes = 30. 30/60 = 50%.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does a change in the company's tax rate affect its DCF valuation?",a:"Taxes hit both levers in a DCF. Decrease in taxes leads to higher FCF (good) but also higher WACC (bad). FCF: NOPAT = EBIT x (1 - T). Lower T increases FCF. WACC: Lower T increases after-tax cost of debt and levered beta. Typically, for a profitable company, the benefit of higher FCF from a tax cut outweighs the negative impact of higher WACC.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you value an avocado tree?",a:"Use all usual approaches: Comparable Analysis (publicly-traded avocado or citrus farms valued per-acre or per-tree), Precedent Transactions (recent sales of similar orchards), DCF (project cash flows from future harvests, discount to present value), Liquidation Value (land plus salvage value of the tree as timber) as a floor.",category:"Valuation",difficulty:"Advanced"},
// === DCF QUESTIONS (from PDF upload) (145 new questions) ===
{q:"Can you explain, in simple terms, how a DCF provides a company's value?",a:"A DCF values a company by forecasting its cash flows and determining how much those cash flows are worth today. You project free cash flow each year and discount it at an appropriate rate, then estimate a terminal value at the end and discount that as well. Summing these discounted values yields the company's total present value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you define free cash flow in a DCF context?",a:"Free cash flow is the cash flow available to all providers of capital, after operating expenses, taxes, and reinvestment needs. It's typically EBIT x (1 - Tax Rate), plus non-cash items, minus CapEx, minus changes in working capital.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the purpose of discounting future cash flows?",a:"Money in the future is worth less than money today because of factors like inflation and opportunity cost. Discounting adjusts those future amounts back to a present value so you can compare them on an apples-to-apples basis.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the typical projection period for a DCF, and why?",a:"Usually around 5 to 10 years. Anything shorter than 5 years might be too little time, and beyond 10 years becomes too speculative.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you estimate the discount rate used in a standard DCF?",a:"You typically use the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC), which reflects the required returns of both debt and equity holders. It includes factors like the cost of equity, the cost of debt, and the capital structure mix.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can you describe how to get from revenue to unlevered free cash flow?",a:"Start with revenue and subtract operating costs to get EBIT. Then multiply by (1 - Tax Rate), add back depreciation and other non-cash items. Finally, subtract CapEx and any increases in working capital.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are two ways to estimate the terminal value in a DCF?",a:"The first is the Multiples Method, applying an exit multiple to the final year's EBITDA or EBIT. The second is the Gordon Growth Method, using a perpetual growth rate formula.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How is the terminal value calculated under the Gordon Growth Method?",a:"You take the final year's free cash flow, multiply by (1 + growth rate), then divide by (discount rate - growth rate).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Which typically produces a higher valuation: the Multiples Method or the Gordon Growth Method for Terminal Value?",a:"It varies. Multiples can be more volatile due to changing market sentiment, while Gordon Growth depends on a stable long-term rate. No strict rule says which is higher; it depends on assumptions.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you respond if the terminal value makes up 80% of the DCF's total value? Is that too high?",a:"Many DCFs yield high reliance on the terminal value. If it's above 70-80%, you might review assumptions, but it's not necessarily wrong.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why might you use levered free cash flow instead of unlevered free cash flow in your DCF?",a:"If you're only interested in equity value, you can use levered FCF to reflect cash flow available after debt payments. This approach discounts at the cost of equity rather than WACC.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you switch from enterprise value to equity value in a DCF model?",a:"The unlevered (FCFF) DCF discounted at WACC gives Enterprise Value (TEV). Apply the standard formula: EqV = TEV + Cash - Debt - Preferred Stock - Minority Interest. Divide equity value by fully diluted shares outstanding to obtain implied share price.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If cost of equity rises, does that necessarily mean WACC rises as well?",a:"WACC might rise if the debt portion doesn't change. But if the company's debt ratio is large, or cost of debt changes, it may offset the equity changes.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you handle working capital changes in a DCF forecast?",a:"If working capital increases, it's a cash outflow, so you subtract it from free cash flow. If working capital decreases, it releases cash, so it's an inflow you add to free cash flow.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In what scenario might a DCF not be very useful?",a:"It's less useful for companies with unpredictable cash flows or for financial institutions where debt is integral to operations. In these cases, other valuation methods like comps, transaction multiples, or a dividend discount model might be preferred.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If a company's growth is expected to slow drastically after year 3, what does that mean for your DCF model?",a:"You'd likely project higher growth in initial years, then reflect a step-down to a lower growth rate afterward. It underscores the importance of carefully modeling revenue growth and margins each year, not just a uniform growth assumption.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are some ways to sanity-check your DCF results?",a:"Compare implied multiples (like EV/EBITDA) to the current market or comps. Run sensitivity analyses on key inputs and see if valuations seem reasonable. Check if terminal value is dominating too large a portion of total value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you factor cyclical industries, like steel or semiconductors, into a DCF?",a:"It's tricky. You might project through an entire cycle or normalize earnings over an average cycle to avoid overstating or understating any single year. You could also do scenario analyses for boom vs bust conditions.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you treat stock-based compensation in a DCF?",a:"Some view it as a real expense and subtract it from cash flow, then factor in additional share count. Others might add it back as a non-cash expense but increase diluted shares outstanding, thus adjusting equity value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why do you typically use 5-10 years for the projection period?",a:"Need enough time before terminal value to achieve steady state. Less than 5 years is too short, more than 10 is too speculative.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the relationship between Debt and the Cost of Equity?",a:"More debt raises cost of equity. Shareholders are last in line, so every dollar of debt ranking ahead of them makes their claim riskier and their returns more volatile.\n\nMechanically it runs through levered beta: relevering at a higher debt-to-equity ratio raises beta, which raises cost of equity through CAPM.\n\nThe point: this is why adding debt does not lower WACC forever. Debt is cheaper, but it makes the equity underneath more expensive, and eventually the second effect overtakes the first. That is the bottom of the U-shaped WACC curve.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you calculate WACC for a private company?",a:"Use comparables to estimate the cost of equity and debt, and approximate capital structure from similar companies.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a mid-year convention in a DCF, and why might you use it?",a:"Mid-year convention assumes cash flows are generated evenly throughout the year, rather than all at period-end. It shifts discount periods by 0.5 for each year, slightly increasing present value because you discount less heavily.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you adjust the terminal value if you use the mid-year convention?",a:"When using the mid-year convention, projection period cash flows are discounted using (n. 0.5). For the Terminal Value using the Exit Multiple Method, the sale is assumed to occur at the end of the year. Therefore, you must discount the Terminal Value using the full period N, rather than N-0.5.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you implement a partial stub period (like 6 months) in a mid-year convention DCF?",a:"Split the initial period into that half-year, discounting at 0.5 / 2 = 0.25 if truly mid-quarter. Then for subsequent full years, the mid-point would be the end of the stub period plus half a year (0.5 + 0.5 = 1.0), then 2.0, 3.0, etc.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you value a company that's planning a major acquisition in Year 3 of your DCF forecast?",a:"You might either model the combined company's free cash flow from Year 3 onward, adjusting for synergy assumptions and purchase price. Or keep it simpler by showing an outflow in Year 3 if it's purely a cash purchase, though more detailed M&A modeling might be needed for accuracy.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you're using leveraged free cash flow (LFCF) in a DCF, what discount rate should you use?",a:"You'd use the cost of equity, because leveraged free cash flow is cash available only to equity holders.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you handle a significant debt repayment each year in a levered DCF model?",a:"Since levered FCF includes interest and debt principal payments, you'd explicitly subtract the mandatory principal repayment each period. This reduces the free cash flow available to equity holders each year.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Explain why a DCF might not be accurate for certain cyclical sectors like airlines.",a:"Airlines can have large swings in revenue and expenses due to fuel costs, demand cycles, and labor contracts. Projecting stable growth or margins is difficult, and a small assumption error can greatly skew valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If your mid-year convention DCF is yielding a much higher value than the standard approach, is that logical?",a:"It can be higher, but typically the difference is modest. If it's dramatically higher, you might be double-counting or applying mid-year discounting incorrectly for the terminal value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When does using a Dividend Discount Model (DDM) make more sense than a typical DCF?",a:"DDM is often used for financial institutions or firms that pay out a stable dividend tied closely to earnings, such as certain utilities. These companies' capital structures rely heavily on deposits or insurance float, making standard unlevered FCF analysis less relevant.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In a Dividend Discount Model, how do you calculate the terminal value?",a:"You typically use a P/E-based approach for the final projected year. Multiply that year's estimated EPS by an appropriate P/E multiple, or use a Gordon Growth approach on dividends.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If two companies share identical WACC, cash flows, and growth, but one has convertible debt and the other does not, do they have the same enterprise value in a DCF?",a:"Enterprise value from the DCF might be similar initially, but the convertible debt may convert to equity if in-the-money, affecting final equity calculations. On a purely enterprise value basis, they could appear similar, but final per-share equity might differ.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Does a high beta necessarily mean a higher WACC?",a:"Yes, because beta influences cost of equity, so a higher beta typically increases that. Since equity is part of WACC, a higher beta usually raises the overall discount rate unless debt is large enough to offset it.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you reflect a rapidly changing capital structure (e.g., repeated share issuances) in a DCF?",a:"You might do a levered DCF, factoring new equity issuances into the share count each year. Alternatively, if using unlevered FCF, you still note changes that might affect WACC or net debt. Some advanced models recalc WACC yearly.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company has intangible assets that amortize over time, how does that factor into a DCF?",a:"Amortization is a non-cash expense, so you add it back if it's lowering EBIT. However, watch for any real cash costs tied to intangible maintenance or renewal that might not appear as standard CapEx.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If your DCF's implied value is far below a public company's current share price, what are possible reasons?",a:"You might have used overly conservative forecasts or a too-high discount rate. The market may be factoring intangible positives or synergy prospects not captured in your model. Or the stock might be overvalued from a pure fundamental standpoint.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why might you unlever and re-lever beta when looking at comparable companies for a DCF?",a:"Each company has a unique capital structure, so you unlever betas to remove the effect of debt. Then you re-lever with your target's structure to reflect its specific risk profile.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you handle capital leases or operating leases in the DCF discount rate calculation?",a:"Capital leases are typically treated like debt, which can slightly affect WACC. Operating leases might be off-balance historically, but under new standards, they appear as lease liabilities, so they can also be seen as debt-like.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If your discount rate is 10% and your terminal growth is 3%, does a 3% perpetual growth automatically mean you're assuming infinite expansion in real terms?",a:"Mathematically, yes, a 3% growth rate into perpetuity implies the company grows forever. Practically, we keep that rate modest (like GDP or inflation) to avoid unrealistically large values.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Could we use a negative growth rate for terminal value in a DCF if the business is declining?",a:"Technically yes. If the company's cash flows are expected to shrink perpetually, you could model a small negative rate. However, negative indefinite growth often implies the business goes to zero, so you must be cautious.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In your final output, do you present a single figure for your DCF valuation or a range?",a:"Typically, you present a range using sensitivity tables for the discount rate and terminal multiples (or growth rates). You rarely rely on a single number but rather show best-case, base-case, and worst-case scenarios.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a DCF/can you walk me through a DCF in under 60 seconds?",a:"You project and discount a company's FCF plus its terminal value: Forecast free cash flow 5-10 years. Discount at WACC. Find terminal value (exit multiple or perpetuity growth). Discount terminal value back and sum for enterprise value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is WACC, conceptually? How do you calculate it?",a:"WACC is the required return on the company's capital structure, weighted by each capital slice's proportion. WACC = Cost of Equity x % Equity + Cost of Debt x % Debt x (1 - Tax Rate) + Cost of Preferred x % Preferred.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Tell me 3 places where taxes affect a DCF.",a:"Calculating Beta (conversion from unlevered to levered). Calculating FCF (NOPAT). Calculating Cost of Debt (interest is tax deductible).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you are valuing a coal mine company, would you use the Gordon Growth Method or the Multiples Method to calculate the TV? Explain.",a:"Would use the multiples method, since Gordon Growth assumes cash flows exist into perpetuity and coal is a depleting resource.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you change a DCF to value a highly speculative technology company?",a:"Longer projection horizon, as it may take longer to stabilize. Higher discount rate to reflect higher risk. Adjust growth/margin assumptions for uncertainty.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company buys a factory for $100 in its 4th year. How would the DCF/Enterprise Value change?",a:"Add $100 of CapEx in Year 4, reducing that year's FCF by $100 and lowering EV by its PV: 100 / (1 + r)^4.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you calculate the long-term growth rate for the Gordon Growth Method?",a:"Typically choose a conservative rate (e.g. inflation or GDP, around 2-3%). Anything above 5% is aggressive for most developed markets.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are the three ways that lowering tax can affect a DCF valuation?",a:"Boosts net income leading to higher FCF. Raises cost of debt (less tax shield) increasing WACC. Lowers tax shield in levered beta increasing cost of equity. Net effect depends on which is stronger: FCF increase or WACC increase.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are common alterations to the basic WACC formula to make it more company-specific?",a:"Add a size premium or liquidity discount for smaller/private entities. Include preferred stock if part of the capital structure. Use alternative cost of equity formulas if Beta is unusable.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Ignoring taxes, how would changing from LIFO to FIFO affect FCF during a period of rising costs?",a:"Lower COGS via FIFO increases net income, but also increases inventory, which is a use of cash. The two effects offset, so FCF is neutral (in a simplified scenario).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In a DCF valuation, which increases the valuation the most: $10 decrease in CapEx, $10 decrease in expenses, or $10 increase in revenues?",a:"The $10 decrease in CapEx has the most significant impact. Decreasing CapEx directly increases FCF by $10 with no tax effect. Reducing expenses by $10 increases FCF by $10 x (1 - Tax rate). Increasing revenues by $10 also increases FCF by $10 x (1 - Tax rate).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between asset beta and equity beta?",a:"Asset beta (unlevered) measures business risk excluding debt. Equity beta (levered) includes debt risk, making it higher if leverage exists.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would raising $100M debt in Year 3 affect the DCF valuation of a company?",a:"Unlevered FCF is unaffected by new interest costs, but the capital structure changes after Year 3 could alter WACC. You might recalc WACC post-Year 3, discounting from that point onward.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you categorize maintenance, growth, and acquisition CapEx when analyzing a company's spending?",a:"Maintenance CapEx is the baseline amount needed to sustain operations. Growth CapEx supports expansion and can often be deferred. Acquisition CapEx is funding for M&A. In valuation, mandatory maintenance spending is more critical to subtract from operating cash flow, while other categories can be more discretionary.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is cheaper. Debt or equity?",a:"Debt is cheaper because interest is tax-deductible, and debt sits above equity in a firm's capital structure.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Within WACC, can the cost of debt ever be higher than the cost of equity?",a:"Typically, no. Debt ranks above equity in the capital structure, so it carries a lower required return. However, in extreme distress, yields on debt can spike, but rational equity investors would still demand a higher return than debt holders.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How does changing an asset affect the DCF?",a:"If an asset decreases, the change in NWC is lower, so FCF is higher. If an asset increases, the change in NWC is higher, so FCF is lower.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Calculate stub-year discount factors with mid-year convention for the end of Q1, Q2, Q3, and Q4.",a:"Q1: First = 0.375, Second = 1.25. Q2: First = 0.25, Second = 1. Q3: First = 0.125, Second = 0.75. Q4: First = 0.5, Second = 1.5. Stub period = months to 12/31 / 12. Mid-year convention discounts the stub cash flow at half the stub length (s / 2). First full-year cash flow arrives six months into the next year, so exponent = s + 0.5.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company has 11% NWC/Sales and another has 12% NWC/Sales, which is valued higher if sales are increasing?",a:"The company with the lower NWC ratio (11%) is generally valued higher because it ties up less cash in working capital as sales grow.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Can you describe a company with a beta close to zero?",a:"A government utilities company (or extremely non-cyclical, regulated entity) typically has a near-zero market beta.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you get from Unlevered FCF to Levered FCF?",a:"Subtract after-tax interest expense and mandatory debt repayments. Unlevered cash flow sits above interest and belongs to everyone; levered cash flow is what survives after the lenders are paid, so it belongs to shareholders alone.\n\nInterest is after tax because it is deductible, so a dollar of interest only costs one minus the tax rate.\n\nThe point: the discount rate has to follow. Unlevered cash flow gets discounted at WACC and produces enterprise value. Levered cash flow gets discounted at cost of equity and produces equity value directly. Mixing them either double counts the financing or ignores it.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If debt of a company is going down, how does that affect the cost of equity and the cost of capital?",a:"Less debt lowers beta, theoretically reducing cost of equity. Overall WACC could move either way, but typically, if you reduce cheaper debt, cost of capital may rise slightly.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Rank these three changes from biggest to smallest impact on FCF: 10% increase in Revenue, 10% decrease in COGS, 10% decrease in Working Capital.",a:"Biggest: 10% decrease in Working Capital (no tax effect). Next: 10% decrease in COGS. Least: 10% increase in Revenue.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are three questions you would ask the CEO of a company to do a DCF?",a:"Three that actually change the output.\n\nWhat constrains your growth? Not how fast will you grow. You want the binding constraint, whether it is capacity, salespeople, or demand, so the growth rate ties to something physical instead of a trend line.\n\nWhat CapEx keeps the business flat? This splits maintenance from growth capex, which sets the reinvestment rate and tells you whether earnings convert to cash.\n\nWhat margin does this business earn at scale, and when? This sets the terminal margin, and terminal value is usually 60% to 80% of a DCF, so that one assumption outweighs everything in the projection period.\n\nThe point: a DCF has only three levers, growth, reinvestment, and terminal economics. Naming that is the actual answer.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are ways you could have negative free cash flow in a DCF?",a:"Heavy capex, a large build in working capital, or simply operating losses.\n\nEach has a different meaning. Capex-driven negative cash flow usually means the company is investing to grow, which can be fine. Working capital driven means growth is outrunning collections, which is a financing problem. Loss-driven means the business does not work yet.\n\nThe point: negative free cash flow is not automatically bad, and the cause decides. A company burning cash to build a factory that will produce for twenty years is doing something very different from one burning cash because customers will not pay. The DCF treats them identically, so you have to look.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How can you calculate the Equity Value of a company using a DCF?",a:"Either use a Levered DCF directly to calculate Equity Value, or find Implied Enterprise Value from an Unlevered DCF and then subtract net debt (subtract debt, add cash).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Let's say you have WACC on the y-axis and the debt/equity ratio on the x-axis. What does the graph look like?",a:"It is a U-shaped parabola, where moderate leverage can minimize WACC, but too much or too little raises it.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You are valuing a company. How do you increase the valuation only using NWC?",a:"Increase current liabilities (or reduce current assets) so that the changes in NWC are smaller and FCF is higher, boosting valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the greatest driver of value in a DCF?",a:"The terminal value is typically the greatest driver, usually representing 50-80% of total enterprise value. It captures all cash flows beyond the explicit forecast period in perpetuity. Within terminal value, the perpetuity growth rate and terminal multiple assumptions have outsized impact. Small changes in these inputs dramatically affect valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Explain the concept of WACC as if you were talking to a 6-year-old.",a:"Imagine you want to buy a lemonade stand. You need money, so you ask your parents for some and borrow the rest from your piggy bank. Your parents want you to share some profits as a thank you. Your piggy bank needs a little money back each week. WACC is figuring out how much, on average, it costs you to get all that money from both places. You need to make sure your lemonade stand earns more than what it costs to borrow.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does a decrease in the tax rate impact a DCF analysis?",a:"Increased Net Income from lower taxes. Higher Free Cash Flows since more cash is available. Higher WACC because lower tax rate reduces the tax shield (increases after-tax cost of debt). Higher Enterprise Value because increased free cash flows typically outweigh the WACC increase. Overall, a decrease in the tax rate generally increases DCF valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk from revenue to levered free cash flow (FCFE).",a:"Levered free cash flow represents cash available to equity holders after reinvestment and debt obligations. Steps: Revenue - COGS = Gross Profit. GP - OpEx = EBIT. EBIT - Interest Expense - Taxes = Net Income. Net Income + D&A - CapEx - Increase in NWC + Net Borrowing (Debt Issued - Debt Repayments) = Levered Free Cash Flow.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If WACC is 10% and the perpetuity growth rate (g) is 5%, what is the implied perpetuity exit multiple?",a:"21x. Terminal Value = FCF x (1 + g) / (WACC - g). TV / FCF = (1 + g) / (WACC - g) = 1.05 / 0.05 = 21x. The implied exit multiple is 21x the terminal year's FCF.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How do you set key assumptions when building a DCF?",a:"Analyze historical performance, discuss management guidance, examine industry benchmarks for growth, margins, capex, and working capital. Then form best estimates for revenue growth rates, operating margins, tax rates, capex, and WACC.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What would make the cost of equity low for a company?",a:"A lower beta (less volatile stock), lower risk-free rate environment, or a lower equity risk premium. Also, stable, diversified business models or strong brand moats lead to lower perceived risk, reducing the required return by investors.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Assuming a 5% discount rate, how much would you pay to receive $1 per day, every day, forever?",a:"$7,300. Annual cash flow = $1/day x 365 = $365. Perpetuity Value = $365 / 0.05 = $7,300.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the impact of a rising risk-free rate on a company's WACC and its DCF valuation?",a:"A rising risk-free rate increases WACC, which decreases DCF valuation. Higher risk-free rate directly increases Cost of Equity (via CAPM). Cost of Debt also typically rises. Higher WACC means future cash flows are discounted more heavily, resulting in lower valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me from revenue down to unlevered free cash flow.",a:"Revenue - COGS - OpEx = EBIT. EBIT x (1 - tax rate) = NOPAT. NOPAT + D&A and other non-cash charges - CapEx - Change in Working Capital = Unlevered Free Cash Flow.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is the effect of using the mid-year convention in a DCF?",a:"Shifts each cash-flow discount date back half a period, raising present value and enterprise value. The uplift reflects the fact that cash is earned throughout the year, not just at year-end.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is Free Cash Flow, and why do we focus on it?",a:"Free Cash Flow is the discretionary cash a company generates after funding operations and maintenance capex. UFCF = EBIT x (1 - tax rate) + D&A - Capex - Change in NWC. It matters because it is the cash available to all capital providers and drives intrinsic value in a DCF.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What happens to a DCF valuation if the tax rate increases?",a:"Higher taxes reduce after-tax EBIT (NOPAT) and thus reduce unlevered free cash flow. The lower cash flows lead to a lower DCF valuation, all else being equal.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"When valuing an apple tree using a DCF, would you prefer the Gordon Growth Model or Exit Multiple Method for terminal value?",a:"Gordon Growth Model. The tree is a stand-alone, non-traded asset whose cash flows grow at a steady, biologically limited rate rather than be sold at a market multiple. A perpetual growth assumption aligns with the asset's economic reality (ongoing harvests), avoids arbitrary exit multiples with no observable market comps, and reduces valuation noise.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Is the cost of equity always greater than the cost of debt? Explain.",a:"Yes in theory; usually in practice. Equity holders are residual claimants and face greater risk. Debt enjoys contractual coupons, seniority, and often collateral. Tax deductibility of interest lowers after-tax cost of debt further. Exceptions arise in distress situations (very high debt yields) or when models break down.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Back-to-back DCF questions: 1. Why use unlevered FCF? 2. How do you calculate WACC? 3. Explain CAPM.",a:"UFCF represents cash flow available to all investors (equity and debt) and produces Enterprise Value. WACC = Cost of Equity x % Equity + Cost of Debt x % Debt x (1 - Tax Rate) + Cost of Preferred x % Preferred. CAPM: Cost of Equity = Risk-Free Rate + Beta x Equity Risk Premium. You may add a size premium and industry premium. Intuitively, CAPM says investors need compensation for time value of money (risk-free rate) and risk (beta x ERP).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why is the 10-year U.S. Treasury yield used as the risk-free rate? How do you determine a company's actual cost of debt?",a:"Risk-Free Rate: Backed by U.S. government with negligible default risk, 10-year matches long-term corporate cash-flow horizon, highly liquid. Cost of Debt: Use yield-to-maturity on existing traded bonds. If private, add credit-spread from rating comps to risk-free rate. Adjust for tax shield: after-tax cost = pretax x (1 - tax rate).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"$10 in revenue, Opex, and Capex: Which has the biggest impact on a DCF? Rank order.",a:"Greatest negative to least: $10 increase in CapEx (full $10 cash outflow). $10 increase in Operating Expenses (hits EBIT but partly offset by lower taxes). $10 increase in Revenue actually raises value. CapEx directly reduces FCF dollar-for-dollar, so its impact is largest.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Which has the bigger impact on valuation in a DCF: $10 increase in revenue, $10 decrease in operating expenses, or $10 decrease in Capex?",a:"$10 lower Capex. Capex reduction raises free cash flow dollar-for-dollar (no tax). Operating-expense savings add $10 x (1 - Tax). Extra revenue lifts FCF by margin x (1 - Tax); both smaller than the Capex impact.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What does the cost of equity represent in a valuation context? How is it calculated? Explain each component.",a:"The cost of equity represents the annual return investors require to compensate for the risk of investing in a company's equity. Calculated using CAPM: Cost of Equity = Risk-Free Rate + (Beta x Equity Risk Premium). Risk-Free Rate: return on risk-free investment like a government bond. Beta: sensitivity to systematic risk relative to broader market. Equity Risk Premium: additional return demanded for stocks vs risk-free investments.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me through the calculation from EBITDA to Unlevered Free Cash Flow.",a:"EBITDA - D&A = EBIT. EBIT x (1 - tax rate) = NOPAT. NOPAT + D&A and other non-cash charges - Capex - Changes in Working Capital = Unlevered Free Cash Flow.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"In a DCF model, what are three key levers to increase the company's valuation?",a:"Raise revenue/margin growth, lower the discount rate, and use a higher terminal growth or exit multiple. Higher cash flows in the explicit forecast period, lower WACC increases PV of each dollar, and higher terminal value boosts the perpetuity portion.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What is unlevered free cash flow, and how do you calculate it?",a:"UFCF is cash flow available to all investors (debt and equity) before debt payments. Start with EBIT, subtract taxes to get NOPAT, add back D&A, subtract CapEx, subtract increase in NWC. Formula: UFCF = NOPAT + D&A - CapEx - Change in NWC.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How would you explain the Cost of Equity to someone with no finance background?",a:"Cost of Equity is the return investors expect for investing in a company's stock, given the risk involved. Like lending money to a friend. You expect interest as compensation for risk. Riskier companies require higher returns to attract investors. For the company, this is the minimum return it must generate to satisfy equity investors.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Why would one company have a higher WACC than another?",a:"Higher Business Risk (volatile cash flows, cyclical industry). Higher Financial Risk (more leverage increases cost of debt and equity). Lower Credit Rating. Less Debt in Capital Structure (less tax shield). Smaller Size (higher liquidity and risk premiums). Industry (tech startups inherently higher than stable utilities).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"If you were given a company's cash flow for each of the next 30 years, how would you derive its value?",a:"Discount each year's cash flow to present value using WACC, then sum all discounted values. Formula: Value = Sum of (CF_t / (1 + r)^t) for t = 1 to 30. In practice, you'd also add a terminal value beyond year 30 to capture perpetual cash flows.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does an increase in leverage affect unlevered free cash flow?",a:"No direct impact. Unlevered FCF excludes interest and debt principal, so changing the capital structure leaves the metric unchanged.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"How does an increase in A/R affect valuation in a DCF?",a:"It lowers the valuation. An A/R build is a use of cash, raising change in NWC and reducing Free Cash Flow in every forecast period. Lower FCF translates into smaller present value and lower enterprise value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"An asset is expected to generate $100 in cash flow each year into perpetuity. Discount rate is 10%. What is it worth today?",a:"$1,000. Perpetuity Value = Annual Cash Flow / Discount Rate = $100 / 10% = $1,000.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me through a DCF, and conceptually explain what WACC is.",a:"DCF steps: Project unlevered FCF over 5-10 years. Discount and sum at WACC. Calculate and add PV of terminal value. WACC = blended opportunity cost to all capital providers weighted by market value shares. It reflects required return on a like-risk asset and is the discount rate for enterprise-level cash flows.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Can a DCF analysis be used to calculate the value of synergies in a transaction?",a:"Yes. Build standalone DCF for target without synergies. Separately forecast incremental cash flows from synergies (revenue growth, cost savings, reduced CapEx). Apply appropriate timing (phase in over 2-3 years). Discount at appropriate rate (potentially higher for execution risk). PV of synergy cash flows represents synergy value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"What are the key drivers you would sensitize in a DCF model?",a:"Revenue growth rate, EBITDA/operating margin, WACC, terminal growth rate, terminal multiple, CapEx as % of revenue, working capital changes, and tax rate. Typically create 2-way sensitivity tables for WACC vs terminal growth rate or terminal multiple.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"Walk me through a DCF. Follow-up: Why use 5-10 year projection? Could we do 25 years?",a:"DCF: Project unlevered FCF for 5-10 years, estimate terminal value (Gordon Growth or exit multiple), discount both at WACC and sum. Follow-up 1: Forecast accuracy drops sharply beyond 5-10 years; that range balances visibility and value capture. Follow-up 2: 25-year DCF is theoretically possible but small forecasting errors compound, so most practitioners rely on shorter explicit period plus terminal value.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is a levered DCF? What discount rate do you use? How do you calculate cost of equity?",a:"A levered DCF discounts cash flows after interest and mandatory principal at the Cost of Equity to value equity directly. The discount rate is the company's Cost of Equity. Cost of Equity = Risk-free rate + Beta x Equity risk premium, plus or minus size/sector adjustments (CAPM).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you factor cross-border risk in a DCF?",a:"Add a country risk premium to the cost of equity reflecting political, economic, and currency risks. Adjust the discount rate for higher uncertainty. Incorporate scenario analyses for potential currency swings, regulatory changes, or macroeconomic volatility.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A stable utility company shifts to renewables. How far out would you project, and what's the risk of a shorter projection period?",a:"Project 10-15 years to capture the full transition, ramping renewables build-out and new model adoption. Longer asset useful lives in renewables (20-30 years) mean benefits accrue well beyond a 10-year window. A shorter period pushes too much value into the terminal, making valuation overly sensitive to exit assumptions and risking missing multi-year capex inflection points.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"You're valuing a high-growth SaaS firm (30% growth, 30% margin) in a DCF. How do you build projections and choose an EBITDA exit multiple?",a:"Build projections: Model revenue ramp from 30% toward a long-term stable rate (3-5%), gradually expand margins from 30% to mature levels (40-45%). Choose exit multiple: Use public and M&A comps in a stable-growth SaaS group (12-15x EBITDA), adjusted for size, growth differential, and margin profile. If applying LTM exit multiple, anchor on final projection year; if NTM forward multiple, apply to year after projection period.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company switches accounting from LIFO to FIFO. How does that affect a DCF valuation?",a:"In inflation (rising costs): FIFO lowers COGS, raising EBITDA but also increasing taxes; inventory increases tie up cash in working capital, reducing FCF. In deflation (falling costs): FIFO raises COGS, lowering EBITDA and taxes; inventory decreases release working capital, increasing FCF. In DCF, project the new EBITDA, adjust cash-tax line, model working capital changes. Net impact depends on relative size of EBITDA change versus tax and working-capital effects.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you account for Stock-Based Compensation (SBC) in a DCF?",a:"SBC is a non-cash expense added back when calculating unlevered FCF, but creates real economic dilution. Two approaches: 1) Add back SBC but use diluted share count (including in-the-money options via treasury stock method) when calculating equity value per share. 2) Treat SBC as a real cash expense by not adding it back, keeping basic share count. Most practitioners use approach 1 as it better reflects dilution while maintaining consistency.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you calculate cost of equity for a company whose cash flows are in a foreign currency?",a:"Use CAPM with a country risk premium for emerging markets. Alternatively, convert cash flows to USD (if using USD-based CAPM) or use a local risk-free rate, local market risk premium, and local beta in foreign currency, then convert final values back to USD.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What if you're 90% terminal value in a DCF?",a:"That suggests value is heavily in the terminal period, typical of high-growth or long-duration cash flows. It indicates forecasting uncertainty in earlier years and that small changes in terminal assumptions can dramatically affect valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk me through a DCF for a solar farm, starting with how you would project revenue.",a:"Revenue: Capacity (MW) x Capacity Factor (%) x Hours per Year x Power Price ($/MWh). Consider PPAs with fixed pricing or merchant exposure. Account for degradation (typically 0.5% annually). Cash Flow: Revenue minus Operating Costs (O&M, insurance, land lease), subtract taxes (consider ITC/PTC benefits), subtract minimal maintenance CapEx. Terminal Value: Use perpetuity with low/zero growth or asset salvage value. Consider useful life (25-30 years). Discount at project WACC reflecting contracted cash flows.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Rank impact on DCF: $1 increase in revenue, $1 increase in cash OpEx, or $1 increase in changes in NWC.",a:"NWC > OpEx > Revenue. NWC has largest effect because it impacts cash flows directly without influencing taxes. Cash OpEx ranks higher than revenue because increasing revenue also drives up COGS. Caveat: If the change occurs in the terminal year using Exit Multiple method, order flips to OpEx > Revenue > NWC because OpEx and Revenue permanently affect EBITDA.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"As an investor using a DCF, would you rather have a $10 increase in revenue, $10 increase in gross profit, or $10 decrease in CapEx?",a:"Most impactful: decrease in CapEx (no tax impact), followed by increase in gross profit, then increase in revenue (since revenue growth also drives up COGS).",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Assuming 40% tax rate, which has biggest impact on FCF: $10 increase in Revenue, $10 decrease in Depreciation, or $10 decrease in CapEx? Follow-up: Which has biggest impact on terminal value?",a:"FCF Impact: $10 Decrease in CapEx is biggest (+$10 direct cash savings). $10 Increase in Revenue adds $6 after tax. $10 Decrease in Depreciation actually decreases FCF by $4 (loss of tax shield). Terminal Value Impact: $10 increase in Revenue has biggest impact because it grows the base for all future periods, compounding into perpetuity, whereas CapEx or Depreciation changes are one-time adjustments.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If WACC increases, can the Present Value in a DCF also increase?",a:"Yes, in rare cases where future cash flows are negative. If a project has significant upfront investment followed by negative terminal cash flows (e.g., decommissioning costs), higher discount rate reduces PV of those negative flows, potentially increasing NPV. In practice, extremely rare.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If you could only see one number from an analyst's DCF model to determine Enterprise Value, which would you choose?",a:"The terminal value. It typically represents 60-80% of total enterprise value, capturing all cash flows beyond the explicit forecast period. Knowing terminal value plus assuming reasonable forecast-period cash flows gives a strong EV approximation. Alternative: WACC, since combined with cash flow assumptions you could reconstruct the valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If your terminal value assumptions imply a perpetuity growth rate of 6%, what does that signify and what adjustments should you make?",a:"6% is unrealistically high, implying the company grows faster than GDP indefinitely. Adjustments: Reduce growth rate to 2-3% (closer to long-term GDP). Use exit multiple approach instead. Review terminal year assumptions for sustainability. Consider if you're in a high-growth year that shouldn't be perpetualized.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company discovers its annual depreciation was understated by $10 million. After correcting, what is the net impact on Unlevered FCF? Assume 40% tax rate.",a:"+$4M increase. Higher Depreciation reduces Pre-Tax Income by $10M. Reduces Taxes by $10M x 40% = $4M. Net Income decreases by $6M. In UFCF: Lower NI (-$6M) + Higher D&A add-back (+$10M) = +$4M. The tax shield from additional depreciation increases UFCF by $4M.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you handle changes to debt levels in your WACC for an all-equity company that 'matures' in 10 years?",a:"Even if all equity now, assume it will add debt as it matures. Model a target capital structure for year 10 and gradually move WACC toward that. Alternatively, keep a pure equity discount rate but mention that if the company leverages, cost of debt would be factored in.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What are three ways that a change in interest rates can affect a DCF valuation?",a:"1) Discount Rate (WACC): Higher rates increase WACC, reducing PV of cash flows. 2) Cash Flows (Interest Expense): Higher rates increase interest expense, reducing Net Income and FCF. 3) Terminal Value: Higher discount rate reduces PV of terminal value (50-80% of total DCF value). Net effect: Rising rates compress valuations through multiple channels.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If an analyst miscalculates D&A to be 50% too low, how would correcting this affect a DCF valuation?",a:"Valuation would increase. Correcting D&A upward increases the D&A add-back in FCF. EBIT decreases but the tax shield increases (lower taxes). Net effect: Higher FCF due to non-cash add-back exceeding the tax impact. Higher FCF leads to higher present value and valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"When would it be appropriate to use a negative growth rate in the perpetuity calculation of a DCF?",a:"When the company is in structural decline: Obsolete technology or products (print newspapers, DVDs). Shrinking end markets with no pivot strategy. Regulated industries facing phase-outs (coal power plants). Companies with depleting natural resources.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What does a levered DCF represent, conceptually?",a:"It discounts the cash flows left after debt service to equity holders at the Cost of Equity, giving equity value directly and embedding the capital structure in the valuation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Revenues = 1000, COGS + SG&A = 400, D&A = 200, Capex = 100, tax rate = 10%. Last year NWC was 150; this year it's 175. Calculate FCF.",a:"$435. EBIT = 1000 - 400 - 200 = 400. NOPAT = 400 x 0.9 = 360. Add back D&A: +200. Less Capex: -100. Less change in NWC: 175 - 150 = 25. FCF = 360 + 200 - 100 - 25 = 435.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Why is WACC U-shaped?",a:"As you initially add debt, WACC decreases due to the tax shield (debt cheaper than equity). But adding too much debt raises financial distress risk, pushing up cost of both debt and equity. At low leverage, adding debt lowers WACC; at high leverage, adding debt raises WACC. This creates a U-shaped curve.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Discuss the key components and assumptions in deriving a discount rate for a DCF: risk-free rate, equity risk premium, size premium, and country risk premium.",a:"Risk-Free Rate: Typically 10-year government bond yield for time value of money. ERP: Additional return demanded for equity vs risk-free assets (typically 5-7%). Beta: Measures systematic risk, multiplied by ERP in CAPM. Size Premium: Small-cap stocks require higher returns (0-3%). Country Risk Premium: Additional return for emerging market or political risk. Cost of Equity = Risk-Free Rate + (Beta x ERP) + Size Premium + Country Risk Premium. WACC blends this with after-tax Cost of Debt.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"What is the difference between DCF and LBO cash flows, from revenue down?",a:"DCF: EBIT x (1 - Tax) + D&A - CapEx - Change in NWC = Unlevered FCF. LBO: Net Income + D&A - CapEx - Change in NWC - Debt service = Levered FCF to equity. UFCF ignores capital structure and is discounted at WACC. LFCF reflects interest expense and principal pay-down, is cash only to equity holders, and feeds an IRR calculation in LBO context.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Revenue is 1000, EBITDA margin 20%, tax rate 20%, depreciation 50, capex 60, inventory up 10, accounts payable up 50. Calculate unlevered free cash flow.",a:"EBITDA = 200. EBIT = 200 - 50 = 150. NOPAT = 150 x (1 - 20%) = 120. Change in NWC = 10 - 50 = -40 (source of cash). UFCF = 120 + 50 - 60 + 40 = 150.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Two companies: 1) Coal company with cash flows going from 100 to 0 over 10 years. 2) Tech company with cash flows going from 0 to 100 over 10 years. FED rate goes from 3% to 8%. Which is valued higher?",a:"At 8%, the coal company may be valued higher. Its cash is front-loaded, so higher discount rates hurt less. Tech's long-duration cash flows get heavily discounted, crushing terminal value. At low rates the result reverses; duration drives sensitivity.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you determine the cost of equity for a gold mine, and what would be unusual about its beta?",a:"Apply CAPM using un-levered average of publicly traded gold-miner betas, then re-lever for target capital structure. The beta is often low or even slightly negative because gold prices can move counter-cyclically to equities.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How do you incorporate considerations of risk into a DCF analysis?",a:"1) Discount Rate (WACC): Higher risk means higher WACC and lower valuation. 2) Cash Flow Projections: Conservative assumptions for uncertain scenarios. 3) Terminal Growth Rate: Lower rates reflect maturity and competitive pressures. 4) Scenario Analysis: Base, upside, downside cases. 5) Probability Weighting: Assign probabilities to scenarios. 6) Sensitivity Analysis: Test impact of key variables.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Walk me through how you would perform a DCF valuation for a gold mine.",a:"1) Forecast Production: Annual gold ounces based on reserves, extraction rates, mine life. 2) Gold Price Assumptions from spot, futures curve, or long-term average. 3) Revenue = production x price. 4) Operating Costs per ounce plus capital expenditures. 5) Calculate Unlevered FCF. 6) Discount at WACC reflecting mining sector risk and commodity volatility. 7) Terminal Value: Typically zero (finite reserves) or residual land value. 8) Sum discounted cash flows for NPV.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company has a changing capital structure over the forecast period, should you use levered or unlevered FCF?",a:"Use unlevered FCF (FCFF). It isolates operating performance from financing decisions. When capital structure changes, levered FCF becomes inconsistent. By using UFCF and WACC, you value the enterprise independent of capital structure changes. The changing debt levels are captured in WACC, which should be updated annually. Alternatively, levered FCF with changing cost of equity works but is more complex.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If given a 100-year DCF, what would you expect about CAPEX and D&A at the 100th year?",a:"They should converge: maintenance CAPEX approximately equals D&A, both growing at or below inflation, reflecting a steady-state business with no incremental growth spend.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Which depreciation method results in a higher DCF valuation: straight-line or accelerated?",a:"Accelerated depreciation results in higher DCF valuation. It front-loads tax deductions, creating larger tax shields in earlier years. This increases near-term FCF, which are more valuable due to time value of money. While total depreciation over the asset's life is identical, the present value of tax savings is higher with accelerated depreciation.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would your DCF approach differ for a Starbucks on a college campus, in a downtown city area, and in an airport terminal?",a:"College campus: Seasonal demand (lower during breaks), predictable customer base, moderate pricing. Forecast adjusted for academic calendar. Downtown city: Steady weekday traffic, commuter-driven, premium pricing. Higher rent, stable cash flows. Airport terminal: High volume, captive customers, premium pricing. Volatile based on flight schedules. Very high rent and operating costs. Supply-Side Constraints differ: campus has university contract restrictions, downtown has commercial leases and zoning, airport has concession agreements and strict schedules.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Comparing a management consulting firm (asset-light) and a heavy manufacturing firm (capital-intensive) with the same EBITDA. Which DCF yields higher valuation?",a:"The consulting firm would have higher DCF valuation. Lower CapEx means higher FCF despite same EBITDA. Less working capital investment needed. Higher cash conversion ratio. Lower reinvestment needs. The manufacturing firm requires significant ongoing CapEx for equipment, reducing FCF available to equity holders.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"3 places taxes affect the DCF? How does each get affected if taxes increase?",a:"NOPAT in FCF, higher taxes cut NOPAT and FCF. Cost of Debt, higher taxes increase the shield, lowering the after-tax cost and WACC. Levered Beta. Conversion from Unlevered to Levered. Overall, FCF falls and the discount rate may fall; valuation typically declines.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"In a DCF, where is idiosyncratic (company-specific) risk accounted for: numerator or denominator?",a:"Primarily in the numerator through probability-weighted cash flow projections and scenario analysis. The denominator (WACC) reflects systematic market risk via beta, not company-specific risk. Under CAPM theory, idiosyncratic risk can be diversified away and is not priced in the discount rate.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would you adjust a DCF for a major economic shock (e.g., a global pandemic)?",a:"Near-term: Model severe revenue declines, adjust margins for disruptions, incorporate government support, extend recovery period, increase discount rate. Terminal growth rate: Typically unchanged if shock is temporary. Reduce if shock permanently impairs industry (e.g., retail shift to e-commerce). Consider scenario analysis with multiple terminal assumptions.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"How would an increase in employee stock-based compensation impact unlevered free cash flow?",a:"Mechanically, SBC is non-cash so it's added back in UFCF calculation, which increases reported UFCF. However, many practitioners prefer to treat SBC as a cash expense (do not add it back) to reflect real economic dilution to shareholders, resulting in lower UFCF.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"Company A and B are identical except A has a terminal multiple of 20x EBITDA and B has 12x. What could justify this?",a:"Higher expected perpetual growth beyond forecast period. Superior competitive positioning or sustainable advantages. Lower risk profile or more stable cash flows. Better management or governance. More attractive industry dynamics. Higher barriers to entry or network effects. Better capital efficiency or higher ROIC. Lower capital intensity or working capital requirements.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A pre-revenue startup takes 20 years to reach maturity. Boss asks for a 5-year DCF. What are the challenges? What methods could you use instead?",a:"DCF Challenges: No historical financials, high uncertainty (5-year forecast misses most value creation), terminal value would be nearly 100% of value, and discount rate is hard to determine with no comparable betas. Alternative Methods: Venture Capital Method (value at exit, discount back at target IRR), Precedent Transactions, Comparable Company Analysis using EV/Revenue or EV/Users, Scorecard/Checklist Method adjusting average startup valuations by qualitative factors.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"If a company only gave you one year of financials, how would you calculate FCF for the remaining four years of a DCF?",a:"Use the actuals for year 1. Then apply logical assumptions or benchmarks for years 2-5: industry growth rates, historical trends, management guidance. Project revenue growth, operating margins, and capex assumptions. Forecast free cash flows and discount them back.",category:"DCF",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A PE firm acquires a company for 10.0x EBITDA. EBITDA = $50M, Debt = 60% of purchase price, EBITDA grows 8% annually for 5 years, Exit multiple = 10.0x, All excess cash flow goes to debt paydown, Debt at exit = $120M. What is the sponsor's MOIC?",a:"Entry EV = 10 x 50 = $500M. Debt = 60% x 500 = $300M. Equity = $200M. Exit EBITDA = 50 x (1.08)^5 = $73.5M. Exit EV = 10 x 73.5 = $735M. Equity Value at Exit = 735 - 120 = $615M. MOIC = 615 / 200 = 3.1x.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company is purchased for $800M EV using 50% debt, 50% equity. After 4 years, EV = $1.1B, remaining debt = $250M. What is the equity IRR?",a:"Initial Equity = $400M. Exit Equity = 1,100 - 250 = $850M. MOIC = 850 / 400 = 2.125x. Using the MOIC-to-IRR approximation for 4 years: IRR = (2.125)^(1/4) - 1 = approximately 20.8%.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A sponsor buys a business at 12x EBITDA. EBITDA = $40M, EBITDA margin stays constant, Revenue grows from $200M to $320M over 5 years, Exit multiple contracts to 10x, Debt at entry = $300M, Debt at exit = $100M. What is the equity value at exit?",a:"Initial EBITDA margin = 40 / 200 = 20%. Exit EBITDA = 20% x 320 = $64M. Exit EV = 10 x 64 = $640M. Exit Equity Value = 640 - 100 = $540M. Note that despite multiple contraction from 12x to 10x, EBITDA growth and debt paydown still created significant equity value.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A PE firm acquires a company for 9x EBITDA. EBITDA = $70M, Purchase funded with 70% debt. EBITDA grows to $90M by exit. Exit multiple = 8x. Remaining debt = $250M. What is the sponsor MOIC?",a:"Entry EV = 9 x 70 = $630M. Debt = 70% x 630 = $441M. Equity = $189M. Exit EV = 8 x 90 = $720M. Exit Equity = 720 - 250 = $470M. MOIC = 470 / 189 = 2.5x. Despite multiple contraction from 9x to 8x, EBITDA growth and debt paydown drove a strong return.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company generates EBITDA = $100M, Capex = $20M, Cash taxes = $15M, Interest expense = $25M, Change in NWC = $10M outflow. What is annual cash flow available for debt paydown?",a:"Free Cash Flow for Debt Paydown = EBITDA - Capex - Cash Taxes - Interest - Change in NWC = 100 - 20 - 15 - 25 - 10 = $30M per year. This is the levered free cash flow that can be used for mandatory amortization and optional prepayments.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A PE firm buys a company for 11x EBITDA. EBITDA = $60M. Debt = $400M. After 5 years: EBITDA = $90M, Exit multiple = 12x, Debt fully paid off. What is the sponsor MOIC?",a:"Entry EV = 11 x 60 = $660M. Equity = 660 - 400 = $260M. Exit EV = 12 x 90 = $1,080M. Debt at exit = $0. Exit Equity = $1,080M. MOIC = 1,080 / 260 = 4.2x. This is a home run driven by all three LBO value levers: EBITDA growth (50%), multiple expansion (11x to 12x), and full debt paydown.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company is purchased for $1.2B EV using $700M debt and $500M equity. Five years later, sold for $1.5B EV with $300M debt remaining. What is the sponsor profit?",a:"Exit Equity = 1,500 - 300 = $1,200M. Sponsor Profit = Exit Equity - Initial Equity = 1,200 - 500 = $700M. MOIC = 1,200 / 500 = 2.4x.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A sponsor buys a company with Revenue = $500M, EBITDA margin = 25%, Entry multiple = 8x EBITDA. Revenue grows 10% annually for 3 years. Margin expands to 30%. Exit multiple = 9x. What is exit enterprise value?",a:"Initial EBITDA = 25% x 500 = $125M. Exit Revenue = 500 x (1.10)^3 = $665.5M. Exit EBITDA = 30% x 665.5 = $199.7M. Exit EV = 9 x 199.7 = approximately $1.80B. Value creation driven by revenue growth, margin expansion, and multiple expansion.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
{q:"A company has beginning debt = $350M, mandatory amortization = $20M annually, excess cash flow sweep = $15M annually. How much debt remains after 5 years?",a:"Annual Debt Paydown = Mandatory Amort + Cash Sweep = 20 + 15 = $35M per year. Total Paydown over 5 years = 35 x 5 = $175M. Remaining Debt = 350 - 175 = $175M.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Intermediate"},
{q:"A PE firm acquires a business for EV = $900M, Debt = 65% of EV. After 5 years: Exit EV = $1.3B, Debt balance = $250M. What is the equity IRR?",a:"Initial Debt = 65% x 900 = $585M. Initial Equity = 900 - 585 = $315M. Exit Equity = 1,300 - 250 = $1,050M. MOIC = 1,050 / 315 = 3.33x. 5-year IRR using MOIC approximation: (3.33)^(1/5) - 1 = approximately 27%.",category:"LBO",difficulty:"Advanced"},
// New original cards. Standard analyst-interview caliber, written from the
// underlying accounting rather than adapted from any existing question set.
{q:"Depreciation increases by $25. Tax rate is 20%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $25 of depreciation is an expense, so pre-tax income falls $25. At 20% the tax bill drops $5, so net income falls $20.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $20. Depreciation never cost cash, so add the full $25 back. Cash rises $5.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $5 and PP&E is down $25, so assets fall $20. Retained earnings fall $20 and both sides balance.\n\nThe point: the $5 of cash is the tax you avoided. Depreciation is the cleanest example of an expense that lowers earnings and raises cash.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why does a non-cash expense change the cash balance at all?",a:"Because it is tax-deductible. The expense itself moves no money, but it lowers taxable income, and tax is paid in real cash.\n\nSo the cash effect of any non-cash charge is the charge multiplied by the tax rate. A $100 write-down at a 25% rate leaves the company with $25 more cash than it would have had.\n\nThe point: if there were no taxes, non-cash charges would have zero cash impact. Tax is the only channel through which they touch cash.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Accrued expenses rise by $40 and the expense is being recognized now. Tax rate is 20%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $40 is recognized as an expense even though nothing has been paid, so pre-tax income falls $40. Tax drops $8, leaving net income down $32.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $32. The accrued liability rose $40, and an expense booked but not paid is a source of cash, so add $40 back. Cash rises $8.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $8, accrued liabilities are up $40, retained earnings are down $32. Liabilities plus equity are up $8, matching cash.\n\nThe point: the company recorded a cost and its cash went up, because the only money that moved was the tax it saved.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Inventory rises by $25, purchased on credit. What happens to the three statements?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Inventory sits as an asset until it sells and becomes COGS.\n\nCash flow statement. Inventory rising is a use of cash, so subtract $25. Payables rising is a source of cash, so add $25. They cancel, and net cash does not move.\n\nBalance sheet. Inventory is up $25 and accounts payable are up $25. Assets and liabilities both rise $25.\n\nThe point: buying on credit means no cash leaves yet. Compare this with paying cash, where cash would fall $25 and the balance sheet would just swap one asset for another.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company records $60 of revenue but the customer has not paid. COGS is $35. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Revenue is up $60 and COGS is up $35, so gross profit is $25. Tax of $6.25 leaves net income up $18.75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $18.75. Receivables rose $60, a use of cash, so subtract $60. Inventory fell $35, a source of cash, so add $35. Net cash falls $6.25.\n\nBalance sheet. Receivables are up $60, inventory is down $35, cash is down $6.25, so assets rise $18.75. Retained earnings rise $18.75.\n\nThe point: a profitable sale that drained cash. The tax is due now and the customer has not paid, which is exactly how growing companies run out of money.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company writes off $50 of goodwill. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. A $50 impairment cuts pre-tax income $50. The tax benefit of $12.50 leaves net income down $37.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $37.50. The charge is non-cash, so add the $50 back. Cash rises $12.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $12.50 and goodwill is down $50, so assets fall $37.50. Retained earnings fall $37.50.\n\nThe point: goodwill only exists because someone paid above fair value. Writing it off is management admitting the deal disappointed. No cash leaves, and cash actually rises by the tax benefit.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company pays a $45 cash dividend. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. A dividend is a distribution of already-taxed profit, not a cost of running the business.\n\nCash flow statement. A $45 outflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $45 and retained earnings are down $45.\n\nThe point: dividends bypass the income statement entirely and reduce equity directly. That is the structural difference between paying lenders, which is a deductible expense, and paying owners, which is not.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company repays $150 of debt principal plus $15 of interest. Tax rate is 20%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Only the interest appears. The $15 cuts pre-tax income $15, tax falls $3, so net income falls $12. The principal never touches the income statement.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $12, which already carries the interest paid. The $150 of principal is a financing outflow. Net cash falls $162.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $162, debt is down $150, retained earnings are down $12. Assets fall $162 and liabilities plus equity fall $162.\n\nThe point: earnings fell $12 and cash fell $162. Principal repayment is real money that never shows up in net income, which is why a profitable company can still be strangled by its amortization schedule.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What happens to the three statements when a company issues $80 of stock to raise money?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Money from owners is never revenue.\n\nCash flow statement. An $80 inflow in financing.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $80 and equity is up $80, split between common stock at par and APIC for the remainder.\n\nThe point: this is the most common trap in a statements question. The company obviously has more money, so people want to run it through the income statement. Revenue comes from customers, not from investors.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company capitalizes $40 of costs that it could have expensed. Tax rate is 25%. How do the statements differ from expensing?",a:"If capitalized. Nothing hits the income statement, so net income is unchanged. The $40 leaves as an investing outflow and a $40 asset appears, which then amortizes over future years.\n\nIf expensed. Pre-tax income falls $40 and net income falls $30 after the tax benefit. Cash falls $30, since the deduction offsets part of the outlay.\n\nThe point: identical cash out, in the same amount, on the same day. Capitalizing reports higher earnings now, stronger operating cash flow, and a drag later. It is why a jump in capitalized costs is always worth a second look.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Bad debt expense of $20 is recorded by increasing the allowance. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $20 expense cuts pre-tax income $20. Tax falls $5, leaving net income down $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $15. The allowance is an estimate, not a payment, so add the $20 back. Cash rises $5.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $5, the allowance rises so net receivables fall $20, and retained earnings fall $15.\n\nThe point: the company is predicting some customers will not pay and taking the hit now. Because it is management's estimate, the allowance is a known lever for smoothing earnings.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A customer prepays $75 for work to be done next quarter. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Cash has arrived but nothing has been earned.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash rises $75, shown as an increase in deferred revenue within operating.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $75 and deferred revenue, a liability, is up $75. It is a liability because the company owes the customer the work.\n\nThe point: this is the best cash a business can take in, money before delivery. It is also why deferred revenue is the most watched line at any subscription company.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has a $400M market cap, $250M of debt, $50M of cash, and $30M of preferred stock. What is its enterprise value?",a:"$630M. Start at the $400M market cap, add the $250M of debt, add the $30M of preferred, and subtract the $50M of cash.\n\nThe logic. Enterprise value is what the whole business is worth to every capital provider. You add debt and preferred because a buyer inherits those claims. You subtract cash because a buyer gets the cash back the moment the deal closes, so it effectively reduces the price.\n\nThe point: equity value is what the shareholders own. Enterprise value is what the business itself is worth, independent of how it was financed.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do you subtract cash when calculating enterprise value?",a:"Because a buyer gets the cash. If you pay $400M for a company holding $50M of cash, you have really paid $350M for the operations, since the cash comes straight back to you.\n\nThe cleaner reasoning is that cash is a non-operating asset. Enterprise value is meant to capture what the core business is worth, and cash sitting in the bank is not part of the operations.\n\nThe point: strictly you should only subtract excess cash, the amount above what the business needs to run day to day. In practice most people subtract all of it, which is a simplification worth knowing.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has 80 million shares at $25 and 8 million options with a $15 strike. What is its fully diluted equity value?",a:"$2,080M. Start with the basic equity value: 80 million shares times $25 is $2,000M.\n\nThe options are in the money, $15 strike against a $25 price, so assume they are exercised. That creates 8 million new shares. But the holders have to pay the company the strike, 8 million times $15, which is $120M. The company uses that cash to buy shares back at the market price of $25, retiring $120M divided by $25, or 4.8 million shares.\n\nNet new shares are 8 million less 4.8 million, or 3.2 million. Diluted shares are 83.2 million, and at $25 that is $2,080M.\n\nThe point: this is the treasury stock method. The company does not hand out shares for free, it collects the strike price and buys stock back with it, so real dilution is always smaller than the raw option count suggests.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Can enterprise value be negative? What would that tell you?",a:"Yes. It happens when cash exceeds the market cap plus debt, which usually means either a very large cash pile or a collapsed share price.\n\nWhat it tells you. Either the market thinks the operations are worth less than nothing, meaning it expects the business to burn the cash, or the company is in distress and the equity is pricing in bankruptcy.\n\nThe point: a negative enterprise value looks like free money on a screen and almost never is. The market is usually saying the cash will not survive contact with the business.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do you add noncontrolling interest to get to enterprise value?",a:"Because of consolidation. If a company owns more than 50% of a subsidiary, accounting rules make it report 100% of that subsidiary's revenue and EBITDA, even though it does not own all of it.\n\nSo your EBITDA already reflects the whole subsidiary. If you did not add back the minority stake, your multiple would have the full EBITDA in the denominator and only the parent's share of value in the numerator.\n\nThe point: this is an apples-to-apples fix. Whenever the metric includes 100% of something, the value has to include 100% of it too.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the difference between equity value and shareholders' equity?",a:"Equity value is a market number: shares outstanding times the share price. Shareholders' equity is a book number: assets minus liabilities as recorded by the accountants.\n\nThey rarely match. Book value reflects historical cost, and it ignores things like brand and intellectual property that were never purchased. For a healthy company, market value is usually far above book.\n\nThe point: equity value can never be negative, since neither shares nor share price can be. Shareholders' equity can go negative easily, through sustained losses or a debt-funded dividend.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What are the three main valuation methodologies and what does each really measure?",a:"Comparable companies. What the market pays right now for similar businesses. It is a snapshot of sentiment as much as value.\n\nPrecedent transactions. What acquirers actually paid for similar businesses. It includes a control premium, since buying the whole company is worth more than buying a share of it.\n\nDiscounted cash flow. What the business is worth based on the cash it will generate, discounted back to today. It is the only one that does not depend on what anyone else is paying.\n\nThe point: the first two ask what the market says, the third asks what you believe. That is why a DCF is the most defensible in theory and the easiest to manipulate in practice.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Which usually gives a higher value, comparable companies or precedent transactions? Why?",a:"Precedent transactions, usually, because of the control premium. A buyer purchasing an entire company gets to run it: appoint management, change strategy, capture synergies. That control is worth paying for, typically 20% to 30% above the trading price.\n\nComps only tell you what a passive investor pays for a small, non-controlling slice.\n\nThe point: it is a tendency, not a rule. If the M&A deals in your set closed in a distressed period and the public market has since recovered, comps can come out higher.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"When would you not use a DCF?",a:"When you cannot forecast the cash flows with a straight face. That covers early-stage companies with no revenue, biotech waiting on a binary trial outcome, and anything deeply cyclical where the five-year path is a guess.\n\nIt also fails for banks and insurers, because debt is raw material rather than financing for them, and working capital swings dwarf net income. There you use a dividend discount model instead.\n\nThe point: a DCF projects cash flow. If the honest answer to what cash flow looks like in year three is nobody knows, the model manufactures precision it does not have.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"How would you value a company with negative EBITDA?",a:"Move up the income statement to a line that is still positive. EV/Revenue is the usual fallback, since revenue is positive even when profit is not.\n\nIf revenue is also tiny or zero, use whatever drives value in that industry: EV per subscriber, per user, per daily production, per store. The metric should be the thing the business will eventually monetize.\n\nThe point: negative EBITDA does not make a company worthless, it makes profit multiples arithmetically meaningless. A negative denominator produces a negative multiple, which tells you nothing.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why can't you use equity value / EBITDA as a multiple?",a:"Because the numerator and denominator disagree about who they belong to. EBITDA is earnings before interest, so it is the pool of money available to every capital provider, lenders and shareholders alike.\n\nEquity value belongs only to shareholders. Pairing them compares a claim on part of the business against a metric generated by all of it.\n\nThe point: match the metric to the claim. Anything before interest pairs with enterprise value. Anything after interest, like net income, pairs with equity value. That is the whole rule behind EV/EBITDA and P/E.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Two companies are identical but one trades at a higher multiple. What could explain it?",a:"Growth. The market pays more for a company expected to grow faster, since the multiple is a claim on the future, not the present.\n\nRisk. Steadier, more predictable earnings get a higher multiple, because the cash flows are worth more when you trust them.\n\nSomething not in the financials. A patent, a lawsuit just won, a dominant market position, an earnings beat that has not annualized yet, or simply thin trading in a small-cap name.\n\nThe point: a multiple is shorthand for growth and risk. Identical current financials say nothing about either.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is a control premium and why does it exist?",a:"It is the amount an acquirer pays above the current share price to buy the whole company, usually 20% to 30%.\n\nWhy it exists. Buying every share gets you something buying one share never does: the right to control the business. You can replace management, change the strategy, cut costs, and take the synergies. That is worth real money.\n\nThe other half is simply that shareholders will not sell without a reason. If you offer the market price, nobody tenders, because they could already sell at that price.\n\nThe point: the premium is paid for control and for persuasion, and it is why precedent transactions typically print above comps.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"How do you pick comparable companies?",a:"Industry first, and it is not close. A business is comparable when it faces the same demand drivers, the same cost structure, and the same competitive dynamics.\n\nThen size, because a $500M company and a $50B company in the same industry do not trade alike. Then geography, since regulation, growth, and tax differ by market. Then business model, which often matters more than the industry label.\n\nThe point: you are looking for companies whose value is driven by the same forces, not companies with the same SIC code. A software firm selling perpetual licenses is not comparable to one selling subscriptions, however similar they look.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why might you apply a discount when valuing a private company off public comps?",a:"Liquidity. A public share can be sold in seconds at a known price. A private stake can take months to sell, may need buyer approval, and has no observable price.\n\nInvestors will not pay the same for an asset they cannot exit, so the multiple gets discounted, often 10% to 20%.\n\nThe point: you do not apply the same discount to precedent transactions, because those already involve buying an entire private company. Once you own the whole thing, the shares were never liquid to begin with, so there is nothing extra to discount.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Walk me through a DCF.",a:"First, project the company's free cash flow, usually five to ten years out, by forecasting revenue, margins, taxes, capital spending, and working capital.\n\nSecond, discount each year back to today using WACC, which is the blended return every capital provider requires.\n\nThird, calculate terminal value, since the business does not stop in year five. Use either an exit multiple on final-year EBITDA or a perpetuity growth rate. Discount that back too.\n\nFourth, add the discounted cash flows to the discounted terminal value. That gives you enterprise value. Subtract net debt to get to equity value, and divide by shares for a per-share number.\n\nThe point: it is just the idea that a business is worth the cash it will produce, adjusted for the fact that a dollar later is worth less than a dollar now.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"How do you get from revenue to unlevered free cash flow?",a:"Start at revenue, subtract COGS and operating expenses to reach EBIT. Multiply EBIT by one minus the tax rate to get the after-tax operating profit.\n\nThen add back depreciation and amortization, because they reduced EBIT but never took cash. Subtract capital expenditures, which take cash but never touched EBIT. Finally subtract the increase in working capital, since growing receivables and inventory tie cash up.\n\nThe point: it is unlevered because you started at EBIT, which sits above interest. That makes the cash flow available to lenders and shareholders both, which is why it pairs with WACC and produces enterprise value.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do you use WACC as the discount rate?",a:"Because it is the blended cost of every dollar funding the business. If lenders want 6% and shareholders want 10%, and the company is half each, then the business has to earn about 8% just to keep everyone whole.\n\nThat blended rate is the hurdle. Cash flows are discounted at it because anything the business earns above it creates value and anything below destroys it.\n\nThe point: the discount rate has to match the cash flow. Unlevered cash flow belongs to everyone, so it gets discounted at everyone's blended required return. Levered cash flow belongs only to shareholders, so it gets discounted at cost of equity.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"How do you calculate cost of equity?",a:"Risk-free rate plus beta times the equity risk premium.\n\nThe risk-free rate is what you earn with no risk, usually a ten-year government bond. The equity risk premium is the extra return investors demand for holding stocks instead. Beta scales that premium to this specific company: a beta of 1.5 means the stock swings 50% more than the market, so investors want 50% more of the premium.\n\nThe point: it is the rate shareholders require, not the rate the company pays. Nobody sends anyone a cheque for cost of equity, which is exactly why it is easy to underestimate.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do you unlever and relever beta?",a:"Because the beta you look up is contaminated by that company's debt. Leverage amplifies equity risk, so a heavily indebted comp shows a high beta partly because of its balance sheet, not because its business is risky.\n\nUnlevering strips the debt effect out, leaving the risk of the operations alone. You take the median of those clean betas, then relever it at your company's own capital structure.\n\nThe point: you want your comps to tell you how risky the business is, then you apply your own leverage on top. Skipping this imports someone else's balance sheet into your discount rate.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What are the two ways to calculate terminal value and which do bankers prefer?",a:"Exit multiple. Apply a multiple, usually EV/EBITDA, to the final projected year, as though you sold the business then. Bankers prefer this, because the multiple comes from observable comps.\n\nPerpetuity growth. Assume cash flow grows forever at a modest rate and capitalize it: final year cash flow times one plus the growth rate, divided by the discount rate minus the growth rate.\n\nThe point: they are two ways of saying the same thing, and you should cross-check one against the other. If your exit multiple implies a 6% perpetual growth rate, your assumption is broken, because nothing grows faster than the economy forever.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is a reasonable perpetuity growth rate and why?",a:"Somewhere between the rate of inflation and long-term GDP growth, so roughly 2% to 3% in a developed economy.\n\nThe reason is arithmetic. Any company growing faster than the economy forever eventually becomes the entire economy. That cannot happen, so a growth rate above long-term GDP is not conservative or aggressive, it is impossible.\n\nThe point: this assumption drives most of the value in a DCF and people pick it casually. Moving it from 2% to 3% can swing the valuation 15% or more, which is why you always show a sensitivity range.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Your terminal value is 85% of your DCF value. Is that a problem?",a:"It is a warning sign, not automatically an error. It means almost none of the value comes from the years you actually forecast, so the model is really one assumption wearing a disguise.\n\nContext matters. Terminal value being 60% to 75% of the total is normal, since most of a company's life lies beyond year five. At 85% and above, the projections are doing no work.\n\nThe point: the honest response is to check whether the exit multiple and the implied growth rate agree, and to widen the sensitivity table. Do not pretend the forecast is driving the answer when it is not.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What has a bigger effect on a DCF, a 1% change in the discount rate or a 1% change in revenue growth?",a:"Usually the discount rate, because it compounds against every year and against the terminal value, which is most of the value.\n\nA 1% revenue change flows down to cash flow scaled by the margin, so a 10% margin business only sees a tenth of it. The discount rate hits the whole stream.\n\nThe point: it depends on the business. For a high-margin, high-growth company, revenue can dominate. The instinct to check is which assumption touches the terminal value hardest, because that is where the value lives.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Two identical companies, one has debt and one does not. Which has the higher WACC?",a:"The one without debt, in almost every case.\n\nDebt is cheaper than equity for two reasons. Lenders get paid first in a bankruptcy, so they take less risk and demand less return. And interest is tax-deductible, so the government subsidizes part of the cost, which is the one minus tax rate term in the formula.\n\nThe point: adding cheap debt pulls the blend down. That only holds up to a point. Load enough debt on and both lenders and shareholders start demanding more for the added default risk, and WACC turns back up. The bottom of that curve is the optimal capital structure.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is the relationship between debt and cost of equity?",a:"More debt raises cost of equity. Shareholders are last in line, so every dollar of debt ahead of them makes their claim riskier and their returns more volatile.\n\nMechanically this runs through levered beta. Relevering at a higher debt-to-equity ratio raises beta, which raises cost of equity.\n\nThe point: this is why adding debt does not lower WACC forever. Debt is cheaper, but it makes the equity underneath it more expensive, and eventually the second effect wins.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Walk me through a merger model.",a:"First, set the assumptions: what price is being paid, and what mix of cash, stock, and debt is funding it.\n\nSecond, build a sources and uses to see where the money comes from and where it goes, including fees and any debt being refinanced.\n\nThird, project each company's income statement separately, then combine them line by line.\n\nFourth, layer in the deal effects: interest lost on the cash spent, interest paid on new debt, new shares issued, amortization of any written-up intangibles, and synergies.\n\nFifth, tax the combined pre-tax income at the buyer's rate, divide by the new share count, and compare the combined EPS with the buyer's standalone EPS.\n\nThe point: the whole model exists to answer one question, does the buyer's EPS go up or down. Everything else is machinery.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What makes an acquisition accretive or dilutive?",a:"Compare what the buyer gets against what it gives up. It gets the seller's earnings plus any synergies. It gives up interest on the cash it spent, interest on the debt it raised, and earnings per share diluted across new shares issued.\n\nIf what it gains exceeds what it gives up, EPS rises and the deal is accretive. If not, it is dilutive.\n\nThe point: accretion is not the same as value creation. A buyer can overpay wildly and still print higher EPS by funding with cheap debt. It is an accounting outcome, not a verdict on the deal.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"In an all-stock deal, how can you tell instantly whether it will be accretive?",a:"Compare the P/E multiples. If the buyer's P/E is higher than the seller's, the deal is accretive. If it is lower, dilutive. If they match, neutral.\n\nThe intuition. Your P/E is the price the market puts on your earnings. If you trade at 20x and buy someone at 15x, you are buying earnings more cheaply than the market values your own, so every share you issue brings back more earnings than it gives away.\n\nThe point: this shortcut only works for all-stock deals. Introduce cash or debt and it breaks, because then you are comparing the seller's earnings yield against an interest rate instead of against your own P/E.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A buyer with a 20x P/E acquires a seller at 25x in an all-stock deal. What happens to EPS?",a:"It falls. The buyer is paying 25 times earnings using stock the market values at 20 times earnings, so it is issuing cheap currency to buy expensive earnings.\n\nPut differently, the seller's earnings yield is 4% (one over 25) and the buyer's is 5% (one over 20). Every share issued gives up more earnings than it brings in.\n\nThe point: the deal can still be right. If the target grows much faster, near-term dilution reverses within a couple of years, which is the standard defense when a buyer announces a dilutive deal and the stock falls anyway.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why would a buyer use stock instead of cash even when it has the cash?",a:"Because its shares are expensive. If the market is valuing the buyer richly, stock is cheap currency and it makes sense to spend it rather than cash.\n\nOther reasons. The cheque may simply be too large. Management may want to keep the cash cushion for a downturn. Or the buyer may want the seller's shareholders to hold stock, so they share the risk that the promised synergies never appear.\n\nThe point: it is a signal worth reading. Buyers tend to pay in stock when they think their stock is overvalued, which is why the market often marks the buyer down on an all-stock announcement.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What are synergies and which type do people actually believe?",a:"Cost synergies are savings from combining: closing duplicate offices, eliminating overlapping roles, consolidating suppliers. They are countable, so you can point to a building and a headcount.\n\nRevenue synergies are extra sales from the combination: selling your product to their customers, entering their markets. They are the ones nobody believes.\n\nThe point: cost synergies are believed because you can name the line item you are cutting. Revenue synergies require customers to behave the way a spreadsheet says they will, which they rarely do. Most deals that fail, fail on revenue synergies that never materialized.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why does goodwill get created in an acquisition?",a:"Because buyers pay more than the fair value of the identifiable net assets. You buy a company for $500M whose assets minus liabilities are worth $300M at fair value. The extra $200M has to go somewhere, or the balance sheet stops balancing.\n\nThat $200M is goodwill. It represents what you paid for that is real but not separately recordable: the brand, the customer relationships, the workforce, the position in the market.\n\nThe point: goodwill is a plug, but not a meaningless one. It is the price of everything valuable that accounting cannot put a line item on.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the difference between goodwill and other intangible assets?",a:"Other intangibles are things you can identify and value on their own: a patent, a customer list, a trade name, a licence. They have finite lives, so they amortize, and that amortization hits the income statement every year.\n\nGoodwill is the residual, everything left over that you cannot point at individually. It does not amortize. It sits there until an impairment test says it is worth less than the books claim.\n\nThe point: the split matters to the buyer's earnings. Allocate more of the purchase price to identifiable intangibles and you create years of amortization drag. Allocate more to goodwill and reported earnings look better until the day you impair it.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company is acquired for $800M. Its book value is $500M and its assets are written up by $100M. Tax rate is 25%. How much goodwill is created?",a:"$225M. Work through it in order.\n\nStart with the $800M purchase price and remove the $500M of book value you are buying, leaving $300M of excess.\n\nThe $100M asset write-up absorbs part of that excess, because it is a real asset now on the balance sheet, so subtract it. That leaves $200M.\n\nBut writing up assets creates a deferred tax liability, because you get more depreciation for book purposes than the tax authority allows. That DTL is $100M times 25%, or $25M. A new liability needs an offsetting asset, so add it back: $200M plus $25M is $225M.\n\nThe point: goodwill is whatever makes the balance sheet balance after every other adjustment is booked. It is calculated last, not first.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do deferred tax liabilities get created in an acquisition?",a:"Because the books and the tax authority start disagreeing. When you write an asset up in a deal, its book value rises, so book depreciation rises with it. But in a stock purchase the tax basis does not change, so tax depreciation stays where it was.\n\nThat means the company reports lower book profit than taxable profit, so it will pay more cash tax than the books suggest, for years. That future extra tax is a liability today.\n\nThe point: a DTL is not a tax bill, it is a timing difference. The write-up gave you book depreciation you cannot deduct, so you owe the difference over the asset's life.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the difference between a stock purchase and an asset purchase?",a:"In a stock purchase, the buyer takes the whole legal entity: every asset, every liability, including the ones nobody knew about. The tax basis of the assets carries over unchanged, so no step-up and no extra depreciation. The seller pays capital gains once.\n\nIn an asset purchase, the buyer picks exactly which assets it wants and which liabilities it will assume. It gets a stepped-up tax basis, so it can depreciate the assets at their new value and save real cash tax. The seller is taxed twice: at the company level on the gain, then again on the proceeds.\n\nThe point: buyers want asset deals for the tax step-up and the ability to leave liabilities behind. Sellers want stock deals to avoid double tax and to walk away clean. That tension gets priced into the deal.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do most acquisitions fail?",a:"Because integration is harder than the model. Two companies with different systems, incentives, and cultures do not merge because a spreadsheet says they should.\n\nThe synergies get missed, particularly revenue synergies, which were optimistic to begin with. Key people leave once their equity vests. And the price often already assumed everything would go right, so there was no margin for anything going wrong.\n\nThe point: many deals are done for reasons that never appear in the model. CEO ambition, pressure to look active, fear of being left behind. A deal built on those does not fail because the numbers were wrong. The numbers were decoration.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is an earnout and why would a buyer want one?",a:"Deferred payment tied to future performance. The buyer pays part now and the rest only if the business hits agreed targets, say $20M more if revenue reaches $100M in two years.\n\nIt exists to bridge disagreement about value. The seller says the business is about to take off, the buyer is not convinced. Rather than argue, they let the future settle it.\n\nThe point: it also keeps the seller's management working. It is most common with private companies and founders, and almost unheard of with public sellers, because public shareholders want a clean price and an exit, not a bet on the next two years.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Walk me through an LBO.",a:"First, set assumptions: purchase price, how much debt versus sponsor equity, interest rates, and how the business performs.\n\nSecond, build sources and uses. Sources are the debt raised plus the equity the sponsor writes a cheque for. Uses are the purchase price, refinanced debt, and fees. The equity is the plug.\n\nThird, adjust the balance sheet for the new capital structure and create goodwill to make it balance.\n\nFourth, project the business, and critically, track the debt: how much cash is generated, how much interest is owed, and how much principal gets paid down each year.\n\nFifth, assume an exit, usually a multiple of the final year's EBITDA. Subtract remaining debt to get the equity proceeds, and compare that with the equity put in to get the IRR.\n\nThe point: the sponsor makes money three ways, growing EBITDA, paying down debt with the company's own cash, and selling at a higher multiple than it paid.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why does using debt increase returns in an LBO?",a:"Because it shrinks the cheque you write. Buy a $1,000 company with $1,000 of your own money, sell for $1,500, and you made $500 on $1,000, a 50% return.\n\nBuy the same company with $300 of equity and $700 of debt. Suppose the business paid down $200 of debt along the way. At the same $1,500 exit you repay the remaining $500 and keep $1,000, having invested $300. That is more than three times your money on the same company at the same exit.\n\nThe point: leverage does not make the company better, it concentrates the same gain onto a smaller base. It works identically in reverse, which is why a modest miss on EBITDA can wipe out the equity entirely.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What variables matter most to LBO returns?",a:"Entry and exit multiples, by a wide margin. Buying at 8x and selling at 10x creates value out of nothing; buying at 10x and selling at 8x can destroy an otherwise good deal.\n\nThen leverage, since it sets the size of the equity cheque. Then EBITDA growth. Then how much debt gets paid down, which is really a function of cash conversion.\n\nThe point: the uncomfortable truth is that the two biggest drivers, entry and exit multiples, are the two the sponsor controls least. Exit multiple depends on the market five years out, which is why underwriting multiple expansion is considered a mark of a bad investment case.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why is an LBO sometimes called a floor valuation?",a:"Because a financial sponsor can generally pay less than a strategic buyer. The sponsor has no synergies. It cannot fold the target into an existing business or fire the duplicate finance department, so the target is worth only its standalone cash flow.\n\nA strategic buyer can pay for the target plus the synergies, so it can go higher and still earn its return.\n\nThe point: an LBO tells you roughly the lowest credible price in a competitive process, since a sponsor will always bid up to its IRR hurdle and stop. That sets the floor a strategic has to clear.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the difference between bank debt and high-yield debt?",a:"Bank debt is cheaper, secured, and floating rate. It amortizes, so principal comes down over time, and it carries maintenance covenants, which are tested every quarter and require the company to keep ratios inside a limit.\n\nHigh-yield is more expensive, usually unsecured and fixed rate. It is bullet maturity, so nothing is repaid until the end, and it carries incurrence covenants, which only bite when the company actively does something like raising more debt or paying a dividend.\n\nThe point: the real trade is flexibility against cost. Bank debt is cheap and watches you constantly. High-yield costs more and leaves you alone. A sponsor planning heavy investment often pays up for the freedom.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the difference between a maintenance covenant and an incurrence covenant?",a:"A maintenance covenant is tested regularly whether you do anything or not. Keep leverage under 5x, tested quarterly. Miss it and you are in default even if you have paid every dollar on time.\n\nAn incurrence covenant only triggers when you take an action: raising debt, selling an asset, paying a dividend. Do nothing and it never binds.\n\nThe point: maintenance covenants are an early warning system for lenders, which is why bank debt has them. They turn a bad quarter into a negotiation, which is exactly what a lender wants and exactly what a sponsor does not.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a dividend recap and why is it controversial?",a:"The company borrows money and pays the proceeds straight out to its private equity owner as a dividend. The business gains nothing; it simply carries more debt.\n\nIt boosts returns because the sponsor pulls its capital back early. Returns are measured against invested equity, and getting cash back sooner improves the IRR even if the eventual exit is unchanged.\n\nThe point: it is controversial because the risk and the reward split. The sponsor takes cash off the table while the company carries the debt, so if things then go wrong, lenders and employees absorb it. Credit agreements restrict it for exactly this reason.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the tax shield in an LBO and why does it matter?",a:"Interest is tax-deductible, so every dollar of interest reduces taxable income and cuts the cash tax bill. At a 25% rate, $100 of interest saves $25 of tax, so the true cost of that interest is $75.\n\nIt matters because it makes debt structurally cheaper than equity. Dividends to shareholders get no deduction at all; interest to lenders does.\n\nThe point: the shield reduces the cost of debt, it does not make debt free. The company still writes the interest cheque, and cash flow is still lower than it would be with no debt at all. The government just pays a quarter of it.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A sponsor buys a company for $500M at 10x EBITDA using $350M of debt. In five years EBITDA grows to $70M, $150M of debt is repaid, and it exits at 9x. What is the equity multiple?",a:"About 2.9x. Walk through it in order.\n\nEntry. A $500M price at 10x means EBITDA was $50M. With $350M of debt, the sponsor wrote a $150M equity cheque.\n\nExit. EBITDA of $70M at 9x is $630M of enterprise value. Debt is $350M less the $150M repaid, so $200M remains. Equity proceeds are $630M less $200M, or $430M.\n\nReturn. $430M divided by the $150M invested is 2.9x over five years, which is roughly a 24% IRR.\n\nThe point: the multiple moved against them, 10x in and 9x out, and the deal still returned nearly 3x. EBITDA growth and debt paydown did all the work. That is what a sponsor means when they say they do not underwrite multiple expansion.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why would a private equity firm buy a business in a boring industry?",a:"Because boring means predictable, and predictable is what services debt. Waste collection, pest control, and industrial distribution are unglamorous and utterly reliable, which is exactly what leverage requires.\n\nBoring industries are also often fragmented, which enables a roll-up: buy one platform, bolt on small competitors at lower multiples, and sell the combined business at a higher multiple purely because it is bigger.\n\nThe point: sponsors are not buying excitement, they are buying cash flow they can borrow against. A dull business with contracted revenue is worth more to them than an exciting one that might not be there in three years.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"How does a private equity firm actually make money on a deal?",a:"Three levers, and you should be able to separate them.\n\nEBITDA growth. Grow revenue or margin so the business is simply worth more at the same multiple.\n\nDebt paydown. The company uses its own cash to repay debt. Every dollar repaid converts directly into equity value, without the enterprise value moving at all.\n\nMultiple expansion. Sell at a higher multiple than you paid, from timing, scale, or a better story.\n\nThe point: the first two are things you can control, the third is the market. Good sponsors underwrite the first two and treat the third as upside, because a deal that only works on multiple expansion is a bet on conditions five years out.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"You are screening a list of companies for a buyout. What disqualifies one immediately?",a:"Volatile cash flow. Debt payments are fixed and the business must cover them in a bad year, not an average one. Anything cyclical, project-based, or dependent on one contract fails here first.\n\nHeavy capital needs. If the business must spend constantly on equipment just to stand still, that cash cannot service debt.\n\nCustomer concentration. One client at 40% of revenue is one phone call away from a covenant breach.\n\nNo exit. If nobody obvious buys this in five years, the returns are theoretical.\n\nThe point: sponsors are not screening for the best business, they are screening for the most financeable one. A great company with lumpy cash is a worse LBO than a mediocre one with contracted revenue.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is working capital and what does it tell you?",a:"Current assets minus current liabilities. In a model, bankers usually strip out cash and debt to get operating working capital, since those relate to financing rather than operations.\n\nWhat it tells you. It is how much cash is tied up in running the business: money sitting in inventory and in receivables that customers have not paid, offset by money you owe suppliers but have not paid yet.\n\nThe point: it is a use of cash when it grows. Every dollar more inventory is a dollar you have spent and not yet recovered. That is why fast-growing companies with positive working capital burn cash even while profitable.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Is negative working capital a bad sign?",a:"Usually the opposite. It means suppliers and customers are funding the business. McDonald's, Amazon, and most subscription companies run negative working capital because customers pay upfront and suppliers get paid later.\n\nIt is only alarming when it comes from distress: the company is stretching payables because it cannot pay, or has drawn its revolver into current liabilities.\n\nThe point: the sign tells you nothing on its own. What matters is why. Negative because customers prepay is a business model. Negative because you are dodging suppliers is a countdown.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Can shareholders' equity be negative? What causes it?",a:"Yes, and it is more common than people expect. Two normal causes.\n\nSustained losses. Retained earnings are cumulative. Enough loss-making years and the balance turns negative and drags total equity with it.\n\nDebt-funded distributions. A company borrows and pays the proceeds out as a dividend, or buys back so much stock that treasury stock exceeds everything else. Plenty of healthy companies show negative equity for exactly this reason.\n\nThe point: negative equity is a book artifact, not a verdict. It says liabilities exceed the recorded value of assets, and recorded value ignores brand, people, and everything else earned rather than purchased.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has had positive EBITDA for ten years and just went bankrupt. How?",a:"Because EBITDA ignores almost everything that consumes cash.\n\nIt excludes interest, so a company drowning in debt payments still shows healthy EBITDA. It excludes capital expenditures, so a business spending everything it earns on equipment looks profitable. It excludes working capital, so a company whose cash is trapped in unsold inventory looks fine. It excludes debt maturities entirely, and companies fail when they cannot refinance, not when EBITDA turns negative.\n\nThe point: EBITDA measures operating profitability, and companies do not go bankrupt from unprofitability, they go bankrupt from running out of cash. Those are different things, and the gap between them is exactly what EBITDA hides.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the difference between cash and accrual accounting?",a:"Cash accounting records revenue when money arrives and expenses when money leaves. Simple, and it tracks the bank balance.\n\nAccrual accounting records revenue when it is earned and expenses when they are incurred, regardless of when cash moves. Deliver in March and get paid in June, and the revenue is March's.\n\nThe point: accrual exists because cash timing distorts performance. A company that prepays a year of rent is not having a terrible month. But the cost is that profit and cash diverge, which is precisely why the cash flow statement exists.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"When would a company collect cash and not record revenue?",a:"When it has been paid but has not delivered. Any prepaid arrangement does this: annual software subscriptions, magazines, gift cards, airline tickets bought months ahead, gym memberships.\n\nThe cash sits in deferred revenue, a liability, because the company owes the customer something. As delivery happens, it converts into revenue.\n\nThe point: this is the matching principle. Revenue is earned when the obligation is satisfied, not when the money lands. Companies love these models because customers fund the business, and investors like them because the revenue is already contracted.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the difference between accounts receivable and deferred revenue?",a:"They are opposites. Receivables mean you delivered and have not been paid: revenue is booked, cash is owed to you. Deferred revenue means you were paid and have not delivered: cash is in hand, revenue is owed to the customer.\n\nOne is an asset, the other a liability.\n\nThe point: the difference tells you who is financing whom. Heavy receivables mean you are lending to your customers. Heavy deferred revenue means your customers are lending to you. The second is a far better business to own.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How do you decide whether to capitalize or expense a purchase?",a:"Useful life. If the benefit lasts beyond a year, capitalize it and spread the cost across the years it helps. If it is consumed now, expense it now.\n\nA factory serves you for decades, so it goes on the balance sheet and depreciates. This month's salaries bought this month's work, so they hit the income statement immediately.\n\nThe point: it is the matching principle again, put the cost in the periods that get the benefit. It is also a soft judgment at the edges, which is why software development costs get argued about so much: whether an engineer's salary is an asset or an expense depends on what they were building.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why would D&A on the income statement differ from D&A on the cash flow statement?",a:"Because on the income statement it is often buried. Companies frequently embed depreciation inside COGS or operating expenses rather than showing it separately, so the D&A line you see may be only part of it.\n\nThe cash flow statement has to add back every non-cash charge to reconcile to actual cash, so it carries the full number.\n\nThe point: always take D&A from the cash flow statement when calculating EBITDA. Use the income statement figure and you will understate D&A, understate EBITDA, and overstate the multiple.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What are examples of non-recurring charges you would add back to EBITDA?",a:"Restructuring and severance, goodwill impairments, asset write-downs, litigation settlements, and costs from a natural disaster. The test is that it is genuinely one-time and it sits in operating income.\n\nTwo cautions. If the charge is below the operating line, it is already excluded from EBITDA, so adding it back double counts. And if a company reports restructuring charges every year for five years, it is not non-recurring, it is a cost of doing business.\n\nThe point: D&A and stock compensation are added back too, but they are not non-recurring. They are non-cash. Different reason, and interviewers do check whether you know the difference.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why do companies report both GAAP and non-GAAP earnings?",a:"Because management argues GAAP obscures the underlying business. They strip out stock compensation, acquired intangible amortization, restructuring, and other charges to show what they say is real performance.\n\nSometimes that is fair. Amortization of an intangible from a deal five years ago tells you nothing about how the business is running today.\n\nThe point: non-GAAP is always higher, without exception, because nobody adjusts their earnings downward. It is management marking its own homework. The useful test is whether the excluded items keep appearing every single year, because then they are just costs with a nicer label.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is the difference between LIFO and FIFO and when does it matter?",a:"They are assumptions about which inventory you sold, not about what physically moved. FIFO assumes the oldest units go first; LIFO assumes the newest do.\n\nIt only matters when prices change. With costs rising, LIFO puts the newest and most expensive units into COGS, so profit is lower and the tax bill is smaller, while the inventory left on the balance sheet is old and understated. FIFO does the reverse: higher profit, higher tax, and a more current inventory value.\n\nThe point: LIFO usually means lower reported earnings and more actual cash, because of the smaller tax bill. It is also banned outside the US, so it never comes up under IFRS.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"If you could only look at one financial statement to judge a company, which would you pick?",a:"The cash flow statement. It is the hardest to manipulate and it answers the question that actually matters: is this business generating cash or consuming it.\n\nNet income depends on estimates: useful lives, reserve levels, revenue recognition timing. Cash is cash. And the cash flow statement starts at net income anyway, so you get a view of profitability plus a reconciliation to reality.\n\nThe point: it is the only statement that shows the gap between reported profit and money in the bank. That gap is where nearly every accounting scandal has lived.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"If you could only have two statements, which two and why?",a:"The balance sheet and the income statement, because from those two you can construct the third.\n\nThe cash flow statement is a derivation, not new information. Net income comes from the income statement, and every other line is a change in a balance sheet account. You need two balance sheets, a beginning and an end, but with those you can build the whole thing.\n\nThe point: the trap is answering cash flow statement, since that is the right answer to the one-statement version. With two, you should pick the pair that lets you generate the third rather than picking the third itself.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How do the three statements link together?",a:"Net income is the hinge. It comes off the bottom of the income statement, lands at the top of the cash flow statement, and flows into retained earnings on the balance sheet.\n\nThe cash flow statement then reverses every non-cash item and tracks every balance sheet change: working capital in operating, capex in investing, debt and equity in financing. The bottom line, the change in cash, updates the cash account on the balance sheet.\n\nThe point: cash is the plug. Once net income hits equity and every other balance sheet line has moved, cash is whatever makes both sides equal. If your balance sheet does not balance, the error is somewhere in that loop.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do we care about EBITDA at all if it hides so much?",a:"Because it strips out choices and leaves the operations. It ignores capital structure, so a levered company and an unlevered one are comparable. It ignores tax, so companies in different countries are comparable. It ignores depreciation, so companies with different asset ages and useful lives are comparable.\n\nThat makes it a rough proxy for operating cash flow that can be compared across a whole industry, which revenue and net income cannot do.\n\nThe point: it is useful precisely because of what it excludes, and dangerous for exactly the same reason. It is a comparison tool, not a measure of what a business actually earns. Buffett's line about the tooth fairy paying for capex is the standard rebuttal.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does Warren Buffett dislike EBITDA?",a:"His objection is that it pretends capital spending is free. His line is asking whether management thinks the tooth fairy pays for capital expenditures.\n\nDepreciation is a real cost. It is the accounting recognition that machines wear out and must be replaced. Adding it back and calling the result earnings implies the replacement never has to happen.\n\nThe point: the objection has force in capital-intensive businesses, where the gap between EBITDA and EBIT is enormous and the company must reinvest constantly just to stand still. It bites much less for asset-light software, where D&A is small and often unrelated to any real reinvestment need.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's EBITDA is growing but its cash flow is falling. What is going on?",a:"Something between EBITDA and cash is consuming the money. Work down the gap.\n\nWorking capital. Receivables ballooning means sales are being made to customers who do not pay. Inventory building means goods are not selling.\n\nCapex. The growth may require constant spending that EBITDA ignores entirely.\n\nInterest and tax. Both are real cash and both sit below EBITDA. A rising rate on floating debt drains cash with no effect on EBITDA at all.\n\nThe point: this pattern is the single most common early warning of trouble, and the most common version is receivables growing faster than revenue. That usually means either weak collections or revenue being recognized too aggressively.",category:"Accounting"}
,

// Original IB cards, standard analyst-interview caliber. Written from the underlying
// accounting and finance; every arithmetic claim verified mechanically.
{q:"How do you select precedent transactions?",a:"Same filters as comps, plus time. Industry first, then size, then geography, then deal type.\n\nTime matters more here than anywhere else. A deal from 2007 tells you what buyers paid in a credit boom, not what they will pay now. Most bankers stay inside three to five years, and less in a fast-moving sector.\n\nThe point: you also separate strategic buyers from financial ones. Strategics pay for synergies and print higher multiples; sponsors bid to an IRR and stop. Mixing them without noting which is which produces a range that means nothing.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why are precedent transactions harder to build than comps?",a:"Because the data is worse. Public comps have audited quarterly financials and a live share price. Deals have whatever the parties chose to disclose.\n\nIf the target was private, you may never learn its EBITDA. If it was a division, the financials may not exist separately. Terms like earnouts and assumed debt often sit in a footnote or nowhere at all.\n\nThe point: the multiple is only as good as the denominator, and in precedents the denominator is frequently an estimate. That is why the range is wider and why bankers lean on comps for the tighter read.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a sum-of-the-parts valuation and when would you use it?",a:"You value each business line separately using multiples appropriate to that line, add them together, then subtract net debt and any corporate overhead.\n\nYou use it for conglomerates, where one blended multiple would be meaningless. A company with a software division and a shipping division should not be valued at one EV/EBITDA, because the market pays completely different multiples for those cash flows.\n\nThe point: it often reveals a conglomerate discount, where the parts are worth more than the whole. That gap is exactly what activists target when they push for a breakup or a spin-off.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a football field and what does it actually show?",a:"A chart with one horizontal bar per methodology: DCF, comps, precedents, LBO, and often the 52-week trading range. Each bar spans the low-to-high valuation that method produced.\n\nIt shows the overlap. Where the bars converge is the defensible range, and that is the number you take into a negotiation.\n\nThe point: it exists because no single method is right. Its real function is honesty, it forces you to display how wide the uncertainty is rather than presenting one false-precision number. If your bars barely overlap, your assumptions disagree and you should find out why before someone else does.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A DCF gives you $50 per share and comps give you $35. What do you do?",a:"Find out why before you pick. The gap is information, not a problem to average away.\n\nCheck your DCF assumptions first, since it is the easier one to break. Is the growth rate too generous, the discount rate too low, the terminal value doing all the work?\n\nIf the DCF holds, then the market may genuinely be underpricing the company, or the market knows something your model does not: a lawsuit, a customer loss, a sector rerating.\n\nThe point: never split the difference to make it tidy. The honest answer is to present both, explain the driver of the gap, and let the reader judge. A banker who reconciles a gap by averaging it has hidden the most interesting fact in the analysis.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is the difference between Chapter 7 and Chapter 11?",a:"Chapter 7 is liquidation. The business stops, a trustee sells the assets, and proceeds are distributed by priority. The company ceases to exist.\n\nChapter 11 is reorganization. The company keeps operating while it renegotiates its obligations, usually converting debt to equity, and emerges with a viable balance sheet.\n\nThe point: the choice turns on whether the business is worth more alive than dead. If going-concern value exceeds liquidation value, Chapter 11 makes everyone better off. If the assets are worth more sold piecemeal, Chapter 7 is the honest outcome.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Walk me through the priority of claims in a bankruptcy.",a:"Top to bottom. Secured creditors first, up to the value of their collateral. Then administrative claims, meaning the lawyers and bankers running the process. Then unsecured creditors: bondholders, suppliers, pension claims. Then preferred shareholders. Common equity last.\n\nThe point: this is the absolute priority rule, and each class must be paid in full before the next sees a dollar. In practice it gets negotiated, because senior classes often hand equity a token recovery just to avoid a fight that delays everyone. Common equity is usually wiped out entirely, which is why bankrupt-company stock trading above zero is often just speculation.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the fulcrum security?",a:"The class of debt that gets converted into equity in a restructuring. It sits exactly where the value runs out: everything senior to it gets paid in full, everything junior gets wiped, and this class straddles the line.\n\nBecause it converts, the holders end up owning the reorganized company.\n\nThe point: identifying it is the central analytical task in restructuring. You value the company, walk the debt from the top, and find where the money stops. Distressed funds buy the fulcrum on purpose, cheaply, so they end up owning a business for a fraction of its value.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why would a creditor prefer to keep a company alive rather than liquidate it?",a:"Because they usually recover more. A functioning business with customers, contracts, and staff is worth more than its equipment at auction.\n\nLiquidation values are brutal. Specialized machinery sells for cents, brands evaporate, and the good employees leave the day the news breaks. A creditor recovering 60 cents in a reorganization does better than one recovering 20 in a fire sale.\n\nThe point: it depends entirely on the asset. A retailer's real value may be its property, which sells perfectly well without the retailer. A services firm whose value walks out of the building every evening is worth almost nothing dead.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is a debt-for-equity swap and who wins?",a:"Creditors cancel their debt in exchange for shares in the reorganized company. Leverage drops overnight, no cash moves, and the company survives.\n\nCreditors win relative to the alternative, since they trade a claim that will not be paid for ownership of something that might be worth more. Existing shareholders lose, because they are diluted heavily or wiped out.\n\nThe point: it is the standard restructuring move, and it works because the enterprise still has value, just not enough to cover the debt at face. The swap simply moves the ownership down the capital structure to whoever the value actually reaches.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What are the three main ways a company gets into distress?",a:"Too much leverage. The business is fine but the balance sheet is not. A good company bought at too high a multiple with too much debt fails on the interest, not the operations.\n\nOperational decline. The business itself is broken: demand fell, a competitor won, the product is obsolete. No balance sheet fixes this.\n\nA liquidity event. The business and the leverage are both survivable but the company cannot refinance a maturity, or a covenant trips, or a customer stops paying. Solvent on paper, out of cash in practice.\n\nThe point: the fix depends on which one it is. A leverage problem is solved with a restructuring. An operational problem is not, and adding a new balance sheet to a dying business just resets the clock.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a covenant breach and what actually happens next?",a:"A covenant is a promise in the loan agreement, usually a ratio like keeping leverage under 5x. Breaching it puts the company in technical default, even if it has never missed a payment.\n\nWhat happens next is almost never a seizure. The lender gains leverage and uses it. Typically they grant a waiver in exchange for a higher rate, extra fees, more collateral, or tighter terms.\n\nThe point: covenants exist to give lenders a seat at the table before the money runs out. The breach is the trigger for a negotiation, not the end of the company. Lenders generally do not want the keys, they want to be paid.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Walk me through an IPO process at a high level.",a:"The company selects underwriters and picks a lead bank. Then due diligence and drafting the S-1, which is the registration statement laying out the business, the risks, and the financials.\n\nFile with the SEC, respond to their comments, and revise. Then the roadshow, where management pitches institutional investors over a couple of weeks.\n\nBuild the book of orders, price the deal the night before, and trade the next morning.\n\nThe point: the whole process takes four to six months and the pricing decision is the contentious part. Price too low and you left money on the table. Price too high and the stock breaks issue, which embarrasses everyone. Banks tend to underprice slightly on purpose, which is why a first-day pop is normal.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do companies IPO?",a:"To raise permanent capital without repaying it, and to create a liquid currency. Public shares can be used to pay for acquisitions and to compensate employees in something they can actually sell.\n\nIt also gives early investors and founders an exit path, and public listing brings credibility with customers and lenders.\n\nThe point: the costs are real. Quarterly reporting, disclosure of things competitors read, and a share price that turns every decision into a referendum. Plenty of good companies stay private specifically to avoid managing to a quarter, which is why sponsors and private credit have made staying private so much easier.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the difference between a primary and a secondary offering?",a:"Primary shares are new shares issued by the company, and the cash goes to the company's balance sheet. The share count rises and existing holders are diluted.\n\nSecondary shares are existing shares sold by current holders. The cash goes to those sellers, not the company. The share count does not change and nobody is diluted.\n\nThe point: the mix is a signal. A deal that is heavily secondary means insiders are cashing out rather than funding growth, and the market reads that accordingly.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is a green shoe?",a:"An over-allotment option letting underwriters sell up to 15% more shares than planned, and buy them from the company at the offer price within about 30 days.\n\nIts real function is price stability. The underwriters short the extra shares at pricing. If the stock trades down, they buy in the market to cover, which supports the price. If it trades up, they exercise the option and take the shares from the company.\n\nThe point: it is a stabilization mechanism dressed as an option. The bank cannot lose on the short, and the issuer gets a floor under the stock in the fragile first month.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why would a company issue convertible debt instead of straight debt or equity?",a:"Because the coupon is lower. Investors accept less interest in exchange for the option to convert into stock, so the company gets cheap money now.\n\nCompared with issuing equity, it avoids dilution today and only dilutes if the stock rises, at which point the company can afford it.\n\nThe point: it is popular with growth companies that cannot support a high coupon and think their stock is undervalued. The catch is that if the stock does perform, you sold equity at yesterday's price, and if it does not, you still owe the principal at maturity.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the difference between an investment grade bond and a high yield bond?",a:"The rating line, at BBB minus for S&P or Baa3 for Moody's. Above it is investment grade, below is high yield.\n\nThat line has real consequences. Investment grade pays a lower coupon, carries lighter covenants, and can be bought by institutions whose mandates forbid junk. High yield pays more, carries tighter terms, and has a much smaller buyer base.\n\nThe point: the drop from BBB minus to BB plus is the single most expensive downgrade in credit. It is not a small step in risk, it is a step off a cliff in demand, because a whole class of buyers becomes forced sellers.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What does it mean when a bond trades at a discount to par?",a:"Buyers want a higher yield than the coupon pays. Either market rates have risen since issue, which repriced every bond, or the market thinks this borrower is now riskier and demands more compensation.\n\nHow to tell which. Compare with government bonds of the same maturity. If everything fell together, it was rates. If only this bond fell, the credit spread widened and the problem is the company.\n\nThe point: the balance sheet still carries the debt at face, because debt is held at amortized cost. The market is saying it is worth less, and a company with cash could buy it back at the discount and book a gain.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Buyer has 100M shares at $30 and net income of $150M. It acquires a target for $600M in all stock. The target earns $40M. Is the deal accretive?",a:"Accretive. Work it through.\n\nBuyer standalone EPS is $150M over 100M shares, or $1.50.\n\nTo pay $600M in stock at $30 a share, the buyer issues 20M shares. Combined shares are 120M. Combined net income is $150M plus $40M, or $190M, since no cash or debt is involved and there is no interest effect.\n\nCombined EPS is $190M over 120M, which is $1.58. That is up from $1.50, so accretive.\n\nThe point: check it with the P/E shortcut. The buyer trades at $30 over $1.50, which is 20x. It paid $600M for $40M of earnings, which is 15x. Buyer P/E above seller P/E means accretive, and the full math agrees.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Buyer has a 15x P/E and buys a target at 15x in an all-stock deal. What happens to EPS?",a:"Nothing. It is exactly neutral before any synergies.\n\nThe buyer is issuing stock the market prices at 15 times earnings to buy earnings priced at 15 times. Every share issued brings back exactly as much earnings as it gives away, so EPS is unchanged.\n\nThe point: this is why synergies matter so much in a same-multiple deal. Without them the transaction does nothing for EPS at all, and the buyer has taken on integration risk for zero accounting benefit. Any accretion has to come from cost cuts.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"How do you decide whether to fund an acquisition with cash, debt, or stock?",a:"Compare the cost of each against the target's earnings yield.\n\nCash is cheapest, since you only give up the interest you were earning on it, maybe 2%. Debt is next, at the after-tax interest rate, maybe 4% to 5%. Stock is most expensive, since your earnings yield is the inverse of your P/E, so a 20x P/E means a 5% cost.\n\nWhichever is cheaper than the target's earnings yield makes the deal accretive.\n\nThe point: the ranking assumes you have the choice. Balance sheet capacity, credit ratings, and market conditions usually decide for you, which is why the cheapest option is often unavailable.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A buyer pays $500M cash for a target earning $30M. The buyer was earning 3% on that cash. Tax rate 25%. Is it accretive?",a:"Accretive, clearly.\n\nWhat the buyer gives up: $500M at 3% is $15M of interest income, and after 25% tax that is $11.25M of net income lost.\n\nWhat it gains: $30M of the target's net income.\n\nNet effect is a gain of $18.75M with no new shares issued, so EPS rises.\n\nThe point: cash deals are almost always accretive in a low-rate world, because forgone interest income is trivial next to the target's earnings. That is precisely why accretion is a weak test. The buyer could be overpaying enormously and this math would still say yes.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the difference between accretion and value creation?",a:"Accretion is an accounting outcome: does combined EPS go up. Value creation is an economic one: is the business worth more than what you paid.\n\nThey diverge constantly. A buyer can fund a deal with cheap debt, print higher EPS, and still have destroyed value by paying twice what the target is worth. The EPS math does not know the price was wrong; it only compares earnings against financing cost.\n\nThe point: accretion is popular because it is easy to calculate and easy to put in a press release. The right question is whether the return on the invested capital beats the cost of that capital, which is a much harder number to spin.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why does an all-cash deal usually look more accretive than an all-stock deal?",a:"Because cash is the cheapest currency. Its cost is the interest you stop earning, which is small.\n\nStock is the most expensive. Issuing shares at a 20x P/E means you are effectively paying a 5% cost, and it permanently increases the share count so every future dollar of earnings gets divided further.\n\nThe point: it is why accretion is a poor way to judge deals. The funding choice drives the answer more than the quality or price of the target. Two identical acquisitions at identical prices can print opposite EPS outcomes purely because of how they were paid for.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do you discount cash flows at all?",a:"Because a dollar today is worth more than a dollar in five years. You could invest today's dollar and have more than a dollar by then, so future money must be marked down to compare fairly.\n\nThe discount rate captures two things: the time value of money, and the risk that the future cash never arrives. Riskier cash flows get discounted harder.\n\nThe point: it is not an accounting convention, it is the entire idea. A business is worth the cash it will produce, adjusted for when it arrives and how sure you are it will.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is the mid-year convention and why use it?",a:"By default a DCF discounts each year's cash flow as though it all lands on the last day of the year. That is wrong, since companies collect cash continuously through the year.\n\nThe mid-year convention discounts as though the cash arrives in the middle instead, using 0.5, 1.5, 2.5 rather than 1, 2, 3.\n\nThe point: it raises your valuation, because the cash is treated as arriving sooner and gets discounted less. The effect is usually a few percent, so it is a refinement rather than a rescue. If it changes your conclusion, the conclusion was never solid.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is a stub period in a DCF?",a:"The partial year between today and the next fiscal year end. If you are valuing a company in September and it reports in December, you have roughly a quarter of a year before the first full projected year begins.\n\nYou discount that stub over its actual fraction of a year rather than a full one, so about 0.25 years.\n\nThe point: it is a precision issue, and it matters most for deals that close mid-year. Getting it wrong shifts every subsequent cash flow's timing, which compounds through the model.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Your DCF gives a value far above the current share price. What do you check first?",a:"Your own assumptions, in order of how much damage they do. The terminal growth rate, since anything above long-term GDP is impossible. The discount rate, since a WACC that is too low inflates everything. The margin path, since assuming steady expansion forever is the most common fantasy in a model.\n\nOnly after those hold up should you conclude the market is wrong.\n\nThe point: the market is a lot of people with real money at stake. When your spreadsheet disagrees with all of them, the base case is that you made a mistake, not that you found a mispricing. Being able to say that in an interview matters more than the number.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"How do you get from enterprise value to equity value in a DCF?",a:"Subtract net debt, meaning total debt minus cash. Then also subtract preferred stock and noncontrolling interest, since both are claims ahead of common shareholders.\n\nThen add back any non-operating assets your cash flows never captured, such as investments in unconsolidated affiliates.\n\nThe point: the logic is that a DCF of unlevered cash flow values the whole business, so it belongs to everyone with a claim. Peel off the claims that rank ahead of common equity, and whatever remains is the shareholders'. Then divide by fully diluted shares, not basic.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do you use fully diluted shares rather than basic shares?",a:"Because options and convertibles will become shares, and they will divide the same earnings across more claims. Ignoring them overstates value per share.\n\nUse the treasury stock method for options: assume exercise, assume the company uses the strike proceeds to buy stock back, and count only the net new shares.\n\nThe point: it matters most for companies that pay heavily in equity, where the option overhang can be a real percentage of the count. Using basic shares for a tech company with a large equity program will overstate your per-share value materially.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A perpetuity pays $50 a year forever. Your discount rate is 8%. What is it worth?",a:"$625. It is $50 divided by 0.08.\n\nThe intuition. Ask what amount, earning 8%, throws off $50 a year forever. $625 at 8% is exactly $50. So $625 is the amount of capital that reproduces the payment stream.\n\nThe point: a perpetuity is the simplest version of the terminal value formula. Add growth and it becomes cash flow divided by the discount rate minus the growth rate, which is exactly what a DCF does to the final year.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A perpetuity pays $50 next year and grows 3% forever. Discount rate is 8%. What is it worth?",a:"$1,000. It is $50 divided by 0.08 less 0.03, so $50 over 0.05.\n\nNotice it is worth $375 more than the flat $50 perpetuity, which was $625. A 3% growth rate nearly doubled the value.\n\nThe point: this is why the terminal growth rate is so dangerous in a DCF. It sits in the denominator, so small changes swing the answer hard. Move it to 4% and the value jumps to $1,250. As growth approaches the discount rate the denominator approaches zero and the value goes to infinity, which is the mathematical reason terminal growth can never exceed WACC.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"You have $100 today or $150 in five years. Your discount rate is 10%. Which do you take?",a:"Take the $100 today.\n\nDiscount the $150 back: $150 divided by 1.1 to the fifth power. 1.1 to the fifth is about 1.61, so the present value is about $93. That is less than $100, so the $150 is worth less than it looks.\n\nThe other direction is the same answer. Invest $100 at 10% for five years and you have about $161, which beats $150.\n\nThe point: the instinct is to grab the bigger number. At 10%, money roughly doubles every seven years, so five years of compounding is worth more than the extra $50. Refusing to compare cash flows from different points in time without adjusting is the entire discipline of valuation.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"How would you value a company that has never made a profit and has no revenue?",a:"By what drives value in its industry, not by earnings. A biotech gets valued on its pipeline: probability-weight each drug's chance of approval against the market it would address, and discount at a very high rate.\n\nA pre-revenue app might be valued per user, or on the cost to rebuild what it has, or on what comparable companies were acquired for at the same stage.\n\nThe point: with no revenue and no profit, you are valuing an option, not a business. That is why venture investors do not run DCFs. They size the outcome if it works and the odds that it does, which is a fundamentally different exercise from projecting cash flow.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Company A trades at 20x earnings, Company B at 10x. Which is the better investment?",a:"You cannot tell. The multiple only tells you the price, not the value.\n\nCompany A might be growing 30% a year with recurring revenue and no competition, making 20x cheap. Company B might be a declining business with one customer and heavy debt, making 10x expensive.\n\nThe point: the multiple is a claim on the future. Comparing two of them without comparing growth, risk, and quality of earnings is comparing prices without knowing what is being sold. That is why the answer to any high-versus-low multiple question always starts with what is the growth and how sure is it.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why might two companies in the same industry with the same growth trade at different multiples?",a:"Quality of earnings. One may have recurring contracted revenue, the other one-off project work. Same growth, very different reliability, and the market pays for reliability.\n\nCapital intensity. One may convert most of its EBITDA into free cash while the other spends it all on equipment. The cash that reaches shareholders is what gets valued.\n\nBalance sheet, management credibility, customer concentration, or simply liquidity in the stock.\n\nThe point: growth is only one of two inputs and risk is the other. Identical growth with different certainty is not identical at all.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is WACC and how do you calculate it?",a:"The blended return every capital provider requires. Take the cost of equity times the equity weight, plus the cost of debt times one minus the tax rate times the debt weight.\n\nCost of equity comes from CAPM: risk-free rate plus beta times the equity risk premium. Cost of debt is what the company would pay to borrow today, not the historical coupon on old debt. Weights are at market value, not book.\n\nThe point: the one minus tax rate term is the only place the tax shield appears. It is why debt is structurally cheaper, and why WACC falls as you add debt right up until the added default risk starts pushing both costs back up.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Should you use the book value or market value of debt and equity in WACC?",a:"Market value for both, though in practice debt often gets used at book.\n\nEquity must be at market, because the whole point is what investors require on today's value, not on an accounting number from years ago. Using book equity for a company trading at three times book would badly distort the weights.\n\nDebt is usually close enough at book, since most debt trades near par unless the company is distressed or rates have moved sharply. When it is distressed, the difference matters a lot.\n\nThe point: WACC is a forward-looking required return, so every input should be what the market says today, not what the ledger recorded.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is beta and what does a beta of 0.5 mean?",a:"Beta measures how much a stock moves relative to the market. A beta of 1 moves with the index. A beta of 0.5 moves half as much: the market drops 10% and the stock drops roughly 5%.\n\nLow-beta names are typically utilities, consumer staples, and anything whose demand does not care about the economy. High-beta names are cyclicals and anything discretionary.\n\nThe point: beta only measures market risk, the kind you cannot diversify away. It says nothing about company-specific risk, because CAPM assumes you hold a diversified portfolio and have already diversified that away. That assumption is exactly why people criticize it.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is the risk-free rate and what do you actually use?",a:"In theory, the return on an asset with no default risk. In practice, the yield on a long-dated government bond, usually the ten-year in the relevant currency.\n\nYou match the maturity to the cash flows. Valuing a company as a going concern with decades of cash flow means a long bond, not a three-month bill.\n\nThe point: it is only risk free in the sense that the government will not default in its own currency. It is not free of inflation risk or interest rate risk. It is a convention that works because everyone uses the same one.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is the equity risk premium and roughly what is it?",a:"The extra return investors demand for holding stocks instead of government bonds. Historically it has run around 5% to 7% in the US, though estimates vary widely by method and period.\n\nThere are two ways to get it. Historical, meaning the realized gap between stocks and bonds over decades. Implied, meaning working backwards from today's index level and expected cash flows to solve for the rate investors must be using.\n\nThe point: it is one of the least precise inputs in finance and it drives cost of equity directly. Reasonable people use numbers a full two points apart, which is why DCF outputs get presented as ranges rather than points.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do smaller companies get a size premium in the discount rate?",a:"Because they have historically returned more than CAPM predicted, and the accepted explanation is that they are riskier in ways beta does not capture.\n\nSmall companies have less access to capital, thinner customer bases, key-person dependency, and shares that are harder to sell. Investors demand extra return for that.\n\nThe point: it is an empirical adjustment, not a theoretical one, typically a few percentage points bolted onto cost of equity. Some argue it has shrunk or vanished since it was documented, which is the usual fate of a published market anomaly.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is the difference between systematic and unsystematic risk?",a:"Systematic risk affects the whole market: interest rates, recessions, wars, inflation. You cannot diversify it away, because it hits everything at once. This is what beta measures and what you get paid to bear.\n\nUnsystematic risk is company-specific: a factory fire, a failed product, a lawsuit. You can diversify it away by holding many stocks, and because you can, the market does not pay you to bear it.\n\nThe point: this is the core of CAPM. The only risk that earns a return is the one you cannot escape. It is also the assumption people attack, because a founder with everything in one company is very much exposed to unsystematic risk and is not compensated for it.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"How would you value a company with volatile, cyclical earnings?",a:"Normalize first. Do not build a DCF off a peak year or a trough year, because both are lies about the average. Take a mid-cycle earnings level, often an average across a full cycle, and value from there.\n\nFor multiples, use a mid-cycle multiple on mid-cycle earnings. A cyclical at the peak looks deceptively cheap, since earnings are inflated and the multiple collapses. At the trough it looks expensive for the mirror reason.\n\nThe point: cyclicals invert the usual signal. A low P/E on a cyclical is often a sell, because it means earnings are peaking. A high P/E can mean earnings are bottoming. That is why people use price to book or EV/sales for these instead.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why might EV/EBIT be better than EV/EBITDA for some companies?",a:"Because EBIT accounts for depreciation, and depreciation is a real cost when the assets genuinely wear out.\n\nCompare two companies with identical EBITDA where one owns its equipment and one leases, or one has old fully depreciated assets and one just rebuilt its plant. EBITDA calls them identical. EBIT does not, because it recognizes that one of them has to spend money to keep going.\n\nThe point: EBITDA is more common because it makes companies with different asset ages and depreciation policies comparable. But in capital-intensive industries, ignoring depreciation ignores the business model. That is why manufacturing and telecoms often trade on EBIT or on free cash flow instead.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is free cash flow and why do people disagree about it?",a:"Broadly, the cash a business generates after paying to maintain itself. The common version is operating cash flow minus capital expenditures.\n\nPeople disagree because of what counts. Should you subtract all capex or only maintenance capex, since growth capex is optional? Should stock compensation be added back when it dilutes shareholders? Should working capital swings be normalized?\n\nThe point: there is no single definition, which is why the term is easy to abuse. A company can present a flattering free cash flow number by classifying growth spending generously. Always ask which definition is being used before you compare it to anything.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the difference between unlevered and levered free cash flow?",a:"Unlevered free cash flow sits above interest. It is the cash the whole business produces, available to lenders and shareholders alike. You discount it at WACC and it produces enterprise value.\n\nLevered free cash flow is after interest and debt payments. It is what is left for shareholders only. You discount it at cost of equity and it produces equity value directly.\n\nThe point: the two must stay matched. Discounting unlevered cash flow at cost of equity, or levered cash flow at WACC, double counts or ignores the financing. Bankers use unlevered because it lets you value the business independent of capital structure, which makes comparison possible.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company has $100M of EBITDA and $400M of debt. Is that too much leverage?",a:"4x leverage, and the answer depends entirely on the business.\n\nFor a software company with recurring revenue, 4x is comfortable, because the cash arrives reliably and there is little capex competing for it. For a cyclical manufacturer, 4x could be dangerous, since a normal downturn might cut EBITDA in half and take leverage to 8x, breaching covenants.\n\nThe point: leverage is meaningless without cash flow stability and interest coverage. The better question is how many times EBITDA covers the interest, and what happens to that in a bad year. Investment grade tends to run under 3x, and leveraged buyouts routinely run 5x to 6x.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is interest coverage and why do lenders care more about it than leverage?",a:"EBITDA divided by interest expense. It answers whether the company can actually pay its interest bill out of operations.\n\nLenders care because it is immediate. Leverage tells you the size of the problem eventually; coverage tells you whether the cheque clears this quarter. A company at 6x leverage with 3x coverage is servicing its debt fine. A company at 3x leverage with 1.1x coverage is one bad quarter from missing a payment.\n\nThe point: default happens when you cannot make a payment, not when a ratio looks bad. Coverage is closer to that moment, which is why credit agreements are usually built around it.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do you add back stock-based compensation in EBITDA but it still hurts shareholders?",a:"It is added back because it is non-cash. The company paid in shares, so no money left, and EBITDA is meant to proxy operating cash generation.\n\nIt still hurts because the shares are real. Every award that vests divides future earnings across more claims, so existing shareholders own less of the same business. The cost was paid in ownership rather than money.\n\nThe point: this is the most contested add-back in the market. Buffett's position is that if compensation is not an expense, what is it. The defensible answer is that it belongs in EBITDA as non-cash but must be captured in the share count, which is exactly why you value on fully diluted shares.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Walk me through how you build a comparable companies analysis.",a:"Pick the universe first: companies facing the same demand drivers, of roughly the same size, in the same geography.\n\nPull the financials and clean them. Strip out non-recurring items so the earnings you use are what the business really produces. Calendarize so everyone is on the same fiscal year, since one company's December and another's June are not comparable.\n\nCalculate enterprise value and equity value for each, then compute the multiples: EV/Revenue, EV/EBITDA, EV/EBIT, P/E.\n\nTake the median rather than the mean, and apply the range to your company's metric.\n\nThe point: the cleaning is the actual work. Anyone can pull a multiple off a screen. The judgment is in which companies belong in the set and what counts as recurring.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do you use the median rather than the mean of a comps set?",a:"Because the mean gets destroyed by outliers. One company in a small set trading at 40x because it just missed earnings will drag the average somewhere no company actually trades.\n\nComps sets are small, often six to twelve names, so a single distorted multiple has enormous weight. The median ignores the extremes and reports what a typical company in the set trades at.\n\nThe point: if the mean and median are far apart, that itself is the finding. It means the set is not homogeneous, and the right response is to look at why rather than to pick whichever number you preferred.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is calendarization and why does it matter?",a:"Adjusting companies onto a common fiscal year so their financials cover the same period. A company with a June year end and one with a December year end are reporting different halves of the economy.\n\nYou do it by adding and subtracting quarters: take the full year, subtract the quarters that fall outside your target window, add the ones that fall inside.\n\nThe point: without it you are comparing a multiple built on 2024 conditions against one built on 2025 conditions and calling them peers. It matters most when something changed sharply mid-year, which is exactly when the comparison is most likely to be used.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is the difference between LTM and forward multiples?",a:"LTM, meaning last twelve months, uses actual reported results. Forward multiples use projected results, usually next fiscal year.\n\nLTM is factual and cannot be argued with, but it is backward-looking and can be stale for a fast-changing company. Forward reflects where the business is going, which is what the share price is actually pricing, but it depends on analyst estimates that may be wrong or biased.\n\nThe point: forward multiples are almost always lower for a growing company, because the denominator is bigger. Comparing one company's LTM multiple against another's forward multiple is a classic error that makes the second look artificially cheap.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How do you calculate LTM figures?",a:"Take the most recent full fiscal year, add the year-to-date results from the current year, then subtract the same year-to-date period from the prior year.\n\nSo if you want LTM as of Q3, take full year, add the first three quarters of this year, subtract the first three quarters of last year. What remains is the trailing twelve months.\n\nThe point: the logic is that you are rolling the window forward by adding the new quarters and removing the stale ones. Getting the subtraction backwards is one of the most common mechanical mistakes in a comps build, and it is invisible unless someone checks.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Should you include a company in your comps set if it is much larger than your target?",a:"Usually not, even in the same industry. Size changes the multiple on its own. Large companies get better access to capital, more diversification, more index inclusion and liquidity, and they typically trade at a premium for it.\n\nA $500M company and a $50B company selling the same product are not comparable, because the market prices scale and survivability differently.\n\nThe point: if the set is too thin without the larger names, include them and note it, or apply a size discount. Silently mixing them and taking the median imports a scale premium your company has not earned.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why can't you use EV/EBITDA for a bank?",a:"Because enterprise value is meaningless for a bank. EV subtracts cash and adds debt, but for a bank, deposits and borrowings are raw material, not financing. Debt is what a bank sells, and cash is inventory.\n\nEBITDA is equally broken. Interest is the core revenue line, so stripping it out removes the business itself.\n\nThe point: you use equity-side metrics instead: price to earnings, price to book, and price to tangible book. Book value means something for a bank because assets are financial and marked closer to fair value, unlike a factory carried at historical cost.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How do you value a bank?",a:"On the equity side, because enterprise value does not apply. The main multiples are price to book and price to tangible book, plus price to earnings.\n\nFor an intrinsic value, use a dividend discount model rather than a DCF. You cannot compute unlevered free cash flow for a bank, since debt is part of operations. So you project distributable earnings, meaning what can be paid out after keeping enough capital to meet regulatory requirements, and discount those at cost of equity.\n\nThe point: everything reduces to return on equity versus cost of equity. A bank earning above its cost of equity trades above book; one earning below trades below. That relationship explains most of bank valuation.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do REITs use FFO instead of net income?",a:"Because depreciation makes net income meaningless for property. Accounting depreciates buildings on a schedule, but well-maintained real estate in a good location usually appreciates. So GAAP shows a large non-cash charge for an asset that is gaining value.\n\nFFO adds depreciation back to net income and strips out gains on property sales, leaving a much better proxy for the cash the portfolio actually produces.\n\nThe point: this is a case where the accounting genuinely misrepresents economics. You value REITs on price to FFO and on net asset value, meaning the market value of the properties less debt, rather than on earnings.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How would you value an oil and gas company?",a:"On reserves, since the asset is what is in the ground. The standard is a net asset value model: forecast production from proved reserves, apply a commodity price deck, subtract costs, and discount the cash flows.\n\nFor multiples, use EV/EBITDAX, which adds exploration expense back, because accounting choices differ on whether exploration is capitalized or expensed. Also EV per barrel of reserves and EV per unit of daily production.\n\nThe point: the business is a depleting asset. Every barrel sold is inventory that will not be replaced unless the company spends to find more, which is why reserve replacement matters as much as production and why a straight EBITDA multiple hides the depletion.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How do you value a subscription software company?",a:"On revenue, usually, since most are unprofitable by design, spending on growth. EV/Revenue and EV/ARR are the standard, adjusted for growth rate, because a 40% grower and a 10% grower do not deserve the same multiple.\n\nThen look at the underlying quality: net revenue retention, meaning whether existing customers spend more each year; gross margin; and the payback period on sales and marketing spend.\n\nThe point: revenue multiples are a placeholder for profitability that has not arrived. The whole question is whether growth is buying durable customers or renting them. That is why retention is the number people actually argue about, not the multiple.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A retailer and a software company both have 20% EBITDA margins. Which is worth more?",a:"The software company, almost certainly, and by a lot.\n\nSame margin, completely different economics. Software costs almost nothing to serve an extra customer, so margins expand with scale. Revenue is recurring, so this year's base carries into next year. Capital needs are minimal.\n\nA retailer has to build stores, hold inventory, and start every year from zero. The next dollar of revenue costs nearly as much as the last.\n\nThe point: the margin tells you today's profitability, not the shape of the future. The market pays for incremental margins and durability, which is why software trades at multiples retail never sees despite identical EBITDA margins.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How many gas stations are there in the United States?",a:"Structure it, do not guess. Start with about 330 million people and roughly 2.5 people per household, so about 130 million households. Call it just under two cars each, so around 250 million cars.\n\nA car fills up roughly once a week, so about 13 billion fill-ups a year. Now size a station. A pump serves maybe one car every five minutes, so 12 an hour, and say 12 busy-equivalent hours a day, which is about 144 a day or 52,000 a year. A station with eight pumps handles maybe 400,000 fill-ups a year at full tilt.\n\n13 billion divided by 400,000 is about 33,000 stations. The real number is roughly 145,000, so I am off by more than four times, and the culprit is my utilization: real pumps sit idle most of the day.\n\nThe point: they are not testing the answer, they are testing whether you structure it, say your assumptions out loud, and sanity check at the end. Catching that your own utilization assumption was unrealistic is worth more than landing on the number.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How would you estimate the market size for electric vehicle charging in a city?",a:"Build it from the population. Take the city's people, get to households, then to cars, then apply an EV penetration rate.\n\nSay 1 million people, 400,000 households, 1.5 cars each is 600,000 cars, and 8% are electric, so 48,000 EVs.\n\nEach EV needs charging maybe twice a week, so about 5 million charges a year. Most happen at home, say 80%, leaving 1 million public charges. At an average of $15 per session, that is a $15M annual public charging market.\n\nThe point: state the assumption that drives everything, which here is the home-charging split. If it is 60% rather than 80%, the market doubles. Naming that is the answer they want.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do interviewers ask market sizing questions at all?",a:"Because it is the closest thing to the job. Deal work constantly requires estimating something nobody can look up: how big could this segment be, what happens to volume if a competitor enters, what is this business worth if the market is half what management claims.\n\nThey are watching whether you break a big problem into parts, whether your assumptions are stated rather than buried, whether your mental arithmetic holds, and whether you notice when your answer is absurd.\n\nThe point: the worst response is silence followed by a number. The best is thinking out loud, being explicit about what you assumed, and flagging which assumption would move the answer most.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why investment banking?",a:"Have one real reason, not three rehearsed ones. The credible answers are that you want to see how capital decisions get made at the top of a business, that you want the technical foundation fast, and that you want responsibility on real transactions early.\n\nWhat kills the answer. Saying you love finance, that you are a hard worker, or that you want to learn. Everyone says those, and none of them explains why banking rather than anything else.\n\nThe point: the answer has to connect to something you actually did. A class, a club, a project, a prior internship where you saw a piece of this and wanted more. The specific story is the answer. The general enthusiasm is noise.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why our bank?",a:"Name something only true of them. A specific deal they advised on that you can discuss. Their position in a particular sector or product. The size of the group and what that means for your role.\n\nWhat fails. Culture, people, reputation, and prestige. Every bank claims all four and no interviewer believes you have compared them.\n\nThe point: the honest subtext is that they know you applied everywhere. What they are testing is whether you did any homework and whether you would actually show up. Naming a real deal and having a view on it does both.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Walk me through your resume.",a:"Two minutes, chronological, and every stop needs a reason it led to the next. Not a list of what you did, a narrative of why each decision followed the last and why they add up to this seat.\n\nStructure. Where you started, the moment your interest in finance became concrete, what you did about it, what you learned that pushed you here, and why this role is the logical next step.\n\nThe point: they have your resume. They are not asking for the contents, they are testing whether your path has a story or is a series of accidents you are now rationalizing. Land on the role you are interviewing for as the obvious conclusion.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is your greatest weakness?",a:"Name a real one, with evidence you are fixing it. Something like: you took on too much yourself early rather than delegating, it cost you on a specific project, and here is what you changed.\n\nWhat fails. Perfectionism, working too hard, caring too much. These are boasts wearing a disguise and every interviewer has heard them hundreds of times.\n\nThe point: the question tests self-awareness, not the weakness. Someone who cannot name a genuine flaw either lacks the insight to see one or lacks the confidence to admit one. Both are worse than the flaw itself.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you failed.",a:"Pick a real failure with a real cost, and take the responsibility yourself. Situation, what you did, what went wrong, and specifically what you changed as a result.\n\nWhat fails. Choosing something trivial, or choosing a failure that was somebody else's fault. Both dodge the question.\n\nThe point: they are testing whether you can own an outcome without either collapsing or deflecting. The change you made is the real answer. A failure you learned nothing from is just a story, and a failure you blame on someone else is a red flag about how you will behave when a deal goes wrong.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why should we hire you over someone with more finance experience?",a:"Do not argue you know more. Argue about what actually breaks in the seat: reliability under pressure, precision, and being someone people want in the room at 2am.\n\nPoint at evidence. Something you built and shipped, something you ran that had consequences, something where you were the person who caught the error.\n\nThe point: they are hiring an analyst, not a finance professor. The technical content is learnable in weeks and they will teach it. Judgment, work ethic, and attention to detail are not, and the interview is mostly a proxy for those.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Where do you see yourself in five years?",a:"Be honest but not naive. Most analysts do not stay, and everyone in the room knows it. Saying you will be a lifer sounds like a lie; saying you are using this to get to private equity sounds like you are using them.\n\nThe workable answer is that you want to be excellent at this first, that you want to be the analyst people trust with the hard work, and that you are focused on the next two years rather than mapping the next ten.\n\nThe point: they are checking whether you are serious about the actual job. A candidate already planning their exit before starting is a retention risk. A candidate who has clearly never thought about the future is a different problem.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What do you think an analyst actually does day to day?",a:"Be specific and unromantic. Building and updating models, putting together pitch books and CIMs, running comps and precedents, doing diligence, and a great deal of formatting and checking.\n\nMuch of it is unglamorous. Turning comments at midnight, chasing a number that does not tie, rebuilding a page because the managing director changed his mind.\n\nThe point: this question is a filter. Candidates who describe advising CEOs on strategy have not spoken to anyone in the job. Showing you know the work is mostly grinding, and that you want it anyway, is far more convincing than enthusiasm about deals.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"How do you handle working 90 hour weeks?",a:"Do not claim you love it. Nobody does, and saying so signals you have not done it.\n\nThe credible answer is that you have been through something demanding before, you know how you behave when tired, and you have specific habits that keep the quality up: protecting sleep where you can, front-loading the hardest work, checking your own numbers before someone else does.\n\nThe point: they are not testing endurance, they are testing self-knowledge. Everyone burns out sometimes. The question is whether you know your limits and manage around them, or whether you will discover them at 3am on a live deal.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"A managing director asks for an analysis you think is wrong. What do you do?",a:"Do it, and raise the concern properly. Say what you think is wrong, why, and what the alternative shows. Then, if they still want it their way, deliver it their way and deliver it well.\n\nWhat fails. Silently doing it, since you noticed a problem and let it into a client deck. Or refusing, since you are an analyst and they have context you do not.\n\nThe point: they are testing whether you can disagree without being difficult. The right instinct is to flag once, clearly, with evidence, and then commit. Being right and unusable is worse than being wrong and coachable.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you worked on a team with someone difficult.",a:"Pick a real situation and be specific about what you did, not about how annoying they were. What the friction was, what you tried, what actually resolved it.\n\nWhat fails. Making them the villain. The interviewer is not there to judge your former teammate, they are judging how you talk about people who are not in the room.\n\nThe point: the whole test is whether you can describe conflict without contempt. You will spend three years working with people under pressure at strange hours. Someone who narrates a past teammate as an idiot is telling you exactly how they will describe this team later.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What questions do you have for me?",a:"Have real ones and make them specific to that person. Ask about a deal they worked on and what surprised them. Ask what separates the analysts who do well from the ones who struggle. Ask what they would change about the group.\n\nWhat fails. Asking about hours, comp, or exit opportunities. Asking something you could have Googled. Or saying you have no questions, which reads as you not caring.\n\nThe point: this is the only part of the interview you control completely. It is also the last impression. A sharp question about their actual work signals you were listening and that you are interested in the job rather than in the title.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"A company buys $200 of inventory on credit, then sells half of it for $180 cash. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through both events.",a:"At purchase. Nothing on the income statement. Inventory rises $200 and accounts payable rise $200. Cash does not move, because nothing has been paid.\n\nAt sale. Revenue is $180 and COGS is $100, being half the inventory, so gross profit is $80. Tax of $20 leaves net income up $60. On the cash flow statement, net income is up $60 and inventory falls $100, a source of cash, so cash rises $160. On the balance sheet, cash is up $160 and inventory is down $100, so assets rise $60, matching retained earnings.\n\nThe point: the company is sitting on $160 of cash and still owes suppliers $200. It looks flush and it has not paid for the goods yet, which is exactly why payables timing can flatter a cash balance right up until the bill lands.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's customer goes bankrupt owing $50, which was fully reserved. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The loss was already taken when the allowance was created, which is the entire purpose of reserving.\n\nCash flow statement. Nothing. No cash moves, because the cash never arrived in the first place.\n\nBalance sheet. Gross receivables fall $50 and the allowance falls $50, so net receivables are unchanged.\n\nThe point: this is bookkeeping, not a loss event. If writing off a reserved receivable hit earnings, the company would be taking the same loss twice. The economic damage happened the day the company decided the customer would not pay.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company issues $100 of debt at a discount, receiving $95. Walk through what happens.",a:"At issuance. Cash rises $95, which is what was actually received. The debt is recorded at $95 carrying value, not $100 face, with the $5 discount amortized over the life of the bond.\n\nOver time. That $5 gets amortized into interest expense, so the effective interest expense is higher than the coupon alone. It is non-cash, so it gets added back on the cash flow statement, and the carrying value of the debt climbs toward $100 by maturity.\n\nThe point: the discount exists because the coupon was below what the market demanded. Rather than paying more interest, the company took less money up front. The economics are the same, and the accounting spreads the difference across the life.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company's warranty reserve turns out to be too large and $20 is released. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Releasing the reserve reverses an expense, so it is a benefit. Pre-tax income rises $20 and tax rises $5, leaving net income up $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $15. The release is non-cash, so subtract the $20. Net cash falls $5, which is the tax now owed.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $5, the warranty liability is down $20, and retained earnings are up $15.\n\nThe point: earnings went up and cash went down, on a transaction where the company did nothing. Reserve releases boost reported profit at the cost of real tax. Because the reserve is management's estimate, repeated releases are a recognized way of manufacturing an earnings beat.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company acquires a competitor and writes up its PP&E by $200. Tax rate 25%. What happens over the following years?",a:"At close. PP&E rises $200 and a deferred tax liability of $50 appears, because book value went up but the tax basis did not.\n\nEvery year after. Book depreciation is higher on the written-up asset, so reported earnings are lower. But tax depreciation did not change, so the actual cash tax paid is unchanged. The company pays more tax than the books imply, and the DTL unwinds as the gap closes.\n\nThe point: the write-up creates an earnings drag with no cash benefit whatsoever, in a stock deal. That is exactly why acquirers argue over purchase price allocation, since the more you assign to depreciable assets, the worse your reported earnings look.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Revenue is flat but receivables have doubled. What is happening?",a:"Something is wrong with collection, and there are three candidates.\n\nCustomers are struggling. They are stretching payment because they cannot pay, which means some of that revenue will never turn into cash.\n\nThe company loosened terms to hold volume. Same revenue, but now funded on longer credit, which is a quiet price cut.\n\nRevenue is being recognized too aggressively. Sales booked that have not really been earned, or channel stuffing at quarter end.\n\nThe point: with revenue flat, doubling receivables cannot be growth. Days sales outstanding is the number to check, and this exact pattern, receivables outrunning revenue, precedes most accounting scandals.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company changes the useful life of its equipment from 5 years to 10 years. What happens?",a:"Income statement. Annual depreciation halves, so pre-tax income and net income both rise. Nothing about the business changed.\n\nCash flow statement. Net income is higher but the add-back is smaller, and the tax bill is now larger, so cash actually falls slightly.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E declines more slowly, so assets look larger for longer, and retained earnings are higher.\n\nThe point: earnings improved and cash got worse, which is the signature of an accounting change rather than an operating one. Extending useful lives is one of the best-known ways to manufacture earnings growth, and it costs real money through the lost tax shield. Always check the useful life disclosure when depreciation drops without capex dropping.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company sells a division for $300 that has a book value of $250. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The gain is $50 against book value. Tax of $12.50 leaves net income up $37.50. The division's own results get reclassified into discontinued operations.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $37.50. Subtract the $50 gain out of operating, then add the $300 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $287.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $287.50 and the division's net assets of $250 come off, so assets rise $37.50. Retained earnings rise $37.50.\n\nThe point: the gain is measured against book value, which may bear no relation to what the division is worth. A business carried at $250 could easily be worth $300 or $3,000, since accounting records what you paid, not what it grew into.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Two identical companies, one leases its equipment and one owns it. How do the financials differ?",a:"The owner has the asset and the debt on its balance sheet, takes depreciation and interest, and both sit below EBITDA. So its EBITDA looks higher.\n\nThe lessee, under current rules, also puts a right-of-use asset and a lease liability on the balance sheet, and splits the cost into depreciation and interest. So the two now look much more alike than they used to.\n\nThe point: before the lease rules changed, leasing kept the obligation off the balance sheet entirely and rent sat as a single operating expense inside EBITDA. That made leasing companies look far less levered than they were, which is precisely why the standard was rewritten.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company capitalizes interest during construction. Two years later the asset is finished. What has happened across the statements?",a:"During construction. No interest expense hits the income statement, so earnings are higher than they otherwise would be. PP&E rises by the capitalized interest. The cash still leaves, but it is classified in investing rather than operating, so operating cash flow looks stronger.\n\nAfter completion. The capitalized interest is now part of the asset's cost, so it comes back as extra depreciation every year for the asset's life.\n\nThe point: nothing was saved, it was deferred and relabelled. The company reported better earnings and better operating cash flow during the build, and pays for it with a depreciation drag afterwards. Total cash across the whole period is identical.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A sponsor triples its money in 5 years. Roughly what IRR is that?",a:"About 25%. Use the rule of 72 as a sanity check: at 25%, money doubles in roughly three years, so five years gets you comfortably past double and near triple.\n\nThe exact math is 3 to the power of one fifth, minus one, which is 24.6%.\n\nThe point: memorize the common ones because they come up constantly. 2x in 5 years is about 15%, 2.5x is about 20%, 3x is about 25%, and 4x is about 32%. Sponsors typically underwrite to 20% to 25%, which is why 2.5x to 3x over five years is the standard target.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"A deal returns 2x in 3 years or 3x in 5 years. Which is the better IRR?",a:"The 2x in 3 years. It works out to about 26%, against about 25% for the 3x in five years.\n\n2 to the power of one third is 1.26, so 26%. 3 to the power of one fifth is 1.246, so 24.6%.\n\nThe point: this is why sponsors care so much about exit timing. A smaller multiple achieved faster can beat a bigger one that takes longer, because IRR is time-weighted. It is also why IRR alone is a manipulable metric: an early dividend recap boosts it without the underlying business improving at all.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is the difference between IRR and multiple of money, and why do LPs look at both?",a:"Multiple of money is total cash out over cash in. Simple, and it ignores time completely. IRR is the annualized return, so it is entirely about time.\n\nThey disagree constantly. Flipping a deal in one year for 1.5x is a 50% IRR and only half your money back. Holding eight years for 3x is a 15% IRR but far more actual profit.\n\nThe point: LPs look at both because each is gameable alone. IRR can be juiced by selling early or recapping fast. Multiple ignores that money returned sooner can be reinvested. Neither is the truth by itself, which is why you always see them quoted together.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A sponsor is deciding between paying down debt and holding cash. What drives the choice?",a:"Compare the interest rate on the debt against what the cash earns, and then against what else the cash could do.\n\nPaying down debt is a guaranteed return equal to the after-tax interest rate. If the debt costs 8% and cash earns 2%, repaying is worth 6% risk-free. But debt paydown also converts directly into equity value at exit, dollar for dollar.\n\nHolding cash buys optionality: an acquisition, a downturn cushion, or a covenant buffer.\n\nThe point: in most LBOs the cash sweep is mandatory anyway, the credit agreement requires excess cash to repay debt. So the choice is often the lender's, not the sponsor's, which is one of the real costs of leverage.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do sponsors care about the exit multiple more than almost anything else?",a:"Because it is the single biggest swing factor and the one they control least. Entry multiple times EBITDA sets what you pay; exit multiple times EBITDA sets what you get. A one-turn move on a 10x deal is a 10% swing in enterprise value, and because equity is a thin slice underneath the debt, that becomes a much larger swing in equity value.\n\nThe point: this is why underwriting multiple expansion is treated as a bad sign. The sponsor is betting on market conditions five years out, which nobody can forecast. Serious cases assume flat or lower exit multiples and make the returns work on EBITDA growth and debt paydown instead.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Break down where returns come from in a deal that returns 3x.",a:"Attribute it to three sources, and be able to separate them.\n\nEBITDA growth. Higher EBITDA at the same multiple means more enterprise value. This is operational and it is what a sponsor can genuinely influence.\n\nDebt paydown. Every dollar of debt repaid with the company's cash converts to equity value with no change in enterprise value at all.\n\nMultiple expansion. Selling higher than you bought. This is the market, not you.\n\nThe point: LPs run this attribution to find out whether a firm is good or lucky. A track record built on multiple expansion during a decade of falling rates is not a repeatable skill. One built on EBITDA growth is.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a management rollover and why do sponsors want it?",a:"Management reinvests some of their sale proceeds into the new company rather than cashing out entirely. They roll, say, 20% of their equity into the deal.\n\nSponsors want it for alignment. If the CEO cashed out completely, they have no stake in whether the next five years work. If a meaningful part of their net worth rides on the exit, incentives point the same direction.\n\nThe point: it is also a signal. If management refuses to roll anything, ask why. The people who know the business best declining to invest in it is information the sponsor should take seriously.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is an exchange ratio and when would a deal use a floating one?",a:"The number of buyer shares each target share converts into. A fixed ratio locks the share count and lets the value move with the buyer's stock. A floating ratio locks the value and lets the share count move.\n\nFixed means the seller carries the risk of the buyer's stock falling between signing and closing. Floating means the buyer carries it, and issues more shares if its price drops.\n\nThe point: which one you get is a negotiation about who bears market risk over a period that can run months. Deals often compromise with a collar, fixing the ratio inside a price band and letting it float outside.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a contribution analysis?",a:"A comparison of what each side brings against what each side gets. You calculate what percentage of combined revenue, EBITDA, and net income comes from the buyer versus the target, and compare that with the ownership split after the deal.\n\nIf the target contributes 30% of the EBITDA but its shareholders end up with 40% of the company, the buyer is paying a premium, and this frames how large.\n\nThe point: it is most useful in merger-of-equals situations, where the language is partnership and the question is really who is buying whom. It is a reality check on the ownership split, not a valuation method.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A buyer and target both have 100M shares at $20. They merge as equals. Who controls the company?",a:"On paper, nobody, since each side owns 50%. In practice, control is decided by everything except the share split.\n\nWho becomes CEO. Who chairs the board and how many directors each side appoints. Whose headquarters survives. Whose systems get adopted. Whose name goes on the door.\n\nThe point: mergers of equals are usually acquisitions with better manners. The 50-50 framing is often there to help the smaller side's board sell it to shareholders. Within two years the reporting lines usually reveal who actually bought whom, which is why these deals have a poor track record: two management teams with equal claims and no single decider.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do buyers pay a premium at all if the market already prices the target?",a:"Two reasons, one economic and one practical.\n\nEconomic. The buyer gets control, so it can capture synergies that no passive shareholder could. If combining creates $200M of value, the buyer can share some of that with the seller and still come out ahead.\n\nPractical. Shareholders will not sell at the market price, because they can already sell at the market price. You need to give them a reason to tender.\n\nThe point: the whole negotiation is about how the synergy value gets split. A buyer paying a premium larger than the synergies has handed the entire benefit to the seller's shareholders, which is the single most common way acquirers destroy value.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the difference between an operating lease and a finance lease today?",a:"Both now sit on the balance sheet with a right-of-use asset and a lease liability, which is the big change from the old rules. The difference is how the cost hits the income statement.\n\nA finance lease splits the cost into depreciation and interest, both below EBITDA, so EBITDA looks higher. An operating lease keeps a single straight-line lease expense in operating costs, so it stays inside EBITDA.\n\nThe point: the balance sheet no longer hides anything, but the income statement classification still matters for every EBITDA-based multiple and every leverage covenant. Two companies with identical economics can report different EBITDA purely on lease classification.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why did off-balance-sheet leases get eliminated?",a:"Because they hid enormous obligations. A retailer with hundreds of leased stores had a contractual commitment to pay rent for years, economically almost identical to debt, and none of it appeared on the balance sheet. It sat in a footnote.\n\nAnalysts had to reconstruct it by capitalizing rent at a rough multiple, typically eight times, which was a crude guess at best.\n\nThe point: two companies could be identical, one owning its stores and one leasing, and the leasing company would look far less levered while carrying the same fixed obligations. Putting leases on the balance sheet closed a gap between the accounting and the economics.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has $500M of debt and $2B of lease obligations. How levered is it really?",a:"Far more than the debt number suggests. Lease obligations are contractual fixed payments the company cannot walk away from, which is the defining feature of debt.\n\nCredit analysts treat them as debt-like. Adjusted leverage would use $2.5B against EBITDAR, meaning EBITDA before rent, so both sides of the ratio are consistent.\n\nThe point: the answer depends on the leases. A ten-year lease on a specialized facility is essentially debt. A two-year lease on generic office space is closer to a real operating cost, since you can exit it soon. Treating all leases identically is as wrong as ignoring them.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is EBITDAR and who uses it?",a:"EBITDA before rent. You add rent expense back so the metric is comparable across companies that own their assets and companies that lease them.\n\nAirlines, restaurants, and retailers use it, because within those industries the own-versus-lease decision varies enormously and would otherwise dominate the comparison.\n\nThe point: it only works if you are consistent on both sides. Add rent back to EBITDA and you must also add the capitalized lease obligation to debt. Using EBITDAR against unadjusted debt makes every leasing company look artificially cheap, which is the entire trap.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How does working capital affect a DCF?",a:"It is a direct cash adjustment. Growing working capital consumes cash, so you subtract the increase from free cash flow. Shrinking working capital releases cash, so you add it.\n\nThe mechanism is that receivables and inventory tie up money, while payables and deferred revenue supply it. A growing company usually has to fund more of both, which is why growth consumes cash even when profitable.\n\nThe point: people forget it in the terminal year. If revenue is still growing at 3% forever, working capital must keep growing too, and terminal free cash flow should reflect that. Modeling terminal working capital at zero overstates the value.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is the difference between capex and maintenance capex?",a:"Maintenance capex is what you must spend just to keep the business at its current level: replacing worn equipment, refreshing stores. Growth capex is discretionary spending to make the business bigger: new factories, new locations.\n\nCompanies rarely disclose the split, so analysts estimate it, often by anchoring maintenance capex near depreciation, which is roughly the cost of assets wearing out.\n\nThe point: the distinction drives free cash flow. A company spending heavily on growth looks cash-poor while being highly profitable at its current size. Judging it on total capex misses that most of the spending is optional, which is exactly the case a sponsor makes when they cut growth capex post-buyout.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Two companies have identical revenue and EBITDA. One converts 90% of EBITDA to free cash flow, the other 40%. Where did the difference go?",a:"Into the gap between EBITDA and cash, and there are only a few places it can hide.\n\nCapex. The 40% company is likely capital intensive, spending constantly on equipment.\n\nWorking capital. It may be funding customers on long terms or holding heavy inventory.\n\nInterest. It may be more levered, so more of the cash goes to lenders.\n\nCash taxes. Different jurisdictions, or the other company may have NOLs shielding it.\n\nThe point: EBITDA called them identical and they are not remotely. This is the strongest argument against valuing anything on EBITDA alone, and it is why cash conversion is one of the first diligence questions in any buyout.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is a NOL and why does a buyer care about it?",a:"A net operating loss is a past loss the company can use to offset future taxable income. It is a real asset, because it means cash tax the company will not have to pay.\n\nA buyer cares because it changes the after-tax cash flow of the target. Buying a company with large NOLs means the first several years of profit may be tax-free.\n\nThe point: the rules limit how much of an acquired NOL you can use after a change of control, precisely to stop companies being bought for their tax attributes alone. So the value of the NOL to a buyer is usually far less than its face amount, and it gets discounted accordingly in the model.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why is a dollar of EBITDA in a software company worth more than a dollar in a manufacturer?",a:"Because of what happens to the next dollar. Software has almost no marginal cost, so incremental revenue drops to the bottom line and margins expand with scale. Manufacturing has real marginal cost, so growth requires proportional spending.\n\nSoftware also converts more EBITDA into free cash, since capex is minimal, and the revenue is usually recurring, so this year's base carries forward.\n\nThe point: a multiple is a claim on future cash, not present cash. Identical EBITDA today with different growth, durability, and conversion is not identical at all. That gap is the whole reason multiples differ across sectors.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company reports adjusted EBITDA of $100M and GAAP operating income of $20M. What do you want to know?",a:"What is in the $80M gap. Walk it line by line.\n\nDepreciation and amortization are legitimate and expected. Stock compensation is non-cash but dilutes shareholders, so it is contested. Restructuring charges are fine once, and meaningless if they appear every year. Anything described as one-time, non-recurring, or normalized deserves a hard look.\n\nThe point: an $80M gap on $20M of GAAP income means the adjustments are four times the reported profit. That is not a rounding difference, that is the entire story of the company. Management is asking you to ignore most of its cost base, and the burden is on them to justify each line.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has EBITDA of $80M, capex of $30M, and D&A of $20M. What does that tell you?",a:"That the company is growing, or that it is capital intensive. Capex above depreciation means it is spending more than its assets are wearing out, so the asset base is expanding.\n\nRough maintenance capex is near depreciation, so about $20M. The other $10M is growth spending, which is discretionary.\n\nThe point: sustained capex above D&A is either a growth story or a treadmill, and the difference is whether revenue is growing with it. Capex persistently at 1.5x depreciation with flat revenue means the company is spending just to stand still, which is a much worse business than the EBITDA suggests.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do you subtract capex but not depreciation when calculating free cash flow?",a:"Because capex is the actual cash and depreciation is the accounting echo of it. You already added depreciation back precisely because it moved no money; subtracting it again would double count.\n\nCapex is when the money truly leaves. Depreciation is the same money being recognized as an expense across the years the asset serves you.\n\nThe point: they represent the same spending at different times. In a stable business they roughly offset, which is why EBITDA minus capex is a rough proxy for EBIT. In a growing one they diverge sharply, and the divergence is exactly what free cash flow is trying to capture.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the difference between EBIT and operating income?",a:"Usually nothing, and they are used interchangeably. Both mean earnings before interest and tax.\n\nThe difference appears when a company has non-operating income or expense sitting between the two, such as investment income or a gain on an asset sale. Operating income strictly covers the core business; EBIT is sometimes calculated as net income plus interest plus tax, which sweeps those non-operating items back in.\n\nThe point: know which one you are being handed. If a company has meaningful non-operating income, EBIT computed from the bottom up will be higher than operating income read off the top, and using the wrong one distorts every margin and every multiple.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's gross margin is falling but operating margin is flat. What is happening?",a:"Costs are rising in COGS and being offset below it. A few candidates.\n\nInput costs rose, or the mix shifted toward lower-margin products, or the company cut price to hold volume. Meanwhile operating expenses fell enough to hold the operating line, through cost cuts or through operating leverage as fixed costs spread over more revenue.\n\nThe point: flat operating margin is masking a deteriorating core. Gross margin is the cleanest read on pricing power, and losing it while propping up the bottom line with cost cuts is not sustainable, because you can only cut overhead once.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Revenue grew 20% but operating income grew 5%. What does that suggest?",a:"Costs grew faster than revenue, so the company is buying growth. Margins are compressing.\n\nCauses to check. Sales and marketing scaling faster than sales, meaning acquisition is getting more expensive. Price cuts driving volume. Mix shifting toward lower-margin customers. Or heavy investment ahead of revenue, which is deliberate.\n\nThe point: the interpretation depends on whether the spending is investment or leakage. A company deliberately spending to capture a market can justify it. A company where costs simply rose faster because pricing power slipped cannot, and the two look identical on the income statement. That is why you check gross margin first.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is operating leverage and why does it matter?",a:"The share of costs that are fixed. High operating leverage means most costs do not move with volume, so incremental revenue drops mostly to profit.\n\nIt cuts both ways. A software company or an airline has huge operating leverage: past breakeven, each extra sale is nearly pure margin. Below breakeven, the fixed costs are still there and losses compound fast.\n\nThe point: it explains why some businesses swing violently with small revenue changes. It is also why lenders are wary of high operating leverage combined with high financial leverage. Fixed costs plus fixed interest means a modest revenue decline can wipe out the equity.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has high fixed costs and revenue drops 10%. What happens to profit?",a:"It falls by much more than 10%, because the costs do not fall with the revenue.\n\nSay revenue is $100 with $70 of fixed costs and $10 of variable, so profit is $20. Drop revenue 10% to $90 and variable costs fall to $9, but fixed costs stay at $70. Profit is now $11, down 45% on a 10% revenue decline.\n\nThe point: that is operating leverage in reverse. It is why cyclicals with heavy fixed cost bases are dangerous LBO candidates. A normal downturn does not reduce earnings proportionally, it can eliminate them, and the interest bill does not care.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do banks care about tangible book value rather than book value?",a:"Because goodwill and intangibles cannot absorb losses. If a bank fails, goodwill from an old acquisition is worth exactly nothing to a depositor or a regulator.\n\nTangible book strips those out, leaving the real capital standing between the bank's losses and its creditors. Regulators think this way too, which is why capital ratios are built on tangible measures.\n\nThe point: for a bank the balance sheet is the business, so what counts is the capital that genuinely absorbs a loss. That is why price to tangible book is the standard, and why a bank that made a big goodwill-heavy acquisition can look better capitalized than it is.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is net interest margin and why does it matter for a bank?",a:"The difference between what a bank earns on its assets and what it pays for its funding, expressed as a percentage of earning assets. Lend at 6%, pay 2% on deposits, and the margin is roughly 4%.\n\nIt is the core profitability measure, because lending spread is the business.\n\nThe point: it moves with rates in ways that are not obvious. Rising rates usually help, since loan yields reprice faster than deposit rates, at least until depositors demand more or move their money. That lag is exactly what the 2023 bank failures were about, deposits repricing faster than anyone modeled.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How would you value an insurance company?",a:"On the equity side, like a bank, because enterprise value does not apply. Price to book and price to earnings are the standard multiples.\n\nThe intrinsic approach is to look at the two profit engines separately. Underwriting profit, measured by the combined ratio: below 100% means the premiums exceeded the claims and expenses. And investment income on the float, meaning the premiums held between collection and payout.\n\nThe point: an insurer can lose money underwriting and still be highly profitable, because it invests the float in the meantime. That is Buffett's entire model. So the combined ratio alone does not tell you whether the business works.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do utilities trade at lower multiples than software?",a:"Growth and reinvestment. A regulated utility grows with population and approved rate increases, so low single digits, and it must spend enormous capex on infrastructure just to serve that.\n\nSoftware grows far faster with almost no capital. The returns on incremental capital are wildly different.\n\nThe point: the multiple is not a judgment about quality, it is arithmetic about growth and cash conversion. A utility is often a fine investment, it just gets paid for through dividends and stability rather than through appreciation, which is exactly why they trade as bond substitutes and get repriced when rates move.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is a revolver and why does a company have one?",a:"A revolving credit facility, a line the company can draw on and repay repeatedly up to a limit. It is a credit card for a corporation.\n\nIt exists for timing, not for funding. Businesses with seasonal working capital, a retailer building inventory before the holidays, draw the revolver and repay it once the goods sell. It bridges the gap between paying suppliers and collecting from customers.\n\nThe point: a company drawing its revolver to fund operating losses rather than seasonal swings is in trouble, and a fully drawn revolver is one of the classic distress signals. In a model, the revolver is usually the plug that keeps cash from going negative.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the difference between a term loan A and a term loan B?",a:"A TLA is held by banks, amortizes meaningfully over its life, has a shorter maturity, and carries tighter covenants. Cheaper, but the principal comes down every year and the lender watches you.\n\nA TLB is held by institutional investors, usually funds. It amortizes at a token 1% a year with the balance due at maturity, runs longer, and has looser covenants. More expensive, far more flexible.\n\nThe point: sponsors prefer TLB precisely because minimal amortization leaves cash inside the business to fund growth or be swept at the sponsor's discretion. You pay a higher spread to avoid a repayment schedule, which is the trade at the heart of leveraged finance.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is mezzanine debt and where does it sit?",a:"Between senior debt and equity in the capital structure. It is subordinated, often unsecured, and typically carries a high coupon plus equity warrants.\n\nIt exists to fill a gap. If senior lenders will only fund 4x EBITDA and the sponsor needs 5.5x, mezzanine covers the difference at a price that reflects being paid after everyone else.\n\nThe point: it is expensive because of where it sits, not because of what it costs to originate. In a bankruptcy, senior gets paid first and mezzanine may recover little, so the return has to compensate. The equity kicker is how the lender participates in the upside they are taking equity-like risk for.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why would a company issue preferred stock instead of debt?",a:"Because it is not debt. Missing a preferred dividend does not trigger default; missing an interest payment does. That optionality is worth a lot to a company with volatile cash flow.\n\nRating agencies also give preferred partial equity treatment, so it can add capital without the same hit to credit metrics.\n\nThe point: it is more expensive than debt for two reasons. It sits behind debt in a bankruptcy, and the dividend is not tax-deductible, unlike interest. So the company pays it from after-tax money with no shield, which is why preferred is usually a tool for companies that cannot or should not add more debt.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the capital structure and why does the order matter?",a:"The stack of claims on a business, ordered by who gets paid first. Senior secured debt, then senior unsecured, then subordinated, then preferred, then common equity.\n\nThe order matters because it determines both risk and return. Senior secured lenders take the least risk, so they accept the lowest return. Common equity is last, so it can be wiped out entirely, which is why it demands the highest return.\n\nThe point: the order is the price. Every layer's cost is a function of its position, not of any negotiation. It also determines who controls a restructuring, since the class where the value runs out is the one that ends up owning the company.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why is equity the most expensive form of capital?",a:"Because it is last in line and has no promise attached. A lender has a contract: a coupon and a maturity date. A shareholder has a residual claim on whatever is left, which may be nothing.\n\nAdd the tax treatment. Interest is deductible so the government subsidizes it; dividends are paid from after-tax income with no shield.\n\nThe point: the intuition people miss is that equity feels free because nobody sends you a bill. No cash leaves when you issue stock. But shareholders require a return whether or not you pay it, and if you do not deliver it, they sell and your cost of capital rises. It is expensive precisely because it is invisible.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What does it mean if a company has a credit rating of BB?",a:"It is below investment grade, so high yield or junk. BB is the top of the speculative tier, one notch below BBB minus.\n\nPractically it means a higher coupon, tighter covenants, and a smaller pool of buyers, because many institutional mandates prohibit sub-investment-grade paper.\n\nThe point: the single most consequential move in credit is the step from BBB minus to BB plus. It is not a small increase in risk, it is the point at which a whole class of buyers becomes a forced seller. That is why companies fight so hard to defend the last investment-grade notch, sometimes with decisions that make no operating sense.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What happens to a company's WACC if it issues debt to buy back stock?",a:"In the short run it falls, since you are replacing expensive equity with cheaper, tax-deductible debt and shifting the weights toward the cheaper source.\n\nBut both components respond. More leverage makes the remaining equity riskier, so cost of equity rises through a higher levered beta. Lenders also demand more as leverage climbs, so cost of debt rises.\n\nThe point: WACC falls, bottoms out, then rises. The bottom of that curve is the theoretical optimal capital structure. In practice nobody can locate it precisely, which is why companies target a credit rating instead of a WACC number.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do companies hold cash instead of paying it out?",a:"Optionality and fear, mostly. Cash funds acquisitions without a financing round, survives a downturn without going to the market at the worst moment, and covers working capital swings.\n\nThere are also structural reasons. Cash held overseas may face tax on repatriation. And once you pay a dividend, cutting it is punished brutally, so companies are cautious about starting.\n\nThe point: the counterargument is that a company hoarding cash it cannot deploy at a decent return should give it back, because shareholders can invest it themselves. Excess cash is a drag on return on equity and it makes the company a target, which is exactly the case activists make.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company announces a large buyback and the stock falls. Why might that happen?",a:"Because the market read it as an admission. If a company cannot find anything better to do with its cash than buy its own stock, it may be signaling that it sees no growth opportunities worth funding.\n\nOther readings. The buyback may look like management propping up EPS to hit a compensation target. Or the market thinks the shares are already expensive, so the company is destroying value by buying high.\n\nThe point: a buyback is only value-creating below intrinsic value. Above it, management is transferring value from continuing shareholders to the ones who sold. The market sometimes notices which one is happening.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company buys a supplier. What is that called and why do it?",a:"Vertical integration, specifically backward integration since it is moving up its own supply chain.\n\nReasons. Secure supply of something critical. Capture the supplier's margin. Control quality or timing. Or shut a competitor out of a scarce input.\n\nThe point: it looks attractive in a model because you are buying a margin you currently pay away. In practice you have also bought a business you do not know how to run, with different economics and different customers, and you have converted a variable cost into a fixed asset. That is why vertical integration works best when the input is scarce or strategic, and poorly when it is just a cost line.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the difference between a horizontal and a vertical merger?",a:"Horizontal is buying a competitor at the same stage: two airlines, two banks. Vertical is buying up or down the supply chain: an airline buying a maintenance provider.\n\nHorizontal deals are where the cost synergies live, since the overlap is real. They also draw antitrust scrutiny for exactly that reason.\n\nThe point: the synergy case differs completely. Horizontal deals promise cost cuts, which are countable and believable. Vertical deals promise control and margin capture, which are harder to quantify and easier to overpay for. Regulators generally worry more about horizontal deals because they directly reduce the number of competitors.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What would block a deal on antitrust grounds?",a:"Concentration. If the combination gives the merged company enough share to raise prices, the regulator objects. They look at market share, how concentrated the market already is, and whether customers have alternatives.\n\nThe fight is usually over market definition. A company will define the market as broadly as possible to look small; the regulator defines it narrowly.\n\nThe point: deals often clear with remedies rather than being blocked outright, divesting overlapping assets to a third party. That is why merger agreements negotiate hard over who bears regulatory risk, and why reverse termination fees exist: the seller wants compensation if the buyer cannot get it approved.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a hostile takeover and how does it work?",a:"An acquisition pursued against the target board's wishes. The buyer goes around the board directly to shareholders.\n\nTwo main routes. A tender offer, buying shares directly from holders at a premium. Or a proxy fight, persuading shareholders to replace the board with directors who will approve the deal.\n\nThe point: they are rare and expensive, because you cannot do diligence. The target will not open its books, so you are bidding on public information alone. That uncertainty means you usually have to pay more, and you inherit a management team that did not want you there.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What defenses does a company have against a hostile bid?",a:"A poison pill is the main one: if a bidder crosses a share threshold, all other shareholders can buy stock cheaply, massively diluting the acquirer and making the purchase impossible.\n\nOthers. A staggered board, so only a third of directors can be replaced each year, meaning a proxy fight takes two years. Finding a white knight, a friendlier buyer. Or the target buying something itself to become less digestible.\n\nThe point: most defenses do not stop a deal, they buy time and leverage. A pill is almost always negotiated away once the board has extracted a higher price. Its real function is to force the bidder to the table rather than to the shareholders.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a go-shop provision?",a:"A window after signing, often 30 to 45 days, during which the target may actively solicit other bidders despite already having a deal.\n\nIt exists to protect the board. Directors have a duty to get the best price, and if they signed with the first bidder without testing the market, they are exposed to a lawsuit. A go-shop lets them run the check after locking in a floor.\n\nThe point: it is most common in private equity deals where the process was not broadly marketed. It rarely produces a topping bid, since the break fee and the head start deter rivals. Its function is largely defensive: it is evidence of process.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a break fee and who pays it?",a:"A payment triggered if the deal falls apart. The target pays a break fee, typically 2% to 4% of deal value, if it walks away, usually to accept a better offer.\n\nThe buyer pays a reverse termination fee, often larger, if it fails to close, usually because financing collapsed or regulators blocked it.\n\nThe point: the fee is not really compensation for costs, it is a deterrent. A target break fee raises the price a rival must beat, which protects the first bidder. Its size is negotiated precisely because too large a fee makes a competing bid uneconomic, which courts have pushed back on.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is due diligence actually looking for?",a:"Whether the numbers are real and whether the risks are known. Quality of earnings work tests whether the reported EBITDA is repeatable or propped up by one-time items and aggressive accounting.\n\nBeyond that: customer concentration and contract terms, whether revenue is truly recurring, pending litigation, environmental liabilities, tax exposure, the state of the systems, and whether key employees will stay.\n\nThe point: diligence rarely kills a deal outright. It repriced it. The finding that matters is usually a number: adjusted EBITDA is $85M, not $100M, so the price at the same multiple drops accordingly. That is why QofE is the first workstream and the one buyers pay most attention to.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a working capital adjustment in a purchase agreement?",a:"A true-up. The parties agree a normal level of working capital the business should have at closing, called the peg. If actual working capital at close is above the peg, the buyer pays the seller the difference; below, the price drops.\n\nIt exists because working capital swings and the seller controls the business until closing.\n\nThe point: without it the seller has an obvious incentive to strip cash out before closing, collect every receivable aggressively, stop paying suppliers, and run inventory down. The buyer would then inherit a business that needs an immediate cash injection just to operate. The peg removes the incentive to game the last month.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why would a seller prefer a private equity buyer over a strategic buyer?",a:"Usually they do not, because strategics pay more, since they have synergies. But there are reasons.\n\nSpeed and certainty. A sponsor has no antitrust overlap, so approval is simpler. Confidentiality, since you are not opening your books to a competitor who may walk away with your customer list. Management continuity, because a sponsor needs the team to stay while a strategic often has its own. And the chance to roll equity and get a second bite at the exit.\n\nThe point: for a founder, who runs the business afterwards can matter more than the last turn of price. That is exactly what a sponsor sells against a strategic bid.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company trades at 8x EBITDA. Its peers trade at 12x. Is it a buy?",a:"Not on that alone. The gap is the question, not the answer, and there are three possibilities.\n\nThe market is right and you are misreading the comps. It may have worse growth, higher customer concentration, more leverage, worse margins, or a governance problem.\n\nThe comps are wrong. It may not actually belong in that set, or the set is being dragged by one expensive name.\n\nThe market is wrong. Possible, but it is the least likely of the three and needs the most evidence.\n\nThe point: a discount to peers is a starting question. Cheap relative to peers with a reason is not cheap, it is correctly priced. The work is finding out which of the three explains it.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How do you sanity check a valuation?",a:"Cross the methods against each other. If the DCF says $50 and comps say $30, one of them is wrong and you should find out which before presenting either.\n\nInside the DCF, check the implied exit multiple against your comps set, and the implied perpetuity growth against long-run GDP. Check what percentage terminal value is of the total.\n\nThen step back. Does the implied enterprise value make sense against the company's revenue? Does the implied share price look sane against the 52-week range?\n\nThe point: models produce numbers regardless of whether the inputs were sensible. The sanity check is where you find the assumption that quietly broke, and it is what separates an analyst who builds models from one who understands them.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"You are handed a model and told the balance sheet does not balance. Where do you look?",a:"Work the loop, since the error is always in the links. Check that net income flows correctly from the income statement to both the cash flow statement and retained earnings.\n\nThen check signs, which is where most errors live. Capex should be negative, a working capital increase should be a use of cash, debt repayment should be an outflow.\n\nThen check that every balance sheet change appears somewhere on the cash flow statement, and that the ending cash on the cash flow statement is what the balance sheet is pulling.\n\nThe point: the imbalance amount is a clue. If it equals a number you recognize, that item is either double counted or missing entirely. If it is exactly twice something, you have a sign flip.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is a circular reference in a model and why does it happen?",a:"Interest depends on the debt balance, the debt balance depends on how much cash is available to repay, cash available depends on net income, and net income depends on interest. The model chases its own tail.\n\nIt is handled either by enabling iterative calculation, which lets the model converge, or by breaking the circularity, typically by calculating interest on the beginning-of-period balance rather than the average.\n\nThe point: circularity is a genuine feature of the economics, not a mistake. The debt schedule really does depend on itself. Most banks ban iterative calc because a single error propagates everywhere and the model becomes unstable, so they use beginning balances and accept the small inaccuracy.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a cash sweep in an LBO model?",a:"A mechanism where excess cash automatically repays debt rather than accumulating on the balance sheet. The credit agreement requires it.\n\nMechanically, the model calculates cash available after all obligations, applies a percentage, often 50% to 100%, and pays down the most senior tranche first.\n\nThe point: it drives returns directly, because every dollar swept converts into equity value at exit. It also explains why sponsors negotiate hard over the sweep percentage. Cash inside the business is optionality for the sponsor; cash swept to lenders is safety for them. That tension is one of the main points of contention in a credit agreement.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do you build a debt schedule in an LBO model?",a:"Because the debt is the entire point. You need to track each tranche separately: opening balance, mandatory amortization, optional prepayment from the sweep, and closing balance. Interest is then calculated off those balances and fed back into the income statement.\n\nWithout it you cannot compute interest correctly, cannot know the debt remaining at exit, and therefore cannot compute equity proceeds.\n\nThe point: the debt schedule is where an LBO differs from a DCF. A DCF values the business; an LBO tracks who owns the cash the business produces, year by year. The returns come out of that schedule, not out of the operating model.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is PIK toggle debt?",a:"Debt that lets the borrower choose each period whether to pay interest in cash or roll it into the principal. The PIK option usually carries a higher rate as the price of the flexibility.\n\nIt exists to protect liquidity. In a bad year the company toggles to PIK, preserves cash, and grows the balance instead.\n\nThe point: it is a safety valve that quietly compounds. Toggling feels free in the moment and each toggle enlarges the obligation at a higher rate. It appeared heavily before the financial crisis and is treated as a late-cycle marker precisely because it lets weak deals postpone the reckoning.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the difference between secured and unsecured debt in a recovery?",a:"Secured debt has a claim on specific collateral: property, equipment, receivables, or all assets. In a bankruptcy it gets paid from those assets first, up to their value.\n\nUnsecured debt has a general claim on whatever is left after secured lenders are satisfied.\n\nThe point: the difference is enormous in a recovery and it is why the pricing differs. Secured lenders in a typical bankruptcy might recover 70 to 90 cents; unsecured might get 20 to 40; equity usually zero. But secured is only as good as the collateral. A first lien on specialized machinery nobody wants is a claim on an auction that raises very little.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What does it mean to be structurally subordinated?",a:"Your claim sits at the wrong entity. Lend to a holding company whose only asset is stock in an operating subsidiary, and you are behind every creditor of that subsidiary, even if your debt is labeled senior.\n\nThe reason is that the operating company's creditors get paid from its assets first. Only what is left flows up to the holding company as equity, and only then does the holdco lender see anything.\n\nThe point: the label on the paper does not tell you where you stand. Senior holdco debt can be worse than subordinated opco debt. Where the debt sits in the corporate structure matters more than what it is called, which is exactly what catches people out in restructurings.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is a springing lien or a covenant that only applies when the revolver is drawn?",a:"A term that stays dormant until a trigger. A springing financial covenant typically only applies if the revolver is drawn beyond a threshold, say 35%.\n\nIt exists because revolver lenders want protection when they have real money out, but the borrower does not want a quarterly test when the line is undrawn.\n\nThe point: it explains a behavior that looks strange from outside. Companies sometimes repay a revolver right before quarter end specifically to stay below the trigger. It is a legitimate reading of the agreement and it also means the reported balance can understate how much the company actually relies on the line.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company has a 40% gross margin and wants to grow revenue 50%. What does it need?",a:"Working capital, mostly, and the amount depends on the model. Growing revenue 50% typically means growing receivables and inventory close to 50% too, and that cash has to come from somewhere before customers pay.\n\nIt may also need capacity, meaning capex, and more people, meaning higher operating expenses before the revenue arrives.\n\nThe point: at a 40% gross margin, every dollar of new revenue costs 60 cents in COGS that must be paid before collection. This is why growth is a use of cash, and why fast-growing profitable companies still raise money. The margin determines how self-funding the growth can be, which is why software at 80% margins scales differently from distribution at 15%.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the cash conversion cycle?",a:"Days inventory outstanding plus days sales outstanding minus days payables outstanding. It measures how long cash is trapped in the business.\n\nYou buy inventory, hold it, sell it, wait to be paid. That is the outflow. Meanwhile you owe suppliers and have not paid them, which is the offset. The net is how many days you are funding the gap.\n\nThe point: it can be negative, which is excellent. Amazon collects from customers before paying suppliers, so it runs on other people's money. A long positive cycle means growth requires cash, which is why the metric matters far more than it sounds.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Days sales outstanding jumps from 45 to 70. What do you do?",a:"Find out whether it is collections, customers, or accounting. Three checks.\n\nIs it concentrated in one customer? A single large client stretching payment is a different problem from a broad deterioration.\n\nDid the company change terms? Extending payment terms to win business is a quiet price cut that shows up here.\n\nIs revenue being recognized too early? Sales booked that customers dispute, or channel stuffing at quarter end.\n\nThe point: a 25-day jump means about 7% of annual revenue moved from cash into receivables. That is a real cash cost and it is often the first visible sign of either customer distress or aggressive accounting.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why is inventory turnover important?",a:"It measures how many times a year the company sells and replaces its stock. High turnover means capital is not sitting idle on shelves.\n\nLow turnover ties up cash, costs money to store, and risks obsolescence, which matters enormously in fashion, electronics, and food.\n\nThe point: the right number is industry-specific, so the comparison must be against peers. A grocer turns inventory dozens of times a year; a jeweller a couple. Falling turnover with flat sales is a warning: the company bought goods it cannot move, and a write-down is usually coming.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's inventory is growing faster than sales. What does that suggest?",a:"Demand is weaker than the company expected. It built or bought stock against a forecast that did not materialize.\n\nOther readings. It may be stocking up deliberately ahead of a launch or a supply disruption. Or it may be building inventory to absorb fixed manufacturing costs, which flatters gross margin now and creates a problem later.\n\nThe point: it consumes cash today and threatens earnings tomorrow, because unsold inventory eventually gets written down. Inventory outgrowing sales is one of the most reliable early indicators that the next quarter will disappoint.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is channel stuffing?",a:"Pushing more product to distributors than they can sell, usually near quarter end, to book revenue now. The company offers discounts or extended terms to get it out the door.\n\nIt shows up in the numbers. Revenue spikes at period end, receivables balloon, days sales outstanding jumps, and returns rise the following quarter.\n\nThe point: it is borrowing from the future. The distributor is now overstocked and orders nothing next quarter, so the problem compounds and requires more stuffing to hide. That is why it usually ends in a restatement, and why the pattern of receivables outrunning revenue is worth taking seriously.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"How can a company manipulate its operating cash flow?",a:"By moving things across the boundaries. Stretch payables so cash sits in operating a little longer. Squeeze receivables at period end with discounts, pulling cash forward. Sell receivables outright through factoring, converting a future collection into cash today.\n\nOr reclassify. Capitalize costs that could be expensed, so the outflow moves from operating to investing and operating cash flow rises with nothing changing.\n\nThe point: operating cash flow is harder to manipulate than earnings, not impossible. The tells are one-time working capital improvements that do not repeat, and a widening gap between operating cash flow and free cash flow, which is where the capitalized spending hides.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the difference between operating cash flow and free cash flow?",a:"Operating cash flow is cash from running the business, after working capital and cash taxes and interest, but before any investment.\n\nFree cash flow subtracts capital expenditures, so it is what remains after paying to maintain and grow the asset base. It is what could actually be returned to investors.\n\nThe point: the gap is the whole story for a capital-intensive company. A telecom can post enormous operating cash flow and almost no free cash flow, because it spends everything on the network. Judging it on operating cash flow alone makes it look like a cash machine when it is a treadmill.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company shows growing net income and declining operating cash flow for three straight years. What is your conclusion?",a:"That the earnings are not real, or at least not converting. Sustained divergence between profit and cash is the single most reliable warning in financial analysis.\n\nThe likely causes. Receivables growing faster than revenue, meaning sales to customers who do not pay. Inventory building. Aggressive revenue recognition booking earnings before cash. Or capitalizing costs that should be expensed, which lifts net income and moves the cash out of operating.\n\nThe point: net income is an opinion, cash is a fact. One year of divergence has explanations. Three years in the same direction means the accounting and the economics have separated, and the accounting will eventually be forced to catch up.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do you care about revenue recognition policy?",a:"Because it determines when a sale becomes revenue, and that timing decision is where the most aggressive accounting lives.\n\nThe questions. Is revenue booked on shipment or on delivery? Is a multi-year contract recognized upfront or over the term? Are there side agreements letting customers return goods? Is the company recognizing gross when it is really an agent earning a fee, which inflates revenue without touching profit?\n\nThe point: revenue is the top line, so every multiple and every margin is built on it. Shifting recognition earlier is the easiest way to manufacture growth, it requires no cash, and it is self-correcting in the worst way: you eventually run out of future quarters to borrow from.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Pitch me a stock.",a:"Structure it in four parts and keep it under two minutes.\n\nThe recommendation first. Buy or sell, and the price target. Do not build suspense.\n\nWhat the company does, in one sentence, and how it makes money.\n\nWhy the market is wrong. This is the whole pitch. Not that the company is good, everyone knows that, but what you believe that the current price does not reflect.\n\nValuation and the risk. What it is worth on your numbers, and the one thing that would break your thesis.\n\nThe point: the third part is what they are testing. A pitch that says a great company with strong management is not a pitch, it is a description. The thesis has to be a disagreement with the price.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is a variant view and why do interviewers want one?",a:"A belief you hold that the market does not. The stock is at $40 because consensus expects margins to stay at 10%; you think they reach 15% because of a specific reason, so it is worth $60.\n\nWithout one, there is no reason to own the stock. If you agree with consensus on everything, the price is already right and there is no return in it.\n\nThe point: this is what separates a pitch from a summary. Most candidates describe a good business and stop. Naming the specific thing you believe that others do not, and why you might be right when the market is not, is the entire exercise. It is also why it should be falsifiable.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A stock is down 40%. How do you decide whether it is a buying opportunity?",a:"Ask what changed, and separate price from value. Three possibilities.\n\nThe business genuinely deteriorated, so the lower price is correct and it is not cheap.\n\nThe market overreacted to something temporary: a bad quarter, a sector selloff, an earnings miss driven by timing.\n\nSomething broke that has not fully surfaced yet, and 40% will look generous later.\n\nThe point: the number itself is meaningless. A stock down 40% from a bubble is still expensive; one down 40% on a fixable problem may be a gift. The work is deciding whether the earnings power changed or only the multiple did.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What do you think is going on in the markets right now?",a:"Have a view and support it with two or three specifics. What rates are doing and why it matters for valuations. What is happening in deal volumes and IPO activity, which is directly relevant to the job. One sector or story you have actually followed.\n\nWhat fails. Reciting headlines without a view, or claiming everything is uncertain.\n\nThe point: the question is not testing prediction, it is testing whether you pay attention and can form an argument. Having one specific, defensible opinion with a reason beats a broad summary of the news. They also want to hear you connect it back to what the bank does, since M&A and financing volumes are the business.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"How do rising interest rates affect valuations?",a:"Through the discount rate, primarily. Higher risk-free rates raise cost of equity and cost of debt, so WACC rises, so the same future cash flows are worth less today.\n\nIt hits growth companies hardest. Their value sits far in the future, and distant cash flows get discounted most severely when rates rise. A company earning cash now is less affected than one promising cash in ten years.\n\nThe point: there is a second channel people forget. Higher rates also raise the cost of borrowing, which reduces what a leveraged buyer can pay, so deal multiples compress. And they slow the economy, so the cash flows themselves shrink. Rates hit the numerator and the denominator at once.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why did M&A volumes fall when rates rose?",a:"Because leverage got expensive and the bid-ask spread widened.\n\nSponsors fund with debt, so higher rates mean less debt supportable at the same coverage, which means a bigger equity cheque and a lower price to hit the same return. Buyers had to bid less.\n\nMeanwhile sellers anchored to the valuations of the prior cycle and refused to accept lower prices. Deals do not happen when the buyer's maximum is below the seller's minimum.\n\nThe point: volumes fall not because nobody wants to transact but because the two sides are pricing off different reference points. Activity resumes once sellers accept the new level, which is why the gap usually closes on the seller's side, slowly.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What happens to a leveraged company when rates rise on its floating-rate debt?",a:"Interest expense rises immediately with no change in the business. Net income falls, cash falls, and coverage ratios deteriorate.\n\nThe danger is covenants. A company running interest coverage at 2x can drop toward 1x on a rate move alone, breaching a maintenance covenant despite having missed no payment and lost no customer.\n\nThe point: this is why fixed versus floating mix matters so much in an LBO. A sponsor that financed floating in a low-rate world made the deal cheaper at the time and took on a risk that had nothing to do with operations. Hedging exists precisely because that risk is uncompensated.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do banks care about deal volumes?",a:"Because advisory fees are the revenue. M&A fees, underwriting fees on equity and debt, and financing fees all scale with transaction activity.\n\nWhen volumes fall, the fee pool shrinks, and banks are largely a fixed-cost business made of people. That is why headcount follows the cycle so closely.\n\nThe point: it matters to you directly. Analyst hiring, bonuses, and deal experience all track volumes. Knowing roughly where volumes are and why is one of the easiest ways to sound like someone who understands the business they are applying to rather than the version in a textbook.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the difference between a bull and a bear case, and why present both?",a:"The bull case is what happens if the thesis works: what assumptions and what value. The bear case is what happens if it does not, and specifically what would have to be true for you to be wrong.\n\nYou present both because a one-sided pitch is not analysis, it is advocacy. Anyone can build a case for anything by choosing assumptions.\n\nThe point: the bear case is where credibility is earned. A candidate who cannot articulate the strongest argument against their own recommendation has not done the work, or has done it and ignored the inconvenient half. Knowing precisely what would falsify your view is what makes the view worth hearing.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"If you had $1 million to invest today, what would you do with it?",a:"Have an actual answer with reasoning, not a hedge. A defensible structure: what proportion in equities and why, what in fixed income given where rates are, and one or two specific ideas you can defend.\n\nWhat matters is the reasoning. Why that allocation, given your time horizon and what you think the market is mispricing.\n\nThe point: the trap is saying index funds and stopping, which is probably correct financially and tells them nothing. They are testing whether you have opinions and can defend them under questioning. Name something specific, expect to be challenged on it, and have the second layer of the argument ready.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company acquires another for $1B. $600M is allocated to identifiable intangibles with a 10-year life, the rest to goodwill. Tax rate 25%. What happens to earnings?",a:"Income statement. The $600M of intangibles amortize at $60M a year, so pre-tax income falls $60M annually. Tax falls $15M, so net income falls $45M every year for a decade. The $400M of goodwill does not amortize, so it costs nothing until impaired.\n\nCash flow statement. The amortization is non-cash, so it is added straight back. No cash effect beyond the tax treatment.\n\nThe point: the allocation decides the earnings drag. Push more into goodwill and reported earnings look better for ten years. Push more into intangibles and you carry $45M of annual dilution. Nothing about the business changes either way, which is why buyers argue over purchase price allocation and why analysts add amortization of acquired intangibles back.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do acquirers add back amortization of acquired intangibles?",a:"Because it says nothing about how the business is running. It is an accounting consequence of a purchase that happened years ago, not a cost of operating today.\n\nThe argument is reasonable. A customer list acquired in 2020 amortizing through 2030 tells you nothing about 2026 performance, and the cash left long ago.\n\nThe point: the counterargument is that if a company acquires continuously, the amortization is effectively a recurring cost of its growth strategy. A serial acquirer adding back amortization every year is excluding the cost of the very thing driving its growth, which is why the add-back is fair for a one-off deal and misleading for a roll-up.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a roll-up and why does it work?",a:"Buying many small companies in a fragmented industry and combining them. A sponsor buys a platform, then bolts on competitors.\n\nIt works on multiple arbitrage. Small companies trade at low multiples because they are risky, illiquid, and dependent on one owner. A large combined company trades higher because it is diversified and professionally run. Buy at 5x, integrate, sell the whole at 10x, and value is created purely by scale.\n\nThe point: it only works if integration is real. Buying twenty companies that keep operating separately is a holding company with twenty problems, not a platform. The multiple arbitrage is the reward for actually integrating, and it disappears when a buyer is just accumulating.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the difference between a platform and a bolt-on acquisition?",a:"The platform is the first, larger purchase in a space. It needs to be able to carry the debt, have management worth keeping, and have systems capable of absorbing others.\n\nBolt-ons are the smaller subsequent purchases folded into the platform. They are cheaper per dollar of EBITDA, often bought at lower multiples, and they need no separate infrastructure.\n\nThe point: the economics are completely different. The platform gets bought at a full price and full diligence. Bolt-ons get bought at a discount and immediately revalued at the platform's multiple, which is where the value comes from. That gap is why sponsors will pay up for a platform with a real integration capability.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why can a private equity firm pay more for a company than it appears to be worth on a standalone DCF?",a:"Because the sponsor is not buying the cash flows the way a passive investor would. Several reasons.\n\nLeverage lets them capture returns on a small equity base. Cost cuts a public company would not make, because it fears the earnings hit. Bolt-ons that raise the exit multiple. And a rollover of management equity that reduces the cheque.\n\nThe point: the DCF says what the business is worth to its current owner running it the current way. A sponsor is underwriting a different business: more levered, leaner, larger at exit. That is why LBO valuation is an IRR calculation working backwards from a target return, not a value calculation working forwards.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A sponsor says they will improve EBITDA margin from 15% to 20%. How would you test that?",a:"Ask where the 500 basis points come from, specifically. Then check each source against evidence.\n\nHeadcount reduction: which roles, and what does that do to the business. Procurement savings: what is the actual spend and what discount is realistic. Pricing: is there evidence customers will pay more. Facility consolidation: which sites.\n\nThen benchmark. If peers run at 17%, a 20% target needs an explanation for why this company beats every competitor.\n\nThe point: margin improvement is the most casually assumed line in any model. The test is whether it is a list of specific actions with owners and timelines, or a number typed into a cell because the returns needed it.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is quality of earnings and why does every deal have one?",a:"A diligence exercise that tests whether reported EBITDA is real and repeatable. Accountants strip out one-time items, correct for aggressive accounting, and normalize for anything that will not recur.\n\nThe output is adjusted EBITDA, which is usually lower than what the seller presented.\n\nThe point: it directly moves the price. At an 8x multiple, finding that EBITDA is $85M rather than $100M cuts the value $120M. That is why QofE is the first workstream and why sellers increasingly commission their own before going to market, so they control the narrative rather than reacting to the buyer's version.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A seller presents adjusted EBITDA with 15 add-backs. What is your reaction?",a:"Scepticism proportional to the count. Go through them individually and sort into three buckets.\n\nLegitimate: genuinely one-time, like a single litigation settlement or a one-off restructuring, with documentation.\n\nArguable: owner compensation above market, personal expenses run through the business, rent paid to an entity the owner controls. These are real adjustments for a change of ownership but need verification.\n\nUnacceptable: anything recurring dressed as one-time, or pro forma synergies the buyer has not earned yet.\n\nThe point: fifteen add-backs is itself the finding. A business with genuinely clean earnings needs two or three. A long list usually means the real EBITDA is materially lower and the seller is negotiating through the accounting.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the difference between a strategic buyer and a financial buyer?",a:"A strategic buyer is an operating company in or near the same business. It can capture synergies, folding the target into its own operations, so it can pay more and still earn its return. It usually holds forever.\n\nA financial buyer is a sponsor. No synergies, so it pays standalone value. It uses leverage, improves the business, and must sell within a defined horizon because its fund has a life.\n\nThe point: the difference shows up in price and in what happens after. Strategics usually pay more and eliminate the target's management and brand. Sponsors pay less, keep the team, and sell in five years. Which one a seller prefers is often about what they want to happen to the company, not just the number.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why do private equity firms have to sell eventually?",a:"Because the fund has a finite life, typically ten years, and LPs committed capital on the promise of getting it back with a return. The sponsor cannot hold indefinitely, however good the business.\n\nIt also drives returns mechanically. IRR is time-weighted, so holding a good asset too long drags the annualized return down even as the multiple grows.\n\nThe point: this creates a structural feature worth understanding. Sponsors are forced sellers on a schedule the market does not care about, which is why exits cluster and why a fund reaching the end of its life during a bad window has a real problem. Continuation vehicles exist largely to solve this.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company has $50 of cash, $200 of debt, and a $400 market cap. It uses all its cash to repay debt. What happens to enterprise value?",a:"Nothing. EV was $400 plus $200 minus $50, or $550. After repaying, cash is $0 and debt is $150, so EV is $400 plus $150 minus $0, which is $550.\n\nEquity value is unchanged too, at least in theory, because the company swapped one asset for the removal of one liability of the same size. Shareholders own the same business.\n\nThe point: this is the cleanest demonstration of why EV is the right measure for comparing businesses. Moving cash around the balance sheet changes the equity-side optics and changes nothing about what the operations are worth. In practice interest expense falls, so future earnings rise slightly.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company issues $100 of stock and holds it as cash. What happens to enterprise value?",a:"Nothing. Equity value rises $100 because new shares were sold, and cash rises $100, which is subtracted. The two offset exactly, so EV is unchanged.\n\nThe point: this is the test of whether you understand what EV measures. The company obviously has more money and is obviously bigger on the equity side. But the operations produce exactly the same cash as yesterday, and EV is a measure of the operations. Raising money does not make a business more valuable, it just parks capital inside it.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why is EV/EBITDA the most common multiple?",a:"Because it neutralizes the things that differ for reasons unrelated to the business. Capital structure, since EBITDA is before interest and EV covers all capital providers. Tax jurisdiction, since it is before tax. Asset age and depreciation policy, since it is before D&A.\n\nThat lets you compare a levered company in one country with an unlevered one in another.\n\nThe point: every one of those advantages is also its weakness. Ignoring interest ignores that the levered company genuinely owes money. Ignoring D&A ignores that assets wear out. It is a comparison tool that works precisely because it strips out reality, so you have to put the reality back before concluding anything.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"When would you use EV/Revenue instead of EV/EBITDA?",a:"When EBITDA is negative, meaningless, or not comparable. That covers early-stage companies spending on growth, biotech before approval, and any business deliberately running at a loss to capture a market.\n\nAlso when accounting differences make EBITDA incomparable across a set, or when margins vary so much that the EBITDA multiples span an unusable range.\n\nThe point: revenue multiples are a confession that you cannot value on profit yet. They only work if you also anchor on the growth rate and the eventual margin, because a 3x revenue multiple on a 40% grower heading to 30% margins is completely different from 3x on a 5% grower heading to 8%.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's P/E is 10x and its competitor's is 25x. Both grow 10%. What explains the gap?",a:"Something other than growth, since growth is identical. Work through the candidates.\n\nRisk and durability. The 10x company may have customer concentration, cyclical demand, or contract revenue that must be rewon each year.\n\nCapital structure. P/E is after interest, so a heavily levered company shows lower earnings and can carry a lower multiple for the leverage risk.\n\nEarnings quality. The 10x company's profit may not convert to cash, or may rely on one-time gains.\n\nThe point: identical growth with different multiples means the market disagrees about the certainty of that growth, not the amount. P/E is a claim on future earnings weighted by confidence, and confidence is what is being priced here.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why is P/E affected by capital structure when EV/EBITDA is not?",a:"Because P/E sits at the bottom of the income statement, after interest. A levered company pays interest, so its net income is lower, so the same equity value produces a higher P/E, or the same P/E implies a lower price.\n\nEV/EBITDA sits above interest. EBITDA does not care who financed the business, and EV includes debt and equity both, so both sides are financing-neutral.\n\nThe point: this is why you use P/E for banks and financial institutions, where leverage is the business and stripping out interest destroys the meaning, and EV/EBITDA for operating companies, where you want to compare the operations independent of how someone chose to fund them.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What does a negative P/E mean?",a:"That the company lost money. The multiple is arithmetically negative and analytically useless, because there is no sense in which a company is trading at negative 15 times earnings.\n\nWhat you do instead. Move up the income statement to something positive: EV/EBITDA if EBITDA is positive, EV/Revenue if not. Or use price to book, or normalize earnings across a cycle if the loss is temporary.\n\nThe point: the mistake is treating it as a very low multiple and therefore cheap. A negative multiple carries no information about value at all. It is a signal that this metric does not apply to this company right now, not a signal to buy.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Two companies have the same EV/EBITDA but different EV/EBIT. What does that tell you?",a:"That they have different depreciation, so different capital intensity or different asset ages.\n\nIf EBITDA multiples match but one has a higher EV/EBIT, that company has more depreciation dragging EBIT down. It is either more capital intensive, or it recently invested heavily, or it depreciates faster.\n\nThe point: the EBITDA multiple called them identical and they are not. The company with more depreciation probably has to keep spending to stay in business, so more of its EBITDA never reaches shareholders. This is exactly the case for looking at EBIT or free cash flow in capital-intensive sectors rather than trusting EBITDA alone.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How does a company's growth rate justify a higher multiple?",a:"Because the multiple is a claim on future earnings, not current ones. A company growing 30% will have roughly double the earnings in under three years. Paying 30x today for that is paying about 15x on the earnings it will have soon.\n\nThe crude shorthand is PEG, dividing the P/E by the growth rate, where 1.0 is considered fair.\n\nThe point: PEG is a rule of thumb, not analysis. It ignores risk entirely, treats a 40% grower and a 4% grower as linearly comparable, and says nothing about whether the growth is durable or bought. The real question is not the growth rate but how long it persists and what it costs to sustain.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company beats earnings and the stock falls. Why?",a:"Because the beat was already priced, and something else in the report was not. The market trades on expectations, not on results.\n\nCommon causes. Guidance was cut, so the future looks worse even though the quarter was good. The beat came from a one-time item rather than operations. Margins compressed even as revenue grew. Or the whisper number was above consensus, so a beat against published estimates was actually a miss against what people expected.\n\nThe point: this is the most useful market lesson for an interview. Price reflects consensus expectations, so the result only matters relative to them. A company can post record earnings and fall hard because it told you next quarter will be worse.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has 100M shares at $40, $500M of debt, and $100M of cash. It buys back $200M of stock using cash and new debt equally. What happens to EV?",a:"Nothing, and that is the point. Before: EV is $4,000M plus $500M minus $100M, which is $4,400M.\n\nAfter: it spent $100M of cash and raised $100M of debt. Equity value falls $200M to $3,800M. Debt rises to $600M. Cash falls to $0. So EV is $3,800M plus $600M minus $0, which is $4,400M.\n\nThe point: enterprise value is untouched because the operations are untouched. All that changed is who has a claim: less equity, more debt, no cash. EPS will rise because the share count fell, and the company is riskier. The multiple looks identical and the equity underneath it does not.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do you use market value of equity but book value of debt in enterprise value?",a:"Because equity has an observable market price and debt usually does not, at least not reliably. Shares trade continuously, so market cap is a fact. Most corporate debt trades rarely or not at all.\n\nIt is also usually harmless. Debt trades near par unless rates have moved sharply or the credit has deteriorated, so book is a decent approximation.\n\nThe point: it stops being harmless exactly when it matters most. A distressed company's debt might trade at 60 cents while the balance sheet still says 100. Using book there overstates enterprise value badly, which is why distressed analysis uses market prices for the debt and why the discrepancy is where restructuring opportunities live.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the treasury stock method and what does it assume?",a:"A way of counting the dilution from in-the-money options. Assume every in-the-money option is exercised, which creates new shares. Assume the company takes the strike proceeds and buys shares back at the current market price. Count only the net increase.\n\nIt assumes the company uses the proceeds efficiently and that out-of-the-money options are worthless.\n\nThe point: the assumption that out-of-the-money options are worth zero is the weak spot. They have time value and could easily be in the money later, so the method understates true dilution. It is a convention that everyone uses because it is simple and consistent, not because it is precisely right.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has options that are out of the money. Do they matter?",a:"Under the treasury stock method, no. If the strike is above the share price, exercising would mean paying more than the stock is worth, so you assume nobody does and they add zero dilution.\n\nBut they are not actually worthless. They have time value, and if the stock rises they become dilutive.\n\nThe point: this is a known limitation of the convention. A company whose stock is depressed will show minimal option dilution today, and if the thesis works and the stock doubles, a large overhang appears exactly when it hurts. Worth checking the strike distribution rather than accepting the diluted count at face value.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the difference between basic and diluted shares?",a:"Basic is shares currently outstanding. Diluted adds everything that will become a share: in-the-money options, restricted stock units, convertible securities, warrants.\n\nDiluted is always higher or equal, so diluted EPS is always lower or equal.\n\nThe point: use diluted for valuation, always. Basic overstates value per share by pretending the equity awards do not exist. The gap tells you something too, because a wide spread between basic and diluted means the company pays heavily in equity, and the existing shareholders are quietly funding compensation.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"How do you handle convertible bonds in enterprise value?",a:"It depends on whether they are in the money. If the conversion price is below the current share price, treat them as equity: add the shares they would convert into to the diluted count, and do not count them as debt.\n\nIf they are out of the money, treat them as debt at face value, since they will most likely be repaid in cash.\n\nThe point: the mistake is counting them twice, adding the face value to debt and the shares to the count. That inflates EV on both sides. You pick one treatment based on where the stock trades, and note that the answer changes as the share price moves.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company has $200M of convertible bonds with a $25 conversion price. The stock is at $40. How do you treat them?",a:"As equity, since they are well in the money at $40 against a $25 conversion price.\n\nThe bonds convert into $200M divided by $25, which is 8 million shares. Those get added to the diluted share count, and the $200M does not get counted as debt.\n\nThe point: unlike options, there is no treasury stock adjustment here. The holder is not paying anything to convert; they are exchanging a bond they already own for shares. The company receives no cash, so there is nothing to buy stock back with. That is why convertibles dilute more per dollar than options do.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is a warrant and how does it differ from an option?",a:"Both give the right to buy stock at a set price. The difference is who issues them. Warrants are issued by the company itself, so exercising creates new shares and dilutes existing holders. Options in the traded market are contracts between investors, so exercising transfers existing shares and dilutes nobody.\n\nEmployee stock options are effectively warrants in this sense, since the company issues new shares.\n\nThe point: warrants show up attached to debt as a sweetener, particularly in mezzanine and distressed financing. The lender accepts a lower coupon for equity upside. When you see warrants in a capital structure, someone was being compensated for taking risk they were not being paid enough in cash to take.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's diluted share count is 15% above its basic count. What does that tell you?",a:"That the company pays heavily in equity, and that existing shareholders own meaningfully less than the basic count suggests.\n\nIt is common in technology, where compensation is deliberately weighted to stock, and in companies that have issued convertibles or warrants.\n\nThe point: 15% is high and worth interrogating. Most bankers treat anything above about 10% as unusual enough to double check the calculation. If it is real, it means the market cap you read off a screen understates the true equity claim by 15%, and every per-share number needs to be recalculated on the diluted count.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does a company's market cap not equal what an acquirer would pay?",a:"Two reasons in opposite directions.\n\nMarket cap prices a single share traded between passive investors. An acquirer needs every share and needs the board's agreement, so it pays a control premium, typically 20% to 30%.\n\nBut the acquirer also inherits the debt and receives the cash, so what it really pays for the business is enterprise value, not market cap.\n\nThe point: the two effects are separate and people conflate them. The premium is about control. The debt and cash adjustment is about what you are actually buying. A company with a $1B market cap and $2B of debt costs an acquirer far more than $1B, before any premium at all.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has negative working capital and is growing fast. Is that good?",a:"Very. Negative working capital means customers pay before suppliers do, so growth generates cash instead of consuming it. Every new customer funds the business.\n\nThis is the subscription and retail model. Collect upfront, pay suppliers on 60-day terms, and the float grows with the business.\n\nThe point: it reverses the usual constraint. Most growing companies need financing because working capital scales with revenue. A negative working capital business gets more liquid as it grows, which is why these models can scale without raising money and why the same mechanic becomes lethal in reverse. If growth stops, the float unwinds and cash drains fast.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do growing companies run out of cash?",a:"Because growth consumes working capital before it produces profit. You buy inventory now, pay staff now, and collect from customers in 60 days. The faster you grow, the wider that gap gets.\n\nMeanwhile tax is due on the profit you booked, regardless of whether the customer paid.\n\nThe point: this is why profitable companies go bankrupt, and it is the most counterintuitive thing in accounting. The company is not failing, it is succeeding faster than its balance sheet can fund. That is precisely what a revolver is for, and why a company growing 50% a year with 60-day receivables is a financing problem wearing a growth story.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a sources and uses table?",a:"A statement of where the money comes from and where it goes in a transaction. Sources are new debt, sponsor equity, cash on the balance sheet, and any rollover equity. Uses are the purchase price, refinancing existing debt, and fees.\n\nThe two sides must equal. Sponsor equity is normally the plug, the amount needed to make it balance.\n\nThe point: it is the first thing you build in an LBO because it defines the equity cheque, and the equity cheque is the denominator of every return calculation. It also forces you to be explicit about fees, which people forget and which can be 2% to 3% of deal value, coming straight out of returns.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do transaction fees matter in an LBO?",a:"Because they come out of the equity, not out of thin air. Advisory fees, financing fees, legal, and accounting can total 2% to 3% of deal value. On a $1B deal, that is $20M to $30M the sponsor funds on day one and never recovers.\n\nFinancing fees get capitalized and amortized over the life of the debt; transaction fees are expensed immediately.\n\nThe point: they are a permanent drag on returns. The sponsor pays $1B for a business worth $1B and has invested $1.03B. The company must appreciate 3% before the sponsor breaks even, which is exactly why fees get negotiated hard and why they are one of the first things a returns bridge shows.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the difference between a leveraged buyout and a leveraged recapitalization?",a:"In a buyout, the sponsor acquires control. Ownership changes hands, the old shareholders exit, and the sponsor runs the company.\n\nIn a leveraged recapitalization, the company borrows and uses the proceeds to pay a large dividend or buy back stock, but the owners do not change. It is a change in capital structure, not a change of control.\n\nThe point: they produce similar balance sheets and completely different situations. A recap lets existing owners take money off the table while keeping control, which is common with founders who want liquidity without selling. Same leverage, same risk to lenders, and no new owner with a plan.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do lenders require a minimum equity contribution in an LBO?",a:"So the sponsor has something to lose. If a sponsor put in 5% and borrowed 95%, they would take enormous risk with the lender's money and walk away from a small loss if it failed.\n\nLenders typically require 30% to 40% equity. That way the business must lose a third of its value before the debt is impaired.\n\nThe point: it is the same principle as a mortgage deposit. The equity is a loss buffer that protects the lender, and it aligns incentives, because a sponsor with a large cheque at risk will manage the company carefully. Equity contribution requirements loosen in frothy markets, which is reliably a late-cycle signal.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"A sponsor buys a business at 10x and sells at 10x five years later, having grown EBITDA 50% and paid down half the debt. Did they make money?",a:"Yes, substantially, with no help from the multiple at all.\n\nSay EBITDA was $100M, so EV was $1,000M, funded with $600M of debt and $400M of equity. Five years on, EBITDA is $150M, so at 10x the EV is $1,500M. Debt is down to $300M. Equity proceeds are $1,500M less $300M, which is $1,200M.\n\nThat is $1,200M on $400M, so 3x, roughly a 25% IRR.\n\nThe point: flat multiple in and out, and the sponsor tripled its money. EBITDA growth added $500M of enterprise value, debt paydown converted another $300M into equity. This is what a real underwriting case looks like, which is why relying on multiple expansion is treated as a weak thesis.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is the equity cushion and why do lenders care?",a:"The portion of enterprise value below the debt, meaning the sponsor's equity. If a business is worth $1,000M with $600M of debt, the cushion is $400M, or 40%.\n\nLenders care because it is their margin of safety. The business must lose more than $400M of value before a dollar of debt is impaired.\n\nThe point: the cushion is measured at entry and erodes with the market. If the business is worth $700M two years in, the cushion is $100M and the lender is close to the money. That is when covenants get tested, lenders get involved, and the sponsor faces the choice of injecting more equity or handing over the keys.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why would a sponsor inject more equity into a struggling portfolio company?",a:"To protect the option. The existing equity may be worth nothing at today's value, but it still has time value if the business can recover. Injecting capital keeps that option alive.\n\nPractically it is usually to cure a covenant breach, fund a maturity, or buy time for a turnaround.\n\nThe point: it is one of the hardest decisions in the job, because it is textbook sunk cost territory. The right question is not whether you already invested $400M, it is whether the next $50M earns a return on its own. Sponsors call it good money after bad when it fails and conviction when it works, and the distinction is only clear afterwards.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What happens to the sponsor's equity if the company breaches a covenant and cannot fix it?",a:"The negotiation starts, and the sponsor's leverage is weak. Lenders can accelerate the debt, meaning demand immediate repayment the company cannot make.\n\nIn practice the outcomes are: the sponsor injects equity to cure the breach, the lenders grant a waiver in exchange for fees and tighter terms, or the debt converts and lenders take ownership, wiping the sponsor out.\n\nThe point: which one happens depends entirely on whether the business is worth more than the debt. If it is, lenders take fees and wait, because they would rather be paid than own a company. If it is not, they take the equity, because the sponsor's stake is already worthless and everyone knows it.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why would a company spin off a division instead of selling it?",a:"Because a sale may not be available or attractive. A spin-off distributes shares in the division to existing shareholders, creating a separate public company, and it is generally tax-free, unlike a sale which triggers a gain.\n\nIt also unlocks the conglomerate discount. A slow division inside a fast company drags the whole multiple down; separated, each gets valued on its own merits.\n\nThe point: the parent gets no cash, which is the trade. A sale gives you money and a tax bill. A spin gives you a cleaner story and lets shareholders decide what to hold. Activists push for spins precisely when the sum of the parts exceeds the whole.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a carve-out and why is it harder than it looks?",a:"Selling a piece of a company that was never a standalone business. The division shares systems, staff, contracts, and overhead with the parent.\n\nThe difficulty is that you must construct financials that never existed. What did this division actually earn once you allocate a fair share of corporate costs it never paid for? What will it cost to run alone, with its own finance team, its own IT, its own insurance?\n\nThe point: the gap between reported divisional profit and true standalone profit is where carve-out deals go wrong. Buyers underestimate stranded costs, the overhead the parent keeps that the division was absorbing. That is what transition service agreements exist to bridge.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the conglomerate discount?",a:"When a diversified company trades below the sum of what its divisions would be worth separately. A group with a software arm and an industrial arm gets valued closer to the industrial multiple than to a blend.\n\nWhy it happens. Investors cannot get clean exposure to the piece they want. Capital gets allocated across divisions by managers rather than by the market. Reporting is opaque, so nobody trusts the segment numbers.\n\nThe point: it is the entire logic of sum-of-the-parts analysis and the entire playbook of activist investors. Identify the discount, push for a spin or a sale, and let the market reprice each piece. It is also why conglomerates went out of fashion.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do companies do stock splits if nothing changes?",a:"Nothing does change economically. Twice the shares at half the price is the same company and the same ownership.\n\nThe stated reasons are liquidity and accessibility. A $3,000 share price is awkward for retail investors and for options trading, so splitting makes the stock easier to trade in round lots.\n\nThe point: the interesting part is that splits are usually followed by outperformance, which makes no sense mechanically. The explanation is signaling. Companies split after the stock has risen and when management is confident, so the split is a message rather than a cause. Fractional share trading has made the whole exercise largely obsolete.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the difference between a merger and a tender offer?",a:"A merger goes through the board. The two companies negotiate, the board approves, and shareholders vote. It is the normal path.\n\nA tender offer goes directly to shareholders. The buyer offers to purchase shares at a premium, and holders decide individually whether to tender. No board approval needed.\n\nThe point: the tender offer is the mechanism of a hostile bid, but it is also used in friendly deals because it can be faster, closing in weeks rather than months, without a shareholder meeting. The tradeoff is that you may not get 100%, and you need a squeeze-out to clean up the stragglers.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do most deals include a material adverse change clause?",a:"Because months pass between signing and closing, and the buyer wants an exit if the business collapses in the meantime.\n\nA MAC clause lets the buyer walk if something materially damages the target. In practice the bar is set extremely high, and courts have almost never allowed a buyer to invoke it.\n\nThe point: the carve-outs are the real negotiation. General economic conditions, industry-wide downturns, and market movements are almost always excluded, so the change has to be specific to the target and durationally significant. That is why buyers with cold feet usually negotiate a price cut rather than litigating a MAC they will lose.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a fairness opinion and what does it actually do?",a:"A letter from a bank stating that the consideration in a deal is fair, from a financial point of view, to shareholders. It is delivered to the board.\n\nIts actual function is legal cover. Directors have a duty of care, and having an independent bank bless the price is evidence they discharged it. It protects the board from litigation.\n\nThe point: it is not an endorsement of the deal or a valuation of the company. The language is deliberately narrow: fair, from a financial point of view, as of this date. Banks get paid for it regardless of outcome, which is exactly the criticism, and it is why the fee is disclosed in the proxy.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why does a seller run an auction instead of negotiating with one buyer?",a:"To create competition, which is the only reliable way to raise the price. A single bidder has no pressure and every incentive to slow-play and chip the price during diligence.\n\nAn auction sets a deadline, forces bidders to move, and gives the board evidence it tested the market.\n\nThe point: auctions are not free. They leak information to competitors, they take longer, and they can fail publicly, which damages the asset. That is why a seller with one obviously right buyer sometimes negotiates bilaterally and accepts a slightly lower price for speed and confidentiality. A failed auction is worse than a quiet deal.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is a stalking horse bid?",a:"An initial bid in a distressed sale that sets the floor. The seller agrees terms with one buyer, then runs a public process where others can top it.\n\nThe stalking horse gets protections for taking the risk of going first: a break fee, expense reimbursement, and bidding increments that make topping it costly.\n\nThe point: it exists mainly in bankruptcy sales, where the court requires a market test to prove the price is fair. The seller gets a guaranteed floor and the credibility of a real bid; the stalking horse gets protections and a strong chance of winning. Everyone else is bidding against a deal that was already negotiated.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do buyers and sellers disagree about price even with the same financials?",a:"Because price is about the future, and they are looking at different futures.\n\nThe seller knows the business and believes in the pipeline, the new product, the customers about to sign. The buyer sees the risk in all three and will not pay for growth it has not verified.\n\nThey also value it differently. A strategic includes synergies the seller thinks it should be paid for; the buyer thinks it created them.\n\nThe point: this is exactly why earnouts exist. Rather than argue about a forecast neither can prove, they let the outcome decide. The disagreement is not about arithmetic, it is about who bears the risk of the seller being right.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company has $80M of EBITDA and wants to borrow. How much debt can it raise?",a:"Depends on the business, but work it from two directions.\n\nLeverage: a stable business might support 4x to 5x, so $320M to $400M. A cyclical one maybe 2x to 3x.\n\nCoverage: at a 9% rate, $400M costs $36M of interest, so EBITDA covers it 2.2 times. That is thin. Lenders typically want 2x or better, and more for a volatile business.\n\nThe point: the binding constraint is usually coverage, not leverage, because coverage is what determines whether the cheque clears. Check both and take the lower answer. Also remember EBITDA is not cash: subtract capex and working capital before deciding what really services the debt.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do lenders look at debt to EBITDA when EBITDA is not cash?",a:"Because it is standardized and comparable, not because it is right. Every company reports it the same way, so a lender can benchmark across a portfolio and write a covenant that means something.\n\nThey know it overstates. That is why credit agreements define EBITDA precisely, often over several pages, and why they layer on coverage tests and capex limits alongside the leverage test.\n\nThe point: the metric is a convention that works until it does not. A company at 4x leverage that spends all its EBITDA on capex has no capacity at all, and the leverage ratio will not tell you. That is precisely why lenders test coverage and free cash flow too, rather than trusting one number.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a leveraged loan and who buys them?",a:"A loan to a company that is already heavily indebted, usually below investment grade. It is typically senior secured and floating rate.\n\nBanks originate them and mostly distribute rather than hold. The buyers are institutional: CLOs, which package loans into tranches and sell them, plus loan funds and insurers.\n\nThe point: the originate-to-distribute model is what makes the market work and what makes it fragile. The bank underwriting the loan often does not keep it, so its incentive is to get the deal done and sold. When the buyer base steps back, deals get hung on bank balance sheets, which is precisely what happened in 2022 and why underwriting standards tighten abruptly rather than gradually.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why did private credit grow so much?",a:"Because it solved a speed and certainty problem. A direct lender can commit to a whole financing quickly, without syndicating to a market that might not show up. For a sponsor on a deadline, certainty of close is worth paying for.\n\nBanks also retreated from leveraged lending under capital rules, leaving room.\n\nThe point: the trade is price for certainty. Private credit charges more than a broadly syndicated loan, and sponsors accept it because the deal actually closes and the terms are negotiated with one counterparty rather than a market. The concern is that the loans are not marked to market, so nobody quite knows what they are worth until something breaks.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a unitranche facility?",a:"A single loan that combines what would otherwise be senior and subordinated debt into one instrument at one blended rate. One lender, one document, one interest rate.\n\nBehind the scenes the lenders may split the economics between themselves through an agreement among lenders, but the borrower sees one facility.\n\nThe point: the appeal is simplicity and speed. Rather than negotiating a senior facility and a mezzanine piece with different lenders and intercreditor terms, the sponsor signs once. The borrower pays a blended rate that is higher than senior alone and lower than mezzanine, and buys execution certainty with the difference.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's debt matures in 18 months and it cannot refinance. What happens?",a:"It becomes a crisis quickly, and the clock is already running. The debt reclassifies to current liabilities, which wrecks the liquidity ratios and may trip covenants on other facilities.\n\nAuditors may issue a going concern qualification, which itself makes refinancing harder.\n\nThe options: refinance at a much worse rate, sell assets, raise equity at a depressed price, negotiate an extension with existing lenders, or restructure.\n\nThe point: this is how most companies actually fail. Not from losing money but from a maturity they cannot meet. Solvency and liquidity are different, and the wall arrives on a date that was known years in advance.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a maturity wall?",a:"A concentration of debt coming due in a narrow window, either for one company or across a whole market.\n\nFor a company it is a structuring failure: all the debt raised at once, all maturing at once, so the entire capital structure depends on one refinancing window. For a market, it means a large volume of leveraged debt maturing in the same couple of years.\n\nThe point: it matters because refinancing depends on conditions you do not control. A company that would refinance easily in a normal market cannot in a closed one. That is why treasurers ladder maturities deliberately, spreading them so no single year can kill the company.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do companies refinance debt before they have to?",a:"To avoid needing to. Refinancing when markets are open and results are good gets a better rate than refinancing when you are forced to.\n\nOther reasons. Lower rates are available. Covenants can be loosened. Maturities can be pushed out to remove a wall. Or the company wants to change the structure entirely, moving from bank debt to bonds.\n\nThe point: the timing is the whole skill. A treasurer who waits until twelve months before maturity is negotiating from weakness, because the lender knows the alternative. The best refinancing happens when the company does not need it, which is exactly when nobody feels urgency to do it.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is the difference between a bond and a loan?",a:"A loan is a private agreement, originally with a bank, though now often with funds. Terms are negotiated bilaterally, it is usually secured and floating rate, and it can be amended by talking to a manageable group of lenders.\n\nA bond is a security sold to public investors. Fixed rate, usually unsecured, a standardized indenture, and it trades. Amending it means getting consent from a dispersed base of holders you may not be able to identify.\n\nThe point: the practical difference shows up in a restructuring. You can renegotiate a loan in a room. Renegotiating a bond means a consent solicitation across hundreds of anonymous holders, which is why bond-heavy capital structures are so much harder to fix.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does a company's cost of debt not equal the coupon on its existing bonds?",a:"Because the coupon was set when the bond was issued and reflects the conditions of that day. Cost of debt for a valuation is what the company would pay to borrow today.\n\nIf a bond was issued at 4% and the company's credit has since deteriorated so its debt now yields 9%, then 9% is the cost of debt. The 4% coupon is history.\n\nThe point: this trips people up in WACC. The correct input is the yield to maturity on the company's traded debt, or the yield on comparable credits if it has none. Using the historical coupon understates the cost of capital and overstates the valuation, exactly when the company is in trouble.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"How would you value a hotel chain?",a:"On the real estate and the operations separately, because they are different businesses.\n\nThe property is valued on net operating income and a cap rate, like any real estate. The management business, running hotels under a brand, is a fee stream valued on a multiple of EBITDA and deserves a higher one because it is asset-light and recurring.\n\nIndustry metrics: RevPAR, meaning revenue per available room, plus occupancy and average daily rate.\n\nThe point: the split matters because the market values them completely differently. That is exactly why hotel groups have spent two decades separating property from brand, selling the buildings and keeping the fees.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How would you value an airline?",a:"On EV/EBITDAR, because the own-versus-lease decision for aircraft varies enormously and would otherwise dominate any comparison. Add rent back to EBITDA and add the capitalized lease obligation to debt, so both sides stay consistent.\n\nIndustry metrics: revenue per available seat mile, cost per available seat mile, and load factor.\n\nThe point: airlines are the textbook case of high operating leverage and high financial leverage together, which is why they fail so regularly. Fixed costs are enormous, fuel is uncontrollable, and demand is cyclical. A modest revenue decline does not reduce profit proportionally, it eliminates it.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How would you value a mining company?",a:"Like oil and gas, on the resource. A net asset value model is the standard: take proved reserves, apply a production profile and a commodity price deck, subtract operating and capital costs, and discount.\n\nMultiples include EV per tonne of reserves and EV/EBITDA, though the latter is unreliable across a cycle.\n\nThe point: the asset depletes. Every tonne mined is inventory that will not be replaced without spending, so reserve life and replacement matter as much as current production. And because the company has no control over the commodity price, the price deck is the single assumption that decides the valuation, which is why these models are presented as sensitivity grids.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How would you value an asset manager?",a:"On assets under management and the fee rate. Revenue is essentially AUM times the fee, so the value is a function of how much money they run and how sticky it is.\n\nMultiples: EV/EBITDA, price to earnings, and EV as a percentage of AUM.\n\nThe point: the real question is the quality of the AUM. Sticky institutional money on long mandates is worth far more than retail flows that leave after two bad quarters. Performance fees are worth less than management fees because they are volatile. That is why a passive manager with low fees and permanent assets can be worth more than an active one with higher fees and flight risk.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How would you value a pharmaceutical company?",a:"Product by product, because the value is a portfolio of patents with expiry dates. For marketed drugs, project revenue to patent expiry, then model the cliff, because generics take most of the volume almost immediately.\n\nFor the pipeline, probability-weight each candidate by its phase and discount heavily.\n\nThe point: the patent cliff is what makes pharma unlike other businesses. A drug earning $3B a year can earn $500M eighteen months later with no warning and no fix. That is why the pipeline is the whole valuation debate, and why big pharma acquires constantly. They are buying replacement revenue for a cliff they can see coming years out.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How would you value a telecom company?",a:"On EBITDA and on infrastructure, with heavy attention to capex. Multiples are EV/EBITDA, plus EV per subscriber and EV per tower or per home passed.\n\nThe critical adjustment is capital intensity. Telecoms generate enormous EBITDA and spend most of it on the network, so EBITDA badly overstates what reaches shareholders.\n\nThe point: this is the sector where EV/EBITDA is most misleading. A telecom converting 30% of EBITDA to free cash flow is not comparable to a software company converting 90%, even at the same multiple. That is why the industry has been separating towers and fibre into separate vehicles, since infrastructure assets get valued on stable cash flows rather than on the operating business's multiple.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company operates in 30 countries. What does that do to your valuation?",a:"It complicates the discount rate and the cash flows. Each market has a different risk profile, so a single WACC is a blunt instrument. You may add a country risk premium for exposure to less stable markets.\n\nCurrency matters. Cash flows earned in local currency must be translated, and you either forecast in local currency and discount at a local rate, or convert and discount at your own. Mixing the two is a common error.\n\nThe point: also check whether the cash can actually come home. Profit trapped in a jurisdiction with capital controls or a punitive repatriation tax is worth less than the same profit earned domestically, which is a real adjustment people forget.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is a country risk premium and when do you use it?",a:"An addition to cost of equity for operating in a market with more political, legal, or economic instability. It is typically derived from the sovereign's credit spread against a benchmark like US treasuries, sometimes scaled for equity volatility.\n\nYou use it when a meaningful share of cash flows comes from that market.\n\nThe point: the sharper approach is to adjust the cash flows rather than the discount rate. If the risk is that the government might expropriate the asset, that is a specific scenario with a probability, and modelling it explicitly is more honest than adding a vague 3% to the WACC and hoping it covers everything.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why might the same company be worth different amounts to two different buyers?",a:"Because value is not a property of the asset alone, it depends on what the buyer can do with it.\n\nA strategic with overlapping operations captures cost synergies nobody else can. A competitor may pay a premium simply to keep a rival from owning it. A sponsor has no synergies but may see cost cuts management would not make. A foreign buyer may want the distribution more than the profit.\n\nThe point: this is why an auction works and why fair value is a range rather than a number. The winning bid is usually the buyer with the most synergies or the most strategic desperation, which is also why the winner is often the one who overpaid.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the winner's curse in M&A?",a:"The observation that in a competitive auction, the winner is usually the bidder who most overestimated the target's value. Everyone bids their own estimate; the highest estimate wins; the highest estimate is most likely the wrong one.\n\nIt is worse in M&A because the price includes a control premium and the synergies justifying it are forecasts made by the people who want the deal.\n\nThe point: it explains the persistent finding that acquirers underperform. The discipline against it is deciding your walk-away price before the process and holding it, which sounds obvious and is extremely rare once a CEO has decided they want the asset.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company reports revenue growth of 20%, but 15% came from acquisitions. What do you think?",a:"That organic growth is 5%, and that is the number that matters. Acquired growth is bought, not earned, and it costs capital to buy.\n\nCheck the return. If the company paid 12x EBITDA for that growth and its own cost of capital is 9%, the acquisitions need to earn more than that to create value. Growth alone does not.\n\nThe point: serial acquirers can report attractive headline growth indefinitely while destroying value, because the income statement shows the revenue and not the price paid for it. The tells are goodwill climbing, share count rising, and organic growth quietly disappearing under the headline.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is organic growth and why does it matter more than total growth?",a:"Growth from the existing business: more customers, more volume, higher prices. It excludes anything bought.\n\nIt matters because it is the only growth that tells you whether the business is actually working. Acquired growth can be purchased by anyone with access to capital, and it stops the moment the acquisitions do.\n\nThe point: it is also the harder number to fake, which is why companies that lean on acquisitions often stop disclosing it. If a company reports total growth prominently and organic growth in a footnote, or not at all, that omission is the finding.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do serial acquirers eventually run into trouble?",a:"Because the model requires ever-larger deals. Once the base grows, a small acquisition no longer moves the growth rate, so each one must be bigger, which means paying more and taking more integration risk.\n\nMeanwhile the balance sheet fills with goodwill and debt, and integration debt accumulates as systems never fully merge.\n\nThe point: the mechanism is arithmetic, not misconduct. A company adding 15% growth through acquisition on a $1B base needs $150M of acquired revenue. At $10B it needs $1.5B. The deals get harder, the discipline slips, and the eventual goodwill impairment reveals what was really paid. That is the shape of most roll-up failures.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company has a lot of goodwill on its balance sheet. Is that bad?",a:"Not inherently, but it tells you the company grew by buying. Goodwill is the record of everything paid above fair value in past acquisitions.\n\nWhat to check. How much of total assets is goodwill, since a company that is mostly goodwill has few real assets. Whether it has been impaired before, which shows a pattern of overpaying. And whether the acquisitions actually delivered.\n\nThe point: goodwill cannot be sold, borrowed against, or used to make anything. In a liquidation it is worth zero, which is exactly why lenders look at tangible assets and why tangible book value exists as a separate measure.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What does a goodwill impairment actually tell you?",a:"That management has conceded an acquisition is worth less than they paid. It is an admission, delivered years late, in an accounting entry.\n\nWhat it does not tell you is anything new about cash. No money moves, and the cash left when the deal closed.\n\nThe point: the market usually knows before the charge. The share price typically reflects the failed acquisition long before the impairment test forces it onto the income statement, which is why the stock often does not move much on the announcement. The information value is confirmation, not news. What is worth watching is whether the same management keeps acquiring afterwards.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why do companies write off goodwill in one big charge rather than gradually?",a:"Because the rules changed. Goodwill used to amortize on a schedule, which spread the cost and implied it declined predictably. Now it is tested for impairment and written down only when it is genuinely worth less.\n\nThe logic is that goodwill does not decline on a timetable. A good acquisition may be worth more every year; a bad one collapses at once.\n\nThe point: the side effect is a well-known incentive. A single large charge in a year that is already bad, often around a management change, gets treated as one-time and excluded from adjusted earnings. That is why big bath accounting is a recognized pattern, and why a new CEO's first impairment deserves a closer look.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company's return on invested capital is below its cost of capital. What does that mean?",a:"That growth is destroying value. Every dollar invested returns less than it costs to raise, so the more the company grows, the worse off shareholders are.\n\nIt sounds abstract and it is the central question in corporate finance. A company earning 6% on capital that costs 9% should shrink, return cash, and stop investing.\n\nThe point: management rarely does this, because growth is rewarded and shrinking is not. That is exactly what activists target, and it is why a company with poor returns and high capex is a better short than a company with declining revenue and discipline. The first is compounding the problem.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is ROIC and why do investors care about it?",a:"Return on invested capital: after-tax operating profit divided by the capital in the business, meaning debt plus equity less cash.\n\nInvestors care because it measures whether the business creates value at all. Compare it with WACC. Above it, growth creates value. Below it, growth destroys it.\n\nThe point: it also identifies a moat. A company sustaining ROIC well above its cost of capital for years is telling you competitors cannot compete the returns away, which means something is protecting it. High returns should attract entrants and get arbitraged down. When they do not, ask why, and the answer is usually the reason to own the business.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why can two companies with the same growth have completely different value?",a:"Because growth is only valuable if it earns more than it costs. A company growing 10% at a 20% return on capital is creating enormous value. A company growing 10% at a 5% return is burning it.\n\nThe capital required differs too. Software grows without capital, so growth is nearly free. Manufacturing needs a factory for every increment.\n\nThe point: this is the most important idea in valuation and it is why growth rate alone tells you nothing. The right question is not how fast it grows but how much capital that growth consumes and what it earns on it. Growth is a multiplier on returns, and if returns are below the cost of capital, the multiplier works against you.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is a moat and how would you test whether a company has one?",a:"A durable structural advantage that stops competitors from competing away the returns. Network effects, switching costs, scale economies, regulatory barriers, or a genuine brand.\n\nThe test is in the numbers, not the story. Has the company sustained high returns on capital for many years? Has it held or gained share? Has it raised prices without losing customers?\n\nThe point: high returns attract competition, so any company earning well above its cost of capital for a decade is either protected or lucky. If you cannot name the specific mechanism keeping competitors out, and describe how it could break, you have not identified a moat. You have identified a company that has done well so far.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's revenue is $500M growing 8%, EBITDA margin is 25%. It trades at $2B EV. Is that expensive?",a:"Run the multiple first. EBITDA is 25% of $500M, so $125M. Enterprise value of $2,000M divided by $125M is 16x EBITDA, and $2,000M over $500M of revenue is 4x.\n\nSo it is not cheap. 16x for a business growing 8% is a premium multiple for modest growth.\n\nThe point: the market must be expecting something the current numbers do not show, either margin expansion from 25% toward something much higher, or an acceleration in growth, or a moat durable enough to justify paying up for safety. The right response is not expensive or cheap, it is what would have to be true to justify 16x, and then go check whether it is.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A business generates $50M of free cash flow and you can buy it for $500M. What return are you getting?",a:"A 10% free cash flow yield, which is $50M over $500M. That is your unlevered return if the business never grows.\n\nCompare it with alternatives. If government bonds yield 4%, you are being paid 6 points more for taking equity risk in a single company. Whether that is enough depends on how certain the $50M is.\n\nThe point: this is the cleanest way to think about any acquisition. The free cash flow yield is the inverse of the multiple, so 10x free cash flow is a 10% yield. If the business grows, your return is the yield plus the growth. If it shrinks, the yield is a mirage.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a free cash flow yield and why do investors use it?",a:"Free cash flow divided by market capitalization, or unlevered free cash flow divided by enterprise value. It is the inverse of a cash flow multiple.\n\nInvestors use it because it is directly comparable to other returns. A 7% free cash flow yield sits next to a 4% bond yield in a way that a 14x multiple does not.\n\nThe point: it also cuts through the EBITDA problem. A company can post enormous EBITDA and produce no free cash because it spends everything on capex and interest. The yield only counts money that actually reaches investors, which is why it is harder to dress up than almost any other metric.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do investors compare equity yields to bond yields?",a:"Because they are competing uses of the same dollar. If a safe government bond yields 5%, an equity has to offer meaningfully more to justify the risk of owning a business that might not deliver.\n\nThe gap is the equity risk premium in practice, and it moves with rates. When bond yields rise, equities must reprice down to offer a competitive return, all else equal.\n\nThe point: this is the mechanism behind the phrase that rates are gravity for asset prices. Nothing about the company changed when the bond yield moved, but the alternative got better, so the price of everything else has to adjust. It explains why growth stocks fall on a rate move that has nothing to do with them.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company could return cash to shareholders or reinvest it. How should it decide?",a:"Compare the return on reinvestment against the shareholders' alternative. If the company can earn 20% on new projects and shareholders' cost of capital is 9%, reinvest every dollar. If it can only earn 5%, give the money back.\n\nThe test is not whether the project is profitable, it is whether it beats the cost of capital.\n\nThe point: management almost always prefers to reinvest, because a bigger company means more prestige and more pay. That is why capital allocation is the main thing that separates good management from bad, and why a CEO who shrinks the company deliberately is rare and usually worth owning.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the difference between a dividend and a buyback?",a:"Both return cash. A dividend pays every shareholder in cash. A buyback reduces the share count, so continuing holders own more of the same company.\n\nDividends are sticky, since cutting one is punished severely, so companies only start when they are confident. Buybacks are discretionary and can be stopped quietly.\n\nThe point: the real difference is that a buyback only creates value below intrinsic value, while a dividend is value-neutral by construction. A company buying back overvalued stock is transferring value from continuing shareholders to sellers. A dividend cannot make that mistake, which is the honest argument for preferring it.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do some companies never pay dividends?",a:"Because they have better uses for the money. A company earning 30% on reinvested capital should keep every dollar; paying it out forces shareholders to find a worse alternative.\n\nThere is also a tax argument. Dividends are taxed on receipt; capital appreciation is not taxed until you sell, so buybacks and reinvestment let shareholders control the timing.\n\nThe point: the answer stops being convincing when the reinvestment opportunities dry up. A mature company hoarding cash while earning 6% on it is not being disciplined, it is empire building. The question is always whether the retained dollar earns more inside than shareholders could earn outside.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company announces a dividend cut and the stock falls 30%. Why so severe?",a:"Because of what the cut signals rather than the cash. The dividend itself might be 4% of the share price, so losing it does not justify 30%.\n\nThe market reads it as management admitting the cash flow will not support the payment, and management would only concede that if the situation were bad. Companies defend dividends long past the point of sense precisely because cutting is so punishing.\n\nThe point: it also forces selling. Income funds and dividend mandates must sell a company that stops paying, regardless of value, so the cut triggers mechanical selling on top of the signal. Both effects compound, which is why the move is so much larger than the arithmetic.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What does it tell you when insiders are buying their own stock?",a:"That the people with the best information are willing to back it with their own money. Insider buying is one of the few signals with genuine information content, because insiders have no reason to buy except that they think it is cheap.\n\nInsider selling is much weaker as a signal. People sell for a hundred reasons: taxes, diversification, a house, a divorce.\n\nThe point: the asymmetry is the whole point. There is one reason to buy and many to sell. Cluster buying by several insiders after a decline is the version worth noticing, since it means the people who know most disagree with the market.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company keeps beating earnings by exactly one cent every quarter. What do you think?",a:"That the earnings are being managed. Real results are noisy; a business that genuinely beat by a random amount would sometimes miss, sometimes beat by a lot.\n\nBeating by exactly a penny, repeatedly, means someone has a lever and is using it: reserve releases, timing of expenses, revenue recognition at the margin, or guidance set deliberately low.\n\nThe point: it is not necessarily fraud, and it is a warning. Managing earnings works until the levers run out, and then the miss is enormous because the accumulated shortfall arrives at once. Suspiciously smooth earnings in a volatile business is one of the oldest red flags there is.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How many piano tuners are there in Chicago?",a:"Structure it. Chicago has roughly 2.7 million people, so about 1 million households. Say 5% own a piano, which is 50,000 pianos. Add institutions, schools and churches, call it 55,000.\n\nA piano gets tuned about once a year, so 55,000 tunings. A tuner does maybe 4 a day, 5 days a week, 50 weeks, so about 1,000 a year.\n\n55,000 divided by 1,000 is about 55 tuners.\n\nThe point: the classic version of this problem. Nobody knows the real answer and it does not matter. They are watching whether you decompose it, state the assumptions you are least sure of, which here is the 5% ownership rate, and do clean arithmetic out loud.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How much revenue does a single Starbucks store generate in a year?",a:"Build it from throughput. Say 500 customers a day at an average ticket of $7, which is $3,500 a day. Multiply by 365 and you get about $1.3M a year.\n\nSanity check the inputs. 500 customers over roughly 14 open hours is 36 an hour, which is under one a minute. That feels reasonable for a normal store and low for a busy downtown one.\n\nThe point: the check at the end is the part that matters. If your assumption implies four customers a minute all day, you have built something absurd and should say so before the interviewer does. Stating the number you are least confident in is the answer they want.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How would you estimate the number of cars sold in the US each year?",a:"From the installed base. About 250 million cars on the road, and a car lasts roughly 12 years. To keep the fleet stable, you replace about a twelfth of it each year, so about 21 million.\n\nAdjust for growth in the fleet and for cars scrapped early, and call it around 17 to 20 million. The real number is roughly 15 million, so the estimate is close.\n\nThe point: the replacement approach is the right instinct for any durable good. The market size is the installed base divided by the average life, and this method works for appliances, aircraft, and phones. Starting from population and guessing purchase rates is much weaker.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A restaurant has $2M of revenue. Roughly what does it make?",a:"Very little. The industry structure is brutal and roughly consistent: food cost around 30% of revenue, labour around 30%, rent around 10%, and other operating costs around 20%.\n\nThat leaves about 10%, so around $200,000 before the owner's own compensation, interest, or tax.\n\nThe point: this is why restaurants fail constantly. Every line is large, none is easily compressible, and there is no operating leverage because food and labour scale with volume. A bad month does not just reduce profit, it eliminates it. It is also why restaurant groups fight over rent, since it is the only genuinely fixed line and therefore the only one where scale helps.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do interviewers ask brainteasers at all?",a:"To watch you think under pressure with no preparation. They are not testing the answer, they are testing whether you panic, whether you ask clarifying questions, whether you narrate your reasoning, and whether you sanity check.\n\nThe behaviours that fail: silence, guessing a number with no structure, or refusing to commit.\n\nThe point: the job involves being asked things you cannot look up, in a room, with a client waiting. The brainteaser is a proxy for that. Thinking out loud and being wrong beats being quiet and right, because your process is the only thing they can actually observe.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's stock is $50 and it has 20M shares. It earns $40M. What is its P/E?",a:"25x. Market cap is $50 times 20M, which is $1,000M. EPS is $40M over 20M shares, which is $2. So $50 divided by $2 is 25x.\n\nOr get there directly: market cap over net income, $1,000M over $40M, is 25x. Same answer, fewer steps.\n\nThe point: P/E is just market cap divided by net income, and the per-share version is the same fraction with both sides divided by the share count. People overcomplicate this by insisting on computing EPS first. If you have the market cap and net income, you already have the P/E.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has EBITDA of $200M and net debt of $600M. What is its leverage?",a:"3x. Net debt of $600M divided by $200M of EBITDA.\n\nNet debt means total debt less cash, since cash could theoretically repay debt tomorrow. Some lenders use gross debt instead, particularly if the cash is trapped overseas or needed for operations.\n\nThe point: 3x is moderate for most businesses, comfortable for a stable one, and aggressive for a cyclical. But leverage alone does not tell you whether it is serviceable. Check coverage: what does the interest cost against that $200M, and what happens to both numbers in a downturn.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"If a company's WACC is 10% and it earns 8% on capital, what should it do?",a:"Stop investing and return the cash. Every dollar it deploys destroys two cents of value, so growth is making shareholders poorer.\n\nThe options: return capital through dividends or buybacks, sell the assets earning below cost of capital, or fix the returns by cutting cost or raising price.\n\nThe point: what actually happens is that management keeps investing, because a bigger company means more pay and more status, and because admitting the business does not earn its cost of capital is career-limiting. That gap between what the arithmetic says and what management does is the entire business model of activist investing.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A DCF gives you a value of $80 per share. The stock is at $80. What do you conclude?",a:"Almost nothing, and that is the honest answer. A DCF landing exactly on the market price usually means your assumptions were anchored to it, consciously or not.\n\nIt is very easy to build a DCF to any answer. If you started knowing the stock was $80 and picked a growth rate and discount rate that felt reasonable, you probably tuned your way there.\n\nThe point: the useful exercise is the reverse DCF. Rather than solving for value, solve for what the market must be assuming to justify $80, then ask whether those assumptions are plausible. That question has an answer. Does my model agree with the price does not.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is a reverse DCF and why is it more useful?",a:"Instead of projecting cash flows to produce a value, you take the current price as given and solve for the assumptions that justify it. What growth rate, what margin, what duration must the market be expecting?\n\nThen you judge those assumptions rather than your own.\n\nThe point: it removes the main weakness of a DCF, which is that you choose the inputs and therefore choose the answer. A reverse DCF turns a modelling exercise into a falsifiable question: the market is implying 15% growth for a decade, is that plausible for this company in this industry. That is something you can actually research and be wrong about.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Walk me through what happens between signing and closing a deal.",a:"The gap runs from weeks to a year. In it: regulatory approvals, antitrust filings, and any foreign investment reviews. Shareholder votes if required. Financing gets syndicated and funded. Third-party consents get collected, since customer and supplier contracts often have change-of-control clauses.\n\nMeanwhile the target must run the business normally, constrained by interim operating covenants.\n\nThe point: this period is where deals die. The buyer is exposed to the business deteriorating and cannot control it; the seller is exposed to the buyer walking. Every term in the agreement about MAC clauses, break fees, and the working capital peg exists to allocate that risk.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a CIM and what is it for?",a:"A confidential information memorandum. The seller's bank writes it, and it is the marketing document for the business: the story, the financials, the market, the growth plan.\n\nIt goes to buyers after they sign an NDA.\n\nThe point: it is a sales document, not an objective one. Everything in it is chosen to present the business well. Adjusted EBITDA will be generous, the growth plan will be management's best case, and the risks will be handled briefly. Reading a CIM is an exercise in noticing what is not there: which customer is not named, which year is excluded from the chart, which metric changed definition.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do sellers hire a banker at all?",a:"For process and competition, mainly. A banker runs an auction, which creates the tension that raises the price. A seller negotiating alone with one buyer has no leverage.\n\nThey also bring buyer relationships, know what comparable assets fetched, prepare the materials, and absorb the workload so management can keep running the business.\n\nThe point: the underrated part is that the banker is a buffer. They can push hard on price, ask awkward questions, and play bad cop without damaging the relationship between buyer and seller, who may have to work together afterwards. That separation is worth real money in a negotiation.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the difference between a broad auction and a targeted process?",a:"A broad auction contacts everyone plausible, dozens of parties, and maximizes competition. A targeted process approaches a handful of likely buyers.\n\nBroad gets a better price through tension but leaks. Competitors learn the business is for sale, and if it fails publicly, the asset is damaged.\n\nThe point: the choice reveals what the seller is optimizing for. A financial sponsor selling a portfolio company usually runs broad, since price is everything and there is no relationship to protect. A founder selling a business with their name on it often runs targeted, accepting a lower price for confidentiality and control over who ends up owning it.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why would a deal be structured with an earnout when the seller hates them?",a:"Because the alternative is no deal. The earnout exists precisely when the two sides cannot agree on the forecast. The seller says the business will grow 40%; the buyer will not pay for growth it has not seen.\n\nRather than splitting the difference on a number neither can prove, they let the outcome settle it.\n\nThe point: sellers hate them because they lose control of the outcome. Once the buyer owns the business, the buyer decides the spending, the accounting, and the priorities, all of which affect whether the target is hit. That is why earnout disputes are so common and why sellers negotiate hard over how the metric is defined and who controls the levers.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a management presentation and what are buyers actually assessing?",a:"A session where the target's management team presents the business to a shortlisted buyer, usually after first-round bids.\n\nBuyers are assessing the team as much as the business. Do they know their numbers cold? Do they answer directly or deflect? Do they disagree with each other? Does the CEO know the operational detail or only the story?\n\nThe point: for a sponsor this is close to the whole diligence. They are buying a business they will not run, so the management team is the asset. A polished presentation from a team that cannot answer a specific question about churn tells a buyer more than any spreadsheet.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do private equity firms keep management in place when strategics replace them?",a:"Because the sponsor has nobody else. A sponsor is a small investment team, not an operating company. They cannot run a manufacturer or a software business, so the existing team is essential and gets equity to stay.\n\nA strategic already has a finance function, a sales organization, and a management layer. The target's team is duplicate cost, which is exactly where the cost synergies come from.\n\nThe point: this is why the seller's management team almost always prefers the sponsor bid. The strategic may pay more to shareholders while eliminating the people in the room, which is a real conflict when management is also negotiating the deal.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a data room and what goes in it?",a:"A secure repository where the seller posts diligence materials: financials, contracts, cap table, employee data, litigation, tax filings, insurance, IP.\n\nAccess is staged. Early rounds get summary information; the final bidders get everything.\n\nThe point: what to notice is the staging and the gaps. If a specific customer contract is withheld until the last week, or the churn data arrives in an unusable format, that is information. Sellers control the sequence deliberately, and a buyer's job is to notice which document arrived late and ask why.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do deals leak and does it matter?",a:"They leak because too many people know. Bankers, lawyers, accountants, lenders, and multiple bidders, each with their own teams. Any one of them can talk.\n\nIt matters a lot. A leak moves the target's share price, which raises the price a buyer must pay, since the premium is now measured against an inflated base. It alerts other bidders and invites an interloper. It unsettles employees and customers.\n\nThe point: this is a real argument for a targeted process over a broad auction. Every additional party in a process is another leak risk, and the price benefit of the tenth bidder may be smaller than the cost of the story appearing before you are ready.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What actually makes a good analyst?",a:"Reliability, mostly. Work that comes back correct so nobody has to check it. Numbers that tie. Files someone else can open and understand. Deadlines that hold.\n\nAfter that: noticing. The analyst who spots that a number moved and asks why, before the MD does, becomes the one people trust.\n\nThe point: technical skill is assumed and it is the easiest part. Everyone learns to build a model within months. What separates people is whether the work is dependable under pressure at 2am on the fourth revision, and whether you flag your own mistake before someone finds it. The willingness to say I got this wrong is worth more than being right the first time.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"A company changes its revenue recognition from upfront to over the contract term. What happens?",a:"Reported revenue falls sharply in the transition year, because you stop booking whole contracts at signing and start spreading them. Deferred revenue builds on the balance sheet instead.\n\nCash does not change at all. The customer pays the same amount on the same day.\n\nThe point: this is the cleanest illustration that revenue is an accounting construct and cash is not. The business is identical, the reported growth rate collapses, and a company making this change will report a terrible year that means nothing. It is also why the transition disclosures matter, because the comparison to the prior year is not a comparison at all.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why is deferred revenue a liability and not an asset when the company has the cash?",a:"Because the cash comes with an obligation attached. The company has been paid and has not delivered, so it owes the customer a service. If it never delivers, it owes the money back.\n\nAn asset is a resource you control. A liability is an obligation you owe. Holding customer money you have not earned is the second.\n\nThe point: this is one of the most common conceptual mistakes, because the cash is sitting right there in the bank. The cash is the asset, recorded separately. The deferred revenue is the promise that came with it, and those are two different entries on two different sides.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A software company's deferred revenue is shrinking while revenue grows. What does that mean?",a:"That the company is recognizing revenue faster than it is signing new business. Deferred revenue is the backlog of contracts already paid for, so a declining balance means the pipeline feeding future revenue is drying up.\n\nCurrent revenue looks fine because it is being released from a balance built earlier.\n\nThe point: it is a leading indicator and current revenue is a lagging one. The income statement is showing you the past. Deferred revenue, or billings, shows you what has actually been sold. A subscription company with growing revenue and shrinking deferred revenue is reporting a good quarter and telling you the next few will be worse.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What are billings and why do investors watch them for subscription companies?",a:"Revenue plus the change in deferred revenue. It approximates what the company actually sold in the period, rather than what it recognized from prior sales.\n\nInvestors watch it because revenue for a subscription business is a slow-moving average of past bookings. Billings move first.\n\nThe point: it is the closest public proxy for sales momentum. A company whose revenue is growing 30% while billings grow 10% is decelerating, and the revenue line will not show it for another year. That gap is one of the more reliable ways to see a subscription business turning before the headline does.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is net revenue retention and why does it matter more than growth?",a:"How much revenue you keep from existing customers a year later, including upsells and downgrades but excluding new customers. Above 100% means the existing base grew by itself.\n\nIt matters because it separates growth you keep from growth you rent. A company at 120% retention grows even if it never signs another customer. A company at 80% must sell hard just to stay flat.\n\nThe point: it is the single best test of whether a product is genuinely valuable. Customers who expand their spending are voting with money after they have used it. Two companies growing 40% with retention of 120% and 85% are completely different businesses, and only one of them has a real product.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do subscription companies look unprofitable when they are healthy?",a:"Because they expense the cost of acquiring a customer immediately and recognize the revenue over years. Sales and marketing to win a customer hits this quarter; the contract pays back over three.\n\nSo the faster the company grows, the worse it looks. Growth spending scales with new customers; revenue lags.\n\nThe point: the test is unit economics, not the income statement. What does a customer cost to acquire, what do they pay over their life, and how long is the payback. If payback is 18 months and retention is high, the losses are an investment. If payback is 4 years and customers churn in 2, the losses are just losses.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's customer acquisition cost is rising. What does that tell you?",a:"That growth is getting more expensive, and there are a few reasons why.\n\nThe easy customers are gone. Early adopters were cheap; the mainstream is not. Competition bid up the channels. Or the product is losing differentiation, so it takes more spend to convince anyone.\n\nThe point: rising acquisition cost with flat pricing means the payback period is stretching and the lifetime value to cost ratio is compressing. It is the most reliable early sign that a growth story is maturing, and it usually shows up well before the growth rate itself falls, because companies can hide it for a while by simply spending more.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"How would you value a marketplace business?",a:"On take rate and gross merchandise value. GMV is the total transacted through the platform; the take rate is the percentage the marketplace keeps. Revenue is the product of the two.\n\nValue it on revenue or EBITDA multiples, but the analysis is about the network. Does more supply attract more demand, which attracts more supply?\n\nThe point: the key question is defensibility against disintermediation. If buyers and sellers can meet once on the platform and transact off it forever, the take rate collapses. That is why marketplaces invest so heavily in payments, guarantees, and reviews. Those exist to make leaving the platform costly, not to be nice.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is a network effect and how do you tell a real one from a story?",a:"A network effect means each additional user makes the product more valuable to every other user. A phone network is worthless with one user and essential with a million.\n\nThe test is whether value genuinely rises with scale, or whether the company just has a lot of users. Many businesses claim network effects when they only have economies of scale, which is a different and weaker thing.\n\nThe point: ask whether a new entrant with a better product could win anyway. If yes, there is no network effect, only a head start. Real network effects show up as improving unit economics and falling acquisition costs as the company grows. If acquisition cost is rising with scale, whatever the deck says, there is no network effect.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company says it has 100 million users but revenue is flat. What do you think?",a:"That the users are not worth much, or the company has not worked out how to charge them. Users are not revenue, and a user count is the easiest metric to inflate.\n\nQuestions to ask. Are they active or registered? What is revenue per user, and is it rising? Are the users in markets that monetize, since a user in a low-income market may be worth a fraction of one elsewhere?\n\nThe point: flat revenue against a large user base means either the product is not valuable enough to charge for, or the business model does not convert attention into money. Both are serious. A headline user number with no revenue per user disclosed is usually the tell.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has $100M of cash and a $90M market cap. Should you buy it?",a:"Not automatically, and the fact that it looks free is the warning. A negative enterprise value means the market is saying the operations are worth less than nothing.\n\nAsk why. The business is probably burning cash, so the $100M is shrinking. Management may have no intention of returning it. There may be liabilities that do not appear on the balance sheet: litigation, pensions, leases.\n\nThe point: cash inside a company you do not control is not your cash. It is only worth its face if it gets returned or invested well, and a company trading below net cash usually means the market expects neither. These situations are the classic value trap.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is a value trap?",a:"A stock that looks cheap on every multiple and stays cheap, or gets cheaper, because the business is deteriorating faster than the price falls.\n\nThe pattern is that the multiple is low for a reason. Earnings are declining, so today's P/E is on a number that will not exist next year. The cheapness is a forecast, not a discount.\n\nThe point: this is the danger of screening on multiples. Cheap and getting cheaper looks identical to cheap and mispriced at the moment you buy. The distinction is whether earnings power is stable, and that is a judgment about the business, which is exactly what a screen cannot tell you.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How do you know if a business is genuinely cheap or cheap for a reason?",a:"Test the earnings, not the multiple. Is the current earnings level sustainable, or is it a peak? Is the industry in structural decline or a cyclical trough? Is there a specific, identifiable reason the market is wrong that you can name?\n\nThen ask what breaks the thesis, and what the timeline is.\n\nThe point: the honest position is that cheap for a reason is the base case. The market has many people with more information than you, so a low multiple usually reflects something real. The burden is on you to name what they are missing. If you cannot say specifically what you know that they do not, you have found a cheap stock, not an opportunity.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is mean reversion and when does it fail?",a:"The tendency for margins, returns, and multiples to drift back toward historical averages, because high returns attract competition and low returns drive capacity out.\n\nIt fails when something structural changed. A business earning unusual returns because it has a genuine moat will not revert. An industry in permanent decline will not revert upward, however cheap it looks against its own history.\n\nThe point: this is the central mistake in mechanical value investing. Buying a company because its multiple is below its ten-year average assumes the ten-year average is still the right anchor. If the business changed, the history is not a target, it is a memory.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do most stock pitches fail in interviews?",a:"Because they describe rather than argue. The candidate explains the company, praises management, notes the growing market, and never says what the market has wrong.\n\nThe other failures: no valuation, so no view on price. No risk, which signals you have not looked. Or a thesis that is really just the consensus repeated confidently.\n\nThe point: a pitch needs a disagreement. The company being good is not a reason to buy it, because everyone knows it is good and the price reflects that. What you believe that the price does not is the only thing worth two minutes of an interviewer's time.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"You recommend a stock and the interviewer says the market already knows all of that. What do you say?",a:"Engage with it, because they are usually right and it is the correct challenge. The strong answer identifies why the information is known but mispriced.\n\nThe reasons a known fact can still be mispriced: the market is discounting the wrong time horizon, focusing on this quarter when the thesis plays out over three years. The information is known but its magnitude is underestimated. Or structural sellers, index changes, or a forced flow have pushed price away from value.\n\nThe point: what fails is insisting nobody has noticed. That is almost never true for a liquid stock. The credible version is that people know and are weighting it wrongly, and you should be able to say why.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What would make you sell a stock you own?",a:"Three reasons and only three. The thesis played out and the price now reflects it. The thesis broke, meaning the specific thing you believed turned out to be wrong. Or you found something better and capital is finite.\n\nWhat is not a reason: the price fell. That is only a reason if the reason it fell invalidated your thesis.\n\nThe point: the discipline is deciding the sell conditions when you buy, in writing, before you have any emotional stake. Everyone rationalizes afterwards, and a thesis that quietly evolves to accommodate whatever the stock is doing is not a thesis. Naming what would prove you wrong is what makes the view real.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How do you think about position sizing?",a:"By conviction and by what you can lose. The size should reflect how confident you are and how bad the downside is, not how excited you are.\n\nThe framework: how much is this worth if I am right, how much do I lose if I am wrong, and what is the probability of each. An asymmetric payoff justifies more size than a coin flip with the same expected value.\n\nThe point: the mistake is sizing to conviction alone. Highest conviction and highest downside is exactly the position that ends careers, because conviction is not correlated with being right. The right question is how much of this can I be wrong about and survive.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the difference between a good company and a good investment?",a:"A good company has durable economics: high returns on capital, a moat, real growth. A good investment is one bought at a price below what it is worth.\n\nThey are not the same and often diverge. The best company in the world at 60x earnings can be a poor investment. A mediocre business at 4x can be an excellent one.\n\nThe point: this is the single most useful distinction in investing and the one candidates most often miss. Interviewers ask about it because most people pitch great companies and think they have made an argument. Quality is a fact about the business. Value is a relationship between that business and its price.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"If everything you believe about a company is already in the price, what is your edge?",a:"There is none, and saying so is the right answer. If the price fully reflects what you know, the expected return is just the cost of capital, and you should own an index instead.\n\nAn edge comes from one of three places. Information others do not have, which is rare and often illegal in public markets. Better analysis of the same information. Or a different time horizon, being willing to hold through three bad quarters when the market cannot.\n\nThe point: the third is the only one available to most people, and it is real. Most market participants are forced to care about the next quarter. Structural patience is a genuine edge precisely because so few can afford it.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company takes a $60 restructuring charge, all paid in cash this year. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The $60 charge cuts pre-tax income $60. Tax falls $15, leaving net income down $45.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $45. The whole charge was paid in cash, so there is nothing non-cash to add back. Cash falls $45.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $45 and retained earnings are down $45.\n\nThe point: contrast this with an accrued restructuring, where part of the charge sits as a liability and the cash leaves later. Here the earnings hit and the cash hit are the same size in the same period, because nothing was deferred. The $15 gap between the charge and the cash is just the tax.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company receives $90 of insurance proceeds for a building destroyed in a fire. The building's book value was $70. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the statements.",a:"Income statement. The proceeds exceed the book value, so there is a $20 gain. Tax of $5 leaves net income up $15.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $15. Subtract the $20 gain out of operating, then show the $90 of proceeds in investing. Cash rises $85.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $85 and the building comes off at $70, so assets rise $15. Retained earnings rise $15.\n\nThe point: the company lost a building and reported a profit. The gain exists only because the insurance paid more than the depreciated book value, which says nothing about whether the building was worth $90. Book value is what accounting recorded, not what the asset was worth.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company pays $40 to settle a liability it had already accrued at $50. Walk through the statements.",a:"Income statement. The company reserved $50 and settled for $40, so it over-accrued by $10. That $10 reverses as a gain, lifting pre-tax income.\n\nCash flow statement. $40 of cash goes out, and the $10 reversal is non-cash so it is subtracted from operating.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash falls $40, the liability of $50 comes off entirely, and retained earnings rise by the after-tax gain.\n\nThe point: the earnings benefit is not the company doing well, it is the earlier estimate having been too conservative. That is the mechanism behind reserve releases, and it is why a company that consistently over-accrues has a quiet lever for producing earnings whenever it needs them.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's supplier demands cash on delivery instead of 60-day terms. What happens?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The cost of goods is unchanged, only the timing of payment.\n\nCash flow statement. Payables collapse as the balance unwinds, which is a large one-time use of cash. Going forward the company funds its own inventory instead of the supplier funding it.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash falls, accounts payable fall.\n\nThe point: this is what a liquidity crisis actually looks like from the inside. The business has not changed, the income statement looks identical, and the company may not survive it. Suppliers tightening terms is both a symptom of distress and a cause of it, which is why it accelerates so quickly once it starts.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company capitalizes $30 of costs in year one and amortizes them over three years. Show the difference from expensing across all three years.",a:"If capitalized. Year one: no expense, so net income is $30 higher pre-tax than under expensing. Years one through three: $10 of amortization each year.\n\nIf expensed. Year one takes the full $30. Years two and three take nothing.\n\nAcross all three years. Total expense is $30 either way. Total cash is identical. The only difference is the shape.\n\nThe point: capitalizing borrows earnings from the future. It makes year one look better by $30 and years two and three look worse by $10 each. It is why a company that suddenly starts capitalizing costs shows an earnings improvement that reverses on a schedule, and why the cash flow statement is unaffected in aggregate.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do you add back D&A on the cash flow statement but not other expenses?",a:"Because D&A is the only major expense where no money moved this period. Salaries were paid, rent was paid, interest was paid. Depreciation is the recognition of cash that left years ago when the asset was bought.\n\nThe cash flow statement starts at net income, which is after every expense, and its job is to strip out the ones that were not cash.\n\nThe point: the same logic applies to every non-cash charge, which is why impairments, stock compensation, and provisions are all added back too. D&A is just the most common. The test is always the same: did money actually leave the building this period, and if not, add it back.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has $500 of PP&E and takes $50 of depreciation a year, but spends $80 a year on capex. What is happening to its asset base?",a:"It is growing. Capex of $80 against depreciation of $50 means the company is adding $30 of net PP&E a year, so the asset base expands.\n\nWhether that is good depends on revenue. If revenue is growing with it, the spending is building capacity. If revenue is flat, the company is spending $30 a year more than its assets are wearing out and getting nothing for it.\n\nThe point: the ratio of capex to depreciation is a quick read on whether a company is growing, maintaining, or harvesting. Below 1x sustained means the company is shrinking its asset base, which flatters free cash flow now and creates a problem later.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company reports $200M of EBITDA, $150M of operating cash flow, and $20M of free cash flow. What do you conclude?",a:"That it is capital intensive and most of the EBITDA never reaches investors. The gap from $200M to $150M is interest, cash taxes, and working capital. The gap from $150M to $20M is $130M of capex.\n\nSo capex is 65% of EBITDA. This is a business that must spend most of what it earns just to keep operating.\n\nThe point: at a 10x EBITDA multiple this company would be valued at $2B, which is 100x its free cash flow. That gap is the entire argument against EBITDA multiples in capital-intensive sectors, and it is why telecoms, utilities, and airlines get valued on free cash flow instead.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's tax rate is 10% when the statutory rate is 25%. What explains it?",a:"Something is shielding income. The likely candidates: net operating losses from prior years offsetting current profit. Income earned in lower-tax jurisdictions. Tax credits, often for research. Or a one-time item, like the release of a valuation allowance.\n\nCheck whether it is sustainable.\n\nThe point: this matters for valuation because a DCF uses a tax rate for decades. Using 10% because that is this year's effective rate assumes the shield lasts forever, and NOLs run out. The right approach is to model the low rate while the shield lasts and the statutory rate afterwards, rather than picking one number for the whole projection.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do you use a marginal tax rate rather than the effective tax rate in a DCF?",a:"Because you are valuing future cash flows, and the effective rate reflects the past. It is distorted by one-time items, NOLs that will expire, and credits that may not recur.\n\nThe marginal rate is what the company will pay on the next dollar of profit once the temporary shields are gone.\n\nThe point: the nuance is that neither is right on its own. If a company has $500M of NOLs, ignoring them overstates the tax and undervalues the business. The correct treatment is to model the actual cash tax through the shield years and use the marginal rate thereafter, and to value the NOL as the separate asset it is.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why is the balance sheet a snapshot but the income statement a video?",a:"Because they measure different kinds of things. The balance sheet reports stocks: what the company owns and owes at one instant. Freeze time and count.\n\nThe income statement reports flows: what happened across a period. It only means something with a duration attached.\n\nThe point: this is why you average balance sheet items when comparing them to income statement items. Return on assets divides a full year of profit by assets on one day, which mismatches a flow against a stock. Using average assets fixes it. The same logic applies to inventory turns and receivable days, and it is why those ratios use averages.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why must the balance sheet balance?",a:"Because it is not a law of nature, it is an identity. Every asset was funded by something: either someone lent the money, which is a liability, or someone owned it, which is equity. There is no third source.\n\nSo assets equal liabilities plus equity by construction, not by coincidence.\n\nThe point: this is why an unbalanced model is always an error and never a finding. If it does not balance, you have either recorded one side of a transaction and not the other, or made a sign error. The identity cannot be violated by the business, only by the modeller.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is double-entry bookkeeping and why does it matter for interviews?",a:"Every transaction hits at least two accounts. Buy inventory with cash and inventory rises while cash falls. Book revenue on credit and revenue rises while receivables rise.\n\nIt matters because it is the whole logic behind three-statement questions. Every walkthrough is just tracing both sides of an entry across the statements.\n\nThe point: if you internalize that nothing happens in isolation, the questions get easier. When someone says depreciation rises $10, you know something else moved. The discipline of always asking what is the other side is what stops people getting lost halfway through, and it is why the balance check at the end catches errors.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has strong earnings and cannot pay its bills. How?",a:"Because earnings are not cash and the timing differs. The company booked profitable sales to customers who have not paid, so the profit is sitting in receivables. Meanwhile suppliers, staff, and the tax authority all want money now.\n\nAdd inventory build and capex and the gap widens.\n\nThe point: this is the single most important idea in accounting and it is why the cash flow statement exists. Solvency and liquidity are different. A company can be worth far more than it owes and still fail because it cannot make a payment on Tuesday. Profitable companies going bankrupt is not a paradox, it is the normal case.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"If you had to check one thing to see if a company's earnings are real, what would it be?",a:"The gap between net income and operating cash flow, tracked over several years. If profit is real, cash should follow it, roughly, over time.\n\nWhen they diverge persistently in the same direction, something is wrong. Either revenue is being recognized before cash arrives, costs are being capitalized rather than expensed, or working capital is absorbing everything.\n\nThe point: one year of divergence has innocent explanations, since growth genuinely consumes working capital. Three or four years of net income exceeding cash flow means the accounting and the economics have separated. Nearly every large accounting fraud shows this pattern years before anyone acts on it.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What is the single most important number on a company's financial statements?",a:"There is no single one, and picking is the wrong instinct, but the closest is free cash flow. It is the hardest to manipulate and the one that determines everything else: whether you can pay lenders, invest, return capital, or survive.\n\nRevenue can be booked without cash. Earnings depend on estimates. Cash flow eventually reveals both.\n\nThe point: the honest answer names the number and its limits. Free cash flow is noisy year to year, it punishes companies investing heavily for good reasons, and it can be flattered by underinvesting. Any single metric is a summary of something more complicated, which is exactly why interviewers ask.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A management team tells you their business has no competitors. What do you think?",a:"That they have defined their market too narrowly, or they are not paying attention. Almost nothing has no competition, because the alternative to using your product is always doing something else, including nothing.\n\nAsk what customers did before this existed. That is the competition, even if it is a spreadsheet or an intern.\n\nThe point: it is a red flag about the team more than the market. A management team that cannot name a credible threat either has not looked or is selling you something. The best operators are usually the most specific about who they are losing to and why, because that is what they spend their time on.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do you always show a range rather than a single valuation number?",a:"Because a single number implies a precision that does not exist. Every input is an estimate: growth, margins, the discount rate, the exit multiple. Compounding estimates does not produce a fact.\n\nA range is honest about that, and it shows how sensitive the answer is to the assumptions that matter.\n\nThe point: it also changes the conversation. A single number invites an argument about whether it is right. A range invites a discussion about which assumption drives it, which is the useful conversation. That is what a football field chart is for, and why fairness opinions are expressed as ranges rather than a price.",category:"DCF"},

// Original IB cards to 2000. Written from underlying finance; every arithmetic
// claim verified mechanically; every card carries a category.
{q:"If you could ask a CEO only one question before investing, what would it be?",a:"How do you allocate capital, and what did you turn down last year?\n\nThe first half tells you their framework. The second half is the real question, because anything they approved has a story attached, while what they rejected reveals the actual hurdle and whether one exists.\n\nThe point: capital allocation is the thing management genuinely controls and the thing that compounds. A CEO who cannot name a project they killed either approves everything, which means there is no discipline, or has never thought about it in those terms. Either answer tells you more than an hour on strategy would.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is the difference between a company that is growing and a company that is compounding?",a:"Growth is getting bigger. Compounding is getting bigger while earning a return above the cost of capital on the money it reinvests.\n\nA company growing 20% at a 6% return on capital against a 9% cost is destroying value every year, faster as it grows. One growing 10% at a 25% return is compounding.\n\nThe point: this is why growth is not a virtue on its own, it is a multiplier on returns. If returns exceed the cost of capital, growth multiplies value. If they do not, growth multiplies the destruction. Most people treat the growth rate as the answer when it is only half the fraction.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why is reinvestment rate as important as growth rate?",a:"Because it determines what the growth costs. Two companies both growing 10%: one reinvests 30% of earnings to do it, the other reinvests 80%. The first returns 70% of earnings to shareholders while growing identically.\n\nGrowth equals reinvestment rate times return on capital, so the two are linked mechanically.\n\nThe point: this is what a DCF is actually capturing when it subtracts capex and working capital. A company that grows without consuming capital is worth dramatically more than one growing at the same rate while swallowing everything it earns, and the growth rate alone shows neither.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company can grow 15% or return cash and grow 5%. Which creates more value?",a:"Depends entirely on the return on the reinvested capital. If it earns 20% on new investment against a 9% cost of capital, growing 15% creates far more value. If it earns 7%, the shareholders are better off with the cash, since they can find 9% elsewhere.\n\nThe point: this is the central capital allocation question and management almost always chooses growth, because a bigger company means more pay and more status. That is why a CEO who deliberately shrinks the company is rare and usually worth owning, and why activists exist. The arithmetic is simple and the incentives run the other way.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do investors pay more for predictable cash flow than for larger cash flow?",a:"Because predictability lowers the discount rate and raises how much debt the business can carry. A contracted, recurring stream gets discounted gently and can support real leverage. A volatile stream gets discounted hard and supports little.\n\nThe point: the same expected cash flow is worth substantially more if you are confident about it. That is the entire reason infrastructure, utilities, and subscription software command the multiples they do, despite unremarkable growth. It is also why a business with a lumpy $100M of EBITDA is worth less than one with a steady $80M, which looks wrong until you consider what happens to each in a bad year.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the most important thing on a balance sheet that is not on the balance sheet?",a:"The things that make the business work and were never purchased: the brand, the customer relationships, the engineering culture, the distribution. Accounting only records what was bought, so a brand built over fifty years is worth nothing on the books while one acquired last year sits there as goodwill.\n\nThe point: this is why book value is close to meaningless for most operating companies and why price to book only works for banks. It also explains the paradox that the best businesses often have the weakest-looking balance sheets, since their real assets are the ones accounting cannot see.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why is off-balance-sheet exposure worth hunting for?",a:"Because it is where the obligations that did not fit the rules end up. Guarantees of a joint venture's debt, purchase commitments, unconsolidated affiliates, receivables sold with recourse, and contingent litigation.\n\nThey live in the footnotes.\n\nThe point: the footnotes are where the balance sheet tells the truth. Every major accounting failure involved obligations that were real, disclosed somewhere, and not on the face of the statements. The discipline is to read the commitments and contingencies note before the income statement, because a company's reported leverage means nothing if the guarantees are larger than the debt.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's footnotes disclose a $400M guarantee of a joint venture's debt. How do you treat it?",a:"As a contingent liability, and probably as debt if the joint venture is weak. The company has promised to pay if the JV cannot, so the obligation is real even though it is not on the balance sheet.\n\nAssess the JV. If it comfortably services its own debt, the guarantee is remote. If it is struggling, the $400M is effectively the parent's.\n\nThe point: this is exactly what guarantees are designed to obscure. The parent gets the JV's economics without the JV's debt on its balance sheet. Credit analysts add it back, which can transform a company that looked moderately levered into one that is not.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What question would you ask to find out if a company's growth is real?",a:"Show me the cohorts. Not the aggregate revenue, the behavior of each group of customers by the year they arrived.\n\nThat single view answers most of it: whether newer customers behave worse than older ones, whether retention is decaying, whether the growth is new customers or the same customers spending more.\n\nThe point: aggregate metrics blend everything, so growing volume masks deteriorating quality for years. A company adding customers faster than it loses them looks healthy right up until it does not. The cohorts show the decay while there is still time to notice, which is exactly why companies with a problem present aggregates.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"If a company only gave you one number to judge it by, which would you ask for and why?",a:"Return on invested capital, tracked over ten years. It tells you whether the business creates value at all, whether it has a moat, and whether growth is worth having.\n\nSustained high ROIC means competitors could not compete the returns away, which means something is protecting it.\n\nThe point: the honest caveat is that one number is never enough, and ROIC can be gamed by an aging asset base or by acquisitions carried at goodwill. But if you can only have one, it answers the question that matters most: does deploying capital here make shareholders richer or poorer. Growth, margins, and multiples all follow from that.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Walk me through what happens to a company from the day it decides to IPO.",a:"Roughly six to nine months. It picks underwriters in a bake-off, then drafts the S-1 with lawyers and accountants, which is the bulk of the work. It files confidentially, the SEC reviews and comments, and the company responds over several rounds.\n\nThen the roadshow, usually two weeks of meetings, during which the book builds. Pricing happens the night before trading.\n\nThe point: the real work is the audit and the disclosure, not the marketing. Most delays come from the SEC's comments or from the company discovering its financials cannot survive being audited to public standards.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do IPOs get underpriced?",a:"Because the bank is selling to investors it needs again next time, and a deal that trades down damages everyone. Underpricing guarantees a first-day pop, which rewards the buyers, builds the bank's reputation for good allocations, and reduces the risk of a failed deal.\n\nThe point: the cost is borne by the issuer, who sold shares below what the market would have paid. A 30% first-day pop means the company left roughly 30% on the table. Founders complain about it constantly, and it persists because the bank's repeat relationship is with the buy side, not with the company doing this once.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is a green shoe and what is it actually for?",a:"An option letting underwriters sell up to 15% more shares than the base deal and buy them back later. Its real function is price support.\n\nThe bank oversells the deal, so it is short. If the stock falls, it buys in the market to cover, which supports the price. If the stock rises, it exercises the option and buys from the company at the offer price.\n\nThe point: it lets the bank stabilize a new issue without risking its own capital. The name comes from the Green Shoe Manufacturing Company, which did it first.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does a lockup expiry move a stock?",a:"Because supply arrives suddenly. Insiders are barred from selling for typically 180 days, so the float during that window is artificially small. When the lockup lifts, a large block becomes sellable at once.\n\nThe point: the move usually happens before the date, since the market anticipates it. The size of the effect depends on how much of the company is locked and whether insiders actually want out. A stock well above the IPO price with early investors sitting on large gains sees real selling. One below the IPO price often sees little, since nobody wants to crystallize a loss.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why would a company choose a direct listing over an IPO?",a:"Because it does not need the money. A direct listing just lists existing shares, so there is no capital raised, no underwriting, no dilution, and no lockup. It avoids underpricing entirely, since the market sets the opening price rather than a bank.\n\nThe point: it only works for companies that are already famous and already funded. Without a roadshow and a bank building a book, you need investors who already know who you are. That is why Spotify and Slack could do it and most companies cannot. The tradeoff is no capital and no price support.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is a SPAC and why did they lose favor?",a:"A shell company that raises money in an IPO, then has two years to find a private company to merge with, taking it public.\n\nThey lost favor because the incentives were poor. The sponsor typically got 20% of the shell for a nominal sum, so they profited from almost any deal closing, good or bad. Meanwhile redemptions meant the cash promised often did not arrive.\n\nThe point: the structure paid the sponsor for doing a deal, not a good deal. When most of the 2021 cohort traded far below their trust value, the market reached the obvious conclusion.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does a company do a follow-on offering after its IPO?",a:"To raise more capital, usually because growth needs funding or because a maturity is approaching. It can also be to let early holders sell in an orderly way.\n\nThe point: the timing is the signal. Companies issue equity when they think the stock is fairly valued or expensive, since selling cheap shares hurts existing holders. That is why follow-ons often cluster after a run-up and why the announcement typically knocks the stock down a few percent. The market reads it as management's own view that the shares are not undervalued.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do convertible bonds have lower coupons than straight debt?",a:"Because the investor is being paid partly in optionality. The conversion feature is a call option on the stock, and the option has value, so the investor accepts a lower cash coupon in exchange.\n\nThe point: the issuer is effectively selling equity upside to reduce interest expense today. That is attractive to a growth company that wants cheap capital now and expects the stock to rise, but it means giving away the appreciation. The trade is cash today for dilution later, and companies often underestimate the second half, especially if the stock does what they hoped.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why would a company issue equity when it says the stock is undervalued?",a:"That is the contradiction worth naming, and there are only a few resolutions. It needs the money and has no alternative, which means the raise is forced. It is defending a credit rating. Or management does not actually believe the stock is undervalued.\n\nThe point: issuing equity you believe is cheap transfers value from existing shareholders to new ones, so a management team that does it while claiming the stock is undervalued is telling you one of those two statements is not sincere. The market usually assumes it is the undervaluation claim, which is why the stock falls on the announcement.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company can raise debt at 7% or equity at a 25x P/E. Which is cheaper and which is safer?",a:"Debt is cheaper. At 7% with a 25% tax rate, the after-tax cost is 5.25%. Equity at 25x has an earnings yield of 4%, but the true cost of equity is well above that, since shareholders require compensation for bearing residual risk.\n\nEquity is safer. Missing a dividend is embarrassing; missing interest is a default.\n\nThe point: that is the entire tradeoff in capital structure. Debt is cheaper precisely because it is riskier for the company and safer for the provider. You are paid to take risk, and with debt the company keeps it.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What does a rating downgrade from BBB to BB actually do to a company?",a:"It changes who can own its debt. Many institutional mandates prohibit sub-investment-grade paper, so a downgrade forces mechanical selling regardless of price and shrinks the future buyer base.\n\nBorrowing costs rise, covenants tighten, and some contracts have rating triggers.\n\nThe point: the step from BBB minus to BB plus is the single most consequential move in credit. It is not a marginal increase in risk, it is a change in the buyer universe. That is why companies defend the last investment-grade notch with decisions that make no operating sense, like cutting capex or selling good assets.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do companies care about their credit rating more than their cost of debt would suggest?",a:"Because the rating affects things beyond interest. Access to commercial paper, terms with suppliers, the ability to bid on long contracts, counterparty willingness to trade, and collateral requirements in derivatives all key off it.\n\nThe point: a downgrade can trigger a chain of obligations at once. Rating triggers in contracts can require posting collateral exactly when liquidity is tight, which is how a downgrade becomes a liquidity crisis. The rating is not a description of risk, it is an input to contracts, which makes it partly self-fulfilling.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why is commercial paper dangerous funding despite being cheap?",a:"Because it is very short term, often under 90 days, so it must be continuously rolled. It is cheap precisely because lenders can walk away almost immediately.\n\nThe point: it works until the market decides it does not want your paper, and that decision arrives without warning. A company funding long-term assets with commercial paper has a duration mismatch identical to a bank's. That is exactly what killed several finance companies in 2008, since the assets were fine and the funding vanished in a week. It is why CP programs are backstopped by revolvers.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the point of a revolver a company never draws?",a:"Insurance. The company pays a commitment fee for the right to borrow, and the value is the certainty that the money is there in a bad month.\n\nIt also backstops commercial paper, which is what lets rating agencies treat the CP program as reliable.\n\nThe point: the paradox is that a revolver is most valuable when never used and least available when you need it. Facilities have conditions, and drawing one during a crisis can itself signal distress. That is why companies drew their revolvers en masse in March 2020: not because they needed the cash, but because they doubted it would be there later.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A target's EBITDA is $50M. The buyer pays 10x with 60% debt at 8%. Does the deal service itself?",a:"Just about, and not comfortably. The price is $500M, so $300M of debt at 8% is $24M of interest. Coverage is $50M over $24M, or 2.1x.\n\nAfter interest there is $26M left, before capex, tax, and working capital. If capex is $15M, the company is running on roughly $11M of slack.\n\nThe point: this is what lenders mean by a tight structure. The deal works in the base case and has no room for a bad year. That is why sponsors stress a 20% EBITDA decline as a matter of routine: at $40M, coverage falls to 1.7x and the slack disappears entirely.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why would a buyer prefer an asset deal when the seller insists on a stock deal?",a:"For the tax step-up and the liabilities. In an asset deal the buyer resets the tax basis of the assets to the purchase price, so it can depreciate them at the new value and save real cash tax for years. It also picks which liabilities to assume, leaving unknown risks behind.\n\nThe seller resists because it gets taxed twice: at the company level on the gain, then again on the proceeds.\n\nThe point: this is a genuine economic conflict with a price attached. The step-up is worth real money to the buyer, so a rational buyer will pay a higher price for an asset deal, and the negotiation is really about splitting that tax benefit.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is a 338(h)(10) election and why does it exist?",a:"It lets a transaction that is legally a stock purchase be treated as an asset purchase for tax purposes, so the buyer gets a step-up in basis while the deal itself stays a simple stock sale.\n\nIt requires both parties to agree, because the seller usually takes a worse tax outcome.\n\nThe point: it exists to solve exactly the conflict between buyer and seller preferences. The buyer wants the step-up, the seller wants the clean stock sale, and the election gives both. Since it costs the seller, the buyer typically compensates them for the difference, which means the step-up value gets negotiated explicitly rather than fought over.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company's operating margin fell from 18% to 12% while revenue grew 30%. What happened?",a:"Costs outran revenue. Six margin points on a growing base is a large deterioration, and the candidates are: sales and marketing scaling faster than sales, so acquisition got more expensive; mix shifting toward lower-margin customers or products; price cuts driving the volume; or deliberate investment ahead of revenue.\n\nThe point: check gross margin first to locate it. If gross margin held and operating margin fell, the problem is in opex and may be investment. If gross margin fell too, the company is losing pricing power, which is far more serious because it cannot be cost-cut back.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"What does it mean that terminal value is 75% of a DCF?",a:"That three quarters of the value depends on one assumption about a period you did not forecast. It is normal, since most of a company's life lies beyond year five, and it is also the honest weakness of every DCF.\n\nThe point: the response is not to panic, it is to cross-check. Compare your implied exit multiple against the comps. Compare your implied perpetuity growth against long-run GDP. If your terminal assumptions produce a multiple the market has never paid, the model is telling you something. At 75% the projections are barely doing any work, which is why sensitivity tables exist.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do you discount the terminal value back to today?",a:"Because it is a value as of the end of the projection period, not today. If your forecast runs five years, the terminal value represents everything from year six onward expressed as a single number at the end of year five.\n\nSo it gets discounted five years, like any year-five cash flow.\n\nThe point: forgetting this is one of the most common modelling errors and it massively overstates value. At a 10% discount rate, five years of discounting cuts the terminal value by roughly 38%. Since terminal value is most of the answer, the error is not small, and it is invisible unless someone checks the discount factor.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company's beta is 1.4. What does that tell you about its cost of equity?",a:"That shareholders demand 40% more of the equity risk premium than the market average. At a 4% risk-free rate and a 5% premium, cost of equity is 4% plus 1.4 times 5%, which is 11%.\n\nCompare with a beta of 1.0, which gives 9%. The extra 2 points is the price of the volatility.\n\nThe point: a beta above 1 usually means cyclicality or leverage. Check which, because they have different implications. Cyclicality is the business; leverage is a choice. If the 1.4 is mostly leverage, unlevering it will reveal a much lower business risk underneath.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company's WACC calculation uses its historical coupon rate for cost of debt. What is wrong?",a:"It should use what the company would pay to borrow today, not what it agreed to years ago. WACC is a forward-looking required return, so every input has to be current.\n\nIf a bond was issued at 4% and the company's credit has since deteriorated so its debt now yields 9%, the cost of debt is 9%.\n\nThe point: this error always runs the same direction for troubled companies. Using the old coupon understates the cost of capital and overstates the valuation, exactly when the company is in trouble and the valuation matters most. Use the yield to maturity on traded debt, or comparable credits if none trades.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do you use the market value of equity rather than book value in WACC weights?",a:"Because WACC asks what return investors require on today's value. Book equity is historical cost and bears no relation to what the shares are worth.\n\nA company trading at 3x book would show a wildly distorted debt-to-equity ratio if you used the book figure, understating the equity weight and therefore understating WACC.\n\nThe point: the same logic technically applies to debt, though book is usually close enough since most debt trades near par. It stops being close enough when the company is distressed and its debt trades at 60 cents, which is precisely when the distinction matters.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company generates $100M of EBITDA and pays $30M of cash taxes. Its statutory rate is 25%. What do you check?",a:"Whether the cash tax is consistent with the earnings. If EBITDA is $100M and D&A is, say, $20M and interest is $10M, pre-tax income is $70M, and 25% of that is $17.5M. Paying $30M means something is off.\n\nThe candidates: prior-year settlements, foreign taxes at higher rates, non-deductible items, or a repatriation charge.\n\nThe point: cash tax exceeding the statutory rate on reported profit is unusual and worth explaining, because it means the company is paying tax on income the income statement is not showing. That is often a sign of aggressive book accounting that the tax authority does not accept.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do sponsors care about maintenance capex specifically during diligence?",a:"Because it sets the floor on cash the business must spend forever. Growth capex can be cut the day after closing; maintenance capex cannot, without the business slowly degrading.\n\nCompanies rarely disclose the split, so buyers estimate it, often anchoring near depreciation.\n\nThe point: the number decides whether the leverage is supportable. If a business generates $50M of EBITDA and truly needs $30M of maintenance capex, only $20M is available to service debt, and a structure built on the $50M will fail. Sellers have every incentive to classify capex as growth, which is exactly why buyers dig.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company defers maintenance capex for two years and free cash flow improves. What is really happening?",a:"It is borrowing from the future. Free cash flow rose because the company stopped spending, not because it earned more. The assets are degrading on schedule regardless.\n\nEventually the deferred spending arrives all at once, usually with interest in the form of emergency repairs or lost capacity.\n\nThe point: this is one of the easiest ways to manufacture cash flow and one of the hardest to see from outside. The tell is capex falling below depreciation for a sustained period with no change in the business. It is also a favourite pre-sale move, which is why buyers reconstruct maintenance capex rather than trusting the recent trend.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What does it mean when a company's capex is consistently below depreciation?",a:"That the asset base is shrinking. Depreciation measures assets wearing out; capex measures replacement. Spending less than the wear rate means the company is consuming its asset base.\n\nSometimes it is legitimate: an asset-light transition, or depreciation schedules that are simply too aggressive.\n\nThe point: sustained underinvestment flatters free cash flow now and creates a cliff later. The company looks like a cash machine right up to the year it has to spend. Check whether revenue is holding, because harvesting a declining business and quietly underinvesting in a healthy one look identical for about three years.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's interest expense fell but its debt is unchanged. What happened?",a:"Either it refinanced at a lower rate, or it has floating-rate debt and rates fell, or capitalized interest is now being excluded from the expense line.\n\nCheck the debt footnote for fixed versus floating mix.\n\nThe point: the third possibility is the interesting one. A company building a large asset can capitalize the interest into PP&E rather than expensing it, so reported interest drops while the cash payment is identical. Earnings improve, operating cash flow improves, and nothing real changed. The cost reappears later as extra depreciation.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why do lenders care about the fixed versus floating mix of a borrower's debt?",a:"Because floating-rate debt transfers interest rate risk to the borrower, and a borrower who cannot bear it becomes the lender's problem. Rates rise, interest expense rises, coverage falls, and a covenant trips despite the business performing exactly as underwritten.\n\nThe point: it is an uncompensated risk from the lender's perspective. They did not underwrite a rate view, they underwrote a business. That is why credit agreements often require the borrower to hedge a portion of floating exposure, so a rate move does not turn a healthy company into a default the lender has to manage.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do you care whether revenue is recurring or one-time?",a:"Because it changes what next year looks like without any selling. Recurring revenue carries forward, so the company starts each year with most of its base intact. One-time revenue resets to zero, so the company must rebuild from nothing every January.\n\nThe point: this is why software trades at multiples project businesses never see, despite sometimes identical margins. A consultancy earning $100M of project revenue and a software company earning $100M of subscriptions are not comparable, because one has to win $100M of new work next year just to stand still. The multiple is pricing the starting line, not the finish.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company calls its revenue recurring but customers sign one-year contracts with no auto-renewal. Is it recurring?",a:"Not really. It is repeating, which is different. Recurring implies the default is continuation and the customer has to act to leave. Here the default is termination and the customer has to act to stay.\n\nThe point: check the retention rate rather than the label. If 95% renew every year without a sales effort, the distinction is academic. If renewal requires a full sales cycle each time, the company has a one-year business calling itself a subscription. The word recurring appears in every deck; the renewal mechanics are in the contracts, and only one of those is evidence.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is the difference between gross retention and net retention?",a:"Gross retention measures how much revenue you keep from existing customers, counting only losses. It caps at 100%. Net retention adds upsell and expansion, so it can exceed 100%.\n\nA company can show 120% net retention while losing a third of its customers, if the survivors expand enough.\n\nThe point: this is why you need both. Net retention alone can hide serious churn behind a few expanding accounts, which is a concentration risk dressed as growth. Gross retention tells you whether the product holds customers; net tells you whether it grows inside them. A company that will not disclose gross is usually hiding the answer.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's net revenue retention is 130% but gross retention is 70%. What is happening?",a:"It is losing 30% of its revenue base annually and making it up by expanding hard inside the customers who stay. The headline looks excellent and the underlying churn is severe.\n\nThe point: this is a concentration problem in disguise. Growth depends on a shrinking group of accounts spending progressively more, which cannot continue indefinitely. Every account has a ceiling. When expansion inside the survivors runs out, the 30% churn is still there and the growth collapses. Companies quote net retention precisely because it can look wonderful while the product is failing most of the people who buy it.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do investors care about the payback period on customer acquisition cost?",a:"Because it determines how much cash growth consumes. If it takes 6 months to recover what you spent acquiring a customer, you can self-fund growth. If it takes 30 months, every new customer is a financing event.\n\nThe point: payback matters more than the lifetime value to acquisition cost ratio, even though the ratio gets quoted more. A 5:1 ratio sounds great and tells you nothing about timing. If the value arrives over eight years, the company will run out of cash long before the ratio is realized. Ratios ignore time; payback is entirely about it, which is why lenders and sponsors look at payback first.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has a 3:1 LTV to CAC ratio. Is that good?",a:"It is the conventional benchmark, and it depends entirely on the inputs. LTV is built on assumed retention and assumed margins projected years out, so it is a forecast wearing the costume of a fact.\n\nCheck how it was calculated. What churn assumption? What margin? Over what horizon?\n\nThe point: companies routinely compute LTV over a customer life that exceeds the age of the company itself. A 3:1 ratio built on a seven-year assumed life from a four-year-old business is not evidence, it is a projection. The honest version uses observed cohort behavior, and the gap between the two is where these numbers go wrong.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is cohort analysis and why is it more honest than aggregate metrics?",a:"Grouping customers by when they signed and tracking each group over time. It shows whether the customers who joined in 2023 behave better or worse than those who joined in 2021.\n\nAggregate metrics blend everything, so new customers mask the decay of old ones.\n\nThe point: this is how you catch a business that looks healthy and is deteriorating. If each successive cohort retains worse than the last, the company is acquiring progressively lower-quality customers, and the aggregate number hides it because volume keeps rising. Growth can paper over decay for years, and cohorts are the only thing that shows it in time.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's revenue growth is decelerating from 60% to 40% to 25%. What is the honest read?",a:"That growth is normalizing, which is what happens to everything. The question is where it settles and why it is slowing.\n\nIf the market is saturating, the deceleration continues. If it is the law of large numbers on a bigger base, the absolute dollars may still be growing nicely. If it is competition, the trajectory is worse than the numbers suggest.\n\nThe point: check absolute dollar additions rather than percentages. A company adding $100M, then $110M, then $120M is decelerating in percentage terms and accelerating in dollars. Those are completely different stories and the percentage hides which one you are looking at.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why is a high customer acquisition cost not automatically bad?",a:"Because it has to be judged against what the customer is worth and how long they stay. Paying $50,000 to acquire an enterprise customer who pays $200,000 a year for a decade is excellent. Paying $50 for a consumer who churns in three months is terrible.\n\nThe point: the useful comparison is CAC against first-year revenue, which gives payback, and against gross profit rather than revenue, since you only recover the margin, not the top line. A company reporting a 12-month payback on revenue with a 40% gross margin actually has a 30-month payback on cash, and that distinction decides whether the model works.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company spends 60% of revenue on sales and marketing. When is that defensible?",a:"When growth is fast, retention is high, and payback is short. A company growing 50% with 120% net retention and a 15-month payback is buying an annuity, and the spending is investment.\n\nIt stops being defensible when growth slows without the spending falling, because that means the money is buying replacement rather than expansion.\n\nThe point: the test is what happens if they cut it. If the company would be profitable and stop growing, the spend is discretionary. If it would be unprofitable and shrink, the spend is maintenance, and the business does not have the economics it claims.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do software companies front-load losses and what does that hide?",a:"Because acquisition costs hit immediately and the revenue arrives over years. Sales commission, marketing, and onboarding are all paid to win a contract that pays back across three.\n\nSo the faster the company grows, the worse the income statement looks.\n\nThe point: what it hides is the difference between a company losing money because it is growing and one losing money because the unit economics do not work. Both report losses that scale with growth. The way to separate them is to look at a single cohort's economics rather than the consolidated income statement, because the consolidated view mixes profitable old customers with unprofitable new ones and reports the blend.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's growth is entirely from price increases, not volume. What do you think?",a:"That it is running out of room. Price increases are the highest-margin growth there is, and they are finite. Eventually customers substitute, negotiate, or leave.\n\nCheck whether volume is flat or declining underneath. Flat volume with rising price is a mature business harvesting; declining volume with rising price is a business losing customers and covering it by charging the survivors more.\n\nThe point: the second pattern is dangerous because it looks like growth on the income statement while the customer base erodes. It is also self-accelerating, since each price rise pushes more customers out and requires a larger rise on fewer accounts.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why is pricing power the thing investors actually pay for?",a:"Because it is the cleanest evidence of a moat and the highest-leverage variable in any business. A price increase flows almost entirely to profit, since no cost moves with it.\n\nThe reason it matters more than growth is durability. Anyone can grow by cutting price. Only a company customers cannot easily leave can raise price and keep them.\n\nThe point: this is why the test is not whether the company raised price, it is whether it raised price and kept the volume. Buffett's version is that the single most important decision in evaluating a business is pricing power, because if you have to pray before raising prices 10%, you have a terrible business.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company raises prices 8% and loses 3% of volume. Was that a good decision?",a:"Yes, comfortably. Start with $100 of revenue at a 40% gross margin, so $60 of COGS and $40 of gross profit.\n\nAfter the change, volume is 3% lower and price is 8% higher, so revenue is 1.08 times 0.97, which is $104.8. COGS falls with volume to $58.2. Gross profit is $46.6, up from $40.\n\nThe point: gross profit rose 16% because the price increase carried no cost at all while the lost volume removed cost as well as revenue. This is why elasticity matters so much. A business can afford to lose real volume on a price rise and still come out well ahead, and most companies badly underestimate how much.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do subscription businesses get valued on revenue when other businesses get valued on profit?",a:"Because the profit is deliberately suppressed and the revenue is unusually predictable. A subscription company spending heavily to acquire customers reports losses that reflect growth rather than economics, so profit is not measuring anything useful yet.\n\nMeanwhile the revenue is contracted and recurring, which makes it far more forecastable than a project business's.\n\nThe point: the revenue multiple is a placeholder for future profit, and it only holds if retention is real and margins eventually arrive. When either fails, the whole framework collapses, which is what happens when a company at 10x revenue turns out to have 70% gross retention.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why does a bank fail when its loans are still performing?",a:"Because banks fail on funding, not on assets. Deposits are payable on demand and loans are not. If depositors leave faster than the bank can raise cash, it must sell long-dated assets immediately, crystallizing losses that only existed on paper.\n\nThe point: this is what happened in 2023. The loans and bonds were mostly fine if held to maturity. Rates had risen, so their market value had fallen, and the bank was solvent on an accrual basis and insolvent the moment it had to sell. A bank run is not a judgment about credit quality, it is a race, and the asset side has no say in it.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is duration mismatch and why is it a bank's core risk?",a:"Borrowing short and lending long. Deposits can leave tomorrow; a 30-year mortgage cannot be called. The bank earns the spread between short rates and long rates, and that spread is the compensation for bearing the mismatch.\n\nThe point: it is not a flaw, it is the business. Maturity transformation is what banks exist to do, since savers want liquidity and borrowers want term. The risk is that the mismatch is fine until it is not, and it turns fatal in hours rather than quarters. That is why deposit insurance and central bank liquidity facilities exist, since without them the model is inherently unstable.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do rising rates initially help a bank's margin and then hurt it?",a:"Because the asset side reprices before the liability side. Loans, especially floating-rate ones, reset quickly to higher rates while depositors keep earning almost nothing, so the net interest margin widens.\n\nThen depositors notice. They demand higher rates or move money to treasuries and money funds, so funding costs catch up.\n\nThe point: the lag is the whole trade, and it is temporary. Banks report excellent margins early in a hiking cycle and the market extrapolates them. What follows is deposit beta, meaning how much of the rate rise the bank must pass on, and that is what decides whether the gain was real or borrowed.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A bank has a 12% ROE and a 10% cost of equity. What should it trade at relative to book?",a:"Above book, roughly 1.2x on a simple model. The intuition is that if the bank earns exactly its cost of equity, the equity is worth exactly book, so 1x. Earning 2 points above means the equity generates surplus value.\n\nA rough relationship is price to book equals ROE minus growth divided by cost of equity minus growth.\n\nThe point: this is the entire mechanic of bank valuation in one line. It also explains why banks trading below book are common after a crisis, since the market is saying they cannot earn their cost of equity. That is a statement about future profitability, not about the accounting.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why is EBITDA meaningless for an insurance company?",a:"Because interest and investment income are the business, not financing. An insurer collects premiums, holds the float, and invests it. Stripping out investment income removes a core profit engine, and stripping out interest makes no sense when the balance sheet is the operation.\n\nThe point: you value insurers on the two engines separately. Underwriting profit, measured by the combined ratio, where below 100% means premiums exceeded claims and expenses. And investment income on the float. An insurer can lose money underwriting and be highly profitable, which is Buffett's entire model, so the combined ratio alone tells you nothing about whether the business works.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is float and why is it valuable?",a:"The money an insurer holds between collecting premiums and paying claims. It can be years, and during that time the insurer invests it and keeps the returns.\n\nIt is effectively a loan from policyholders. If underwriting breaks even, the float is free money; if underwriting is profitable, the insurer is being paid to borrow.\n\nThe point: that is the whole insight behind Berkshire. Most people see insurance as selling policies. Buffett saw it as a financing vehicle that generates investable capital at negative cost, which is why the combined ratio matters less than whether the float is growing and what it earns.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How would you value an exchange or a payments network?",a:"On EV/EBITDA, and expect a high multiple. These are close to ideal businesses: enormous operating leverage since the marginal transaction costs almost nothing, network effects since more participants attract more participants, and minimal capital intensity.\n\nWatch volume growth, take rate per transaction, and regulatory risk.\n\nThe point: the risk is not competition, it is regulation and disintermediation. A network with genuine network effects rarely loses to a better product. It loses when a regulator caps the take rate or mandates interoperability, which is why these businesses spend so heavily on lobbying rather than on R&D.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's take rate falls from 3% to 2.5% while volume doubles. What happened to revenue?",a:"It rose 67%. Revenue is volume times take rate, so doubling volume at 2.5% against the old 3% gives 2 times 0.833, which is 1.67.\n\nThe point: the interesting question is why the take rate fell. If it is mix, meaning larger customers who negotiate better pricing, that is the natural cost of scale and it continues. If it is competition, the compression continues too and volume growth will not always outrun it. Marketplaces live and die on this trade, since take rate is the price of the platform and the easiest thing for a competitor to attack.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do marketplaces obsess over disintermediation?",a:"Because the platform's entire economics depend on the transaction happening on it. If a buyer and seller meet once through the marketplace and then transact directly forever, the platform paid to introduce them and earns nothing thereafter.\n\nThe point: this is why marketplaces invest so heavily in things that look like customer service and are actually lock-in. Payments, escrow, guarantees, reviews, dispute resolution. None of those exist to be nice. They exist so that leaving the platform costs the user something, whether it is protection, reputation, or convenience. The take rate is only defensible if leaving is expensive.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company reports GMV of $2B and revenue of $60M. What is the take rate and does it matter?",a:"3%. Revenue over gross merchandise value.\n\nIt matters because GMV is not the company's money. Only the $60M is. A marketplace quoting GMV growth is describing activity on its platform, not its own business.\n\nThe point: watch for companies valuing themselves on GMV multiples, which is a category error. The company's value derives from the $60M and its growth, and from whether the take rate can rise. A marketplace with $2B of GMV and a 3% take rate that cannot raise pricing is a $60M revenue business, however impressive the headline sounds.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do investors distinguish between a marketplace and a reseller?",a:"Because of who bears the risk and how revenue is reported. A marketplace connects buyer and seller and books only its fee, so revenue is small and margins are high. A reseller buys inventory, takes ownership, and books the full sale, so revenue is large and margins are thin.\n\nThe point: the reseller carries inventory risk, working capital, and obsolescence. The marketplace carries none. Same transaction, completely different balance sheets and completely different multiples. This is exactly the principal versus agent question, and it explains why companies fight to classify themselves as principals when valued on revenue and as agents when valued on margin.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why can a company have great unit economics and still be a bad investment?",a:"Because the market may be too small, or the price may already reflect the economics. Unit economics tell you whether each customer is profitable. They say nothing about how many customers exist or what you are paying for the business.\n\nThe point: a company with wonderful economics on 10,000 possible customers has a ceiling. One with wonderful economics at 60x revenue has priced in a decade of flawless execution. Both are good companies and bad investments. This is the distinction most candidates miss, since quality is a fact about the business and value is a relationship between that business and its price.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company operates in a $500M market and has $300M of revenue. What is the problem?",a:"It owns 60% of its market, so growth has to come from somewhere new: expanding the market itself, entering adjacent ones, or raising price.\n\nThe point: first, interrogate the market size figure, since companies define their market to suit the story. If the $500M is genuinely the ceiling, the growth story is over and the multiple should reflect a mature business. If the definition is too narrow, and it often is, the real question is whether the company's advantage travels into the adjacent market or stops at the border. Dominance in a small market is frequently mistaken for a growth company.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why is total addressable market the most abused number in a pitch?",a:"Because nobody can falsify it and everyone benefits from it being large. A company can define its market as all software, or all enterprise software, or all mid-market CRM software, and the number swings by orders of magnitude.\n\nThe point: the honest test is bottom-up rather than top-down. How many customers actually exist who have this problem, can pay, and can be reached? Multiply by realistic pricing. That number is always smaller and always more useful than a top-down slice of an industry report, and the gap between the two is a decent measure of how much the deck is selling you.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company says its market is growing 25% a year. What do you check?",a:"Where the number came from, and whether the company's own growth is consistent with it. If the market grows 25% and the company grows 15%, it is losing share while sounding like a growth story.\n\nThe point: market growth is often cited from an industry report the company commissioned or cherry-picked. The more useful figure is the company's growth relative to the market. Growing slower than your market in a boom is a serious signal, because it means you are losing the easiest possible customers, the ones already looking to buy. That shows up long before revenue actually declines.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company writes down $80 of PP&E but the asset still works fine. Why would it do that?",a:"Because impairment tests value, not function. If the asset's expected future cash flows fall below its carrying value, it gets written down even if it runs perfectly.\n\nA factory making a product nobody wants is fully operational and worth less than the books claim.\n\nThe point: this separates accounting value from physical condition. The write-down is a statement about demand, not about maintenance. It costs no cash, and cash actually rises by the tax benefit. What it tells you is that management has conceded the asset will not earn what they once assumed.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company reports positive net income every quarter for five years and never generates cash. Is that possible?",a:"Yes, and it is the classic fraud pattern. Book revenue to customers who never pay, so profit is real on paper and sits permanently in receivables. Capitalize costs that should be expensed, so the income statement stays clean while cash leaves through investing.\n\nThe point: this is exactly why the cash flow statement exists. Net income is built on estimates: when revenue is earned, what an asset's life is, how much to reserve. Cash is not an estimate. Five years of profit with no cash is not a timing difference, it is the accounting and the economics having separated, and the accounting eventually loses.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why does a company with high depreciation often have a low P/E and a normal EV/EBITDA?",a:"Because depreciation sits between the two. It reduces net income, which inflates P/E, but it is added back in EBITDA, so the EV/EBITDA multiple is unaffected.\n\nA capital-intensive company with heavy depreciation will look expensive on earnings and ordinary on EBITDA.\n\nThe point: neither multiple is lying, they are measuring different things. The question is whether the depreciation reflects real economics, meaning assets that genuinely must be replaced. If it does, the low P/E is the honest signal and EV/EBITDA is flattering the business by ignoring a real cost.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has no debt. Should it take some on?",a:"Probably some, because it is leaving the tax shield on the table. Interest is deductible, so debt is structurally cheaper than equity, and a company with zero debt has a higher WACC than it needs.\n\nBut the answer depends on cash flow stability. A cyclical business with no debt may be making a deliberate choice to survive downturns.\n\nThe point: the theoretical answer is that WACC falls as you add cheap debt, then rises as default risk pushes both costs up, so there is an optimum. The practical answer is that nobody can locate it, which is why companies target a credit rating instead. Zero debt is either discipline or laziness, and the cash flow tells you which.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What happens to a DCF if you extend the projection period from 5 years to 10 years?",a:"Not much, usually, and that surprises people. Extending the explicit forecast shifts value from terminal value into the projection period, but the total barely moves, because you are discounting the same cash flows either way.\n\nWhat changes is where the value appears, not how much there is.\n\nThe point: the benefit is honesty rather than accuracy. If a company will not reach steady state for a decade, a five-year forecast forces the terminal value to absorb a growth phase, which the perpetuity formula handles badly. Extending lets the model show the maturation explicitly rather than burying it in one assumption.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company's WACC is 9%. It finds a project returning 11%. Should it invest?",a:"Yes, if 11% is a genuine risk-adjusted return on capital of similar risk. The project earns two points above what the capital costs, so it creates value.\n\nThe caution is that WACC reflects the risk of the existing business. A project riskier than the company average should be discounted at a higher rate than 9%, not at the company's blended cost.\n\nThe point: this is where firms destroy value quietly. Using a single corporate hurdle rate for every project means risky projects look attractive and safe ones look marginal, so capital systematically flows to the wrong places. The rate should match the project's risk, not the company's average.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A target has $40M of EBITDA. A strategic bids 11x and a sponsor bids 9x. Why the gap?",a:"Synergies. The strategic can fold the target into its existing business, eliminating duplicate overhead and capturing revenue overlap, so the target is worth more in its hands than standalone.\n\nThe sponsor has none of that. It is buying standalone cash flow and bidding to an IRR hurdle, so it stops at 9x.\n\nThe point: this is why an LBO analysis is often called a floor valuation. A sponsor will always bid up to its return threshold and no further, which sets the minimum a strategic has to clear. The 2x gap, worth $80M here, is roughly the synergy value the strategic is willing to share with the seller.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company acquires a target and reports EPS accretion of 8%, but the stock falls. Why?",a:"Because the market is not valuing the accretion, it is valuing the price. EPS accretion can be manufactured with cheap debt regardless of whether the deal was smart.\n\nThe likely readings: the market thinks the buyer overpaid, so value transferred to the seller. Or the leverage used to create the accretion made the company riskier. Or the market doubts the synergies underpinning the math.\n\nThe point: accretion is an accounting outcome, value creation is an economic one. A buyer can print higher EPS while destroying value, and the market frequently notices the difference even when the press release does not.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A sponsor buys at 8x and the business misses EBITDA by 15% in year one. What happens?",a:"Leverage amplifies it immediately. If the deal was funded at 5.5x EBITDA of debt, a 15% EBITDA miss takes leverage from 5.5x to about 6.5x without a dollar of new borrowing, purely because the denominator shrank.\n\nThat may breach a maintenance covenant, and interest coverage deteriorates at the same time.\n\nThe point: this is the asymmetry of leverage that returns math hides. A 15% operating miss is survivable for an unlevered company and a crisis for a levered one. The equity absorbs the whole shortfall, which is exactly why sponsors underwrite predictability over growth.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do LBO returns fall so sharply if the hold period extends from 5 years to 7?",a:"Because IRR is time-weighted. The same 3x return earned over five years is about 25%; stretched to seven, it drops to roughly 17%. Nothing about the business changed, only the clock.\n\nThe point: this is why a sponsor will sell a perfectly good company rather than hold it. It also explains a real conflict. Holding longer may grow the multiple of money, which is what LPs ultimately spend, while damaging the IRR the fund reports and markets on. Those two metrics can point in opposite directions, which is why LPs insist on seeing both.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's inventory turns fell from 8x to 5x. What is happening and what does it cost?",a:"Goods are sitting longer. At 8 turns, inventory sits about 46 days; at 5 turns, about 73 days. That is a month of extra holding.\n\nIt costs cash directly, because more money is tied up in goods that have not sold. It also risks obsolescence and eventual write-downs.\n\nThe point: with sales flat, falling turns means the company bought against a forecast that did not happen. Inventory outgrowing sales is one of the most reliable predictors that next quarter disappoints, because unsold goods eventually get marked down and the margin goes with them.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company issues $500M of 10-year bonds at a 6% coupon when treasuries yield 4%. What is the credit spread and what does it tell you?",a:"200 basis points. The spread is what investors demand above the risk-free rate to compensate for default risk.\n\nAt 200bps the market is treating this as solid investment grade. High yield issuers pay 400 to 600 over, and distressed credits far more.\n\nThe point: the spread, not the coupon, is the market's actual verdict on the company. A 6% coupon sounds expensive in a 2% world and cheap in a 5% one. Strip the risk-free rate out and what remains is the price of this specific company's risk, which is the only part management can influence.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company can borrow at 6% or issue equity at a 20x P/E. Which is cheaper?",a:"Debt, comfortably. At 6% with a 25% tax rate, the after-tax cost is 4.5%. Equity at a 20x P/E has an earnings yield of 5%, and that is before accounting for the fact that shareholders bear more risk and demand more than the earnings yield implies.\n\nThe point: the comparison people miss is that equity feels free because nobody sends an invoice. No cash leaves when you issue stock. But you have permanently given away a share of every future dollar, which is why the true cost of equity is well above the earnings yield and why debt is almost always the cheaper marginal dollar until leverage gets dangerous.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company's free cash flow is negative but it is growing 40%. Should you worry?",a:"Not necessarily, and the answer is in what is consuming the cash. If it is working capital and growth capex, the burn is the cost of expansion and it reverses when growth slows. If it is operating losses, the business does not work.\n\nCheck the unit economics: what does a customer cost to acquire, what do they pay over their life, and how long is the payback.\n\nThe point: the test is whether the company could be profitable tomorrow by simply stopping growth. If yes, the burn is a choice. If no, it is a condition. Those look identical on the cash flow statement and are completely different businesses.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why might a company deliberately keep its leverage below what lenders would allow?",a:"To preserve optionality. Unused debt capacity is the ability to act when others cannot: buy a competitor in a downturn, survive a bad year without a dilutive equity raise, fund a project without asking permission.\n\nIt also protects the credit rating, and the step from investment grade to high yield is enormously expensive.\n\nThe point: the textbook says lever up to minimize WACC. The practical counterargument is that the optimal capital structure is calculated for a normal world, and the value of dry powder shows up precisely when the world is not normal. Companies that survive downturns tend to be the ones that looked over-equitized during the boom.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you had to work with incomplete information.",a:"Pick a real one with a decision attached. The structure: what you did not know, why waiting was not an option, how you decided what mattered most, what you assumed explicitly, and what you did to reduce the risk of being wrong.\n\nThe point: this is banking in one question. You will constantly build models on information that does not exist yet. What they are testing is whether you can act without certainty while being honest about what you assumed. The strong version names the assumption you were least confident in and explains how you flagged it, rather than pretending you were sure.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you disagreed with someone more senior.",a:"Show that you can push back without being difficult. The structure: what you disagreed about, how you raised it, what evidence you brought, and what happened.\n\nThe key is that you raised it once, clearly, with evidence, and then committed either way.\n\nThe point: what fails is a story where you were right and they were an idiot, or one where you said nothing. The first tells them how you will describe this team later; the second tells them you will let an error into a client deck. They want someone who flags a problem and then executes the decision that gets made.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you made a mistake that affected other people.",a:"Name a real one and own it without deflecting. What happened, what the consequence was for others, how you found it, whether you flagged it yourself, and what you changed.\n\nThe point: the single most important detail is whether you found and raised it, or whether someone else did. An analyst who catches their own error and says so immediately is worth enormously more than one who is right slightly more often but hides the misses. Mistakes are certain in this job. What they are underwriting is what you do in the twenty minutes after you notice.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you had to manage competing deadlines.",a:"Be specific about how you decided, not that you worked hard. The structure: what was competing, how you determined what actually mattered, who you told, and what you dropped or renegotiated.\n\nThe point: the answer they want includes communication. An analyst with three deliverables due at once who quietly tries to do all three and fails at all three is the failure mode. The one who tells the VP early which one will slip, and by how much, is managing the situation. Prioritizing is expected; telling people before it becomes a surprise is the part most candidates leave out.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why do you want to do this job when you know the hours are brutal?",a:"Be honest rather than heroic. The credible answer is that the hours are the price of the exposure, that you want to see how these decisions get made at a stage of your career when you can afford the intensity, and that you have done demanding things before and know how you handle them.\n\nThe point: do not say you love working hard or that you thrive under pressure. Everyone says it and nobody believes it. What is convincing is a specific prior experience where you were genuinely stretched, what you learned about your own limits, and why you want this anyway with your eyes open.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What would your last manager say is your biggest area for improvement?",a:"Name something real, specific, and fixable, with evidence you are working on it. The framing matters: it should be a genuine limitation, not a strength in disguise.\n\nThe point: this is the weakness question with a witness attached, which makes it harder to dodge. Saying your manager thought you were too detail-oriented is a non-answer and they know it. A candidate who says their manager pushed them to delegate earlier, describes the project where that cost them, and explains what changed is demonstrating exactly the self-awareness the question is testing.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"How do you deal with getting a piece of work back covered in comments?",a:"Treat it as information, not judgment. The honest answer is that it stings the first few times and you get over it, because the comments are how you learn what good looks like here.\n\nPractically: read them all before starting, ask about the ones you do not understand rather than guessing, and try not to make the same one twice.\n\nThe point: that last part is what they are actually testing. Everyone gets marked up. The analyst who needs the same comment three times is the problem, and the one who keeps a running list of their own recurring errors is the one who improves fast.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Tell me about a time you had to learn something difficult quickly.",a:"Pick something with a deadline and a consequence. Structure: what you had to learn, why the timeline was tight, how you approached it, and how you knew you had actually learned it rather than just read about it.\n\nThe point: the method is the answer. Banking will require you to become passably conversant in an industry you have never thought about, in a weekend, before a client meeting. They want to see that you have a process for it: find the primary sources, talk to someone who knows, build something with it, and identify what you still do not know. The last part is what separates competence from confidence.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What do you do when you disagree with the valuation your team is presenting?",a:"Raise it internally, with evidence, before it goes out. Say which assumption you think is wrong, what the alternative shows, and what it does to the answer.\n\nThen accept the decision and deliver it well.\n\nThe point: the line to draw is between a judgment call and an error. If it is a judgment call about growth rates, flag it and move on, since reasonable people differ and the MD has context you do not. If it is an actual mistake, a broken formula or an unsupportable assumption, keep escalating until someone engages, because that is not a disagreement, it is a defect.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"An MD asks you for something at 7pm that you know will take until 4am. What do you say?",a:"Say yes, and then say when. Confirm what they actually need, ask whether the whole thing is required or whether a subset answers the question, and tell them realistically when it will be ready.\n\nThe point: the mistake is silent heroism. An analyst who says nothing, works until 4am, and delivers something rushed has served nobody. Most MDs, asked whether they need all forty pages or the three that matter, will take the three. The information they cannot act on is the information you never gave them, and finding out at 4am that half the work was unnecessary is the worst outcome for everyone.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"How would you explain a DCF to someone with no finance background?",a:"Money later is worth less than money now, because you could invest today's money and because tomorrow is uncertain. So to value a business you estimate the cash it will produce in future years, then shrink each year's figure to reflect how far away and how risky it is.\n\nAdd those up and that is what the business is worth today.\n\nThe point: this question tests whether you understand it or memorized it. Anyone can recite unlevered free cash flow discounted at WACC. Explaining it without jargon requires actually holding the idea, and it is exactly what you will need to do when a client asks.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A client asks why your valuation is lower than what they think the company is worth. How do you handle it?",a:"Do not defend the number, walk them through the assumptions. Show which inputs drive the answer, growth, margins, and the discount rate, and ask which one they see differently.\n\nThen show what their view is worth. If they think growth is 12% rather than 7%, put that in and show the result.\n\nThe point: this converts an argument into a conversation about a specific assumption, which is a conversation you can have. Arguing about the output is unwinnable, since they have a number in their head and you have one in a model. Arguing about a growth rate is at least a discussion about something checkable.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What separates an analyst who gets a return offer from one who does not?",a:"Reliability, mostly, and it is less about talent than people expect. Work that comes back correct. Numbers that tie. Files someone else can open. Deadlines that hold. Not needing the same comment twice.\n\nAfter that, being pleasant to be around at 2am.\n\nThe point: almost nobody loses an offer for being bad at modelling, since that is teachable and everyone starts poor at it. They lose it for being careless, for hiding mistakes, or for being difficult. The bar is trust: can this person be given something and will it come back done. Everything else is secondary.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Why should we take you over a candidate who has already done an IB internship?",a:"Do not argue you know more, because you do not. Argue about what actually breaks in the seat: reliability under pressure, precision, and picking things up fast.\n\nPoint at evidence. Something you built and shipped, something you ran with real consequences, a time you caught an error nobody else did.\n\nThe point: the honest framing is that the technical gap closes in weeks and they know it. What does not close is judgment and work ethic. The strongest version names something specific you have done where the stakes were real, since that is evidence, whereas claiming you are a fast learner is not.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"What is the most interesting deal you have followed and why?",a:"Pick one you can actually discuss and have a view on. Not the largest or the most famous, one where you understand the logic and can say what was interesting about the structure, the price, or the strategic rationale.\n\nHave an opinion on whether it was a good deal.\n\nThe point: the failure is naming a huge deal and reciting the headline. The follow-up is always why, and a candidate who cannot say what the buyer was actually paying for, or whether the premium made sense, has revealed they read a news alert. One well-understood mid-cap deal beats a famous one you cannot discuss.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"A company sells a factory for $200 and immediately leases it back for $18 a year. Was that smart?",a:"Depends what it does with the $200. It has raised cash at an implied 9% cost, since $18 on $200 is 9%. If it can borrow at 6%, this was expensive money.\n\nIt also swapped an owned asset for a contractual obligation that now sits on the balance sheet as a lease liability, so the leverage did not disappear, it changed name.\n\nThe point: sale-leasebacks are often a financing decision dressed as a real estate decision. The test is the implied rate against alternatives. Companies reach for them when cheaper financing is unavailable, which is exactly why they can signal distress.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has $1B of goodwill and $1.2B of total assets. What does that tell you?",a:"That 83% of the balance sheet is an accounting residual from past acquisitions. There is almost nothing real here: $200M of tangible assets supporting the whole business.\n\nGoodwill cannot be sold, borrowed against, or used to produce anything. In a liquidation it is worth zero.\n\nThe point: this is a company built entirely by buying other companies. Ask whether those deals worked, whether goodwill has been impaired before, and what the tangible book value is. Lenders will look straight past the $1B, which is why heavily acquisitive companies often have less borrowing capacity than their asset base suggests.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's operating cash flow jumped 40% but revenue was flat. What happened?",a:"Working capital, almost certainly, and it is probably one-time. The candidates: payables stretched, so the company is holding cash it owes. Receivables collected hard at period end. Inventory run down. Or receivables sold through factoring, converting future collections into cash today.\n\nThe point: none of these repeat. Working capital improvements are a one-time release, not a new run rate, because you cannot stretch payables forever or collect the same receivable twice. A jump in operating cash flow with flat revenue should be traced line by line, since the flattering version and the desperate version look identical.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company capitalizes its sales commissions instead of expensing them. What is the effect?",a:"Earnings rise now and the cost reappears later. The commission still gets paid in cash, but instead of hitting the income statement at signing, it becomes an asset amortized over the customer's expected life.\n\nCash is unchanged, though classification may shift.\n\nThe point: there is a legitimate argument here, since the commission bought a multi-year contract, so matching says spread it. There is also an obvious incentive. Watch the amortization period. A company stretching it from two years to five improves earnings with no operational change, and the reversal is mechanical and certain.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company reports adjusted EBITDA of $60M, GAAP net loss of $40M, and stock compensation of $50M. What do you make of it?",a:"That the entire adjusted profit is stock compensation. Strip out the $50M of SBC and the adjusted figure collapses to roughly $10M.\n\nThe company is telling you it is profitable because it pays its people in shares rather than money.\n\nThe point: SBC is genuinely non-cash and the dilution is genuinely real. Cash did not leave, and shareholders paid through a rising share count. When SBC is that large relative to adjusted EBITDA, the adjusted number is not measuring the business, it is measuring an accounting choice about how to compensate people.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"Why is a 10% decline in revenue worse for an airline than for a software company?",a:"Operating leverage. An airline's costs are overwhelmingly fixed in the short run: the plane flies, the crew is paid, the gate is leased, whether the seats are full or not. Revenue falls 10% and almost none of the cost follows, so profit can be eliminated entirely.\n\nSoftware has high gross margins but its costs are more discretionary, so it can cut sales and marketing.\n\nThe point: high operating leverage means small revenue changes produce enormous profit swings in both directions. Combine it with high financial leverage, which airlines also carry, and you get the industry's famous record of bankruptcies.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has a $400M market cap and $1.5B of debt. Whose company is it really?",a:"The lenders'. The capital structure is 79% debt, so the equity is a thin slice of option value sitting underneath a very large obligation.\n\nEnterprise value is roughly $1.9B, and the shareholders own about 21% of it. A 25% decline in enterprise value wipes out the equity entirely.\n\nThe point: at this leverage the equity trades more like a call option on recovery than like ownership. That is why distressed equity can double or go to zero on modest business news, and why in a restructuring the lenders, not the shareholders, decide what happens.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company beats on revenue, misses on margin, and the stock rises. What does that tell you?",a:"That the market cares more about growth than near-term profitability for this company, which usually means it is early in its life and expected to expand margins later.\n\nThe reading: revenue proves demand, which is the harder thing. Margin can be fixed with pricing and scale once the customer base exists; demand cannot be manufactured.\n\nThe point: the same result at a mature company would sink the stock, because there the margin is the story and revenue growth is assumed. The market's reaction tells you which variable it thinks is doing the work, and that changes as a company matures.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"You are given two years of financials and nothing else. What do you calculate first?",a:"The bridge from net income to operating cash flow, then to free cash flow. That single walk tells you whether the earnings are real, where the cash is going, and how capital intensive the business is.\n\nThen growth and margins, so you know direction. Then leverage and coverage, so you know survivability.\n\nThe point: starting with the income statement is the instinct and it is the wrong one. The income statement is where the estimates live. Starting at cash and working backwards to earnings shows you the gaps, and the gaps are where anything interesting is hiding.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's effective tax rate jumps from 15% to 26%. What happened?",a:"A shield ran out or the mix changed. The likely causes: net operating losses were fully used, so the company is now paying full freight. Income shifted from a low-tax jurisdiction to a higher one. A tax credit expired. Or a one-time item flattered the prior year.\n\nThe point: this matters more than it looks, because it hits cash directly with no operating cause. Eleven points of tax on a company earning $500M pre-tax is $55M of cash a year, gone. It also means every historical earnings figure was flattered by a shield that no longer exists, so the growth rate off that base is misleading.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A sponsor is choosing between a 6x-levered deal at a 12% return and a 3x-levered deal at a 10% return. What else matters?",a:"The downside, which the returns do not show. At 6x, the equity is thin and a modest EBITDA miss can wipe it out. At 3x, the same miss is absorbed and you still own the company.\n\nAsk what happens at minus 20% EBITDA in both cases: does coverage hold, does a covenant trip, is more equity needed.\n\nThe point: comparing expected returns without comparing loss scenarios is how funds blow up. The 12% is not two points better, it is a different risk. Sponsors size the downside first because leverage makes the distribution asymmetric, and a wipeout cannot be averaged away across a portfolio.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is the fastest way to sanity check whether an LBO model is realistic?",a:"Check three things against reality. Does the exit multiple exceed the entry multiple, since underwriting expansion is a bet on the market. Does EBITDA growth require the company to outperform every peer. And does the debt paydown assume cash conversion the business has never achieved.\n\nThe point: models produce whatever return the assumptions demand, and the returns are usually solved for backwards from the hurdle. The tell is when every assumption is individually plausible and collectively requires the company to be the best operator in its industry for five straight years. Check the assumptions jointly, not one at a time.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's largest customer is 35% of revenue. How does that change your valuation?",a:"It lowers the multiple, and it may change the whole analysis. That customer can renegotiate price at will, and losing them removes a third of revenue and probably all the profit, since the fixed costs stay.\n\nIt also caps leverage. Lenders will not fund normal debt against revenue that can vanish with one phone call.\n\nThe point: concentration is a risk that does not show up in any historical financial. The numbers look fine right up until they do not. That is why diligence obsesses over contract length, renewal history, and whether the relationship sits with the company or with one salesperson.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do bankers show a 52-week trading range on a football field?",a:"Because it is the one number nobody can argue with. Every other bar on the chart is built from assumptions: your DCF, your comps set, your precedents. The trading range is what actual buyers and sellers paid in actual transactions.\n\nIt anchors the discussion in observable fact.\n\nThe point: it also frames the premium. If the board is being offered $50 and the stock traded between $30 and $45 all year, the offer looks generous. If it traded to $70 six months ago, the same $50 looks opportunistic, and that context is precisely why the range is on the page.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company announces it is exploring strategic alternatives. What does that phrase mean?",a:"That it is for sale, or trying to find out if anyone wants it. The language is deliberately vague because the board has to disclose that a process exists without committing to an outcome.\n\nIn practice it can also mean a spin-off, a recapitalization, or nothing at all.\n\nThe point: the phrase is a signal to buyers as much as to shareholders. It usually follows activist pressure, a failed strategy, or an unsolicited approach the board has to take seriously. The risk is that saying it publicly and then failing to sell damages the asset, because customers and employees now know the company was shopped.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do you tax-effect EBIT in a DCF rather than using actual taxes paid?",a:"Because unlevered free cash flow has to be independent of financing. Actual taxes paid are reduced by the interest deduction, so they reflect the company's debt load. If you used them, the financing benefit would be inside the cash flows and inside WACC at the same time.\n\nSo you compute tax on EBIT as if the company had no debt.\n\nThe point: this is the discipline that keeps a DCF coherent. The tax shield belongs in WACC, through the after-tax cost of debt. Putting it in both places double counts it and inflates the value, which is one of the more common errors in a first-draft model.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why is the tax shield captured in WACC rather than in the cash flows?",a:"Because that is the convention that keeps the unlevered cash flows clean. WACC uses the after-tax cost of debt, meaning the rate times one minus the tax rate, so the deductibility of interest lowers the discount rate rather than raising the cash flows.\n\nThe point: there is an alternative called adjusted present value, which values the unlevered business and adds the tax shield separately as its own stream. It is arguably more honest, since it shows exactly how much value comes from leverage rather than operations. Banks use WACC anyway because it is simpler and everyone reads it the same way.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"What is adjusted present value and when is it better than WACC?",a:"You value the business as if it had no debt, discounting unlevered cash flows at the unlevered cost of equity, then add the present value of the tax shield separately.\n\nIt is better when the capital structure is changing, which WACC handles badly. WACC assumes a constant debt-to-equity ratio forever.\n\nThe point: that assumption breaks precisely in an LBO, where leverage starts at 6x and falls to 2x over five years. A single WACC cannot describe that. APV handles it naturally by valuing the shield year by year, which is why academics prefer it and why bankers still use WACC anyway.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company has a beta of 1.6 and debt-to-equity of 1.0. What is its unlevered beta at a 25% tax rate?",a:"About 0.91. Unlevered beta is levered beta divided by one plus one minus the tax rate times debt-to-equity, so 1.6 divided by 1 plus 0.75 times 1. That is 1.6 over 1.75, which is 0.91.\n\nThe point: the 1.6 you observe in the market is a blend of business risk and borrowing. Stripping the leverage out reveals underlying business risk of 0.91, slightly below the market. This is why you unlever every comp before averaging and then relever at your target's capital structure. Averaging raw observed betas mixes together companies with completely different debt loads and calls the result comparable, which it is not.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do you relever beta at the target's capital structure rather than the peer average?",a:"Because you are valuing your company, not the average of its peers. The peers' betas reflect their debt loads. Once you strip those out, you have clean business risk. Then you add back the leverage your company actually carries.\n\nThe point: using the peer average capital structure is a defensible alternative if you believe the company will migrate toward industry norms, which is often true over time. What is never defensible is skipping the unlever-relever step entirely and averaging observed betas, because that silently assumes your company has the same debt as its peers when the whole point of the exercise is that it does not.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company's equity risk premium assumption moves from 5% to 6%. What happens to the DCF?",a:"The value falls, and by more than people expect. With a beta of 1.2, cost of equity rises 1.2 points. If equity is 70% of the capital structure, WACC rises about 0.84 points.\n\nOn a business where terminal value is most of the answer, that is a large move, since the perpetuity divides by WACC minus growth.\n\nThe point: at a 9% WACC and 3% growth, the denominator is 6%. Push WACC to 9.84% and the denominator becomes 6.84%, so the terminal value falls about 12% from a one point change in an assumption nobody can observe. That fragility is the honest weakness of a DCF.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why can't you observe the equity risk premium directly?",a:"Because it is a forward-looking expectation and only the past is measurable. What people do is take a long historical average of equity returns over bonds and assume the future resembles it.\n\nThat assumption is doing enormous work.\n\nThe point: the range of defensible estimates is roughly 4% to 7%, and that spread alone moves a DCF by 20% or more. It is why the discount rate is where valuations get argued, and why a banker can defend almost any answer by moving inputs nobody can falsify. That is the strongest argument for a reverse DCF, which asks what the market is assuming rather than what you assume.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A DCF and a comps analysis disagree by 40%. What do you do?",a:"Find out why before presenting either. The likely causes: your terminal assumptions imply an exit multiple the market has never paid, your growth or margin projections are more optimistic than what peers are delivering, or the comps set contains companies that are not really comparable.\n\nThe point: the reconciliation is the analysis. Compute the exit multiple your DCF implies and put it next to the comps. If your DCF implies 15x and peers trade at 9x, you are assuming this company deserves a 67% premium to its industry, and you should be able to say why. A 40% gap is not a range, it is an error somewhere.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do bankers present a football field rather than a single number?",a:"Because every method produces a range and pretending otherwise is false precision. The football field shows DCF, comps, precedents, LBO, and the 52-week range side by side, so the board can see where the methods overlap.\n\nThe point: the overlap is the useful part. If four independent methods cluster between $40 and $50, that band is meaningful. If they scatter from $20 to $80, the honest conclusion is that the value depends entirely on which future you believe, and that is worth saying out loud. A single number invites an argument about whether it is right; a range invites a discussion about which assumption drives it.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What does it mean when precedent transactions are far above current comps?",a:"That the deals were done in a different market, or that control is worth a lot in this industry. Precedents reflect what buyers paid at a moment in time, including a control premium and expected synergies. Comps reflect what passive investors pay today.\n\nThe point: check the dates. If the precedents are from a period of cheap credit and the current market has repriced, they are historical artifacts rather than evidence. That is exactly why bankers present both and why sellers quote precedents while buyers quote comps. The gap between them is usually a disagreement about whether the last cycle is coming back.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company is being valued for a fairness opinion. Why does the banker care about the process, not just the number?",a:"Because the opinion is legal cover for the board, and courts examine how the board reached its decision more than the price itself. A defensible process, meaning a real market check, an independent committee, and no conflicts, protects directors even if the price is later criticized.\n\nThe point: this is why boards run go-shops, hire second banks, and document everything. The duty is to be informed and to act in good faith, not to achieve the highest conceivable price. A good price from a rushed, conflicted process is more legally exposed than a fair price from a rigorous one.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do minority stakes trade at a discount to control stakes?",a:"Because control is worth paying for. A controlling owner sets strategy, hires and fires management, decides distributions, and can sell the whole company. A minority holder has none of that and can be trapped in decisions they oppose.\n\nThe point: the discount is largest when the controlling holder can extract value at the minority's expense, through related-party transactions, excess compensation, or refusing to pay dividends. That is why governance matters so much for minority stakes and why dual-class share structures trade at persistent discounts. You are not buying a smaller share of the same thing, you are buying a different thing.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has dual-class shares where founders hold 10% of economics and 60% of votes. How does that affect valuation?",a:"It usually warrants a discount. Public shareholders bear 90% of the economic risk and have almost no ability to change anything. They cannot replace the board, cannot force a sale, and cannot pressure management.\n\nThe point: the argument in favour is that it insulates founders from short-term pressure, which can be genuinely valuable for a long-horizon business. The argument against is that it removes the only mechanism shareholders have when management is wrong. Both are true, which is why the discount varies with the track record. The market pays for founder control when the founder has earned it and discounts it when they have not.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why does a company with a large controlling shareholder rarely receive a hostile bid?",a:"Because the arithmetic does not work. A hostile bid goes around the board directly to shareholders, and if one holder controls a majority of votes, there is no path. You cannot win a proxy fight or a tender offer against someone who can simply refuse.\n\nThe point: this is why control blocks are the strongest takeover defense there is, stronger than any poison pill. It also means the stock carries a structural discount, since the possibility of a takeover premium is permanently removed. Part of what any minority shareholder pays for is the option that someone might buy the whole company, and that option does not exist here.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company's founder wants to sell but keep running it. What structure fits?",a:"A sponsor deal with a meaningful management rollover. The founder sells most of the business for cash, rolls a portion of the proceeds into the new equity, and stays as CEO with a board that includes the sponsor.\n\nA strategic would typically not work, since it usually has its own management.\n\nThe point: the rollover is what makes it viable for both sides. The founder gets liquidity now and a second bite at the exit; the sponsor gets the person who knows the business and an aligned incentive. It also answers a diligence question directly, because a founder refusing to roll anything tells the buyer something worth knowing.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's EBITDA margin is 30% and its free cash flow margin is 5%. Where did 25 points go?",a:"Into capex, working capital, interest, and cash taxes, in some combination. Walk it down.\n\nOn $100 of revenue: $30 of EBITDA. Interest and cash taxes might take $10. Working capital growth might take $5. That leaves capex absorbing the other $10.\n\nThe point: the specific split matters enormously. If capex is the culprit and it is growth capex, the company could stop and harvest cash. If it is maintenance capex, the 5% is the real economics of the business and the 30% EBITDA margin is a fiction. Always ask what capex would be if the company simply stopped growing.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has $600M of debt at 7% and refinances at 5%. What is that worth?",a:"$12M a year pre-tax, or $9M after tax at a 25% rate. That flows straight to net income with nothing about the business changing.\n\nCapitalized at, say, 15x earnings, it is roughly $135M of equity value created by a phone call.\n\nThe point: this is why treasurers matter more than people think. No product improved, no customer was won, and shareholders are meaningfully better off because less of the same operating profit now goes to lenders. It also shows why refinancing windows matter, since the same trade is unavailable when credit markets close.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do you subtract preferred stock when bridging from enterprise value to equity value?",a:"Because preferred ranks ahead of common. It is a claim on the business that must be satisfied before common shareholders receive anything, so it behaves like debt in the bridge even though it sits in the equity section of the balance sheet.\n\nThe point: the balance sheet classification misleads people here. Preferred is legally equity and economically closer to debt: a fixed payment, priority over common, and usually no upside. Treat it the way the cash flows behave, not the way the accountants filed it. The same logic drives subtracting noncontrolling interest.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company reports EBITDA of $200M and interest of $90M. Should you worry?",a:"Coverage is 2.2x, which is thin. More importantly, nearly half of operating profit goes to lenders before a dollar of capex or tax.\n\nStress it: a 25% EBITDA decline takes EBITDA to $150M and coverage to 1.7x, which is close to typical covenant floors.\n\nThe point: 2.2x is survivable for a business with contracted revenue and dangerous for a cyclical. The real question is what remains after capex. If the company also spends $60M on capex, then $200M of EBITDA less $90M of interest less $60M of capex leaves $50M before tax, and there is almost no margin for error.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's stock trades at 3x book value. What does that tell you?",a:"That the market thinks the assets are worth three times what the accountants recorded, or that most of the value is in things the balance sheet never captured: brand, people, customer relationships, intellectual property built rather than bought.\n\nThe point: book value is historical cost, so it systematically understates a healthy business. That is exactly why price to book is useless for most operating companies and meaningful for banks, where assets are financial and marked closer to fair value. A 3x book for a software company says nothing. A 3x book for a bank says the market expects returns well above its cost of equity.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why is a bank's price to book almost a direct function of its ROE?",a:"Because a bank's assets are financial, so book value approximates what the equity is really worth. If the bank earns exactly its cost of equity, the equity is worth book, so it trades at 1x.\n\nEarn above the cost of equity and it trades above book; earn below and it trades below.\n\nThe point: this relationship explains most of bank valuation in one sentence. A bank at 10% ROE with a 10% cost of equity is worth 1x book, no matter how well managed. One at 15% ROE against a 10% cost is worth meaningfully more. It is why bank analysts obsess over ROE and net interest margin rather than EBITDA.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's revenue is growing 20% but its deferred revenue is flat. What does that mean for a subscription business?",a:"That it is recognizing revenue from contracts sold earlier and not replacing them. Deferred revenue is the backlog of paid-for future service, so a flat balance against 20% revenue growth means bookings are decelerating hard.\n\nThe point: revenue is the lagging indicator here and deferred revenue is the leading one. The income statement is showing you sales made a year ago. The company will report good growth for another few quarters and then fall off a cliff, and this is visible now on the balance sheet. Check billings, meaning revenue plus the change in deferred revenue, since that is what actually got sold.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company buys back stock when its P/E is 40x. Good or bad use of capital?",a:"Almost certainly bad. At 40x, the earnings yield is 2.5%, so the company is earning a 2.5% return on the cash it just spent. Unless it genuinely believes the stock is worth well above 40x, it is destroying value.\n\nThe point: a buyback is an investment decision, and the hurdle is the same as any other. Buying your own stock at 40x is only defensible if intrinsic value is higher still. The EPS will rise regardless, which is the trap. Management gets rewarded for the accretion and shareholders bear the overpayment, which is why buyback timing correlates so poorly with value.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has $50M of cash, burns $5M a quarter, and has no access to capital. How long does it have?",a:"About 10 quarters, so two and a half years of runway on a straight burn. But that is the optimistic read.\n\nThe burn usually accelerates as trouble compounds. Suppliers tighten terms, which consumes working capital. Customers hesitate. And the company must act well before zero, since nobody can operate at $0 of cash.\n\nThe point: practical runway is shorter than arithmetic runway. The company needs to raise or sell with maybe a year of cash left, because doing it at three months means negotiating from a position where everyone knows you have no choice.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do distressed companies often sell their best assets first?",a:"Because those are the ones anyone will buy, and quickly. In a liquidity crisis you need cash on a deadline, and the crown jewel has a ready buyer at a fair price while the struggling division does not.\n\nThe point: this is the tragedy of distressed asset sales and why creditors resist them. Selling the good business to service debt leaves a weaker company carrying the same obligations, so it buys time and worsens the underlying position. Credit agreements restrict asset sales specifically to stop this, usually requiring proceeds to repay debt rather than fund losses.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company has a 90% gross margin and is unprofitable. How?",a:"Operating expenses, which sit below gross profit. At 90% gross margin, the cost of serving a customer is trivial, so the losses come from sales and marketing, R&D, and overhead.\n\nThis is the standard software profile: it costs almost nothing to serve the next customer and a fortune to acquire them.\n\nThe point: the question is whether those costs are investment or structural. If sales and marketing is 60% of revenue because the company is growing 50%, it could be profitable tomorrow by stopping. If it is 60% because customers churn and must constantly be replaced, the losses are permanent and the gross margin is irrelevant.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why can a company with 90% gross margins still be a bad business?",a:"Because gross margin says nothing about customer acquisition cost, retention, or capital intensity elsewhere. A business that spends $3 to acquire a customer who pays $1 and leaves after a year has wonderful unit economics on paper and destroys money in practice.\n\nThe point: high gross margin means the product is cheap to deliver, not that the business works. The full test runs further down: what does a customer cost, how long do they stay, what do they spend over that life, and how long is payback. Gross margin is the ceiling on the business model, not evidence of one.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A sponsor exits by selling to another sponsor. What does that tell you?",a:"That there was no strategic buyer willing to pay more, which is worth thinking about. Strategics normally pay the highest price because they have synergies. A sponsor-to-sponsor deal means either no strategic wanted it or none would clear the price.\n\nThe point: it can be benign. The business may be too small to matter to a strategic, or in a fragmented industry with no obvious acquirer, or the second sponsor may see an operational angle the first did not pursue. But the pattern is worth noticing. It also means the next buyer must find returns the first one left behind, which gets harder each time the asset changes hands.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What does it mean when a company's auditor issues a going concern qualification?",a:"That the auditor has substantial doubt the company can survive twelve months. It is not a prediction of failure, it is a statement that the auditor could not satisfy itself otherwise.\n\nIt is usually triggered by a maturity the company cannot obviously meet, recurring losses, or covenant breaches.\n\nThe point: it is often self-fulfilling. The qualification makes lenders nervous, may itself trip covenants that require clean audits, and makes refinancing harder precisely when refinancing is the thing that would fix it. That reflexivity is why companies fight so hard to avoid one.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company's tangible book value is negative but it is profitable and growing. Is that a problem?",a:"Usually not. Negative tangible book normally means either past acquisitions filled the balance sheet with goodwill, or the company has bought back stock or paid debt-funded dividends.\n\nPlenty of excellent businesses show it. A software company's real assets are its code and its people, neither of which the balance sheet records.\n\nThe point: it matters for lenders, since there is little to secure against, and it matters in a downturn, since there is no equity cushion. But for a profitable, growing business with reliable cash flow, book value is measuring the wrong thing entirely. Cash flow services debt, not book equity.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's segment reporting shows one division losing money. What do you do with it?",a:"Value it separately, because the market may not be. Sum-of-the-parts: value the profitable division on its own multiple, value the loss-making one on assets or on a turnaround case, and add them.\n\nThe point: the losing division may be worth more to someone else, or worth more shut down. If the good business would trade at 12x standalone and the group trades at 8x because the loser drags the blended number, there is a conglomerate discount and an obvious activist case. Ask what the group would be worth if the losing division simply did not exist, because that number is often higher than the whole.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do sum-of-the-parts valuations often exceed market value?",a:"Because investors cannot buy the piece they want, capital gets allocated internally by managers rather than by the market, and segment disclosure is usually too thin to trust.\n\nThe point: the honest caveat is that a sum-of-the-parts is not free money. Separating the divisions costs something: stranded overhead, lost tax efficiency, dis-synergies, and transaction fees. A group trading 15% below its parts may be correctly priced once you subtract those. The discount only matters if it is larger than the cost of closing it, which is exactly the argument a management team makes when resisting a spin.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What are stranded costs and why do they kill carve-out math?",a:"The overhead that stays with the parent after a division is sold. The division was absorbing a share of corporate IT, finance, HR, and insurance. Sell it and that cost does not leave, it just has a smaller business to sit on.\n\nThe point: this is the most underestimated number in any carve-out. A parent selling a division reporting $50M of profit may find its own profit falls by more than $50M, because the division was covering overhead the parent still has. That is why transition service agreements exist, and why buyers and sellers fight over standalone cost estimates that nobody can prove.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why is a transition services agreement necessary in a carve-out?",a:"Because the business being sold cannot function alone on day one. It ran on the parent's systems, payroll, and contracts. A TSA has the parent keep providing those for a period, usually six to twenty-four months, for a fee.\n\nThe point: the risk is that the TSA becomes permanent. Standing up independent systems is expensive and slow, and buyers routinely underestimate it. Meanwhile the seller has no incentive to provide good service to a business it no longer owns. That misalignment is why TSA terms and exit rights get negotiated as hard as the price in a complex carve-out.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company says it will realize $100M of synergies. How do you test that?",a:"Split them and treat them differently. Cost synergies are countable: which roles, which facilities, which contracts, and by when. Ask for the headcount number. Revenue synergies are a forecast and usually do not arrive.\n\nThen ask what it costs to achieve them, since restructuring charges frequently consume a year or two of the benefit.\n\nThe point: the useful question is not whether $100M is achievable but who else could achieve it. If any buyer could capture those synergies, competitive bidding hands the value to the seller. Synergies only create value for the buyer if the buyer is uniquely able to realize them.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do cost synergies get believed and revenue synergies get discounted?",a:"Because cost synergies are under the buyer's control and revenue synergies depend on customers. You can decide to close a facility. You cannot decide that a customer will buy your other product.\n\nThe point: the empirical record is stark. Cost synergies usually land close to plan, sometimes better. Revenue synergies land far below, because the assumptions behind them, cross-selling and channel access, run into sales forces that resist, customers who resent the consolidation, and integration that takes attention away from selling. That is why bankers model revenue synergies and buyers rarely pay for them.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A merger promises $200M of synergies and $150M of one-time integration costs. How do you think about that?",a:"Net it and discount it properly. The synergies are recurring and the cost is one-time, so the value is the present value of $200M a year less $150M once. At a 10x multiple, the synergies are worth $2B against $150M of cost, which is clearly worth doing if they are real.\n\nThe point: the arithmetic almost always looks compelling, which is exactly why it deserves suspicion. The failure mode is not the math, it is that the synergies arrive at 60% of plan two years late while the integration costs arrive in full and on time. Model the timing, not just the totals.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do most acquisitions destroy value for the acquirer?",a:"Because the premium usually exceeds the synergies. The buyer pays 30% above market for a company the market already priced, so it must create more value than that premium just to break even.\n\nAdd competitive bidding, which pushes the price toward the buyer's maximum, and management incentives that reward size over returns.\n\nThe point: the mechanism is the winner's curse. In an auction, the winner is usually the bidder who most overestimated the value, and M&A adds a control premium and synergies forecast by the people who want the deal. The discipline against it is a walk-away price set before the process, which is rare once a CEO has decided they want the asset.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What would make you tell a client not to do a deal they want?",a:"When the price exceeds what the target is worth to them, and you can show it. Specifically: when the premium is larger than the credible synergies, when the acquirer's own stock is the currency and it is undervalued, when the leverage puts the credit rating at risk, or when the integration risk is larger than anyone is admitting.\n\nThe point: you say it once, clearly, with the analysis. Then it is their decision. The job is to make sure they are choosing with the numbers in front of them rather than to win the argument, and a banker who has never advised against a deal is not advising, they are selling.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company is buying a competitor to stop a rival from buying it. Is that a good reason?",a:"It can be, and it is dangerous. Defensive acquisitions have a real logic: the strategic cost of a competitor gaining scale or locking up a channel can exceed the price of preventing it.\n\nBut it detaches the decision from valuation. The question stops being what is this worth and becomes what would it cost us if they had it.\n\nThe point: that framing has no ceiling, which is exactly the problem. It is how buyers talk themselves into any price. The disciplined version quantifies the defensive value explicitly, treats it as a synergy, and still sets a walk-away price. The undisciplined version calls it strategic and stops thinking.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the difference between a merger of equals and an acquisition?",a:"Mostly the framing. In a merger of equals the ownership split is near even and the language is partnership. In an acquisition someone is clearly buying.\n\nBut control is settled by everything except the split: who is CEO, who chairs the board, whose systems survive, whose headquarters stays.\n\nThe point: mergers of equals are usually acquisitions with better manners, and the framing exists to help the smaller side's board sell it. They also have a poor record, because two management teams with equal claims and no single decider makes every integration decision a negotiation. Within two years the reporting lines usually reveal who actually bought whom.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why does integration usually take longer than planned?",a:"Because the plan is built by deal teams and executed by operators who were not in the room. Systems do not talk to each other, cultures differ, key people leave, and customers use the disruption to renegotiate.\n\nMeanwhile the business still has to run.\n\nThe point: the underestimated cost is attention. The management team spends a year integrating instead of competing, and competitors know it. That is why the period right after a large acquisition is when rivals attack, and why the revenue synergies fail at exactly the moment the organization is least able to pursue them.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A buyer discovers a material problem three days before closing. What are the options?",a:"Four, roughly. Close anyway and accept it. Renegotiate the price, which is the usual outcome. Delay to investigate, if the agreement allows. Or walk, which usually means invoking a MAC clause.\n\nThe point: the MAC is almost never the answer, because the bar is deliberately set high and courts have very rarely allowed a buyer to invoke one. So the realistic leverage is a price cut, and how much depends on how badly the seller needs to close and how public the process was. A buyer with cold feet three days out negotiates rather than litigates, because litigation is a fight they will probably lose.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do sellers push for a shorter period between signing and closing?",a:"Because everything that can go wrong for them happens in that window. The business could deteriorate, giving the buyer leverage or an exit. Markets could turn. Employees could leave. A regulator could intervene. Meanwhile they are running the company under interim covenants that restrict what they can do.\n\nThe point: the seller has already made the decision to sell, so the gap is pure risk with no upside. That is why cash deals win against slightly higher stock bids, and why a buyer offering speed and certainty can pay less. The gap is a cost, and the seller is the one paying it.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What is the single most common mistake candidates make in a technical interview?",a:"Answering before understanding the question. Someone hears depreciation increases and starts reciting the three-statement walkthrough without noticing the question specified a different tax rate, or asked only about cash.\n\nThe second most common is not saying the answer first. Candidates build to a conclusion when the interviewer wants the conclusion and then the reasoning.\n\nThe point: both are fixable and neither is about knowledge. Repeat the question, state your answer, then explain. If you need a moment, say so. The interviewer is watching how you handle a question under pressure, and thinking out loud is not a weakness, it is the thing being tested.",category:"Behavioral"},
{q:"Depreciation increases by $30. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Depreciation is an expense, so pre-tax income falls $30. Tax falls $7.50, so net income falls $22.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $22.50. Depreciation is non-cash, so add back the full $30. Cash rises $7.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $7.50 and PP&E is down $30, so assets fall $22.50. Retained earnings fall $22.50, and it balances.\n\nThe point: cash went up because of an expense. The only real event was the tax bill shrinking, since no money left for the depreciation itself. That $7.50 is the depreciation tax shield, and it is why depreciation is worth having.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company writes down inventory by $40. Tax rate is 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The write-down hits COGS or a separate charge, so pre-tax income falls $40. Tax falls $10, leaving net income down $30.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $30. The write-down is non-cash, so add back $40. Cash rises $10.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $10 and inventory is down $40, so assets fall $30, matching retained earnings.\n\nThe point: the cash actually left when the inventory was purchased. This entry just admits the goods are worth less than paid. The only cash effect is the tax saving, which is why write-downs improve cash flow while destroying earnings.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company issues $200 of debt at 6% and holds it as cash earning 2%. Tax rate 25%. What is the annual effect?",a:"Income statement. Interest expense is $12 and interest income is $4, so net interest expense is $8. Pre-tax income falls $8, tax falls $2, and net income falls $6.\n\nCash flow statement. Net income is down $6, and there is nothing non-cash, so cash falls $6 a year.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash falls $6, retained earnings fall $6.\n\nThe point: borrowing to hold cash costs the spread. Here it is 4 points on $200, or $8 pre-tax and $6 after. Companies do it anyway for optionality, but it is not free, and it is exactly why holding a large cash balance funded by debt drags on return on equity.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company prepays $60 of rent for next year. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The expense has not been incurred yet, since the company has not used the space.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash falls $60, and prepaid expenses rise $60, which is a use of cash in working capital.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is down $60 and prepaid expenses are up $60. Assets are unchanged in total, one asset simply became another.\n\nThe point: this is the mirror image of deferred revenue. There, you take cash and owe a service. Here, you give cash and are owed one. In both cases the cash moves first and the income statement waits, which is exactly what accrual accounting is for.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company grants $50 of stock compensation. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. It is an operating expense, so pre-tax income falls $50. Tax falls $12.50, leaving net income down $37.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $37.50. Stock compensation is non-cash, so add back $50. Cash rises $12.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $12.50 and additional paid-in capital rises $50, while retained earnings fall $37.50, so equity is up $12.50 net.\n\nThe point: cash went up, because the company got a deduction for something it paid in paper. But the share count rose, so existing shareholders own less. The cost is real and it lands on shareholders rather than on the cash balance, which is exactly why adding SBC back to EBITDA is contested.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company collects $90 of receivables. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing. The revenue was already recognized when the sale was made; this is just the customer finally paying.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash rises $90, and receivables fall $90, which is a source of cash in working capital.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $90 and receivables are down $90. Total assets unchanged.\n\nThe point: this is the moment the earlier profit becomes real. The income statement recorded it months ago on the promise; the cash flow statement records it now on the payment. The gap between those two events is exactly where receivables live, and where aggressive revenue recognition hides.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company takes a $70 goodwill impairment. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Pre-tax income falls $70. Goodwill impairment is usually not deductible, so assume no tax benefit and net income falls the full $70.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $70. The impairment is non-cash, so add back $70. Cash is completely unchanged.\n\nBalance sheet. Goodwill falls $70 and retained earnings fall $70.\n\nThe point: this is the purest non-event in accounting. No cash moves, not even tax. It is management conceding, years late, that an acquisition was worth less than they paid. The money left the day the deal closed.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company sells inventory that cost $40 for $70 cash. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Revenue $70, COGS $40, so gross profit is $30. Tax of $7.50 leaves net income up $22.50.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, up $22.50. Inventory falls $40, which is a source of cash. So cash rises $62.50.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $62.50 and inventory is down $40, so assets rise $22.50, matching retained earnings.\n\nThe point: cash rose far more than profit, because the inventory was paid for in an earlier period. The $40 outflow already happened; this period only collects. That timing difference between paying for goods and selling them is the entire reason working capital matters.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's customer pays a $100 deposit for goods to ship in six months. What happens?",a:"Income statement. Nothing. Nothing has been delivered, so nothing has been earned.\n\nCash flow statement. Cash rises $100, offset by a $100 increase in deferred revenue, which is a source of cash in working capital.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $100 and deferred revenue, a liability, is up $100.\n\nThe point: the company has the money and owes the goods. That is why it is a liability despite the cash being real. This is also the mechanic behind negative working capital businesses: collect first, deliver later, and the customers fund your operations for free.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company converts $150 of debt into equity. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing at the moment of conversion, though future interest expense disappears, so subsequent earnings rise.\n\nCash flow statement. Nothing. No cash moves; this is a non-cash financing transaction disclosed separately.\n\nBalance sheet. Debt falls $150 and equity rises $150. Total assets are unchanged.\n\nThe point: the company just got healthier without spending a penny. Leverage fell, interest coverage improved, and the risk of default dropped. Someone paid for it: the existing shareholders, who now own a smaller slice. That is why debt-for-equity swaps are the standard restructuring outcome, since lenders take the company and shareholders get diluted or wiped.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company records $25 of bad debt expense. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Bad debt is an operating expense, so pre-tax income falls $25. Tax falls $6.25, leaving net income down $18.75.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $18.75. The allowance increase is non-cash, so add back $25. Cash rises $6.25.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $6.25, and net receivables fall $25 because the allowance rose. Assets fall $18.75, matching retained earnings.\n\nThe point: the company is admitting some customers will not pay. Cash rises only because of the tax deduction. The actual loss occurred when the sale was made to someone who could not afford it.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company buys $500 of equipment with $200 cash and $300 of debt. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing on day one. Depreciation starts next period.\n\nCash flow statement. Investing shows $500 of capex as an outflow. Financing shows $300 of debt raised as an inflow. Net cash falls $200.\n\nBalance sheet. PP&E is up $500 and cash is down $200, so assets rise $300. Debt rises $300, and it balances.\n\nThe point: the full $500 shows as capex even though only $200 left the bank, because capex measures what was bought, not how it was funded. The financing sits in its own section. That separation is deliberate, since it lets you see investment and funding as distinct decisions.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's warranty provision rises by $35. Tax rate 25%. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. The provision is an expense, so pre-tax income falls $35. Tax falls $8.75, leaving net income down $26.25.\n\nCash flow statement. Start at net income, down $26.25. The provision is non-cash, so add back $35. Cash rises $8.75.\n\nBalance sheet. Cash is up $8.75, the warranty liability is up $35, and retained earnings are down $26.25.\n\nThe point: the company is recognizing a cost it expects to pay later, which is accrual accounting doing its job. The estimate is management's, which cuts both ways: over-provision now and you can release it into earnings later, which is one of the oldest levers there is.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company issues $100 of stock and uses it to repay debt. Walk through the three statements.",a:"Income statement. Nothing today, though future interest expense falls, so subsequent earnings rise.\n\nCash flow statement. Financing shows $100 raised from stock and $100 used to repay debt. Net cash is unchanged.\n\nBalance sheet. Debt falls $100 and equity rises $100. Assets are unchanged.\n\nThe point: the company deleveraged by diluting. Enterprise value is unchanged, since debt fell $100 and equity value rose $100. What changed is who owns the business and how risky it is. This is the classic move by a company that has borrowed too much, and it is why equity raises by levered companies are usually bad news for existing holders.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company capitalizes $60 of software development costs. Tax rate 25%. What happens versus expensing it?",a:"If capitalized. No expense this year, so pre-tax income is $60 higher than under expensing, and net income is $45 higher. On the cash flow statement, the $60 outflow moves from operating into investing, so operating cash flow looks $60 better. Assets rise $60.\n\nIf expensed. Net income is $45 lower now and the cost is gone.\n\nThe point: total cash is identical either way, and the classification changes both reported earnings and operating cash flow. The capitalized version reverses as amortization over the following years. Watch for a company that starts capitalizing what it used to expense, because that is an earnings improvement with a mechanical, certain reversal.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"How many golf balls would fit in a school bus?",a:"Size both, then divide. A bus is roughly 8 feet wide, 6 feet high in the usable cabin, and 30 feet long, so about 1,440 cubic feet. A golf ball is about 1.7 inches across, so roughly 2.5 cubic inches in its bounding box.\n\nThere are 1,728 cubic inches in a cubic foot, so the bus is about 2.5 million cubic inches. Divide by 2.5 and you get about 1 million balls.\n\nThen adjust. Spheres do not pack perfectly, so apply roughly 65% packing efficiency, giving about 650,000. Subtract seats, call it 500,000.\n\nThe point: state the packing adjustment out loud. That is the part that separates a structured answer from a volume calculation.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How much does a Boeing 747 weigh?",a:"Build it from parts rather than guessing. Passengers: about 400 people at 200 pounds with luggage, so 80,000 pounds. Fuel: a long-haul flight burns roughly 150,000 pounds. The airframe itself is the big unknown.\n\nAnchor it. A car is about 4,000 pounds and a 747 is vastly larger, call the empty aircraft 400,000 pounds.\n\nTotal is roughly 630,000 pounds at takeoff. The real maximum takeoff weight is around 900,000, so I am low, and the airframe estimate is the culprit.\n\nThe point: saying which input you are least sure of, and that your answer is probably light because of it, is worth more than the number.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"How many haircuts happen in the US each year?",a:"About 330 million people. Say men get roughly 10 a year and women roughly 4, and split the population evenly.\n\nSo 165 million men at 10 is 1.65 billion, and 165 million women at 4 is 660 million. Total is about 2.3 billion.\n\nSanity check it against supply. At about 600,000 barbers and stylists doing maybe 8 a day, 250 days a year, that is 1.2 billion, so my demand estimate is roughly double what the supply supports.\n\nThe point: checking demand against supply and finding they disagree is the whole exercise. It means one assumption is wrong and I would revise the frequency down.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do interviewers ask you to estimate something with no right answer?",a:"Because the job is full of them. What is this segment worth, what happens to volume if a competitor enters, how big could this be. Nobody can look those up, and a client is waiting.\n\nThey are watching four things: do you decompose the problem, do you state assumptions out loud, is your arithmetic clean, and do you notice when the answer is absurd.\n\nThe point: the worst response is a long silence followed by a number. The best is thinking aloud, naming the assumption you are least sure of, and sanity checking at the end. Being wrong with visible reasoning beats being right with none.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has 200M shares at $30, $800M of net debt, and $120M of EBITDA. What is its leverage and EV/EBITDA?",a:"Market cap is $6,000M, so enterprise value is $6,800M. That is 56.7x EBITDA, and leverage is $800M over $120M, or 6.7x.\n\nThe point: those two numbers do not belong together. A 56.7x EBITDA multiple implies enormous growth expectations, while 6.7x leverage is what you would put on a stable, slow business. Either the market expects EBITDA to multiply, in which case the leverage will look fine in two years, or something is badly mispriced. When the multiple and the leverage tell opposite stories, that contradiction is the thing to investigate.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company earns $250M of EBITDA and trades at $3B EV. It has $1.2B of debt. What is the equity worth and what is the leverage?",a:"Equity value is $1.8B, since $3B less $1.2B of net debt. The multiple is 12x EBITDA and leverage is 4.8x.\n\nThe point: notice the equity is only 60% of enterprise value, so the shareholders own a levered claim. If EBITDA falls 20% to $200M and the multiple holds at 12x, enterprise value drops to $2.4B and the equity falls to $1.2B, a 33% decline from a 20% operating miss. The debt does not shrink with the business, so the equity absorbs the whole move. That asymmetry is what leverage does in both directions.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company generates $90M of free cash flow and has $600M of debt. How long to pay it off?",a:"About 6.7 years using every dollar, which nobody does. Realistically some cash goes to capex beyond maintenance, working capital, and possibly dividends.\n\nThe point: the useful version of this question is the credit agreement's version. If the cash sweep requires 75% of excess cash to repay debt, the real number is roughly 9 years, and if EBITDA grows the free cash flow grows with it, so it accelerates. Lenders care about this figure because it tells them whether the debt amortizes naturally or depends entirely on a refinancing they will have to decide on later.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A sponsor buys at $500M with $150M of equity and sells at $700M with $50M of debt remaining. What is the multiple of money?",a:"4.3x. The exit equity is $700M less $50M of debt, which is $650M, against $150M invested.\n\nThe point: notice where the return came from. Enterprise value only rose $200M, or 40%, while the equity went up 4.3x. Most of that is debt paydown, since the sponsor started with $350M of debt and ended with $50M, converting $300M of borrowing into equity value with no change in the business. That is the leverage engine, and it is why sponsors care so much about cash generation rather than only about growth.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's EBITDA margin is 22% and its peers average 30%. What is the opportunity and what is the catch?",a:"Eight points of margin. On $400M of revenue that is $32M of EBITDA, and at 10x it is $320M of enterprise value.\n\nThe catch is that the gap usually exists for a reason. The company may serve smaller customers, run an older asset base, be subscale, or sell a genuinely different mix. If it were simply mismanagement, someone would likely have fixed it.\n\nThe point: the diligence question is whether the gap is structural or operational. Sponsors underwrite margin convergence constantly and the ones who lose money assumed the gap was laziness when it was actually the business model.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company trades at 9x EBITDA. A sponsor needs a 22% IRR over five years. What does that imply?",a:"Work backwards. A 22% IRR over five years is about 2.7x the money. So the equity must nearly triple.\n\nWith 55% debt, the sponsor writes a 4-turn equity cheque. To get 2.7x on that, the combination of EBITDA growth, debt paydown, and any multiple movement has to produce roughly 11 turns of exit equity.\n\nThe point: this is why LBO valuation is a solve rather than a calculation. You do not value the business and see what return falls out. You fix the required return and solve for the maximum price, which is exactly why a sponsor's bid is a floor rather than an opinion about value.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why does an LBO give you a floor valuation rather than a fair value?",a:"Because a sponsor bids to a required return, not to intrinsic value. It solves for the highest price that still clears its hurdle and stops there.\n\nSo the LBO answer is the minimum a rational strategic must beat.\n\nThe point: it is a floor because financial buyers have no synergies. They are buying standalone cash flow with borrowed money, so whatever they can pay, a strategic with real cost synergies should be able to pay more. If a sponsor is winning an auction against strategics, either the synergies are not there or the strategics are being disciplined, and both are worth understanding before you assume the sponsor overpaid.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why is a company with 40% EBITDA margins and 5% growth worth less than one with 15% margins and 30% growth?",a:"Because a multiple prices the future, not the present. The 15% margin company will be much larger in five years, and margins usually expand with scale, so its future earnings dwarf today's.\n\nAt 30% growth, revenue roughly triples in five years. At 5%, it grows 28%.\n\nThe point: the caveat is that the growth has to be real and the margins have to arrive. A company at 15% margins growing 30% by spending everything on acquisition may never see 40%. The market pays for the trajectory, which is why growth companies collapse so violently when the trajectory changes rather than when the current numbers do.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's revenue triples in five years. What annual growth rate is that?",a:"About 25%. Three to the power of one fifth minus one is 24.6%.\n\nThe point: this is the same arithmetic as an LBO return, since a 3x over five years is a 25% IRR whether it is revenue or equity. Worth having the ladder memorized: doubling in five years is about 15% a year, tripling is 25%, and quadrupling is 32%. It lets you sanity check a growth plan instantly. If a company's five-year plan shows revenue quadrupling, it is claiming 32% compound growth, and you can ask whether anyone in the industry has ever done that.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A model shows revenue growing 30% a year for ten years. What is wrong with that?",a:"The arithmetic gets absurd. Thirty percent for ten years is about 13.8x, so a $500M company becomes a $6.9B one and would have to take enormous share from everyone.\n\nThe point: almost no company sustains 30% for a decade. The ones that do are famous precisely because it is so rare. The test is to compound the assumption out and compare the result against the market size. If your model implies the company ends up with 80% of its industry, the growth rate is the problem, not the market. This is the fastest way to find an unrealistic model, and almost nobody does it.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"Why do most five-year plans show a hockey stick and why should you distrust it?",a:"Because they are built by people who need the answer to look good, and the near years are checkable while the far ones are not. Years one and two are constrained by reality; years four and five are where the growth and margin expansion get placed.\n\nThe point: the tell is that improvement always starts just beyond the forecast horizon anyone will be held to. Check what the company delivered against its last three plans. If it has missed every one in the same shape, the plan is a wish. The useful response is to build your own case off actual historical performance, then ask management to explain the delta rather than debating their number.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company acquires a target using 100% stock. What happens to the buyer's balance sheet?",a:"Equity rises by the value of the shares issued. On the asset side, the target's assets come on at fair value, with any excess over identifiable net assets recorded as goodwill.\n\nNo cash moves, and no debt is added unless the target had some, which the buyer now assumes.\n\nThe point: the balance sheet looks healthier than a cash deal, since leverage does not rise. But the buyer's existing shareholders now own a smaller share of a larger company. Stock deals hide the cost, because dilution never appears as an expense. The price was paid in ownership rather than money, and it is just as real.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why does a buyer's stock usually fall on announcing an acquisition?",a:"Several reasons, and they compound. The market often reads it as overpaying, since the premium is visible and the synergies are a forecast. In a stock deal, arbitrageurs short the buyer to hedge their long in the target, which creates mechanical selling pressure. And issuing stock signals management may think their shares are expensive.\n\nThe point: the pattern is consistent enough that acquirer underperformance is one of the best documented findings in corporate finance. The buyer's shareholders are usually paying for a benefit that accrues to the seller's, which the market prices immediately and the press release does not mention.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A target trades at $40 and the buyer offers $50. The target trades to $47. Why not $50?",a:"Because the deal might not close, and the market is pricing that risk. The $3 gap is the arbitrage spread, and it reflects the probability of failure plus the time value of waiting.\n\nRisks: regulatory rejection, financing falling through, a shareholder vote, or a MAC.\n\nThe point: the spread is a live market forecast of closing probability. A wide spread means the market doubts the deal, and it usually widens the moment a regulator raises questions. Merger arbitrage funds exist to harvest that gap, which means the spread also reflects how much capital is willing to bet on the close.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"What happens to a merger arbitrage position if the deal breaks?",a:"It loses badly, and that is the whole structure of the trade. The arb bought the target at $47 expecting $50, so the upside was $3. If the deal breaks, the target falls back toward its unaffected price of $40 or below, so the loss is $7 or more.\n\nThe point: the payoff is deeply asymmetric. Small gains most of the time, large losses occasionally, which is the same shape as selling insurance. That is why arbs care obsessively about regulatory risk and financing conditions rather than about whether the combination makes strategic sense. They are underwriting closing probability, not the business.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why do stock deals take longer to close than cash deals?",a:"Because issuing shares triggers a registration statement and usually a vote by the buyer's own shareholders, both of which take months. The target's shareholders also need disclosure about what they are receiving, since they are being handed a security rather than money.\n\nCash deals skip most of that.\n\nThe point: the delay is itself a cost. Months of exposure to the business deteriorating, to a competing bid, to markets moving. That is why a cash buyer can often win with a lower headline price, since certainty and speed have real value to a board that has decided to sell.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company's pension is underfunded by $300M. How do you treat it in enterprise value?",a:"As debt. It is a contractual obligation to pay people, the company cannot walk away from it, and a buyer inherits it. Add the after-tax underfunding to net debt.\n\nThe point: also look at the assumptions behind the number, because it is an estimate and management picks the inputs. A higher assumed discount rate shrinks the reported liability; a higher expected return on plan assets flatters the funded status. Two identical pensions can report very different deficits. Buyers rerun the numbers on their own assumptions, and the gap between the two is often material to the price.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why are operating leases treated as debt-like by credit analysts even now that they are on the balance sheet?",a:"Because the classification still splits the income statement. An operating lease keeps a single expense inside operating costs, so it sits above EBITDA, while a finance lease pushes it into depreciation and interest below EBITDA.\n\nSo two companies with identical obligations report different EBITDA.\n\nThe point: since every leverage covenant and every multiple is built on EBITDA, the classification changes the reported leverage even though the economics are identical. That is why credit analysts use EBITDAR and add capitalized leases to debt, so both sides of the ratio are consistent.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A retailer leases all 400 of its stores. How does that change your view of its leverage?",a:"Substantially. Those leases are contractual fixed payments for years, which is the defining feature of debt. Reported debt might be small and the real fixed obligation enormous.\n\nCapitalize the rent and add it to debt, then use EBITDAR so the ratio is consistent.\n\nThe point: the nuance is lease length and specificity. A two-year lease on generic mall space is closer to a real operating cost, since you can exit soon. A fifteen-year lease on a purpose-built distribution centre is debt in every meaningful sense. Treating all 400 identically is as wrong as ignoring them.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is a sale-leaseback and when does it make sense?",a:"Selling an asset you own and immediately leasing it back, so you keep using it and convert the asset into cash.\n\nIt makes sense when the implied financing rate beats your alternatives, or when the buyer values the real estate more than you do, which is often true since a REIT may pay a lower cap rate than your business multiple.\n\nThe point: that second reason is the legitimate one. If your operating business trades at 8x EBITDA and the property trades at a 6% cap rate, the same building is worth more owned separately. The arbitrage is real. Doing it because you cannot borrow is a different story entirely.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's implied cap rate is 7% and comparable properties trade at 5.5%. What does that suggest?",a:"That the market is valuing the company's real estate below what the private property market would pay. The cap rate is net operating income over value, so a higher cap rate means a lower price per dollar of income.\n\nThe gap suggests either a hidden discount or that the market disagrees about the income's durability.\n\nThe point: this is the classic sum-of-the-parts case for separating property from operations. If the buildings are worth more to a property investor than the market credits inside the operating company, there is value in a sale-leaseback, a spin, or a REIT conversion. Activists run exactly this screen.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do companies with volatile earnings trade at lower multiples than stable ones with the same average earnings?",a:"Because a multiple prices certainty as much as amount. Volatile earnings mean the average is a poor guide to any given year, the company may need capital at the worst moment, and it can support less debt.\n\nThe point: the deeper reason is that volatility raises the cost of capital. Cash flows that swing get discounted at a higher rate, so the same expected value is worth less today. It also raises the probability of distress, and distress destroys value beyond the earnings dip: customers leave, suppliers tighten, talent goes. That is why cyclicals trade at persistent discounts even in good years.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company earns $50M in a good year and loses $10M in a bad one, averaging $20M. How do you value it?",a:"On normalized earnings across a full cycle, not on either endpoint. The $20M average assumes good and bad years are equally frequent. If the real cycle is three good years to two bad, the average is $26M, and if it is two good to three bad it is $14M. So the first question is what the cycle actually looks like.\n\nThen apply a lower multiple than a stable company would get, because volatility deserves a discount regardless of the average.\n\nThe point: the trap is valuing at the peak. This business at $50M of earnings on a 12x multiple looks like a $600M company right before earnings collapse to a loss. That is why cyclicals look cheapest exactly when they are most expensive, since the P/E bottoms at the top of the cycle.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"Why do cyclical companies look cheap at the top of the cycle?",a:"Because the E in P/E is at its maximum. Earnings peak, so the ratio collapses, and the stock looks like a bargain at the precise moment the earnings are about to fall.\n\nThe reverse is also true. At the trough, earnings are minimal or negative, so the P/E is enormous or meaningless, and the stock looks expensive exactly when it is cheapest.\n\nThe point: this is why P/E is close to useless for cyclicals and why practitioners use price to normalized earnings, price to book, or EV per unit of capacity instead. The multiple is telling you where you are in the cycle, not what the business is worth.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"What is normalized EBITDA and why does it matter in a cyclical business?",a:"EBITDA adjusted to what the business earns through an average year of the cycle, rather than at a peak or trough.\n\nYou build it by averaging across a full cycle, or by applying mid-cycle margins to current volume.\n\nThe point: it is the difference between a sensible deal and a disaster. A sponsor underwriting a cyclical at peak EBITDA sets leverage against a number that will not exist in two years. The debt is fixed and the EBITDA is not, so leverage doubles without anyone borrowing a dollar. That is why lenders to cyclicals underwrite trough EBITDA, not last year's.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do lenders underwrite a cyclical business against trough EBITDA rather than current EBITDA?",a:"Because they get no upside. A lender's best case is being repaid in full, so they care only about the scenario where things go wrong. Underwriting against a peak means the structure fails exactly when it is tested.\n\nThe point: this asymmetry is the whole psychology of credit. Equity is paid for optimism and debt is paid for survival, so the two look at the same company and see different questions. A sponsor asks what this earns if things go well; a lender asks whether the interest gets paid if they do not. It is why leverage available to a cyclical is half what a contracted business gets on identical EBITDA.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does a company file for Chapter 11 rather than just negotiating with lenders?",a:"Because Chapter 11 gives it tools no negotiation can. An automatic stay stops every creditor from collecting. It can reject unprofitable contracts and leases. It can borrow ahead of existing creditors through debtor-in-possession financing. And it can bind holdout creditors through a court-approved plan.\n\nThe point: that last one is usually the reason. Out-of-court deals need near-unanimous consent, so a single holdout can extract a premium or block everything. Chapter 11 lets a supermajority within a class force the rest along, which is why the threat of filing is itself the main lever in an out-of-court negotiation.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the absolute priority rule?",a:"In a bankruptcy, each class of claims must be paid in full before the class below it receives anything. Secured lenders first, then unsecured, then subordinated, then preferred, then common equity.\n\nThe point: in practice it is bent constantly. Senior creditors often hand equity a small recovery to buy cooperation and speed, since fighting costs more than the giveaway. So common shareholders in a hopeless bankruptcy sometimes receive a token stub. That is not the rule working, it is senior creditors paying for consent, which is a very different thing and worth understanding when people cite recoveries.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the fulcrum security and why does it matter?",a:"The class of debt where the value runs out. Everything senior to it gets paid in full; everything junior gets nothing. The fulcrum class gets partial recovery and typically converts into the equity of the reorganized company.\n\nThe point: identifying it is the entire distressed investing game. If you buy the fulcrum security at 40 cents and it converts into 100% of the post-emergence equity, you have bought the company at a discount through the debt market. Buy one tranche too senior and you get paid par with no upside. Buy one too junior and you get nothing.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"How do you find the fulcrum security?",a:"Value the enterprise, then walk the capital structure down until the money runs out. If the business is worth $600M and there is $400M of secured debt and $300M of unsecured, the secured is covered and the unsecured recovers $200M of $300M, so 67 cents. The unsecured is the fulcrum.\n\nThe point: everything depends on the enterprise valuation, which is exactly what everyone fights about in a restructuring. Creditors senior to the fulcrum argue for a low valuation to consolidate control; junior creditors argue for a high one to stay in the money. The valuation is not an analysis, it is a negotiating position with a spreadsheet attached.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do distressed investors want to own the fulcrum rather than the most senior debt?",a:"Because senior debt gets paid par and stops. Your upside is the discount you bought it at, and nothing more. The fulcrum converts to equity, so you own the recovery.\n\nThe point: it is a completely different trade. Buying senior at 85 cents is a credit bet, and you win if the company survives. Buying the fulcrum at 40 is an equity bet made through the debt market, and you win if the company is worth more than the market thinks. Distressed-for-control funds specifically target the fulcrum because it is the cheapest way to own a business without an auction.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is debtor-in-possession financing and why would anyone lend to a bankrupt company?",a:"A loan made to a company already in Chapter 11. Lenders do it because DIP loans get super-priority, ranking ahead of every existing creditor, and are usually secured by unencumbered assets with tight controls.\n\nThe point: it is often the safest loan in the entire structure, despite the borrower being bankrupt. You are first in line, the court is supervising, and the company cannot spend without permission. The existing creditors usually consent because without the financing the business liquidates and their recovery collapses, so they accept being primed to protect what they have.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is a prepackaged bankruptcy?",a:"A Chapter 11 where the plan is negotiated and voted on before filing. The company arrives at court with agreement already in hand and emerges in weeks rather than years.\n\nThe point: it is the best of both worlds when it works. You get the court's power to bind holdouts without the cost, delay, and business damage of a contested case. Bankruptcy destroys value through uncertainty as much as through legal fees, since customers leave and suppliers tighten terms. A prepack minimizes the window in which that happens, which is why it is the preferred route for a pure balance sheet problem.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does a company in bankruptcy often keep operating normally?",a:"Because it is worth far more as a going concern than in liquidation. A functioning business with customers, employees, and contracts has value; the same assets sold piecemeal at auction do not.\n\nThe automatic stay is what makes this possible, since it stops creditors seizing assets while the business continues.\n\nThe point: this is the entire economic purpose of Chapter 11. Liquidation destroys the organizational capital, meaning the relationships and know-how that made the assets productive. The bankruptcy is a fight over who owns the business, and everyone involved has a shared interest in the business surviving the fight.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"What is the difference between a liquidity problem and a solvency problem?",a:"Liquidity means you cannot pay today; solvency means you cannot pay ever. A company with a valuable business and a maturity it cannot refinance has a liquidity problem. A company whose assets are worth less than its debts has a solvency problem.\n\nThe point: the distinction decides the solution. A liquidity problem is fixed with financing, since someone lends against the underlying value. A solvency problem cannot be fixed with more debt, only with less, which means someone has to lose money. The danger is that an unresolved liquidity problem becomes a solvency problem, because distress destroys real value while everyone argues.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why do restructurings usually end with lenders owning the company?",a:"Because the equity is already worthless and everyone knows it. If the enterprise is worth less than the debt, the shareholders' claim is under water, so the cleanest fix is converting debt to equity: lenders forgive some debt and take ownership in exchange.\n\nThe point: this is not lenders being aggressive, it is arithmetic. They are the residual claimants once value falls below the debt, so they already own the economics; the paperwork is just catching up. It also explains why sponsors sometimes inject fresh equity, since it is the only way to keep an option that would otherwise be extinguished.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"A company's bonds trade at 45 cents. What is the market saying?",a:"That it expects a restructuring and roughly a 45% recovery. Bond prices in distress stop being about yield and become a forecast of what you get back.\n\nThe point: the useful exercise is to reverse it. At 45 cents on $500M of bonds, the market is implying about $225M of value flows to that class. Add the senior claims ahead of it and you can back out the enterprise value the market is assuming. Then compare it with your own. If you think the business is worth more, the bonds are cheap and you may be buying the fulcrum. That is the whole trade.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Why does a covenant breach matter if the company has not missed a payment?",a:"Because it hands the lenders control. A breach is an event of default, so lenders can accelerate the debt, meaning demand it all back immediately, which the company cannot pay.\n\nThey usually do not. They negotiate.\n\nThe point: the leverage is the point. The lender gets to reprice the deal, charge amendment fees, tighten terms, demand an equity injection, or take warrants. The company has performed on cash and still ends up giving something away, because the covenant was an early warning system the lenders bought precisely so they could act before the cash actually ran out.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"What is covenant-lite and why did it become standard?",a:"Debt with no maintenance covenants, meaning no quarterly test the borrower must pass. It has only incurrence covenants, which are triggered by actions like raising more debt, not by results deteriorating.\n\nIt became standard because credit was abundant and sponsors had leverage over lenders.\n\nThe point: it removes the early warning system. With maintenance covenants, lenders find out something is wrong while there is still equity value and time to fix it. With cov-lite, the first hard signal is a missed payment, by which point the value is gone. It shifts control from lenders to sponsors, which is exactly why sponsors wanted it and why recoveries have been worse this cycle.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"Why do recoveries tend to be lower on cov-lite deals?",a:"Because problems get discovered later. A maintenance covenant trips while the business is merely deteriorating, so lenders intervene when there is still enterprise value to protect. Cov-lite lets a company burn through its cushion unimpeded until it misses a payment.\n\nThe point: by the time the default happens, the company has usually drawn the revolver, stretched suppliers, sold assets, and deferred capex. The value that would have supported a recovery has been consumed keeping the lights on. The covenant was never about the ratio, it was about the timing of the conversation.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A sponsor asks lenders for a covenant waiver. What does it cost?",a:"Money and control. Typically an amendment fee, a higher spread, tighter covenants going forward, and often a condition like an equity cure, meaning the sponsor injects cash.\n\nThe point: lenders grant waivers when the business is fundamentally sound and the breach is temporary, because they would rather be paid than own a company. They refuse when they think the value is below the debt, since at that point taking the keys is better than extending. So the answer to whether the waiver is granted tells you what the lenders believe about the enterprise value, which is often more informative than the sponsor's own model.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's DSO is 45 days, DIO is 60 days, and DPO is 30 days. What is the cash conversion cycle and what does it cost?",a:"75 days. Inventory sits 60 days, receivables take 45 to collect, and suppliers are paid in 30, so 60 plus 45 minus 30 is 75 days of funding the gap.\n\nOn $365M of revenue, that is roughly $75M of cash permanently tied up in the business.\n\nThe point: every extra day of cycle is another day of revenue locked in working capital. Cut DSO by 15 days and you free about $15M without selling anything more. That is why working capital is the first place a sponsor looks post-close, since it is cash sitting in plain sight.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company grows revenue 30% a year with a 75-day cash conversion cycle. What is the problem?",a:"Growth eats cash. Each year revenue rises 30%, so the working capital funding that 75-day cycle has to rise roughly 30% too. The company must find that money before customers pay.\n\nAt $100M of revenue, 75 days of it is about $21M tied up. Grow to $130M and it becomes about $27M, so the growth alone consumed roughly $6M of cash that never appears on the income statement.\n\nThe point: this is why profitable companies raise money. The faster you grow, the more working capital you fund, and the income statement shows none of it. It is also why a negative cycle business scales without financing, because the customers fund the growth instead of the shareholders.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A buyer discovers in diligence that $12M of the target's $60M EBITDA is one-time. What happens to the price at 9x?",a:"It should fall $108M. Real EBITDA is $48M, and at 9x that is $432M rather than $540M.\n\nThe point: this is why quality of earnings is the first workstream and why the multiple is the least interesting part of a deal. Everyone argues about 9x versus 10x, worth $48M here, while the EBITDA definition itself is worth $108M. The seller will fight to keep those add-backs precisely because each dollar of EBITDA is worth nine dollars of price. Diligence rarely kills a deal, it reprices it.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company has $80M of NOLs and is about to be acquired. What is that worth to the buyer?",a:"Less than it looks. At a 25% tax rate, $80M of NOLs shields $20M of future cash tax, but only if the buyer can use them.\n\nAfter a change of control the rules limit annual usage, so the benefit stretches over many years, and discounting it back cuts the value further. Call it meaningfully below $20M.\n\nThe point: the limitation exists specifically to stop companies being bought for their tax attributes. That is why buyers model NOLs as a separate, discounted asset rather than adding the face value to the price, and why sellers who quote the gross number are overreaching.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Two identical companies. One reports revenue gross, the other net. How different do they look?",a:"Enormously on revenue, identically on profit. A company acting as a principal books the full sale as revenue and the cost in COGS. One acting as an agent books only its fee.\n\nOn a $100 transaction with a $10 fee, one reports $100 of revenue and the other $10. Both make $10.\n\nThe point: gross reporting inflates revenue with no effect on earnings, so it makes growth and scale look dramatic while gross margin collapses. Any company valued on EV/Revenue has an obvious incentive here, which is why the principal versus agent test is one of the most litigated areas in revenue recognition.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company's gross margin is 25% and it wants to double net income. What is easier, raising price 5% or cutting costs 5%?",a:"Raising price, by a wide margin. A 5% price increase on $100 of revenue adds $5, and it is nearly pure profit because the costs do not move. Cutting total costs 5% saves $3.75 on the $75 of COGS.\n\nSo price is roughly a third more powerful, and that ignores that cost cuts often damage the product.\n\nThe point: price is the highest-leverage variable in any business, which is why pricing power is what investors actually pay for. The catch is volume. If a 5% price rise loses 10% of customers, the arithmetic reverses, and whether that happens is the entire question.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has fixed costs of $40M and a 60% contribution margin. What revenue does it need to break even?",a:"About $67M. Break-even is fixed costs divided by contribution margin, so $40M over 0.60.\n\nAbove that, 60 cents of every additional revenue dollar drops to profit. Below it, losses compound at the same rate.\n\nThe point: the contribution margin tells you the slope on both sides of break-even. A business at 60% is highly geared, so it swings hard in either direction. That is why break-even analysis matters more for high-fixed-cost businesses, and why lenders care where a company sits relative to it, not just whether it is profitable today.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company earns $100M and pays $60M in dividends. Is that sustainable?",a:"A 60% payout ratio, which is sustainable if the earnings are stable and the business does not need the cash. Check three things: is free cash flow at least $60M, since dividends are paid from cash and not earnings; is capex being underfunded to make the payment; and how cyclical are the earnings.\n\nThe point: the danger is paying dividends out of earnings the business cannot convert. A company with $100M of net income and $40M of free cash flow paying $60M is funding the gap with debt, which works until it does not. That is why dividend cuts are punished so brutally, since they are usually an admission the company was paying from the wrong pocket.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company is valued at 12x EBITDA. It acquires a competitor at 7x. Why is that immediately accretive?",a:"Because it is buying earnings more cheaply than the market values its own. The target's EBITDA is worth 7x when purchased and gets revalued at the acquirer's 12x once consolidated, so the arbitrage is 5 turns.\n\nThat gap is created purely by scale and multiple, not by improving anything.\n\nThe point: this is the roll-up engine. Buy small at low multiples, consolidate, sell large at a high one. It works while the target multiples stay low and the integration is real. It breaks when the deals get big enough that sellers demand your multiple, which is the arithmetic behind most roll-up failures.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"Why is EV/EBITDA usually lower than EV/EBIT for the same company?",a:"Because EBITDA is a bigger number. EBIT is after depreciation and amortization, so the denominator is smaller and the multiple is larger.\n\nA company with $100M of EBITDA and $30M of D&A has $70M of EBIT. At $1B of enterprise value that is 10x EBITDA and 14.3x EBIT.\n\nThe point: the gap between the two multiples is a direct read on capital intensity. A software company with minimal D&A shows almost no gap. A manufacturer shows a wide one, and the wider it is, the more the EBITDA multiple is flattering a business that has to keep spending to survive.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company reports a 20% ROE and 8% ROIC. What explains the gap?",a:"Leverage. Return on equity divides profit by a small equity base, and debt shrinks that base without reducing net income proportionally. Return on invested capital measures the whole capital base, debt included, so it strips the borrowing out.\n\nThe point: this gap is the single best test of whether returns are operational or financial. A 20% ROE built on 8% ROIC means the business is mediocre and the balance sheet is doing the work. It also means the ROE is fragile, since it evaporates the moment rates rise or the debt is repaid. ROIC is what tells you if there is a moat.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's share price is $60 and it has $4 of EPS and $8 of free cash flow per share. Which multiple do you trust?",a:"The cash one. It trades at 15x earnings and 7.5x free cash flow, and free cash flow exceeding earnings usually means large non-cash charges, most often depreciation on assets bought long ago.\n\nThat can be genuine, as with a company harvesting an old asset base, or it can mean underinvestment.\n\nThe point: when the two multiples diverge this much, the interesting question is why. Check capex against depreciation. If capex is well below D&A, the free cash flow is being flattered by not replacing assets, and that is borrowed from the future rather than earned.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A sponsor wants to buy a business at 10x but can only get 4x of debt. What does that do to returns?",a:"It forces a much bigger equity cheque, which crushes the IRR. At 10x with 6x of debt, equity is 4 turns. At 4x of debt, equity is 6 turns, so 50% more capital for the same asset.\n\nSince returns are measured against equity invested, the same exit produces materially lower IRR.\n\nThe point: this is why leverage availability drives deal pricing as much as the asset does. When credit tightens, sponsors cannot pay as much and still hit their hurdle, so bids fall. It is the mechanism connecting rates to M&A volumes, and it works even when nothing about the target changed.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company has been losing 2% of customers a month. Is that bad?",a:"Very. Monthly churn of 2% compounds to roughly 22% a year, so nearly a quarter of the base disappears annually and the average customer lasts about 50 months.\n\nFor a consumer product that might be tolerable. For enterprise software it is a broken business, because acquisition costs are paid upfront and recovered over years.\n\nThe point: churn compounds, so people underestimate it badly. The number that matters is whether lifetime value exceeds acquisition cost given that churn. At 2% monthly with an 18-month payback, the customer is barely profitable before they leave.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's revenue per employee is $180K and its peers run at $400K. What does that suggest?",a:"That it is either far less efficient or a different business. Revenue per employee is a crude productivity measure, and a gap that wide usually means the company is people-intensive where peers have automated, or it is doing services work classified alongside product companies.\n\nThe point: it also signals margin risk. If peers generate more than twice the revenue per head, they can price aggressively and still make money, while this company cannot follow. For a sponsor, it is either the thesis, meaning there is a real cost opportunity, or the reason to walk, meaning the business model is structurally different from the comps it is being valued against.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has $50M of EBITDA and takes on $200M of debt at 8%. What is its interest coverage and is it safe?",a:"Coverage is 3.1x. Interest is $200M at 8%, which is $16M, and $50M divided by $16M is 3.1x.\n\nWhether it is safe depends on volatility. For a business with contracted revenue, 3.1x is comfortable. For a cyclical, imagine EBITDA falling 40% in a downturn to $30M, which takes coverage to 1.9x, close to a typical covenant floor.\n\nThe point: never judge coverage at today's EBITDA. Stress it. Lenders set covenants against the bad year, not the good one, and the whole question is what happens to the ratio when the cycle turns.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company's revenue is $800M with a 12% EBITDA margin. A sponsor thinks it can reach 18%. What is the EBITDA uplift and what is it worth at 9x?",a:"EBITDA goes from $96M to $144M, an uplift of $48M. At 9x that is $432M of additional enterprise value.\n\nThe point: notice how much value sits in six margin points. That is why sponsors fixate on margin improvement, and why you should interrogate it hard. Six points on $800M of revenue means finding $48M of annual savings or price. Ask which specific costs, who owns the plan, and what peers run at. If competitors operate at 13%, an 18% target needs an explanation for why this company beats every one of them.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A company trades at 14x earnings and grows 7%. Another trades at 28x and grows 25%. Which is cheaper?",a:"Probably the 28x company, though the multiple says otherwise. Use PEG as a rough check: 14 over 7 is 2.0, and 28 over 25 is 1.1. On that crude measure the faster grower is cheaper per unit of growth.\n\nThe point: PEG is a shorthand, not analysis. It ignores risk entirely and assumes growth is linearly comparable, which it is not. The real questions are how long each growth rate persists and what capital it consumes. A 25% grower decelerating to 8% in two years is expensive at 28x. One holding 25% for a decade is cheap.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has $2B of enterprise value, $150M of EBITDA, and $120M of capex. What do you notice?",a:"That it trades at 13.3x EBITDA and capex eats 80% of EBITDA. Only about $30M of EBITDA survives capex before interest and tax.\n\nSo the business is being valued at roughly 67x what it actually generates, before financing costs.\n\nThe point: the EBITDA multiple looks ordinary and the underlying economics do not. This is the single strongest argument against valuing capital-intensive businesses on EBITDA. Always run EBITDA less capex as a sanity check, because that is the number with any claim to being cash.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A sponsor puts in $200M of equity and exits five years later with $500M. What is the IRR?",a:"2.5x over five years, which is about 20%. The exact figure is 2.5 to the power of one fifth minus one, or 20.1%.\n\nThe point: this is right at the standard PE underwriting hurdle. Sponsors typically target 20% to 25%, so 2.5x to 3x over a five-year hold is the benchmark to have memorized. Note that IRR is time-sensitive in a way the multiple is not. The same $500M returned in year three would be a 36% IRR on identical profit, which is exactly why exit timing gets negotiated as hard as entry price.",category:"LBO"},
{q:"A buyer pays $1B for a target with $80M of EBITDA and expects $20M of synergies. What multiple did it really pay?",a:"12.5x on reported EBITDA, but 10x on synergized EBITDA of $100M.\n\nThe point: this is the number buyers quote in press releases and it deserves scrutiny. Paying 10x post-synergy only works if the synergies actually arrive, and cost synergies usually do while revenue synergies usually do not. If half the $20M is revenue synergy, the realistic multiple is closer to 11.1x on $90M.\n\nThe deeper issue is who captured the value. If the target was worth 10x standalone and you paid 12.5x, you handed the entire synergy value to the seller's shareholders.",category:"M&A"},
{q:"A company has 50M shares, earns $100M, and buys back 10% of its shares at $40. What happens to EPS?",a:"EPS rises from $2.00 to $2.22. It buys 5M shares for $200M, leaving 45M shares, and $100M over 45M is $2.22, up 11%.\n\nBut check the cost. If the $200M was cash earning 3%, it gives up $6M pre-tax, so at 25% tax net income falls to $95.5M. EPS is then $2.12, still up 6%.\n\nThe point: the naive calculation ignores what the cash was doing. The buyback is still accretive here because forgone interest is small, which is exactly why almost every buyback is accretive and why accretion is a useless test of whether it was smart.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company reports $500M of revenue, up 25%, but receivables rose from $80M to $140M. What do you think?",a:"That the growth is not converting. Revenue rose 25% while receivables rose 75%, so receivables are growing three times faster than sales.\n\nCheck days sales outstanding: $80M on $400M of prior revenue is 73 days; $140M on $500M is 102 days. Collections deteriorated by a month.\n\nThe point: that 29-day slip is roughly 8% of annual revenue moved from cash into a promise. Either customers are struggling, terms were loosened to buy the growth, or revenue is being recognized too aggressively. All three mean the 25% is worth less than it looks.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A company has a 60% gross margin and 10% operating margin. Where is the money going?",a:"Into operating expenses, which are consuming 50 points of margin. That is sales and marketing, R&D, and general administrative costs.\n\nWhether it is a problem depends on why. A software company spending 40 points on sales and marketing to grow 40% is investing. One spending it to grow 5% has a distribution problem it cannot fix.\n\nThe point: a wide gap between gross and operating margin is not automatically bad, it is a question about operating leverage. Ask whether those costs scale with revenue or with headcount. If the 50 points shrink as revenue grows, it is investment. If they stay at 50 points forever, that is just the cost structure.",category:"Accounting"},
{q:"A DCF has a 10% WACC and 3% terminal growth. What is the implied exit multiple on terminal free cash flow?",a:"About 14.7x. The perpetuity formula divides by WACC minus growth, so one divided by 0.10 less 0.03 is 14.3x on next year's cash flow, and slightly higher on the final projected year once you gross up for the growth.\n\nThe point: this is the cross-check every DCF should carry. If your comps trade at 8x EBITDA and your perpetuity assumptions imply an exit at 15x cash flow, your terminal assumptions and the market disagree, and you should find out why before presenting either. The two methods are meant to triangulate, not to be picked based on which gives the answer you wanted.",category:"DCF"},
{q:"A company earns $60M of net income on $400M of equity. Is that good?",a:"That is a 15% return on equity, which is decent. Compare it with the cost of equity, say 9% or 10%. Earning 15% against a 10% cost means the company creates value for shareholders.\n\nBut check how it got there. Return on equity can be inflated by leverage, since debt shrinks the equity base without touching net income. A company at 15% ROE with no debt is far better than one at 15% carrying 5x leverage.\n\nThe point: decompose it with DuPont. ROE is margin times asset turnover times leverage. Two of those are operating skill and one is just borrowing.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company has $300M of debt maturing next year and $50M of cash generating $40M of free cash flow. What happens?",a:"It has to refinance, because $90M of available cash against a $300M maturity leaves a $210M hole.\n\nThe outcomes: refinance, possibly at a much worse rate; sell assets; raise equity at whatever price the market offers; negotiate an extension; or restructure.\n\nThe point: this is how companies actually fail. Not from losing money, since it generates $40M a year, but from a maturity it cannot meet. Solvency and liquidity are different things. The debt also reclassifies to current liabilities, which wrecks the current ratio and may trip covenants elsewhere, so the problem compounds before the maturity even arrives.",category:"Capital Markets"},
{q:"Two companies both grow revenue 15%. One converts 25% of revenue to free cash flow, the other 5%. Which deserves a higher multiple?",a:"The one converting 25%, and by a wide margin. Both are growing identically, and one delivers five times the cash per dollar of revenue.\n\nA multiple is a claim on future cash, not future revenue. Growth that never converts is a treadmill.\n\nThe point: this is why revenue multiples across different business models are close to meaningless. The 5% company is probably capital intensive or funding customers through working capital. Its growth costs money. The 25% company's growth pays for itself, which means it can compound without raising capital or diluting anyone.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's stock falls 30% on an earnings beat. What single thing would you check first?",a:"Guidance. The most common cause by far is that the company beat this quarter and cut the outlook, so the future got worse even though the past was good.\n\nAfter that: whether the beat came from a one-time item rather than operations, and whether margins compressed even as revenue grew.\n\nThe point: price reflects expectations, not results. A beat only matters relative to what was already priced, and guidance resets expectations for every future quarter at once. One quarter is worth a fraction of the value; the forward path is worth most of it.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A private company wants to know what it is worth. Its public peers trade at 11x EBITDA. What do you tell it?",a:"Somewhere below 11x, because public multiples carry a liquidity premium the private company does not have. A public share sells in seconds at a known price; a private stake takes months, may need approval, and has no observable price.\n\nThe discount is typically 10% to 20%, so call it 9x to 10x.\n\nThe point: do not apply that discount to precedent transactions, because those already involve buying entire private companies, so the illiquidity is baked in. And note the discount shrinks if the company is genuinely saleable, since the buyer pool is what actually creates liquidity.",category:"Valuation"},
{q:"A company's five-year plan assumes it takes 10 points of market share from a competitor. What do you ask?",a:"Ask what the competitor does in response, because the plan almost certainly assumes they stand still.\n\nMarket share is zero-sum. Ten points has to come from someone, and that someone has a sales force, a balance sheet, and every incentive to defend. If your plan works by winning their customers, their plan works by keeping them, and both plans cannot be right.\n\nThen ask the mechanism. Is it price, which invites a price war and destroys the margin assumption sitting next to the share assumption. Is it a product advantage, and how long until it is copied. Is it distribution the competitor cannot access.\n\nThe point: share gain plans usually model your actions and not theirs. The question that breaks them is simply what does the competitor do, and the honest answer often reveals that the margin and the share assumptions in the same model contradict each other.",category:"Valuation"}
];

